<HEADLINE>
D COLUMN: A SHIFT IN POWER FOR J. WALTER THOMPSON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif. Texas)  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charlotte Beers, often called the most powerful woman
in advertising, is for the third time becoming a top leader at a
giant agency.
</P>
<P>
   Effective immediately, Ms. Beers is joining the J. Walter
Thompson Co. in New York as chairwoman. Chris Jones, Thompson's
chairman since January 1998, is relinquishing those duties in an
unusual shifting and sharing of power; he continues as chief
executive, a post he has held since January 1997, in charge of
agency management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving up part of my title,'' Jones, 43, said in an
interview Monday morning at the Thompson headquarters in midtown
Manhattan, ``but titles are not as important as what each of us is
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers, 63, who joined Jones for the interview, said, ``The
person with the best idea in the room is the leader.'' She
described her duties as focusing on ``the vitality of brands'' sold
by clients, acquisitions, new business and ``long-term strategic
development, which in the advertising business is next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the linchpin of that is talent, talent, talent, talent,
talent,'' Ms. Beers said, tapping on a table for emphasis. ``We
must find the best people in the business; nothing happens without
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers emphatically dismissed a description of her new job as
being a nonexecutive chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many serious responsibilities,'' she said, adding that
she and Jones would have ``a natural fellowship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it particularly ticks me off that people talk about the
partnership as a `client hand-holding exercise,' '' Ms. Beers said,
referring to articles in newspapers and trade publications
depicting her as the schmooze queen of Madison Avenue, wooing chief
executives responsible for ad spending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything more disdainful of our clients, as
if they needed hand-holding,'' she added. ``And nothing offends me
more than to say I specialize in client dinners.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with her reputation as a steel magnolia, Ms. Beers, a
charming, tenacious Texan, delivered those remarks softly, with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers' high profile in the industry is exemplified by her
appearance on the cover of Fortune magazine and items in society
and gossip columns that chronicle her hobnobbing with friends like
style doyenne Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In her two previous stints as a chairwoman, at Euro RSCG Tatham
in Chicago and Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in New York, Ms. Beers
made significant contributions, helping those agencies manage
accounts and clients, as well as helping to attract new business
and talented employees.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers is hoping to repeat those feats at Thompson, the
world's No. 5 agency, with 246 offices in 81 countries. Thompson's
billings are estimated at $7.6 billion from blue-chip advertisers
like Ford Motor, Philip Morris and Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thompson has endured a roller coaster ride during Jones'
tenure, suffering losses of big accounts like Eastman Kodak, Dell
Computer and Sprint, that have been partly offset by recent gains
from the Bermuda Department of Tourism, Kimberly-Clark and Merrill
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the San Francisco office of Thompson U.S.A.
landed the account of the Pacific Gas and Electric Co. in San
Francisco, a unit of the PG&AMP;E Corp., with estimated billings of $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got plenty to do,'' Jones said of himself and Ms. Beers,
``but the collaboration will be easy to do because we have a shared
passion, a shared vocabulary, a shared belief in building brands.''
The Thompson philosophy is known as ``Total branding,'' while
Ogilvy's is ``Brand stewardship.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also shares a parent with Ogilvy, the No. 6 agency,
with billings estimated at $7.4 billion; both are owned by WPP
Group P.L.C., which assisted in Ms. Beers' switch between sibling
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Her arrival at Thompson is indicative of the efforts by the
largest agencies to avoid losing ground as competition intensifies.
Thompson has been eagerly seeking an experienced senior executive
to bolster its management capabilities in the crucial North
American market.
</P>
<P>
   Trade publications reported that the search had been spurred, or
even directed, by Martin Sorrell, chief executive at WPP in London,
who was described as eager to improve Thompson's results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris initiated the idea and the decision, and Martin
supported it,'' Ms. Beers said, calling Sorrell ``a very productive
handmaiden'' in arranging her arrival. To take the Thompson job,
Ms. Beers will sever her remaining ties to Ogilvy, where she has
been chairwoman emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers was considered instrumental in reviving Ogilvy, which
before her arrival had suffered severe setbacks in the early 1990s
that were far more serious than any now plaguing Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to Ogilvy, I said, `This job cannot be done,' ''
Ms. Beers recalled. ``I was brought in there as a change agent.
It's quite night and day from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers joined Ogilvy as chairwoman and chief executive in
April 1992. Two years later, she helped land the IBM account, with
billings estimated at $500 million, in what was then the largest
account consolidation in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said my first job was to remove the `beleaguered' in
front of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather,'' Ms. Beers said, laughing. She
relinquished the chief executive's duties to Shelly Lazarus in
September 1996 and the chairwoman's duties to Ms. Lazarus in April
1997, when she became chairwoman emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Ogilvy, Ms. Beers worked at Euro RSCG Tatham,
part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising, from
1979 to 1992. She served as chief operating officer (1979-82),
chief executive (1982-92) and chairwoman (1986-90).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beers expects a similarly long stay in her new job _ ``I
doubt it will be less than five years,'' she said. Unlike her
stints at the other two giant agencies, which she joined from the
outside, Ms. Beers' move to Thompson represents a homecoming. Her
first job in advertising _ ``all my basic training,'' as she put it
_ was at the Chicago office of Thompson U.S.A. from 1969 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ogilvy brought in Charlotte,'' Jones said, smiling,
``they brought in someone originally from Thompson.''
</P>
<P>
   At Thompson, she rose to senior vice president and client
services director, but no further. In interviews in the 1980s,
former co-workers said her career had stalled because Thompson was
loath to have women in top posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful a woman gets to do all these things''
today, Ms. Beers said. ``I'll probably have four more jobs just to
prove that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
