<HEADLINE>
MARGIELA ON SCREEN  
 FROM SHOES TO SKIRTS  
 W&AMP;LT FOR ASIA ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Margiela on Screen
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ The creativity of Martin Margiela will not be on the
runways in Paris, where the fall women's shows are under way.
Instead, Margiela is showing his line by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Margiela and Kostas Murkudis, a designer who once worked
for Helmut Lang, invoked an ``at the movies'' setting to present
their clothes. A visitor to the drafty Margiela atelier was led
into a white room with eight creaking red-velvet theater seats.
Once the guest was settled with popcorn and soda, the projectionist
_ really, a less romantic VCR operator _ got down to work, showing
a 10-minute video of Margiela's designs. The clothes were also
available for viewing on a fit model or on the hanger.
</P>
<P>
   Margiela has only a few cards to play for the season, but he has
dealt a superb hand. For starters, there's the duvet coat, made in
Italy by a manufacturer of bed linens. It continues the designer's
experiments of the past year, cutting clothes that lie flat. This
coat is a square with two detachable sleeves and a large sheltering
collar. You can wear the coat, which will sell for about $1,000, as
is. Or you can buy one of three shells, which can be worn alone in
mild weather or as coverings over the duvet. A clear shell of PVC
is the hippest choice, one of brown wool is more traditional, and a
denim shell offers a casual street look.
</P>
<P>
   Margiela has chosen to make his big end-of-the-century statement
with jewelry rather than clothing. He is selling an unclosed
necklace with two sharp nails at either end. The nails are for
sticking into each side of the cork from your first bottle of
Champagne in the year 2000. Cheers!
</P>
<P>
   From Shoes to Skirts
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the shoes make it too couture?'' Patrick Cox asked Annabel
Tollman, as both looked a model named Bracha up and down.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tollman, an editor of Wallpaper magazine and the stylist for
Cox's first Paris show, which is to be held Tuesday, stared at the
model. Cox stared harder. After a few minutes, they reached a
decision that the crystal-covered mules did not make the black
sweater and diamante black tea-length skirt look too sickly sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, the Canadian shoe designer, who is based in England, wants
to become as well known for clothes as he is for footwear. ``It's
been three years now that I've been doing clothes, and I'm now
proud enough to put them on the runway in Paris,'' he said. ``That
I do clothes in England is a very well known fact, but people who
are going to come to this show don't even come to England.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox hopes to show next in New York, where he has a store on
Madison Avenue. If Americans are familiar with Cox's clothes, it is
most likely because of his casual Wannabee collection, named for
his Wannabee shoes _ gawky loafers with thick soles and wide toes.
Wannabee will now be sold only in Japan, as Cox attempts to build a
name in clothes with more elegance. Like satin tea skirts.
</P>
<P>
   W&AMP;LT for Asia Only
</P>
<P>
   Walter van Beirendonck, the Belgian designer whose W&AMP;LT
collection melded streetwise flair with computer-game iconography,
is restructuring his business.
</P>
<P>
   His women's collection has been suspended, although as van
Beirendonck _ a bear of a man with a bald pate, bushy beard and
gigantic rings on almost every finger _ pointed out, many of his
designs for men are in fact unisex.
</P>
<P>
   Van Beirendonk, who was in Paris this week viewing friends'
shows rather than staging his own, said W&AMP;LT (the letters stand for
Wild and Lethal Trash) will now be sold only in Asia. Relinquishing
his role as designer, van Beirendonck will serve as a consultant.
Bloomingdale's and Charivari were among the American stores that
carried the line. Most of his efforts will now go into his own
signature collection, which he designs in Antwerp, where he
recently opened a boutique. The W&AMP;LT label had become so demanding,
he said, that he had stopped producing a top line.
</P>
</TEXT>
