<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND LAND TAXES ARE CALLED BIASED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ The Justice Department says Nassau County's
method of assessing property taxes discriminates against black and
Hispanic homeowners, causing them to pay disproportionately high
taxes, according to government documents.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Zachary W. Carter, in a letter to top Nassau
officials, threatened a government lawsuit unless the county
voluntarily takes steps to end ``the discriminatory assessments,''
and consents to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate but related action, a New York state Supreme Court
judge refused Monday to dismiss a suit about discriminatory
assessments filed against Nassau County by the New York Civil
Liberties Union on behalf of six black homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford M. Cohen, chief of civil rights litigation in the U.S.
Attorney's office, said the homeowners' suit would not affect the
government's actions against the county. He added that he was
hopeful that Nassau would voluntarily resolve the tax issue. ``If
not, we are authorized to sue,'' he said. Cohen said the county had
been aware for years that its assessment system was discriminatory,
yet had made no effort to change it.
</P>
<P>
   In Nassau, homes are assessed based on 1938 construction costs,
while the land they are built on is assessed according to 1964
property values. Because property values have appreciated faster in
wealthier, predominantly white areas than in poorer, more heavily
minority areas, homes that may have cost the same when they were
built decades ago and are currently assessed at the same rate could
have widely varying prices.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hezekiah Brown, a labor negotiator who says his
home in a predominantly African-American neighborhood in Hempstead
is worth around $200,000, pays a little over $8,000 a year in
property taxes. He said a house similar to his in nearby Garden
City was worth more than $400,000, but the owners also paid $8,000
a year in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said a Justice Department study compared the assessed and
market values of more than 11,000 residential properties in Nassau
from August 1995 through July 1996 with Census Bureau figures. The
study showed that the average assessment in predominantly minority
areas was 27 percent higher than the total average assessment rate
of all property in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, owners of residential property in minority
communities have for years borne a disproportionate share of the
cost of governmental services that are funded by real property
taxes,'' Carter said in his letter, dated March 2. Carter's letter
and the Justice Department's findings were first reported Monday by
Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County Executive Thomas S. Gulotta defended the county's
property tax system as fair and as one that had been upheld by the
courts. He had no immediate comment on Monday's court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 study by the Nassau Citizens Budget Committee estimated
that a reassessment would cost at least $40 million. Gulotta said
such a step ``may be harmful and costly to our taxpayers,
regardless of race or national origin.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta noted that the county recently enacted a year-round
grievance system enabling property owners to appeal their
assessments.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the appeals have been so successful, they have cost the
county more than $100 million in tax refunds, which it has had to
borrow. In the view of some critics, this expense indicates that
the old assessment system should be revised to help solve the
county's fiscal crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The county's $2.3 billion budget has become so structurally
imbalanced that Standard &AMP; Poor's recently lowered the county's
credit rating to A-minus and placed its bonds on a credit watch. It
is facing a $160 million deficit for 1998 and a projected $125
million deficit for 1999, despite the generally robust health of
Long Island's economy.
</P>
<P>
   However, a revision of its assessment procedures would not help
the county's finances, said Richard J. Marino, a director at
Standard &AMP; Poor's. ``It might shift the burden around among the
taxpayers, but the financial outcome would be the same,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
