<HEADLINE>
CAN'T GET ENOUGH VITALE AUDIO? TRY ESPN.COM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN.com knew exactly what it was doing when it picked today's
scheduled chat with college basketball analyst Dick Vitale as the
site's first audio chat.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious.
</P>
<P>
   When someone is screaming ``Diaper dan-dees!'' or ``Eeet's
Mee-sha-gan, baybee! (It's Michigan, baby!),'' the translation gets
lost as transcribed text. You have to have ``sound'', and Vitale _
like it or not, baybee _ is all about audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Text doesn't reflect sarcasm and jokes,'' said Ted Bishop,
ESPN.com's interact department manager. ``With Dick, we have
someone who talks with so much enthusiasm that you want to be able
to capture it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Vitale's chat is scheduled for 3:30 p.m. today. ESPN.com users
can log on to the site's chat section and post questions as usual.
If all goes as planned, users will be able to see Vitale's
responses on screen and hear him answer selected questions.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia chat has been tried before. ABCNEWS.com conducted a
video chat with television anchor Peter Jennings two years ago.
America Online had a video chat session with Koko the gorilla last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said he doesn't believe the online video technology,
which tends to be choppy, is advanced enough for entertaining video
chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for entertainment for the user, and I'm not sure (if
video) adds a lot,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vitale audio chat will be watched carefully to see if other
audio chats can be produced, Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this gets to be such a production, we'll need to take that
into consideration; at the same time, you want to get the
(traffic),'' Bishop said. ``I'll doubt that you 'll see this become
the standard.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR THOSE WHO PLAN AHEAD ...: Fans of the National Finals Rodeo
better hold off awhile if they're planning to conceive a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Using its handy due-date function, the Baby Center
(www.babycenter.com/conflicts) can calculate what major sporting
events can be missed for parents-to-be. For example, if a couple
plans to conceive this week, they face the chance of missing the
NFR, which is scheduled Dec. 3-12 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The site lists 3,000 sporting events that could be missed as the
result of a conception within a particular time frame. Also listed
are handy directions to the hospital from your favorite sporting
event.
</P>
<P>
   The due-date calculator includes a disclaimer, stating only 5
percent of births occur on the due date.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO CHECK: Good news for March Madness fans confined to their
office cubicles: Broadcast.com is providing live audio coverage of
every NCAA men's and women's basketball tournament game.
Broadcast.com apparently believes it has the demographics for this.
In a news release, the Dallas multimedia company pointed out that
99 percent of the business professional respondents in a recent
study it commissioned have personal computers on their desks at
work, 32 percent have radios and 9 percent have televisions on
their desks.
</P>
<P>
   POLL OF THE WEEK: Try MSNBCSports.com's (www.msnbcsports.com)
50-Game Finish Line, which is polling users on who they think will
win the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
