<HEADLINE>
ALLIED WASTE BUYS BFI IN MEGADEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Allied Waste Industries Inc., a Scottsdale
garbage company whose Harley-riding executives have been on a
non-stop buying spree, bagged its biggest deal yet Monday when it
announced a $9 billion acquisition of larger rival Browning-Ferris
Industries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, which will be based in Scottsdale, will be
the second-largest waste-management firm in the country and will
probably steal the crown as Arizona's largest public company from
Avnet Inc. Allied Waste and BFI together have sales of about $6.6
billion; Avnet's sales totaled $5.9 billion last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Waste also will become Arizona's fourth ``Fortune'' 500
company, ranking in the top half of the annual list.
Browning-Ferris on its own was No. 273 on the 1998 list.
</P>
<P>
   The blockbuster deal, heavily rumored last summer, was cinched
early Monday in New York after a weekend of negotiations and board
meetings, Allied Waste Chief Executive Officer Tom Van Weelden
said. Allied Waste initiated the talks five weeks ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Waste will pay $45 a share in cash for each share of BFI
stock, or $7.3 billion, plus assume $1.8 billion in debt, valuing
the deal at approximately $9.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That dwarfs the proposed buyout of America West Airlines, which
had a price tag of about $1 billion, and ranks as one of the
largest transactions in Arizona business history.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood Hotel's $14.6 billion purchase of ITT Sheraton last
year was bigger, but the company was managed out of New York and
soon moved its headquarters there. Excluding that deal, the only
thing close to Allied Waste's deal was Eli Lilly's $4 billion
purchase of PCS Health Systems Inc. in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   BFI's stock rose $4.50 on the news, to $38.88. Allied Waste's
stock, which fell $5 a share Friday, rose $1.94, to $16.94.
</P>
<P>
   Van Weelden called the pairing ``an almost perfect marriage,''
noting that the two companies only overlap in 20 to 25 markets
across North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you find is a very complementary mix and not an
anti-competitive mix,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In markets where there is overlap, Van Weelden said the company
will have to sell operations due to antitrust concerns. Analysts
cite Chicago, Atlanta and Southern California as among the areas
likely to see divestitures.
</P>
<P>
   There is virtually no overlap in Arizona, as BFI's only
operation is a landfill in La Paz County.
</P>
<P>
   BFI's familiar blue trucks used to pick up garbage in the state
but those operations were bought last year by USA Waste, which then
turned around and acquired Waste Management. The combined company,
which took the Waste Management name, is No. 1 in the industry with
about $12 billion in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Waste also likely will sell some of BFI's non-solid-waste
businesses. Altogether, the sales and divestitures are expected to
raise $900 million next year, which will be used to pay down Allied
Waste's hefty debt load from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts like the transaction, which must be approved by the
U.S. Justice Department and other regulators, as well as BFI
shareholders. They say Allied Waste is a young, nimble, efficient
company with a good track record of getting the most out of
companies it acquires.
</P>
<P>
   BFI, in contrast, has a bigger bureaucracy and has struggled to
cut costs in recent years to stay competitive. At the same time, it
has a well-known name and nationwide network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allied is acquiring a poorly managed, underperforming company
with good market positions and strong assets,'' Cotton Swindell of
BT Alex Brown Inc. said in a report Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He maintained his buy rating on Allied Waste's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Oline, a vice president with Duff &AMP; Phelps Credit Rating in
Chicago, said there's much to be gained in a merger of two garbage
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The larger Allied Waste will instantly have more landfills. That
means drivers won't have to truck garbage as far as in the past in
certain markets, saving lots of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you want to do is have your trucks on the street picking
up the garbage, not driving around,'' Oline said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Weelden puts it this way: ``This is truly a business where
two and two make five.''
</P>
<P>
   Oline said Allied Waste's bigger debt load is a concern, as the
company already was more leveraged than the average company in the
industry. But he notes that BFI's debt level was relatively light,
and that Allied Waste can use its substantial cash flow as well as
asset sales to reduce the acquisition debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has some flexibility to pay it down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Weelden and Allied Waste's other top executives will run the
combined company. There will be job losses, most significantly in
BFI's home base of Houston since the headquarters are going away,
but Van Weelden wouldn't provide any estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a transaction that will take over a year after it
closes to transfer all of the moves across from one company to
another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Weelden did say it's not a given that all the BFI office
jobs retained will be based in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is not the cheapest job market in the country,'' he
said, adding that Houston has a lower cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which was unanimously approved by each company's board
of directors, is expected to close in the fall. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Dawn Gilbertson can be reached at dawn.gilbertson &LR; pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
