<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASTE GIANTS THRIVE IN SLOW-GROWTH INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Thomas Van Weelden, the head of Allied Waste
Industries Inc., once told a joke about why it's hard to retain
upwardly mobile managers in the solid-waste business.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys come in, spend six months learning everything
there is to know about the garbage business, then want to know
what's next,'' said Van Weelden, the company's president, chairman
and chief executive officer. ``There is nothing next. You just go
back out and get more garbage collected.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the Internet and other revolutionary businesses,
there's nothing exciting about solid waste. The industry is about
as basic as they come, and investors have turned their attention
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Waste-management stocks rose just 8.7 percent on average last
year, compared with 26.7 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index. They also had been lagging in 1999 before Monday's
announcement that Allied Waste would purchase rival Browning Ferris
Industries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mature business,'' said Stewart Scharf, a stock analyst
for Standard &AMP; Poor's. The garbage industry in recent years has
been marked by low volume growth and weak pricing, he said, with
profit margins squeezed by increasingly stringent government
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Internal growth has averaged less than 5 percent a year, added
David Cohen, an analyst for Value Line in New York. He terms the
industry's overall prospects as ``lackluster.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Allied Waste and a few other firms have thrived, partly by
using their size and managerial skills to acquire and integrate
smaller operations. The Scottsdale company completed 14 purchases
in 1998's fourth quarter alone. Small, private operators haul
roughly 30 percent of the nation's trash, and these companies are
finding it increasingly difficult to compete against the giants.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions enable a surviving company to eliminate certain
trash-hauling routes, mothball trucks, reduce administrative staffs
and realize other ``synergies,'' said Linda Bolton Weiser, who
manages the Alliance Global Environment Fund in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Privatizations also present opportunities for well-positioned
firms such as Allied Waste. Municipalities collect and dump roughly
one-third of the nation's trash, yet many cities and counties would
rather turn these tasks over to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton Weiser is optimistic about investing in solid-waste
stocks. She said pricing for garbage-collection services has
started to increase, partly because few landfills are being built
and partly because a recent wave of mergers has reduced competition
among big players.
</P>
<P>
   Other blockbuster deals in recent months have included Waste
Management's merger with USA Waste Services and Safety-Kleen's
combination with Laidlaw Environmental. The Waste Management-USA
Waste deal, which closed in July, has resulted in noticeable
cost-cutting, Bolton Weiser said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen cites Allied Waste and Waste Management as two firms that
have been able to boost their profit margins over the past five
years thanks to efficiencies that result from acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   As a further lure, the solid-waste business is relatively immune
to economic cycles _ a factor that may make the stocks attractive
among recession-wary investors.
</P>
<P>
   In today's low-inflation environment, Bolton Weiser said,
``There are few industries with a positive pricing trend, but this
is one of them.'' &QL; 
(Russ Wiles can be reached at russ.wiles(at)pni.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
