<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     03-09 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
JOLTIN' Joe has left and gone away.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A wave of Joe DiMaggio obituaries had been prepared months ago,
after his surgery for lung cancer, when he rallied from one crisis
after another. He had been given the last rites two or three times.
When he awoke from a coma, his first words were to tell his doctor
to quit releasing bulletins to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Those tales of his death were premature. But he slipped away
early Monday, at 84, with the dignity and privacy that were so much
a part of his persona. Contrary to the words of the poet Dylan
Thomas, he did go ``gentle into that good night.'' He had defied
time and death longer than anyone expected, and we had been well
warned. Still, the news saddened us. It was a loss not only to
baseball but to an America that once was and will never be again.
</P>
<P>
   He was the last custodian of the tradition the New York Yankees
created in the 1920s, the Babe Ruth era. When he retired after the
1951 World Series, he said simply, ``I'm not Joe DiMaggio
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew what he meant, but he could not have been more
wrong. No one in sports, and maybe anywhere, was more consistent,
more certain of who he was, more faithful to his legend or his
fans.
</P>
<P>
   I once collaborated with DiMaggio on a photo layout for a sports
magazine. He picked his five favorite New York restaurants, and the
headline read: ``A Great Night at the Plate After a Great Day at
the Plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Few athletes of this century had more great days than the Yankee
Clipper, whose 56-game hitting streak in 1941 electrified the
country and remains the Mona Lisa of vintage baseball records.
</P>
<P>
   I remember meeting Joe DiMaggio in the parking garage of the
Shamrock Hilton Hotel, after a baseball dinner, many years after
his heroic career had ended. A friend turned to introduce him to a
group of us and discovered that Joe had slipped behind a pillar,
hoping he would not be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Then he walked over, ducking his head and grinning, as if to
acknowledge we had caught him fair and square. He shook hands and
made polite small talk until the cars came.
</P>
<P>
   On another night, he was in Houston for an old-timers game at
the Astrodome, and a young artist recruited me to ask if Joe would
autograph a portrait she had sketched from a photograph. He did not
consider it an imposition. I regretted not getting his signature
for myself.
</P>
<P>
   These are thin memories, but I cling to them because I never saw
Joe DiMaggio play, except on the black-and-white film clips that
showed him at bat, striding into a pitch, the stance always wide,
or catching a fly ball over his shoulder. In my imagination, he is
always tall and lean and full of grace, which means I saw him play,
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The closest I came to knowing DiMaggio was in co-authoring a
book with Mickey Mantle, who played one season with Joe, succeeded
him in center field and knew him very little.
</P>
<P>
   Mantle called him ``the best all-around player in history. My
locker was next to his, but I thought it would be out of line for
me to speak to him first. As a result, we hardly spoke the entire
season. I should have asked Joe to help me in some way. I think he
would have liked that, and we might have become friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mick admired him greatly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing not to like about Joe,'' he said. ``He
wouldn't let just anybody get close to him, and after a certain
time in my career, I understood that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantle could not picture strangers coming up to Joe D., as they
did to Mick, draping an arm around his shoulder and spilling beer
in his lap. Mantle, who lived faster and harder, died of cancer in
1994, at 63.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio could be distant and austere, but he was a man of
honor, unforgiving of conduct he regarded as crude, cheap or below
the belt.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1947 World Series, Jackie Robinson of the Dodgers went
out of the baseline to throw a rolling block into the Yankees'
shortstop, Phil Rizzuto, who was turning a double play. There was
some booing, and then the inning was over. Later in the game,
DiMaggio ran out a routine ground ball, and Robinson, who was
playing first base and not very experienced at it, had his foot
planted on the bag. It was almost an invitation to a spiking, but
Joe swerved as he crossed the bag and avoided him.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, a New York writer asked Joe why he hadn't
retaliated after what Jackie had done to Rizzuto. DiMaggio
considered the question for a moment and said, ``I thought about it
running down to first base. Then it occurred to me that Phil's an
Italian, I'm an Italian, and Robinson is black. I didn't want
anyone to think it was (racial). If Jackie was an Italian, I guess
I would have spiked him.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to recite Joe's numbers. His greatness was
established long ago. But his class can't be reduced to math. When
Chuck Dressen was a Yankees coach, he once protested an umpire's
call by flinging towels out of the dugout. Joe was at his side
instantly. ``Go out and pick up that stuff now,'' he ordered. ``On
this ballclub, when we don't like decisions, we don't throw things.
We hit home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, DiMaggio was more open and accessible. Like
a lot of men when they pass 60, Joe began to enjoy some of the
attention he had avoided for so many years. He decided it was a
nice thing to walk into a restaurant and have the customers give
you a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The fans always understood there was not going to be another era
like his, when he led the Yankees to the World Series 10 times,
winning on nine occasions. There isn't going to be another Joe
DiMaggio. In that sense, he hasn't gone away after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 0018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
