<HEADER>
A2847 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FARNHAM-LADN-(SLA     03-09 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FARNHAM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S FARNHAM IS MORE THAN JUST A `RUDY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA walk-on Sean Farnham likes ``Rudy,'' the
movie about a Notre Dame student who fulfills his dream by playing
football for the Irish. Farnham owns a copy of the film and he
watched it over Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   However, he does not like Rudy, the comparison. In fact, he
hates it. He's seen Rudy and he's no Rudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed his ability to persist in situations far more
challenging than I've seen at UCLA,'' said Farnham, a junior
forward. ``But he played for one play his senior year _ that's the
only time he suited up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear (the comparison) a lot and it frustrates me. In the
movie, the whole team tells the coach they won't suit up unless
Rudy plays. That didn't happen here. No one had to ask coach (Steve
Lavin) to let me play. Comparing me to Rudy makes it seem like I
don't deserve to be out there, like it's charity or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnham, a native of Clayton, Calif., was a recruited walk-on in
1996 _ meaning the Bruins suspected he could contribute but weren't
impressed enough to offer a scholarship. He played sparingly for
two years but has scurried up the depth chart this season with
solid play and high spirits. That's where his story and Rudy's tale
diverge: Farnham has earned his minutes, and without injured center
Dan Gadzuric, the Bruins need him: they're 6-0 in games he's
started.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-5 power forward, Farnham specializes in passing,
setting screens, defense and rebounding. He runs the floor well and
he's UCLA's most fundamentally sound player. Unlike his more gifted
teammates, Farnham does not attempt what he cannot accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   He'd have been perfect for Gene Hackman's team in ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a throw-back player,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said.
``He plays the game the way it was played in the 1950s and '60s. He
understands his strengths and weaknesses and plays within himself.
He doesn't do anything outside his capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnham is smaller but more talented than Bob Myers, the former
walk-on who played sparingly from 1994-97. Farnham started every
game for his final 2{ years at Concord De La Salle High, which
produced the Barry brothers, Jon and Brent, but is better known as
a football powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   His watershed game came in the 1996 state playoffs against
Crenshaw, when Lavin, an assistant at the time, watched him score
22 points and grab seven rebounds. The next day, ex-UCLA coach Jim
Harrick called. It didn't take much for Farnham to shun the Big Sky
scholarship offers _ he planned to sign with Montana _ and join the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Because of personnel shortages, UCLA gave Farnham a scholarship
for two years. But last summer, when Lavin secured his second big
recruiting class and the roster expanded, Farnham's conditional
free ride was withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was tough to swallow,'' he said. ``It made me question
whether there would be an opportunity for me here. It would have
been easy to sulk with all those freshmen coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Farnham spent the summer lifting weights and jumping
rope. He reported for practice 15 pounds heavier and a step
quicker. He started the Arizona game, figuring that was his 15
minutes, then returned to the end of the bench. When he played 11
enthusiastic minutes in the lethargic loss at Cal, Lavin annointed
him a starter. He stayed in the lineup for five games.
</P>
<P>
   With 146 minutes and 30 points this season, Farnham has tripled
and doubled his career totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's living a dream,'' said UCLA sophomore Todd Ramasar,
Farnham's closest friend. ``He's always been excitable, but he's
even more excited now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he was recognized in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a Costco and the checkout guy asked, `Are you Sean
Farnham? Well, good job,' '' Farnham said with a grin. ``I thought,
`Wow, the guy recognized me.' Then two older people tapped me on
the shoulder and said, `We're season-ticket holders and we love the
way you play.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my freshman year, and everybody recognized Toby
(Bailey) and Charles (O'Bannon). Now they're starting to notice
that Sean Farnham plays for UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rudy doesn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
