<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOE-AZR &LR;      03-09 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO BROUGHT GRACE TO LIFE, SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ I have seen him on the TV screen a thousand times: the
same clip they always show, Joe DiMaggio in grainy black and white
cruising in broad stride from deep center into shallow right,
cutting off the parallax of a baseball with his outstretched glove.
</P>
<P>
   What is so riveting about that bit of film is what is so
riveting about DiMaggio. Like the mathematically prescribed arc of
the batted ball, he seemed to move as a force of physics. DiMaggio
and the ball might as well have been the paths of two mesons
colliding in a cloud chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Others might gallop, or rumble or lumber in the field. Babe Ruth
had his famous mincing trot. But DiMaggio moved as effortlessly and
surely as a cat, showing neither effort, nor calculation nor the
constraining weight of human flesh.
</P>
<P>
   He was just as smooth at the plate. With his wide stance and the
controlled torsion of his swing, he stood after hitting the ball
with his straight left leg and beaky nose pointed in tandem to the
place the ball was headed, and his right leg bent behind him and
the bat wrapped around his back. It was a perfect swing he
possessed, and as effortless as his fielding, his base-running and
his rare but toothy smile.
</P>
<P>
   But while he was certainly one of the handful of greatest
players of all times _ in 1969, on the centennial of professional
baseball, a poll of sportswriters named DiMaggio the greatest ever
_ there were other ballplayers with swings nearly as sweet and
other outfielders who amazed the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   What made DiMaggio important, not just on the ball field, but
for the rest of his long life, 47 years after he retired from the
game, was that he carried himself, on and off the field, with such
dignity and grace that he transcended the sport.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to imagine now, when nearly all professional
athletes seem to be spoiled crybabies, grabbing for money, looking
to build up their personal statistics and yelling ``throw me the
damn ball,'' but DiMaggio always acted as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that he couldn't be emotional. There are two or three
episodes recorded where he showed his feelings. Once when Dodger
outfielder Al Gionfriddo caught what should have been a DiMaggio
home run in the 1947 World Series, DiMaggio kicked the dirt in
front of second base in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   More profoundly, he could be seen barely containing his tears at
the funeral of his second wife, Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   But what made those moments seem mythically important was that
he didn't cheapen them by supplying too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   He was as under control as a Greek or Roman epic hero, and
always true to himself. And, as a Hector or Aeneas, he spoke to
something in each of us, some person we would wish we could be.
</P>
<P>
   Each of us finds in ourselves some shortcoming, a moment we
blurted out what should have remained unsaid, a time we acted
selfishly when we should have given in, a time we were lazy at just
the moment some extra exertion would have brought us success.
</P>
<P>
   We always want to think those are exceptions, that our real
selves are found in the noble gestures we are capable of at our
peak moments.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us are fragmented personalities bagged in a single
skin.
</P>
<P>
   But DiMaggio always seemed to be of a piece. On or off the
field, his life was equally as dignified. He managed, by choice or
genes, to be a unified personality, and thus seemed to transcend
the vicissitudes of human frailty.
</P>
<P>
   Even his baseball career is marked by its consistency.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Yankees two years after Babe Ruth retired, and his
last season was also Mickey Mantle's first, so he spanned the
middle period of the Yankees' incredible four-decade dominance of
major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   During his 13 years, the Yankees won 10 pennants and nine World
Series titles. He was named league MVP three times _ a feat never
surpassed _ compiled a career batting average of .325, won two
batting titles and topped 100 RBIs nine times.
</P>
<P>
   He won the home run title twice and logged in 361 dingers for
his career, matched to only 369 strikeouts, a ratio unheard of
among sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest record is also the most difficult measure of
consistent play. He hit successfully in 56 consecutive games, from
May 15 through July 16, 1941. No one else among the 15,000 men who
have played major league baseball even comes close: Second place is
12 games behind.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody recalls that after that hitless 57th game,
DiMaggio went on another tear of 16 games, making 72 games out of
73 with at least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   And not everybody recalls that DiMaggio had an earlier streak of
61 consecutive games with a hit, in 1933, when he played for the
Seals.
</P>
<P>
   It is that kind of consistency as a player that made DiMaggio
special.
</P>
<P>
   During the 56-game streak, he batted .408, scored 56 runs and
drove in another 55, accounting for an average of just under two
runs per game. The Yankees won 41 of those games.
</P>
<P>
   But these are merely statistics, and as Jimmy Breslin once said,
``Baseball isn't statistics, it's Joe DiMaggio rounding second
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Or playing center field.
</P>
<P>
   As Yankee teammate Phil Rizzuto once said, ``He'd just be there.
You'd turn your head as a screeching line drive would be headed
toward the alley between left and center and you knew, you just
knew from years of experience, that it was going to the wall. By
the time your head turned all the way around to follow, Joe would
be there, just waiting for it, like you'd wait for a bus. I don't
know how he got there, but he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio wasn't perfect; he had faults. He sometimes seemed
surly to teammates and sportswriters, although it was just as
likely that he was exhibiting painful shyness. Both his marriages
ended in divorce for the same reason: DiMaggio's old-fashioned view
of women and their role. It is hard to imagine him expecting Monroe
to stay home and saute the pork chops, but that was, indeed, his
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   But, no matter how out of date his expectations were, they were
consistent. His insistence on his public dignity came from the same
Old World view of life.
</P>
<P>
   It must have taken that secure view of the world to allow him to
shill for the Bowery Savings Bank and Mr. Coffee and never seem
goofy. He dripped elegance and always had: In 1940 he was named one
of the 10 best-dressed men in America.
</P>
<P>
   Many words have been used to describe DiMaggio. He has been
called elegant, and he was. It was said he had class, and he did,
although the word was most often mouthed by those who recognized
they didn't have it. And he has been called graceful.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it is this last that most accurately hits the mark. Joe
DiMaggio was touched by grace, that ineffable quality that descends
upon a select few, like a bit of divinity, and makes them burn just
a little more intensely and move with just a certain bit of
detachment from the world, as though they were in it but not of it.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix lawyer Curtis Beckman remembers seeing DiMaggio play in
Phoenix in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Del Webb made a deal with New York Giants owner
Horace Stoneham to trade spring training sites. They played at the
old stadium on Central and Mohave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a 9-year-old boy and had started to like baseball, but
hadn't chosen a team to root for,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was DiMaggio's last year and there were so many people at the
spring training games that they put a rope up in center field so
that the excess crowd could sit in the far outfield grass and the
game could be played inside the rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember making my mind up about which team I was going to
be a fan of,'' Beckman recalls. ``I became a Yankee fan when Joe
DiMaggio was playing center field in front of me and glided across
the grass to catch a fly ball hit from Al Rosen. I could see the
No. 5 on his back. He became my hero then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most beautiful thing I had ever seen in my life.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 0021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
