<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-MAPLELEAF     03-09 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DEFEAT MAPLE LEAFS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Playing against a top team that attacks with speed
and style, the Rangers could have been overwhelmed last night at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They stood almost flat-footed in the early minutes while Toronto
zipped around them and scored twice within a minute to take a
two-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
   Last season's Rangers _ and even the Rangers of early this
season _ might have meekly allowed their undefeated streak to end
at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for this team, not now. New York scored once late in the
first period to keep it close, once in the third to tie it and once
in overtime with 13.7 seconds remaining for a 3-2 victory that
ended with fans cheering as loudly as they have in two seasons as
players swarmed in celebration under flashing spotlights.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring the last two goals was Petr Nedved, who played with a
bloody cut stitched over his left eye and the big letter ``A'' of
the alternate captain stitched over his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved wore the letter for the first time as a Ranger because
Ulf Samuelsson (concussion) was the latest player to leave the
lineup with a serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also announced late in the game that Wayne Gretzky
will have a cortisone shot in the next 48 hours and will be
re-examined about a week after the injection.
</P>
<P>
   Minus Gretzky, the Rangers have turned to Nedved. His goals were
set up by Brian Leetch, the captain, who also set up the first one
by Kevin Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Although many in the Ranger locker room praised Nedved, it was
Nedved who praised Leetch for sparking the Rangers to a six-game
undefeated streak, the last three of them victories.
</P>
<P>
   In raising their record to .500, the Rangers also tied the
Boston Bruins for the eighth and final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   With 18 games to play, the Rangers have 64 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have played one more game than both the Bruins and
the Florida Panthers, who have 63 points.
</P>
<P>
   The tie extended the Rangers' undefeated streak to six games,
4-0-2. They are 7-2-2 in their last 11, their best stretch of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feel great,'' Nedved said, referring to the playoff
position in the final stretch of the regular season. ``We have to
keep winning. It's a lot more fun. Before, we were afraid to make a
mistake. Now, the guys feel a lot looser.''
</P>
<P>
   They also seem more calm and less inclined to weaken under
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch said: ``You don't feel as tired or sore when you're
winning. It's all in front of us.'' He also praised Mike Richter,
who stopped 24 of 26 shots,
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike saves you,'' Leetch said. ``Instead of being down 3 or 4
to nothing, you stay within striking distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Leetch played 30 minutes 35 seconds and he put five shots on
goalie Glenn Healy.
</P>
<P>
   He frequently joined the attack and did not get discouraged when
his turnover in the first period accidentally set up Toronto's
first goal by Mike Johnson at 12:29. Toronto's Derek King scored 44
seconds later, but Stevens brought the Rangers back to 2-1 at 14:41
of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers gradually took control of the game by driving hard
to the net and controlling the puck in the Toronto zone.
</P>
<P>
   They finished with 35 shots on goal, the last of them on the
power play in overtime after Toronto's Lonny Bohonos was sent off
for boarding at 3:10 of the extra session.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Toronto Coach Pat Quinn yelled at the referee,
Paul Devorski, and threw a towel on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   On the Rangers' side, Coach John Muckler was in a better mood.
``It's like a snowball rolling down a hill,'' he said.``It's
getting getting bigger and bigger and bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs, who missed the playoffs last season, are one of
the best teams in the Eastern Conference this season and one of the
most entertaining in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   They came into the game with a league-best 201 goals-scored and
they added two in a 44-second span of the first period to lead,
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Play leveled out in the scoreless second period and the Rangers
still trailed by just a goal as the third period began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
