<HEADLINE>
TROJANS COME CLEAN, BID WAS A SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF and CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Not everyone was so sure after all that USC would
receive a bid to the National Invitation Tournament. Sophomore
guard Jeff Trepagnier was among those willing to admit he was
stunned when the Trojans (15-12) received a bid to play Wyoming
(17-9) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised,'' Trepagnier said. ``Cal had lost and
that meant we dropped to seventh place in the Pac-10, so I was kind
of doubtful.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the shock is over, Trepagnier is confident the Trojans
can actually win the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure we can go pretty far in this tournament,'' he said.
``We all want to go to New York, so we'll play extra hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier isn't the only Trojan with high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play the way we're capable of playing, I know we can win
the whole thing,'' freshman forward David Bluthenthal added.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough loss:The first postseason men's basketball appearance
for Pepperdine in five years might be dampened by the loss of one
of the Waves' key players.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore forward Kelvin Gibbs, an honorable mention All-West
Coast Conference selection, has a swollen knee and is doubtful for
the Waves' first-round game Wednesday at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like (Gibbs) will play,'' head coach Lorenzo
Romar said. ``He can barely walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs has an infection in the knee. He was healthy in the WCC
Tournament two weeks ago when he was the Waves' top scorer and
rebounder, averaging 16.5 points and 9.5 rebounds in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Marc McDowell, Pepperdine's standout sixth man, probably moves
into the starting lineup if Gibbs can't play.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Gibbs hobbling, Romar said he was ``ecstatic'' when he
found out the Waves had been invited to the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three years, we've made it to the NIT,'' he said, referring
to the Waves' 6-21 record in 1996-97. ``We've come further than a
lot of people have in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Time change: Wednesday's USC game against Wyoming has been
changed to 6:08 p.m. (PST), instead of 6:30.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lobbying effort: USC is working on NIT officials to let the
Trojans host a second-round game if they defeat Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unlikely considering their next opponent will be Oregon
or Georgia Tech. USC averaged 3,801 per game this year, while
Oregon averaged 8,158.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
