<SLUG> BC-ROAD-RAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. IN MIDDLE OF ROAD IN AGGRESSIVE DRIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN and YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gridlocked roads upset and frustrate but don't
necessarily lead to rage _ which is why Los Angeles ranked just
15th out of 37 urban areas for deaths caused by aggressive driving,
according to a study.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that deaths due to aggressive driving occurred
most often in spread-out, car-bound areas _ first among them San
Bernardino and Riverside counties _ where roads are gridlocked, but
not always.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sprawling, suburban-style communities like those we live
in have the highest rates, because people have to drive everywhere
and feel trapped behind the wheel,'' said Gloria Ohland, Southern
California project director for the Surface Transportation Policy
Project, a nonprofit think tank that released the study Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list is the San Bernardino-Riverside area,
with 13.4 deaths per 100,000 people, or 178 deaths in 1996.
Tampa-St. Petersburg, Fla., took second, followed by Phoenix,
Ariz.; Orlando, Fla.; and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles ranked 15th, with 728 aggressive driving deaths _
the largest overall number _ but that equaled just six deaths per
100,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the best metropolitan area was Boston, despite its
reputation for bad drivers. It had only 2.1 aggressive driving
deaths per 100,000 people, according to the Los Angeles-based
group, backed by 200 environmental groups including several Sierra
Club chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' results surprised some, among them Granada Hills
resident Mona Galindo, who nearly was killed when an aggressive
driver ran a red light in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I would say, you see it in some form or another,''
said Galindo, 27, as she pumped gas at a Los Angeles service
station near her job. ``There are people cutting in and out of
lanes, people turning in front of you, running yellow lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles still ranked higher than other densely populated
cities such as Chicago, Boston and New York, &UR;  &LR; according to the
study, which is based on analysis of federal and state statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Faul, director of communications for the American
Automobile Association Foundation for Traffic Safety, said the
study's conclusions do not square with other studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the exact opposite of the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration study last year, that found the Northeast to
be the highest in unsafe driving behaviors,'' Faul said.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Policy Project study did not examine
road rage, in which motorists react violently to others. Instead,
the study focused on aggressive or dangerous driving practices that
result in fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Those include speeding over 80 mph, tail-gating, failing to
yield, weaving in and out of traffic, passing on the right, making
unsafe lane changes and running stop signs and red lights. The
study estimates 56 percent of highway deaths in 1996 involved
aggressive driving.
</P>
<P>
   It took a close call to cure Galindo of her penchant for
aggressive driving, she said. Recently she was waiting at stoplight
but was glancing down and did not realize the light had turned
green. She was about to pull forward when a driver ran the opposing
red light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drive more aggressively, but now it's just too
dangerous,'' said Galindo, a workers' compensation claims
assistant. ``Now I get up early to go to work so I'm not in a rush.
I try to stay at the speed limit, I watch everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution for aggressive driving is not to build more roads,
the study said. The 17 states with the highest aggressive driving
death rates, it pointed out, have more than twice the lane miles
per person than states with lower death rates.
</P>
<P>
   And areas with lower congestion have higher death rates, the
study found. That might be because congestion reduces speed _ a key
element in fatal collisions.
</P>
<P>
   But Faul took issue with that explanation as well, saying
congestion might reduce speed, but not collisions and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ohland agreed, saying the study was unable to measure aggressive
driving crashes because there are no federal statistics on that
issue available.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if there were, we think L.A. would show up higher,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   While previous examinations of aggressive driving have focused
on changing drivers' behavior, Ohland said this was the first to
identify factors in the driving environment that contribute to the
problem. Long commutes increase the length of exposure to crashes
and pump up stress that leads to reckless driving, she suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, the study suggests, is not improving highways, but
reducing their use. So the answer, Ohland said, is building
mixed-use communities where work, home, schools and shops are close
enough for a short drive _ or a walk or bike ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really believe that we need to plan communities so as to
reduce the need to drive,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
