<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN DETROIT KEEP UCLA IN FIRST GEAR?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins can't seem to escape Miami. A year
ago, they repelled the Hurricanes in the final seconds of a
first-round NCAA Tournament game. Three months ago, UCLA lost a
fairly significant football game to the Hurricanes. And this week,
the Bruins play Miami again in the tournament's first round.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost.
</P>
<P>
   The opponent will be Detroit when the teams collide Thursday in
the RCA Dome in Indianapolis, but the pace and style, the tenacity
and tempo, will remind UCLA of last year's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very similar to Miami,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for this: Detroit's better.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins needed four free throws in the final 25 seconds to
banish the Hurricanes. If they aren't careful this week _ i.e.: if
they don't correct the mistakes from their 17-point loss at Arizona
_ they'll become the 17th No. 5 seed to lose in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be one of the more exciting games to watch,''
UCLA guard Baron Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans (24-5) aren't frantically reviewing videotape,
reconfiguring their strategy or studying the blueprint to beat UCLA
in March. They !ital!are the blueprint _ just like Princeton and
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   They play in first gear, with smothering defense and a patient
offense that will force UCLA to defend for 25-30 seconds per
possession. They will not take bad shots and they will not get
lulled into the speedy tempo UCLA adores. In recent years, that
combination has been a shock to UCLA's postseason system.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Titans, who received an automatic berth as
champion of the Midwestern Collegiate Conference, have made no
attempt to disguise their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA is a West Coast team that likes to get out and run,''
Detroit forward Bacari Alexander said. ``We'll see if we can slow
them down.''
</P>
<P>
   They have the ingredients and experience to do it. The Titans
defeated Gonzaga in December and played Iowa to a one-point game in
Iowa City. They have two seniors and two juniors in the starting
lineup. They are tall, with 6-foot-11 center Walter Craft, and
tough. They have a future pro in senior guard Jermaine Jackson.
They have tournament experience, bouncing St. John's in the first
round last year, and are not happy just to be involved.
</P>
<P>
   They expect to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well against all kinds of style,'' said Detroit's
sixth-year coach, Perry Watson, an assistant at Michigan during the
Fab Five years. ``We've got confidence in ourselves . . . and we've
been playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   To survive, UCLA must earn every point it scores. Just as Miami
coach Leonard Hamilton emphasized straightjacket defense, so does
Watson. The Titans ranked among the nation's leaders all season,
holding opponents to 64 points and 37 percent shooting. During
Detroit's current seven-game winning streak, opponents are shooting
34.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins execute their offense as poorly as they did
Saturday at Arizona, they'll be home Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word is out that Detroit is a solid team, but when a
smaller school plays a bigger school, the smaller school always has
something to prove,'' Titans guard Rashad Phillips said. ``They're
offensive minded and we're defensive minded. Something will have to
give.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
