<HEADLINE>
PETROFF TO HANDLE PAPERWORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's been a shakeup on the USC football
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant head coach Larry Petroff will no longer coach the
tight ends and will only handle administrative matters. Petroff
will not be considered an on-field coach, and USC coach Paul
Hackett said he intends to hire another assistant to coach tight
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' Hackett said Monday. ``I
haven't ruled out Larry coaching for the spring, but I'm going to
look at my options. I'm going to interview and bring in a number of
different guys. In the fall, we'll definitely have a (new)
tight-ends coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett already contacted Brian Schottenheimer, the son of
former Kansas City Chiefs coach Marty Schottenheimer about the
opening. But Brian Schottenheimer recently accepted a job as
wide-receivers coach with Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   A seemingly natural candidate would be former California
offensive coordinator Doug Cosbie, a former Dallas Cowboys tight
end who played under Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be a candidate for this job,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to sources, it's unlikely Cosbie will be
offered the position.
</P>
<P>
   No other changes are expected on the USC coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   __ Positions change: Sophomore tight end Lonnie Ford has moved
to outside linebacker, the first of several possible position
changes for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who played defensive end in high school, decided to make
the switch after thinking about the move during the season.
</P>
<P>
   His decision hardly leaves USC thin at tight end. The Trojans
have junior Antoine Harris, redshirt freshman Scott Huber and true
freshmen Chad Cook and Jacob Rogers at the position.
</P>
<P>
   In another change, quarterback John Fox has moved to outside
linebacker. This is another switch for Fox, who decided last August
to play tight end. That experiment did not last, however, and Fox
eventually moved back to quarterback near the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Welch out: Offensive tackle Matt Welch has undergone surgery
on both shoulders and will miss spring practice, though he has
hopes of returning in the fall. Welch hurt his shoulders during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Malaefou MacKenzie, recovering from knee surgery,
will be limited in his action during spring practices. Also
questionable for the spring is wide receiver Stanley Guyness, who
tore knee ligaments near the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Faster offers: If USC changes one thing during recruiting
this year, it will be to offer scholarships faster. This past year,
only Hackett had the authority to offer scholarships, but the coach
said he will now allow other coaches to offer them.
</P>
<P>
   __ Spring-practice dates: The Trojans will open spring practice
March 26 and concludes April 23. There will be a scrimmage, open to
the public, on April 10 at Howard Jones Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
