<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG'S HIP INJURY PLAGUES BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA freshman Ray Young sleeps on his stomach, so
he has not suffered insomnia in recent days. When he sleeps any
other way, however, Young feels the pain of his hip pointer, a
bruised bone on the right side of his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered the injury on a hard fall in the Arizona State game
last week and hasn't played much since: 27 seconds, to be exact.
How the injury responds to treatment will help determine UCLA's
fate in its first-round game against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the doctor and got some medication, but it's still
sore,'' said Young, a reserve guard. ``Any type of bending is
painful. Hopefully, I'll be able to play. It's feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   Young is a valuable commodity in UCLA's post-Dan Gadzuric state,
with the emphasis on speed and pressure defense. Young averages
five points and 16 minutes per game. He is a superb athlete and
solid perimeter defender. And for coach Steve Lavin, he means two
fresh legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just what he brings to the floor,'' Lavin said.
``When we put him in the game JaRon (Rush), Earl (Watson) and Baron
(Davis) are allowed to get some rest. That way, they're more
effective when they're playing. There's been a ripple effect with
Ray's injury in our ability to sustain high levels of energy. The
guys are getting tired.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The numbers don't lie: Looking for two stats to track during
the Detroit game? Try rebounding and assists.
</P>
<P>
   Some of UCLA's most impressive victories (Oklahoma State,
Louisville, Syracuse) have come when it has outrebounded opponents.
Yet against the best teams (Stanford, Kentucky, Arizona, Maryland),
the Bruins lost the battle on the boards, and the game.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, assists correlate to high shooting percentage. Two
weeks ago, UCLA had 24 assists against Washington State and shot
53.1 percent. Against Syracuse the Bruins had 19 assists and shot
57.8 percent. However, when they don't move the ball, the Bruins
don't shoot well. Saturday, they had eight assists and shot 38
percent at Arizona in one of their worst offensive performances of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right there, assists and rebounding,'' Lavin said,
displaying a laminated card with the evidence in big, bold type.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Guard Baron Davis, hobbling with a sprained
middle toe on his right foot, will play with a stabilizing metal
plate in his shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jerome Moiso said his tendinitis-plagued feet are feeling
better than they have in weeks, thanks to the sports cream
recommended to him by a friend. ``It feels so good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four games, UCLA has shot 66.3 percent from the foul
line _ improving its overall free throw percentage to 59.9.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's tipoff is approximately 7:10 p.m. If the Bruins win,
they'll play a second-round game Saturday at about 4:10 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
