<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CAMP RUES PASSING OF DIMAGGIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson met Joe
DiMaggio one winter during a ``hot stove league'' tour, sometimes
sharing a table with the Yankees legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife got to know him, too, and they would discuss how to
grow tomatoes,'' Johnson said. ``My wife got his autograph. (She)
didn't know who he was except for the coffee commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   That got a chuckle out of the dozen or so people around Johnson
on Monday, but the mood was certainly somber.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, as did the rest of the Dodgers, got word of DiMaggio's
death during their bus ride from Dodgertown to Fort Lauderdale
Stadium for their game against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a baseball hero, the whole industry feels a
loss,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``You think more
about him because he lived so close to here.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's death hit baseball's iron man, Cal Ripken Jr.,
particularly hard. DiMaggio, 84, died after a long illness that
included a bout with lung cancer. Ripken's father, Cal Sr., is
battling lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a bond between the younger Ripken and DiMaggio.
When Ripken broke Lou Gehrig's record for most consecutive games
played, it was DiMaggio who represented baseball, and the Yankees,
that night at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fortunate and lucky that at certain times I had the
opportunity to talk baseball with him,'' Ripken said. ``It was a
great honor. I really appreciate the way he spent time with me. I
wish I could have seen him play.''
</P>
<P>
   Although DiMaggio's loss will be felt throughout baseball,
expect New York to grieve much more. When Mickey Mantle died, fans
flocked to Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley played across the Triboro Bridge in
Queens with the Mets during his New York days, yet he understands
what the next few days in New York will be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``He owned New York,'' Hundley said. ``This is devastation. I'm
sure it's going to be a painful night in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers assistant to the general manager Bill Geivett, who
joined the Yankees in 1991 as a scout and minor-league instructor,
said the ``Yankee Clipper'' had an aura about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a mythical figure, even when he was alive,'' Geivett
said. ``You didn't even get into the ex-player thing. It transcends
that. He was one of the best, if not the best, at the time he was
playing, and he seems to have gotten better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 0121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
