<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ncaa-HNS &LR;      03-09 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ncaa-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The guys from Tallahassee insist they are not afraid of the big,
bad dudes from Duke. This unlikely turn of events rose from the
ashes of an 0-10 start, after all, and at some point, miracles
simply become part of the package.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ready or not, the Rattlers of Florida A&AMP;M are heading to
Charlotte. When the smoke cleared Sunday night, they were part of
the NCAA Tournament field of 64, even though they: (a) crash the
bracket with a 12-18 record, (b) have only nine players, (c) had to
beat Howard in a play-in game just to make the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference tournament field and (d) have a Ratings Percentage Index
of 269.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the 15th team in NCAA history to make the
field with a losing record (the previous entries are a collective
0-14, by the way) has no plan for Friday's first-round game against
the nation's No. 1-ranked club. Coach Mickey Clayton already has
pondered the matchup, in fact, coming to at least one inescapable
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can't go into a game with Duke and get off to a
slow start and have just three points after 11 minutes or
something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken, it would seem, like a man who has seen his team in
action and recognizes its considerable limitations. If you are
desperately seeking that Upset Special of the Week, then, perhaps
you would be better off seeking it elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But where? Most of the other Cinderella candidates among the
chosen 64 also appear to have flat feet and a five o'clock shadow.
There may be another Valparaiso out there somewhere _ Valpo itself,
unfortunately, looks like first-round dead meat against Maryland _
but no one is going out of his way to thumb his nose at Goliath
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Winthrop? Not likely. Even at 21-7, the NCAA first-timer looks
like no match for No. 1 Auburn in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-San Antonio? Not against a Connecticut team that seems to
be regaining its early-season form.
</P>
<P>
   Mount St. Mary's? Let's hope venerable coach Jim Phelan enjoyed
win No. 800, because No. 801 isn't coming against Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is to be expected, of course. Nary a 16th seed has
won a first-round game against a No. 1 since the field was expanded
to 64, though the occasional No. 2 or 3 has been known to exit,
red-faced, after one not-so-shining moment.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, though, the potential gems may be found a
little higher in the seedings. A year ago, only one of the four No.
1s (North Carolina) reached the Final Four, and there may be some
troublemakers lurking out there this time as well.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five to watch:
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky: OK, so this is no big secret, but the defending
national champion is seeded just third in the Midwest. The Wildcats
broke out of a late-season slump to run the table in the
Southeastern Conference tournament, and it's never wise to write
off the old king until the great scorekeeper makes it official.
</P>
<P>
   Tubby Smith's team has a shot. After No. 14 New Mexico State, UK
gets up-and-down Kansas in a second-rounder that could leave
Jayhawks coach Roy Williams in tears again.
</P>
<P>
   That most likely sets up another meeting with Utah, with the
'Cats prevailing again in a rematch of last year's title game. It
also would leave the Michigan State-Arizona survivor as the final
obstacle to a fourth consecutive Final Four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas: Nolan Richardson's team came on late, upsetting Auburn
and Kentucky and making it to the SEC final before losing to UK.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks, No. 4 in the West, open with Siena before facing
the UAB-Iowa winner. They would be underHogs against UConn in a
potential West semifinal, certainly, but their aggressive defense
and up-tempo style could cause problems for the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga: The lads from Spokane are the No. 10 seed in the West,
but John Stockton's old school has a chance to rain on a parade or
two before calling it a season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs' first-round matchup is with Minnesota, which
staggered into the Dance after a first-round loss in the Big Ten
tournament. If that one goes well, Gonzaga would likely face No. 2
seed Stanford, a team that has struggled to live up to the
glittering legacy of last year's Final Four run.
</P>
<P>
   Opening play in fan-friendly Seattle won't hurt the Bulldogs,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona: Lute Olson tends to be boom or bust in the Tournament.
His young team could go either way, but the draw could be
favorable.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 4-seeded Wildcats open Midwest play against Oklahoma, a
team that nearly didn't make the cut. The Rhode Island-UNC
Charlotte winner is up next, and each of those expended valuable
energy in conference tournaments in order to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Win two, and a likely regional semifinal against Michigan State
could get interesting, offering a matchup between gifted guards
Jason Terry and Mateen Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington: Tom Penders, the erstwhile Mr. March, is
blessed once again with a first-round matchup ripe with
possibilities _ Bob Knight and his stumbling Indiana Hoosiers, the
No. 6 seed in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonials, the No. 11 seed, are led by 5-4 Shawnta Rogers,
who has flourished in Penders' free-lance system. Indiana's lack of
inside strength plays into GW's hands, and a second-round game with
St. John's _ coached by Penders' predecessor, Mike Jarvis _ could
be one of the Tournament's more interesting matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Five to avoid:
</P>
<P>
   Stanford: Got to love smart kids who can play. Got to wonder
about the way they've played for too much of this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal, No. 2 in the West, lost just six times but
struggled often. That final-game loss to Oregon State not only cost
Mike Montgomery's team a No. 1 seed but also helped bring
Connecticut to the region. The Huskies dominated Stanford in their
last two meetings, but the Cardinal may not last long enough to see
if the third time is the charm.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State: A No. 4 seed in the South, the Buckeyes' turnaround
from last year's 8-22 record is admirable, but questions linger.
OSU could get caught looking ahead to UCLA in a first-round match
with No. 13 Murray State.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas: An uncharacteristic No. 6 seed in the Midwest, the
Jayhawks just aren't up to snuff, even if they did regroup
sufficiently to win the Big 12 tournament. First-round opponent
Evansville can shoot, and KU is nothing special guarding the
perimeter. Even if Round One goes well, a game against Kentucky
isn't likely to be a pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   Utah: The Utes' unexpected 27-4 season may have merited a No. 2
seed, but Rick Majerus' team had to go to the Midwest to claim it.
Utah can win a few, but the annual loss to Kentucky awaits in the
Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa: The Hawkeyes, playing out the string for deposed coach Tom
Davis, are a No. 5 seed in the West. If they get past
Alabama-Birmingham in the first round, Arkansas should send them
packing in the second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
