<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN-(SL     03-09 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE CLIPPERS DESPERATE TO DEAL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What do you give the team that has everything
going wrong?
</P>
<P>
   You give it a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's trading deadline arrives Thursday, and the vultures
are on the runway. They are prepared to circle the carcass of the
league's only winless team, hoping desperate straits can propel the
0-15 Clippers into a not-so-smooth move.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always the case when you're struggling,'' said Elgin
Baylor, the team's vice president of basketball operations. ``They
feel there is going to be a fire sale.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year Coach Chris Ford, who has been one of the
organization's minds inquiring about potential talent upgrades,
doesn't believe in trading just because the ashes are getting deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to just give things away,'' said Ford, who
offered a few ideas Monday in a three-way phone chat with Baylor
and Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling. ``We can't add problems. We
have to make decisions for the future. If there's something on the
table that will help us, we'll go out and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford also feels better after talking with the man who pays his
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voiced some opinions,'' Ford said of his gab session with
Sterling and Baylor. ``He (Sterling) agreed with some of the things
I said.''
</P>
<P>
   According to team sources, it's agreed that second-year power
forward Maurice Taylor and rookie center Michael Olowokandi will be
staying put. But a few Clippers are in the final year of their
contracts, and could be considered functional role players for
teams involved in the playoff chase. Those with the most value
figure to be forwards Lamond Murray, Lorenzen Wright and Rodney
Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around this league enough to know that quite a few
deals are talked about,'' Ford said, ``but very few happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor seconded that motion, but did admit the Clippers have put
an offer on someone else's table and are waiting for a response.
</P>
<P>
   __ Losing games and patience: Now ... about that streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers haven't won since defeating Sacramento in last
year's season finale. Tonight, they will be visited by the Lakers,
who have won seven in a row, and wouldn't mind tagging their
crosstown cousins with a franchise-tying 16th consecutive setback.
</P>
<P>
   A league-tying 17th consecutive defeat could come Wednesday at
the Forum. Sacramento arrives at the Sports Arena on Thursday,
hoping the Clippers will grab the league record and keep it to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to continue to try finding ways to make things
work,'' Ford said of dealing with the extended losing skid. ``I
certainly think the frustration has grown.''
</P>
<P>
   That goes double for Ford, who believes it's time for the
players to be accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the response from them that is needed for us to
win,'' he said. ``There's not enough self-sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't much second-guessing on Ford's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would be a challenge,'' Ford said of coaching the
Clippers. ``But that's what you live for as a coach - to help make
the situation better. I didn't come here to go through the motions,
for the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   __ `Kandi' almost dandy: Tonight's game will be Olowokandi's
fifth on the injured list, a visit that requires a five-game
minimum. He practiced with the team Monday at Carson and his
left-ankle sprain should have sufficiently healed for him to play
at the Forum on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he plans to start Sherman Douglas, Charles Smith,
Tyrone Nesby, Maurice Taylor and Wright tonight vs. the Lakers.
Their combined salary is less than the $7 million (minus the
pro-rated lockout loss) backup forward Elden Campbell is being paid
by the Lakers this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
