<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-ANALYSIS-AZR &LR;      03-09 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-ANALYSIS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 Charter school accountability critical 
(ANALYSIS) (Third of a three-part series) 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The strength of Arizona's charter school law is also its
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   While state lawmakers gave charters freedom to mold fresh, new
programs, they did little to ensure those programs meet minimum
standards imposed on traditional public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But after four years of experience with charters and because the
stakes have been raised _ 30,000 children now attend publicly
funded, privately run schools _ some are lining up to propose new
restrictions on the freedom.
</P>
<P>
   What charter school history has shown is that even a top charter
school can stumble because the operator has to wear two hats, that
of educator and business person. Sometimes, an operator offers fine
academics but goes under because of financial mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   No one is calling for dumping the schools altogether. Even
critics say charter schools fill a need and that the law needs to
be tweaked, not scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be children who aren't best served by the
traditional system,'' said Sen. Mary Hartley, D-northwest Phoenix,
who has harshly criticized the lack of charter school
accountability. ``I view them as the shining hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of what lawmakers want to do:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask prospective charter operators to submit a business plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stop doling out upfront funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a clearinghouse of charter school information so
parents can make informed decisions about where to send their
children. The best information now available comes from the
Goldwater Institute's Web site _ www.cmbe.org _ and report cards
published by the Arizona Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prevent school districts with financial woes from sponsoring
charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strengthen accounting practices of charters and provide ways
for sponsors to withhold the money of those out of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make districts liable for the schools they charter.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers might also bar districts from chartering outside their
boundaries and cut the length of a charter from 15 years to three
or five. Both measures face an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpened oversight
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say lawmakers should do even more.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, they could sharpen oversight of the charters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, oversight is split between school districts, the Board of
Education, and the state Board for Charter Schools.
</P>
<P>
   No one public body checks up to see if the charters are
accurately reporting how many students are showing up for class, if
the charters are on solid financial ground, or if they are
improving student performance.
</P>
<P>
   Some sponsors keep an eye on these matters, but they aren't
forced to do so by law. And most of them don't have enough staff
members to do a thorough job.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, observers of charter schools say, Department of
Education staff members should be assigned to visit each school
each year, check up on record-keeping, observe classes and meet
with parents.
</P>
<P>
   The department should also determine if schools are meeting the
goals they set, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   State educators tried to do that in 1996. Education Department
employees reported that they found charter schools violating
health, safety and civil rights laws and deviating from their
stated missions. But top department officials later said those
findings were unofficial.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona could look to Colorado, where yearly evaluations are
mandatory. Or Massachusetts, home to an expansive charter law with
stronger accountability.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, charter schools must report on their
operations each August. Then state education officials and citizens
visit each school to check up on it.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping an eye on charter schools doesn't destroy their
independence, critics and advocates both say, even if the schools
are forced to reveal information about their operations, or even
detailed business plans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some observers think first-time charter operators
should have to be trained and made to refresh their skills by
attending periodic seminars.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that charter operators who falter financially
should have to seek out bank loans and grants just like other
small-business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state can't come in and artificially prop up schools,''
said Jaime Molera, Gov. Jane Hull's executive assistant for
education.
</P>
<P>
   But the state does do that, to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools in Arizona may defray start-up costs by applying
for up to $100,000 from a $1 million state stimulus fund each year
for two straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that tempts some operators to play fast and loose
with their operating funds. It allegedly happened at the defunct
Citizen 2000. In the end, the founder was charged with misusing
$179,000 in public money.
</P>
<P>
   When the charter school law was passed five years ago, advocates
of the new schools asserted they would create strikingly successful
programs that could then be implanted in traditional public
schools. But no system is in place to allow that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to letting outside people in to make sure things are
in good shape inside charter schools, the schools should have ways
of showing off the good things they are doing, observers say. For
instance, charter educators could write papers about their
programs, invite district officials for visits and hold statewide
public education conferences each year.
</P>
<P>
   Charter history
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools were envisioned as a catalyst for change, and
they have been.
</P>
<P>
   But it's been a slow change.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, superintendents considered charters an an
inferior &UR; step-sibling that wouldn't survive. Then, students began
leaving their neighborhood district schools. And charter schools
continued to mushroom across the state. Today, there are 270
charter schools with 30,000 students and district officials in
traditional public schools _ which teach 750,000 students _
realized they had to respond to the charters.
</P>
<P>
   They did. They advertised, set up programs for younger kids and
opened magnet schools and other specialized schools.
</P>
<P>
   As more students go to charters, districts will be forced to
change to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The future will mean more schools and more competition,
especially from for-profit companies that can build schools
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more neighborhood-type charter schools, especially
if districts are unsuccessful in lobbying for construction money.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatives in the school districts will abound, including a
slew of specialized programs in the arts, sciences and other
popular areas. Eventually, all schools will be true schools of
choice. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Kelly Pearce can be reached at kelly.pearce(at)pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
