To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JEWS (Moscow) _ After a promising new chapter when the
Soviet Union expired, Russia's Jews are now facing growing
anti-Semitism. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR-FLORES (San Salvador) _ A man-in-the-news profile:
Francisco Flores, the ``moderate'' rightist who will be El
Salvador's next president and who invoked death-squad leader
Roberto d'Aubuisson at victory rally. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ILL-PROSECUTORS-CHARGED (Chicago) _ In a case that could have
reverberations throughout the nation's criminal justice system, a
group of seven prosecutors and sheriff's deputies are to go on
trial on Tuesday on charges that they conspired to frame an
innocent man. The officials, charged with perjury and conspiring to
obstruct justice, are accused of using false evidence or
withholding evidence in order to convict a man of the 1983 rape and
murder of a 10-year-old girl in DuPage County, outside Chicago. By
Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-LAND-TRUST (Wetumka, Okla.) _ The federal government,
which holds more than 10 million acres in trust for up to
half-a-million individual Indians, seems incapable of keeping track
of the money from the land, which is often leased to oil and gas
companies. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MO-EXECUTE (Kansas City, Mo.) _ A month after bowing to a plea
from the pope and commuting the death sentence of a confessed
triple killer, Gov. Mel Carnahan of Missouri faces the clemency
petition of a condemned man who has submitted to a lie detector
test to buttress his claim of innocence. By Shirley Christian.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AEROSPACE-LEAN (Chula Vista, Calif.) _ A decade after U.S.
automakers began adopting lean manufacturing techniques, the
aerospace industry is embracing the concept to cut costs.
Executives are now bandying about Japanese terms like kaizen
(continuous improvement) and kanban (the just-in-time system). They
often mispronounce them horribly, but are applying them well enough
to achieve some startling efficiency gains in an industry long
known for high costs and wasteful procedures. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-DIMON (New York) _ Jamie Dimon, former Citigroup
president, received a severance package with an estimated value of
at least $30 million on the condition that he agree to restrictions
of as long as three years on his ability to lure Citigroup staff to
work for him at any new employer. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ When Allied Waste Industries Inc.
announced Monday that it would acquire Browning-Ferris Industries,
a much bigger rival in the trash-hauling business, the message from
the company was simple: We can better manage those huge assets. By
Laura M. Holson and David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BEERS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Charlotte Beers, once called the
most powerful woman in advertising, is for the third time becoming
a top leader at a giant agency. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
