<P>
   COMEDY-FESTIVAL (Aspen, Colo.) _ A report from the Aspen Comedy
festival and some serious talk about what should be out of bounds.
By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   TIMERMAN-WRITING (Punta Del Este, Uruguay) _ After Argentina's
junta freed him in 1979, Jacobo Timerman's testament of prison
life, torture and anti-Semitism stirred comparisons to Dostoyevsky,
Camus and Hannah Arendt. ``Prisoner Without a Name, Cell Without a
Number'' brought Timerman lasting fame and fortune. Since the death
of his wife, Risha, eight years ago, however, Timerman has been
virtually silent. At 76 he speaks of depression, drinking and the
constant pain in his legs. But finally the haze seems to be
lifting, Timerman said in an interview, and he is finding his
writing powers again. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-FASHIONS (Milan, Italy) _ The bigger names in Italian
fashion may lead impeccably civilized lives up in their art-filled
palazzi, but give one of these titans of chic a rich, feel-good
dish like risotto and suddenly the napkin is under the chin and
he's hogging the whole platter of congealed rice for himself. Such
a scene was recounted last week after a lunch for a small group of
magazine editors, and while the witnesses said they didn't go
hungry (the designer's cook fed them pasta), the risotto story
hints at the self-centered isolation of Milan's Old Guard, who for
too long have held onto the pot. By Cathy Horyn
</P>
