<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2916 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-09 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOE DIMAGGIO: YANKEE WHO RULED BASEBALL LIKE A KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a measure of time's cruelty, an entire generation
of Americans has come of age after the last of his Mr. Coffee
commercials disappeared from TV in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   How is Joe DiMaggio explained to them?
</P>
<P>
   Try this: He was American royalty.
</P>
<P>
   For a society that more than 200 years ago banished by
constitution the unearned nobility of European despots, DiMaggio
was the embodiment of true benevolent kingship.
</P>
<P>
   The most elegant of baseball players had two qualities that set
apart an individual from all others in a society required by law to
be classless, yet mandated by disposition to reward the individual
winner.
</P>
<P>
   By achievement, he was uniquely dominant; by personality, he was
utterly unknowable.
</P>
<P>
   Humans do not get more regal.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are so unused to the royal distance that the best we
do is political analogies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walked into that clubhouse,'' said Billy Martin, his
late Yankee teammate, ``it was like a president or senator walking
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he was the opposite of what we have come to know as the
modern politician. Beyond an uneasy, occasional willingness to
share a public smile and a ceremony, DiMaggio didn't want or need
the validation of undeserved adoration.
</P>
<P>
   It is the fashion of the American day to let everyone share in
one's thoughts, secrets, eccentricities and perversions. From O.J.
Simpson to Mary K. Letourneau to Monica Lewinsky, conventional
wisdom is that a life carefully laid open is a life bettered. This
may or may not be true. What I do know is that the book and movie
rights are almost always blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   Six-decade celebrity that he was, DiMaggio never let anyone in
on himself. Seems to have worked out pretty well, for him and us.
Public tours of the castle are always fun, but kings lose a little
something when they become theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   In the volumes of copy that will follow DiMaggio's death Monday,
almost no one who is being honest will say they knew him. They knew
about him. They knew of him. But unlike most prominent figures in
contemporary sports, he locked his elbows and kept everyone out.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody much minded.
</P>
<P>
   For journalists, this is normally bad news. But the job of king
is not an elective office. It is a cosmic appointment. Public
disclosure rules do not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, apparently, did many laws of nature. For the last months of
his life, the joke was that he had more rebounds than Dennis
Rodman. DiMaggio had last rites administered what seemed like a
half-dozen times, yet kept popping up to rail against his obit in
the newspapers and on TV.
</P>
<P>
   He beat back death. What else can be required of a king?
</P>
<P>
   As was mentioned: Achievement. In his most notable contribution
to sports history, the 56-game hitting streak in 1941, DiMaggio
created a record that was the perfect definition of the man _
ceaseless, unwavering excellence. The fact that no one has come
closer than a dozen games to the DiMaggio streak is testament to
its unbreakability.
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball is the hardest game, and DiMaggio set its
highest standard. After his baseball career ended, he moved through
the culture and the generations with the same precision that his
bat sliced the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   The man stood in the gale of the world's most blustery city and
married the most glamorous movie star, yet left them mysteriously
while keeping all creases pressed. His bearing was commanding, his
appearance flawless and his requirement for respect politely
insistent.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked to throw out the first pitch for a Yankee
World Series I was covering, I was surprised that my
celebrity-exhausted eyes would not leave his every move. The pull
he had on the baseball was nothing compared with the pull he had on
the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In a time that has perfunctory respect, but little reverence,
for the icons of past generations _ soldiers, explorers,
scientists, educators _ the entertainer has become the center of
the culture. We put them in the White House, the Senate, governor's
mansions, the forefront of social causes and on the ads and
packages of nearly every consumer product, despite their having
little legitimate claim to the platform beyond notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was an entertainer too, but it was the least of his
graces. During the American century hailed for its egalitarianism,
he had power over our imaginations through what he did and the way
he did it, leading the unknowable life of the true noble.
</P>
<P>
   Joltin' Joe has left and gone away, leaving no successors.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
