<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD, GUILLEN COMING TOGETHER AS DOUBLE-PLAY COMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ It was smooth, stylish, exactly what the
Mariners hope to see all year from their new infield tandem.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Randy Velarde ripped a grounder toward the hole in the
fourth inning of Monday's 10-3 Mariners win. Alex Rodriguez dropped
to his knees, extended and speared it, whipping the ball to Carlos
Guillen at second, who hurdled Mo Vaughn and completed the double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of outs in an exhibition game, but the play
exemplified what the M's have seen in early-morning infield drills
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been getting ground balls early, getting used to each
other,'' infield coach Steve Smith said. ``It's nice being away
from everyone, and it's important they know each other on and off
the field so they get along when they're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, who came over from Houston in the Randy Johnson trade
last July, is expected to be a marked improvement over Joey Cora,
who led American League second basemen with 20 errors last year.
The 23-year-old is the same age as Rodriguez, but the shortstop's
major league tenure has made him a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tables turn,'' Rodriguez said. ``Joey taught me a lot of
things about playing in the middle of the infield, leadership and
different situations. Now it's my turn to show (Guillen) the way.
Even though I'm young, I have four years of experience and can help
him out a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Rodriguez's work ethic is enough of an example for
Guillen, a rookie who already has shown comparable dedication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him and he's working every day, and I like to be like
him,'' Guillen said.
</P>
<P>
   There also have been mechanical adjustments for Guillen, who was
developed as a shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   When starting a double play, the shortstop has an easier flip
than the second baseman because he throws across his body, not off
to the side. Guillen has learned to deliver the ball underhanded,
instead of pushing it as a quarterback would a shovel pass. Smith
said Guillen also is learning to take the ``little, tiny steps'' of
a second baseman instead of the longer strides of a shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there's the process of learning Rodriguez _ and
vice versa. Becoming comfortable with a new double play partner
sometimes takes just a few weeks, Rodriguez said. Sometimes it
never happens. So far, he and Guillen seem more like the former.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played enough to be comfortable yet,'' Rodriguez
said, ``but I can see us getting comfortable pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   MARINER NOTES: How does a pitching prospect win over manager Lou
Piniella? By throwing strikes. No young pitcher has impressed
Piniella as much as right-hander Brett Hinchliffe, who threw two
scoreless innings Monday and minimized his pitches by finding the
strike zone. Piniella said Hinchliffe is putting himself on track
to start an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mac Suzuki, meanwhile, allowed three runs and walked three in
one inning. He was hit hard by a Korean team in a ``B'' game last
week, but this performance was more discouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got hit a little bit the other day, but he threw strikes,
and I like that,'' Piniella said. ``Today, with a 6-0 lead, he came
in and walked the first two hitters and all of a sudden he's in hot
water for no reason at all.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Jay Buhner saw his first exhibition action Monday, going
3-for-5 with two doubles and four RBIs. Buhner will rest Tuesday,
then make his debut in left field Wednesday on a program prescribed
by team trainers as he continues to recover from elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner will not accompany the team on the trek to Tucson to play
the Colorado Rockies on Thursday. ``We're having trouble filling
that bus for Tucson,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reliever Bobby Ayala threw his second scoreless inning this
spring, prompting fans to stand and cheer as he trotted down the
right-field line on his way back to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mariners minor leaguers have reported to camp, but
18-year-old phenom Cha Sueng Baek remains in South Korea with visa
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
