<HEADER>
A2923 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIMAGGIO-APPRECIATION     03-09 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CIRCUMSTANCES PROVED GREATNESS OF NATIVE SON  &HT;     By KEN GARCIA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco lost the biggest star it ever produced Monday, a
high school dropout who combined a rare athletic talent with an
elusive quality called dignity to climb to mythical heights.
</P>
<P>
   That Joe DiMaggio began his ascent playing on the fields of
Funston Playground is as much a part of local lore as his
appearances at another long-gone San Francisco institution, Seals
Stadium. The fact that the city has not produced another athlete or
ball yard of similar status in more than 60 years does not speak
well for the Yankee Clipper's home, but it does remind us that
impossible feats can happen anywhere _ even in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that neither the city nor DiMaggio ever lost was
their singular style, an almost quiet acceptance of certain
God-given gifts. For San Francisco, it was its magical, unending
beauty. For DiMaggio, it was his graceful, fluid movement.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio proved that fame often grows when you don't pursue it,
a lesson that future generations of athletes and film stars would
do well to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the legend of Joe DiMaggio will never go away in large
part because of the way he handled his celebrity. The word
``class,'' rightly enough, is little used in sports these days, but
it applied to DiMaggio as much as any of the hyperbolic adjectives
used to describe his feats on the diamond.
</P>
<P>
   And class in San Francisco has always been more about good
manners than noble birthrights. DiMaggio was at heart a Pabst Blue
Ribbon guy living a champagne cocktail life. Even at the height of
his fame, he spent the offseason living away from the media glare
in New York, biding his time at his family's restaurant at
Fisherman's Wharf or hanging out at Reno Barsocchini's place on
Post Street. Many writers came calling, but none was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt helped during his celebrated career that DiMaggio
was just a local kid from a modest working family in San Francisco
and that he never lost sight of it. His humble background seemed to
capture the spirit of an era when heroes walked quietly, almost
dismissive of their own achievements.
</P>
<P>
   About as flashy as DiMaggio ever got was the lighted neon sign
of his likeness that hung outside the restaurant his brother Tom
ran. DiMaggio was often spotted about town, and would acknowledge
greetings politely, but kept to himself almost intensely. A
television special on his life last year all but suggested that it
was all part of DiMaggio's plan to protect and secure his public
image. If it's true, at least he had an image worth protecting.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity has a way of distorting values and images _ or have
you not heard of Dennis Rodman, John McEnroe and Albert Belle?
Selfishness and boorish self-promotion have become such a standard
for people we regard as stars that DiMaggio's behavior seems like a
quaint memory from our past.
</P>
<P>
   But he could not be more timely. Or necessary. And that makes
his passing all the more sad. San Francisco lost more than a
skillful native son _ it lost its greatest cultural ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   By the time DiMaggio was 18, he was already a star here, tearing
up the Pacific Coast League almost as if he were playing pickup
games in North Beach. In his rookie year, he hit safely in 61
straight games _ foreshadowing greatness with the Yankees that
would see him set one of the greatest records in sports _ 56
straight games with a hit _ in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wonder why San Francisco was such a hotbed of Yankee
fan support in the late '30s and early '40s need only to remember
that the team was filled with city ballplayers, including Frankie
Crosetti, Lefty Gomez and Tony Lazzeri, all stars in their own
right. In that regard, New York became San Francisco East, and the
papers and newsreels were filled with the exploits of the kids from
the West Coast sandlots.
</P>
<P>
   Yet DiMaggio became a king, whose legend was determined by a
life of greatness on the playing field and unerring self-effacement
off it. There may be a handful of American athletes who have
achieved as much fame, but none who ever handled the pressure
better, or with more style and grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that he had a manner that was the complete
antithesis of the behavior of current athletes,'' said longtime
Sports Illustrated writer Ron Fimrite, who first met DiMaggio as a
Chronicle columnist in 1966. ``He carried himself well, dressed
immaculately, and he was wise enough not to talk too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Fimrite, whose appreciation of DiMaggio will appear in Sports
Illustrated this week, pursued a longer profile piece with the
Clipper for more than a decade. DiMaggio never played ball, but
Fimrite says he was unfailingly polite to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was because he didn't have that much to say, but he
always managed to maintain that dignity because of some natural
self-restraint,'' Fimrite said. ``He was always good to the press,
even if you couldn't get that much out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio achieved more success in sports than probably any
athlete in this century, playing in 10 World Series in 13 seasons
and winning nine of them. The only other athlete who even came
close to that was USF's Bill Russell, who teamed with K.C. Jones on
the great Celtics teams of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell left basketball an angry and bitter man, outspoken
in his views, while DiMaggio just kept to himself, carefully
guarding his privacy. History shows us which style is more
enduring.
</P>
<P>
   So now, we finally know where Joltin' Joe has gone. He's gone
home. A place that, at least in his values, he never really left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
