A3040 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIR-RAISING-(NEW-SCI     03-09 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR-RAISING-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET TO RESTORING THOSE LUSCIOUS LOCKS IS IN YOUR HEAD  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MARCH 8, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ANDY COGHLAN  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Substances that make brain cells grow might lead to treatments
for baldness, say dermatologists in Germany. They expect their
bizarre discovery could also open up new avenues for keeping
unwanted body hair at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first evidence that growth factors previously
thought to be important for the development of brain cells are also
important for the growth of hair follicles,'' says Ralf Paus, who
carried out the work while at Humbolt University in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Paus and his colleagues had previously shown that a growth
factor in the brain called neurotrophin-3 triggers the formation of
hair follicles in embryonic mice. When mammals are born, however,
the follicles shrink and regress, which is why a baby's hair often
falls out a few weeks after birth.
</P>
<P>
   In the next ``resting'' phase of the cycle, the shrunken
follicle hangs onto the original hair shaft until a new hair pushes
it out of the way. Finally, after a short burst of growth, when new
hairs take over, the follicle shrivels and resumes its resting
phase once again. In mice, the cycle lasts a matter of weeks. In
humans, it can take two to six years.
</P>
<P>
   In experiments with shaved mice, Paus' team has shown that just
before the shriveling phase, hair follicles are awash with two
growth factors: brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) and
neurotrophin-4 (NT-4). And the two genes which make the proteins
are abnormally active at the same time. This suggested that the
chemicals actually trigger the shrinking of follicles.
</P>
<P>
   To confirm this, the researchers engineered mice to churn out
too much BDNF. As expected, their hair fell out earlier than usual.
Conversely, hair took longer than normal to fall out in
``knockout'' mice that could not make either protein.
</P>
<P>
   The same series of experiments, published in FASEB Journal (vol.
13, p. 395), reveal that the two substances work by binding to a
receptor called tyrosine kinase B. If humans have a similar system,
then drugs that block the receptor could prevent hair loss.
Alternatively, drugs that mimic the brain proteins and bind to the
receptor might help people shed unwanted hair.
</P>
<P>
   Paus says such drugs have already been developed as potential
treatments for neurological conditions such as Alzheimer's disease
and multiple sclerosis. ``It's not too farfetched to propose using
them for hair disorders, particularly if you can apply them
topically in lotions,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is too early to say whether the mouse results are
relevant to humans, adds Paus, who is now at the University
Hospital in Hamburg. One difference, he points out, is that mouse
hair grows in synchronized waves, whereas each human hair has its
own individual growth cycle, so overall hair growth is much more
erratic than in mice.
</P>
<P>
   George Cotsarelis, director of the hair and scalp clinic at the
University of Pennsylvania Medical Center in Philadelphia, agrees
that if the results hold true for humans, new treatments might be
possible. ``These new findings might be more useful for getting rid
of hair than restoring it,'' he adds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3041 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIR-RAISING-(NEW-SCI     03-09 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR-RAISING-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET TO RESTORING THOSE LUSCIOUS LOCKS IS IN YOUR HEAD  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MARCH 8, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
