r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-TIPS-FROM-OW     03-09 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-TIPS-FROM-OWLS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY AIRCRAFT DESIGNERS COULD LEARN A LOT FROM NATURE'S SILENT
KILLERS  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MARCH 8, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By CHARLES SEIFE  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Owls are the original stealth aircraft, dropping silently,
talons at the ready, onto their prey. That's why engineers working
with military and defense agencies will be all ears later this
month during a meeting of the European Acoustics Association to be
held at the Technical University of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Lilley, an acoustics expert at the University of
Southampton, will describe how the trailing edge of owl feathers
helps to stifle the sound of the bird's flight. This could give
designers tips for reducing noise in future stealth aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The prey of owls _ rats, mice and voles _ often has excellent
hearing, so they can't afford to fly as noisily as other birds.
``The owl has to be able to fly silently to have a good dinner,''
says Lilley, who also works at NASA's Langley Research Center in
Hampton, Va.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, the owl has evolved feathers that are different from
those of other birds. ``The flight feathers of most birds have a
fairly sharp, clean edge,'' says Gerry Carr, a biomechanist at the
University of Victoria in British Columbia, Canada. ``But the
leading edges of the flight feathers of an owl coupled with the
outer third of the hand section of the wing's trailing edges are
characterized by soft, feathery `fringes' which have the effect of
muffling the flow of air as it passes over the wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how these fringes reduce noise was unclear, so Lilley used
computer simulations to work out what they did. ``The devices at
the trailing edge are acting like some sort of pressure release,''
he said. ``The various gaps in the trailing edge allow pressure
relief, and as a result, the noise generation of the turbulent flow
decreases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's plausible that the owl will yield secrets engineers can
use,'' says Jeremy Rayner, a bird flight expert at the University
of Bristol. He notes that engineers have already used birdlike
designs to improve the efficiency and reduce the noise of
helicopter blades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3086 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-EVICTION10-COX     03-09 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-EVICTION10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    County wants to uproot lone Deem City dweller
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A 3-foot, yellow rat snake is loose in
the bathroom of Clifton Lirette's ramshackle trailer. But, at this
particular moment last week, he finds more entertaining the 6-foot
yuppie businessman who has come looking for monster cheeseburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Snakes he sees all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger customers have become an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the doorstep of what hunters know as the Terrytown
reserve and most everyone else knows as no place, Lirette attracts
visitors by his presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet all kinds of people here just because I'm here,'' he
says, acknowledging the paradox with a toothless smile.
</P>
<P>
   Few men are so defined by location as this sun-worn 67-year-old.
When Lirette first settled here 20 years ago, a sign across U.S. 27
read: ``Deem City, Pop. 2.'' Then a fire destroyed the convenience
store and service station and, for practical purposes, Deem City
ceased to be.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lirette remained at his remote outpost at the edge of the
Everglades in southwestern Palm Beach County, 100 yards from the
Broward line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no-man's land,'' he says, ``but I love it because I
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-mile stretch of two-lane highway south of South Bay once
was known as Bloody 27 for its many horrific accidents. Lirette
says he is in danger of becoming the road's last casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the state widened the road to four lanes, and
claimed the hamburger stand Lirette ran from an old panel truck.
Clif's Superburgers died.
</P>
<P>
   Now the county wants Lirette to move himself off the land. He
bought his three-quarter acre lot 12 years ago for $45,000, but it
is zoned for agriculture use, not residential. Today the
dilapidated 60-foot trailer and two sheds Lirette calls home are a
code inspector's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't live there,'' said Terry Verner, the county's
director of code enforcement. ``He doesn't have an approved
structure to live in. We're assuming he's not living there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lirette most certainly is. Though mammoth Florida Power &AMP;
Light towers are above him, he must run a gas-powered generator 18
hours a day to pump his water and run his freezer. A friend stops
by to haul away his garbage. Sanitation facilities tend to be
rather primitive.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody dropped off a pit bull-collie mix Lirette named Butch.
Somebody else dropped off a rooster. A spaniel-Labrador female came
by a few weeks back, and now Butch is the father of four puppies.
Everyone puts up with each other, snakes included.
</P>
<P>
   Lirette spends most days on the couch or at his desk in the
10-by-15-foot shed. Cans of Jack Mackerel, Beefaroni and sardines
line the shelf, the pantry of a man who lives on a $700 Social
Security check each month.
</P>
<P>
   A proven routine makes life manageable here. During the week
Lirette enjoys Busch beer then moves up in class to Corona or
Heineken for the weekend. Each morning he drives 14 miles south to
the nearest civilization _ a Winn Dixie on the outskirts of Weston
_ and buys Doral cigarettes, the morning newspaper, gas for the
generator and fresh food for the day. He alternates his trips in
either an '86 Audi or an '85 Dodge pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be sure to have two cars,'' he says. ``That way if
one breaks, you're not stranded.''
</P>
<P>
   Born with polio, Lirette's right hand is crippled, and he has
suffered five strokes in three years. Blood thinners and beta
blockers are chased with the Coronas now. He has two telephones to
summon help if he needs it.
</P>
<P>
   A former New Orleans tugboat pilot, Lirette came to the
Everglades in the mid-1970s to haul barges and liked it so much he
stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area used to be booming,'' he said. ``I could sit here
and watch dozens of snakes cross the road all at once. I used to
share my hamburger stand with the snakes. Possum, coon, even
bobcats _ they were all over here. Now you just don't see as
many.''
</P>
<P>
   When the burger business was peaking and he was selling 400
Superburgers at $3 apiece each day, he would entertain customers
with a collection of a dozen snakes. One of them was a python he
got in a trade for a native bull snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to turn them all loose when the new highway came,'' he
said. ``I think the python will be happy though, wherever he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Lirette's future is nebulous, too. For the last six
years, Verner and his inspectors have been citing him for
violations and urging him to move elsewhere. He has fought them at
each turn.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, they were horrified when they drove by and saw 14
trailer homes there. Lirette was selling them for a friend, at
between $1,000 and $1,500 each, and pocketing a commission. All but
two are gone now, but those are torn apart, unlivable and
considered eyesores by the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't make any real money,'' he says, ``but $100 is still
$100.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Slutsky, a Fort Lauderdale attorney who specializes in
probate work, was moved to assist Lirette in his battle with the
county after making a will for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who's not on welfare, who's hurting no one and
is just trying to live his life,'' Slutsky said. ``What are they
going to do to him anyway? He owns the property.''
</P>
<P>
   Verner says the county has showed restraint in its dealings with
Lirette, but unless he cleans up his lot and conforms to code, a
legal showdown is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Clif,'' Verner said. ``He's a good guy, and I
like him. He reminds me of a picture of one of those old cowboys
who needs to drink a beer to hold his jeans up. But he can't be
doing some of the things he's been trying to do there.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the county agreed to let Lirette put up a
mobile produce stand, so long as it did not cover more than 150
square feet and had sanitary facilities. He believes it impossible
to turn a profit with an operation that small.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have the right to make a living on my property,'' he
says, ``and they don't want me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Wallace Post, a Palm Beach Gardens attorney, represented
Lirette on a pro-bono basis two years ago. She said several social
service agencies offered to help him move elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He refused that. He told them he was happy and content living
where he was. He doesn't want charity. But he's in tough situation
because that's such a strange parcel of land he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Lirette maintains he has performed a public service just by
being there when needed. For a time, his was the only telephone
within a dozen miles.
</P>
<P>
   Late one night eight years ago, three children, none of them
older than 7 and all of them dripping wet and screaming, ran up to
his hamburger stand.
</P>
<P>
   They had been returning from a fishing trip in the Terrytown
wildlife area behind him when their father drove the family pickup
into the canal. Lirette called 911 and, with the help of some
hunters, put the man on his picnic table until an ambulance came.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the family returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man healed up all right,'' Lirette said. ``They all had
dinner here.''
</P>
<P>
   Truckers still honk their horns at Lirette's place when they
drive by. Last week, Demetrius Washington, 30, a consultant with a
South Florida health care company, pulled in searching for
hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a college student at Florida Memorial in Miami, he
would make regular trips to his home in Arcadia. He said he stopped
at Clif's Superburgers every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry he's not selling those burgers anymore,'' Washington
said. ``Trust me. They were big, and they were nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lirette thanked Washington for dropping by, then headed into the
bathroom to chase out that rat snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not,'' he said, ``I have a reputation out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
