A3087 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN10-COX     03-09 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The littlest duckling: Sometimes being the youngest isn't all
it's quacked up to be
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I call it the ``duckling syndrome.'' There's the
mother duck at the front of the line and all the little ducklings
waddling behind her, the youngest one at the end.
</P>
<P>
   I'm the littlest duckling in my family, the baby. I have spent
my life following after older siblings and trying not to ruffle any
feathers.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has been written about birth order and how it affects
children. I've read much of it and don't remember most of it. I do
know the oldest child often is the high-achieving, angst-ridden,
overly responsible one. The middle child's existence typically is a
lifelong scream for attention. And the youngest many times is
spoiled, laid back, easygoing and the happiest of the bunch. You
see, by the time the last child comes along, the parents have
foregone all their high-falutin' parenting skills, relaxed, and
just allowed that baby to develop as he or she was meant to.
</P>
<P>
   Those stereotypes may hold some truth, but there are certain
burdens the youngest child must bear.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment we are born, someone is telling us what to do,
how to do it, and when to do it. Much of it doesn't come from the
parents, either. It's the siblings. Whether it's brothers or
sisters, they're there. And they resent you for popping into their
world uninvited. They resent their parents making them sit on the
couch and hold you while pictures are taken for the baby book.
</P>
<P>
   They resent all the grown-ups making such a fuss over you just
because you can burp and wiggle. They resent that you are
permanently attached to their mother for the first six months of
your life.
</P>
<P>
   So, they get even . . . in little, deceptive, hidden ways. They
stand at your bassinet and watch you cry instead of going to get
mother. They pull the bottle out of your mouth on the way to the
back yard. They get inches away from your face on your second day
of life and tell you, ``I'm the boss of you and don't ever forget
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot for the youngest to overcome. We follow behind our
parents and siblings in the grocery store, at the zoo, in the park,
down the church aisle. There's always someone in front of us
leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine, the youngest of four sisters, is a grown woman
and has a daughter of her own. Yet she tells me of being on a trip
with a group of co-workers when they decided to go to a mall.
Everyone scattered and she found herself alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood there in that mall like I was 12 years old, waiting
for someone to come and tell me where to go. I will always be 12
years old in my mind!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Our parents treat us differently, too. We're their ``last
chance'' to get things right. We must be the perfect ones. Whatever
mistakes our older siblings made, we must not. Sometimes we're able
to pull this off, superficially. If nothing else, youngest children
learn early how to evaluate their environment.
</P>
<P>
   While older sister and brother are rebelling against mom and
dad, we sit in the background, observe and make mental notes. Where
our siblings confront, we cajole. We're not stupid, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Parents also spend more time protecting the youngest. They keep
older siblings from bullying us when we're children, and they keep
distressing news from us when we're adults. To this day, my mother
will tell my older sister all the details of a medical problem, but
when I ask her, she'll say, ``I'm fine. Everything's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the opinions or advice of the youngest get taken
seriously. Often we're the background noise in family discussions.
We are forever given the pat-on-the-head, aren't-you-cute,
go-off-and-play treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The duckling syndrome. Sometimes the view from the end of the
line isn't all that pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
