<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3088 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN10-COX     03-09 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A vivid, different generation
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The first question eighth-graders ask when I
tell them we're going to see a movie: ``Is it in color?'' Lord help
me if I say no. There's always a Johnny or a Susie who, in the
infinite wisdom of any 13-year-old, proclaims: ``Geez! Life was
so-ooo boring in the `olden days.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Life happened just the same in black and white as it does
today in living color,'' is my standard comment, but they just
don't get it. A few nod politely, and one or two let out a
know-it-all snort of disbelief. Frustrating, but it comes with the
age, I remind myself. Youthful egocentricity endows them with the
firm conviction that whatever it is they're experiencing at any
given moment, puppy love or test anxiety, is a first and unique to
their generation. And as for the ``good old days,'' forget it.
Anything that happened before ``Baywatch'' reruns and Korn is
antediluvian.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of like they've all bought into the ``Pleasantville''
hoax. That's the movie that depicts the '50s (my generation) as a
sepia blur of nonpersons living repressed lives in a picket-fenced
Stepford town where emotions, like bosoms, are confined by
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   What the writer of this monochromatic aberration of history
(``Pleasantville'') doesn't seem to understand (probably because he
was only 2 when the decade ended) is that his imaginings of life in
the '50s are just as stereotypical as the folks he wrote into his
sanitized little town. In Pleasantville, everyone sleeps alone, no
one is ever caught in the act of spontaneous anything, and lust is
simply a four-letter word in the dictionary that comes between
Lusitania and Lutheran.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the way it was. Sure, our emotions (as well as
our chests) were confined, but not by any pretense of piety.
Rather, we were guided by what we'd been taught was appropriate. We
knew better than to make a public display of ourselves, and we
cherished our privacy. Certainly, we'd never heard of anyone
messing up big time, confessing it on television, and then selling
the book rights for seven figures. Our parents would have killed
us.
</P>
<P>
   Folks of my generation bought into the notion of doing what was
expected of us (most of the time) because no one had told us we
were entitled to ``find'' ourselves or do our ``own thing.'' It was
our naive belief that assuming responsibility for ourselves meant
not letting down those who were counting on us.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us obeyed the rules laid out by our parents and schools,
but we definitely were not, as the movie suggests, zombies
shuffling through our teen years. We had a ball. Best of all, we
never had to make adult decisions while we were still kids.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us suppressed our teen-age libidos because that's what
we were expected to do. If we hadn't, and if we'd been caught, it
would have been instant mortification with our peers and suicide
with our parents. Funny, but I don't remember that any of us felt
shortchanged because we were expected to stomp on our instincts. We
felt curious, and we felt disadvantaged, but we were kids. As far
as we knew, that's how we were supposed to feel. Besides, we knew
it gave us something to look forward to when we were grownups.
</P>
<P>
   Our '50s clothes would probably look a little funny by today's
standards, but back then, we were the coolest. The girls wore their
skirts long and the boys wore their hair short. No morality
statement _ it was just the style. Could we help it if we came
along during saddle oxfords and crinolines instead of navel rings
and purple hair? Just try to imagine how ``with it'' the current
baggy pants fad is going to look 40 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to youthful belief, life in the '50s happened in vivid
color. Whether it was better than now or worse, I can't say. It was
just different. But I suspect it was also a heck of a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio, writes for Cox
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
