<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3089 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MECHANIC-COLUMN10-COX     03-09 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MECHANIC-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fast-good-cheap work an unlikely trifecta
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Automotive trade journals often contain articles concerning auto
repair issues that should be read by the public but are not because
they appear in publications normally read only by automotive
people.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I read an article that sums up much of what I have
been trying to impart for the past 4 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Mitch Schneider, an automotive writer for more than
15 years, agreed that the consumer and the automotive industry must
come to some meeting of the minds. His article, ``Cognitive
Dissonance,'' appears in the January issue of MotorAge Magazine.
(http://www.motorage.com; click on Schneider's World)
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the comments I hear are from disgruntled car
owners who have been the victims of less-than-pleasant auto repair
experiences. With few exceptions, the circumstances surrounding
these situations are the result of two distinct categories of auto
repair shoppers: those who are honestly trying to take care of
their vehicles and those who avoid servicing their cars until
something breaks or quits running.
</P>
<P>
   While it's easy to understand how people who neglect their
vehicles' needs end up on the losing end of repair encounters, it
would seem that the maintenance-minded group should have little to
fear. Not so. Although these two groups may appear to have
different philosophies, between them is a common thread: They want
quality repair, they don't want it to cost much and they want it
done yesterday, in short, as Schneider puts it, ``good, cheap and
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Is good, cheap and fast too much to ask for?
</P>
<P>
   Discount auto service commercials promise consumers everything
from same-day complete brake jobs to oil changes at bargain prices,
while mailboxes are stuffed with auto repair and service coupons.
This tangled web of ``great deals'' captures many.
</P>
<P>
   The ``drive it till it drops'' shoppers expect low-cost repairs
to apply to everything that could conceivably be wrong. They are
outraged that the two-digit advertised brake job is going to cost
them several hundred dollars because the shop has to replace
destroyed parts, or that an oil change is not going to fix the
knock in their engine.
</P>
<P>
   They are the victims of their own procrastination and
unrealistic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The service-minded victims get their oil changed regularly at
whatever ``quickie lube'' place is cheapest or most convenient.
They go for the ``free'' brake inspections and use coupons for
other maintenance or service needs. Should the vehicle develop an
unadvertised problem, they let their fingers do the walking until
they find a shop that will give them the least-expensive phone
quote for repairs. Preferably, this is a shop that has a complete
computer printout of anything and everything else wrong with the
vehicle so the mechanic can fix it fast (as long as its not too
expensive) and they can pick it up on the way home from work.
</P>
<P>
   They are caught in an illusionary web of finding quality and
expediency at rock-bottom prices.
</P>
<P>
   As Schneider writes: ``Fast. Good. Cheap. Pick any two. ... If
you want high-quality work and you want it done yesterday, we can
deliver without missing a beat. But in order for us to accomplish
an impossible assignment like that, we'll have to put two
technicians on the job. Will it be fast? Yes. Will it be good? You
bet! Will it be cheap? Uh, I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
near Atlanta, Ga. and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1.
Write her in care of Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA
30302. Or send comments online to nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us
or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
