<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARPDDRIVING-COLUMN1     03-09 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPDDRIVING-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford's takeover of Volvo likely to benefit both
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This past Monday, Volvo cars officially became part of Ford
Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some longtime Volvo die-hards who see the corporate
marriage as a potential contamination of the Volvo heritage. My
guess is that nothing could be further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   If Ford's track record with Jaguar and Aston Martin is any
indicator _ and there is no reason to think it is not _ Ford will
be more like a benevolent uncle than Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the industry now say that in spite of Ford's position of
ownership with the two British brands, both are more British than
ever. More importantly, each has a much higher quality rating than
in any time in either's storied history. I think the impending
marriage of Volvo and Ford is a more natural match than the
arrangements with Jaguar or Aston Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Even those with the most casual automotive interest know that
Volvo's claim to fame is its expertise in safety.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo was the first to introduce seat belts as standard
equipment, and that was just the first in a long line of safety
innovations that have long been the benchmark of the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also seems to be taking a leading role in producing cars
with outstanding safety ratings. At least five of its passenger
vehicles _ Ford Crown Victoria, Ford Taurus, Ford Windstar, Mercury
Sable and Mercury Grand Marquis _ all have received the federal
government's five-star safety rating in crash tests.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing of knowledge with a company such as Volvo seems a
natural progression on the path of safety innovations for Ford.
</P>
<P>
   An infusion of corporate capital by Ford is certainly welcomed
by Volvo cars, but Ford potentially stands as much to gain. Volvo
is currently offering leading technology in the area of all-weather
traction control systems.
</P>
<P>
   This system uses a viscous drive with locking rear differential
and anti-lock brake-controlled traction for the front wheels.
</P>
<P>
   The Stability Traction Control is standard on the Volvo S80
luxury sedan, and buyers can add an optional Dynamic Stability
Control System, which utilizes a yaw sensor to help eliminate
lateral loss of traction, or spin. Volvo's DSTC is the only system
in the industry that provides a duplicate system, so that if one
fails there is a backup.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout might mean an all-wheel-drive Taurus or Sable or
installation of Volvo interior safety components such as side air
curtains or proactive head restraints on Ford product lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Volvo/Ford wedding is one to which I think corporate
marriage counselors would quickly give their blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers.
Write her in care of Cox News Service P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA
30302. Or send comments online to sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
