<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS10-COX     03-09 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH BRIEFS: New drugs `godsend' for arthritis sufferers
 &HT;    (EDS: This is a compilation of health stories which moved to the
wires this week.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two days after trying Enbrel injections for her
rheumatoid arthritis, Melody Ray felt so good she wanted to tell
all her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised it worked so fast,'' said Ray, a 51-year-old
homemaker who has tried several remedies the past 17 years. ``The
swelling in my joints is much less, and I can actually make a fist
and feel my fingers. I know I still have the disease, but it's so
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray is among the thousands of arthritis patients nationwide
being prescribed Enbrel and two other new medicines for their
condition that control pain and swelling with fewer side effects,
such as stomach and kidney distress.
</P>
<P>
   The development of these drugs, Enbrel, Arava and Celebrex, is
considered as significant as the discovery of cortisone in the late
1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some patients say it's a godsend,'' said Dr. W. Hayes Wilson,
Atlanta's Piedmont Hospital chief of rheumatology. ``It's the first
medicines that they could take in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Enbrel and Arava are aimed specifically at rheumatoid arthritis,
which differs from the more common osteoarthritis, the result of
wear and tear on joints that occurs as people age. Rheumatoid
arthritis can strike early in adolescence, turning into a
debilitating condition of fatigue, painful swollen joints and
difficulty with the simplest of tasks. The exact cause of
rheumatoid arthritis remains elusive. About 2 million Americans
suffer RA; 60 percent of them are women.
</P>
<P>
   But some arthritis sufferers are finding they cannot afford some
of the drugs they've waited so long to try. For example, one shot
of Enbrel costs $125. At twice weekly doses, that's $13,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ray says her health insurance company agreed to pay for the
prescription, which arrives by mail. But Ben Starr of Columbia,
Mo., says the ``exorbitant'' Enbrel is out of reach to thousands of
retired middle-class people who are not covered by private
insurance, and whose Medicare benefits don't pay for prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two weeks I enjoyed great relief, but cut back to
one shot per week with less satisfactory results because of the
cost,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex, the third drug, relieves pain without causing
gastrointestinal turmoil. People needing daily nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory drugs for arthritis or other chronic pain can
suffer stomach ulcers and internal bleeding from these drugs. It
has been a major flaw of such drugs, estimated to cause 107,000
hospitalizations yearly, and resulting in 16,500 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   An easier way to fill an empty place in a child's heart
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's natural for developing infants to have a small
opening in their heart while in the womb and as newborns.
</P>
<P>
   The hole is between the two main arteries _ aorta and pulmonary
artery _ that carry blood out of the heart to body and lungs. The
opening is within its own small blood vessel. In utero, as the
placenta oxygenates the fetus' blood, this opening is diverting
blood from the lungs, which are not used until delivery. The first
gulp of air jolts a newborn's lungs into functioning, and that's
when the vital circulating loop of blood from heart to lungs
begins.
</P>
<P>
   The hole is considered harmless because it typically closes in
the first few days after birth. But it often doesn't in premature
babies. Though considered rare in the overall statistics of live
births, it is, in fact, a common congenital problem for infants
born with heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Annually, about 32,000 babies born in the United States have
heart problems, and of those, about 10 percent to 12 percent will
have the open vessel condition, called PDA for short, requiring
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few babies born with it, but if it's in your
family, it's a 100 percent statistic,'' says Dr. Zahid Amin of the
Medical College of Georgia, one of five sites in the country
plugging these holes with the new device, called the Amplatz
occluder. About 25 babies will receive the device at the sites as
the first phase of study required for federal government approval;
it's already been inserted successfully in about 300 babies in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hole in these babies' hearts may be 4 millimeters in
diameter, smaller than a dime,'' Amin said. ``For a small baby,
that is a very significant opening. It is a huge pressure
difference on one side of their heart and it shunts blood to the
lungs.''
</P>
<P>
   Left untreated, the defect can lead to pulmonary hypertension,
thickness of the heart and endocarditis, a possibly fatal infection
of the heart lining requiring weeks of hospitalization and massive
antibiotics. The baby also doesn't gain weight because it spends
excessive calories pumping its own blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest interest is to save small babies from pain,'' Amin
said. ``And this (procedure) saves them from a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
