<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3096 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN10-CO     03-09 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funds with low fees give biggest returns
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's a startling statistic: The Vanguard Group of
mutual funds netted more than $2 billion a week in new investments
last year.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about money moving that fast, you expect the
subject to be federal government spending, not private investing.
</P>
<P>
   It indicates a lot of Americans have acted on one of the basic
lessons of successful investing: Lower costs mean better returns.
</P>
<P>
   A number of studies have strongly suggested the mutual funds
that give investors the best returns are those with the lowest
fees. I tested that assertion against the latest data available in
the Morningstar database. The short-form answer: As of Jan. 31,
it's still true.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at returns of funds that invest in U.S. stocks. I
tossed out funds closed to new investment, that are sold only to
big, institutional investors or otherwise unavailable to the
public. That left 3,186 funds, certainly a significant sample.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying table summarizes the results. If you had put
your money into one of the cheapest funds, your annual rate of
return would have been 17.9 percent _ 2.6 percentage points better
than the average for all of those domestic equity funds. If you're
a long-term investor, that's a big enough spread to be worth your
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The table also reaffirms the hypothesis with the most up-to-date
data: If you pay more for your mutual fund, you must expect lower
returns. Note the Morningstar data include both major costs for
mutual funds _ the annual expenses and any sales fee, or load.
</P>
<P>
   I am not saying all investment expenses are outrageous, or even
a bad thing. You are hiring a specialist to manage your money, and
you certainly should expect to pay for the service.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how much are you are willing to pay?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's not hard to do some comparison shopping. You can
find basic data in the prospectus for any mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission requires each fund
manager to tell you, in the prospectus, the total cost of a
hypothetical investment in the fund. The example is how much you
would pay for a $1,000 investment, assuming a 5 percent return each
year and holding periods of one, three, five and 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Fidelity's Growth and Income Fund _ one of the
largest in the United States _ would cost you $22 over three years
and $38 over five years. The rest of the data is on page 6 of the
prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Vanguard's huge Index 500 fund would cost $6 over
three years and $11 over five years. The numbers include both loads
and annual expenses.
</P>
<P>
   I would not want to suggest cost is the only consideration when
you pick a mutual fund. You might think of cost as a tie-breaker,
once you have narrowed your selections.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the very low-cost funds among the 3,186 in my study are
index funds. An index fund tries to mimic the performance of a
given index, such as the S&AMP;P 500. If the index goes up, so does the
value of the fund. But it's the same thing on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   Index funds have been tremendously popular in the past few
years, as the market has continued its climb. Vanguard's Index 500
fund _ the second largest mutual fund in the world _ grew by 46
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   But index funds are not universally popular. A lot of investors
want to find a more actively managed fund, in hopes it will do
better than the indexes. Their thought: Why be average?
</P>
<P>
   Other investors want to get into particular areas of the market.
Some want to stick with the stocks of blue chip companies, for
example, or with funds known for a growth or value approach. Others
want to get even more selective, investing in foreign stocks or in
sector funds, such as technology or health care.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in picking mutual funds is making some general
decisions about your aims. How big a rate of return are you looking
for? How much risk are you willing to take? How can you balance
those two aspirations?
</P>
<P>
   Conservative investors might look to a balanced fund, which
invests in both stocks and bonds. The most aggressive investors
might seek out funds that invest in small-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   After those general considerations are settled, you can get to
the details. Those include such things as who the manager is, how
well he or she has done in the past, the fund's volatility as the
market goes up and down, and _ here it is _ the cost of investing
in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   For those details, a good place to start is the rankings
published by Morningstar or Value Line. Major libraries will have
their reports.
</P>
<P>
   When you are studying costs, here are some things to think
about:
</P>
<P>
   _ Loads are mostly sales fees. Two of the five largest mutual
funds in the country have loads of 5.75 percent and are sold only
through stockbrokers and other advisers.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with paying a commission. Many investors
want the advice that goes with it. For those people, the question
is: How much is that advice worth? Maybe it's 5.75 percent; maybe
it's more like 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't think you need the advice, it clearly pays to stick
with no-load or low-load funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not all loads are the same. Some mutual fund groups offer you
choices. You can pay a front-end load, or skip the load but pay
higher annual expenses, or lean toward a back-end load, which is
imposed when you sell the shares.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to hold the shares for more than four or five years,
it will probably be cheaper to pay a front-end load and avoid funds
with high annual expenses. Conversely, if you don't expect to hold
the shares more than a few years, you may be better off dodging the
loads and accepting the annual expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
