<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-CATSCAN10-COX     03-09 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-CATSCAN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Science/Health: New CAT scan gives quick pictures
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Douglas and Patricia Toler weren't looking
forward to taking their 10-month-old grandson to the hospital for a
CAT scan last week.
</P>
<P>
   He would need to be sedated so he could hold still for 10
minutes, they figured. ``We didn't like that idea with the medical
problems he had,'' Patricia said. Besides, they knew the drugs
would make him groggy and grouchy for another 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   So they were delighted to arrive at Children's Medical Center
and find out it had a new high-speed CAT scan machine that could
take the necessary pictures in only two minutes. For that long,
Patricia could distract little Brando Holland from the discomfort
of being strapped down by blowing soap bubbles in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of needing more than an hour to administer the
sedatives, position Brando for the scanner, shoot the images and
wait for him to wake up sufficiently, the whole procedure took less
than 10 minutes. The scanning itself took two minutes instead of
10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful surprise,'' Douglas Toler said.
</P>
<P>
   CMC spent about $1 million for the machine that will cut CAT
scanning by half to four-fifths the time conventional scanners
take. Besides decreasing the drugs and increasing the comfort for
fidgety children, the Aquilion scanner installed Wednesday will
enable the radiation department to streamline its schedule and
sooner accommodate people without emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was such new technology, we actually waited for it,''
said Dr. Elizabeth Ey, the medical director of radiology, who began
looking for a new scanner a year ago. Only two hospitals previously
had the Aquilion, in Iowa City, Iowa, and Japan, but Ey said
Toshiba plans to install 40 more by July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes such a significant difference in a children's
hospital because they don't have the attention span that adults
do,'' said administrative director Mary Beth Vaughn of radiology
and cardiology. ``They can't stay still as long.''
</P>
<P>
   If fewer patients need sedation, Vaughn said nurses will have
more time for actual scanning, ``although we'll probably need to
buy more bubbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Brando needed the scan to evaluate a shunt that had been put in
his head after his premature birth to draw fluid from his brain.
Even with the new scanner, Ey said a lot of 10-month-olds won't be
mellow enough to go without sedation.
</P>
<P>
   CAT scans, or computerized axial tomography, capture better
images of soft tissues than X-rays and also can provide more of a
three-dimensional look by stacking a number of two-dimensional
images. Brando needed 13 such ``slices,'' and a teen-ager would
need about 15 slightly thicker ones. The new scanner will take
thinner slices than previous models to help examine premature
babies.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the monthly 400 to 450 CAT scans at Children's
are of patients' heads, where Ey said the superior soft-tissue
detail creates the biggest advantage. CAT scans are also valuable
for trauma cases ``because they're very sensitive to acute
bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), Ey said CAT
scans are cheaper and faster with better bone detail, but less
revealing of soft-tissue detail. Another frequent use for CAT scans
is in contrast studies, in which dye is injected through the
patient's blood stream to help doctors better see blood vessels or
certain tumors, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have to use as much contrast dye with this scanner,''
Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   As 16-year-old Stacie Lake followed Brando on the scanner table,
Vaughn said she always hates to see kids go through sinus scans
because they have to stay in such awkward positions. Stacie had
sinus polyps blocking all of her right nostril and 90 percent of
her left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have fallen asleep,'' she said after the procedure
lasted less than 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really excited about this,'' Vaughn said. ``Probably
more excited than normal people should be. But this will make
everybody's lives so much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
