<HEADER>
A3100 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN     03-09 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unified title or not, no fight like Ali-Frazier
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a classic moment of give-and-take in what many
consider the greatest single sporting event of this half-century.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Frazier _ head down, body low, bobbing and weaving
incessantly _ bore in on Muhammad Ali with a remorseless body
attack that was climaxed by searing hooks to the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Ali fired a series of jabs, landed some stinging
right hands and then shouted at his stumpy nemesis: ``Fray-sha,
don't you know, I am God?''
</P>
<P>
   ``God, you're in the wrong place tonight,'' Frazier shot back.
</P>
<P>
   And what names Frazier could have written down that glorious
Madison Square Garden night 28 years ago. It was the first of three
Ali-Frazier fights and Frank Sinatra leaned on the ring apron
shooting photographs for Life magazine. Actor Burt Lancaster was
doing the broadcast. Edward Kennedy, Burt Bacharach and astronaut
Alan Shepard were in the $150 ringside seats. So was Diana Ross,
who was allowed in Ali's post-fight dressing room. Outside,
meanwhile, 76-year-old former champ Jack Dempsey knocked out two
thugs who tried to mug him.
</P>
<P>
   As for that sellout crowd of more than 20,000, they showed up
with orange and green and pink velvet hot pants, alligator shoes,
zebra-striped capes, mink stoles, black leather knickers, purple
fedoras and diamond-crowned walking sticks. It was, Sports
Illustrated noted, as if ``Manhattan listed toward Babylon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down from the ring and it was a sea of glitter,''
said Eddie Futch, one of Frazier's trainers. ``I had never seen any
boxing event that had so many celebrities,''
</P>
<P>
   No one had seen a fight like this . . . nor have they since.
With each boxer receiving a then-unheard-of $2.5 million, this was
the richest financial backing ever given a sporting event. It would
usher in a new era of glamour, money and visibility _ 300 million
worldwide watched the TV broadcast _ not just to boxing, but sports
in general.
</P>
<P>
   America was swept up in the anticipation of what would happen
between Frazier and Ali _ both unbeaten, except for Ali's lone loss
to the U.S. government. That cost him 3 years of exile for refusing
military service during the Vietnam War and it left the fight
swirling prominently in the turbulent political currents of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier and Ali did nothing to calm the waters. No hyphen-held
matchups in sports _ not Schmeling-Louis, Palmer-Nicklaus,
Borg-McEnroe, Sosa-McGwire _ are bound more fiercely in such
dramatic theater.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ali and Frazier fought three times, nothing tops that
first bout. It's been become the standard by which all other
heavyweight fights _ especially this Saturday's unification bout at
the Garden between champs Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis _ are
measured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had NBA finals, Stanley Cup finals, All-Star games, but
there's nothing like a heavyweight title fight,'' said Madison
Square Gardens president Dave Checketts.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's long-anticipated match to unify the title for the
first time in seven years has all the earmarks of a classic
encounter. Experts are split on their predictions though most
expect a slugfest. That's helped make the fight only the fourth
Garden sellout in history. This time ringside seats went for
$1,500, yet I don't think you'll get more for your money than
Ali-Frazier offered.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Ali, the fight game was raised to high drama. A
classy, stylish boxer, he was an extrovert who thrived on media
attention. Frazier, on the other hand, was the fearsome puncher,
who was intensely private away from the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier grew up poor in Beaufort S.C., the son of a struggling
farmer and bootlegger. He migrated to Philadelphia and became a
real life Rocky, working in a slaughterhouse where he tenderized
sides of beef with that left hook. Eventually, he won the
heavyweight crown stripped from Ali
</P>
<P>
   To return to the ring, Ali enlisted Frazier's vocal support. But
soon after reinstatement, Ali _ whether simply selling wolf tickets
or blatantly violating all cannons of fairness and decency _ began
to humiliate Frazier. He called him a gorilla, then painted him as
an ignorant errand boy for White America, a shuffling, mumbling
Uncle Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier _ whose whole life had been defined by being poor and
black _ felt betrayed and could barely control his rage The
electricity of the confrontation crackled through the Garden crowd
on fight night and then _ with the opening bell _ Ali and Frazier
turned up the juice even more.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 rounds, Frazier had beaten Ali's handsome face lopsided
and won a unanimous decision. But Ali salvaged something greater _
he got respect. It came in the final round when Frazier dropped him
with a thunderous left hook. No one thought Ali would survive, but
instead he climbed to his feet and fought on, forever erasing
questions of his courage.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward both men went to the hospital. Ali got a brief exam,
but Frazier needed a month of checkups for exhaustion, high blood
pressure and kidney problems. Ali would needle him about that until
it almost seemed as if he'd won the first bout, just as he would
the last two.
</P>
<P>
   That was the magic of Ali and why he once said: ``When I'm gone,
boxing will be nothing. The fans with cigars and hats turned down
will be there, but no more housewives and little men in the street
and foreign presidents. It's going back to the fighter who comes to
town, smells a flower, visits a hospital, blows a horn and says
he's in shape. Old hat. I was the onliest boxer in history people
asked questions of like a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, just before he left his training camp in the
Poconos, Lennox Lewis stressed to everyone that he was in shape. He
wore a white cap. It looked kind of old.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
