<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3102 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PARK10-COX     03-09 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PARK10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park faces memories of AMS crash in Atlanta return
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a year ago Saturday that Bob Park got the
telephone call from Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Park, a gear specialist for Dale Earnhardt Inc., was preparing
to drive to Atlanta for last year's Primestar 500 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. His son, rookie driver Steve Park, was going to make his
eighth start on NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Park and his wife, Dorothy, wouldn't be making the drive
from Charlotte, N.C. last March 6. Instead, Earnhardt was sending
his private jet. Only minutes earlier, Steve Park had been
air-lifted to Georgia Baptist Hospital after hitting the pit-road
wall head on in his No. 1 Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was headed to the track the day it happened,'' Bob Park
recalled. ``It was a long plane ride, especially not knowing
exactly what had happened. We didn't know the extent of his
injuries, mentally or physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Park suffered a broken right leg, left collarbone and
right shoulder in the wreck, which occurred after something in the
right side of his car broke. As he exited turn 4 of the 1.54-mile
oval during a Friday practice session, Park's car veered into the
outside wall and then careened into the wall on the front
straightaway. His car cut across the infield grass and hit the
pit-road wall at nearly 140 mph. It took medics several minutes to
extricate Park, but, miraculously, he suffered no internal or head
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit the wall, I wanted to get out of the car to see
what was wrong, but I couldn't move,'' Park said. ``I looked down
and saw my leg and knew I wouldn't be jumping out of any car for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, 31, didn't return to racing until August and missed nearly
half of the 1998 season. He didn't finish higher than 11th in the
17 races after his return. He says he has put the accident in the
past, but it undoubtedly derailed what had been a very promising
start to his career.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Park returns to Atlanta for Sunday's Cracker Barrel
Old Country Store 500. It will be his second trip to AMS since the
severe crash _ he finished 17th in last year's season-finale in
Atlanta _ and Park says he has faced his bad memories much as he
did his wreck _ head on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back to Atlanta in November and pretty much got rid of
any demons that were still there after the wreck,'' he said. ``You
don't totally forget that this is a track where you got hurt, but
once you are in the race car, you don't have a lot of time to dwell
on that type of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, Park was hand-picked by ``The
Intimidator'' to drive DEI's Busch car. Earnhardt made the
surprising choice after watching Park finish 11th in a Craftsman
Truck Series race in 1996 and again when he won the pole in a truck
event at Watkins Glen later that season.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1996, Earnhardt called Park's home in
Connecticut and left a message on his answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I checked, there were about 20 messages, so I'm buzzing
through them, taking down the important ones,'' Park said. ``In the
middle of all the messages, came the voice of some guy saying he
was Dale Earnhardt, and he was looking for a guy named Steve Park.
I just kind of laughed and continued on my way. I have a lot of
friends who like to play jokes, so I figured that it was just
somebody messing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Park was hired to drive for Earnhardt, and he won
rookie of the year in the Busch Series in 1997. Last year, he
finished 41st and 31st at Daytona but failed to qualify at the
third race in Las Vegas. Park wrecked the next week at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing is a high-speed sport, but sometimes the fastest thing
about racing isn't the car,'' he said. ``It's how fast you can go
from the top of the world to the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Park started this season where he left off last year _ near the
bottom. While some have questioned whether he lost his edge after
the accident, Park attributes the slow start to poor luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the 135th lap of the season-opening Daytona 500, Park got
knocked out of the race when teammates Dale Jarrett and Kenny Irwin
wrecked. He finished 34th.
</P>
<P>
   At Rockingham the next week, Park passed about 25 cars in the
first 100 laps. But when he pitted during lap 209, a yellow flag
came out while he was still on pit road, relegating him to a
26th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Park finished 16th in the Las Vegas 400, but he took that outing
with a grain of salt. With about 60 laps remaining in the 267-lap
event, Park was one of only a few drivers who could have finished
the race without making another pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   With only 32 laps remaining, however, NASCAR officials put out
the yellow flag when they spotted oil on the pavement. The leaders
were able to return to pit road for fuel and new tires.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Atlanta, Park says his team is encouraged. He says
his accident at AMS last year has helped put things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned not to take what I have now for granted and how
fleeting this whole thing can be,'' he said. ``I mean that as far
as career-wise, health-wise and life-wise. It may sound crazy, but
that wreck did more for my desire than anything could have.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
