r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MAKEOVER10-CO     03-09 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MAKEOVER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    75 pounds lighter, she's ready for a new look
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This is one of those times when math is
fun.
</P>
<P>
   From 211 pounds to 136. From size 18 to size 8.
</P>
<P>
   After trying and failing with numerous diets, Jodie Conrad moved
from New York to Wellington in 1996 and decided to make a few
``lifestyle changes.''
</P>
<P>
   She left a stressful job in retail management. She joined Weight
Watchers _ for the third time _ and started walking every day. In a
year and a half, she lost 75 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the mind-set _ you've got to be ready, even the weeks
when you lose nothing,'' said Conrad, 42 and the mother of two
boys.
</P>
<P>
   Now she works part time for Weight Watchers as a receptionist
and group leader, talking others through their diets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm a leader, I've got to give the appearance of
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So the folks at Salon Margrit in Palm Beach took over. Conrad
describes herself as ``one of those people who goes from place to
place'' for hair care. Her salon visits consist of a cut and color,
nothing more. For makeup she wears blush, lip gloss and a concealer
with sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Jaye Bryant, a stylist at Salon Margrit, checked out Conrad's
coarse, dark-brown hair. There was too much of it, she said,
``distributed all over her head; you don't know where to look.''
Also, the color was too dark for her skin tone.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant added red and gold highlights in front but left the rest
alone. Stylist Michel Loeb trimmed and layered Conrad's hair for a
more controlled, professional look.
</P>
<P>
   Then they waxed the undersides of Conrad's eyebrows and the area
between the brows to open up the eye area more.
</P>
<P>
   On to makeup. ``I want to open the eyes. They're one of her
stronger features,'' said makeup artist Mary Ann Ceccarelli.
</P>
<P>
   She worked quickly, applying concealer, even on the eyelids, to
even out Conrad's skin tones. Then she added a light beige
eyeshadow, black eyeliner and mascara. She lined her lips in mauve
and filled them in with plum lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Then, hustling to catch the last bit of sunlight for the
``after'' photo, the staff put Conrad in a black cardigan (on
backward for a better neckline), a silver necklace and clip-on
earrings.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very nice!'' she said. ``Obviously, I'm not going to have
the makeup as jazzed up, but the hair is easy. I would just blow it
dry and push it to the side.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
