<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, March 9, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEDESTRIAN-DEATHS (San Francisco) _ The dramatic rise in
pedestrian deaths in San Francisco has prompted calls for public
hearings on how to make the streets safer. In the one-year period
ending June 30, 1998, 39 pedestrians were killed on city streets,
and another two were mowed down on local highways, according to the
San Francisco medical examiner's office. During the previous year,
23 pedestrians lost their lives in San Francisco. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   CHINTATOWN-GANGS (San Francisco) _ In his forthcoming book,
``Chinese Playground: A Memoir,'' Bill Lee provides the first
insider look into the lethal mix of youthful bravado, cultural
maladjustment and turf warfare that culminated in the 1977 shootout
at the Golden Dragon restaurant, one of the worst massacres in San
Francisco history. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GE-WELCH (Clifton Park, N.Y.) _ The General Electric Co. will
outperform the Standard &AMP; Poor's Index this year as it prepares for
a change in its top leadership, Chairman John F. Welch Jr. said.
Welch's successor is expected to take over in 2000. But who the
next GE chairman will be is a matter of speculation. By KENNETH C.
CROWE II.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEWBORNS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Besides the routine physicals and
vaccinations, Dr. Kevin Karpowicz dispenses a lot of parenting
advice. For a newborn, he believes nothing is better than a
parent's love and attention to ensure a good foundation for the
child's future. If that sounds like common sense, you're not too
far behind the last research in infant brain development, much of
which builds on age-old parenting techniques rather than expensive
toys or classes. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   UMBILICAL-CORDS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Sue Tighe wanted to donate her
newborn's umbilical cord blood for good use. ``Otherwise it just
goes down the drain, so why not bank it?'' she asked. Tighe, who
had her son in December, was talking about one of the newer
innovations in transplant science. Blood from a newborn's discarded
umbilical cord offers a dense concentration of stem cells _ the
same stuff found in bone marrow, the manufacturing center for
healthy blood cells. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-WEIGHT (San Francisco) _ What happens to a woman's body
between the time she graduates from college and then enters
menopause some 30 years later is enough to send her to a shrink.
Depressing? Well, unless a figure stays basically the same through
childbirth, hormone replacement and just plain gravity _ and
believe it or not, some women are able to keep their girlish
figures through excellent genes or rigorous dieting and exercise _
clothing sizes creep up along with those extra pounds. By CYNTHIA
ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-DiMAGGIO-COOPERSTOWN (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ The Hall of Fame
Gallery is a mausoleum of sorts, dedicated to the immortals of
baseball's past. It is a place in the National Baseball Hall of
Fame and Museum where talk is naturally muted, reserved for
reverential, hushed tones. On Monday, that quiet was amplified and
echoed. Joe DiMaggio, the game's designated Greatest Living Player,
was dead. It was a time to pay respects to one of the most
respected players in the history of sport. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-DiMAGGIO-APPRECIATION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Where have you gone,
Joe DiMaggio? I don't have the connections to find out the answer.
All I have are my hopes and prayers. This is what I hope. This is
what I pray. That DiMaggio is in a place where he is forever young
on the outside, with a lifetime's worth of wisdom on the inside. By
STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Everybody has a DiMaggio story,
even my dad, who used to play golf with Joe's brother Dom, a great
player for the Red Sox who always suffered by comparison with the
Yankee Clipper. They're talking about Joe on Cape Cod, in Iowa and
in Cuba. In New York, Mayor Giuliani is talking about naming the
West Side Highway after DiMaggio, probably because Giuliani wants
to put a new Yankee Stadium next to the highway. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany. N.Y.) _ I'll let you in on a little secret
about northern cities like Albany. The cops know about it, and so
does everybody else with any experience with the criminal justice
system. That secret is this: In cold weather, a certain percentage
of the residents of any local jail are people for whom doing time
constitutes a winter vacation. The rest of the year, they're on the
street. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE-BIRTHDAY (Danville, Calif.) _ Wednesday is the
anniversary of the world's first phone call. Lines have been busy
ever since. On March 10, 1876, in the course of an experiment in
the extremely new field of telephony, Alexander Graham Bell
successfully transmitted a one-sentence message to his partner Tom
Watson, who was standing next door by a large receiver. It was the
birth of a revolution. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
