<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, March 10, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ A lot has been written about birth order and how
it affects children. I do know the oldest child often is the
high-achieving, angst-ridden, overly responsible one. The middle
child's existence typically is a lifelong scream for attention. And
the youngest many times is spoiled, laid back, easygoing and the
happiest of the bunch. You see, by the time the last child comes
along, the parents have foregone all their high-falutin' parenting
skills, relaxed, and just allowed that baby to develop as he or she
was meant to. Those stereotypes may hold some truth, but there are
certain burdens the youngest child must bear. (Kabat, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ In questioning a company's conviction in the
Mike Espy case, Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer wondered if,
in matters such as questionable gifts, ethics regulations aren't
preferable to ``bringing the blunderbuss of federal law into the
prosecutor's arsenal, where they can prosecute trivialities.'' If
that doesn't make sense to you, it's probably because you haven't
heard a sane voice for so long. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ There is no telling how many hundreds
have drowned attempting to escape the hellish depressiveness of
Haiti, a country that has little to no economy and has had no
working government for almost two years and likely has no prospect
of one until November, if then. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist
for Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Contrary to youthful belief,
life in the '50s happened in vivid color. Whether it was better
than now or worse, I can't say. It was just different. But I
suspect it was also a heck of a lot easier. (Elizabeth Schuett, a
teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio, writes twice a week for Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
