<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      03-09 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CENTENARIANS: THE STORY OF THE 20TH CENTURY BY THE AMERICANS WHO
LIVED IT &QL; 
 &UR; Bernard Edelman (FSG, $35)
</P>
<P>
   You don't need Peter Jennings to tell you about the past 100
years when you can listen to Philip Lord Carret _ born in 1896,
founder of one of the first mutual funds, called the ``Lou Gehrig
of investing'' by no less than Warren Buffett, survivor of 31 bull
markets, 30 bear markets, 20 recessions and the Great Depression.
Or Audrey Stubbart, born in 1895, a wife at age 15, mother at age
17, Wyoming homesteader, publishing copy editor and, until well
past her 100th birthday, a proofreader and columnist for the
Independence (Mo.) ``Examiner.'' Or Chester Cornelius ``Red'' Hoff,
born in 1891, the major league baseball player who, in 1911,
playing for the New York Highlanders, struck out Ty Cobb. Or Victor
Mills, born in 1897, inventor of Pampers disposable diapers and
Pringles potato chips. Edelman conducted interviews for this book
from 1995 through April, with centenarians who told stories about
their lives and about 100 years of American troubles and triumphs.
He groups their anecdotes under subheadings (Love and Marriage,
Pride and Prejudice, Prohibition, The Great Depression, The Second
World War, etc.) that make them easy to read in small doses. Of all
the recent books on the 20th century, this is the most charming.
``Never look back,'' says Geneva McDaniel, at age 111 the oldest of
Edelman's interviews. ``You always have to look forward. And
whatever you do, do it well.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ME &QL; 
 &UR; Jimmy (Big Boy) Valente as told to Garrison Keillor (Viking,
 &UR; $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   In November of last year, a professional wrestler named Jesse
``The Body'' Ventura was elected governor of Minnesota. Garrison
Keillor was watching, of course, although we do not know how he
voted. He was largely unfamiliar with Ventura, so in the spirit of
political inquiry, he rented a videotape of highlights from
Ventura's wrestling career and discovered that the governor-elect
had made his living by wearing a pink boa and dangling earrings and
hitting other men with folding chairs. Keillor was mildly impressed
_ ``I admired his chutzpah,'' he says, ``not a quality one
associates with Minnesotans'' _ but was unsure that he could write
anything fresh about a boa-wearing politician. In the end, he says,
because Ventura ``is his own invention and is in the midst of a
period of intense re-invention and realignment, it made sense to
write a work of fiction.'' Enter Jimmy (Big Boy) Valente, who is
none too kicked off about the ghostwriter sent by his publisher
(``I specifically asked them to assign a California writer, or a
European, someone who could appreciate me as an individual, and I
specifically said, `Not a Minnesotan,' so who do they send?'').
Indeed, Jimmy complains, Keillor is ``a tired old hack with a gecko
face and thinning hair and a body like a 6-foot stack of
marshmallows.'' This memoir is Jimmy's triumph over Keillor's
shortcomings. We learn of Jimmy's early life as a wimp named
Clifford Oxnard, of the mail-order body-building course that saved
him, of his enlistment in the Navy's elite Walrus program and his
service in Vietnam, of his entry into professional wrestling and
politics and his meeting with his hero, Arnold Schwarzenegger. We
think Jimmy should send copies of this to Paul Reiser, Chris Rock
and others who have written allegedly funny books, so they can see
what the real thing is. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; COWBOY: A LOVE STORY &QL; 
 &UR; Sara Davidson (HarperCollins, $24)
</P>
<P>
   ``How old are you?'' she asked. ``Thirty-nine,'' he said. ``Do
you know how old I am?'' she asked. ``No, ma'am, that's none of my
business.'' ``Older than you,'' she admitted. ``You've vintaged
well,'' he replied. She lived in Los Angeles, where she wrote
scripts for television's ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman.'' He was a
poor cowboy who lived in a trailer in Casa Grande. He wrote her a
note after they met at a cowboy poetry festival, and every third
word was misspelled. But her affair with a record producer wasn't
going well, so she invited the cowboy to come to Los Angeles for a
weekend. By the time she dropped him off at the airport for the
return trip to Phoenix, they had hit the sheets with a vengeance
and she was telling him she loved him. That's the way it goes in
this story of an affair between two people from different worlds.
Davidson (``Loose Change'') tells all _ more, in fact, than we ever
wanted to know _ although she uses fake names to preserve the
privacy of her children and her cowboy. That hardly seems necessary
_ if he's anything like she says he is, we doubt he'll ever read
it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HITCHCOCK'S NOTEBOOKS &QL; 
 &UR; Dan Auiler (Avon, $30)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Hitchcock's opinion was that Fontaine was just too coy
and simpering to a degree that it was intolerable. She thought her
voice was irritating and was distressed about the whole thing.''
Those lines are from a memo written by Alfred Hitchcock to David
Selznick after he'd shown his wife, Alma, Joan Fontaine's screen
test for ``Rebecca.'' Auiler includes lot of other correspondence,
the storyboards for the crop-dusting and Mount Rushmore scenes from
``North by Northwest,'' Hitchcock's rough sketches for the shower
sequence in ``Psycho,'' transcripts of meetings between Hitchcock
and Tippi Hedren during the making of ``The Birds,'' and screenplay
draft comparisons that show the evolution of the script for ``The
Paradine Case'' and the interplay among the director, his wife and
the writer. Auiler is the author of ``Vertigo: The Making of a
Hitchcock Classic.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
