<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3188 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FESTIVAL-AZR &LR;      03-09 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FESTIVAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAGSTAFF'S BOOK FESTIVAL: A LITERARY MIRACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unread story, Ursula Le Guin once wrote, is not really a
story at all, but ``little black marks on wood pulp. The reader,
reading it, makes it live: a living thing, a story.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 17, readers and writers will come together to celebrate
their stories at the second annual Northern Arizona Book Festival,
four days of readings and panel discussions throughout Flagstaff,
Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Among the writers will be Nobel Prize winner Czeslaw Milosz;
Michael Ondaatje, whose novel, ``The English Patient,'' won the
Booker Prize and was the basis of 1997's Academy Award Best Picture
winner; Russell Banks (``Cloudsplitter''and ``The Sweet
Hereafter''); and biographer Ron Chernow, who won the National Book
Award for ``The House of Morgan'' and critical acclaim last year
for ``Titan: The Life of John D. Rockefeller Sr.''
</P>
<P>
   Other participating authors include Grace Paley, Cristina
Garcia, Robert Pinsky, Dorothy Allison, Anchee Min, Bharati
Mukherjee, Leslie Marmon Silko, Susan Straight, Carolyn See, Ron
Carlson, David Haynes, Jewell Parker Rhodes, Daisy Zamora and Luis
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The slate is long, diverse and unabashedly literary, perhaps
because the organizers of the festival, which is sponsored by
Literacy Volunteers of Coconino County, set the bar so high last
year when their headliners were Banks and Nobel Prize-winning
novelist Toni Morrison. More than 4,000 people came out to see
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they really were interested in the immensity of it,''
says Jeff Biggers, 36, the festival's artistic director. ``It was
very high-caliber, and it wasn't just one or two big names. If we'd
only had Toni Morrison, it would have been just a lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``People liked having lots of readings to choose from, and they
liked the panels because we had unusual topics that started funny
and meaningful discussions. It almost seemed as if the smaller
events drew the greatest enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a constant schedule of author readings, this
year's festival will feature discussions on women in world
literature, the work of Edward Abbey and the place of literature in
commercial publishing. There will be appearances by theologian and
social activist William Sloane Coffin ``in conversation'' with
Chernow and Milosz. And like last year's festival, this one will
include ``poetry cafes,'' in which high school students read their
own poetry to some very sophisticated audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids read last year to standing room only,'' says
Priscilla Aydelott, who in June became director of the Literacy
Volunteers but before that taught English at Monument Valley High
School in Kayenta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joy Harjo was there, and Luis Rodriguez and Cin Salach. The
kids couldn't believe that writers like that had come to hear them.
They had fireworks in their eyes, constantly. It validated their
feelings and their sense of who they were and what sort of impact
they could have on the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Root, who came with his students from Hopi High School in
Keams Canyon, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best experiences they ever had,'' he says.
``I have the feeling that even if we'd flopped, we would still be
invited back _ that's how welcome we felt. But the kids got up
there and did great. It gave them a chance to see themselves as
poets. I sure was proud of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The schools are not the only participants coming back. Banks
will return (he appeared at the festival last year just as the
movie version of ``The Sweet Hereafter'' opened, and he comes now
after the release here of ``Affliction,'' which is based on his
1989 novel), as will Dorothy Allison, Alfredo Vea Jr., Susan
Straight, Quincy Troupe, Luis Rodriguez, John Nichols, Demetria
Martinez, Martin Espada, Ron Carlson and Jewell Parker Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That core group of regulars gives us a certain depth of
experience,'' Biggers says. ``Besides, these writers are important.
They should be household names. They are making major impacts in
poetry and literary fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   They also had a real good time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of us are coming back just because it was fun,'' Vea
says. ``It wasn't like other festivals. It was so naturally done.
It wasn't self-conscious. There were no imperious matrons running
around in a huff, getting people here and there. It was a community
festival. Writers stayed in local hotels, and they walked from one
venue to the next with other writers and with people from the
community. There was no distance between them and the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of mouth also helped _ Banks and Ondaatje are friends, and
Banks encouraged Ondaatje to accept an invitation to Flagstaff this
year.
</P>
<P>
   All of this contentment is due in large part to the
persuasiveness and formidable organizing skills of Biggers, who,
Aydelott says, ``is not just an extraordinary man, but someone who
manages to make other people believe that they can be
extraordinary, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in southern Arizona, Biggers has worked in adult
education since the early 1980s, both in the United States and
abroad. He became director of Literacy Volunteers in 1994. In
addition to expanding its literacy program, he set out to launch a
creditable reading series that would bring writers to audiences who
had never seen them before.
</P>
<P>
   He started small, with local authors and with audiences composed
mostly of his own friends. But the series grew and received a boost
when Biggers began to work with New York's PEN American Center,
which sponsors a ``Readers and Writers'' program that sends
nationally known writers to rural communities across the country,
free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   In Kayenta, Aydelott was already working with PEN American, and
she and Biggers became part of a cluster of PEN American sites
throughout Arizona. Among the writers who have come through the
program are Dorothy Allison, Sherman Alexie, Joy Harjo and Cristina
Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we had all these great writers visiting,'' Biggers says,
``and I said to each of them, `Hey, if I could bring you all back
at one time, would you be interested?' They all said `Sure.' And I
said, `Well, would you help me by cutting your fees? Because I
can't afford you all at once.' It turned out that many of these
wonderful writers were willing to come for next to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggers still depends on such kindnesses, but fund-raising is
easier after last year's success. The Northern Arizona University
Centennial Committee has been so generous this year that Biggers
refers to it as a ``co-sponsor.'' Other funders include the
Flagstaff Arts and Science Commission, the Marshall Fund and the
Arizona Commission on the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will cost roughly $70,000, Biggers says. Almost all
of it will go toward authors' fees, travel costs and
accommodations. The festival itself will be run by a small army of
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any problem asking for money,'' Biggers says,
``because I believe so much in what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the country is beginning to notice. Chernow, who was
chairman of the Readers and Writers program last year, met Biggers,
Aydelott and other people from the program's Arizona sites when
they came to a meeting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jeff told me about his festival, I asked him how many
people came last year,'' Chernow says. ``I thought he'd say he had
a few hundred people, but when he told me he had a few thousand,
that the entire town was swept up in it, I began to be very
excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to seeing firsthand what he has done. If
it's as good as I suspect it is, it could be a model, it could be
imitated by other parts of the country that aren't on the standard
writers' circuit. I'm always surprised by how imaginative and
enthusiastic people like Jeff and the others from Arizona can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggers would take that compliment for what it is, a sign that
any effort on behalf of literature should be noticed and enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can do this in Flagstaff _ if I can sell this wildly
diverse and very serious slate of writers and pull in thousands of
people to see them _ then we should be doing this in New York, in
LA, in San Francisco, in Phoenix,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books matter. Events like this enrich our lives. We come
together, we find out we have common stories and we have things we
need to discuss. Writers play a huge role in that. They not only
tell our stories, but they help us to understand who we are.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
