<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PARIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marc Jacobs has `ho-hum' in the bag
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Any designer who has his own New York-based signature
collections to produce twice yearly, as well as collections for a
luxury Parisian label, needs a deep bag of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   At least Marc Jacobs, who designs for Louis Vuitton, got the
deep-bag part right.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the buyers, editors and groupies attending Vuitton's
fall/winter runway preview Monday wondered what the purple leather
wristbands they'd received with their invitations signified.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came quickly when the first models strolled out
toting enormous red and purple backpacks, purses and suitcases
plastered with the Vuitton logo.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Jacobs, the darling of Seventh Avenue in spite of his
rebellious streak, intended the bags as a mockery. But of what? Was
he poking fun at his Paris employers, whose handbags are
distributed more widely than their apparel? Was he satirizing the
industry's love affair with small, ultra-modern ``utility'' bags?
Or were his gargantuan bags symbols of defiance against threatened
U.S. trade sanctions that could cause luxury goods from Vuitton to
double in price?
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the bags were merely meant to serve as distractions
from Jacobs' designs. The collection featured flashes of the
brilliance that's made him one of the industry's most mimicked
designers, but for the most part it was dull.
</P>
<P>
   The primary colors were black, tan, moss and brown, with
splashes of red and orange interjected occasionally. The
form-fitting jackets and sweaters, paired with loose skirts or
flared pants, created an A-line silhouette that's already been
shown on countless runways in New York and Milan, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs distinguished Vuitton from other collections, however, in
the way he cut the waistbands: They rose high and loose above the
navel and were tied Elly May Clampett-style, with leather cords.
Jacobs also did interesting things with a foamy metallic fabric
that took the form of suits and eveningwear separates. And he
showed a few of the plush turtlenecks seen this season.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, very little leather was used, and most of the
collection was logo-free. Only the most faithful Vuitton customers
would recognize the label's signature diamond pattern as it was
applied to a few dresses and ponchos.
</P>
<P>
   This was a collection for those who'd grown weary of making
blind-faith purchases and needed their brand loyalty challenged
anew.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
