<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEINSTEIN RENEWS PUSH TO EXPAND ASSAULT WEAPONS BAN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., renewed her effort
Tuesday to clamp more federal controls on rapid-fire guns.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the 1994 law that banned the manufacture of 19
types of semiautomatic weapons reintroduced a bill that would close
what Feinstein called a ``major loophole'' in the law. The loophole
allows imports of so-called clips or magazines that hold more than
10 rounds of ammunition if they were made before the end of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intended to ban the manufacture of all high-capacity clips,
leaving only a narrow clause allowing for the importation of clips
already on their way into this country,'' Feinstein explained.
</P>
<P>
   She said she and other lawmakers who agreed to the clause didn't
realize it would result in millions of high-capacity clips being
allowed into the United States more than four years later.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that, despite the ban on importing post-1994
foreign-made high-capacity clips, U.S. law enforcement officials
have no way of determining when such clips were made. Their
manufacturers simply claim they were made before 1995, Feinstein
said, adding that 128 million high-capacity clips have since
entered the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American companies have been banned from making such clips since
the 1994 assault-weapons ban became law. But U.S.-made
high-capacity clips are still legal to buy and sell as long as they
were made before 1995. Unlike foreign-made high-capacity clips, the
U.S. clips contain serial numbers that allow them to be tracked
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation would not ban the sale or possession of clips
already in circulation,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   She appeared at a news conference Tuesday flanked by police
officers and local government officials who told of recent
shootings in which the gunmen had weapons with high-capacity clips.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Kerns, deputy police chief of Oakland, Calif., said officer
James Williams was killed there in January when a man using an
AK-47 with two 30-round Chinese-made clips opened fire on Williams.
Kerns said the incident was over before the police officers who
were with Kerns knew what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Senate defeated a similar bill authored by
Feinstein. She said she is more optimistic that the measure will
pass this year because the Senate has nine new members. But the
margins are still the same with Republicans controlling 55 seats
and the Democrats controlling 45 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's bill has the support of the National League of
Cities as well as law enforcement groups. She said she plans to
take more time building support among lawmakers this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was just thrown on the floor,'' Feinstein said of
the bill. She noted that it was defeated only a few days after
Russell Eugene Weston Jr., a former mental patient from Montana,
went on a rampage in the U.S. Capitol July 25, shooting and killing
two police officers there with a Smith &AMP; Wesson revolver.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Diana DeGette, D-Colo. introduced a measure identical to
Feinstein's in the House Tuesday. ``Instead of a stop-gap
compromise, we got a Mack-truck sized loophole,'' DeGette said of
the 1994 law. ``There's no legitimate purpose for these clips other
than to kill human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein and DeGette said they intend to keep reintroducing
their legislation until it becomes law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
