SOMETIMES THE REMOTEST DETAILS CAN RUIN YOUR DAY (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can't believe it. I have six remote controls in my lap and not
a single one of them works on this television.
</P>
<P>
   I've been sitting here for 20 minutes, watching ``Rugrats,''
hoping that one of my kids would pass by and change the channel for
me. I wouldn't mind so much if it was ``Teletubbies'' or one of
those other R-rated children's programs, but I'd rather be watching
Rather.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that I could summon one of the boys from their room
but my dad used to do that to me and it really irritated me. I
promised myself that I would never do that to my kids. Now I
realize that Dad must have been as tired as I am this evening. I
just do not have the strength to walk that whole six or seven feet
to the TV and possibly strain my already weak eyes trying to
distinguish the volume buttons from the channel buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Six remotes and I can't change the channel.
</P>
<P>
   This brown one worked fine until we lost the battery cover and
started using tape to keep the AAs from falling out. Now it's
useless.
</P>
<P>
   I don't even know where this long gray one came from. We don't
own an RCA television, but I tried it anyway, just in case. It
doesn't work either.
</P>
<P>
   The black remote will turn the TV on or off, but it won't change
the channels. This expensive, universal remote has always confused
me. Sometimes it works if you stand a few inches from the screen. I
tried that a few minutes ago but nothing happened so I came back to
my chair and sat down.
</P>
<P>
   I think this small, square remote is for the stereo, but I'm not
sure. It does make the floor lamp blink on and off like a strobe
light, which may come in handy later but is of no use to me at this
time. You know, this other thing is the cordless phone. No wonder
it wouldn't control the television. But that does explain the
strange sounds it made when I pressed the buttons.
</P>
<P>
   This kids' show is making me looney. Someone has got to change
the channel! OK, I'm down to my last resort. I'm going to light a
candle. It's a scented candle that's guaranteed to attract
children. I haven't tried it before. I've been saving it for an
emergency. This is definitely an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Wow, only five minutes passed before a child appeared and said,
``Mom, is that popcorn I smell?''
</P>
<P>
   I quickly extinguish the candle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sweetie, that must be coming from the neighbor's house,'' I
reply. ``But do you mind turning to Channel 8 for me?''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, it worked like a charm.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's remote control.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
