<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MESSY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NY     03-09 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MESSY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY I LOVE A MESSY HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  By SUZANNE MATSON 
 c.1999 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For me, order and pleasure go hand in hand. I like a sock drawer
full of neatly rolled balls, a lingerie drawer in which things are
stacked by category. Tables and counters should have only what is
supposed to be on them and no more, their clear surfaces a sign
that life is in harmonious balance.
</P>
<P>
   These standards were formed before I had children.
</P>
<P>
   Before the birth of my two boys, each day's mail was sorted soon
after it arrived. Bills went to the bill folder, junk mail to the
recycling bin, personal mail to a drawer where letters could be
reread and answered.
</P>
<P>
   Before kids, my clothes and my husband's clothes hung tidily in
our closets, our shoes lined up by twos. When pictures came back
from the photo shop, I put the best ones in an album and filed the
rest by date. Dishes were washed as we used them.
</P>
<P>
   Some would say I was too neat. My husband still can't believe
that he once walked into the kitchen and saw me stapling a bag of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, I couldn't even find the stapler if I had a mind
to go sealing up the sugar, flour or rice. If I did find it,
probably in the Tupperware drawer or the magazine rack, you can bet
it would have no staples.
</P>
<P>
   My behavior modification program in learning to live with a mess
(OK, chaos) advanced in stages. When my first son, Nicholas, was a
newborn who stayed in one place, I could round up stray burp cloths
and booties several times a day. I could arrange his stuffed
animals in an esthetically pleasing semicircle at one end of his
changing table. It was hard to get those tiny clothes to stay in
neat stacks in the drawer, but I tried. The only sign of eroding
order was the bed. Because I took naps when I could, and often lay
down with the baby to nurse, the bed tended to stay unmade for days
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicholas started crawling, things got complicated.
Suddenly, we needed lots of toys in lots of areas of the house. The
best arrangement for these, from the baby's point of view, was to
have them scattered all over the middle of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Had we been able to keep it at that, I would have been OK. But a
toddler can cross a room more quickly than the fastest crawler or
cruiser; this means he can be at the fireplace opening doors and
scooping up ashes with his toy backhoe before your mouth can form
the word no.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that your ``no'' has escalated to ``NO!'' your
toddler has vanished into the kitchen to serve himself from the
pitcher of juice you keep in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, with one child, even a dynamo toddler, I found I
still had a fighting chance of straightening up once a day, though
I often had to wait until late evening.
</P>
<P>
   Then our second baby, Henry, arrived, and suddenly we had two
sets of toys on the floor, two sizes of dirty clothes scattered
about, twice as many used diapers overflowing the trash bags, and
Hot Wheels, Hot Wheels everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   With two kids, there is twice the stuff flying around and half
the time to deal with it. After two bathtimes, two bedtimes, two
daycare bags packed for the next day, dinner dishes and laundry, my
husband and I barely have the energy to brush our own teeth before
bed_forget about picking up the clutter.
</P>
<P>
   There is no choice but to surrender to the flow. Parents of
young children are so tuned to the elemental_ food, safety,
comfort, love_so focused on the urgent promptings of the moment,
that even the most committed neatnik has to let go.
</P>
<P>
   I am proud to say that I can now weave a path through our
cyclone-struck house with Zenlike detachment. Without pause I step
over the tote bags home from daycare with their bottles to be
washed; pick my way around coats tossed on the floor; walk past the
breakfast dishes, the mail, the laundry waiting to tee forded. I
can almost ignore the sound of Cheerios crunching underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, I have not seen my boys all day. ``Mom, do you
want to play with me?'' my 3-year-old asks overturning the toy
basket in the den with a joyous racket and cascade of plastic. The
baby in my arms crows and squirms to be let loose in the pile.
</P>
<P>
   We play; we make a huge mess.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Suzanne Matson teaches at Boston College and is the author of
the novel ``The Hunger Moon,'' (Norton, $23.)) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
