<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF THE THANK-YOU NOTE (WITH ART)
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a horizontal color illustration of a hand writing a
thank-you note with a large quill. The Adobe Illustrator file is
available in minutes via e-mail by calling Joe Applegate at
212-499-3342 or graphics assistant William Gonzalez at 499-3355.)
 By DIANE LACEY ALLEN 
 c.1999 New York Times Newspaper Group 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For six decades now, Hazel Haley has been preaching the fine art
of the thank-you note.
</P>
<P>
   So when friends threw her a birthday party on a Sunday night not
long ago, she did exactly as any old-school English teacher would.
By Monday morning, Haley had dashed off, in her own handwriting,
the appropriate thank yous to her hostess and the guests who made
the get-together special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think any human relationship has ever been
damaged by a nice thank-you note. It should be done within 24 hours
after you get home from a visit or a party,'' says Haley, an honors
English teacher at Lakeland High School in Lakeland, Fla. ``I think
people of good breeding still send thank-you notes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the age of electronic mail, the thank-you note seems more
like a throwback to a time when correspondence came by Pony
Express. And while etiquette consultants say e-mail is better than
nothing, few well-chosen lines have the impact of ink on nice
stationery.
</P>
<P>
   Just as snail mail has prevailed, so has the time-honored
obligation of thanking someone for a present or good deed. Kids
still learn the basics in school as ``friendly letters'' _ a
process that begins in elementary school, with a few refreshers
before life's final exam of graduation gift thank yous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty is that we don't have many formal protocols
around the conventions of life,'' says Barbara Pachter, who teaches
business etiquette and communications to corporations. ``People go
into companies, and someone says hello to them, and they don't even
say hello back. People get so preoccupied, and it (writing
thank-you notes) hasn't been stressed enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As president of Pachter &AMP; Associates in Cherry Hill, N.J.,
Pachter knows people are busy. But claiming you don't have time,
she says, is no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only two to four sentences,'' Pachter says. ``Once people
get into the habit of doing it, it's not very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a competitive business climate, those who remember the
thank-you note have the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Pachter says. ``It stands out. To some degree,
they (bosses) expect them. But the quality of your writing counts.
I know of one young man who did not get the job, the promotion,
because after being interviewed he sent a thank-you note _ which is
good _ but it had typos and spelling errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Composing a thank-you card isn't rocket science. It requires
little more than the demure notes known as ``informals'' and a
sincere act of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   The date goes flush right. Under it, to the far left, is the
salutation or ``Dear Jane.''
</P>
<P>
   Indent, thank the person for a nice evening or gift. Talk about
the present during your breezy note. But if the gift was money, do
not use a dollar figure. Adjectives such as ``thoughtful'' or
``generous'' will get the point across.
</P>
<P>
   Haley advises recipients not be too specific about what they
plan to do with a gift of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Be polite, even if it's the sixth crockpot you received this
Christmas. It serves no purpose to say in the note that it will be
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Manners' Judith Martin is a champion of the personal note.
And while her normal credo encourages hostesses to be nice to
everyone, she turns acidic when it comes to brides who refuse to
send thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   In Martin's ``Guide to Excruciatingly Correct Behavior,'' she
answers the question, ``When is a written thank-you note for a
wedding gift not necessary?'' with cold simplicity: ``When no
wedding present has been received.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's weddings are often a cooperative effort between the
bride and groom. According to the etiquette-graced Emily Post,
brides usually write and sign thank-you notes because most gifts
are sent to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Post says, ``there is no reason the groom should not
share this task. There are many relatives and friends of the groom
who would be delighted to receive a thank-you note from him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also not incorrect to sign both names, although it is
preferable to sign only one name and include the other in the text:
``Bob and I are so delighted ...''
</P>
<P>
   Most thank-you notes, however, are a response to events other
than weddings. They are sent after dinner at a friend's home, for
gifts or for favors.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming Allaire, who has an etiquette hotline and is known as
``Dr. Manners,'' says the key to getting notes out is a little
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Allaire, who has a doctorate in education and lives in
Manchester, Conn., has a sure-fire method for making sure a gift is
acknowledged: ``Don't wear it, use it, eat it or spend it until
you've written the thank-you note.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (DIANE LACEY ALLEN writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. The
illustration is by ROBERT HOLST/NYTRENG Grahics) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
