<HEADLINE>
DREAMS TAKE OFF ON THIS RUNWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Strutting someday soon on an international
fashion runway: Sarah Alford.
</P>
<P>
   Or so she hopes. More than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Alford, 15, was one of more than 400 girls and women who showed
up at Dillard's at Scottsdale Fashion Square on Saturday, hoping to
have their faces and features grace an ad for Roxy, a clothing
line.
</P>
<P>
   Roxy and ``Seventeen'' magazine sponsored the model search.
Would-be Cindy Crawfords formed a line that snaked around several
corners as they waited, Polaroids in hand, for one brief trip down
a runway set up in the store.
</P>
<P>
   Most had the model strut down, if not the practiced boredom and
put-upon look favored by so many supermodels. (Give them time,
they're still learning.)
</P>
<P>
   But none had the confidence Alford possessed. Every 15-year-old
girl is the center of her own universe. The refreshing thing about
Alford, who lives in Phoenix, was how freely she admitted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very, very high self-esteem,'' she said. ``Too high. I
have to make myself look just perfect every day even though I'm
only going to school. You never know if there will be a talent
scout.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fashion sense &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alas, sometimes when the talent scouts are there, you don't have
your best day. Alford was decked out in a black halter top,
platform shoes _ that would have made the ``Goodbye Yellow Brick
Road''-era Elton John suffer vertigo _ and a red skirt slit so high
up her thigh a gust of wind would have gotten her arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But she wasn't happy with her runway performance, which included
blowing a kiss to the hundreds of people watching.
</P>
<P>
   She felt like she was too nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally I'm not that shy,'' she said, quickly recovering her
game face and adding, ``although I'd love to (model)
professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   She and everyone else in line. Though not everyone was so
upfront about her ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' Heidi Mendiola said. ``I'm not the one who
wants to do this. I'm just here to make her feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her'' was her friend Julie Ranoa, a confessed Roxy addict who
not only wore all Roxy clothes and a Roxy necklace but also showed
off (discreetly) the Roxy logo tattooed just above her hip.
</P>
<P>
   The two 19-year-olds had driven 12 hours from San Jose. Despite
the lack of sleep _ or maybe because of it _ they were plenty
perky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a fun thing,'' Ranoa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not like `if I don't win, my life is over.' We're going
to LA this summer,'' Mendiola added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're drama queens,'' Ranoa laughed. ``We want to go into
acting.''
</P>
<P>
   Always good to have a backup plan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Natural, informal look &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behind every good model, to mangle a phrase, is an understanding
mother. The line was peppered with several whose patience made Job
look like George Steinbrenner. Alford's mother, Sally, was one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's meant to be, it's meant to be,'' she said of her
daughter's goals. ``There are other things that are more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Without missing a beat, Sarah turned to her mother and said,
``Not to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When most people think of models, they think of tall, stark
beauties with physical attributes that defy gravity. That's not
what Roxy looks for, said Lori Weed, a Roxy representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want a professional model,'' she said. ``Our whole ad
campaign is based on the real girl. Just real natural, informal.''
</P>
<P>
   What about beauty? Not that important, she said. Think active,
healthy. She thumbed through a book of Roxy models to demonstrate.
All were indeed active-looking. And healthy.
</P>
<P>
   And _ what do you know? _ beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first stop on a five-city nationwide search. I
don't know if Weed and a ``Seventeen'' representative found what
they were looking for, but to the untrained eye, there was plenty
of model behavior.
</P>
<P>
   And if not? Nothing ventured, nothing gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to start somewhere,'' Mendiola said with a shrug.
And here was as good a place as any. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL; 
L
</P>
</TEXT>
