<SLUG> BC-MCGARVEY-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHIAPAS REVOLUTION' LANDS ON ARIZONA FRONT PORCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JACK MCGARVEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO RICO, Ariz. - During their brief respite at my Rio Rico
home, a Chiapas father and son consumed big bowls of rice and
ranchero beans, 24 smallish corn tortillas, and big salad plates of
lettuce, ripe tomatoes and sliced avocados that I garnished with
mayonnaise, red chile flakes and chopped cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   They also ate a dozen raw jalapenos and peeled four oranges.
They drank nearly a gallon of milk and later snacked on a bag of
microwave popcorn. They were astounded by the microwave. They also
drank a liter of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Father Ignacio and son Pedro were famished, having subsisted
only on cornmeal gruel during their two-month odyssey north to the
chilly Promised Land from the tropical, revolutionary Mexican state
of Chiapas. They walked on blistered feet, trudging into Arizona
armed only with dreams of a better life, while peeling out scant
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro, whose brown eyes brimmed with teenage optimism, had a
fever and hacking cough. I gave him aspirin and made him sleep for
eight hours in a warm bed instead of on cold ground.
</P>
<P>
   As Pedro slept, father Ignacio emptied his pockets to show me
his six remaining American dollars. He also showed me some fancy
Mexican documents which noted his occupation as ``campesino'' _
loosely translated as farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Ignacio and Pedro, Mayan Indians, were artists. When Pedro awoke
_ feeling somewhat better _ father and son sat elbow to elbow at my
coffee table to draw detailed pictures of my house, my car, the
valley below and the mountains beyond, their appealing drawings
telling the story of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ignacio told me he has hospitality waiting for me _ when, not if
_ I visit his wife and two daughters waiting back in Chiapas. I am
apparently expected there any day now.
</P>
<P>
   I really hated to see them leave. They were among the most
engaging folk I've met in quite a while. As I watched them walk
north along the Union Pacific Railroad tracks, they seemed so
conspicuous with their bad haircuts, short stature and
golden-brown, Mayan skin. When I turned away south to give my dogs
a walk, a Border Patrol helicopter, sounding like a loud lawn
mower, slid down over San Cayetano Mountain toward us.
</P>
<P>
   I expect that Ignacio and Juan likely will be nabbed by the
Border Patrol. But if they're vanned back across the border,
they'll try again. Ignacio told me they'd already been nabbed twice
before. No big deal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a millionaire, I'd work like hell to make them legal.
I'd open a nursery with Ignacio as manager. He's an expert on soil
and plants and knew all about the pocket gopher that's been gnawing
out the roots of my plants. I learned some new Spanish words, but
really learned nothing new from Ignacio about how to keep that
gopher's teeth from doing their damage, except by selling traps in
our new nursery. I'd also import Ignacio's wife and daughters and
send all their kids to college.
</P>
<P>
   Their desperate, two-month journey astounds me, and stirs
memories of my own Irish ancestors' ambition, four generations ago.
Any mystery as to why Mexican nationals keep trespassing into
Arizona has been dispelled. Ignacio told me the average Chiapas
wage is $2 a day. A diet of beans, rice and chiles consumes half of
that, he said, with little left over for schoolbooks.
</P>
<P>
   It is, though, such a helpless situation for this Chiapas father
and son. They bring only a desire to work hard and gardening skill,
which is very, very common and very cheap here in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   They have no friends or relatives in (begin ital) los estados
unidos. (end ital) They were headed for Phoenix, Ignacio said. But
it is Tucson they would first encounter. Imagine their shock of
trekking into huge Tucson from a rural Chiapas village, knowing
nobody.
</P>
<P>
   But I can't really worry about that, can I? It's their choice,
and I'll settle for having given Ignacio and Pedro some food and
warmth during their brief visit here. I'm not really surprised that
the ``Chiapas Revolution'' landed on the front porch of my Rio Rico
home.
</P>
<P>
   More Chiapas folk are on the way. Guaranteed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jack McGarvey is a writer in Rio Rico, Ariz. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
