<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GUITAR HERO' TIM REYNOLDS ENJOYS UNPLUGGED LIFE WITH DAVE
MATTHEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Calling from a hotel room in Indiana, Tim Reynolds
apologizes for technical difficulties that resulted in two abrupt
disconnections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand up and the cord falls right out of the thing,''
Reynolds says. ``Nice expensive hotel, but the phone sucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's just because it's probably been used the way I've
been using it . . . over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   It's probably something he should get used to. Reynolds, as in
Dave Matthews and Tim Reynolds, has been handling all the press for
the third acoustic tour featuring him and his good buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Matthews holds most of the name recognition, but
Reynolds is quickly connecting with Matthews' fans. The duo's
unplugged sessions are wildly popular, selling out in a matter of
minutes _ 15 in Phoenix's case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reynolds remains a mystery to some, namely those who live
outside of the Southeast and Charlottesville, Va., where he and
Matthews first met 10 years ago. Matthews worked as a bartender in
a local club, where Reynolds was playing gigs on Monday nights.
Once the two met, they began to jam, before Matthews formed his
band.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds says their gigs in the area were highly successful, and
once Matthews' band took off, a nationwide acoustic tour became
even more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a different way to present his songs,'' Reynolds
says. ``I think it opens up people's minds to the fact that he
really writes great songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds isn't so shabby himself. Besides Matthews calling him
his ``guitar hero,'' Reynolds has toyed with sitar, violin and
mandolin, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even list (the instruments) because I'm just too
neurotic to stay with one thing,'' Reynolds says. ``I don't
consider myself a master of many styles. But I consider myself a
master of my instrument. And, therefore, whatever style I want to
play, I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that sort of confidence that has Reynolds feeling good
about his own group, which currently has two different names: Tim
Reynolds and His Power Trio or Puke Matrix. Reynolds likes the
latter _ ``It just makes me giggle'' _ while his PR folks
undoubtedly prefer the former.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, his new CD has only one name, ``Tim Reynolds Live.''
To support the album, Reynolds has been ``burning up the road'' and
using his time with Matthews for further inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tours are real great,'' Reynolds says. ``My music
benefits from the activity of this.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, fatigue hasn't been an issue for Reynolds or Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tours are pretty relaxing, pretty user-friendly,''
Reynolds explains. ``It's just acoustic guitars with one tech
onstage. It's so easy . . . when you're like me and Dave _ we just
like to play.''
</P>
<P>
   However, an open-taping policy at the shows has caused some
difficulties with Matthews' record company. The sale of unofficial
_ and most times inaudible _ bootlegs has forced the label to file
injunctions against independent record stores that sell them.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Matthews and Reynolds released this year's
double-CD ``Live at Luther College.'' Reynolds isn't sure who makes
the decisions regarding the policy, but says he allows open taping
because ``it can only help the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, it doesn't seem as if Reynolds needs much help.
He has found what he thinks is his eternal resting place in Santa
Fe _ ``I will probably die there just because it's so awesome
there'' _ and has forged a name for himself sans Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if we can just get him a phone that works. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
