<HEADER>
A3254 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ORGANS-AZR &LR;      03-09 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ORGANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF ORGANS IS THE REAL PROBLEM  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE MARCH 8 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A quixotic bid to exempt Arizona from a national human
organ allocation system should make people sick. The national plan
itself could make people sicker.
</P>
<P>
   Both systems prompt shouts of protest. But when the shouting is
done, when all arguments are made about any system of rationing
human body parts, a somber reality sinks in: No matter which system
is in place, patients will die because of a severe shortage of
lifesaving organs.
</P>
<P>
   Two proposals before the Arizona Legislature would essentially
reject the national plan. Under these proposals, organs harvested
in Arizona would stay in Arizona when at all possible. The sickest
patients would be first in line for transplants, followed by those
less sick on waiting lists here. Only when there were no matches in
Arizona would organs be offered to patients outside of the state.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Sue Grace, R-Phoenix, says her bill is her best
attempt to send Washington a message. Even if the message is
received, federal rule likely would supersede state law.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services wants to
replace local systems with a national plan. Donated organs would go
to the sickest patients in the United States regardless of where
they live.
</P>
<P>
   The federal plan, which is on hold pending further review by
Congress, attempts to bring equity to the organ allocation process.
Waiting lists for patients vary widely from region to region. The
feds believe the disparity creates discrimination based on
geography.
</P>
<P>
   Will the federal plan save more lives? Grace says no. And not
only will it not save more lives, she says it could reduce or
eliminate access in Arizona to lifesaving care.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal plan, a transplant center will lose its status
if it does not perform a minimum number of operations. Grace said
Arizona transplant centers could come up short when competing
against larger counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the geographical dilemma lies the ethical question of
whether precious few organs should go to the sickest patients.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for liver transplant operations, for example, are put
in three categories. Status 1 patients are the sickest of the sick.
They are expected to die within seven days. A successful liver
transplant occurs about 60 percent of the time for Status 1
patients. Those Status 1 patients who reject a liver would be
placed at the top of the list again for transplant operations.
</P>
<P>
   Successful liver transplants in Status 3 patients, by
comparison, occur 84 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Should we allocate resources to highest and best use, or do we
serve the sickest people, knowing that in weighting the decision in
their favor we could deplete the organ supply even more?
</P>
<P>
   Does a legislative postcard to Washington send the wrong message
in the region or nationally: That Arizona would rather let someone
out of state die than give up an organ?
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, 650 people await organs. In 1998, 302 organs were
harvested from donors in this state. An unknown number died
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, 12 people die each day waiting for a
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   All of the questions, the angst and the unseemly hoarding of
body parts would go away with an adequate supply of organs. That
would occur with more donors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
