<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILS AS PRIME WINTER VACATION SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The woman had set up the trip in August, working
through a travel agent. She and her husband teach school. They have
off the same week in February. Unfortunately, the package they'd
signed up for hadn't been at all what they'd planned.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel had turned out to be in a rotten section of San Juan,
Puerto Rico, in a relatively rough urban neighborhood that had
scared hell out of both of them. The room had come with an entire
civilization of burly, tropical bugs as roommates.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted me to write a column about how unreliable travel
agents can be, about how she and her husband had spent hard-earned
money on this long-awaited winter vacation, and the vacation had
been a depressing disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   I did feel sorry for her. It really was a shame that the
vacation hadn't lived up to her expectations and her husband's.
Still, you can't feel too sorry for people who can afford a winter
vacation with sun, surf and palm trees. I've seen too many people
who can't even dream of getting out of this icy part of the world
in February.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, your idea of a vacation getaway involves steel
bars and jail guards in uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   I'll let you in on a little secret about northern cities like
Albany. The police know about it, and so does everybody else with
any experience with the criminal justice system. That secret is
this:
</P>
<P>
   In cold weather, a certain percentage of the residents of any
local jail are people for whom doing time constitutes a winter
vacation. The rest of the year, they're on the street. When the
weather gets grim, a clean bed, three squares a day and a heating
system that doesn't involve setting fire to something or somebody
can look pretty appealing.
</P>
<P>
   For some street people, a few nights of sub-freezing
temperatures means it's time for a little minor crime _ some boozy,
nonviolent disorderly conduct. Hey, they have cable television in
the can.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Keegan, now a justice of the New York Supreme Court, spent
16 years sitting in the Albany Police Court. He doesn't recall the
incident, but a cop I know was in his courtroom some years ago when
a hooker came up on a disorderly conduct beef. Thirty days, said
the judge. ``Hell,'' said the hooker. ``I can do that standing on
my head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' Keegan said. ``Sixty days.''
</P>
<P>
   The hooker beamed. ``Thank you, Judge.''
</P>
<P>
   A street guy known as Michael the Archangel used to specialize
in going to sleep atop the statue of Moses in one of the city's
parks. When the cops spotted him, that was a direct ticket to the
can. Michael the Archangel has straightened out in recent years.
When last heard from, he was working in a flower shop.
</P>
<P>
   But George Flannery is in the can now, just as he was a few
winters ago. He's a good-natured guy of 46 who drinks a bit and
doesn't live any place on a regular basis. I dropped by to see him
at the Albany County Jail the other day. It's boring there, he told
me, except when the TV is on. George will be out in early July.
He's planning to hitch a ride to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better get there before winter,'' I advised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I plan to,'' George Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   I do feel sorry for the lady whose trip to Puerto Rico didn't
work out. But I feel sorrier for a street guy named Cornelius. One
January day some years back, hoping to land in jail or even in the
hospital, Cornelius sacked out in the intersection of Washington
Avenue and Quail, as he'd done for years, waiting for the cops to
show. A car rolled over him and killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's what I call a bad trip.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
