<HEADER>
A3276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-09 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 DiMAGGIO DESERVES A FITTING MEMORIAL IN HIS HOMETOWN  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Everybody has a DiMaggio story, even my dad, who
used to play golf with Joe's brother Dom, a great player for the
Boston Red Sox who always suffered by comparison with the Yankee
Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about Joe on Cape Cod, in Iowa and in Cuba. In
New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is talking about naming the West
Side Highway after DiMaggio, probably because Giuliani wants to put
a new Yankee Stadium next to the highway.
</P>
<P>
   All over San Francisco, people are talking about Joe DiMaggio.
What is there to do but name something in San Francisco after the
city's greatest gift to the rest of America? This is a city and a
man well-matched in grace and class.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco could rename the Marina Green, near where Joe
bought his mother a home, DiMaggio Green.
</P>
<P>
   Aquatic Park, near the old DiMaggio stomping grounds of North
Beach and Fisherman's Wharf, could be renamed DiMaggio Park.
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Island could be renamed DiMaggio Island.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall, where DiMaggio married Marilyn Monroe, could be
renamed DiMaggio Hall. That one probably wouldn't go over, even
with the support of all the city's Marilyn fans.
</P>
<P>
   King Street in front of the new ballpark could be DiMaggio
Street. Then you could give directions involving Second and Third
and DiMaggio and Mays.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell Park could be renamed for Joe DiMaggio. Maybe Pacific
Bell would agree to give up the name if we all agree to sign up for
their phone service.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, I solicited names for Giants stadiums, and the
names Mays, DiMaggio, O'Doul and McCovey dominated the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   They lost to Pacific Bell, which sent its entry to the Giants
along with a promise of $50 million over 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   We name ballparks after corporations, not heroes.
</P>
<P>
   This is a city of heroes with their names on signs. Former Mayor
George Moscone has a convention center. The San Francisco Chronicle
columnist Herb Caen has Herb Caen Way along the water. Colin P.
Kelly, the first Medal of Honor winner in World War II, has a
street named for him. Lefty O'Doul has a bridge. Willie Mays has
Willie Mays Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he (DiMaggio) would have wanted anything named
for him. He was pretty private,'' said Dante Benedetti, DiMaggio's
old friend and owner of the New Pisa Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Benedetti how he'd feel about naming something after
DiMaggio now that he's dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a great thing,'' he said. ``How do you go
about doing it? He certainly deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you go about doing it? First you throw out some
suggestions, then in true San Francisco fashion you have a
controversy, and finally you dedicate something that doesn't quite
do justice to the person being honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any controversy about this one, except is it
good enough?'' said former Mayor Art Agnos, who had two encounters
with DiMaggio and never will forget them.
</P>
<P>
   Once, as a state assemblyman, Agnos was at the New Orleans Room
of the Fairmont Hotel and reached over to borrow a chair from the
next table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear this very deep, stern voice saying, `I'm sorry, this
chair is taken,''' Agnos said. ``There he was, staring at me with
that look he must have given every pitcher he ever faced.''
</P>
<P>
   The second time Agnos met DiMaggio was at the Marina Middle
School after the 1989 earthquake. Sherry Agnos, the former mayor's
wife, had the sad task of telling people that their houses were
unsafe and could be entered only for 15 minutes to remove a few
valuables.
</P>
<P>
   There, at the end of the line, was DiMaggio. When Agnos told an
aide to bring DiMaggio to the front of the line, DiMaggio refused,
saying he didn't want special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Mr. DiMaggio, are you over 60?''' Agnos said.
DiMaggio said he was a few years older than that, and Agnos said,
``Well, we're giving special treatment to people over 60 because of
the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnos said DiMaggio chuckled and finally agreed to come to the
head of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was understated,'' Agnos said. ``He knew how to wear his
hero status.''
</P>
<P>
   Send your ideas for a DiMaggio memorial in his hometown of San
Francisco to dimaggio(at)examiner.com. Faxes may be sent to
415-957-1013 and letters to DiMaggio, c/o The San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco CA 94120.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
