<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3277 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABBEY-REMEMBERED-AZR &LR;      03-09 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBEY-REMEMBERED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS STILL FOLLOW AUTHOR ABBEY'S CALL TO ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Saving the giant redwoods of California.
</P>
<P>
   Taking cattle off taxpayer-owned arid Western lands.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing development across millions of acres of wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Banning cars from portions of Grand Canyon National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   When Edward Abbey talked about these ideas, old ``Cactus Ed''
was considered by many to be radical, a crank, out there, a weirdo
_ and a darn good writer.
</P>
<P>
   His book ``The Monkey Wrench Gang'' helped spawn the Earth
First! movement and was linked to radical eco-terrorists and even
an alleged conspiracy to knock out power lines from the Palo Verde
Nuclear Generating Station west of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after his death in Tucson, many of the thoughts of
this witty Western writer-philosopher-environmental activist are
mainstream, are happening, are embraced by government officials and
chambers of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   His books are selling faster than ever. Across the nation, they
are used in teaching college literature courses. His official Web
page is run by a woman in Sweden. Music, films and readings of
Abbey's works are scheduled throughout the Valley this week.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists everywhere quote him as often as they once did
the likes of 19th-century transcendentalists Ralph Waldo Emerson
and Henry David Thoreau, or Sierra Club founder John Muir.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Abbey is really the modern visionary of the environmental
movement, dealing with our very modern problems, which are vastly
worse than Thoreau or Muir could have ever imagined,'' said Kieran
Suckling of Tucson. He is executive director of the Southwest
Center for Biological Diversity, one of dozens of environmental
groups headed up by folks who knew or were inspired by Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I and others had seen Abbey speak _ eloquently and
irreverently _ on many occasions about really just how incredibly
dire our environmental problems are today and the need for new
environmental groups to arise and take on those challenges in a
very uncompromising and passionate way,'' said Suckling, whose
group successfully has sued the government more than 80 times to
obtain protections for dozens of endangered plants and animals in
the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial aspect of Abbey's writings is his
courting of destructive, even violent, action _ from putting sugar
in bulldozer gas tanks to spiking trees to plans for blowing up
Glen Canyon Dam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of legitimized that sort of conduct, especially for
newcomers (to the West),'' said Dave Skinner, a spokesman for
People for the USA, a Pueblo, Colo., group that advocates mining,
logging, ranching and oil drilling on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who has read Abbey, describes his books as fun, but
worries that they are taken too seriously by ``cranks,'' who go out
and actually ``monkey wrench,'' or sabotage, developments.
</P>
<P>
   In October, an obscure group, the Earth Liberation Front,
claimed responsibility for torching buildings and chairlifts in
Vail, Colo., the nation's busiest ski resort. The $12 million in
damage is believed to be the costliest act of eco-terrorism _ a
crime committed to save nature _ in the nation's history.
Mainstream environmental groups denounced the arson, which was done
in protest of the loss of habitat for the endangered lynx.
</P>
<P>
   Monkey wrenching is not new. There is a history of overt
activism in industrial nations that stems from early-19th-century
England, when Ned Ludd and other ``Luddites'' smashed new
labor-saving textile machinery in protest against unemployment and
reduced wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, to me, is fundamentally against everything I was raised
to believe,'' Skinner said. ``I love the West as passionately as
Abbey did, but I like folks, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I especially treasure is being able to show up at a
farmstead somewhere, learn a little and leave with guarantees of a
full belly next trip. It's getting harder to pull that off anymore.
That open handshake (among rural Americans) is fast turning into a
closed fist.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said he believes Abbey poisoned the political atmosphere
by advocating no compromises.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Zierenberg, who helped found Tucson's Wildlife Damage
Review, a group that rails against government extermination of
predators, said Abbey's writings purposely were rough-edged and
provocative.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were designed to tweak everybody. He said stuff on
purpose to get people mad, and make them think about why they were
mad,'' said Zierenberg, a former staff member of the Earth First!
magazine, which bills itself as ``The Radical Environmental
Journal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people can write beautiful words. But Abbey was a
real thinker, and he translated that in his writings to make people
think about what they're doing and what they believe,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of monkey wrenching is not to hurt any life, people
included. The object is to bring attention to the issue, or to make
something cost so much money that the corporation will abandon the
destructive effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him say that Abbey endures because his own
personal experiences were steeped in the variety, the
contradictions and the lifestyles of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Paul Abbey was born in 1927 in a small Pennsylvania town,
the eldest of five children. His father, Paul Revere Abbey, was a
noted anarchist, atheist and teetotaler. His mother, Mildred
Postlewait, played piano in church and taught her son classical
music and literature.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Abbey served as a military policeman in Europe at the end
of World War II. He attended a Pennsylvania college and the
University of Edinburgh and Yale, but received his graduate and
postgraduate degrees at the University of New Mexico in
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't writing books, he worked as a ranger for the
National Park Service. He was a social worker and a fire lookout in
the forests. He wore cowboy clothes and lived in isolated rural
areas of Arizona and Utah. His friends say he showed his sympathy
for the decline of traditional Western lifestyles in his novel
``The Brave'' ``Cowboy,'' which later was made into the highly
acclaimed movie ``Lonely'' ``Are the Brave'' (1962), starring Kirk
Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Abbey wrote 22 books, fiction and non-fiction. But among his
best known is one of his first, ``Desert Solitaire'' (1968), which
is required reading in English Professor Dick Kirkpatrick's
Southwest literature course at Mesa Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed has been an integral part of the course from Day One. I've
yet to have, in 20 years, anyone walk away from reading Abbey and
have no opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick and others said they see the influence of Abbey in
recent efforts to rein in growth, to save the Sonoran Desert around
Phoenix and Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect he has a tremendous influence, even on people who
have no idea who . . . Ed Abbey is. Even politicians now recognize
that we're dealing with finite resources,'' said Kirkpatrick, who
annually invited Abbey to speak to his students.
</P>
<P>
   ``His detractors would always come in loaded for bear. They
would take him to task on the credibility of something. He loved
that sort of challenge. He never backed down from it. He always did
it with great humor,'' Kirkpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   It's Abbey's humor that environmental activists say keeps them
motivated; keeps them from becoming too angry, or burning out. And
it's Abbey's humor that keeps new readers flocking to his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too few people who can take life seriously, and still
laugh about it,'' said Charles Bowden, also a Western writer from
Tucson, who was a close friend of Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like he was out of step. He was just a little
further down the trail than some of us. You've got to give the guy
credit. He died without any money, and yet the Barry Goldwaters of
the world ended up talking like Ed Abbey.''
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Kintz, an editor for the Earth First! journal in Eugene,
Ore., said the abiding theme in Abbey's work is total commitment to
preservation of what is left of the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the whole idea of someone's passion for wild nature, the
passion Abbey had for wild nature and how good he was at
communicating that,'' said Kintz.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Featherstone, a Washington, D.C., environmental lobbyist
who knew Abbey, said there isn't another contemporary writer who
captured the spirit of the modern environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have the bard around that can paint, ever so
precisely, the word pictures that capture what we are fighting
for,'' said Featherstone, who lived with Earth First! activists in
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I question why we really need to care and why every last
place is still important, it's Ed still asking those kind of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I am out in wilderness, or on a river, and a buzzard
soars over, I wonder if that is Ed up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling. He's still out there, still keeping me
honest and still instilling in me the spirit that we must save it
all.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via the
Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
