<HEADLINE>
BLOOD FROM UMBILICAL CORDS OFFERS LIFESAVING POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sue Tighe wanted to donate her newborn's
umbilical cord blood for good use. ``Otherwise it just goes down
the drain, so why not bank it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Tighe, who had her son in December, was talking about one of the
newer innovations in transplant science.
</P>
<P>
   Blood taken from a newborn's discarded umbilical cord offers a
dense concentration of stem cells _ the same stuff found in bone
marrow, the manufacturing center for healthy blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Although the transplant procedure is still new, cord blood has
been used successfully in place of donated bone marrow to treat
cancer patients dying of leukemia and other diseases that affect
the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Yet cord blood is also prompting some controversy. Along with
the recent development of community banks to accept cord blood
donations from people like Sue Tighe, others are offering a private
banking system for parents.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of dollars, parents may now bank their newborn's
cord blood in the off chance the child develops a life-threatening
blood disease. Some health experts are cautioning parents against
such an individual banking system for financial, ethical and
practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no real oversight to make sure these companies do what
they'll say they do,'' said Dr. Marquis Hodes, a specialist in
blood diseases and an assistant professor of medicine and
pediatrics at the Albany Medical College in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies that are doing this are marketing it to parents
as a fail-safe against the possibility their child has cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientific evidence, however, shows that cord blood does not
need to be perfectly matched to be effective. So another's cord
blood may work just as well, if not better. And because blood
diseases are relatively rare, there also is the chance that a cord
donated by a newborn would be available for his or her future use
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage anyone who has the opportunity and doesn't
have to pay for it to bank cord blood,'' Hodes said.
``Altruistically, it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's easy to collect. After the baby's birth, the umbilical
cord is clamped, breaking the link between the baby and the
placenta. A small amount of blood, typically three to five ounces,
is then drained from the cord and taken to a cord bank, where it's
frozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cord blood increases the options for patients who are looking
for a treatment for their disease,'' said Helen Ng, a spokeswoman
for the National Marrow Donor Program in Minneapolis, which is
hoping to set up a cord blood registry to keep track of donations.
</P>
<P>
   But cord blood has its limitations. Because only a small amount
of blood can be retrieved from an umbilical cord, bone marrow
transplants with cord blood cells have been a treatment option only
for children and those few adults who weigh less than 85 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   And there remains some uncertainty over the long-term effects of
freezing cord blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unknowns associated with cord blood
transplants,'' Ng said.
</P>
<P>
   Tighe, a secretary at the Albany Medical Center, had hoped her
son's cord blood might help some of the young leukemia patients she
sees every day. Yet she had to give up the idea after learning that
the nearest places to Albany that accept donations are in New York
City and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Such donations usually come from women who deliver at nearby
hospitals, not one that's three hours away. ``I was trying to do
this great thing and I had no outlet,'' said Tighe, 32.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there are some 16 cord blood banks in the country with
blood from an estimated 14,000 umbilical cords in storage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet physicians and the National Marrow Donation Foundation are
hoping to expand the number of places that accept donations, so
more cord blood may be collected for patients in desperate need of
a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Considering its lifesaving potential, throwing it away seems
like a waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling among physicians is that cord blood banking for
the general good is a good thing,'' Hodes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
