<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBORNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTAL CONTACT IS VITAL TO CHILD DEVELOPMENT, DOCTORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Alabama)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Besides the routine physicals and vaccinations,
Dr. Kevin Karpowicz dispenses a lot of parenting advice.
</P>
<P>
   For a newborn, the Schenectady doctor believes nothing is better
than a parent's love and attention to ensure a good foundation for
the child's future.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like common sense, you're not too far behind the
last research in infant brain development, much of which builds on
age-old parenting techniques rather than expensive toys or classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do the Mozart or the flash cards,'' said Karpowicz,
who advises parents with infants less than 2 weeks old to hold
their baby often or wear a baby sling to keep him close. ``We're
not trying to make these infants smarter. We're trying to make them
emotionally secure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 30 years, Dr. Craig Ramey, a specialist in child
development and a cognitive neuroscientist at the University of
Alabama at Birmingham, has written more than 200 scientific and
professional articles about child development. He is co-author with
his wife, Sharon, of the new book ``Right From Birth: Building Your
Child's Foundation for Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1990, we've probably doubled our knowledge about how
babies' brains develop,'' Ramey said from his office in Birmingham.
``Between birth and age 2, about 90 percent of the architecture of
the brain will be laid down.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, thanks to new imaging technology, researchers have
found that by age 3, a child's brain is twice as active as that of
an adult as it experiences the outside world through the senses.
</P>
<P>
   These findings underscore the relatively new concept that an
infant's brain is remarkably unfinished at birth, even though it
has all the building blocks for development, including more than
100 billion brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing is a complex network of connections between those
individual cells, a process of development that's encouraged by
appropriate, positive and frequent interactions with parents or
other caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   With such stimuli, an infant's brain develops trillions of
neurological connections that lay foundation upon which a child
builds a lifetime of skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to 15,000 connections might be made from one cell to
another,'' Ramey said. ``It's the old use-it-or-lose-it theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Such complex neuroscience shouldn't frighten or overwhelm
caregivers, who may wonder if they now need a doctorate to raise a
baby.
</P>
<P>
   Ramey is opposed to the current trend to accelerated learning
programs for very young children. Rather, he emphasizes that
intelligence is developed with proper nurturing and age-appropriate
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're talking about a baby, flashcards are utterly
worthless,'' he said. ``You really have to engage children with
concrete three-dimensional props.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents are already taking steps to help their baby's
development when they hold them, talk to them, play with them and
respond to their cues, Ramey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the ways children become secure and attached to
caregivers is to have caregivers who are responsive to them,'' he
said. ``You really have to think of it as being a tennis game, or a
dance, or a great conversation where there's a back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a baby, trusting that someone is going to respond to you is
the foundation of emotional development. The next step for an
infant is realizing that he or she can cause positive reactions in
other people.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ramey, babies who receive repeated opportunities to
do this, through interactive activities like playing, singing and
reading, are more apt to become interested, curious and active
learners in the world around them, now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, Ramey counsels parents against activities that
discourage such positive interplay during a child's first 18
months. His advice:
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not park an infant in front of a television, even when
child-oriented, ``educational'' programs are on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not leave a child where he may be ignored for long periods
of time or where there is no one to play and speak with him or her.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not subject an infant to situations in which the sights and
noises are overwhelming and insensitive to his or her needs.
</P>
<P>
   Ramey urges parents to understand how positive and influential a
role they can play in the development of a baby's brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really clear is that the quality of those early
experiences are vitally important to the short-term and long-term
development of the child,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (How and why emotionally secure babies develop into thinking and
caring children will be the theme of a daylong conference
``Building Baby's Brain'' on March 19 in Albany. The event will
Ramey and other specialists. For information, call 518-426-7181,
ext. 27. The cost of the daylong event, including lunch, is $25.)
</P>
</TEXT>
