<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3313 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEPHONE-BIRTHDAY-HN     03-09 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEPHONE-BIRTHDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS TO BE LEARNED FROM MA BELL'S SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ Wednesday is the anniversary of the world's
first phone call. Lines have been busy ever since.
</P>
<P>
   On March 10, 1876, in the course of an experiment in the
extremely new field of telephony, Alexander Graham Bell
successfully transmitted a one-sentence message to his partner Tom
Watson, who was standing next door by a large receiver. It was the
birth of a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   These days, this revolution _ what with the Internet, cell
phones, electronic mail and cable _ has never been livelier or
better publicized (or better hyped). And as the non-stop IPOs,
megamergers and monsterously high price/earnings ratios indicate,
everyone is trying to divine where the industry is going and who
the next winners will be. If the past is a guide, this will be
tough.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications has been unpredictable since Bell made his
first connection.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Graham Bell was himself most unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Although as a young man he worked fanatically on the telephone _
first to invent it, then to prove it was his invention _ he later
lost almost all interest in it; he once told his secretary he had
no phone in his study because the ringing was so disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his life he regretted that he would be
remembered only because the telephone was a ``money-making
invention.''
</P>
<P>
   Which it certainly was. But the story of how his invention made
money _ eventually, lots _ is itself something nobody could have
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Bell patented the telephone in 1876. For the next 17 years, Bell
Telephone (later AT&AMP;T) guarded this patent with paranoid zeal.
What's weird is that, although company officials knew the patent
expired in 1893, they elected to do little about it.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of suing people, they did not market aggressively and
made only the mildest effort to ready themselves for the inevitable
competition. When competition came (3,000 phone companies by
1902!), AT&AMP;T lost half its share of the market share.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was even more surprising.
</P>
<P>
   In 1907 Theodore Vail became president of AT&AMP;T. Vail believed
phone service should be universal and excellent. He cut rates,
improved access and insisted operators stop hanging up on
customers. He also believed such service could best be supplied by
only one company _ his. Since AT&AMP;T still owned 50 percent of the
telephone market, this thinking smacked of monopoly, and the
company was threatened with government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, AT&AMP;T agreed that they should be subject to
government regulation, but for a price: The government should
declare AT&AMP;T a natural monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   A company volunteering for regulation is most unusual; the
average business sees regulation and dives for the aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, no company ever has had the government hand
over a plum quite so ripe as the one AT&AMP;T received. AT&AMP;T retained a
monopoly in well over 80 percent of the U.S. telephone market, long
distance and local, until 1984.
</P>
<P>
   During this monopoly period, something else unusual happened.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of competition usually results in rising prices, while
innovation stumbles. This didn't occur with phone service; except
during the Depression, basic rates dropped while technology
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both prices and technology might well have responded
even better to competition _ a tantalizing ``what if''? Still, for
many people, the age of the Bell monopoly remains the ``good old
days'' of phone service.
</P>
<P>
   There is one final twist _ the strange tale of how AT&AMP;T failed
to predict its own market. AT&AMP;T knew from the start that phones
were popular, but it didn't know why.
</P>
<P>
   It envisioned phones being used for practical purposes only _
business phones for business, home phones for crises _ and was
appalled to discover that people also were using their telephones
for gossip and fun.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years this frivolity mortified AT&AMP;T; it was only during
the 1920s that it occurred to the corporation's managers to
actively encourage lighthearted consumerism. Next time you ``reach
out and touch someone,'' keep that in mind.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of Alexander Graham Bell's funeral in 1922, all
telephone service in the United States was suspended for one
minute. The history of his invention proves it will be hard to
predict who _ or what _ in the future of telecommunications will
inspire such silence. It's a less all of us _ consumers, businesses
and especially investors _ should well remember.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a historical novelist and columnist for the San
Francisco Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
