A3321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT0310-COX     03-09 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT0310-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT OPEN TO ANTITRUST DEAL -- BUT ON ITS TERMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) finance categories
 &HT;    NOTE EARLY AFTERNOON STOCK PRICE IN 4th GRAPH
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Microsoft and the government remain open to
</P>
<P>
   an out-of-court accord that would resolve their antitrust
</P>
<P>
   dispute, but they remain far apart on the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting Microsoft's ability to leverage its Windows market
power into
</P>
<P>
   other emerging sectors, such as Internet commerce, remains a
central aspect of the government's case. Since Microsoft invariably
cites the ability to innovate using the Windows platform as
non-negotiable, that
</P>
<P>
   issue is not easily prone to a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation Microsoft might be willing to strike a deal
</P>
<P>
   with the Justice Department and the 19 states that took the
software giant to court in May increased when Intel cut a bargain
in its antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Microsoft stock climbed $4.43 3/4 to $163.43 3/4
after the Seattle Times, citing unidentified persons, reported the
two sides are looking for a way to settle the case before the trial
resumes April 12. The Times noted, however, that there is no rush
to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's deal was announced Monday, one day before its antitrust
trial was to have begun. The world's largest maker of computer
chips,
</P>
<P>
   tentatively agreed to settle Federal Trade Commission charges
that it had
</P>
<P>
   used monopoly power to strong-arm customers over patent issues.
</P>
<P>
   As for Microsoft, its stance toward a settlement has been set by
Chairman Bill Gates. Last month, at the World Economic Forum in
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland, Gates said: ``Before the case was filed, we put
every effort into a settlement. But there's a basic principle here:
Are we allowed to make Windows into a better product? It's the key
to our business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, sure, we'll enter into a dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a ``dialogue'' has not yet transpired. If it comes about at
all, it
</P>
<P>
   is unlikely to occur before mid-April when the trial, now in
recess, is
</P>
<P>
   to resume in federal court in Washington. The non-jury trial
began in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe we will prevail in court,'' Bob
</P>
<P>
   Herbold, Microsoft's chief operating officer, said Monday at a
news conference at the company's Redmond, Wash., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (the Intel case) has an effect directly on our
case,''
</P>
<P>
   added Brad Smith, Microsoft's general counsel for international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the Intel matter is more closely related to an
earlier Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   antitrust proceeding, which resulted in a 1995 consent decree
over how it
</P>
<P>
   handled its Windows' licenses to hardware vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Smith declined to comment on whether any negotiations were
underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there were discussions before the antitrust case
was filed a
</P>
<P>
   year ago,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Those brief talks were held between Justice Department antitrust
chief
</P>
<P>
   Joel Klein and William Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel. The
Klein-Neukom negotiating channel is known to remain open.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman said Tuesday that the government
would have no comment on settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
