 CHRON  
 &HT;    These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Food section
plans to move for Tuesday, March 9, on the New York Times News
Servicewire. Questions? Please call Holly Ocasio Rizzo atSan Francisco _  SECRETS-Sole  _ Brown butter, toasted capers and
lemons accent the petrale sole perfectly at A. Sabella's, near
Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco. &HT;    With recipe, chef's secrets for success. 
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco _  &UR; COOKIES  &LR; _ Pastry chef David Chesarek rattled
plenty of readers with his recipe for Oatmeal Walnut Chocolate Chip
cookies calling for a lot of butter and a fairly conservative
amount of flour. Even his mother sent him an e-mail, because her
friends had been calling her to make sure the recipe in the
newspaper was correct. ``They're standing by their mixers and can't
understand how there's 12 ounces butter,'' she told him.
<P>
   The recipe works, he says, but just to make sure, we went back
to the test kitchen to develop four surefire variations.
</P>
<P>
   With tips and recipes. &QL; 
 &UR; By Kim Severson &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
San Francisco _  &UR; CLASSIC-Corned Beef  &LR; _ At this time of year, the
small retail shop of Roberts Corned Meats swarms with customers
seeking corned beef. Roberts, the oldest corned beef company in San
Francisco _ with the fourth generation at the helm _ often is
considered the best. Even the San Francisco Fire Department buys
its corned beef there.
</P>
<P>
   With historic-highlights box.
