<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONDAYWINES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 
 Monday Night Wines:  
 Some value-priced imports let you sip well every day   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Strolling the aisles at wine shops these days can
make a working-class wine lover cry. Zinfandels at $15, Chardonnays
at $20 and Cabernets at $30 line the shelves _ but where is a
decent, affordable bottle for Monday night's meatloaf?
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a strong economy fueling demand and some small California
harvests crimping supply, wine prices aren't what they used to be.
As one Sonoma County vintner said when announcing a price increase
to a local retailer, ``We can sell everything we make at $7.99, or
we can sell everything we make at $12.99. You make the call.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers who would like to put a bottle, or at least part
of a bottle, on the table most nights, these high prices can pinch.
But Bay Area retailers insist that they still carry modestly priced
``Monday night wines'' and that customers who are willing to
consider unfamiliar brands and blends still can drink pleasantly
for a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of wines in that (under $7) price range,'' says
wine industry consultant Eileen Fredrikson. ``There just aren't a
lot of coastal Chardonnays and Merlots in that price range.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's retailers have to look farther afield for bargains _ to
Chile, Argentina, Spain, Portugal and France's Languedoc region,
for example. They have to skim the cream carefully from
California's Central Valley, tasting to find the gems from this
less-distinguished grape-growing region. And they have to be
willing to hand-sell wines that their customers _ and sometimes the
retailers themselves _ don't recognize and often can't pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Les Blanches Fumees from the Pays d'Oc (France) for
$6.99 a bottle,'' says Wilfred Wong, a wine buyer for Beverages &AMP;
More. ``It's a good bottle of wine but you have to lead people to
it. It doesn't fly off the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, consumers searching for bargain wines to have
with a weekday takeout dinner should keep expectations modest.
Often made with grapes grown in hot climates and rarely stored in
oak, inexpensive wines typically lack the complexity and depth of
flavor that more costly wines can have. At their best, they are
clean _ without obvious flaws _ and fresh, with some clear fruit
character.
</P>
<P>
   Most retailers agree that today's values can increasingly be
found among the imports. Bargains seldom come from the prestigious
Napa and Sonoma valleys, where planted vineyards can cost more than
$40,000 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   Grape prices in the two valleys have soared in recent years, in
part because of phylloxera-induced shortages and strong demand, and
in part because there is simply not much more good land to plant.
In just the past two years, reports the California Department of
Food and Agriculture, the value of Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon
grapes has risen 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, jostling for status _ equating top quality with top
dollar, as with so many consumer goods _ has kept prices climbing
as vintners try to match or exceed the price of their competitors'
wines. Some California wine fans on limited budgets have had
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get refugees from that market who just can't handle it
anymore,'' says Morgan Miller, whose Odd Lots Wine Shop in Albany
exclusively sells inexpensive imports. ``They may have a California
palate, but prices have gotten to the point that they're starting
to experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller typically has eight to 10 selections at about $5 a bottle
and rarely sells a wine for more than $10. Distributors bring him
wines that they can't find a home for elsewhere and he cherry-picks
the best, knowing that his customers won't flinch at the
unfamiliar. A mixed case of wine from Odd Lots might include
Spanish, Chilean, Italian and Rhone bottlings as well as
little-known Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   At Beverages &AMP; More, a display of ``Hot Buys'' offers shoppers
more than two dozen wines under $10. At San Francisco's Jug Shop,
Jack Hecker puts his best buys in a corner labeled ``Jed's Top
Ten'' to draw customers to pleasant everyday wines with low name
recognition. The store also holds an annual comparative jug
tasting, with voting by consumers and critics. Last year, a 1996
Montepulciano d'Abruzzo from Zonin (see related story) upset the
usual winner R.H. Phillips Mistura from California, made from a
blend of Rhone grape varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mill Valley's well-heeled residents seek out these
lesser-known but well-priced wines, says Jim Canepa, a manager at
the upscale Mill Valley Market. ``Five years ago, we hardly ever
sold wine out of Chile or Argentina,'' he says. Now he has three
Chilean wines, all under $7.99, prominently displayed in his
grocery department. ``That's the kind of price range that people
buy everyday for themselves,'' says the merchant. ``Instead of
buying a jug, they're buying a $6.99 Merlot from Chile.''
</P>
<P>
   Canepa is right about jug wines. Sales of jugs have headed south
as sales of varietal wines in 750-milliliter bottles have
increased. Increasingly, Fredrikson says, consumers have moved away
from the generic wine that fills most jugs and toward more
flavorful varietal wines such as Chardonnay or Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   For James Arthur Field, an Orinda wine lover who launched his
own jug-wine label 23 years ago, that obsession with varietals is a
nemesis. Field sells 35,000 cases a year _ 30,000 in the Bay Area
alone _ of his two James Arthur Field wines, inexpensive red and
white table wines in 1.5-liter bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible battle,'' says Field. ``My biggest challenge
is overcoming the predisposition of the public to pay attention to
what's on the label, not to what's in the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Field has managed to hold on to what he admits is
an ``amazing niche,'' an audience of Bay Area drinkers who ignore
his wine's lack of status. Made from Central Valley grapes, the
white is French Colombard, the red is Ruby Cabernet. The two wines
are bottled in Healdsburg and delivered to restaurants and stores
by the owner himself.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, Field filled his half-gallon jugs with bulk
wine from Sonoma County. But by the mid-1980s, like other low-cost
producers, he was forced to turn to the Central Valley, where the
hot weather tends to yield fruit with cooked flavors. By that time,
Field claims, better equipment and technology had made it possible
to produce respectable wine from Central Valley grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, his most loyal fans are in Berkeley. ``I used to say, `If
I could clone Berkeley people, I could triple my business.'
Berkeley people, you cannot fool them. They know what they're
eating and drinking and to hell with labels.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Fredrikson, a few other brands have managed to
thrive without varietal identity _ wines such as Spaghetti Red and
Spaghetti White, two blends made by Alan Haywood, son of a Sonoma
vintner; Prosperity Red and Prosperity White made by Firestone
Vineyard; and Hangtown Red from Boeger Winery. ``These are
delightful, fun wines that people are enjoying tremendously at
reasonable prices,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite the breathtaking prices on many wines,
supermarket scanner data indicate that the average price paid for
wine in supermarkets is just $4.13 a bottle. (The calculation
includes generic jug wines by converting total volume sales into
750-milliliter bottles.)
</P>
<P>
   Varietal wines sold in supermarkets aren't much more expensive.
According to recent data from Nielsen WineScan, the average
Chardonnay is $6.37 and the average Cabernet Sauvignon is $6.80.
``That tells you that you can find good, everyday varietal wines at
$5 to $7 rather readily,'' Fredrikson says. ``When you're talking
about wines that people have every day, generally they are
purchased while people shop for food. So these (supermarket data)
really give the clearest picture of what people are drinking every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets may be the primary source for most shoppers'
everyday wine, but at least one other retailer sees opportunity in
the value category. Last November, 7-Eleven stores began offering
an expanded selection of moderately priced wines from producers
such as Kendall-Jackson, Fetzer, Beringer and Korbel. The average
store only sells about 10 bottles a day now, but management hopes
to triple that. And with 3,200 stores, the chain's wine program
could have impact. ``When you have the number of stores we have, 30
of anything starts adding up,'' says Dennis Phelps, the chain's
national manager for alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most positive things that's happened to
wine in a long time,'' Fredrikson says. ``Suddenly, instead of a
guy stopping in after work and picking up a Slurpee, a bagel and a
sixpack, there's a nice, well-edited bunch of national (wine)
brands there.''
</P>
<P>
   For wine advocates who would like to see more wine poured as a
Monday-night beverage, 7-Eleven's new program holds promise. Now
the chain just needs to train its clerks to know what wine goes
with meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; T &LR; IPS FOR BARGAIN HUNTERS &QL; 
 &QL;  &LR; 
Here are a few ways to help find value wines:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Take advantage of case discounts at retail stores and &LR; 
 &UR; supermarkets.  &LR; Many retailers offer a five to 10 percent price
reduction on a case, even a mixed case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pool orders with friends.  &LR; If you can buy at least five cases,
some retailers and winery tasting rooms will give you an extra
discount.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Establish a relationship with a retailer.  &LR; You may not be a big
spender, but a good wine merchant will advise you if asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find someone you can trust and look them in the eye,'' says
Wilfred Wong of Beverages &AMP; More in San Francisco. ``Make them
responsible for taking care of you.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buy well-priced large bottles even if you won't drink the wine &LR; 
 &UR; in one sitting.  &LR; Just pour the leftovers into a well-washed and
dried 750 ml or 375 ml bottles. (Start a collection of used bottles
for this purpose.) Fill the bottles completely, recork, label and
refrigerate. The wine should stay fresh for a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Enthusiast catalog, (800) 356-8466, sells a ``Wine for
Later Set'' that allows you to pour off wine into 1/2- or
1/4-bottle glass decanters with airtight stoppers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Janet Fletcher &QL; 
