<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIET-GUIDELINES (Washington) _ A health organization here
charges that government dietary guidelines exhibit a bias against
African Americans, Hispanics and Asians, many of whom are lactose
intolerant. The Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine says
the government should make its recommended daily intake of dairy
products optional. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-INTERNET (Washington)_ Since minors are finding it easy
to buy alcoholic beverages on the Internet, Congress is considering
a bill that would give state officials more power to police such
activity. But California winemakers say the legislation could
unfairly hamper their efforts to use the Internet to sell wine that
is not widely available in liquor stores. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
renews her effort to clamp more federal controls on rapid-fire
guns. She introduces a bill to close a major loophole in her 1994
law that banned the manufacture of 19 types of semiautomatic
weapons. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ We may not much like Monica
Lewinsky, but she has done a lot for the full-figured woman. The
fact that she and Bill Clinton had fat in common was a bond between
them, not a turnoff. Thanks to them, pleasingly plump is in. In a
world in which being bony is the ultimate beauty ideal, this is the
only heartening feature of their strange, disgusting relationship.
By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
