<SLUG> BC-COOKIE3-10-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   One Cook's Cookie Is Another Cook's Disaster 
 &HT;       
   
 By Kim Severson 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  The recipe for pastry chef David Chesarek's
Oatmeal Walnut Chocolate Chip cookies is fast becoming the most
famous (or infamous) one The Chronicle has published recently.
<P>
   The hoopla boils down to a lot of butter, a little technique and
some very different ideas about how a cookie should look and taste.
</P>
<P>
   We published Chesarek's cookie recipe a couple of weeks ago as
part of a collection of cookies prepared by professional Bay Area
pastry chefs. His recipe builds on a traditional chocolate chip
preparation with a decidedly upscale twist: a lot of butter _ 12
ounces _ and a fairly conservative amount of flour.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Chesarek said, was to create a cookie with the taste
of a Toll House but the crispy, light character of a French tuile.
The result, at least for some Chronicle readers, was a cookie that
confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw his recipe, I was excited because I thought, `He
knows what he's doing,''' said John LaRocque, a practiced home
baker who is known as ``The Cookie Monster'' around his San
Francisco neighborhood. ``But the center was a lump, and the cookie
was thin and spread out like a florentine. It's not pretty, and the
mouth-feel is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray Jaffe, a baker in Napa, Calif., had a similar complaint.
The ratio of flour to butter made the cookies so thin he could
almost see through them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Chesarek's mother, who lives in Los Gatos, Calif., sent him
an e-mail with questions about the recipe. Her friends had been
calling her to make sure the recipe in the newspaper was correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're standing by their mixers and can't understand how
there's 12 ounces butter,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   Chesarek, who last week left the Black Cat to take over as
executive pastry chef at Le Colonial, has a message for the world,
including his mother: Yes, the recipe is right. But there is a
little trick that assures the cookies come out as he intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not supposed to be Toll House. I wanted a crispy,
buttery cookie with those flavors,'' he said. To get the right
result, pat the top of the dough once it's spooned onto the baking
sheet. Chesarek suggests just lightly pressing with your thumb.
That will help spread the chunks of chocolate, oatmeal and nuts to
the edges and assure a more uniform but still delicate cookie.
</P>
<P>
   Also, watch the cookies carefully once they're in the oven. They
can overbake easily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reader interest in the recipe sent us back to the test kitchen,
where we made the cookies as the recipe directed and then tried
four variations. Each change, even one as subtle as adding a
quarter teaspoon of salt, made a distinctly different cookie. For
example, we found that adding an extra half-cup of flour and a
quarter teaspoon of salt made a more traditional chocolate chip
cookie with a less pronounced butter flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the amount of unsalted butter by 4 ounces and adding no
additional salt retained the toasty, buttery flavor but allowed the
chips and nuts to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the original recipe and four variations, plus staff
tasting notes. Each of the five versions has its strong points, and
all taste good.
</P>
<P>
   And the whole experience led us to this conclusion: What
constitutes a good cookie is absolutely in the eye _ and the cookie
jar _ of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
VARIATIONS ON A COOKIE THEME &QL; 
 &QL; 
We made the following changes to David Chesarek's original cookie
recipe:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adding 1/4 cup flour. &LR;  This small change did nothing to alter
the toasty, buttery flavor, but it did turn the cookie's texture to
an unpleasant no-man's land between a tuile and a traditional
chocolate chip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reducing the butter to 8 ounces. &LR;  Less butter made the cookies
hold together better. Nuts and chocolate, not butter, dominated the
flavor. The cookies were still light and crisp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adding 1/2 cup flour and 1/4 teaspoon salt. &LR;  The cookies were
markedly different from the originals, tasting much more like
traditional Toll House. The butter flavor was much more subdued.
These cookies took an additional 5 minutes to bake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adding 3/4 cup flour and 1/4 teaspoon salt. &LR;  This cookie is
very similar in flavor to the previous one, but it is much
sturdier. It may contain almost too much flour, but it might be a
good cookie for shipping to a college student. Also, it took about
5 more minutes to bake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Kim Severson &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DAVID CHESAREK'S OATMEAL WALNUT CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces softened butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole milk
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups instant oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, baking powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, cream the butter and sugars on low
speed. Blend in the egg, vanilla and milk. Add the sifted dry
ingredients and the oatmeal; mix on medium speed until just
incorporated. Fold in the chocolate chips and walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap the dough in plastic wrap and refrigerate for 4 hours,
until chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Drop generously rounded tablespoonfuls of dough onto the
prepared baking sheets, spacing the cookies about 2 inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 15 minutes, or until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 60 to 70 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 105 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 10 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 7 g fat (4 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 53 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
