<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3339 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-IRISH-SFCHRON &LR;      03-09 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-IRISH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   COOKS' BOOKS: Irish Recipes Will Make All Eyes Smile  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Paper shamrocks and green bagels may be sprouting
everywhere as St. Patrick's Day looms, but they hardly capture the
essence of the Emerald Isle. Even the ubiquitous corned beef and
cabbage are little more than a cliche of Irish cooking.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If two new cookbooks are to be believed, today's Irish table
offers a lot more sophistication than this hackneyed combo. Either
book could be a great guide for cooks wanting to explore their
families' Irish roots _ reportedly 40 million Americans have some
ancestral ties to Ireland _ although they differ in approach.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, ``The Irish Heritage Cookbook,'' by Margaret M.
Johnson, an American who grew up in an Irish Catholic community in
Massachusetts, seems the more ethnically pure of the two volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``West of Ireland Summers: A Cookbook,'' by British television
producer/food writer Tamasin Day-Lewis, goes further afield,
skipping cavalierly from traditional Irish potato dishes colcannon
and champ to ceviche or Poulet Vallee d'Auge.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the subtitle, ``Recipes &AMP; Memories From an Irish
Childhood,'' indicates, this is a very personal book, enhanced by
mood-setting pictures by photographer Simon Wheeler. So the latter
book is more of a read, the former more user-friendly for the cook.
</P>
<P>
   While Day-Lewis's international dishes are intriguing, we were
drawn to her Irish fare _ Christmas pudding, roast turkey with
chestnut stuffing, bread sauce, and an Irish stew that's comfort
food of the first order: lamb cubes supported by a gravy thick from
cooked-to-mush potatoes and barley, with carrots, celery and more
potatoes added in the last part of the cooking process so they are
not mushy.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's traditional approach does not preclude new takes on
old favorites. One of the most successful is cheddar colcannon
torte, a variation on the historic potato and cabbage dish given
the author by the chefs of Shaftesbury Square, a Belfast
restaurant. It layers cubed potatoes that have been tossed in bacon
drippings, blanched cabbage with crisp bacon bits and Irish cheddar
in a casserole that needs only a green salad and maybe a piece of
soda bread to make a sturdy supper.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the soda breads in the two books
demonstrate how this signature Irish bread can come in many guises.
We especially liked the complex flavors of the Heritage version
with eggs, buttermilk, caraway and golden raisins, although
specified baking timesand temperatures were on the low side.
</P>
<P>
   Both books offer plenty of the sort of recipes that evoke images
of eating around a wooden table on a blustery island day _ even if
you've never been within 3,000 miles of a peat fire. They will also
gladden the hearts and palates of all who have, once again, become
enamored of simple but luscious desserts _ Johnson's summer
pudding, rhubarb tart and Irish trifle, and Day-Lewis' peach and
almond crumble tart or black currant ice cream, mousse or fool.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Irish Heritage Cookbook,'' by Margaret M. Johnson (Chronicle &LR; 
 &LR; Books, 288 pages, large soft-cover, $18.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``West of Ireland Summers; a Cookbook,'' by Tamasin Day-Lewis &LR; 
 &LR; (Roberts Rinehart, 160 pages hard-cover, $19.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHEDDAR COLCANNON TORTE
</P>
<P>
   This is an update of an Irish classic from ``The Irish Heritage
Cookbook.'' If savoy cabbage is not available, one medium head Napa
cabbage may be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 head savoy cabbage, cored and shredded
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   6 slices bacon, diced
</P>
<P>
   4 baking potatoes, peeled, cut into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cheddar cheese, shredded (2 cups), preferably Kerrygold
from Ireland
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Grease a 9-inch pie plate or
tart pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, blanch the cabbage in boiling salted water
for 2 minutes. Drain and plunge into cold water. Drain again and
transfer to paper towels to dry.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet, heat the butter over medium heat. Add the
bacon and cook until browned. With a slotted spoon, transfer the
bacon to a bowl and reserve the bacon drippings in the pan. Add the
cabbage to the bacon and toss gently. Sprinkle the potatoes with
salt and pepper and toss in the bacon drippings.
</P>
<P>
   Layer 1/3 of the potatoes in the prepared pan. Sprinkle with 1/3
of the cheese, top with half the cabbage mixture and sprinkle with
another third of the cheese. Add another 1/3 potatoes, the
remaining cheese, then the remaining cabbage mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Top with remaining potatoes. Cover with a sheet of parchment
paper or aluminum foil and bake for 45 minutes. Remove from the
oven and let cool for 30 minutes, or to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut into wedges and serve with a green salad.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 265 calories, &LR;   &LR; 11 g protein, 20 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 16 g fat (10 g saturated), 46 mg cholesterol, 301 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
IRISH STEW
</P>
<P>
   Tamasin Day-Lewis writes that this version of Irish stew might
make purists frown, but ``the Irish stew of my childhood always had
barley in it and that's how I like it.'' From ``West of Ireland
Summers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds small potatoes or chopped large ones, peeled
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds boneless lamb slices (such as lamb tenderloin)
</P>
<P>
   1 bouquet garni: 2 bay leaves, 2 sprigs each, rosemary, thyme
and parsley, tied together
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces pearl barley
</P>
<P>
   1 pound carrots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 sticks of celery, sliced
</P>
<P>
   A handful fresh parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large, heavy-bottomed casserole and add the
onions, garlic and half of the potatoes. Cook over low heat until
the onions are slightly softened. Add the lamb, bouquet garni and
the stock and bring to a boil. Cover and simmer for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the barley and simmer for 10 minutes, then add the carrots,
celery, half of the chopped parsley and the remaining potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Simmer for a further 30 minutes, by which time the lamb should
be tender and the first lot of potatoes and the barley will have
thickened the stew. Season with salt and pepper, add the remaining
chopped parsley and serve in bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 475 calories, &LR;   &LR; 39 g protein, 48 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 14 g fat (4 g saturated), 101 mg cholesterol, 162 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3349 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR &LR;      03-09 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVELIST'S LATEST HAS SCREENPLAY WRITTEN ALL OVER IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If film adaptations were a measure of a novelist's achievement,
Sue Miller would be successful beyond her wildest dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel, ``The Good Mother,'' was the basis for a 1988
movie starring Diane Keaton and Liam Neeson. Five years later came
``Family Pictures'' with Sam Neill and Anjelica Huston, a
television movie based on her novel about the dynamics of a large,
troubled family. And in 1997, Liv Tyler starred in ``Inventing the
Abbotts,'' a film based on a collection of Miller's short stories.
</P>
<P>
   She signed over rights to each book with equanimity _ ``I've
always welcomed money,'' she says, ``because it buys time for
writing'' _ but she has refused to see any of the films that were
made of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any writers whose testimony is that the
experience is great fun,'' she says. ``I'm just a very controlling
person. I don't want to see a line spoken differently from the way
I heard it in my head when I wrote it. There are lots of people
involved in a movie, and they'll each see things in a different way
_ the director will, the actor will; there will be so many
possibilities for it to be different that it will have to be. I've
been perfectly comfortable, so far, not seeing any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, her latest novel might be the most cinematic of
all. ``While I Was Gone'' is the story of Jo Becker, a middle-age
wife and mother whose idyllic life in small-town Massachusetts is
shaken when a man from her past moves to town. Eli Mayhew's sudden
appearance brings with it the seductive pull of memory. It also
introduces something new from Miller _ that most dependable of plot
devices, an unsolved murder. This one was committed 30 years
before, in the shadowy history that Jo and Eli share.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really the way the book began in my mind,'' Miller
says. ``I liked the idea of a woman whose past included this
episode, and that she was going to be reconfronted with it in some
way. I wanted to explore questions about what is and isn't
forgivable, and about degrees of guilt. Jo is called upon to
forgive a truly terrible thing, while at the same time she does
something terrible herself and needs to be forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   Novel borrows from current events
</P>
<P>
   Current events played into the path her story took. The O.J.
Simpson trial was in the news when Miller began ``While I Was
Gone,'' and she became fascinated with Simpson's earnest denials of
guilt in the deaths of Nicole Brown and Ronald Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to truly believe that he was an innocent person,''
Miller says. ``Maybe he is. I truly believe he's not. There was a
similar case in Boston _ a kid who was convicted of killing the
mother of one of his friends. He never admitted that he did it, and
his parents were adamant that he didn't. Their belief in him and
his need to believe that he couldn't have done such a terrible
thing made him seem very credible, despite DNA and other evidence
that was very, very convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a logical extension of our `cult of
self-forgiveness,' if you want to call it that. We all do it about
lesser evils in our lives _ we give ourselves a quick, fast-food
sort of forgiveness because we can't stand to think we are capable
of doing these things. We separate ourselves off from things that
we have trouble integrating into our sense of self. That's true in
varying degrees among the characters in this novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller began writing ``While I Was Gone'' after a failed effort
to write a memoir about her father's death of Alzheimer's disease.
She struggled for several years with the project before she fled
back to fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that time I was very worried about myself as a writer,''
she says. ``Non-fiction was new for me, and I was bound to have
trouble with it, but after a few years I felt so terrible that I
just plunged into this novel. The drama of the story was part of
that _ I wanted something that would compel me as much as it would
compel the reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Family interplay rings true
</P>
<P>
   But ``While I Was Gone'' also is graced by Miller's trademark,
her remarkable ear and eye for the understated interplay among
members of a family _ in this case Jo Becker, her husband, Daniel,
and their three daughters. Miller has one son who is now 30, but
she grew up (``the difficult daughter,'' she says) in a family of
two boys and two girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of those sibling scenes that I describe,'' she
says. ``People slamming doors and running away, that kind of thing.
``Family Pictures'' was the most mired in family of all my books.
Sad and terrible things happen in it, but I cautioned myself, when
I was writing it, to make sure it didn't sound like an
overwhelmingly awful life. Because it was a wonderful life in many
ways. That book trained me to write about families. The mother in
it actually says at one point that it's those small moments that
keep us going, the grace notes that embellish our lives and make
them seem beautiful. When they happen, they're worth recording.''
</P>
<P>
   With all of her books, Miller has walked the line between
serious writing and commercial success, sometimes taking critical
flak for the latter. One of two unpublished novels she wrote before
``The Good Mother'' was short on plot and long on literary effort,
she says, ``and I came to see it as weak because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about all of the novels I've loved as a reader,
about their depth and texture and how watching the characters walk
around doing things made me see life in a different way,'' she
says. ``But that's the point. They were walking around doing
things. There were scenes on the page.
</P>
<P>
   ``You owe your readers an engaging experience. Your book should
not make itself difficult. I know there are writers who feel very
differently, who say to hell with the reader who won't do an
enormous amount of work to read their stuff. But not me. It's a lot
to ask of people, at this time in our culture, to stop and read a
book. And it's a great privilege to be read, so your work should
justify itself, as Conrad said, word by word.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller herself is a reader. She loves the books of Alice
McDermott, Alice Munro, Ron Hansen and Carol Shields, writers with
whom she empathizes in their efforts to write fiction that
satisfies both themselves and their audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a woman who compared writing a novel to knitting an
argyle sock the size of a football field,'' Miller says. ``I think
that is very apt. It's just such a struggle to shape it all up. And
then it's published, and I worry about it making its way in the
world. And then I worry about getting another idea. It's always
something.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
