<SLUG> BC-GE-WELCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE CHIEF SEES CONTINUED GROWTH FOR BLUE-CHIP GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KENNETH C. CROWE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. _ The General Electric Co. will outperform
the Standard &AMP; Poor's Index this year as it prepares for a change
in its top leadership, according to the company's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   A successor for GE Chairman John F. Welch Jr. is expected to
take over in 2000. But who the next chairman will be is a matter of
speculation. GE Power Systems President Robert Nardelli is
considered to be on the short list of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have a luxury of having an enormous pool of
talented people,'' Welch said Monday in a satellite news conference
sponsored by the Wall Street brokerage firm Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Welch is credited with building the company into a $325 billion
international giant. It is GE's recent international acquisitions
in Japan and other countries that are expect to continue to push
the company's profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Having a presence in developed countries such as Japan allows
the company to make the big moves that can produce large rewards
due to regulation, Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The developed countries are the place to be if you're going to
make big bets,'' he said, noting Japan's regulations and energetic
and educated work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll outperform the S&AMP;P and the companies in it,'' said
Welch, who wants to match or exceed the 14 percent earnings and
dividend growth rates of the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   GE's global business will play an important role in maintaining
this growth rate. Sales, manufacturing and sourcing of materials
have to be drawn from various countries. Welch described Mexico as
an example of a country that is a great source for products sold by
GE.
</P>
<P>
   Welch also said that the international market will move faster
and that people will have to put aside their aversion to drawing
upon other countries for intellectual investments in products
produced by companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to globalize the intellect of the product,'' Welch
said citing India's wealth of software engineers as a resource.
</P>
<P>
   GE also will see more income from providing services to the
products it and its competitors sell, Welch said. ``Customers
increasingly want to know what is the solution to their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems, the company's turbine business, is booming
currently. Its U.S. plants, including the one in Schenectady, N.Y.,
are operating at full capacity to serve the U.S. marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   With 40 percent of the world's gas turbine business, GE is now
considering the acquisition of the power generation business of
Alstom SA of Paris. Alstom has about 12 percent of the world's
market.
</P>
<P>
   Being the No. 1 maker of power generation equipment in the world
is in keeping with the GE philosophy developed under Welch of being
one of the two largest companies in any field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to be No. 1 or No. 2 to survive in an increasingly
global market,'' Welch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
