<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBRIGHT-CRITICS-BOS &LR;      03-09 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-CRITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT CALLED LACKING IN POLICY FOLLOW-THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Madeleine K. Albright climbed the heights of
Washington's foreign policy establishment with a knack for chewing
out dictators, delivering pithy sound bites, and charming even the
most curmudgeonly Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, dictators don't seem to be listening to the
first female US secretary of state. The Republicans she so
assiduously courted, including Senator Jesse Helms, have not
delivered on some key foreign policy items she needed, including
funding for the United Nations. And Albright has been attacked for
lacking the follow-through to fashion durable foreign policy
solutions to back up her blunt one-liner style.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of unrestrained bipartisan admiration, a more
critical reassessment of Albright's record is emerging as an array
of foreign policy crises have stacked up. The once-undisputed
darling of the media is getting bad press. And even some of
Albright's closest allies are privately asking themselves whether
she is in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albright has handled herself very well in public diplomacy,''
said Joseph Cirincione, the director of the arms proliferation
program at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace and an
ally of the administration on many issues. ``But in finding
creative solutions to new problems, she is just falling way
short.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey of international crises provides an unsettling view.
The ``strategic partnership'' with China has failed to translate
into greater respect for human rights. The Middle East peace
process has been jeopardized by renewed fighting between Israel and
Iranian-backed rebels in Lebanon. The civil war in Kosovo is
threatening to spoil NATO's 50th birthday party in April. The fate
of Russia's new democracy, ever fragile, appears as uncertain as
ever. And the State Department was unprepared when terrorists
targeted US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear arms race has come back to life in the wake of
missile tests in North Korean and nuclear weapons tests in Pakistan
and India. Even Washington's relations with its closest European
allies have been strained by a trade war over bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior US foreign policy specialists say the thorniest
issues _ China, the Middle East peace process and Iraq, arms
control, and missile defense _ have been taken over by President
Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger. Washington's
Asia policy has been dominated by the Treasury Department. And Vice
President Al Gore's national security adviser, foreign policy aide
Leon Furth, has become an increasingly active voice on foreign
policy, according to US officials.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's defenders say the roots of the problem lie elsewhere,
not with her.
</P>
<P>
   She serves a president who pays only sporadic attention to
foreign policy, they say. And she is leading foreign policy in an
era in which the neat strategic symmetry of the Cold War has given
way to an array of complex and intractable troubles that defy easy
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has a lot on the table,'' Democratic
Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts said in an interview. ``And
these problems are going to beset any administration. It's the
nature of the new diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, Madeleine is doing a very good job in a very
tough climate,'' he added. ``I think the Republicans have been
quite partisan. They are very quick to criticize and not very quick
to offer alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Even critics credit Albright with being among the first in the
administration to recognize that US military force would be needed
to end ethnic cleansing in Bosnia. And as US ambassador to the
United Nations, she spearheaded US efforts to create a war crimes
tribunal for Yugoslavia and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also effectively used her personal relationship with
the powerful chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
Jesse Helms, to win ratification of the treaty banning chemical
weapons. But Helms has failed to bring along House Republicans on
paying Washington's $1 billion debt to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's efforts to win US backing for two initiatives close
to her heart _ creation of an International Criminal Court and a
treaty banning land mines _ collapsed in the face of intense
Pentagon opposition. More recently, she stumbled in Kosovo, where
Serbian strongman Slobodan Milosevic ignored, so far without
consequence, a threat by Albright to sign a peace settlement or
face NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Madeleine's fault that we're facing a rough patch for
foreign policy right now,'' said a senior US official in Albright's
inner circle, adding that she is being held to a higher standard
than her male counterparts. ``That's the nature of the ebbs and
flow of foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration, critics say, global strategic
considerations take a back seat to domestic policy. And when an
international crisis threatens to spill over to the national
agenda, the president's foreign policy team focuses on achieving a
quick fix _ before moving onto the next crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an administration that has an `in box' for foreign
policy,'' said Ivo Daalder, a former National Security Council
specialist on the Balkans in the first Clinton administration. ``It
deals with the crisis of the day with sufficient attention to get
it into the `out box.' Some issues, like Russia, go into the `too
hard' box.''
</P>
<P>
   While Daalder gives Albright credit for being tough on Bosnia,
he said she stumbled when it came to crafting a long term strategy
for the region after the bombs stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual policy had to be devised by someone else,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She conveys a mixture of authority and insecurity,'' Britain's
former UN ambassador, Sir John Weston, wrote in a memo to the
British foreign office recounted by Ann Blackman in her biography
of Albright. ``She is not good at devising a detailed game plan for
pursuing broad objectives,'' added Weston, who worked closely with
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's obsession with domestic politics can have
disastrous consequences for foreign policy, say observers. During
the 1996 election campaign, Clinton increased spending on missile
defense research after the issue emerged as a key element of
Republican candidate Bob Dole's platform.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the North Korean missile tests over Japan,
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen announced another $6 billion in
funding for missile defense research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This policy worked politically in 1996 and it will work in
2000,'' said Cirincione. ``But the international consequences are
severe. This all but kills any hope that the Russian Duma will
ratify Start II,'' the still unratified nuclear arms reduction
treaty between the US and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it has spurred weapons development in China,'' he added.
``Our European allies look at us like we are nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, European diplomats say that, personalities aside,
they see little difference between Albright and her predecessor,
Warren M. Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   They complain that American foreign policy is not creative
enough and relies too much on the threat of military action. When
force is threatened and not delivered, as was the case in Bosnia,
Iraq, and Kosovo, it seriously undermines the credibility of the
West and NATO, they say.
</P>
<P>
   To her credit, they said, Albright was willing to put her
credibility on the line in the Kosovo talks to bridge what seemed
an unbridgeable gap. But if Albright's gambit was gutsy, it also
was heavy-handed, several European diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is trying to prove she is as macho as Richard Holbrooke,''
one European complained, referring to the American diplomat who
negotiated an end to the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is unapologetic, saying diplomacy backed by the threat
of force is the only thing that despots like Milosevic and Saddam
Hussein listen to and respond to.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she may be vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians have indicated they are prepared to return
to France next week to sign the agreement that would restore
autonomy to Kosovo but would not guarantee an independence
referendum, although the smart money won't count on anything until
the ink is dry.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Europe's ambivalence about her style, Albright has
displayed sharp instincts for domestic policy.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, she has been unfailingly loyal to the
president. And officials say her tenure is secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was tough and strong on the issues that I thought were
important,'' Clinton said after appointing her. ``I thought she
would be the person most likely to connect with the American
people, to bring the message of our foreign policy home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Rambouillet, France.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
