<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-09 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RED SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Should China be encouraged to join the World Trade
Organization? The Clinton administration has been maneuvering for
years to bring the world's most populous nation into the 133-member
treaty on tariffs and trade. ``I think it should be out of the
question,'' said Senate majority leader Trent Lott (R-Alabama),
when asked about it Sunday on a morning talk show.
</P>
<P>
   That's the business end of the story about Chinese espionage
that made headlines over the weekend. The New York Times and
Newsweek magazine reported that the Chinese recently had made giant
strides in the miniaturization of their nuclear weaponry, thanks at
least in part to the theft of secrets from the United States during
the 1980s. And while the story looks mainly like the continuation
by other means of the GOP campaign against Clinton, it has serious
implications for the future of both the arms race and global trade.
</P>
<P>
   Some background: During the early 1980s, when Ronald Reagan was
in the White House, the Chinese apparently mounted an extensive
campaign to steal from US weapons shops plans for small nuclear
warheads that otherwise would have taken Chinese scientists many
years and huge sums to perfect. For reasons as yet unexplained, the
Chinese apparently found an easy mark at Los Alamos National
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times, the theft went completely unnoticed
until 1995, when weapons experts at Los Alamos monitoring Chinese
underground testing discerned some striking resemblances between
the characteristics of a Chinese device and America's latest
design, the W-88 warhead. A couple of months later, CIA analysts
received a copy of a Chinese document purporting to be dated 1988
that mentioned the W-88 by name and described some of its features.
</P>
<P>
   The central figure here is an US Department of Energy sleuth
named Notra Trulock. The department owns the Los Alamos lab;
Trulock was among those charged with policing its secrets. With the
aid of the FBI, he relatively quickly identified a likely suspect:
a Chinese-American computer scientist who had secretly traveled to
Shanghai in 1985. The suspect was still in his job.
</P>
<P>
   Trulock spread the alarm within the complex US intelligence
community with varying degrees of success; some thought he was
overstating the damage. Eventually he enlisted the support of FBI
director Louis B. Freeh and Central Intelligence director George
Tenet.
</P>
<P>
   But when he went to the top _ to National Security Adviser
Samuel Berger in 1996, to then Energy Secretary Frederico Pena in
1997 _ the administration did not act quickly enough to allay his
fears. President Clinton was briefed as well, but continued to
pursue commercial and scientific links with China _ despite being
under GOP fire for having accepted illegal Chinese donations to his
reelection campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point, Trulock's frustrations became known to a
number of Republican legislators. A select congressional committee
was convened, led by Representative Christopher Cox (R-Cal.); the
whistle-blower gave extensive secret testimony; and the rest is
history _ highly classified history. Portions of the committee's
700-page report, completed last fall, apparently are the basis of
much of the story so far.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has to do with the investigators' judgment _ and
their motives. Is Trulock a great detective? Or simply the latest
of a number of Reagan and Bush administration holdovers, including
Secret Service agent Gary Aldrich and White House secretary Linda
Tripp, who have sought to damage a president of whom they
personally disapprove? Did the White House move too slowly at the
beginning of Clinton's second term in responding to news of the
theft? Without a good deal more information, there is simply no way
to form a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese nuclear capability is not a trivial concern. But there
is a perfectly straightforward approach to the matter. Extend to
Central Intelligence director Tenet the same kind of insulation
from political tampering that has been enjoyed for some years by
Attorney General Janet Reno and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin.
Constructively engage the Chinese on commercial questions and human
rights concern. Bring them into the WTO. Continue working on new
methods of missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Then hold the next election.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
