<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISLAND-DISCONTENT-2TA     03-09 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-DISCONTENT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CARIBBEAN, DREAM VACATIONS FAN DISCONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTRIES, St. Lucia _ Early on a Sunday morning, 250 smiling
vacationers cram into a departure lounge at Logan Airport. Within
hours, they will be on the Caribbean island of St. Lucia, joining
conga lines, sipping banana daiquiris, and making return trips to
buffet tables for second slabs of cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   But their dream vacations will be fanning dark clouds of
discontent over the island, one of dozens of Caribbean locales that
attracted 9 million tourists from the United States last year,
drawn by increasingly inexpensive packages to ``all-inclusive''
resorts _ air, hotel, transfers, meals, drinks, and tips for one
price.
</P>
<P>
   As they settle into their sunnily appointed Club Med rooms,
these guests will be surrounded by St. Lucians who detest the kind
of tourism all-inclusive packages typify: resorts that are islands
themselves, deliberately separate from the life of the tiny nation.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists' sheets will be changed by maids who make as little as
$8 a day, on an island where sneakers cost $75.
</P>
<P>
   Taxi drivers will wait in their cars for hours hoping someone
ventures out of the compound for sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant owners will watch tables sit empty while resort
guests pile their plates high on Mexican Night.
</P>
<P>
   And the residents of shanty towns will see the tourists speed by
in buses on their way to spend money at the island's more
picturesque attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners spend more than a billion dollars annually on trips
to St. Lucia, but only a fraction, $284 million, ever lands there.
Of that, an estimated $198 million goes right back overseas to
suppliers of luxury goods for the travel industry.
</P>
<P>
   What remains, say many St. Lucians, is just enough to keep them
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're killing our country,'' said Stephen Raphael, a taxi
driver whose fares have been curtailed by pre-paid airport
transfers. ``Tourism is our main industry, but with the
all-inclusives, the tourist dollar is circulating only there, and
tourists who come to our country don't see its beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Every March, high season for winter vacationers, thousands of
New England residents head to St. Lucia. Only the New York area
sends more tourists there each year.
</P>
<P>
   And four out of every five passengers on weekly direct charter
flights from Boston end up at all-inclusive resorts, a kind of
cross between a cruise ship and summer camp that provides
everything from free rum punch at the swim-to bar, to all-day
snorkeling _ all on one property, all for one up-front payment.
</P>
<P>
   These full-service resorts, which are highly profitable and
heavily touted by travel agents who stand to make higher
commissions on sales, have been the fastest-growing sector of the
Caribbean tourist industry since the early 1990s. And St. Lucia, an
island of 238 square miles and a population of 150,000, has a
higher proportion of all-inclusives than any of the other islands:
eight of its 14 major hotels, and about half of its total 3,500
beds.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are so many of them, the all-inclusive resorts
have fueled a bitter debate among locals about the future of the
former British colony. Critics say the all-inclusives give little
back to the islands, make locals feel like visitors in their own
country, and turn St. Lucia into a haven for the kind of tourist
for whom ease is all and location an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could take some of these hotels and put them in the middle
of the ocean somewhere and (the guests) would still be happy,''
said St. Lucian financial analyst Richard Peterkin.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least on any other island. One hotel, eager to meet
guests' expectations despite the realities of nature, shipped in
pristine, brochure-quality white sand from Guyana because St.
Lucia's product was too gray.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Caribbean has long been a destination sold less
for its islands' particular attributes than for the generic trinity
of sun, sea and sand. And like many poorer destinations, it has
always raised questions among both visitors and islanders about
us-and-them exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   But tensions heightened in St. Lucia with the proliferation of
all-inclusive resorts, said locals.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of that development, some St. Lucians wonder if this
island, which passed between British and French control 14 times
before gaining independence in 1979, has merely exchanged one set
of colonial rulers for another, less predictable kind, staking its
fate on a tourist industry more concerned with its own bottom line
than with the island's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see this island, it is beautiful,'' said taxi driver
Thomas Favesh. ``But it's a kind of trap for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This past Feb. 22, St. Lucian Independence Day, the Unicorn, a
53-year-old, two-masted brig very popular with tourists here,
dropped its passengers in Soufriere, a poor fishing village, for a
bus ride to the island's renowned sulphur springs, in the bed of a
dead volcano.
</P>
<P>
   St. Lucians sat outside a row of shacks on the waterfront,
beside dinghies with names like Not Much, A Man Must Be Strong, and
Destiny, warily watching the tourists being driven through the
village. Although some tourists do stop in Soufriere, these
visitors, many of whom bought their tours through all-inclusive
resorts, would be back on the boat by lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have tour guides. They have a schedule to follow,'' said
Lily St. Jean, who sells handicrafts at a stall in Soufriere. She
sat under a tarpaulin, crocheting a blanket. ``They keep their
money at the hotels. They're told they don't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Jean says she sometimes goes weeks without selling anything.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks from the waterfront, up a hill and across a
rocky ravine, Stephen Antoine sat in a dank wooden shack, his
soiled purple T-shirt stretched over his bare knees, a bag of
charcoal at his feet, waiting. He said he hoped the crew from the
boat would buy some fuel for their barbecues. But the tourist
dollar rarely penetrates as far as Antoine's home. So far this
year, he has sold a bag and a half of charcoal, earning $13 to
supplement his $30 monthly pension payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I get from them, I'm grateful,'' said Antoine, who
did not know his age, but appeared to be in his 60s. ``I take what
they give me.''
</P>
<P>
   Soufriere has been a flashpoint for the tension at the heart of
St. Lucia's tourist industry: The island, with a per capita income
of $3,200, 20 percent unemployment, and little in the way of
government assistance, depends on tourism for its economic future,
but many residents, unable to see how they benefit from it, resent
the industry, especially the all-inclusives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know for a fact that tourism is bringing millions of
dollars into the country, but not everybody is getting their fair
share,'' said Raphael, the taxi driver, who relies on fares from
the non-all-inclusive hotels to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hotel industry's supplies must be imported into St.
Lucia, which is fertile but does not produce food in sufficient
quantities for a large resort. The situation heightens the sense
that the industry contributes little to the island. According to
Price Waterhouse analyst Richard Peterkin, about 70 percent of the
income St. Lucia makes from tourism goes to imports. He emphasized,
however, that the 30 percent that remains of tourism revenues still
provides the island with far more income than agriculture does.
</P>
<P>
   But restaurant owners, taxi drivers and street vendors from the
north to the south of St. Lucia insisted they could capture far
more revenue from the tourist industry, keeping desperately needed
dollars on the island, had not the all-inclusives created enclosed
camps from which tourists seldom venture. But in Soufriere,
residents made their feelings clearer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been a lot of harassment there,'' said Eudes Bourne,
deputy permanent secretary of the Ministry of Tourism. ``People
were going up to the tourists asking if they want to buy this or
that, that they wanted to get something from them as if they were
encroaching on their property. It's a small pocket of resistance,
but it's being addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders reject locals' concerns that all-inclusives
limit the benefits of tourism to fewer people. If vendors and
restaurateurs are upset, argued Maria Fowell, deputy director of
the St. Lucia Tourist Board, they should change the way they do
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has changed, and their approach must change,'' she
said. ``The restaurants haven't come together to make a great
dine-around (meal exchange) program with the all-inclusives. And
the other problem is pricing. People are not looking to be ripped
off. If the taxi fare is phenomenal, what's the point of leaving an
all-inclusive to go to a restaurant? People will take a chance only
if they feel they'll get value for money.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1436EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3375 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISLAND-DISCONTENT-2ND     03-09 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-DISCONTENT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CASTRIES, St. Lucia: ... for money.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The idea of the money not staying here is a myth,'' added Noel
Cadasse, president of the island's hotel association, who owns a
small, traditional hotel in the capital, Castries. ``I don't
measure the all-inclusives' contribution to St. Lucia purely from
what they purchase. Firstly, they pay salaries. And they pay local
amenities. And they purchase a lot locally from farmers. But their
demand for food is great, and you can't tell me I can't import fish
if the St. Lucia Fishing Corp. can't get me the fish I need.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism employs 11,000 St. Lucians, according to a 1996
government estimate. The upmarket, 600-guest Sandals St. Lucia
resort employs 500 people, most local, said spokeswoman Judy
Deterville. The Odyssey resort, which averages about 900 guests,
employs 460.
</P>
<P>
   But since there is no minimum wage in St. Lucia, salaries vary
widely. At the higher paying resorts _ Odyssey, for example _ maids
earn about $100 a week, plus annual service charges of about
$1,000. Middle-level managers earn about $300 per week. Others pay
much less: At Club Med, in the south of the island, junior maids
make $8 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else is there to do?'' asked one Club Med maid who is
trying to support six children. She asked that her name be withheld
for fear of losing her job.
</P>
<P>
   Among more visible Club Med workers _ receptionists, sports
organizers and child care providers _ of whom just one-third are
locals, St. Lucians are paid less than imported workers _ about $85
per week in addition to their room and board. At Le Sport, one of
the island's most expensive but lowest-paying resorts, a bellhop
makes $70 a week. While the bellhop can buy a barbecued chicken
wing by the side of the road for 40 cents, processed food in St.
Lucia is far more expensive than it is in the United States. And
his sneakers cost more than a week's salary.
</P>
<P>
   Conscious of their long-running public relations problems, some
all-inclusives have launched community outreach programs. Some are
more ambitious than others: Club Med, for example, has budgeted
about $6,000 for charitable programs over the next six months, said
its chief, Christian Aubert. Sandals, one of the pricier resorts,
contributed $37,000 to charity last year, said Deterville.
</P>
<P>
   Odyssey, a budget resort opened in 1987 by St. Lucia resident
Bill Stewart, supports the education of 15 local children, and will
offer college scholarships to St. Lucian children starting this
year. Stewart says the resort also works with local farmers,
guaranteeing them sales if they can grow the kind of produce the
resort needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want tourists to come down and be seen as having no
real benefit to the community,'' Stewart said. ``But educating
people isn't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Lucian government, too, has launched a public relations
campaign to educate schoolchildren about the benefits of tourism,
and to make them more willing to embrace it as important to the
island's future in the wake of its declining banana industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as long as the island is saddled with all-inclusives, there
will be resistance, locals say.
</P>
<P>
   All-inclusives provide ``a pasteurized holiday in a place that
might be a bit menacing,'' said Albert Haman, a Minnesotan who came
to the island 30 years ago and now runs a chain of gift stores.
``Americans like things their way. You go to a foreign destination
but you're protected from it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more successful chains, Sandals, was founded partly
to keep locals away from the guests, industry officials said. Begun
in 1982 in Jamaica at a time of rising crime rates, the first
Sandals resort was made all-inclusive to protect tourists from
attacks, they said.
</P>
<P>
   When the resorts first came to St. Lucia, they alienated locals
by trying to keep them away from tourists, too, even though the
island's crime rate was far lower than Jamaica's, and public beach
access on the island is sacrosanct.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't need (protection from locals) in St. Lucia. There's
not that negativity here like you get in some islands,'' said Colin
Hunte, who operates a small, traditional hotel near one of the
island's two Sandals resorts. ``The all-inclusives had their
philosophy, and then there was the island's philosophy, and the two
clashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after local furor and legal challenges, the resorts
began courting St. Lucians, offering them greater access, although
they sometimes still treat locals with suspicion, searching some
cars as they enter or leave compounds.
</P>
<P>
   And while a few offer island tours, some, like Club Med, make it
hard for vacationers to see the world beyond their fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that it's not something they encourage,'' said
Club Med guest Jennifer Mott-Wylie, of Burlington, Vt. ``We were
talking to (staffers) during dinner, and they say it's not easy to
go into town. They said it was dangerous, and it makes you want to
stay right here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, all-inclusives are also more likely to attract guests
who prefer the generic resort to the specific location, said
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on vacation,'' said Kay Foley, of Neenah, Wisc. ``I'd just
as soon stay in one spot. My biggest worry here is what am I going
to eat and what am I going to drink.'' Foley was wading by the
swim-to bar at Odyssey, drinking a Scotch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is relaxing, and that's what I came for,'' said
Linda Beattie, of Detroit. ``It's more economical and it seems
safer. You're staying put, and they map everything out.''
</P>
<P>
   That worries residents, who say the all-inclusives have helped
to turn the island into Anyplace, Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me and other St. Lucians is that we no longer see
tourists who have come here because they chose St. Lucia,'' said
Haman. ``They chose hotels. They're not coming to the island.
They're coming to Sandals.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has lately been taking steps to discourage new
all-inclusives. They provide tax incentives to standard hotels now
_ 15 years free of tax, compared to 10-year tax holidays for
all-inclusives.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts are pinning their hopes on a new 300-room,
noninclusive Hyatt under construction. The new hotel, they said,
would attract well-heeled tourists who would also be more likely to
explore the island, patronizing local restaurants and stores.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is another all-inclusive on the drawing board, in
the south. And Sandals St. Lucia is in the midst of a $15 million
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, St. Lucia has limited control over what kind of
developments are built. Because the bottom line, say St. Lucians,
is that this island needs the tourists far more than the tourists
need this island.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many thousands of youngsters have nothing to do,'' said
Georges Noah, a 73-year-old retired printer from the island's
poorer South. ``The bananas can't help them now. T'would be a
pleasure for us to see something else to take (their) place, but
what can we expect besides the tourists? St. Lucia is a poor
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
