<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE: A YEAR PACKED WITH EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans are heading to Europe in record numbers. And for good
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a year for great music, a solar eclipse, medieval
events, fine art, royal happenings, a new currency, historic events
including a new capital for Germany, and the opening of Scotland's
own Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The European Travel Commission is predicting more than 11.5
Americans will visit the Continent this year. If this comes true,
it would be a 5 percent increase over 1998, making this the seventh
record travel year in a row for North American visitors. Europe
continues to account for nearly half of all overseas trips by
Americans and more than double the traffic to any other overseas
region, said Joseph E. Buhler of Switzerland, the US chairman of
the 29-nation European Travel Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in tourism can be explained by not only the interest
in Europe but also the growing ease in getting from here to there,
traveling within the Continent, the multitude of tour packages
available, and the bounty of helpful information through guidebooks
and computer-related services.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, for example, now has extensive nonstop air service to
England, Switzerland, Ireland, France, Germany, and Belgium. United
Airlines will begin Boston-London service in April, which will mean
New Englanders will have four airlines flying this route daily _
British Airways has three daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   Still one of the best ways to get around Europe is via rail. The
service is excellent, providing comfortable and reliable
transportation to the heart of European cities. The Eurailpass,
which has provided countless miles of unlimited travel between
nations, has changed, giving travelers more flexibility in their
planning of an itinerary. But giving the rails competition are the
new open skies of Europe, with new discount airlines providing
competitive service between nations.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising in Europe has also made travel there a breeze. Cruises
are one of the easiest ways to discover the countries of Europe.
Ships that travelers are familiar with from Caribbean sailings now
become their European hotel, sailing from nation to nation with
none of the packing and unpacking associated with land tours.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether you travel by sea or land, there are tour
packages for every budget, every interest.
</P>
<P>
   Even guides to the Continent are making it easier for first-time
travelers _ and even experienced ones _ to not only find their way
around but to really experience Europe at its best. Rick Steves,
who Americans have become familiar with through his popular PBS-TV
series ``Travels in Europe,'' projects that same friendly knowing
travel experience through his guides: ``Rick Steves' Europe Through
the Back Door''; ``Europe 101: History &AMP; Art for the Traveler'';
``Mona Winks' Self-Guided Tours of Europe's Top Museums.'' Steves
also offers a free guide to European railpasses (especially good
considering the number of passes available). Write to Europe
Through the Back Door, Box 2009, Edmonds, WA 98020. New are books
that say it all through their titles: ``First-Timer Europe,
Everything you need to know before you to'' (Rough Guide, $9.95),
``The Complete Idiots Planning Your Trip to Europe'' (Alpha Books,
$16.95). New, too, are CD-ROMs to pop in the computer and guide you
on your way. Choice Way Media offers interactive guides to London,
Paris, and Berlin/Munich. These CD-ROMs offer maps and information
on everything from airline terminals to sights, along with color
photos and videos. The CDs are $39.95 each and come with on-line
updates. For more information, call 408-323-1546 or visit
www.choiceway.com.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's nothing like being there. Sure you can go to the
movies and see William Shakespeare ``in love,'' but nothing beats
the experience of seeing the places in England where he lived and
worked and hearing his plays as they were first performed 400 years
ago. The British Tourist Authority has lots of information on
experiencing Shakespeare: Call 800-462-2748 Mondays through
Fridays, 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., or visit
www.usageteway.visitbritain.com.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's '99 calendar is loaded with special events. Germany
celebrates the Year of Goethe, with Weimar as Europe's 1999
Cultural Capital. Denmark plans a full year of medieval celebration
to prove the Dark Ages weren't so gloomy after all. Britain will
mark the Age of Cromwell. Amsterdam's Van Gogh Museum reopens in
June with more paintings on display. Spain celebrates the 100th
birthday of Ernest Hemingway. Monaco marks the 50th year of the
reign of Prince Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, a total eclipse of the sun will sweep across the
middle of Europe. The moon will block the sun and cast its shadow
on a 70-mile-wide path. The eclipse will take about 90 minutes on
its path from Land's End in England (11:10 a.m.) to Turkey (2:40
p.m.). The total eclipse will take a maximum of 2 minutes, 20
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There will be great music with Strauss in Austria and Chopin in
Poland. No composer is more closely loved by the Austrians than
Johann Strauss (1825-1899), whose 400 waltzes (including ``The Blue
Danube'') provided the romantic tempo of late 19th-century Europe.
Poland's affection is equally strong for Frederic Chopin. To
commemorate the 150th anniversary of his death in 1849 at age 39,
Poland is staging an International Chopin Year with recitals
throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of art, it will be Van Dyke in Belgium, Velazquez
in Spain. Antwerp will open the largest showing of Anthony van
Dyck's painting, May 15 through Aug. 20, at the Royal Museum of
Fine Arts (the show goes to London in September). Diego Rodriguez
de Silva y Velazquez, whose portraits of Spanish royalty and dwarfs
are considered among the greatest of European paintings, will have
a major show at Madrid's Prado.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark goes medieval this year. The Danes will be recalling
their medieval period (beginning with the advent of Christianity a
millennium ago) with exhibitions and reenactments. England is
recalling Cromwell and the English Civil Wars with exhibitions and
debates. Oliver Cromwell led the forces of Parliament against
Charles I and established England's only republic in 1653.
</P>
<P>
   Monaco will be celebrating Prince Rainier's 50th anniversary of
his reign all year and especially on National Day, Nov. 19. He is
Europe's longest-reigning royal today.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin will be marking a series of milestones: the 50th
anniversary of the end of the Berlin Airlift; the 10th anniversary
of the Fall of the Wall; and the official establishment of its
federal parliament in the city. In May, the German government will
leave its 50-year old home in Bonn and move into Berlin's rebuilt
Reichstag.
</P>
<P>
   Among other happenings will be Scotland's celebration of its own
parliament; Hungary has declared this to be the Year of the
Pleasures of the Palate; and Oslo's Akershus Fortress will mark its
700th year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
