<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Encounters with Joe DiMaggio
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody cheered more loudly than I did when Al Gionfriddo, a
young Brooklyn Dodger reserve outfielder, chased and miraculously
caught Joe DiMaggio's sure home run in the sixth game of the 1947
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   I was 14, a Dodger fanatic. Joe DiMaggio was the enemy. Maybe it
was Red Barber's description on the radio. (''OH, Doctor!'') Maybe
it was because it was the peerless DiMaggio. Al Gionfriddo had his
six or seven seconds of eternal fame.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, in the '70s, my wife, Ruth, and I were standing on
the veranda of a wonderful old hotel at Cooperstown, N.Y. Joe
DiMaggio _ no longer the enemy _ was across the veranda, chatting
with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to say hello to him,'' Ruth said. You had to know
her. I wouldn't have dared.
</P>
<P>
   She crossed the veranda, and quickly caught his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Ruth Rosenfeld,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Joe DiMaggio,'' he replied. It was, like everything else
about him, perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
