<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VENICE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENICE IS A WONDERFUL AND WATERY PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
``Streets full of water. Advise.'' 
Robert Benchley 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Telegram sent from Venice to New Yorker editor Harold Ross. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy _ My first morning in Venice, I awoke to the loud
wail of an alarm siren. ``A fire somewhere,'' I thought, and went
back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But the alarm was about water, not fire. As I later learned
(getting my shoes damp in the process), it was a warning that there
would be a tidal surge this day and, with it, extensive flooding as
the city's main canals overflowed their banks.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I roused myself and headed to the nearest cafe for
breakfast, there was nearly an inch of water on my narrow
cobblestone street, which ran between two canals. A few hours
later, when I arrived at Piazza San Marco, arguably the grandest
square in Europe, it resembled an ornamental lake designed by some
master landscape artist of the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by a sheet of shallow water, the massive Basilica of
San Marco, a Byzantine extravaganza of domes and minarets, was a
fantasy island. The nearby Doge's Palace, fortified residence of
Venice's ruling dukes, seemed like a stone battleship at anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Venetians are used to their floods, and take them in stride.
Both men and women manage to look stylish, for instance, even when
sloshing around in utilitarian rubber boots instead of the elegant
footwear for which Italy is renowned.
</P>
<P>
   On high-water days, portable wooden walkways are laid down by
public works crews to provide dry passage through flooded areas. On
my visit to Piazza San Marco, a small army of tourists _ directed
with good humor by nattily dressed policemen in knee-high black
rubber boots _ was queuing up on the narrow boardwalks to cross the
vast square and enter the basilica and palace. There were a few dry
spots in the middle of the piazza, but these were all occupied by
San Marco's famous and pampered indigenous pigeons, who obviously
weren't about to share their turf with nonresidents.
</P>
<P>
   For visitors, Venice is about history, art, romance, and
atmosphere. But for the people (and pigeons) who live here, what
makes their city truly unique is water. It is a city defined by
water and dependent on it. There are no cars, and, as in no other
city in the world, boats of all types, from one-man gondolas to
high-speed water buses, are the dominant forms of transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Venice is really an archipelago, a group of several hundred
islands (most small and now surrounded by canals) in a lagoon some
three miles off Italy's Adriatic coast. It was founded in the fifth
century by refugees from the mainland fleeting the horsemen of
Attila the Hun, who could capture walled towns but were utterly
confounded by water.
</P>
<P>
   Water continued to protected Venice from marauding barbarians
and warring armies through the centuries. Water also brought
wealth. The great merchant navy the city developed, largely for
trade with the Byzantine Empire, made Venice one of the world's
wealthiest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Venice began to decline as a European power in the 15th century,
when the Byzantine Empire fell to the Turks and the discovery of
America changed trade and shipping patterns. But the accumulated
wealth of centuries continued to be spent lavishly on the city,
most visibly in the great churches and palaces that still line the
canals and cast their ornate reflections onto the shimmering water
with dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   At its height in the late Middle Ages, Venice had a population
of around 300,000, enormous for the time. A causeway to the
mainland was built in the 1930s, and since World War II many
Venetians have crossed it to settle in the booming industrial
suburb of Mestre, which lacks charm but has lots of jobs, modern
amenities (such as cars), and doesn't get flooded.
</P>
<P>
   Venice now has a year-round population of 65,000, less than half
of what it was 50 years ago. There is great concern in Italy about
``the vanishing Venetian'' and fear that Venice is becoming more a
museum than a city. However, since Venice gets about 12 million
visitors a year, its squares are as bustling and its canals as
heavily trafficked as they ever were.
</P>
<P>
   The streets are pretty busy, too. Since there is no automobile
traffic, all of Venice is a pedestrian zone. To enable walkers to
get around there are more than 400 bridges over the city's canals,
all arched so that the ubiquitous freight barges _ the delivery
vans of Venice _ can pass beneath them.
</P>
<P>
   The one canal that isn't easy to cross on foot is the most
important one of all: the Grand Canal. Shaped like a reversed
letter ``S,'' the Grand Canal both bisects and unites Venice. As
wide as a respectable river, the canal runs for almost 2 1/2 miles
through the heart of the city but has only three bridges across it.
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of water buses called ``vaporetti'' (literally,
``steamers'') plies the main canals but nowhere in such numbers as
on the Grand Canal, in effect, the main boulevard of the city.
Venice is an easy and interesting place to explore on foot, but
wherever I went my feet always seemed to take me back to the Grand
Canal and on to a vaporetto.
</P>
<P>
   The workhorse of the vaporetto system is the No. 1 line which
serves the length of the Grand Canal, with boats arriving and
departing every five or 10 minutes. Since most of Venice's main
sights _ including the principal churches, the grandest of the
palazzi, and the most important museums _ are on the Grand Canal,
an end-to-end trip on the No. 1 line amounts to a sightseeing tour.
This line is so tourist-friendly that stops are announced in
English as well as Italian, not the case on any other vaporetto
route.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
