<HEADER>
A3391 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VENICE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-09 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VENICE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 VENICE: Italy: ... vaporetto route.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The busiest of the Grand Canal vaporetto stops is unquestionably
Piazza San Marco. It's estimated that about half the visitors
Venice sees annually are in the city for less than a day. At least
part of that time is invariably spent in Piazza San Marco, and
sometimes all of it is.
</P>
<P>
   The Basilica of St. Mark and the Doge's Palace are must-see
buildings, their grandeur _ both are filled with art as well as
being works of art themselves _ conveying as no history book can
the glory that was Venice in its heyday. The basilica also holds
the revered remains of the apostle Mark _ the city's patron saint _
smuggled out of Constantinople after its capture by the Turks and
made the city's patron saint.
</P>
<P>
   When not flooded, which, of course, is most of the time, the
piazza is usually filled with swirling crowds and buzzing with
activity. Street performers abound, for instance, and a platoon of
sailors from the local Navy base marches into the square daily at
sunset for an impressive flag-lowering ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza San Marco is rimmed by arcaded buildings on three sides
but open to the Venetian Lagoon on the fourth. Besides vaporetti,
private motor boats, and cruiseship launches, the piazza's
waterfront is also home port for a fleet of gondolas.
</P>
<P>
   No longer a primary means of transportation, the graceful
high-prowed gondola is still a symbol of Venice and a common sight
in the city. As popular tourist attractions, gondola rides are
priced accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Gondoliers are not supposed to charge more than $80 during the
day and $100 at night for a 50-minute ride with up to six people.
They often demand more, however, charging extra for an off-key
rendition of ``O Sole Mio'' or claiming to take a more scenic route
than other gondoliers. Hard bargaining is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Budget travelers (or cheapskates) who want to sample the gondola
experience without spending a lot of money or time should try a
traghetto. That's a gondola water taxi that ferries passengers
across the Grand Canal in the long stretches among the three
bridges. The trip takes just a few minutes but only costs about 35
cents. Tourists usually sit down in a traghetto, but it's a point
of pride with Venetians to make the trip standing up.
</P>
<P>
   The arcades around Piazza San Marco house upscale shops and
restaurants that are among the most expensive in the city. Full of
charm and character, the cafes here _ some, such as Florian's,
little altered since the 18th century _ charge about as much for a
cup of espresso as you might expect to pay for lunch elsewhere. Of
course, what you're really buying is a ringside seat at one of the
world's great people-watching spectacles. Not to mention the
possibility that your table was the very one preferred by Richard
Wagner, Ernest Hemingway, Truman Capote, or some other celebrated
Venice habitue.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza San Marco is classically grand and formal. The streets
radiating from it, however, are mostly narrow, winding, and invite
exploration. Although picturesque and full of old-fashioned
Venetian flavor, this is still the high-rent district with
top-class restaurants, pricey stores, and boutique hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Another much touristed but delightful area for shopping and
dining is the Rialto, which is not only on the Grand Canal but more
or less straddles it. One of the three bridges over the Grand
Canal, the Rialto Bridge not only has lively neighborhoods at both
ends but the bridge itself is lined with small shops and a sort of
mini-mall unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   The third member of Venice's tourist troika, along with the
basilica and the palace, is the Accademia, which is also easily
accessed by vaporetto No. 1. There are other excellent museums in
Venice, but the Accademia is the museum, a sprawling former convent
and school complex housing the city's largest and best-displayed
collection of paintings from the glory days of Venetian art. All
the masters are here _ Tintoretto, Bellini, Titian, Carpaccio, et
al. _ and represented by some of their best work.
</P>
<P>
   The grandest of the palaces built by Venice's wealthy merchant's
and nobles are found along the Grand Canal. These days, few palaces
are in the hands of the families that built them, and those that
are, often badly need work. However, many palazzi have been bought
by wealthy non-Venetians (often foreigners) and completely restored
at great expense.
</P>
<P>
   One such Grand Canal palace, a short walk from the Accademia,
belonged to the late Peggy Guggenheim, a wealthy American socialite
and art collector. Guggenheim lived and behaved in the grand manner
(Venetians nicknamed her ``the last duchess'') but was a serious
collector of modern European painting and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Now a museum, Guggenheim's 18th-century palace still feels like
a home but displays a superb art collection, including paintings by
Picasso, Braque, Chagall, and Pollock and sculpture by Brancusi,
Moore, and Giacometti. The duchess remains in residence: She is
buried in the sculpture garden along with her ``beloved babies,''
the dozen Shih Tzu pet dogs she owned in her long lifetime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The day I left Venice, I had to get up early and take a last
vaporetto ride along the Grand Canal to Piazzale Roma, departure
point for the airport bus. Looking back down the canal from the
deck of the boat, I got the impression that Venice was putting on a
farewell performance just for me.
</P>
<P>
   The rising sun silhouetted the domes and spires of a dozen
churches and turned the murky water of the canal into beaten gold.
A small boat perilously overloaded with a grand piano, of all
things, chugged by, and the white bearded old man at the tiller
waved cheerfully. As the vaporetto approached my stop, a gondola
appeared out of nowhere, and the young gondolier _ dressed in the
once traditional but now less commonly seen blue- and white-striped
jersey and straw hat _ began to gracefully pole away in the
direction of Piazza San Marco.
</P>
<P>
   Images like that are not easily washed from memory. Not even by
the Grand Canal of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
