<HEADLINE>
GOP DOUBLETALK ON TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- It's not exactly the same snake oil, but it sure
looks familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the musings of Congress's Republican leaders as they
continue, post-impeachment, to wrestle with their internal
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cut? Absolutely, the bigger the better. Maybe nothing kicks
in immediately, as in the next 18 months, but something like $800
billion over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Military needs? Fill 'em all, especially Star Wars and other
hardware programs.
</P>
<P>
   Balanced budget? No problem. Keep hard and low ceilings on
domestic programs, at least outside those few we favor, and
there'll be someone here next week or the week after to talk
specifically about how we intend to slash and burn.
</P>
<P>
   Deep tax cuts, steep Pentagon increases, and vague, actually
disguised, intentions toward the rest of the government began to
appear on the national horizon when a front-runner presidential
candidate named Reagan bought into the concept in large part to
ward off a dynamic kid named Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   That was $4 trillion in national debt in our past. That was also
when the country was enduring double-digit inflation and interests
rates, exacerbating an income tax squeeze, not to mention something
called the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But this is now _ deficit-free, inflation-free, Soviet
Union-free, jobs-generating, and generally confident about the
future. Today, shock therapy threatens far more than it beckons.
But it's still around because the ideology behind it is stronger
than the restraints that ordinarily temper the impulses of serious,
governing parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, to keep a precise count, are actually on their
third attempt at presenting a policy face to the country this year.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the night of President Clinton's State of the
Union address six weeks ago. Still mired in the self-delusion of
impeachment proceedings, they presented a Punch and Judy show (via
Representatives Steve Largent of Oklahoma and Linda Smith of
Washington) that symbolized the banishment of serious policy issues
to their back burner.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the president's decisive acquittal, the
Republicans' desperation to talk about something else, anything
else, produced instant tax-cut babble _ 10 percent across the board
in income tax rates as argued by House Budget Committee chairman
and presidential wannabe John Kasich of Ohio, and his Senate
counterpart, New Mexico's Pete Domenici. Outside Congress, in the
nascent presidential field, it was even bigger _ symbolized by Dan
Quayle's spectacularly irresponsible figure of 30 percent (The
Reagan number, by the way).
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as it was last year, was that the Republicans had
yet to understand the political power behind Clinton's
determination to put the Social Security system, including
Medicare, at the head of line for surplus-generated dollars until
it is made whole for the baby boom generation. This year, it didn't
take them long to realize that their dream of deep income tax rate
cuts was not realistic for now, and leaks to that effect began to
cascade off Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The latest fallback position has been articulated in outline
form by Kasich and Domenici, fronting for a nervous Speaker Dennis
Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. It starts by
accepting the president's proposal to wall off 62 percent of any
budget surplus that occurs over the next decade to pay down the
part of the national debt held by the public.
</P>
<P>
   That's a great beginning. This not only frees up huge sums for
private investment in the domestic economy, it also makes the
eventual task of funding social security benefits at generational
crunch time 30-40 years from now that much less onerous.
</P>
<P>
   But that's as far as the Republicans go. They reserve nothing
for the equally important task of revitalizing Medicare, for which
Clinton is willing to dedicate another 15 percent of future
surpluses. However, they do keep the tax-cut spirit alive in
massive form after the year 2000, along with the large boost in
miltary spending. They don't quite acknowledge it yet, but the rest
of the budget would have to be cut overall by as much as 20 percent
to make all this work.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the rest of us, many Republicans in both Houses
are flat out unwilling to do that kind of dirty work on housing,
health care, the environment, and other domestic needs. And they
more than cover the slender margins the GOP enjoys in each chamber.
</P>
<P>
   This is still a very early moment in the budget season, but
until the Republicans accept the responsibility that Ronald Reagan
ducked 20 years ago of paying fully and realistically for tax cuts
and military spending increases, they are not going to fly in an
environment sobered by the lessons of what can go wrong when you
don't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
