<HEADLINE>
FASHION: WHEN THE PRICE, AND FIT, ARE RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What happens to a woman's body between the time
she graduates from college and then enters menopause some 30 years
later is enough to send her to a shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Depressing? Well, unless a figure stays basically the same
through childbirth, hormone replacement and just plain gravity _
and believe it or not, some women are able to keep their girlish
figures through excellent genes or rigorous dieting and exercise _
clothing sizes creep up along with those extra pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ready-to-wear is designed for ``hanger appeal,'' that is: It has
to look great just hanging there in the store. But there are very
few course corrections made for specific bodies in off-the-rack.
</P>
<P>
   Darts are not exact; waist-lines are standardized to whatever
the current template is; armholes are dropped and sleeves are
designed to fit the ``average'' arm length, so they're either too
long or too short.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, much of what you see hanging on the racks in
department stores is generalized and boxy; poorly constructed (have
you ever noticed the shelf-life of a button on a DKNY jacket?) and
getting more expensive all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how many of us are fitting models? How many of us are a
perfect size 6, with hips and busts to match? How many of us don't
need to tweak a sleeve, lift a hem, let out a waist band or buy
something two sizes larger to accommodate the hips and then spend a
fortune on alterations?
</P>
<P>
   Such is the tyranny of sizing: What was once a perfect 6 is
probably an imperfect 10 as years advance. And what is a perfect
size 8 in one designer's line soars to a size 12 in another's.
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear men complaining about having to buy a suit two
sizes too big to fit their expanding gut. Because men have been
having their clothing made for years. In Britain, made-to-measure
Savile Row suits, the closest thing to women's couture, are called
``bespoke'' clothing. Which means: to order.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, there is a growing trend toward a bespoke
mind-set for women _ clothes that are less expensive than European
couture.
</P>
<P>
   There are four designers in San Francisco who specialize in
custom-made-to-measure clothing for women _ Francesca Freedman,
whose new shop on Sutter has recently opened; Lily Samii on
Stockton Street; Azadeh Riaz of Azadeh on Union Street and in
Marin; and Suzanne Hanley of Atelier des Modistes, a comfy,
hand-built studio on Hyde and Green.
</P>
<P>
   Each designer will custom-tailor clothing for women from Size 0
to Size 22. And surprise, surprise: It's not all that expensive.
</P>
<P>
   At Azadeh Riaz's comfortable elevated boutique on Union Street,
skirts start at $175; jackets are as inexpensive as $260. Gowns
range from $450 to $1,000 depending upon the style, the yardage and
the fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Says Riaz, ``My philosophy is that women don't need too many
clothes. People will buy things because they're pretty or they've
gotten a good deal and most of the time, the stuff doesn't fit
right and sits in the back of the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Riaz and her contemporaries embrace the European ideal: That
less and better is more and better.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about having something custom-built is that it is
sizeless. Ask Lily Samii whether her clothing runs true to size and
she and her design partner, Jacques Pantazes, laugh and say: ``You
will not find any sizes here. It's your size.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience of having something made especially for you
begins as a partnership, where client and designer learn to speak
the same language.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main things a designer can do for a woman is to help
her establish her style and eliminate those things that will do
nothing for her. A woman who is 5-feet-tall, built like the Venus
of Willendorf, may yearn for a silk charmeuse slip dress, but
she'll never look her best in it.
</P>
<P>
   For Azadeh Riaz, 36, an Iranian-born designer who worked for the
Saudi Arabian royal family, making clothes to fit each particular
body is like creating art: ``In my mind, I sculpt my women,'' she
says. ``When I put my collections together, I shape my client with
what suits her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty frank with my clients,'' says Suzanne Hanley, the
tall, long-haired Easterner who has been at Hyde and Green in a
quaint, plank-floored workroom and retail space for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shop is very Old World. I believe in having a few really
good pieces. My main goal is to make things people can wear where
they don't question: Is it going to fit? Is it going to look great?
I have clients who insist on making certain changes that I know
won't look good on them. We usually end up redoing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ready-to-wear, designers create seasonal lines. So do custom
designers. They create samples on fitting models in a number of
sizes and when you go to have something made, often, you can try on
the sample to see if you like the style and the material.
</P>
<P>
   If the designer is working with expensive fabric, then she will
create a working model or a ``toile'' _ a muslin replica _ which
will be fit on the client before she takes scissors to fabric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers feel good when they're wearing something made
especially for them,'' says Freedman, 42, a size 2 sprite. ``It is
an incredible luxury to have something that fits correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman talks about one of her clients, a woman with a size 8
top and a size 14 bottom. ``When she tried on her suit, she twirled
in front of the mirror and gasped, `I look so slender.' The clothes
took 25 pounds off her figure,''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman says.
</P>
<P>
   With bespoke or affordable couture clothing, a woman is
guaranteed to get exactly what she wants in a price range she can
afford.
</P>
</TEXT>
