<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTS EXPOSE SUVS' FLIP SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies say the darnedest things.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration released the results of its recent tests of sports
utility vehicles. In roadway accidents, these family-style tanks,
it is well known, are prone to crush opposing vehicles like so many
peanut shells. For this reason, they're better known by the acronym
SUV, which stands for Somebody's Under the Vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   In the usual highway crack-up, the sergeant at the controls, and
any accompanying six-year-old soldiers, often fare better than the
unlucky civilians on their way to the dentist in an average sedan.
But the SUVs do have a vulnerable spot, and this so-called
Achilles' wheel was on full display in the NHTSA tests.
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA wanted to see how well SUVs protected their passengers
in side-impact collisions. So the agency rigged up a movable
barrier, gave it a big shove to 38.5 m.p.h., and then slammed it
into the side of several models. To be fair, it must be pointed out
that the vehicles withstood the battering quite well, and the test
dummies only lost a few teeth and staggered around for a short time
afterward asking whether that good-for-nothing Nixon was still in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   What did the tests reveal? That SUVs, under the slightest
provocation, tend to leave the ground, flip and roll like a
Wallenda brother.
</P>
<P>
   Any fair-minded person knows there is no way to explain away
this fact. A US Department of Transportation report from December
1997 revealed that SUVs are three times more likely to roll over
than are passenger cars. Often the outcome isn't pretty. The most
recent data available show that in 1997, more than 9,400 people
died when their car, van or truck rolled. Of the people involved in
a rollover in a car, 21 percent died. Of those in a truck, 42
percent died. Of those in a SUV that performed a Wallenda, 62
percent were killed. What's more, the popularity of these vehicles
has more than doubled their rollover fatalies in the past decade to
1,482 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent NHTSA tests, three SUV models flipped over when
struck from the side. The test wasn't intended to measure the
vehicles' propensity to roll over. It was meant to gauge passenger
safety in a side-impact collision. The rollovers were wholly
unexpected. So how did the auto makers respond? Did they express
regret? Did they issue a statement of concern and a vow to correct
the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the spokesman from Honda Motor Co., whose CR-V flipped,
as quoted in the Wall Street Journal: ``What the tests are designed
to test, the CR-V passed with flying colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Astounded by this remark, we here at the Dollars &AMP; Nonsense
Institute for Highway Safety decided to put several unnamed SUVs
through our own tests. In separate course runs, we turned on the
windshield wipers, the headlights, the radio at varying speeds. In
one test, we had the test dummy scratch his nose at 43 m.p.h. In
every case, these small actions sent the SUVs rolling like Lincoln
logs.
</P>
<P>
   Most revealing was the response of one automaker whose model
rolled when we flicked on the radio at 60 m.p.h. In the glare of
the TV cameras, he declared, ``Yes, but our radio produces the
finest hi-fidelity in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at levingston(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
