<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-09 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET SEES INTO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is widely believed that the stock market is overvalued and
that investors are caught up in an ``irrational exuberance'' that
eventually will end in a nasty correction. Maybe that's true. But
on one important score, the stock market has been more level-headed
and clear-eyed than anyone else. Simply put, the market's
optimistic view of the US economy has been right on target.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, as it has rallied ever higher, the
market has been saying that the economy is in great shape, that the
US can grow at a solid clip without triggering inflation and that
the world's economic problems are not dire enough to make a big
difference here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has anticipated and reflected the economy's
strength better than any economist,'' admits Mark Zandi, chief
economist at Regional Financial Associates, a Pennsylvania
forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average soared to a new high Friday
after the government said that wages rose only a small amount, even
in the face of robust job growth. The message for the stock market
was clear: the good times continue.
</P>
<P>
   Economists, by contrast, have been relatively pessimistic.
Consider: At the beginning of each year Business Week magazine asks
a group of economists for their annual forecast.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the economists predicted the gross domestic product
would grow 1.9 percent. The actual number turned out to be 3.9
percent. In 1997 the economists looked for growth of 2.1 percent;
the economy delivered 3.8 percent. Last year the forecasters
predicted 2.2 percent; The economy grew 4.1 percent. Raise your
hand if you see a pattern here.
</P>
<P>
   Like vistors to a haunted house, forecasters have seen danger
lurking around each corner. At various times they have worried that
the strong economy would generate inflation; at other times they
have worried that the economic problems of Asia, Russia and Latin
America would stop the economy in its tracks. ``Somehow the economy
manages to skirt every obstacle in its path,'' marvels Nancy
Kimelman, chief economist at Technical Data in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   What has the market seen that forecasters haven't? Rising
productivity growth, for one thing. If we are all working more
efficiently the economy can travel at a higher speed. Productivity
isn't soaring, but it has been consistently better than expected.
The government today will announce productivity numbers for the
fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Related to productivity is the technology's growing role. The
stock market loves technology, probably more than it should. But
the market's basic insight _ that technology is transforming the
economy in profound ways _ is getting harder to dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, investors have been more willing than economists to
believe that intensified competition can keep prices from climbing
as fast as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   Zandi doesn't quarrel with the notion the stock market has done
a better job of seeing the future than he and his fellow
forecasters. But he has some words of warning. The US economy isn't
magical. It's lucky. He argues that the weak world economy has kept
a lid on prices and interest rates here. With demand for goods
depressed around the globe, America is enjoying the benefits of
cheap gas, cheap steel, cheap food and cheap money.
</P>
<P>
   As the world recovers, say forecasters, the American economy may
reach the point where strong growth begins to translate into higher
prices. When that happens, the Federal Reserve will raise interest
rates which, in turn, could spell the end of the long bull market.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasters may be right, of course. Good times and rising
stock prices can't go on forever. But keep one thing in mind: if
you had a nickel for every time in the last few years that an
economist said that the best news on growth, inflation and stock
prices was behind us, you wouldn't have to worry about investing in
the stock market. You'd already be rich.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Fleet Financial Group took some heat for paying a
$13.2 million retention bonus to chief executive Terry Murray.
Murray got the money by agreeing to stay on the job for three
years. Apparently the bonus worked. Murray is still at Fleet. Last
week the bank announced that Murray earned $9.7 million in 1998 for
leading the company to another strong year.
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that paying Murray a retention bonus was
ridiculous because he had no intention of going anyplace else. We
would never be that cynical.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
