<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AGENDA MIRED IN LIGHT FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He ordered the pasta without ever looking at the menu _ ``A
plate of spaghetti,'' to be precise. Then Governor Paul Cellucci
tucked a cloth napkin into his shirt collar in that funny way some
people do, showered his meal in grated cheese and red pepper and
twirled his pasta around a spoon as if he were sitting at some
sun-splashed cafe in Piazza Navona.
</P>
<P>
   My intention _ to come clean _ was to dine with the governor,
then write about his obvious deficiencies, perhaps starting with a
little joke about the wait staff's palpable fear that Cellucci
would insist on paying himself, then have his Mastercard rejected
for exceeding his spending limit.
</P>
<P>
   Then it would be time to launch into the oft-chronicled problems
with his anorexic policy agenda, the abysmal lack of creativity and
vision in his knee-jerk Republican push to cut taxes and enact a
death penalty, the petty small-mindedness of an administration of
post-adolescents solely devoted to itself.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to coffee and dessert.
Paul Cellucci, it ends up, is an eminently likable man, Exhibit A
in that ancient rule of journalism: Never get to know the people
you hope to dislike.
</P>
<P>
   Because there he was, sitting in the back room of Filippo's on
the outskirts of the North End, being self-effacing, telling a
charmingly discolored joke about President Clinton, discussing the
particular problems of being Massachusetts governor at this
particular time. He sipped a cappuccino and seemed to have all the
time in the world.
</P>
<P>
   All of which may help explain the public's early comfort with
him. Massachusetts elected him in the face of a national Democratic
tide. In one recent poll, 68 percent approve of his performance.
Some women swoon over his DeNiro-like looks.
</P>
<P>
   He withstands the onslaught of demands for greater spending on a
laundry list of programs, saying that long after prosperity fades,
any enlarged bureaucracy would need to be funded. He also appears
hellbent on fulfilling a laudable bipartisan promise to cut the
state income tax from 5.95 percent to 5 percent. ``Government is
about finding a balance _ meeting the state's obligations while
allowing people to live a better life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, much as you want to admire him as well as like him,
Cellucci seems adamant about playing to his weaknesses. He is off
to an undistinguished start, following an undistinguished 17-month
stint as acting governor. By choice or incompetence, he is ensnared
in a series of fights over the machinations of government and the
fate of former foes. Unwittingly or not, he has ceded much of the
policy limelight to the aggressive House speaker, Thomas M.
Finneran. Already, some Republicans whisper about his lack of
vision and complain about the narrowness of his inexperienced but
headstrong aides.
</P>
<P>
   His is in a complex predicament: how to lead in prosperous times
that were caused, in part, by the administration of Governor
William F. Weld, of which he was a crucial part. It's always
easier, more politically profitable, to clean up someone else's
mess rather than sustain the success of one's own making.
</P>
<P>
   Weld was blessed with the ability to promote a new vision at a
time when change was needed, confident enough to soar above the
swamp of daily governance, best suited to dealing in symbols.
Cellucci, on the other hand, is a government mechanic, a meddler in
the process, so insistent on involvement in daily decisions that he
can barely see the swamp for the reeds.
</P>
<P>
   He compares himself to Weld like this: ``I'm more from the
heart. He's more from the head. I tend to be more hands on.''
</P>
<P>
   Heart should bring vision, a reason to be. He touts so many new
anti-crime proposals, whether the death penalty or
three-strikes-and-you're-out, that it seems he is governing a
Serbian province rather than a state where violent crime is at a
near four-decade low. His aides carp at those they fear are
disloyal. A persistent target: Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C.
Martin 2d, a Republican who had the audacity to chat with
Cellucci's Democratic opponent, Scott Harshbarger on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is at risk of appearing too much like one of his
mentors, George Bush, a leader of good character who either
couldn't devise or enunciate a governing vision of his own.
Instead, he should seek to be like Texas Governor George W. Bush,
who defined an ambitious but attainable program and then pursued it
with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   He is a good man off to a mediocre start. He has time. He needs
better counsel. And soon enough, he'll need to explain and pursue a
more meaningful agenda. Here's hoping that he can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
