<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-MURPHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY'S LAW: LOTS OF PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Alissa Murphy was in the fourth grade, she asked
her parents to come watch her play basketball with her after-school
team. OK, thought Art and Carol, they'd go watch, but they weren't
expecting much; the Murphys didn't even have a hoop in their
driveway, so all it seemed Alissa could do was dribble and dribble
and dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Well, she could dribble, and she could shoot, and she could pass
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gosh, where did she learn all this?'' Carol Murphy
remembers thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Alissa learned, it turned out, from the boys in the neighborhood
who always were looking for another good athlete to team up with
for games of soccer, baseball, or basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy went on to join a boys' under-15 AAU team, set scoring
records for both San Diego County and the state of California, and
led her high school team to three championships. She was recruited
by the Boston College women's basketball team, and at the end of
her junior season, the guard was named Most Improved Player by the
Big East Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that we couldn't be at this point without
her,'' BC coach Cathy Inglese said of her team's first trip to the
NCAA Tournament. The Eagles (21-7) will face Ohio State (17-11)
Saturday in a first-round game at Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who started every game, led the team in scoring with
15.8 points per game; was the only player to score in double
figures for all 26 games; and shot 88.4 percent from the line _
tops in the Big East, sixth in the country. Her finest moment came
when she scored a career-high 32 points in the Eagles' upset of
UConn in January.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the 5-foot-10-inch Murphy started only two games
a year ago, deflecting to two seniors, and averaged 24.6 minutes
and 9.1 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe the coach needed a spark off the bench,'' said
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked her better coming off the bench,'' Inglese said.
``Either she or Kim (Beezer) could have started, but Alissa really
gave us a spark, and people understand that. Anybody wants to
start, but she still saw a lot of time, and it made her hungrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, she started to realize, if the opportunity is there
for me, I can do it, and really stepped up when Cal (Bouchard) went
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard, Murphy's roommate and also her backcourt mate,
underwent knee surgery halfway through the season for a torn ACL.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who grew up in San Diego, has two older brothers and a
younger one, but they never talked her into playing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was about 9 years old, she'd be up at 6, dribbling
with her right hand and her left hand,'' said her father.
</P>
<P>
   The family eventually got a hoop, but a slanted driveway
rendered it useless, so Art Murphy wound up driving his daughter to
a gym so she could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one year when for 365 days she would not miss a day
in the gym shooting,'' he said. ``I swear to God, I drove her on
Christmas Day.''
</P>
<P>
   When Murphy enrolled at Scripps Ranch High School, the passion
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The city of San Diego's leading scorer for three straight years,
she is San Diego's second all-time leading scorer. As a junior, she
was California's leading point-getter with 908 and averaged 28.2
points per game; as a senior, she averaged 27.5 points, 7.5
rebounds, and 7.5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   During her three years on the high school team, Scripps Ranch
was 20-6, 20-12, and 31-1, city champs each time. And Murphy often
would call coach Dan Regas, asking him to open the gym at 6:45 a.m.
so she could practice.
</P>
<P>
   When BC visited the city last December to play San Diego and San
Diego State, her No. 24 jersey was retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just knows the game of basketball; she knows where to be
on offense or defense and makes everyone around her better,'' Regas
said. ``She plays hard, she plays smart.''
</P>
<P>
   And boy, can she dribble.
</P>
</TEXT>
