<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-TRAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MED SCHOOLS CHANGE COURSE IN ERA OF HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with the rapidly shifting, often harsh realities of
managed care, medical educators across the nation are training more
doctors outside of hospitals and adding new courses in economics,
ethics, law, and even how to document treatment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation, observers say, will not only change the way
patients are treated, but also will likely ensure the continued
growth of managed care as incoming physicians increasingly view it
as a given rather than as one method of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting phenomenon because medical schools in the
past have not generally been about economics and business,'' said
John McCahn, associate dean of academic affairs at Boston
University Medical School. ``All of a sudden we have to deal with
the notion that students cannot walk out of our doors totally naive
about the world in which they will be working.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lee, dean of educational affairs at the four-year-old
Managed Care Institute of the Tufts University Medical School, said
the change has a philosophical dimension as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students coming in today understand there is a shifting
and expanded role for the physician,'' she said. ``We have a
responsibility to . . .get them thinking about what ideal managed
care should be, so they can go out and try to attain that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes take many forms.
</P>
<P>
   A course in public health at BU for first-year medical students,
for instance, now includes a section on law and medicine taught by
a researcher in health-care economics. At Harvard Medical School,
among many other institutions, there is an emphasis on
``health-policy training'' and on teaching ethics because today's
doctors routinely have to weigh costs against benefits in ways that
previous generations did not. And at the University of
Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester, all third-year medical
students must attend a two-day symposium at which issues relating
to managed care are taught and discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable course additions and alterations are becoming
commonplace across the nation. Moreover, in a strong indication
that the new approach is taking hold, the American Association of
Medical Schools last year began sending out recommendations for
broad curriculum changes that incorporate many of the fiscal,
ethical and procedural realities of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly is the biggest shift in medical education in
decades, at least. . .and maybe since the early part of the
century,'' said Gregory Pawlson, associate director for health
affairs at George Washington University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   In one telling departure from the past, a growing number of
medical students _ including at BU _ are now taught to document
their decisions and actions in detailed ways, and for reasons, that
didn't exist before.
</P>
<P>
   In managed-care practices, such records typically become part of
a communal pool of data that can be used for medical purposes by
other doctors _ a practice praised even by critics of managed care.
But there is concern about another use for such records: Insurance
firms and corporate executives review them, in part to help assess
the performance and set the salaries of individual doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic changes in medical education are taking place
in on-the-job training, as students spend more time learning at
outpatient facilities like managed-care offices, rather than in
emergency rooms and elsewhere in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Young physicians receive the bulk of their hands-on experience
during their three-year residencies after graduating from medical
school. Historically, 65 percent to 95 percent of that training
time has been spent in hospitals, on the theory that intensive
exposure to inpatient work is the best way to hone skills and
develop judgment.
</P>
<P>
   But managed care practices permit patients to spend less and
less time in hospitals. So many educators are deciding, whether or
not they like the trend, that future physicians will be better
prepared if they focus more on outpatient care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graduates too often have entered the world able to run an
intensive-care unit, but not an office,'' said Jeanette Shorey, who
directs the Brigham and Women's/Harvard Pilgrim Health Care primary
residency program in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With pressure being exerted from above and below _ student
surveys show a strong appetite for more managed-care instruction _
experimental programs are popping up around the country that allow
residents to spend most of their three years at HMOs, family
practice centers, and other non-hospital settings.
</P>
<P>
   The most extensive and ambitious of these programs is the
Partnership for Quality Education, established in 1996 with an $8.3
million grant from the Pew Charitable Trusts. The Boston-based
project initially brought together eight influential medical
schools and their neighboring managed-care organizations to provide
training, develop curricula, and explore ways to promote such
activities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the partnership has handed out 66 grants, a small number
within the 1,500 US residency programs. But some of the others have
independently embarked on similar initiatives, and officials
believe the prestige of the partnership's founding institutions and
the strength of its ideas will stimulate accelerated growth for
managed care in general and for resident outpatient training in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what we want to do is not just create new
partnerships, but to create a movement,'' said Elizabeth March, the
program director for Partnerships for Quality Education.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants are Harvard University and Harvard
Pilgrim Health Care, which have established a school department
within the HMO to run a large primary-care residency program; the
Tufts Managed Care Institute of Tufts University School of Medicine
and the Tufts Health Plan; and Empire Blue Cross Blue Shield, New
York Hospital, and Cornell University Medical College, which is
testing a novel approach in which some residents rotate into
policymaking positions within the HMO, in addition to their regular
medical training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is wrestling with the issues of managed care, and we
may be turning a corner,'' said Larry Brown, a professor at the
Columbia University School of Public Health and one of three
outside evaluators of the partnership's endeavors. He said that a
great deal of resistance remains among mid-level medical school
officials and the majority of doctors, who detest the idea of
mixing business with medicine, but added that he believes ``it's
only a matter of time'' before so many young doctors have been
trained in managed-care techniques that they will become the norm
for most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of the norm doesn't mean a fondness for every aspect
of the new system, however. While many of those interviewed hailed
managed care's push for more primary-care physicians and lauded the
demise of virtually unrestricted, unmonitored testing and
prescriptions for patients, they said insurance-imposed guidelines
sometimes mean valuable medications aren't prescribed and
potentially revealing tests aren't conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact that someone's watching you is a step toward
self-improvement,'' said Benjamin Gavi, a third-year resident at
the Brigham/Harvard Pilgrim residency program. But, he added: ``The
danger in this kind of program is it forces residents to accept
some things as a given rather than encouraging them to question
what's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Federman, the dean for medical education at Harvard
Medical School, made much the same point even as he praised many of
the educational changes his institution and others are
implementing. ``We're worried that under the pressures of the
bottom line, physicians will feel a pressure to do less. I do
believe that's a risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staunch opponents of managed care, meanwhile, said they feared
residents with too little hospital training might be less adept at
diagnosing some problems and conducting some procedures. In
addition, several doctors said they already encounter residents who
give more weight to financial considerations than to possibly
life-prolonging treatments, especially with elderly or terminally
ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disturbed that we're now hatching a generation of doctors
trained under the aegis of corporate greed, whose education is
based on the principle `first, make a profit,' '' said David
Himmelstein, an associate professor at Harvard Medical School and a
cofounder of the Ad Hoc Committee to Defend Health Care. ``And they
will be practicing for many years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
