<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEELCHAIR-DREAMS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEELCHAIR ATHLETES SHOOT FOR HOOP TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Mass. _ On their own field of dreams, the boys in
wheelchairs charged down the basketball court, chasing each other,
shooting baskets, blocking, sometimes locking wheels, showing no
mercy, asking for none.
</P>
<P>
   If their limbs have failed them, as most have, or are partially
missing, as some are, that does not hinder these wheelchair
basketball players at the Massachusetts Hospital School in Canton,
a state-operated school for youngsters with disabilities, in their
pursuit of the prize.
</P>
<P>
   A national championship is now within their reach.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member team is charged up for the challenge next
weekend at the 7th annual National Junior Wheelchair Basketball
Tournament at the University of Illinois at Champaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big,'' said Richard Crisafulli, the school's director
of athletics. ``This is the World Series, the Super Bowl of
wheelchair competition. The important thing with this is that
college coaches will be there to scout the final 16 top-seeded
teams in the 35-member league. We're one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital school team qualified for the nationals by placing
second in the Mid-South Regional Tournament in Arkansas in January.
There, the team won five games and lost one, placing it among the
top 16 finalists and 11th in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have worked hard for this honor,'' said team coach
Caryn Glazer,. ``During the season (from December to March), they
practice for about eight hours two nights a week.''
</P>
<P>
   When these kids are out there on the court,'' she said,
``they're not people with disabilities, they're basketball
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the hospital school has the only junior wheelchair team in
New England, Glazer said, the players, ranging in age from 12 to
22, come from all over the region.
</P>
<P>
   Zack Beaulieu, 13, travels from Augusta, Maine to join in the
games. He said he ``can't wait'' for the nationals and wants to
play basketball in college.
</P>
<P>
   His father exemplifies the efforts parents make to get their
youngsters to the games. During the basketball season, Raymond
Beaulieu, 38, a pipefitter, drives Zack the seven-hour round trip
from Augusta to Canton twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Zack couldn't play basketball or wheelchair tennis, he'd be
a different kid,'' Raymond Beaulieu said. ``This keeps him in shape
and in better health. It's Zack's positive attitude that gives the
family strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaulieu said his son's spine was severed when he was 4 and
struck by a speeding car as he crossed the street to his
grandmother's house in Grand Isle, Maine. Now, he plans to be a
computer animator.
</P>
<P>
   Another player with a spinal cord injury, Jaime Mazzi, 17, of
Lynn, has been paralyzed from the waist down since he was 4 and a
drunk driver hit the car his father was driving when Mazzi was
living with him in Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, Mazzi's mother, Edith Alvarado, who is legally
blind, accompanied her son to the basketball practices twice a week
and sometimes more on public transportation. The trip took them
three hours each way.
</P>
<P>
   Crisafulli calls Mazzi, ``the team's Larry Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzi, the team's leading scorer, said, ``Playing basketball
makes me feel free.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's other players have their stories, equally poignant,
but would rather talk about basketball and their hopes for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Damian White, 17, of Walpole, hopes to get an athletic
scholarship and study engineering. He has been paralyzed from the
waist down since a car accident when he was 2.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Wise of Needham, 16 next Sunday, said he was born with
spina bifida and has used a wheelchair since he was 3. ``I want to
be a computer graphic designer,'' Wise said.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Vanelli, 17, of Holbrook, lost one leg below the knee after
he was stabbed in the calf. He loves the game, he said, but he also
plays ``to lose weight.'' Reynald ``Ray'' Grandoit, 16, of Boston,
the team's newest member, said he became paralyzed after
contracting spinal meningitis when he was a baby. His main concern
now is choosing a college to study psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Zuluago, 17, of Pawtucket, R.I., missed a recent practice
because of an after-school job, but Glazer said he will be at the
nationals. Zuluago's disability, Glazer said, ``was caused by a bad
polio vaccine he got in Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   Dustin Ferreira, 15, who comes from New Bedford but lives at the
school, is disappointed he won't be able to travel with his team.
``I was born with osteogenesis,'' Ferreira said, ``or brittle
bones. Then, I had to go and break a finger in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Ferreira has something to look forward to. Described as ``a
whiz'' in table tennis, he plans to go to New Mexico in July to
take part in a table tennis tournament. He also participates in
track and field, and archery.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Christian, 15, who attends public school in Canton, was
home with a strep throat during a recent practice at the school,
but planned on being better when the team leaves for Illinois on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Christian, who has set swimming records, plays golf and
baseball, rides a bike, and is a ``gofer'' at a golf club near his
home, was born with partially formed limbs.
</P>
<P>
   He explained how he taught himself to propel his wheelchair and
shoot baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take off one leg so it won't get in the way and I hold the
ball with two arms and push up,'' he said. ``My parents helped me
out a great deal, but I was determined to do it on my own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
