<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-STABLE-BOS &LR;      03-09 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-STABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE OF THE RUNAWAY DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She dreamed of stallions bred for beauty and strength,
descendants of English thoroughbreds that carried pioneers to the
West, and western movie stars into sunset dust.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Shaw fell in love with American saddlebreds, a breed whose
high head and chestnut hair makes it among the most prized in the
genteel, bluegrass world of horse shows. But for the 46-year-old
mother, living on the South Shore but born among the Kentucky
hills, the horses became an all-consuming passion.
</P>
<P>
   It was a passion, and a lifestyle, far beyond the cubicles and
carpeting of her $30,000-a-year job as an insurance claims
processor. But Shaw longed for horses still, and prosecutors say
those dreams led her to secretly siphon millions of dollars from
her Boston employer, New England Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Over a seven-year period, Shaw stole $3.3 million from the
insurance company, according to a 20-count indictment handed down
by a federal grand jury last week. Officials at New England
Financial say she drew the money in steady increments of $15,000 or
$25,000, fooling computer systems with phony names and numbers
dozens of times a year. She might have gone on longer if she had
not tripped herself, trying to deposit a check in December after
she inadvertently had stopped payment on it.
</P>
<P>
   In her scheme, Shaw was anything but the typical corporate
embezzler. There were no mansions or jewels. Instead, investigators
say, she bought, sold and showed some 70 horses _ a cross-country
hobby that demanded not only bottomless wealth, but a curious,
single-minded dedication.
</P>
<P>
   No arraignment has been scheduled yet in Shaw's case. According
to the US Attorney's office, she has not hired a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Following her indictment last week, Shaw returned to her home in
Marshfield. As she pulled into her driveway, wearing a nubby
country sweater and a low ponytail as she pulled into her driveway,
she had no public comment, saying only that reports about the
number of horses she owned were ``way, way off.''
</P>
<P>
   But as she built a prized stable with stolen funds, some say
Shaw found herself with another hobby that required just as much
care _ a double life, one that stretched from her South Shore
cottage to Kentucky's rolling pastures.
</P>
<P>
   To neighbors and co-workers, she was just another insurance
clerk who barely made enough to raise a son in her rented home and
care for her dying mother. But inside a complex circuit of regional
and national horse shows, Shaw was a proud competitor who talked of
a country-club childhood and seemed to come from money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought she had a trust fund,'' said William Wise, a
trainer who stabled Shaw's horses and broke them in to ride on his
farm in Danville, Ky, the heart of bluegrass country. ``I got the
feeling it was a very prominent family.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like a woman of means, Shaw was generous, offering a horse
to a child who admired it, and retiring one of her aging champions
years before a more glory-seeking owner would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she loved the horses so much that she got in too deep,''
said Cherly Innis, a trainer in Somers, Conn. who has known Shaw
for 10 years, but who could do little but speculate about the
charges now facing her friend. ``I don't know what happened. But
she loved those shows. She loved her animals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overlooking a marsh and framed by a low wooden fence, the gray
Cape-style house that is Laura Shaw's home looks as colorless as
the office space where she issued claims. But inside, her living
room is a shrine to her passion.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings of horses, from every angle and every era, are the
wallpaper pattern covering walls painted in the deep blue-green of
Kentucky grass. A table of welded horseshoes sits a few feet from a
shining, chestnut rocking horse. From its wooden neck dangle the
gold, red and royal blue ribbons earned from years of showings at
county fairs and state championships.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows quite when or how Shaw's saddlebred dreams began.
This much, however, is known: While she lived in quiet anonymity in
Marshfield for 15 years, and worked at New England Financial for
21, Shaw's roots were not in New England.
</P>
<P>
   She came from Kentucky, though not the pastoral bluegrass
country where she played out her dreams. Records show she was born
in Paducah, a gray, industrial river port clinging to the banks of
the Ohio River. Her father, Jack Daniel Shaw, was a bookkeeper for
an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, she lived in St. Louis. She never married, and at
age 23, she had a son, Mark Shaw. Two years later, mother and child
appeared in New England, where she began work for the insurance
company she would later become accused of betraying.
</P>
<P>
   But if Shaw had carried on in her father's professional
footsteps, the love of horses grounded family pride. Her mother,
Nell Shaw, also a Kentuckian, was a regular in horse-show social
circles before she died last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the offices of New England Financial, where professional
photographs of Shaw and her son on horses lined her desk,
co-workers said her equine interests were far from secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would come into work smelling like the animals
sometimes,'' said one colleague, who worked with Shaw for years and
who asked not to be named. ``It was definitely out in the open. But
that she had so many of them, and that they were so valuable, we
had absolutely no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the memorabilia was a second career and a serious
investment. It carried Shaw from the drudgery of office life to a
genteel pastime whose heyday ended with the automobile, but lives
on nonetheless in thousands of horse shows scattered across the
vast lands west of the Allegheny River.
</P>
<P>
   Inside that circuit, where owners are as loyal to specific
breeds as baseball fans are to teams, Shaw gravitated to the most
romantic breed of all _ the American saddlebred.
</P>
<P>
   Bred into being along the inlet of Narragansett Bay and prized
for their gait, they are among the most beautiful, and are among
the most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very, very wealthy people involved with
saddlebreds,'' said Lynn Weatherman, senior editor of American
Saddlebred Magazine. Like many in the circuit, Weatherman knew of
Shaw as an accomplished shower, but nothing of her $30,000-a-year
job in Massachusetts. ``I don't see how you could support even a
dozen horses on something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet between 1986 and 1998, Shaw owned some 70 horses, according
to the American Saddlebred Horse Association in Lexington, Ky.
Their price tags averaged in the tens of thousands. According to
Wise, the Kentucky trainer, Shaw sold one of her prized horses, New
Trial, for $150,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And Shaw spent thousands more each year tending to the animals:
boarding them in stables, paying trainers to groom and transport
them, as well as show entry fees and medical bills. According to
two former New England trainers for Shaw, the boarding fees alone
cost close to $7,500 per year, per horse.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was her own frequent travel _ flying
cross-country to show horses, often with her mother, and numerous
trips to Kentucky, where Shaw seemed determined to perfect her
riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not a very good rider at first,'' said Wise. ``But she
worked hard at it. She'd come in on a Friday evening and ride until
Sunday. She'd go home so sore she could hardly walk.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of judges and competitors, the effort paid off.
Between 1993 and 1997, her most prized horse, Shelby Stonewall, won
some two dozen prizes. The horse earned back-to-back world's grand
championships at the Kentucky State Fair, the most prestigious
competition for her breed. In all, the various prizes netted Shaw
close to $25,000 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The purses may have been prestigious, but not lucrative. The
money Shaw earned from Stonewall in four years could have barely
paid for one horse, and Shaw owned a dozen at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like horse racing,'' said Rob Turner, Shaw's longtime
trainer who trains horses in Brentwood, NH. ``The prize money is
minimal compared to what you put into it. The only real money comes
if you have a good horse and his value goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Horse trading, co-workers said, was how Shaw explained her
pricey hobby. It explained changes in her life that were visible
enough to notice, but too subtle to raise suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, she drove these heaps of cars, rusty, five- and
10-year-old things,'' said Shaw's longtime co-worker. ``Then, all
of a sudden, she was driving a Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   Records show that prior to 1990, Shaw mostly drove a
gas-guzzling, 1983 Ford LTD. Then, in recent years, she purchased a
1996 Dodge Intrepid and a 1997 Dodge Ram pickup truck. She also
bought a Mercedes _ a 1987 420 SEL.
</P>
<P>
   But even co-workers, who had the knowledge of Shaw's salary that
horse trainers lacked, never questioned the cars, or the horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was buying horses cheap and selling them for a profit,''
the co-worker said. ``That was the impression we got of why she had
this new money.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, those who shared Shaw's work space and stables wonder how
they never guessed, and why they never asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a problem with Laura paying her bills, and it
never occurred to me to ask where her money was coming from,'' said
Innis, Shaw's friend and Connecticut trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the money came from where they say it came from . . .
Anybody can make a mistake,'' she said. ``I don't know. I think the
world of her, but she'll have to answer to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
