<SLUG> BC-PEDESTRIAN-DEATHS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY SEEKS ACTION TO REVERSE PEDESTRIAN DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alarmed by the dramatic rise in pedestrian
fatalities in San Francisco, the city's Board of Supervisors is
seeking ways to reverse the death toll on streets and highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is awry, and I think it is incumbent on us to look
at the reality that this is a threat to public safety,'' Supervisor
Amos Brown said of the big jump in the number of pedestrians killed
by cars, buses, trucks and trains.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-year period ending June 30, 1998, 39 pedestrians were
killed on city streets, and two more were killed down on highways,
according to the latest statistics compiled by the San Francisco
medical examiner's office. In the previous year, 23 pedestrians
lost their lives in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The police, street safety and traffic officials are baffled by
the startling increase in pedestrian deaths. All agree there is no
single factor causing the rise in fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 32 cases handled by the San Francisco Police Department's
Hit and Run Detail between July 1, 1997, and June 30, 1998, 18 were
determined to be the fault of the pedestrian, including some who
were jaywalking or walking against a red light.
</P>
<P>
   In the cases in which the driver was at fault, several
pedestrians were hit as they were trying to cross the street
legally. Motorists making left-hand turns and not yielding to those
on foot killed several people. No fault was assigned in other
cases.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Brown and Supervisors Gavin Newsom, Alicia Becerril
and Michael Yaki all requested hearings into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom, who called the large number of pedestrian deaths ``quite
significant and alarming,'' said the city needed to look at what
other cities are doing to promote pedestrian safety. He also wants
to look at beefing up the crossing guard program.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom said San Francisco's stepped-up efforts to combat
red-light runners by installing surveillance cameras at
intersections and increasing the fine for red-light running have
proved beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past couple of years, red-light running has
decreased by 40 percent at camera-enforced intersections,'' Newsom
said. ``With this success as our model, I am confident that we can
stem this rise in pedestrian fatalities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
