</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-SANCHEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ LEARNS WELL AT TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Nearly four years ago, Temple coach John Chaney
received a videotape of a basketball player from Argentina and a
note from a good friend who knew the youngster. ``If you want
him,'' George Severini's note said, ``he'd be interested in playing
in your program.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach popped the tape into the VCR, and after a few minutes
spent watching the Argentina junior national team, he called his
friend. ``Where is he?'' Chaney asked, only to be told he would
have to wait a few minutes. Pepe Sanchez was on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went into the game, I didn't see him make a basket,''
recalled Chaney. ``The only thing I saw him do was bring the ball
up and pass it around and play defense. And I said to myself, `Hey,
I'd like to have him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Chaney didn't figure on making Sanchez the
cornerstone of his patient, ball-control offense and menacing 2-3
zone trap defense. He had a scholarship to give. He needed a point
guard. He saw some things in the player from Argentina that showed
some promise. He figured he could teach him the finer points.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Sanchez has earned a lion's share of Atlantic
10 honors (including first-team all-conference this season) and is
one of the primary reasons the Owls (21-10) enter the NCAA
Tournament as the sixth seed in the East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls, in the tournament for the 10th straight time, meet
11th-seeded Kent Friday at 2:30 p.m in their first-round game at
the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he initially inquired about Temple, Sanchez had no
idea he would become one of the most celebrated guards in the
school's storied history. He had spent three seasons on Argentina's
junior national team, losing to a Stephon Marbury-led US squad in
the 1995 Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though he often posted impressive numbers (leading the
1995 World Championships in steals with 4.5 a game), it wasn't
until after he had signed with Temple that he discovered many
programs were interested in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the intensity of play so I wonder if I could play over
there,'' said Sanchez, whose father, Carlos, attended one of
Chaney's clinics when his son was 2.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney had become a popular figure in Argentina after lecturing
there in 1979. Sanchez, who was 16 when he viewed his first US
college game on Argentinian cable television, became a fan and
wanted to play in the States. He asked Severini, a
Philadelphia-area soccer coach who grew up in Bahia Blanca, his
hometown, to put in a good word for him.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sanchez has become one of the top A-10 success stories in
recent years. Last season's defensive player of the year is
averaging 7.4 points and 5.8 assists a game. He led the conference
in assist-to-turnover ratio (2.95 to 1) this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez earned first-team defensive honors with 87 steals, six
short of his own mark of 93 in a season. His eight steals in
Temple's A-10 tournament semifinal win over Xavier tied his own
school mark, which he set twice last season. Sanchez as 266 career
steals, 15 shy of the Temple record set by Mark Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez has shone in the classroom, too, making the A-10
All-Academic team for the second consecutive year and being named
GTE District 2 academic All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 21-year-old entered Temple with budding athletic
talent, both he and Chaney agree it is his improving knowledge of
the game that has made him a celebrated player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball here, it's different, just like it was a different
world,'' said Sanchez. ``When I first got here, coach Chaney
started correcting things I didn't even think about, even nobody at
home thinks about. At home, it was just about making baskets,
period. Or making great passes. If you made a great pass, people
said you were good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I started learning different things like doing the right
things and taking care of the ball. I understand now how basketball
has developed here, and I know why American basketball is the best
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said his defensive skills were initially developed from
playing soccer. Still, learning the other phases of the game
weren't easy, particularly when the teacher is a guy who doesn't
mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a learning process that was hard for me, especially all
the discipline stuff,'' Sanchez said. ``But now, though I don't
like to talk about myself as a basketball player, I have improved
as a person. I always had discipline and work ethic but I had no
direction with that discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney agreed, and added that Sanchez came to the program with
traits he often sees in foreign players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are feel-good players, happy-go-lucky, recreational
players,'' he said. ``Sometimes you holler at them and they quit.
Sometimes if you get pushy with them they get temperamental. So the
harder I got and the more argumentative Pepe became the worse I
got. I just kept pushing him to the point there he wanted to fight
me, because I didn't give a (expletive).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know a person has some talent and some ability or if
you are speculating on it, the only thing you can do is keep
pushing until a light comes on in their head. Then you put them in
a tank of repetition where they say, `Hey something's going on,
here, and maybe it's beyond my control.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney has had his moments with Sanchez this season,
particularly in last Saturday's loss A-10 championship loss to
Rhode Island when Sanchez stopped shooting after missing a few
times, and URI left him open to double-team other Owls. Still,
Chaney is the first to tell you the reserve of three years ago is
Temple's catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone always has to be in charge,'' Chaney said. ``In my
house there was always a chair that only my father sat in, because
he was in charge. When I take one basketball I give it to one guy
to be in charge, and that's Pepe Sanchez.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
