<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MEMORABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIAL NCAA GAMES CAN HOLD THE MOST FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early days of the NCAA Tournament, there was no such
thing as seeding. First-round pairings were regional, and the main
perk awarded a team perceived to be powerful was a first-round bye.
The champions of the established franchises, such as the Big Ten,
the Pac 10, the ACC, and the SEC, were the normal recipients of
these byes.
</P>
<P>
   Numerical seeding began in 1979 on a 1-10 basis. The 7-10 and
8-9 teams played in the opening round, while 1-6 were advanced into
the second round. The current 1-16 seeding was instituted in 1985,
and the first teams to get No. 1s were Georgetown (East), Oklahoma
(Midwest), Michigan (Southeast), and St. John's (West).
</P>
<P>
   While most 1-16 and 2-15 games have been predictable and of the
84-60 variety, there have been some riveting games between teams
supposed to be Haves and teams supposed to be Have-Nots in the
first round. While the first No. 16 has yet to win a game, three
No. 15s have and a few No. 16s have come close.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five memorable first-round games. The first pre-dates
numerical seeding, to go along with two 1-16s and a pair of 2-15s.
But first pay attention to the words of former Louisiana Tech coach
Tommy Joe Eagles, who once said, ``This is March Madness, I
believe, and that's what makes it March Madness _ upsets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. March 13, 1976. Providence &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers 54, Princeton 53 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Undefeated (28-0) Rutgers is staring at possible defeat when
Princeton's Pete Molloy heads to the line for a one-and-one with
four seconds left and the Scarlet Knights leading by 1. Coach Tom
Young takes two timeouts to ice the 5-foot-10-inch sub guard, and
it works as Molloy's first attempt hits the back rim and bounds
away. Princeton had complained that Molloy should have been
shooting two, anyway, but coach Pete Carril is philosophical
afterward, saying to Molloy, ``Just forget it. There are more
important things in life.'' Rutgers advances to its only Final
Four, where it is blown away by Michigan (86-70). Princeton will
have many more first-round heartaches before breaking through
against UCLA in 1996 for Carril's last victory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. March 17, 1989. Providence &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Georgetown 50, No. 16 Princeton 49 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 19-7 Ivy League champs led by 8 at the half and 10 early in
the second half, subsisting almost entirely on a two-fold offensive
diet of threes and backdoor layups. The Tigers treat the basketball
like a winning lottery tricket (three turnovers). Georgetown (26-4)
is led by brawny freshman Alonzo Mourning, who finishes with 21
points, 13 rebounds, and 7 blocks, the last of which, on Princeton
center Kit Mueller, saves the game on the final possession.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. March 15, 1990. Knoxville, Tenn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Michigan State 75, No. 16 Murray State 71 (OT) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murray State (21-8), probably a bit underseeded to begin with,
battles into overtime when guard Greg Coble nails a 3-pointer at
the buzzer. The man who makes it all happen is none other than
Ronald Jerome ``Popeye'' Jones, whose dazzling variety of inside
moves chew up the Spartans (26-5) for 37 points. But the OT belongs
to future NBA All-Star Steve Smith, who scores 6 of his 22 as the
Big Ten champs escape with both a victory and a bruised ego.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. March 14, 1991. College Park, Md. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. 15 Richmond 73, No. 2 Syracuse 69 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richmond (21-9) controls the game from the opening tap,
bothering the Orangemen (21-9) with a confusing matchup zone to
become the first 15 seed to knock off a 2. Curtis Blair (18 points)
is on target throughout, but the big 'Cuse-killer is sub Terry
Connolly, who bounds off coach Dick Tarrant's bench with 14 points,
7 rebounds, and 5 assists. ``It wasn't a case of us playing
poorly,'' sighs Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim, whose team never leads.
``We played this way all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. March 18, 1993. Salt Lake City &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. 15 Santa Clara 64, No. 2 Arizona 61 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're 24-3 Arizona, and you score 14 unanswered points at
the end of the half and 11 more without an opposing whimper to
start the second half, you might figure that a 25-0 run would
decide the game, correct? Not this time. The resilient Broncos
(18-11) shrug it all off, regain their poise, and come back behind
the play of Steve Nash to pull the game out. The dramatics continue
'til the end as the Broncos miss four free throws in the final
seconds and Damon Stoudamire watches his attempt for a game-tying 3
at the buzzer bounce off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other first round games to remember: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1958: Manhattan (15-8) shocks No. 1 West Virginia (28-1), 89-84.
Jaspers coach Ken Norton reveals he had made no transportation
plans to the second-round site . . . 1962: Yale takes mighty Wake
Forest (Lenny Chappell, Billy Packer and, yes, it's that Billy
Packer) into OT before losing, 92-82. Yale's David Schumacher
missed a foul shot at :02 of regulation that could have won it.
Wake rolls on to its only Final Four . . . 1978: Duke 73, Rhode
Island 72. Rhody has two final shots. Duke goes to Final Four
despite Sly Williams's 27 . . . 1984: Northeastern shoots 74
percent _ you read that correctly _ from the floor but loses an
astonishing 70-69 game when Virginia Commonwealth's Rolando Lamb
hits a falling-down jumper at the buzzer. Reggie Lewis dazzles with
31 on 15-for-17 shooting . . . 1985: In the first year of 1-16
seeding, Fairleigh Dickinson goes up by 10 in second half and hangs
with Michigan until the final minute before losing, 59-55 . . .
March 13, 1986: No. 1 seed Duke is terrified by fearless
Mississippi Valley State, which makes 12 steals and blocks five
Blue Devil shots. Duke doesn't gain control until the fourth MVS
starter gets his fourth foul. Johnny Dawkins pops in 16 of his 27
in the final 5:44 as Duke escapes, 85-78 . . . 1989: No. 16 seed
East Tennesssee State, twice up by 17 against No. 1 seed Oklahoma,
loses in overtime, 72-71 . . . 1996: Gabe Lewullis fakes, re-loads,
and goes again for the winning backdoor layup from center Steve
Goodrich as No. 4 Princeton finally bags a buck to hang over the
mantel by defeating No. 13 UCLA, 43-41. On the same day Western
Carolina, a 16, takes Purdue, a 1, to the wire in a 73-71 game. The
final seconds include a missed layup, a blocked layup, and two more
misses. ``We didn't deserve to lose,'' said coach Phil Hopkins.
``We deserved to win.'' . . . 1998: Cincinnati (2) needs a
3-pointer by D'Juan Baker with 3.6 seconds left to hold off No. 15
Northern Arizona, 65-62 . . . Also 1998: Bryce Drew's
buzzer-beating jumper on time-honored ``hook-and-ladder'' play
lifts No. 13 Valparaiso past No. 4 Mississippi, 70-69.
</P>
<P>
   You can probably think of 10 others you like just as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
