<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD-LEWIS TRAINERS SQUARE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They don't like each other much, which is why they
will be happy to get into separate corners of the ring at Madison
Square Garden Saturday night to settle their differences the best
way they can.
</P>
<P>
   They will be there with the same aim _ to beat the other down
and capture what promoter Don King is calling ``the unmitigated,
unadulterated, undisputed heavyweight championship of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   While Holyfield and Lewis have been reasonably respectful of
each other, their trainers have been barely able to conceal the
enmity they feel for each other. The source of this is difficult to
determine, but Don Turner and Emanuel Steward are contemporaries
who have been around boxing for all of their adult lives, so their
paths have crossed many times.
</P>
<P>
   Steward, who trains Lewis, has never forgiven Holyfield for
replacing him with Turner not long after Steward had helped
Holyfield win back the heavywight title he lost to Riddick Bowe.
Turner has never forgotten the time that Steward, he believes,
tried to steal three of his fighters while they were training near
him.
</P>
<P>
   None of these actions are unusual in boxing. Neither is enmity
between competitors. But a week ago Turner went so far as to refuse
to do a teleconference with Steward out of concern for what he
might say if he heard the wrong thing coming out of his rival's
mouth. And they were scheduled to appear on a television show in
New York Sunday but refused, sources said, in part because Turner
is tired of Steward giving him little credit for Holyfield's recent
stirring performances and in part because Steward still believes
he, not Turner, is the one who remade the three-time heavyweight
champion's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly what it is between them,'' said a
high-ranking source in the promotion, ``but when you're around them
it's pretty obvious they don't like each other much. You can feel
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward refuses to talk directly about it and so does Turner,
but when asked about the situation Monday, Holyfield's trainer did
say, ``I know the real Emanuel Steward. Not everybody knows the
real Emanuel. Emanuel gets jealous. He's so egotistical. He wants
everybody to think he's the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's OK. I been married to the same woman for 34 years.
I'm 59 years old and just had cancer and I'm healthy again. I'm
happy with this time in my life. If I could beat cancer, why I got
to worry about Emanuel Steward?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just jealous of Holyfield. He's like a crab in a barrel,
trying to pull everybody else down. So fine. When Holyfield knocks
his guy out, I got nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be farther from the truth, of course. Holyfield
imported Turner after firing Steward over money because he had been
impressed with the job Turner did preparing aged Larry Holmes when
the two of them fought a long and surprisingly difficult fight for
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   In his first fight with Turner, Holyfield looked awful in losing
the title to Michael Moorer on a night when some claimed he
suffered heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   When Holyfield chose to reject the advice of many in boxing and
continued fighting, he kept Turner by his side, which is not the
normal reaction after a champion loses. Normally he blames the
trainer, as Lewis did the night a Steward-trained Oliver McCall
knocked him out to take the World Boxing Council title. But
Turner's stock with Holyfield rose more in defeat than it could
have in victory because he noticed Turner made no effort to blame
the fighter, as trainers so often do in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   They have been together through seven fights and nearly five
years that saw Holyfield lose his title to Moorer and his third
fight with Bowe but also win back the World Boxing Association
title by destroying Mike Tyson and then take the International
Boxing Federation crown from Moorer with an eighth-round stoppage
16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has come to this, a two-pronged battle between two boxers
and two trainers with long histories and longer memories. Steward
is a Hall of Fame trainer who has said Lewis would be the greatest
heavyweight of all time once he finished ``polishing his rough
edges.'' He also said that Holyfield's wins over Tyson were
predictable and gives Turner little credit for them. Beyond that,
he has promised Lewis will stop Holyfield Saturday night because
``Evander is a little man and Lennox is a big man.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner has said little but to echo Holyfield's guarantee that he
will stop Lewis in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through history, size hasn't meant that much in boxing,''
Turner said. ``Bowe is the only big man Evander ever had a problem
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander wants to win this badder than he wanted Tyson. He's
been putting in overtime to get ready. The beauty of boxing is the
trainers can say all they want but they don't fight. The fighters
do. The rest of us watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lennox rises to the occasion, I just think Evander will
rise a little bit higher.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, he'll take Don Turner with him. Right to the top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
