u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-EHLERS-BOS &LR;      03-09 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-EHLERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EHLERS GETS THE PROBLEM IRONED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTON, Pa. _ Brian Ehlers would have been scratching his head,
if he'd had the strength.
</P>
<P>
   Fran O'Hanlon could merely shake his.
</P>
<P>
   Both could see that Ehlers didn't belong on the same court with
his elders among the Lafayette College basketball team. Neither
could see why.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers was doing just as much running as his fellow Leopards. He
was just as diligent on the weights. No, that wasn't true. If
anything, he was doing more work than any of the veterans, putting
himself through ferocious workouts after his teammates had left
Kirby Field House, working maniacally with assistant coach Pat
Brogan to refine his defensive technique.
</P>
<P>
   And getting nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before head coach O'Hanlon began wondering
whether the ruthless shooter he'd lured from Bay Shore, N.Y., to
help resurrect a 2-25 laughingstock had been a monumental waste of
recruiting vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always trying to do the same things we were doing,''
said O'Hanlon. ``And he was always working trying to get better.
But he never seemed to be in shape. I started thinking this wasn't
the same kid I'd seen in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers agreed wholeheartedly. A year after averaging 31.4 points
a game as the Suffolk County Player of the Year, he began thinking
he was out of his league _ a nonscholarship league at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard adjustment,'' he said. ``I think the strength
factor was the toughest. I realized you can't take a play off at
this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you don't have the strength to begin with. It
turned out that was the dirty secret of Brian Ehlers's struggles,
not sloth or ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a logical explanation, O'Hanlon finally figured,
``There's got to be something wrong with this kid,'' and dispatched
him to the infirmary.
</P>
<P>
   There a battery of tests revealed an iron deficiency, a
supplement was prescribed, and Ehlers finally had his legs back.
</P>
<P>
   His steely eye and iron will never had abandoned him, and now,
two years later, the junior guard is the Patriot League scoring
champion (18.2 points per game), Player of the Year, and tournament
MVP. He's also no small reason that Lafayette is in the NCAA
Tournament for the first time in 42 years, a 15th seed hoping to
topple No. 2 Miami Friday at the FleetCenter in the first round of
the East subregional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the difference right away,'' Ehlers recalled of
the medical discovery. ``Suddenly, I was able to keep up. I wasn't
getting tired anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now all that remained was a little fine-tuning of his psyche.
One of the major attractions O'Hanlon had seen in Ehlers during his
high school courtship was the 6-foot-4-inch, 195-pounder's
gunslinger's instinct, his hunger to take the deciding shot, and
utter conviction that he would make it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon wanted to assure Ehlers that such an attitude was
perfectly welcome in the Lafayette program. So during Ehlers's
freshman season, with the Leopards trailing Bucknell by a point and
five seconds left, the coach raised the eyebrows of his
upperclassmen and designed the climactic play for Ehlers: take the
ball downcourt, look for his shot, or dish off.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers took the ball downcourt. He looked for his shot.
</P>
<P>
   He missed.
</P>
<P>
   With no avenue of escape from the gym a despondent Ehlers felt
compelled to apologize to his coach, who immediately set him
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Brian I had you take the shot because I wanted
you to take the shot,' '' recalled O'Hanlon. `` `So what if you
missed? You're going to take a lot more of those and you're going
to make a lot more of those.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The consolation prize _ his coach's unyielding faith _ buoyed
Ehlers. ``Just knowing the coach and players had confidence in me
in that situation made me feel good,'' he said. ``I've always
wanted to have the ball in my hands in that situation ever since
I've been playing ball. I want to be the guy with the ball in his
hands at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much where it's been for the past two seasons, and
both Ehlers and Lafayette have reaped the benefits. Last year he
was second-team all-league and Lafayette just missed an NCAA bid
when it lost the Patriot final to Navy.
</P>
<P>
   This year the results have been more rewarding, even as the task
has been more daunting. The Leopards' summer turned nightmarish
when center Stefan Ciosici, the reigning Patriot Player of the
Year, tore his anterior cruciate ligament during a camp pickup game
and was lost for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really devastated for him,'' said Ehlers. ``And it was
really hard for the team. But I also think we realized that even
without Stefan, we had a great team, people who could step in, who
had a chance to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Ehlers. He has scored in double figures in every
game while shooting 49.7 percent. He killed Bucknell twice during
the regular season, once at the last second, then with a late
3-pointer that wrapped up the league crown. In the tournament, he
kept Lafayette alive with a buzzer-beater that disposed of Colgate
in the semifinals. And in last Friday's title game, he shook off an
indifferent first half (1 for 4) to finish with 16 points, tied for
the team high, while foiling Bucknell yet again with clutch hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the great unknown, the Leopards' foray into the NCAAs,
where if tradition and seeding form hold, they won't linger.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers is aware of that, and undaunted by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great accomplishment to get this far,'' he said, ``but
you always want to do more. Being the underdog makes us all looser.
We know we have nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   And if by chance Lafayette finds it has something to win at the
end of the game against Miami, Brian Ehlers knows he'll have the
strength _ in every sense _ to take the deciding shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
