</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-PROMOTERS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTER DON KING, HBO'S SETH ABRAHAM BACK IN THE SAME CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oscar and Felix returned to Broadway not so long ago,
so why shouldn't Seth and Don get back into boxing's big arena on
Broadway, too?
</P>
<P>
   The successful return of ``The Odd Couple'' to a Broadway stage
was no less remarkable than the recent return of boxing's Odd
Couple to the production of big-time fights. The latter alliance
began in 1978 but had come to a grisly end in 1990 after HBO Sports
president Seth Abraham refused to remove commentator Larry Merchant
from Mike Tyson's boxing shows after promoter Don King promised
Tyson that would be part of their new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was irate, and his bombastic promoter ``went across the
street,'' as both sides now put it, taking Tyson to Showtime, HBO's
bitter rival. Thus began eight years of business acrimony that
overrode a longstanding personal friendship and led in large part
to the consistent blocking of every major match the sport needed to
prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, that squabble, plus the endless chicanery of boxing
sanctioning bodies and the usual greed of promoters, managers and,
yes, often the fighters themselves, led the sport toward what many
felt was the sad sunset of its existence. Gone were the networks.
Gone were most major advertisers. Gone were the marquee names and a
way to create new ones. Gone, all too often, were the fans
themselves, for they could no longer make sense of it all.
</P>
<P>
   But boxing, like so many of its legendary practitioners, is
resilient beyond logic. Mismatches, bad matches, and for too long
no matches have wounded it, some say marginalized it in the United
States, yet the sport still stands, bloody but unbowed, and
apparently the public still stands with it.
</P>
<P>
   The proof is the almost instantaneous sellout of next Saturday's
heavyweight unification fight between Evander Holyfield and Lennox
Lewis at Madison Square Garden. That could easily be seen as an
aberration, except that it comes on the heels of near-record
pay-per-view sales for a non-heavyweight fight when welterweight
champion Oscar De La Hoya squared off with Ike Quartey last month,
a remarkable 16.5 television rating and 28 share for the Pernell
Whitaker-Felix Trinidad match a week later on HBO, the network's
highest rating for a live fight in four years, and the fact that
HBO has now had 11 straight boxing shows do double-digit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   New talent has begun to emerge in Michael Grant, Shane Mosley,
Floyd Mayweather Jr., Fernando Vargas, Vitali Klitchko, Tim Austin,
James Page, and others. ESPN2's reconfigured ``Friday Night
Fights'' has drawn consistently solid ratings. And when TNT tried
its hand in boxing in September, it racked up a rating 24 percent
higher than its NBA broadcasts get.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is not just numbers that indicate boxing is alive again,
but also the presence of three straight championship matches that
fight fans craved in the past month. The public's reaction has
signaled anew that there is always life in boxing if the right
fight is made. But it was not until King and Abraham agreed to do
business again that such matches could become reality.
</P>
<P>
   Big fights, or at least the promise of them, keep boxing in the
public eye during the long months of bad matches, mismatches, and
worse matches. It is for fights such as Muhammad Ali-Joe Frazier
that fans suffer through Muhammad Ali-Richard Dunn. It is for
Marvin Hagler-Thomas Hearns nights that they tolerate Marvin
Hagler-Wilford Scypion. It is for moments such as George Foreman
standing over a fallen Michael Moorer to become the oldest
heavyweight champion in history that they accept George
Foreman-Jimmy Ellis. But even boxing fans will pay that price for
only so long, and the sport was beginning to wither on the vine
during the years of enmity between King and HBO.
</P>
<P>
   That has become more obvious since their recent detente led to
Trinidad's win over Whitaker, the Holyfield-Lewis showdown, and the
possibility of a unification bout between Trinidad and Oscar De La
Hoya before the year is out.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen and why? How did King get away with bringing
the biggest fighters he had at least temporarily to HBO from
Showtime and why did HBO, the most economically powerful force in
the sport, agree to it knowing that if its fighters lose, Showtime
will reap the benefit? The simple answer is that rapper Puff Daddy
was onto something when he sang, ``It's all about the Benjamins,
baby.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `This is what the people wanted,'' King insisted, while
acknowledging, too, that it was the only way to make big money.
``It was a necessity. At this stage, I could do without boxing and
do well, but I continue to work in it because it's a people
business and my power lies in my people ties. If you give the
people what they want, they will respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``In boxing, you can't take nothing for granted, even granite
itself, but if you're dealing with what's practical and real, these
are the biggest events that could be put on. I don't want to argue
any more which network the fight is on. People want to see some
fights. If my guys win, Showtime has it made.''
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly true for Saturday's fight and it, like
Trinidad-Whitaker and De La Hoya-Quartey, is being put on by HBO
and its pay-per-view arm, TVKO, in large part because they were
willing to pay the most and risk losing the titles two of their top
draws hold without an option on their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   King took the same gamble and won when Trinidad easily defeated
Whitaker. Now he's gambling on Holyfield, betting that his man will
win and he'll take the undisputed champion back to Showtime for a
summertime fight against Henry Akinwande for more money.
</P>
<P>
   This has not happened because of a sudden sense of largess on
the part of King or Abraham. It's primarily because the sport had
sunk to a depth where all sides realized a major change in the way
they did business had to happen or boxing could slide so far off
the radar screen that not even the burgeoning Hispanic market would
save it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing is enjoying a bit of a renaissance,'' Abraham said
during a breakfast meeting recently in HBO's Manhattan offices.
``It's not the Golden Age but it's better than tin. At 67 or 68,
Don and Bob (Arum) should be looking at their legacy in boxing.
They've made plenty of money. It's time to leave something to the
sport. These fights help do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don and I realized together we could make some big fights. We
had a trial separation that lasted eight years but it didn't work.
After we made Lewis-Holyfield I was hoping it wouldn't be a
one-date relationship. It wasn't. We made Trinidad-Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don wasn't boxed in there. It was a very level playing field
and he made the deal. He promoted it and generated record numbers.
That one goes in Don's column. He didn't have to make that fight
but he did. Against all odds, boxing people sometimes use common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, King responded between bites of scrambled eggs, ``We
didn't ever have no issues but one. No one was more shocked, hurt,
or disappointed than me to leave HBO over a commentator. We'd made
a lot of history together. You can say it was a miscommunication or
call it what you will or may but that was the only issue between
Seth and me, from my perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with Showtime now. My loyalty is there. I'd love to see
them get these fights but I know the history. HBO's got contracts
and they dig in their heels. This is no battle of the networks. I'd
love to see Showtime broadcast Oscar and Trinidad but don't let the
fight die because HBO's got a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seth understands where my loyalties lie but we put it aside to
make big fights Showtime couldn't make. The world needed to see
those fights. The world needs to see a unification of the
heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seth has a similar passion as I do for this game. We're trying
to get together to bring sanity into this insanity. We're trying to
be winners not whiners. That's why we've come together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO and King have given the world Trinidad's first big fight and
created a viable rival in the public's eyes for De La Hoya, which
is a key to building interest. Now comes Holyfield-Lewis, a fight
that had been discussed and abandoned twice before Holyfield
ordered King to make it and King gambled his biggest draw knowing
that if he loses he will be alone without HBO's dollars or the
power of the heavyweight championship behind him.
</P>
<P>
   But if Holyfield wins, he will not be alone atop the boxing
world. King will be there with him and, they believe, fight fans
will support them both in a way they have had no reason to in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-PROMOTERS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-09 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-PROMOTERS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... recent years.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lewis-Holyfield will be the centerpiece of American sports
Saturday night,'' Abraham insisted. ``We're expecting over a
million buys (at $49.95 each). People want to see the spectacle.
There are two kinds of boxing. There's boxing and heavyweight
boxing. Lewis-Holyfield is that second, magical sport. The
undisputed heavyweight champion is the closest thing we have to
Superman. There's something magical about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the magical things about it is that the undisputed
champion recently disappeared. There has not been one since Riddick
Bowe beat Holyfield and threw the World Boxing Council belt into a
trash can in London rather than make a deal with Lewis. What
followed was Lewis being named WBC champion retroactively, handed
the title for beating Razor Ruddock even though that was not a
title bout at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis would lose that title to Oliver McCall, a King fighter,
and two years after that win it back from McCall when it was again
vacant. There is no need to explain this further; the confusion you
feel at the moment is why boxing was in such sorry shape when King
and HBO rejoined forces in December. Almost immediately, King
insists, the fruits of his services became evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``First fight out and Trinidad is the highest-rated program on
HBO since Foreman-(Axel) Schulz,'' King said. ``Out of the top 10
rated programs in their history, I've had eight. I go away and they
struggle. I come back and they do the biggest program they had in
years. It shows again Don King makes the difference. I have the
distinct ability to bring in the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I got the biggest event in the Garden's history. It's four
times bigger, moneywise, than any promotion they've had. What was
the missing element? They had great fights before. Again, Don King
makes the difference. This is something you can verify. People can
say what they will or may but I'm ecstatic with delight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is little you can verify in boxing except the results, and
sometimes not even those, but there's no question fight fans are
ecstatic with delight because they are finally getting the matches
they've longed for. But is boxing truly in a renaissance or is this
a mere moment of market-driven clarity that will soon turn myopic
after the checks are cashed?
</P>
<P>
   That is difficult to say, but Showtime executive Jay Larkin
indicated that a De La Hoya-Trinidad fight this year may not be as
simple as some want to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big fights are very good for boxing,'' Larkin said. ``That's
why we stepped aside and let these go to HBO. We've done more than
enough to show we're not obstructionists, but we're at a point
where we feel we've taken walkover after mismatch to maintain
Trinidad and we'd like to see our investment pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conceivable that fight ends up over there (HBO) but our
deal is not with the fighters. It's with the promoter (King).
Through him we can insist our rights be looked after. Don would
like to work both sides of the street. We have no problem with that
if our rights are protected.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes it sound like continuing this flurry of big fights
may be more difficult than it appears. Yet the fact is HBO has an
exclusive contract with De La Hoya that prevents him from fighting
elsewhere and a three-fight deal with Trinidad. King promotes
Trinidad and has a promotional deal with Showtime. He can't deliver
De La Hoya, or even Trinidad now, and he has an out clause in his
Showtime deal that allows him to sell pay-per-view fights to the
highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Yet King is not stupid. He knows that if a third straight
big-money fight ends up with his new partner, his old partners may
make him pay for it when his own deal with Showtime expires at the
end of the year. In the past, these types of entanglements led many
a great fight to dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing is firmly established as a niche sport,'' said NBC
Sports executive Kevin Monaghan, who used to buy fights for his
network before it got out of the business. ``The names are
developed on cable now. It's a mainstream sport for Latino fans.
They talk about it. But it's not a regular topic of most sports
fans except when there's a big fight like Holyfield-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's been less of it on TV so it's become more of a
novelty and so it gets bigger ratings. There's some more value back
in it but HBO wanted a sport it could dominate and it did a
wonderful job doing that. It changed the business model to the
point the networks can't afford boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``HBO paid a premium to lock up the sport. It got its victory,
but at what price? Now not enough people know Felix Trinidad
because he only fights on cable. That's an ongoing problem for the
sport: how to create new stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``So have things improved? Yes. Is boxing healthier? Yes. But it
won't ever be what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not, but Abraham understands that if the men who run
the sport make alliances like the one he and King have forged,
boxing can flourish again. That is why he spent last week cajoling
Roy Jones Jr.'s promoter, Murad Muhammad, to persuade Jones that a
unification fight with Reggie Johnson for the light heavyweight
title should not be priced out of existence by demands for a $7
million payday.
</P>
<P>
   It is also why he sent out the word recently that while the
biggest money in boxing is still at HBO, the way to get it may have
become more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last two months we've gone to every promoter we do
business with and told them no more Ricky Frazier fights (an
embarrassment in which Jones destroyed an overmatched New York cop
in two rounds),'' Abraham said. ``We'll use every means available
to enforce that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them all if they want to keep fighting here they have
to stop thinking they're a house fighter that we're protecting.
When the sport is healthy, it benefits all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis had a contract with HBO that is ironclad. We didn't have
to budge but we softened the edges to send Don a message that we
weren't going to stuff a deal down his throat because we knew we
wouldn't be able to make other deals and that's what we all know
the sport needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Saturday night is bigger than just a prize fight. It's an
event. The celebrities want tickets. They want to be seen here.
That creates interest in boxing. We didn't have to sell this to
fight fans. We had to sell it to the rest of the community. No one
can do that better than Don King.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof of that is in the selling, and a week ago King sold
foreign broadcast rights in Bosnia, a country torn apart by civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten both sides to put a moratorium on March 13,'' King
said. ``They gonna stop fighting to watch the fight. Then they can
go back to shooting. That's the power of big-time boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Try and do that in Bosnia with the Final Four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
