<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE EURO WILL MEAN TO TRAVELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The euro is here.
</P>
<P>
   The new single currency of 11 nations has been called ``Europe's
single most daring venture of our time,'' according to Jacques
Santer, president of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The euro will cover nearly 300 million people and a vast economy
comparable to that of the United States. It is trading this week at
.91 units to the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
   When it fully takes, the new currency should make travel for
Americans a lot easier, especially those on grand tours covering
many nations in a week or two. There will be less translating
dollars into local currencies, and spotting a good buy will also be
a lot easier. However, some analysts predict the coming of the euro
will mean higher prices in less-expensive regions and lower prices
in high-cost areas.
</P>
<P>
   While the euro officially arrived on Jan. 1, travelers will not
see much of a change until Jan. 1, 2002. Until then, you'll still
deal in local currencies. You'll pay in francs, pounds, lire, etc.
When you exchange dollars for notes or coins, you will still
receive national currencies _ the only difference will be that
these currencies will be fixed to the euro and will be close to
what they are now. And when you exchange one of the national
currencies for another, the rate will not fluctuate because all
these currencies will be fixed to the euro and therefore fixed to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   You will see prices in both the euro and the local currency.
This is being done to acquaint Europeans with the value of the
euro. While some companies plan to add euro traveler's checks to
their offerings, these will be good for exchange in national
currencies. Some credit card purchases may be charged in euros; if
so, the credit card company will convert the euro charge to dollars
on the bill you receive when home, just as they do now on current
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Not all European Union nations are participating in the new
currency. Those that are include Austria, Belgium, Finland, France,
Germany, Holland, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Spain, and Portugal.
Opting out at this time are Britain, Denmark, and Sweden. Greece
hopes to qualify soon.
</P>
<P>
   With the inauguration of euro notes in 2002, US visitors will
then receive only euros when exchanging dollars in banks and ATM
machines, although travelers will still encounter national
currencies in transactions with individuals and business. The
withdrawal of francs, marks, lire, etc., begins on Jan. 1, 2002,
and is expected to be completed by July of that year. At that time,
the euro will stand alone in the 11 participating countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Keep in contact
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TWA is offering international travelers cellular and satelite
phone rentals. Although all TWA international passengers will be
able to rent a phone, Trans World One (TWA's premium business class
service) passengers will receive free phones for a week.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways is featuring ``create your own vacation'' in
London, the United Kingdom, Ireland, and Europe. The program offers
more options, from hotels in London for $39 to $233 a person a
night, to black taxicab tours, to apartment rentals (great for
families). For those booking by March 31, the airline is offering
discounts of $100 a person on packages valued at $300 and $200 to
those purchasing land arrangements costing at least $500 a person.
For more information, call British Airways Holidays at
877-428-2228.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Save with the card
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many European cities offer special cards that offer savings on
transportation, dining, and more. For example, the Copenhagen Card
provides free admission to more than 70 attractions, museums, and
sights, as well as complimentary rides on buses and trains, and _
new this year _ more than 20 restaurants are offering two drinks
for the price of one. The card costs $20 to $46 depending on length
of use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Holland news
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free gifts, discounts, and more are available to the
Holland-bound traveler. The Netherlands Board of Tourism is
offering a booklet of ``Savings Certificates,'' with 14 coupons
good for use in Amsterdam, The Hague, and Maastricht. Also included
is information on tax refunds and traveling by rail. For a copy,
call 888-GO-HOLLAND or visit www.goholland.com.
</P>
<P>
   Keukenhof Gardens is celebrating its 50th anniversary March 25
through May 19. The famed gardens are known for millions of tulips,
narcissi, hyacinths, and other bulbs. Visitors can also view a
changing display of flowers called Parades. New is the Gerbera
Parade, May 12-19, and an exhibition of photos and paintings,
``Playing with Light and Color.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thistle Hotels has a new and improved Pound for Dollar program
that is available all year with a full English breakfast included.
Guests can save up to 40 percent on the program, which provides
accommodations priced in pounds at the dollar rate. For example, in
Scotland at the Thistle Edinburgh, accommodations begin at 170
pounds or $170. For details, call 800-847-4358.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
New services
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United Airways is beginning Boston-London service on April 4. In
celebration of the new service to Heathrow, United Vacations is
offering an air-inclusive trip to London beginning at $649 that
includes air fare, four nights' accommodations at the Comfort Inn
Hyde Park, breakfasts, discounts on attractions and dining, map and
hotel taxes, and service charges. The package is available April
4-June 15. Call 800-328-6877 for details.
</P>
<P>
   Sabena is expanding its Boston-Brussels service to daily flights
beginning March 28. From its Brussels hub, Sabena offers flights to
more than 70 destinations in Europe, 24 in Africa and other cities
in the Middle and Far East.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The earth moves
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dynamic Earth is Scotland's newest and largest tourist
attraction. Opening this spring opposite the Palace of Holyrood
House and the Scottish Parliament in Edinburgh's Old Town, the
exhibition, the only one in the world, will telll how the earth was
created and will re-create some of nature's most powerful
phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Northern Ireland
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland Vacation Planner offers 24 pages filled
with practical tips on how travelers can discouver the country.
Everything is here, from golf and transportation information to
events and attractions. For a copy, call 800-326-0036.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
EurAir Pass expands
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The EurAir Pass system, which provides European travelers with
$90 flights to cities throughout the Continent, now has 12 airlines
in its system. EurAir Passes are sold in a packet of three, are
valid for 120 days, and are available only in the United States.
Each pass is $90 plus tax and is good for a one-way nonstop flight.
Travel agents have details or call 888-387-2479.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beatles tour
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Beatles fan, this tour is for you. The 16th annual
Beatles Magical Mystery Tour takes place Aug. 22 to Sept. 1. The
tour is led by Charles F. Rosenay, who is said to be America's
premier Beatles fan. The tour includes the Abbey Road studios,
private parties at the Cavern Club, Beatles landmarks, and a party
at Liverpool's Casbah Club with Pete Best, the Beatles first
drummer, who will also perform. For information on the $1,999
package, which includes air fare, accommodations, and events, write
to Liverpool Productions, 315 Derby Ave., Orange, CT 06477; or
telephone 800-777-5295.
</P>
