<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PORTLAND-ART-B     03-09 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PORTLAND-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND: WARM ON THE INSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ This is a city for all seasons, including
snowy winters and wet springs. There are indoor attractions aplenty
to complement the outdoor ones, even in March.
</P>
<P>
   A two-hour drive from Boston, Portland is a compact waterfront
city of 65,000. Nothing in the eminently walkable downtown _ which
has undergone a renaissance in recent years _ is hard to reach. If
the weather turns foul, there is someplace inviting to duck into
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Under the vast timbered ceiling of the new Portland Public
Market, for instance, it's always harvest time. The latest addition
to the lively downtown scene, the market is an urban oasis and a
showcase for Maine's agricultural and marine bounty, from poultry
to potatoes, from eels to elk steaks. You can get bison burgers
made from Maine-bred buffalo and fresh fillets from Down East
salmon farms.
</P>
<P>
   The 23 vendors at the market, which opened in October, include
purveyors of ice cream, homemade pies, wines, fresh fish and
lobster, aged cheeses, exotic coffees, flowers, fresh-baked bread
(made with wheat grown in northernmost Aroostook County), hot
soups, and local crafts. There is, in addition, an unusual amenity
for a farmers' market: a large fireplace flanked by stone benches,
an ideal place to linger on a chilly day over a cup of cappuccino
or a glass of cider.
</P>
<P>
   The market's dramatic interior is frequently used for concerts
and special events. (For information, call 207-228-2000. The
market, at the corner of Preble and Cumberland streets, is open
7-6, Monday-Saturday; 10-5, Sunday.) A covered skybridge connects
it to a garage that provides two hours of free parking with a
validated ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks from the market is the Old Port, a restored
neighborhood that runs back from the waterfront, and is known for
its restaurants, boutiques, specialty stores, and brew pubs.
</P>
<P>
   Portland is the largest fishing port in the area, and the
waterfront _ also a departure point for ferries to Nova Scotia and
the Casco Bay islands _ is active and atmospheric year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Close by, at 7 Congress Square, is the Portland Museum of Art.
One of the best medium-size museums in New England, it has a fine
collection of paintings by artists who have lived and worked in
Maine, such as Robert Henri, Rockwell Kent, and Andrew Wyeth. It
also organizes major special exhibits such as the current ``Louise
Nevelson: Structures Evolving,'' on view until March 21. Considered
one of the country's most innovative sculptors and print makers,
Nevelson, who died in 1988, grew up in Rockland. (Admission: $6,
adults; $5, seniors and students; $1, children 6-12. Open Tuesday,
Wednesday, Saturday, 10-5; Thursday-Friday, 10-9; Sunday 12-5;
closed Monday. Information: 207-773-2787.)
</P>
<P>
   The area around the museum is officially designated ``the Art
District,'' and there are several galleries, including the Frost
Gully Gallery at 411 Congress, which specializes in Maine art. The
Maine College of Art at 522 Congress, which occupies the
turn-of-the-century former Porteous department store building, has
galleries displaying the work of students and faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Housed nearby in a handsome Greek Revival building, the
Children's Museum of Maine, at 142 Free St., is usually filled with
happy kids and beaming parents. Interactive exhibits simulate Maine
landscapes, including a fishing pier complete with lobster boat, a
flowing stream, a mountain traverse, a bear's den (appropriately
dark and just a little spooky), and a giant pine tree that invites
climbing. (General admission $5; under 1 year old, free. Open:
Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, 10-5; Thursday, 9-5; Sunday 12-5;
closed Monday-Tuesday. Information: 207-828-1234, ext. 001.)
</P>
<P>
   The Old Port is between Commercial Street (which parallels the
waterfront) and Congress, a neighborhood of narrow cobblestoned
streets lined with 19th-century brick and granite buildings, most
restored within the last dozen years. Shops sell tacky T-shirts and
souvenirs, but also upscale jewelry, clothing, and hand-crafted
glass and pottery.
</P>
<P>
   Portland is a restaurant mecca, with most in the Old Port or
along the waterfront. There is a restaurant for just about every
taste and budget, and following your nose isn't a bad way to both
sightsee and find some food. Local favorites for fresh seafood at
moderate prices, in an informal atmosphere, include Gilbert's
Chowder House, 92 Commercial St., and the Porthole, around the
corner at 32 Customs Wharf. The core early-morning clientele of
both are fishermen, which says something.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular of the brew pubs is Gritty McDuff's, 396
Fore St. Gritty's brews its own ale, stout, and bitter and serves
fish and chips, shepherd's pie, and other pub-grub favorites. The
paneled decor is pubby as well. Portland has a long and lively pub
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer the city erected a statue to the late movie director
and local resident John Ford _ born Sean Aloysius O'Feeney in 1895
_ at the corner of Center and Pleasant streets. The statue shows
Ford sitting in a director's chair gazing pensively at the spot,
now a parking lot, where his Irish immigrant father ran a saloon
catering to thirsty dock workers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides restaurants and pubs, Portland also has a lot of
bookstores for a city its size. Books Etc. at 38 Exchange St. in
the Old Port is a general-interest independent bookstore with a
good selection of books about Maine and by its authors. Allen Scott
Books at 89 Exchange specializes in used, scarce, and out-of-print
books and has a room devoted to secondhand and rare children's
books. Also rewarding to browse are Cunningham Books in Longfellow
Square at the east end of Congress and Carlson &AMP; Turner Antiquarian
Books at 241 Congress, which stocks 75,000 older books.
</P>
<P>
   A magnet in Portland for railroad buffs of all ages is the Maine
Narrow Gauge Railroad Co. and Museum, on the waterfront at 58 Fore
St. All of the locomotives and cars in the museum were built _ some
as long as 117 years ago _ for use in parts of Maine, commonly to
haul logs and carry passengers through the North Woods. However,
for 50 years they chugged through the cranberry bogs of Carver in
southeastern Massachusetts as the Edaville Railroad, a popular
tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Edaville closed in 1991, and the antique rolling stock was
brought back here. The train museum is housed in one of the old
red-brick buildings of a harborside industrial complex where
locomotives were once manufactured. The museum also operates 1 1/2
miles of 2-foot-wide track and offers rides. The rides, which last
about 30 minutes, are available weekends only until mid-May, when
the daily schedule resumes.
</P>
<P>
   (The Narrow Gauge Museum, open daily 10-4, is free. Excursion
rides are $5 for adults, $4 for seniors, $3 for children 4-12.
Information: 207-828-0814.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
