<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE PLACES RATE A `OUI' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for one of the hottest restaurants in Paris,
visit the crowded but cool Le Buddha Bar or the Louvre's chic Cafe
Marly. But if you want to avoid a dreadful dining experience, skip
the area around Pigalle, which has become ``tacky and touristy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the advice of Jacques Pillet, head concierge at Paris's
elegant Hotel Meurice, writing in A: the Audley Group Hotel
Magazine. More advice:
</P>
<P>
   --Best food. L'Ambroisie, Alain Ducasse, Pierrre Gagnaire,
Laurent, Guy Savoy, and Le Grand Vefour.
</P>
<P>
   --Best breakfast. ``The homemade viennoiserie and fine teas and
coffees at Dalloyau . . . place it at the pinnacle of Parisian
breakfasts.''
</P>
<P>
   --Best afternoon tea. English style: Marriages et Freres.
Parisian style: Laduree (oh, those macaroons!).
</P>
<P>
   --Best spot for a quiet romantic drink. The Forum bar or La
Closerie de Lilas.
</P>
<P>
   --Best show. The Moulin Rouge is still the top Parisian cabaret.
(Expect mostly tourists there, however. That, at least, was our
experience.)
</P>
<P>
   --Hottest clubs. Les Bains Douches, Le Queen, and Niel's.
</P>
<P>
   --Best shopping. The 6th arrondissement represents ``the epitome
of Left Bank chic'' with high-style shops like Sonia Rykiel and
Prada. Also check out Armani's new Emporio Saint-Germain, the
Versace Collection (also on the Boulevard Saint-Germain in the 7th
arrondissement), and the smart antiques shops around the Quai
Voltaire.
</P>
<P>
   --Best souvenir shopping. For general souvenirs, the arcades of
the Rue de Rivoli. For china and glassware, the Rue du Paradis.
Also: Fauchon for gourmet delicacies, Debauve &AMP; Gallais for
chocolates, and La Maison de la Truffe for wondrous truffles.
</P>
<P>
   --Best view of the city. Although the Eiffel Tower and
Montmartre are the classic sites, the Meurice staff recommends the
view from the 59th-floor Terrace of the Tour Montparnasse, and,
understandably, the panorama from the Meurice's newly refurbished
penthouse suite. (For more information on the Hotel Meurice, call
33 (1) 44 58 10 10.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Where in Europe will you find the 3,323-foot-long
April the 25th Bridge? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: In France, Germany, and Great Britain, a US billion is
known as a milliard. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a phrase: We say, ``Let's Splurge.'' In Great Britain, they say,
``Let's splash out.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``You cannot extinguish the Irish passion for freedom.''
_ Padraic Pearse, in 1916. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rhyme time: In warm weather, Dublin's River Liffey can be a bit
aromatic. At such times, local wags refer to it as the ``Sniffy
Liffey.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fascinating fact: The channel between England and France grows 300
mm (11.81 inches) each year. (With thanks to uselessfacts.net via
frequent contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, who adds, ``I'm
sure both the British and the French are happy about this.'') &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel bookshelf: ``Daytrips Ireland'' by Patricia Tunison Preston
(Hastings House, $14.95) offers step-by-step information on 50
one-day getaways from wherever you are in the Emerald Isle. There
are 22 walking tours, 24 tours using a car and/or public
transportation, and four tours that combine walking and public
transportation. Fifty-five maps are also included. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A multistar hotel: What do Stephen Spielberg, Franco Zefferelli,
Elizabeth Taylor, Marlon Brando, Harrison Ford, Warren Beatty,
Shirley MacLaine, Liza Minnelli, Lauren Bacall, Charlton Heston,
Olivia Newton-John, Victoria Principal, Robert Wagner, and
Stephanie Powers have in common, other than the movies? They are
among the many celebrities who have stayed at the Athenaeum Hotel
in London's West End. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oh, that Winston: The underground complex where British Prime
Minister Winston Churchill directed the Allied effort during World
War II is now open to the public. Among things a visitor learns
when visiting the complex, located on King Charles Street in
London: The underground offices and bedrooms were protected by a
three-foot slab of concrete. Yet when the city was being bombed,
Churchill was likely to be found not in his protected quarters but
on the building roof, watching the air raids. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Changing times: The birthplace of the great singer John McCormack
in Athlone, Ireland, is now a Chinese take-out restaurant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The 3,323-foot-long April the 25th Bridge is in
Portugal. April 25, 1974, was the date of the ``Carnation
Revolution'' _ so-called because soldiers put carnations in their
rifle barrels
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
