<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3468 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-DiMAGGIO-COOPERST     03-09 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DiMAGGIO-COOPERSTOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUNDS OF SILENCE AT HOME PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The Hall of Fame Gallery is a mausoleum of
sorts, dedicated to the immortals of baseball's past. It is a place
in the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum where talk is
naturally muted, reserved for reverential, hushed tones.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, that quiet was amplified and echoed. Joe DiMaggio,
the game's designated Greatest Living Player, was dead. It was a
time to pay respects to one of the most respected players in the
history of sport.
</P>
<P>
   Fans trickled past the terse plaque dedicated to DiMaggio that
encapsulates his on-the-field accomplishments, but fails miserably
to capture his impact off it. A wreath of white roses hung around
the bronze memorial, a sign to those who know that Joltin' Joe had
left and gone away.
</P>
<P>
   His death at age 84 in the early hours of Monday morning came
too late for many to make a special weekday trip to the Hall of
Fame. The crowd was light, average for a March Monday, and most of
the pilgrims there learned of DiMaggio's demise while en route.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Moreau, a 25-year-old oncology nurse from Ilion, N.Y., was
an exception. She donned her Yankees jersey and came specifically
to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that (he died) I knew I had to come,'' she said.
``He is an icon in Yankee history, and in all of baseball and
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was the last direct link in the chain of Yankees
dynasties from the 1920s to the 1960s, a lineage that began with
The Babe, carried through Iron Man Lou, and on to Joe D. and
ultimately The Mick. DiMaggio's death leaves Ted Williams and Bob
Hope as among the last surviving cultural icons dating back to
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was blessed with a long, graceful swing and stride, and
a silent, gentlemanly manner, a man who never lashed out in a
tell-all book or sought to grasp at the last rays of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't like the limelight,'' said Charlie Washington, 48,
who was with his wife, Deborah, from Richmond, Va. ``He just wanted
to be known for his accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   They are numerous, from the 10 World Series appearances (nine
wins) to his .325 lifetime batting average, to, of course, The
Streak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, a magical year in which Ted Williams became the last
player to hit .400 (.406), DiMaggio once again one-upped his Boston
Red Sox adversary and friend. The Streak started on May 15, in a
game in which the Bronx Bombers got bombed, 13-1. It stretched two
months, until July 16: 56 games in a row with at least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   The still-standing streak so captured the prewar nation that Les
Brown and his Orchestra, long before Simon &AMP; Garfunkel used
DiMaggio as a metaphor in ``Mrs. Robinson,'' recorded the
impossibly hokey ``Joltin' Joe DiMaggio:'' He'll live in baseball's
Hall of Fame, He got there blow by blow.
</P>
<P>
   When DiMaggio retired after the 1951 season, he demurred when it
was suggested he was irreplaceable. ``There's always some youngster
coming up _ they'll find somebody.'' The Yankees did. His name was
Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   But for excellence mixed with style and dignity on and off the
field, the pickings are slim today. Joe Pelaia, 49, and his
20-year-old son, Mike Pelaia, offered Cal Ripken Jr. as the closest
thing (Ripken, who played the most consecutive games in history,
knows streaks himself), although the Maryland pair admit they are
Baltimore Orioles fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different; I don't think (DiMaggio) was cocky,'' the
son said. ``Most players today are cocky.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, coming back from visiting the troops overseas,
Marilyn Monroe, briefly DiMaggio's wife but the love of his life,
told him, ``You never heard such cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, he replied: ``Yes, I have.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, through the Hall of Fame, there was silence, as loud
as any cheering he ever heard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
