<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-09 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD-CLASS TUBBIES, UNITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ We may not like Monica Lewinsky very much, but she
has done a lot for the full-figured woman.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that she and Bill Clinton had fat in common was a bond
between them, not a turnoff. Thanks to them, pleasingly plump is
in.
</P>
<P>
   In a world in which being skinny and bony is the ultimate beauty
ideal, this is the only heartening feature of their strange,
disgusting relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Monica slimmed down somewhat for her Barbara Walters interview
and gargantuan European book tour but she makes no secret of her
continuing obsession with her life-long effort to control her
weight.
</P>
<P>
   It fluctuates, depending on her seriousness at attempting any
given diet. She has dresses in several sizes and hangs the larger
ones in her ``fat closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if she wished to ignore the poundage, it fascinates the
rest of us, and we will not let her off the hook. The tabloids and
magazines have made a habit of reporting what she eats in
restaurants and how much, with emphasis on the desserts. Her
Walters interview was in part underwritten by not-so-subtle
commercials for a low-calorie drink and diet cookies as well as
supplements meant to help people lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   She told Elle magazine that ``everybody hates me; they think I'm
fat.'' Actually, we don't like her because of her behavior, not her
shape, which is tubby but quite cuddly. Yet she is accurately
reflecting a real problem faced by overweight people. Many studies
have documented that society discriminates against them in covert
ways because their appearance is not seen as attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska writer and teacher Ruth Raymond Thone, in her book
``Fat _ A Fate Worse Than Death?'' describes a multitude of ways in
which weight and size constitute the last socially accepted
prejudice. She rages against snide remarks, cruel ridicule, the
constant commercial barrage for get-thin products, male attitudes
toward sexual beauty and cultural pressure that affects competition
for jobs and husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Thone feels that women are cheated by society's concentration on
weight and outward appearance and distracted from addressing the
real issues of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have confirmed that being overweight damages a
young person's social and economic potential, particularly that of
females. Heavyset women complete about half a year less schooling,
are 20 percent less likely to get married and earn considerably
less per year than their slimmer counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Monica, in fact, attributes some of what she admits were low
``feelings of self-worth'' to her own weight problem. That did not
stop her, of course, from aggressively going after a married
president twice her age.
</P>
<P>
   She empathized with a fellow fat-sufferer. She reports that the
first time Clinton took off his shirt in front of her he sucked in
his stomach. She says he told her that as a child he was so chubby
and ran so slowly the other children beat him to the chocolate eggs
during the annual Easter egg hunt.
</P>
<P>
   In his Clinton biography ``First In His Class,'' author David
Maraniss describes a youthful Clinton preoccupied with his weight.
In a letter to a friend, Clinton lamented that he and his younger
brother Roger were eating too many sweets. ``Sometimes I think the
whole house will sink into a heap of sugar,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The president has lost some girth in the White House, where fast
food is usually banned and the resident chefs serve healthy,
low-calorie meals. Intern-delivered pizza seems to have been an
exception.
</P>
<P>
   But his pudgy, puffy-faced image endures. Cartoonist Mike Peters
told me that he tried to slim down his drawings of Clinton but was
flooded with complaints. A skinny Clinton just didn't look like
Clinton. He lost the buffoon quality.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us who also have to watch our weight can identify
with this miserable couple. They are both physically attractive,
proof that size is not everything. I saw Monica in person only
once, during one of her plumper phases. She was lovely. And every
time I see the president I am struck anew by his friendly, mobile
face and personal magnetism.
</P>
<P>
   It's not their outward appearance that turns us off. It's the
moral emptiness inside that is the trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
