r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     03-09 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH OF CHRIST MINISTER CONDEMNS THAT SWING THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dancing still is considered a wicked activity by some
conservative Christians.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of that recently when a friend gave me a copy of
``36 Reasons Why Christians Should Not Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   At first I thought the document condemning popular dancing as an
evil, lustful activity might be out of date. But its author, Mac
Layton, a veteran Church of Christ minister from Edmond, Okla.,
still stands by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think dancing is wrong, but very few people are teaching
that anymore,'' Layton, a minister at the Deer Creek Church of
Christ near Edmond, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Layton is among Church of Christ leaders who recently condemned
students at Abilene Christian University _ one of the largest
Church of Christ-related universities _ for taking part in
swing-dance lessons off campus.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Church of Christ and Baptist congregations that have
been known to oppose dancing spend less time condemning the
practice these days.
</P>
<P>
   Some Baptist leaders have gone so far as to say that dancing can
be a harmless and wholesome activity.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case three years ago when Baylor University in
Waco, Texas, the nation's largest Baptist-related university,
lifted its 140-year-old ban on campus dances. Robert Sloan,
Baylor's president, led the dancing with his wife. He said
controlled dances on campus could help promote a spirit of
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   But Baylor isn't going wild with dancing since the ban was
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Only four on-campus dances are held at Baylor each year, said
Liz Webb, a spokeswoman for the student activities office. Alcohol
is banned from all dances, even the off-campus ones. And all dances
are strictly chaperoned and have time constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many conservative Christians like Layton say Baylor is
compromising its moral standards by allowing any kind of dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just giving in to the world, I think,'' Layton said.
</P>
<P>
   Layton wrote ``36 Reasons Why Christians Should Not Dance'' 25
years ago. Some of his reasons are:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The dance is the only place where the vilest of men can
embrace the purest of women.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The fondling and embrace in dancing is not permitted in
decent society without music. What is wrong without music, is wrong
with music.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Nightclubs, roadhouses, taverns of infamy, late hours, are
companions of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Young women lose their modesty and chastity, and influence,
by dancing.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Thousands of men engage in the dance as the surest way to
trap an innocent girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxie Boren, preacher at the Brown Trail Church of Christ in
Bedford, Texas, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``disgusted'' that officials at his alma mater,
Abilene Christian, failed to reprimand students for doing swing
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I graduated from Abilene Christian in 1955, we would have
been sent packing if the administration knew we danced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 2.5 million people in Church of Christ congregations
don't hear preaching against dancing anymore, said Tyler Young,
minister at the Granbury Street Church of Christ in Cleburne.
</P>
<P>
   But a minority of congregations, including his own, are still
following what he called ``the old path.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold the position that dancing _ popular dancing that goes
on at bars and clubs _ is lascivious and tends to arouse lust,'' he
said. ``We also believe all that sexual bumping and grinding we see
on MTV is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Young doesn't condemn all dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing in and of itself is not a sin,'' he wrote in his
church's newsletter recently. Married couples who dance in their
homes are not sinning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   People danced joyfully in biblical times, with God's approval,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``David danced before the Lord when the Ark of the Covenant was
returned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Young and other conservative religionists are realists. They
acknowledge they are fighting an uphill battle against dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing has been a popular amusement for many years,'' he
said. ``And the opponent of the modern dance is considered an old
fogy or an ancient fossil.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
