<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ Even though Republicans have
largely agreed with President Clinton's plan to set aside part of
the anticipated budget surplus to shore up Social Security, they
still face challenges in devising an investment-based plan for the
retirement system. Letting individuals invest a portion of their
Social Security funds in the stock market while still guaranteeing
minimum benefits could be tricky, critics say. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   DIET-GUIDELINES (Washington) _ A health organization here
charges that government dietary guidelines exhibit a bias against
African Americans, Hispanics and Asians, many of whom are lactose
intolerant. The Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine says
the government should make its recommended daily intake of dairy
products optional. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION (Washington) _ Republican presidential candidate
Gary Bauer criticizes Texas Gov. George W. Bush's abortion stance,
saying not only that America needs a pro-life president but that
leaders should shape public opinion, not just react to it. By CRAGG
HINES.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-INTERNET (Washington)_ Since minors are finding it easy
to buy alcoholic beverages on the Internet, Congress is considering
a bill that would give state officials more power to police such
activity. But California winemakers say the legislation could
unfairly hamper their efforts to use the Internet to sell wine that
is not widely available in liquor stores. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
renews her effort to clamp more federal controls on rapid-fire
guns. She introduces a bill to close a major loophole in her 1994
law that banned the manufacture of 19 types of semiautomatic
weapons. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-CENSUS (Washington) _ A review by the New Urban
Institute, a public policy organization, of Census data shows a
bigger drop in the number of immigrants on welfare than by American
citizens who rely on public assistance. By JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIP (San Salvador, El Salvador) _ President Clinton
continues his tour of Central America, surveying the aftermath of
last fall's hurricane damage and U.S. relief efforts. By JOHN C.
HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALEXANDER-2000 (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander, ditching his once-trademark plaid shirt for a suit that
says ``I'm a governor, too,'' formally announces he is running for
the 2000 presidential nomination. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   WILDFLOWERS-TEXAS (Undated) _ A lack of rain in January and
February may result in a thinner than usual crop of wildflowers in
Southeast Texas, but the dry spell also has resulted in early
blooms. By ALAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   CUNNINGHAM-OBIT (New York) _ Richard F. Cunningham, a finance
and administrative executive for The Hearst Corporation's
Entertainment and Syndication Group, died Monday at his home in
Suffern, N.Y., after battling cancer. Cunningham, 52, was
responsible for the financial activities of the A&AMP;E cable network,
as well as the History Channel, King Features Syndicate and the New
England Cable News. By The Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ We may not much like Monica
Lewinsky, but she has done a lot for the full-figured woman. The
fact that she and Bill Clinton had fat in common was a bond between
them, not a turn-off. Thanks to them, pleasingly plump is in. In a
world in which being bony is the ultimate beauty ideal, this is the
only heartening feature of their strange, disgusting relationship.
By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas, a school that has been known
for years as a guard-oriented team that specializes in running and
firing up wild three-pointers, now relies almost exclusively on its
inside game. And the Longhorns' front line of center Chris Mihm and
forwards Kris Clack and Gabe Muoneke has proved quite formidable in
leading Texas to the Big 12 regular-season title and into the NCAA
Tournament. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
