<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3546 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMAX-THREE-D-LADN     03-09 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAX-THREE-D-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEBACK OF 3-D FILMS ENVISIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Though it's hard to believe, stereoscopic
photography has been around for 161 years, ever since Sir Charles
Wheatstone figured out how to use a collection of angled mirrors to
create the illusion of three-dimensionality using two
two-dimensional photos of the same shot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1903, the pioneering Lumiere Bros. of France sent Parisian
moviegoers fleeing from the theater with a one-minute, 3-D film of
a train's arrival at a station.
</P>
<P>
   The golden age of 3-D film hit 50 years later, but only briefly,
with 65 films churned out between 1952 and 1954 before new
wide-screen technology proved an inexpensive alternative draw.
</P>
<P>
   Now 3-D might be poised to make a comeback, but on the very big
screen, say Charlotte Huggins and Ben Stassen, the producer and the
director, respectively, of the just released 3-D large-format film,
``Encounter in the Third Dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   The 39-minute show _ which debuted recently at IMAX theaters in
Exposition Park, Ontario and Irvine _ is a fun review of the
science and history of 3-D theater, featuring excerpts of some of
the best recent 3-D theme-park attractions, including ``Terminator
2 3-D.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Encounter'' particularly interesting, however, is
that the 3-D is done on a truly gargantuan scale, pitched for the
five-story-high IMAX screens. Combined with computer-generated
sets, the technology allows for a remarkable experience that
Stassen and Huggins believe soon will be embraced by other
filmmakers looking for an all-consuming cinema experience, if they
can stand the production complications.
</P>
<P>
   Even simple questions such as film magazine size and reloading
time are more difficult with 3-D, they said. Instead of getting 12
minutes per magazine, and needing only five minutes to put in a new
one, 3-D cameras hold only three minutes of film, and take as much
as a half hour to reload.
</P>
<P>
   But the results in a large-format 3-D film can be wonderful,
Stassen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you go (with a) smaller (film format), you have a
window you're looking through,'' Stassen said. ``With large-format,
you don't have a window, you have a space. It's immersive. To me,
it's really a new language of cinema, because it's so different
from what we're used to.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair and their Sherman Oaks-based company, nWave Pictures,
already are working on other 3-D, large-format films, including a
science-fiction title and an undersea adventure.
</P>
<P>
   But only 10 large-format 3-D films ever have been made, despite
a recent building boom in IMAX and other large-format theaters
whose cameras can show the titles.
</P>
<P>
   With only two 3-D camera rigs now available in the world,
Stassen said more needs to be invested in the camera technology for
such films to become more common.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spent $1.5 billion building (large-format) theaters,
$200 million making films and only $5 million on the camera
technology,'' Stassen said. ``The tools aren't there. Something has
to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1613EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
