 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, March 10, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BOOK (Mexico City) _ A new children's book in Spanish and
English is being published by a small press in El Paso, a profusely
illustrated ``History of Colors'' that tells an ancient Mexican
Indian myth of how colors came into the world. The publisher got a
grant from the National Endowment for the Arts. You open the book
and there on the jacket is a picture of the author: Subcommandate
Insurgente Marcos, leader of the left-wing Zapatista rebellion in
Mexico. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ The White House is resisting a House
panel's efforts to make public information about how the Clinton
administration has handled China's campaign to acquire sensitive
American military technology, congressional officials said. A
special bipartisan committee and the administration have been
quietly negotiating how much of the report could be publicly
released, but in recent weeks the discussions have entered a
sensitive stage. The special committee goes out of business at the
end of the month. A few days later China's prime minister comes to
Washington for an official visit. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-POLITICS (Washington) _ On Wednesday, Elizabeth Hanford
Dole is to announce her intention to formally run for president. In
what would be her first race, she appears ready to become the
country's first serious female presidential candidate and a serious
contender, period. As a two-time Cabinet secretary, former head of
the American Red Cross and immensely popular campaigner for her
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, she has stirred enormous interest
among Republicans. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWYER (New Orleans) Over the last five years, Wendell
H. Gauthier has organized the largest ever group of American trial
lawyers and led them in a sustained assault against the tobacco
industry for the damage caused by nicotine addiction. Though he
claims to be neither the smartest nor the richest of the trial
lawyers who have taken on the tobacco industry, he is the architect
and chairman of a growing legal enterprise that is mounting a
similar assault on the gun industry. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP (Undated) _ Dismantling what the 1980s had
wrought and conceding the whole concept was a big mistake, RJR
Nabisco announced it was splitting up its food and domestic tobacco
businesses. At the same time, the company announced it was selling
its international tobacco operations for $8 billion to Japan
Tobacco, a Tokyo-based conglomerate that will become the
third-largest global cigarette manufacturer once the deal is
completed. By Constance L. Hays
</P>
</TEXT>
