<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPLORATORY10-COX     03-09 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLORATORY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENDLESS ANNOUNCEMENTS ARE CANDIDATES' BID TO BE NOTICED
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Presidential hopefuls are using a new ploy to
attract the attention of tuned-out voters: multiple announcements
about ``exploratory committees'' as a prelude to the formal rollout
of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is traveling to Iowa on Wednesday to announce
that she is forming an exploratory committee to determine whether
to run for president, even though few doubt she has already begun
to run.
</P>
<P>
   The best example of this phenomenon is former Vice President Dan
Quayle's campaign for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In a well-publicized appearance on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' in
January, Quayle announced that he would be forming an exploratory
committee. The first week in February in his home state of Indiana,
he announced the actual formation of the committee. Later that same
week, he made the same announcement in his adopted state of
Arizona, then went to Iowa and New Hampshire for similar
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come is Quayle's official announcement of his
candidacy, now expected in April in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually think we're on the light side of announcements,''
said Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron, ``at least compared to
some.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Texas Gov. George W. Bush's numerous pronouncements
about whether he would run prior to last week's announcement to the
Texas media that he intended to announce the formation of an
exploratory committee, which he announced Sunday. No date has been
set for the actual announcement of his candidacy, however.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the process _ sometimes called the
``strip-tease'' by political reporters _ is that presidential
candidates are trying ``to milk every last ounce of publicity,''
said Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia professor who is an
expert on the relationship between presidential candidates and the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a commentary on the short half-life of public memory and
the electorate's general lack of attention to politics,'' added
Sabato. ``It probably takes a half-dozen 'hits' before the public
gets the message that X or Y is running.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, advisers say an exploratory committee is being formed
because federal election regulations require one before the
potential candidate can raise money and travel to ``test the
waters'' before officially entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations of the Federal Election Commission (FEC) contain
no such requirement, according to Ian Stirton, the FEC's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, FEC regulations specifically contain ``testing the
waters'' exemptions from having to register with the federal
agency, which oversees federal elections. And in campaigns prior to
1996, presidential aspirants generally did not register with the
FEC while testing their potential appeal as a candidate. ``We never
used to see much of this,'' Stirton said.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the coming months, the FEC assumes the 2000
presidential candidates will amend the names of their campaign
organizations to drop the word ``exploratory'' from the title,
Stirton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Exploratory' is really a term the candidates have just
decided to use _ for whatever reason,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
