r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNNINGHAM-OBIT-HNS &LR;      03-09 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNNINGHAM-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD F. CUNNINGHAM, HEARST EXECUTIVE, DIES AT 52 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard F. Cunningham, group finance and
administrative officer for The Hearst Corporation's Entertainment &AMP;
Syndication Group, died Monday at his home in Suffern, N.Y., after
battling cancer for several months. He was 52 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cunningham, who joined The Hearst Corporation in financial
planning in 1977, had held the finance and administrative officer
position since the formation of the Entertainment &AMP; Syndication
Group in 1989. Mr. Cunningham was responsible for the financial
activities for all Hearst interests in the group, including A&AMP;E;
Lifetime; ESPN; The History Channel; King Features Syndicate; New
England Cable News; First DataBank; and Hearst Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he was a member of the boards of A&AMP;E Television
Networks, First DataBank-Europe, Hearst/ABC Video Services and New
England Cable News.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cunningham was an adviser to the board of TVA, a supplier of
cable and satellite television services in Brazil in which Hearst
is an investor, and was active in the operations of Hearst's joint
venture in Locomotion, the all- animation channel in Latin America,
Spain and Portugal. He also played a key role in such group
acquisitions as Medi-Span Inc., a supplier of drug product
information to the healthcare industry, which was consolidated into
First DataBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Cunningham was instrumental in the growth and success of
Hearst's many activities in entertainment and syndication,'' said
Raymond E. Joslin, group head of Hearst Entertainment &AMP; Syndication
and vice president of The Hearst Corporation. ``His death is a
tremendous loss to the company and to his many colleagues who were
inspired by his energy, wisdom and foresight. He will be greatly
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cunningham joined The Hearst Corporation as manager of
financial planning in 1977 and was named assistant controller of
the company in 1981. The following year, he was appointed assistant
treasurer and director of financial planning of The Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   In this capacity, he coordinated corporate financial planning
activities and contributed to Hearst's numerous acquisitions in the
1980s, including Esquire magazine, Diversion magazine, and the
Cowles and North America syndicates which were consolidated into
King Features. He was a principal Hearst representative in the
process leading to the merger of ARTS with the Entertainment
Channel, which formed A&AMP;E, and the merger of Daytime with Cable
Health Network, which created Lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining Hearst, Mr. Cunningham was an assistant vice
president for Irving Trust Co., where he was responsible for
financial reporting. He also held executive positions with St.
Regis Paper Co. and Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the American Institute of Certified Public
Accountants, the New York State Society of Certified Public
Accountants and the Financial Executives Institute. He was active
for nine years with the Suffern, N.Y., Little League, as a member
of the board, treasurer and coach, and was a coach for the Suffern
High School baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cunningham served as a sergeant in the U.S. Army's Signal
Corps, with top secret security clearance. He held two degrees from
Fordham University: a B.S. in accounting and an MBA in finance.
</P>
<P>
   He also completed post-graduate study in finance and
econometrics at Pace University.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Dawn, and their four children,
Michael, Brian, Amy and Meghan, of Suffern, N.Y.; two brothers,
Victor of Valley Cottage, N.Y., and Thomas of Monroe, N.Y.; and one
sister, Ann Marie Fitzgerald of Long Valley, N.J. Funeral services
will be held at 10 a.m., Thursday, March 11, at Church of the
Presentation, 271 West Saddle River Road, Upper Saddle River, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Remembrances may be donated to the Suffern Little League, c/o
Cunningham Family, 45 Maplewood Boulevard, Suffern, N.Y. 10961.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
