<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANT-RUDENESS-2     03-09 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-RUDENESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TABLE TAKES TIME. MOSTLY YOURS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The minute Evelyn Kenvin walked into Bouley Bakery
for dinner on the evening of Jan. 30, something felt a little off.
</P>
<P>
   The hostess flashed a surprised look and retreated to confer
with the manager. After this huddle, Ms. Kenvin and her party of
four were seated, and everything was fine.
</P>
<P>
   But some instinct told her to check her machine, so she called
it from her cell phone. It turned out the restaurant had left a
message that afternoon saying their 6:30 reservation had been
canceled. The reason: ``a technical problem.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Kenvin, a vice president at Citibank who has been to her
share of fancy eateries, this was a first. She'd never been
``canceled'' before. Imagine attending a party from which you'd
been disinvited. ``I was amused, frankly,'' she said. ``My husband
was annoyed. He doesn't understand the pompousness of these
places.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers can go almost anywhere in the city for the privilege
of bad treatment, and trendy restaurants are among the most
reliable locales for insult and ego injury. The cruel irony is that
just as it seems servers are getting better _ less surly, more
helpful _ the experience of making it past the front door is
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of a creeping, cavalier callousness are everywhere: the
endless confirming and reconfirming reservations, the ``we'll need
the table back by'' bum's rush. The secret VIP phone lines
segregating diners into two classes: those who have The Number and
those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   Apprised of the cancellation incident, David Bouley expressed
appropriate dismay. Construction in the building had threatened a
power outage, and the possibility existed that the restaurant would
have to close that night, he said. Perfectly plausible, but no such
information was offered the Kenvin party at the time. And the room
was filled with diners. Had they, too, been canceled?
</P>
<P>
   Making reservations, never a walk in the park, has become a
maddening time suck. Some diners are starting to get annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to set my Palm Pilot to remind me to recall places to
make sure I did what I already did!'' said Anthony Giglio, a senior
editor at P.O.V. magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Herscher, a marketing manager at Broadway Books, made a
reservation for four at Bond Street, was asked for his credit card
number and was told that if he didn't show up he'd be charged $50 _
not an uncommon practice for large groups, but this was four
people. ``I understand that Bond Street is hip and busy,'' he said.
``But this isn't an airplane reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad have things become? As an experiment _ albeit a highly
selective and unscientific one _ I called a dozen restaurants for
dinner. I tried to make myself as accommodating as possible: just
two people, something close to 8 o'clock, on a quiet night
(Wednesday), with 10 days' notice. A simple enough request. Or so
it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific asked for a reconfirmation call 48 hours in
advance (italics)and(end italics) a credit card number. ``Don't
worry, we will never charge your card,'' the hostess chirped.
``It's merely an incentive for you to call.''
</P>
<P>
   I was put on hold for what seemed like a very long 30 seconds;
then, a brusquely efficient female voice offered me 8:45, provided
I called the special reconfirmation line the day before between 10
and 5 p.m. I said I'd be traveling that day and asked what would
happen if I couldn't call. ``We will rebook the table if we don't
get a confirmation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Jean Georges, I was transferred into a many-circled voice
mail hell. After a long recorded message advertising Jean-George
Vongerichten's Epicurian empire (Vong, Jo Jo, Mercer Kitchen), a
French-accented woman picked up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm,'' she said twice, furrowing her syllables. ``We can give
you 5:30, but we need the table back by 8.'' Then she noticed a
7:30, but I'd have to be out by 9 or 9:30. I asked if the time
limit was a regular thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually two and a half hours for a party of two,'' she
said cheerily, asking that I reconfirm by 10 a.m. the day before
and assigning me the confirmation number 151.
</P>
<P>
   Balthazar, Veruka, Bond Street and Cena all insisted on
reconfirmation calls, and none of them seemed particularly flexible
about my professed inability to call back. Union Square Cafe,
however, promised to hold my 6 p.m. table until 6:30, even if the
staff didn't hear from me.
</P>
<P>
   All the restaurants called me to check if I was coming, many
with brusque messages detailing the time my reservation would be
terminated if I failed to call back.
</P>
<P>
   The most laid back of the lot was, amazingly, Le Cirque. When I
asked if I should call to reconfirm, the reaction was far from a
cold Continental shoulder. ``No, no problem,'' the hostess said.
``We trust that you're going to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust. The word seemed quaint in the cold, transactional
business of getting into a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, no-shows can cost a restaurant thousands on a bad
night. They are indeed nefarious criminals of New York dining
society, averaging 25 percent to 30 percent, according to studies
by American Express. And they have the effect of the bad kid in
school, whose anonymous mischief means the teacher has to punish
the whole class.
</P>
<P>
   Sirio Maccioni, the owner of Le Cirque, prefers a more lenient
approach. ``Of course there are people who make reservations in two
or three restaurants on one night,'' Maccioni said. ``But what can
you do, call the police?''
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurateurs sound as if they would like to. Keith
McNally, the owner of Balthazar, for one, said: ``There are
customers who walk in who are infuriating, who are drunk or who are
so socially insecure it's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   There does seem to be an increasingly adversarial relationship
between diner and host. Tim Zagat, whose populist guides talk as
much about how customers are served as what they are served,
pointed out that there were ways of dealing with the problem of
hotness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny Meyer makes you feel good even when he's saying no to
you,'' Zagat said. ``Other places, when they're saying yes, you
want to hit them in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger for any restaurateur is that his place gets, in Yogi
Berra's formulation, so popular nobody goes there anymore.
</P>
<P>
   At Asia de Cuba, just try to ascend the stairway to the
restaurant and bar area without a gatekeeper demanding to know if
you have a reservation. Mercer Kitchen has Asia de Cuba's
two-tiered security system: outer and inner sanctums.
</P>
<P>
   Greeter No. 1 waylays you in the Mercer Hotel lobby, while she
double-checks your reservations before permitting descent into the
restaurant downstairs, where Greeter No. 2 awaits. Cafe Moomba
dispenses with even the pretense of politesse: a bouncer with
clipboard mans the velvet rope.
</P>
<P>
   But clubby attitude has trickled down to restaurants that don't
live or die by Leo sightings. Take Balthazar: When I called the
regular Balthazar number to ask for an 8 p.m. reservation, I was
told there was nothing for two and a half weeks. When I called The
Number, an 8 o'clock table opened up the next night.
</P>
<P>
   McNally said he did not believe his system of diner
discrimination _ ``reservationism,'' you might call it _ was
exclusionary. ``It's not really private since it gets printed all
over the place,'' he said of the secret number, exposed in the
March issue of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Its code cracked, Balthazar has been calling Very Important
Diners and giving them a new secret number: 625-8665.
</P>
<P>
   It might work for a few more days. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
