</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: A TOUR FOR EVERY TASTE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 5 COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS)
</P>
<P>
   A group tour of Europe used to mean one thing: 50 people crowded
on a ''motor coach'' (brochure-speak for enormous bus) racing
through 10 countries in as many days. Those tours still exist. But
something strange has happened in the tour business. A ``European
tour'' now can mean many things. (Includes 4 color illustrations,
varying from 3 columns to 1 columns, depicting ways to travel in
Europe such as via bike, hiking, riding a horse and traveling with
a pet.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL COLUMN: Adventure travel used to mean something
along the lines of riding a camel through dust storms in Morocco,
hot on the trail of the mysterious Blue People, or hacking your way
with a machete through Peru's jungles, looking for a lost tribe.
But lately, the word adventure is just a marketing term to make
tame tours sound more thrilling. (Includes a 1-column color
illustration of plane passengers on a wacky flight)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS: An early bloom won't stop Austin's famous floral
festival.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: IYANLA VANZANT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 3 COLOR PHOTOS, 1 COLOR MUG SHOT)
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual guru and author Iyanla Vanzant is the picture of
serene success. Vanzant seems perfectly at peace, and why not?
She's a regular on TV's ``Oprah Winfrey Show,'' Hallmark has turned
her daily affirmations into a line of greeting cards and her string
of best sellers includes ``Acts of Faith,'' a book many loyal
readers call the black women's Bible. (Includes 2-column color
photo of author Iyanla Vanzant)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: ''Monica's Story'' might well be called ''The
Miseducation of Monica Lewinsky.'' It's the story of how an
emotionally needy young woman sought to assuage her low self-esteem
with eating binges and affairs with unavailable men _ one of which
just happened to be the president of the United States _ and who
threw this country into a tabloid frenzy and the first impeachment
trial in 131 years. (Includes 2-column color photo of book jacket)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: ``The Diary of Vaslav Nijinsky,'' widely believed
to be the only first-person, on-the-spot account of a major
artist's collapse into psychosis, is a harrowing book. Losing one's
mind is not romantic. But, oh, how we like to think it is.
(Includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: No one is so romantic as the
hero-worshipping academic, and no one quicker to hiss when the
daydream is punctured. (Includes 1-column color photo of columnist)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH: PLUGGING A HOLE TO SAVE A LIFE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES 3 COLOR PHOTOGRAPHS)
</P>
<P>
   It's natural for developing infants to have a small opening in
their heart while in the womb and as newborns. The hole is
considered harmless because it typically closes in the first few
days after birth. But it often doesn't in premature babies. An
experimental device and procedure being performed in Augusta, Ga.,
is aiming to treat the condition. (Includes 4-column color photo of
child who underwent procedure along with family, a 1-column photo
of surgeon performing procedure and a 6-pica detail photo of device
used in procedure)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: END OF LIFE: Death does not come easily to doctors.
Inevitable as it is in their line of work, it flies in the face of
their training, purpose, even their egos. But many social and
technological issues are forcing doctors to add end-of-life care to
their purview of prevention and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COLUMN: My studies show that if you don't like a study,
just wait a while. Another study will come along to say just the
opposite.
</P>
