<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3598 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-DiMAGGIO-APPRECIA     03-09 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DiMAGGIO-APPRECIATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES KEEP THE YANKEE CLIPPER GOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?
</P>
<P>
   I don't have the connections to find out the answer. All I have
are my hopes and prayers. This is what I hope. This is what I pray.
</P>
<P>
   That DiMaggio is in a place where he is forever young on the
outside, with a lifetime's worth of wisdom on the inside. I can
close my eyes and see DiMaggio standing tall and regal in Yankee
pinstripes, with no ache in his bones or his heart. I can see him
in full glide at the crack of the bat, his legs carrying him across
the vast, old Yankee Stadium outfield as fast as he needs to go.
</P>
<P>
   I see October and afternoon shadows. I see _ in grainy
black-and-white _ DiMaggio at the plate, the bases loaded. The
count is full. The game is in the balance. DiMaggio is at the plate
with his wide stance and supple wrists, No. 5 on his back. There is
no place to put him. Here comes the pitch ...I see into the night.
DiMaggio is wearing a tailored suit and walking hand-in-hand with
the love of his life. Free at last from mourning the loss of
Marilyn Monroe, he allows himself a toothy, uninhibited smile.
Would he explain to her why he sent roses to her grave week after
week, year after year?
</P>
<P>
   None of your business. None of my business. None of anybody's
business.
</P>
<P>
   I see Joseph Paul DiMaggio safe at home. For good. No more
awkward moments with strangers. No more impertinent questions from
nosy people. This is what I hope. This is what I pray.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio died early Monday morning. Cancer and pneumonia must be
so proud of themselves, picking a fight with an 84-year-old man.
What a knock-down, drag-out battle it turned out to be. He'd take
the reading of the last rites as his cue to defy death a little
longer. At one point, a doctor adjusting a breathing tube in
DiMaggio's throat got a quick earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get the hell out of here,'' DiMaggio said, ``and go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, DiMaggio got his way. Just as DiMaggio did upon
coming out of a coma and discovering that the world had been
getting up-to-the-minute updates on his condition. He angrily told
his doctors to keep their mouths shut, and that was that. He got
out of the hospital in January, after a 99-day stay, and spent the
rest of his days at home. Quietly. Privately.
</P>
<P>
   For those who had never seen DiMaggio play, it provided a hint
of the will that it took for the son of Italian immigrants _ the
eighth of nine children _ to become an American icon and a defining
figure of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Joltin' Joe. The Yankee Clipper. Mr. Coffee.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cruel cultural jokes of the 20th century is that far
more people saw DiMaggio pitching coffee makers than saw him
roaming center field at Yankee Stadium. Clearly, there was more to
DiMaggio than his Hall of Fame resume could ever capture. Something
besides numbers moved Ernest Hemingway to rhapsodize about DiMaggio
in ``The Old Man and the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Something besides numbers compelled Richard Rodgers and Oscar
Hammerstein to write the following lyrics in ``South Pacific'':
``Bloody Mary is the girl I love. ... Her skin is as tender as
DiMaggio's glove.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio played 13 seasons, batting .325, with 361 home runs and
1,537 runs batted in. He won the American League's MVP award three
times. His team won 10 pennants and nine World Series. He had the
56-game hitting streak. He was the first $100,000 ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   And to think, DiMaggio was so unsophisticated when he arrived in
the majors that he once acknowledged: ``I can remember a reporter
asking for a quote, and I didn't know what a quote was. I thought
it was some kind of soft drink.''
</P>
<P>
   There were better hitters, better base runners, better defensive
center fielders than DiMaggio. Yet DiMaggio carried the vote in
1969 when a panel decided to anoint ``The Greatest Living
Ballplayer.'' During his later years, DiMaggio would not appear at
public functions unless assured he would be introduced as such.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who weren't around when DiMaggio played will just
have to take it from Connie Mack, who managed more games than
anybody in major-league history: ``As one of nine men, DiMaggio is
the best player who ever lived.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who weren't around then will just have to take it on
the authority of Hall-of-Famer Yogi Berra: ``He was the perfect
ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who weren't around then will have to take the word
of Ted Williams: ``I really in my heart think he was the greatest
player I ever saw. ... He made it look so easy, so good. Never saw
him look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Witness after witness would marvel at the DiMaggian elegance and
grace. He played center field the way Clark Gable played Rhett
Butler. DiMaggio lost three years of his prime fulfilling military
service obligations in World War II. What could he have done at
ages 28, 29, and 30? What could he have done if he hadn't played
half his games in a stadium that was Death Valley to right-handed
pull hitters?
</P>
<P>
   Left center at Yankee Stadium was 457 feet from home plate
during DiMaggio's day. Dead center was 461 feet. Right center was
407. Home run after home run wound up in somebody's glove. DiMaggio
batted .315 with 148 homers at home. He batted .333 with 213 homers
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Joe DiMaggio would have played in any ballpark except
Yankee Stadium,'' Mickey Mantle used to say, ``he would have hit
over 500 easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of DiMaggio's career, somebody asked why he still
pushed himself so hard and demanded so much of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' DiMaggio said, ``there might be somebody in the
stands who hasn't seen me play before.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio retired when he knew his skills had diminished, even
though the Yankees happily would have continued to pay him his
six-figure salary. Having conquered one national pastime, he took
on another in 1954 by marrying Marilyn Monroe. She broke off from
their honeymoon in Japan to perform for U.S. troops in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never heard such cheering,'' Marilyn told him afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have,'' DiMaggio said.
</P>
<P>
   Their marriage lasted less than a year. Still, DiMaggio never
seemed to get her out of his system. Rumors of a re-marriage were
floating when she died in 1962. DiMaggio made the funeral
arrangements and barred people he deemed as unfit influences _
Frank Sinatra and Peter Lawford, to name two _ from attending. For
the next two decades, DiMaggio sent fresh roses to her grave three
times a week.
</P>
<P>
   People knew better than to interrogate DiMaggio about his
feelings for Marilyn. Even as the culture went the way of Barbara
Walters and Jerry Springer, DiMaggio remained zealously private. He
was one of the last of a breed that is dying too fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
