<SLUG> BC-ARTICHOKE-WINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ARTICHOKE FIGHTS WITH WINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Conn.)   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Artichokes can play a nasty trick on the palate. Some people
find that anything they eat or drink after tasting one seems sweet.
Not such a terrible side effect, perhaps, but it can be a nightmare
for sommeliers. An artichoke can make an elegant white wine seem
tinny and cloying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to pair with wines,'' said Doug Washington, a
managing partner and a wine director at Jardiniere in San
Francisco. ``You fumble, you really do fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington encourages people to try Champagne because, he said,
its acidity goes better with artichokes than buttery flavors.
(Chardonnays, for instance, are to be avoided.) Or he will pair the
wine not with the artichoke but with its sauce, hoping that that
flavor bond will overpower the sweetening effect.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Stone, the wine director at Rubicon in San Francisco,
relies on lean white wines from France, particularly Quincy, that
are ``mean'' and aggressively acidic to cut through the sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   He has also found that it helps if the artichoke is young and
has been cooked with some kind of acid _ wine, vinegar or citrus.
</P>
<P>
   Few studies have been done on the subject, but one performed in
1972 by Linda Bartoshuk, a professor at the Yale University School
of Medicine, found that cynarin, an organic compound in artichokes,
is the cause of this reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Cynarin inhibits sweet receptors on the tongue. When it is
rinsed away with liquid, the inhibiting effect is released and the
taste cell misinterprets that as a stimulus. ``The brain gets a
barrage of messages from the sweet receptors, but all you have in
fact in your mouth is water,'' Dr. Bartoshuk said. Or wine.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to cynarin appears to be genetic and, she said,
more prevalent in women.
</P>
<P>
   For now, as long as people hanker for artichokes, sommeliers are
left to sweat it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
