<SLUG> BC-ARTICHOKE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THE MIST, THE ARTICHOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Calif. _ Standing at the edge of the jagged cliffs
that run along Highway 1, you can hear the violence down below, the
powerful Pacific shattering itself on the rocky shoreline. But what
you feel is gentleness, a light briny mist that suffuses the air.
</P>
<P>
   This is the rough-hewn far edge of America that has drawn
painters and movie makers, surfers and tourists. But it is also, as
it turns out, the domain of the artichoke, which flourishes in the
mild mist here _ particularly in the stretch just north of Santa
Cruz _ as it does nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The land is covered with the lush, green bushy plants, a shag
rug that stops just where the land drops off into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Steve Bontadelli, a man with meaty hands and a handlebar
mustache, tends 400 acres of the thistle plants. ``The old-timers
say in April you can grow an artichoke on a telephone pole here,''
Bontadelli said as he drove a two-and-a-half-ton flatbed truck
through his fields.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for growers like Bontadelli, that hasn't been the
case lately. In the 1990s, the artichoke crops in California _
where almost all artichokes in the United States are grown _ have
been pounded to bits like the waves on the shore below.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Bontadelli's fields were hit with frost. In 1995, a
tornado ripped through, flattening the plants like pancakes. Then
in 1998, rains from El Nino _ which artichoke growers refer to as
``the N-word'' _ drowned the roots.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 crop promises to be different. In fact it looks as if
this just might be one of those Aprils. In a harvest that began in
late February, the artichokes are already coming in bountifully.
And when artichokes are good, they are glorious.
</P>
<P>
   The large-petaled bulb that is eaten is actually the plant's
flower bud. It is as dense as a potato, nutty and sweet, a flavor
both unique and perplexing. And though you can buy artichokes all
year round, none compare to the ones harvested in the cool, dewy
spring months.
</P>
<P>
   The abundance is all thanks to a light frost the day before
Christmas, which set the plant's buds. Then a long, cool winter
with temperatures never much lower than 40 degrees or higher than
60 allowed the buds to develop slowly, making them meaty and
succulent.
</P>
<P>
   The plant itself is stunningly beautiful, with large silvery
green leaves that spout up from the base like a fountain. A single
plant can cover 45 square feet in a field. What space it demands in
the field, though, the artichoke makes up for in generosity to the
cook.
</P>
<P>
   Every artichoke plant offers three different-size buds. A single
large one that can be as large as a coconut forms on the central
stem; a handful of medium ones grow around it, and almost a dozen
small artichokes, the size of a lime, form around the base.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that the first artichokes grown in California
were brought from Spain or Italy and raised in mission gardens. As
the immigrant population grew in the 19th century, so did the
variety of crops. ``This whole coast was old Italian guys,''
Bontadelli said of the farmers sprinkled through the area.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of artichoke growing is about 40 miles south of
Bontadelli's land, in the coastal region of the Salinas Valley.
There, the air smells of artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the property in the area was originally Spanish land
grants, and descendants rented it out to farmers. In Castroville,
Andrew Molera, one such descendant, owned a large portion of the
arable land and rented it to sugar beet growers for decades. But
early in the 20th century, when the sugar beet market declined, the
Moleras sought other crops with more stable markets.
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes were still a fairly small industry, but they were
grown near San Francisco and sold in the city's produce markets.
Andrew Molera thought they would be a profitable crop and pushed
for farmers to grow them in Castroville. The first commercial
fields were planted in the Salinas Valley's loamy river-sediment
soil in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't stopped since. Castroville, where 75 percent of all
California artichokes are grown, now calls itself the artichoke
capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The number of farmers dwindled from about 60 in the 1960s to
about 10, and the Molera family slowly sold off its land. Today,
California artichokes are grown either by descendants of the
original families or by the Dole Food Co.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, two groups of small farmers banded together,
forming Sea Mist Farms and Associated Produce Distributors, so they
could share their packing and shipping operations and be more
competitive. But they didn't change how they grew their artichokes
and harvested them, and those tasks are still done as they have
been for hundreds of years: by hand.
</P>
<P>
   The green globe artichoke, the most common variety, can be grown
only from cuttings and does not yield to the methodical motions of
an insensible harvesting machine. Its buds can appear on any part
of the plant. They must be discovered by eye and cut off with the
swipe of a knife.
</P>
<P>
   One small grower, the Leonardini family, has been raising
artichokes for four generations. ``We are the survivors,'' said
Tony Leonardini, 54. He began working on his father's 125 acres in
Castroville when he was a teen-ager. He grew up with the growers
who are now his partners in Associated Produce Distributors, as
well as with his competitors in Sea Mist Farms.
</P>
<P>
   Driving through his fields _ he now has 500 acres _ Leonardini
reminisced about playing football in high school with youths from
other farming families and going out at night with them to shoot
gophers in the artichoke fields. They still stick together. When El
Nino's rains wiped out a neighbor's crop, everyone donated cuttings
to get him back on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But competition is beginning to seep in from outside
Castroville's serene agricultural oasis. Agricultural researchers
have developed artichokes that can be grown from seed. Unlike the
globe _ which is finicky about climate and requires careful
cultivation to preserve the rootstock _ seed varieties will grow
anywhere, even in the desert, and practically any time.
</P>
<P>
   To Traci des Jardins, the chef at Jardiniere in San Francisco,
the flavors of the seed varieties ``are not as intense and they're
more watery.'' She won't use them at all.
</P>
<P>
   Seed varieties have a smaller heart and are often pale in
flavor. They also tend to fall apart after cooking, and if
overcooked at all, Ms. des Jardins said, ``they turn to absolute
mush.''
</P>
<P>
   That the best artichokes are still grown in and around
Castroville is no accident. The Leonardinis and other small growers
have kept their business exclusive. As Leonardini put it, ``If you
were Howard Hughes and said you wanted to go into the artichoke
business, and you needed to buy some cuttings from a grower, I
don't think you could find that grower.''
</P>
<P>
   So outsiders went elsewhere: the lab.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for growers of the globe artichoke lies with
retailers, few of whom mark the name of the variety on their
display bins. Even fewer consumers can detect a difference, before
the artichokes are on the table.
</P>
<P>
   But there are clues: most seed varieties do not have thorns on
the ends of the petals like those on a globe. Globes flood the
market from March through May, then follow with a small second
season in October.
</P>
<P>
   They're now selling for as little as 69 cents each in Manhattan;
growers expect the price to drop even more as the season
progresses. The seed varieties are in the market mainly during the
globe's off-season.
</P>
<P>
   In early spring in Castroville, when the globe seems invincible,
Leonardini's fields in the flat Salinas Valley are flush with
healthy plants and dotted with groups of workers.
</P>
<P>
   With vinyl baskets latched on like backpacks, the workers waddle
down the rows, their heads barely visible in the sea of bushy
plants. As they swipe off an artichoke, they toss it into the air
like a tennis ball and keep on moving, heads bowed, so it drops
ever so gently into the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Because the artichokes on each plant mature at different rates,
each field is harvested once a week. The large central artichoke is
the first to go. The medium ones are usually ready about a week
later, the small ones a week after that. The small ones _ often
called baby artichokes _ are not actually babies at all. They, too,
are mature; they simply never grow bigger.
</P>
<P>
   After a field has been harvested, the workers prune the plants
to the base and give the trimmings to a local dairy farmer to feed
his cows. Because the plant is a perennial, it will regrow the next
year. Most growers keep plants 5 to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In late February, the artichokes in Leonardini's field were
heavy and firm, with thick, rubbery leaves. He held up what
appeared to be a perfect specimen. Then he pointed out a small
black hole. In this case, it wasn't pesky weather, but the plume
moth, that was the invader.
</P>
<P>
   He tore off leaf after leaf riddled with black holes carved by
the moth, which is but one of the plant's enemies. (Mice and
gophers are some others.) ``That sucker,'' he said, ``he'll go all
the way to the center and just munch.''
</P>
<P>
   The pests are what has kept his farm from going organic. ``If I
could go out and not put a chemical on my field and grow a crop
that is profitable,'' Leonardini said, ``I could make more money.''
But, he added, ``who is going to set aside the ground for two years
to get it certified organic?''
</P>
<P>
   Other growers are finding ways. Bontadelli, for instance, who
relies on other crops for part of his income, has set aside a few
plots for the University of California at Santa Cruz to experiment
with organic techniques.
</P>
<P>
   It may be up to future generations to make the transition.
Driving past a neighbor's field, Leonardini slowed to say hello to
Mike Scattini, a son of his partner. Scattini was reporting on the
progress of the fields by cellular phone, but he was growing those
artichokes the same way his family has for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still ask Mike to go on his property,'' Leonardini said.
``It's just common courtesy, even though I used to change his
diapers.''
</P>
<P>
   He sighed, then added: ``It's sometimes difficult to let them do
what they want to do. It's a changing of the guard that we have
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But he does. Because the artichoke, an ancient, succulent
delight, is too precious to lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
