<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST KITCHEN: PERFECT ZEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks like a bird balancing on its belly. A black rubber
handle is its body, and a curved amber plastic shaft is its
outstretched neck. Nothing gives a clue to its clever function. But
if you hold it in your palm, neck upward, and glide the tip
backward over an orange, an amazing thing happens: a perfect strip
of zest, with no pith attached, begins pulling away from the fruit.
And you barely need to apply pressure.
</P>
<P>
   This zester has a second feature, too. On the inside curve of
the shaft is a thin fin of plastic. If you run it along an orange
vertically, and connect the slits, you can easily remove the peel
in sections.
</P>
<P>
   This odd little implement was created last year by Mastrad in
Paris. The design is based on a tool that jam factories use for
peeling oranges, said Mathieu Lion, the president of the company.
It was simply made more ergonomic for home cooks.
</P>
<P>
   And though it has but two uses _ one of them rarely needed _ it
performs so perfectly that it's worth adding to the gadget drawer.
Then, when you're in the mood for a martini, you can marvel at the
perfect curl of lemon bobbing up and down in your drink.
</P>
<P>
   The citrus zester is $7 at Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560 Broadway (Prince
Street), in New York; (212) 431-1691.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3620 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDFLOWERS-TEXAS-HNS     03-09 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDFLOWERS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWER-WATCHERS SINGING THE BLUEBONNET BLUES IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nature has raised the curtain early on Texas' annual
springtime wildflower extravaganza. But even as roadsides burst
into bloom with Indian paintbrush, yellow-petaled coreopsis and
bluebonnets, experts worry that the season will be feeble and
short.
</P>
<P>
   Flower-watchers within a 100-mile radius of Houston report that
bluebonnets and other spring bloomers like golden wave, paintbrush
and evening primrose, are appearing in pastures around Cuero,
Yoakum and Brenham. To the northeast in Woodville, flowering trees
like redbud and dogwood are starting to show their colors.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina jessamine and some violets have been spotted in the Big
Thicket, and, farther afield, rangers at Big Bend National Park
have reported patches of verbena and mustard.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, blossoms have appeared weeks before they normally
would be expected, and in towns where flower tourism is an economic
factor, chamber of commerce officials have heralded the early
blooms with glee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warm weather is just popping them out,'' said Deloris
Gause, president of the Yoakum Garden Club. ``They should peak in a
week or so. Evening primrose, golden wave, bluebonnets _ there is
lots of variety in flowers around here, but those predominate.''
</P>
<P>
   But some plant experts take a darker view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bluebonnets are coming up early,'' said Texas A&AMP;M
University biologist Hugh Wilson. ``But that may be a stress
response. They seem a little stunted. I have a feeling that, for
the short term, this will not be one of our better springs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who has studied native plants for two decades, said last
year's wet fall seemed ``maximal'' for bluebonnets and other winter
annuals. The plants germinated on schedule, set out wreaths of
leaves known as ``rosettes'' and were ``chugging along'' in
preparation for a March bloom, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened, though,'' he said, ``is that January and
February have been remarkably dry. The business of flowering and
doing reproductive things has been inhibited by lack of water. It's
just kind of suppressing the entire operation.''
</P>
<P>
   At Houston's George Bush Intercontinental Airport, only 2.2
inches of rainfall were recorded during those months _ 3.3 inches
below average. No rainfall has been recorded this month.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Marks, senior naturalist at the Houston Arboretum and Nature
Center, suggested the dry spring is only the latest in a series of
climatic events that have hurt plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were exceptionally dry last summer, then exceptionally wet
in the fall, and now we're a little drier than normal,'' she said.
``Separately, each of these things can be harmful; together they
can be devastating. We lost a lot of mature woody plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Wilson's wildflowers, Marks' stressed trees have
compensated by ``putting on extra heavy blooms and put on extra
seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Without rainfall, though, she predicted, some summer-blooming,
daisy-like plants may not make a show at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson may be,'' she said, ``that people need to see the
wildflowers now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of rain definitely is a stress factor,'' said Dee
Howell, Houston's senior horticulture superintendent, who
supervises Memorial Park's wildflower plantings. ``It's an early
season, but it could be short.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the flowers just dehydrate and don't pollinate and make
seed,'' she said, ``it won't eliminate the plantings, but it will
really knock them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Dry conditions also have prevailed elsewhere in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Roadsides in the Texas Hill Country are ``a little parched,''
said Patricia Alholm, spokeswoman for the Austin-based Lady Bird
Johnson Wildflower Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too late for a little rain to help native plants
out,'' Alholm said. ``There are two scenarios in which we can pull
through. One is that we get a little rain. The other is that things
cool off and stay in that holding pattern until we get our spring
rains. Central Texas gets the majority of its rain in April and May
and a couple of months in the fall. In a couple of weeks, we should
know what the season will bring.''
</P>
<P>
   In good years, fields of bluebonnets _ known as ``buffalo
clover'' until pioneer women noted the blossoms' resemblance to
miniature sunbonnets _ cover thousands of acres in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-eight years ago this month, the Texas Legislature
designated one species of the plant, ``Lupinus subarnosus,'' as the
state flower. That designation was expanded to at least four other
bluebonnet species in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The highway department began sowing bluebonnet seeds along Texas
highways in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
