<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMON-ZEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF A LEMON LOVER IN A SEASON OF PLENTY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA KAFKA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there is one idiosyncratic hallmark of my cooking,
it is the plentiful use of lemon juice and lemon zest. As a child,
I always loved unsweetened lemonade, and now, when asked what might
improve a dish, my response is frequently, ``Lemon!'' Both the
juice and the zest give a fresh edge to food, adding a welcome
acidity to some dishes, and a tart sweetness to others.
</P>
<P>
   The zest is not the entire rind or peel, but the thin outer
yellow layer, with none of the underlying white pith attached. Zest
is aptly named, as it has a complex flavor with a slight bitterness
provided by the oils in the rind. Those who do not like this
bitterness can reduce it a bit by blanching the zest for a minute
or so and then running it under cold water.
</P>
<P>
   While there are plenty of devices on the market that will take
off thin strips of the fruit, I don't use one. I find the
traditional four-holed zester inefficient, as it leaves much of the
zest behind. Most zesters also cut the fruit in slivers of uniform
size, and there are many times when I want broader strips to add to
a stew or to chop for other uses. Of course, you could also use a
grater, but once again you leave lots of lemon behind, this time on
the grater.
</P>
<P>
   I use a sharp vegetable peeler, which removes zest easily and
provides 10 to 12 strips, two inches long and a half inch wide, per
lemon. For thinner strips, halve the strips crosswise, stack two or
three and, using a sharp knife, cut them lengthwise; repeat with
remaining strips.
</P>
<P>
   It is always a good idea to give lemons a light scrub with a
vegetable brush under running water before peeling, as they may
have been coated with a preservative to protect them during
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Though lemons are a year-round crop these days, ripe, juicy
lemons from Florida are coming into stores in New York right now,
so it is time for lemon lovers to pounce. A good lemon has no bumps
on its skin and feels heavy with juice. I freeze fresh juice in an
ice-cube tray, using two tablespoons for each cube. After the juice
is frozen, the cubes can be popped out and kept in a plastic sack
in the freezer. This is a particularly nice trick for Meyer lemons
and Key limes, as these fruits are in season for such a short time;
stock up when you can, then enjoy the juice for months afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   To use the frozen juice in uncooked dishes _ in salad dressings,
for instance _ simply let the cubes come to room temperature first.
I never heat them to defrost them, but it is perfectly all right to
pop a frozen cube into a dish that has almost finished cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, both lemon juice and zest are called for in the same
recipe, as they are in the two here. Take the zest off the whole
fruit, then slice and squeeze the juice out. The creamy lemon pasta
dish makes a light first course and can be tossed with some cooked
asparagus tips, peas or even shrimp. It would also be good as a
side dish with broiled fish or roast chicken. The zest infuses the
cream with lemon flavor, and the dish is so quick to assemble that
the cream never gets a chance to curdle.
</P>
<P>
   The lemon wafers are good on their own or as an accompaniment to
fresh fruit or sorbet. They look like old-fashioned vanilla wafers
but have a little surprise _ that little nip that we lemon lovers
can't do without.
</P>
<P>
   CREAMY LEMON PASTA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces wide egg noodles
</P>
<P>
   Zest and juice of 2 lemons; zest cut in very thin strips 1 inch
long
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Lots of freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add noodles, and
stir to separate. Cook for 8 minutes or until tender. Drain, then
return to the cooking pot.
</P>
<P>
   2. Just before noodles are done, in a small saucepan combine the
lemon zest, cream, salt and pepper. Cook over medium heat for 2
minutes, or until cream comes to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour cream mixture over drained noodles, and add the lemon
juice. Stir to coat. Cook over medium heat, stirring, until all the
liquid is absorbed, about 1 to 2 minutes. Season with additional
pepper, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON WAFERS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   { cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, cut in 1-inch pieces, plus more
for buttering cookie sheets
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon strained fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1. In a food processor, combine sugar and lemon zest. Process
until zest is finely minced, about 1 minute. Stop the machine, and
scrape down sides of bowl with a rubber spatula. Add butter, and
process until creamy, about 20 seconds. With processor running, add
egg whites. Continue to process, adding flour (1 tablespoon at a
time), salt, vanilla and lemon juice. Process until a thick batter
is formed. Scrape into a small bowl, and stir to combine
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a rack in center of oven, and heat to 400 degrees.
While oven is heating, let batter sit at room temperature, about 15
minutes. Butter and flour 2 cookie sheets.
</P>
<P>
   3. Drop rounded teaspoons of batter on prepared baking sheets,
and bake for about 8 minutes, or until edges are golden brown.
Remove at once to a cooling rack.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 3 dozen cookies.
</P>
</TEXT>
