<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: UNDISCOVERED, AFFORDABLE BURGUNDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you love Burgundy and you know the region well.
Gevrey-Chambertin, Morey-St.-Denis, Beaune, Volnay _ you're
familiar with them all. OK, ever heard of Marey-les-Fussey? Or
Magny-les-Villers, or Meloisey?
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel bad if you haven't; hardly anyone in this country
has. At least not yet. They are little villages in the region known
as the Hautes Cotes, an area the wine critic Robert Parker Jr. has
called the backwoods of Burgundy. If your idea of the backwoods is
rundown farms and rusted cars, forget it; the Hautes Cotes
(pronounced OAT coat) is rural and quiet but beautiful country. And
it produces some attractive Burgundy wines.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, the great wine towns of Burgundy are known as the
Cote-d'Or, or the golden slopes. The northern half of the Cote-d'Or
is called the Cotes de Nuits and the southern half the Cotes de
Beaune. The Hautes Cotes region, which lies to the west of the
well-known vineyards, is divided in the same way, into the Hautes
Cotes de Beaune and the Hautes Cotes de Nuits.
</P>
<P>
   The name means, literally, the high slopes, and in fact most of
the approximately 2,500 acres of Hautes Cotes vineyards are at an
elevation of 1,000 to 1,500 feet, well above the height of the
famous vineyards of the Cote-d'Or.
</P>
<P>
   There have been vineyards in the Hautes Cotes at least since the
17th century, when they were said to cover some 11,000 acres. Most
were abandoned after a phylloxera blight ravaged them in the late
19th century. Not until after World War II did the demand for
Burgundy wine prompt growers to take another look at this
once-productive area in what amounted to their back yard.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1950s, the price of vineyard land in the Cote-d'Or
had encouraged some winemakers to return to these hidden valleys
and villages, many of them little more than a 15-minute drive from
the bustling towns of Nuits-St.-Georges and Beaune. By 1961, both
the Hautes Cotes de Beaune and the Hautes Cotes de Nuits were
awarded the coveted appellation controllee designation, which meant
that the French government considered them to be among the
country's better wines.
</P>
<P>
   I first visited the Hautes Cotes some years ago with Jean-Claude
Vrinat, the owner of the Taillevent restaurant in Paris and a
passionate wine enthusiast who spends his rare days off prowling
the vineyards of France seeking additions for his incomparable
cellar. We drove up from Beaune to Magny-les-Villers to visit the
cellars of Robert Jayer-Gilles, one of the best-known winemakers in
the Hautes Cotes.
</P>
<P>
   Jayer-Gilles is related to the many Jayers who make wine in
Burgundy, including Henri Jayer of Vosne-Romanee, one of Burgundy's
most respected producers. Like Henri, who is now retired,
Jayer-Gilles is best known for his Echezeaux from the Cote de Nuits
area. But knowledgeable wine lovers, like Vrinat, also treasure his
wines from the Hautes Cotes, both red and white, which have set
admirably high standards for other winemakers in the region.
</P>
<P>
   A common complaint about wines from the Hautes Cotes is that
they lack depth. Because the vineyards are at a higher altitude,
Hautes Cotes grapes do not always ripen as quickly as grapes in the
Cote-d'Or. Jayer-Gilles and winemakers like him compensate by
keeping vineyard yields low. Fewer grapes means more intensive
wines and, at their best, Jayer-Gilles wines show all the intensity
of wines from much more famous Burgundy vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   In almost the same class are the Hautes Cotes de Nuits Clos du
Vignon wines of the Domaine Thevenot le Brun in the village of
Marey-les-Fussey. The Thevenot wines include a delicious pinot
gris, a pleasant change from chardonnay. Thevenot is owned by the
Domaine Antonin Guyon in Savigny-les Beaune, and some of the Hautes
Cotes de Nuits wines appear in this country under the Guyon label.
</P>
<P>
   The Domaine Mongeard-Mugneret in Vosne-Romanee is another
estimable Burgundy maker that turns out limited quantities of a
good Hautes Cotes de Nuits. Michel Gros of the Domaine Jean Gros,
also in Vosne Romanee, is another mainstream Burgundy producer who
turns out good, concentrated wines from the Hautes Cotes de Nuits.
</P>
<P>
   Look, too, for the Hautes Cotes de Beaune from Francois and
Denis Clair, and a somewhat lighter style wine from the same
appellation made by the Domaine Arnoux Pere &AMP; Fils in
Chorey-les-Beaune. One of the best-known estates is Denis Carre at
Meloisey, in the Hautes Cotes de Nuits. Denis Carre also owns
vineyards in Pommard, Auxey-Duresses and Meursault in the Cote de
Beaune.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers less inclined to venture off the main roads, the
growers of the Hautes Cotes maintain a cooperative called Les Caves
des Hautes Cotes on the highway between Beaune and Pommard, to the
south. The coop makes and sells about 25 percent of all the wine
from the two Hautes Cotes appellations.
</P>
<P>
   The best wines of the Hautes Cotes are the reds, made from the
pinot noir grape. The whites, mostly chardonnay, tend to be lean
and are not usually as good buys as some of the less expensive
white Burgundies from the Cote-d'Or.
</P>
<P>
   Wines from the Hautes Cotes are still scarce in this country,
partly because importers are unfamiliar with them and partly
because they are only at their best in years when an abundance of
sun and heat give them that extra bit of intensity they need.
</P>
<P>
   But when they are good _ and both the 1996s and 1997s are good
vintages _ they are bargains: Most are in the $15 to $20 range.
</P>
<P>
   Jayer-Gilles Hautes-Cotes wines cost more, usually in the $25 to
$30 range, at least in part because they are always made in
expensive new oak barrels. The Hautes Cotes may be the back woods,
but at Jayer-Gilles, they are the back woods of Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some wines from the Hautes Cotes region of Burgundy
that are worth seeking out.
</P>
<P>
   HAUTES COTES DE BEAUNE
</P>
<P>
   Reine Pedauque, 1996. About $17.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau de Beaune, 1996, Bouchard Pere &AMP; Fils. About $15.
</P>
<P>
   Arnoux, Pere &AMP; Fils, 1996. About $10.
</P>
<P>
   Francois &AMP; Denis Clair, 1993. About $15.
</P>
<P>
   HAUTES COTES DE NUITS
</P>
<P>
   Jayer-Gilles, 1994. About $27.
</P>
<P>
   Domaine Guyon, 1996. About $15.
</P>
<P>
   Mongeard-Mugneret, 1995. About $17.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Gros, 1993. About $16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
