<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTICHOKE-COOKING-ART     03-09 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTICHOKE-COOKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO TOUGH IN THE FIELD, SUCH A BREEZE IN THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It can seem like a nasty customer, tightly
closed and unyielding, more than forbidding enough to frighten off
a cook or two. But those who know the artichoke know just how to
slip past its defenses. That's especially true in San Francisco,
where artichokes are as familiar in restaurant kitchens as
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, the city's chefs say, is to keep it simple and don't
wear yourself out. A great artichoke doesn't need much work.
</P>
<P>
   At the Black Cat, a restaurant in North Beach, Reed Hearon
slices small artichokes into quarters and fries them in oil with
sliced fennel. The artichokes become crispy on the outside and stay
succulent on the inside; the fennel melts in your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   He also roasts artichokes like potatoes, trimming and quartering
medium ones, tossing them with olive oil, garlic and rosemary, and
roasting them at 500 degrees. The outer leaves curl and brown,
caramelizing the sugars, and the hearts soften.
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes can even be left raw. At Zuni Cafe, Judy Rodgers
thinly slices trimmed small artichokes _ leaves, heart and all _
and dresses them with lemon juice, olive oil, pine nuts and
Parmesan cheese. The hearts stay crunchy and sweet and the leaves
are like buttery soft petals on the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   A taste of just one of these dishes and you soon realize there
is no reason to be cutting artichoke hearts into cubes or pureeing
them into some fussy creation. An artichoke is a precious vegetable
with a preciously short season. It's best to make it easy on
yourself and leave it in its purest form.
</P>
<P>
   But before you begin cooking artichokes, it is important to buy
good ones. You want one that feels heavy for its size. Lift a few
in the pile and compare them. The artichoke should be firm and the
leaves tightly bound. If some of the leaves are streaked with black
lines, this isn't a sign of rotting, but of frost damage. It is a
cosmetic flaw and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get home and are faced with this hard, green bulb it is
difficult to know where to begin and even more difficult to part
with all that needs to be trimmed. ``You have to think of an
artichoke as a big spiny plant,'' said Traci des Jardins, the chef
at Jardiniere, ``and the leaves are part of that spiny plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as you trim the greens from the top of a carrot or the
outer leaves of a head of lettuce, so, too, the outer one or two
layers of leaves of an artichoke must go. This is especially
important when braising or cooking the artichoke whole, so that
none of the tough parts are left on it.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, with a large or medium artichoke, it's simply a
matter of cutting off the top, down to the point where the leaves
are tender _ where they are light green to butter yellow _ and
trimming the base and stem. Then, you can either use a spoon to
scoop out the fuzzy choke or cut the artichoke in half and cut out
the choke with a paring knife.
</P>
<P>
   With small artichokes, the choke is not usually developed enough
to remove. (As you trim artichokes, add them to a bowl of water
acidulated with lemon juice so they don't discolor.)
</P>
<P>
   If you want to try an artichoke in its purest form _ and the
form easiest to prepare _ boil it. Bring a large pot of salted
water to a boil. While it's heating, pull off any tough outer
leaves. Cut off the top, trim and peel the stem and rub cut parts
with lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Add the artichokes to the boiling water and simmer until tender,
about 30 to 35 minutes, depending on their size. An artichoke is
tender when a knife inserted near the heart of the choke offers no
resistance, or a leaf can be pulled out easily.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the water and let cool, petals downward, on a baking
rack, so the water drains out. You may want to squeeze them out a
little before serving. This is the best way to eat the first of the
season. Each person gets a whole artichoke. And he can attack it
any way he pleases _ pulling leaves off one by one and sucking off
the nugget of meat at the base, or forgoing the leaves altogether
and digging into the heart. The stem is edible, too.
</P>
<P>
   Dipping sauces are an item of debate. Real enthusiasts do not
approve of any. Others consider the artichoke merely a vehicle for
the sauce. A simple homemade mayonnaise or vinaigrette is a
reasonable and tasty compromise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   SHAVED ARTICHOKE SALAD WITH PINE NUTS AND PARMESAN CHEESE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Judy Rodgers, Zuni Cafe, San Francisco &QL; 
Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   10 small artichokes
</P>
<P>
   Juice of { lemon
</P>
<P>
   \ cup flat-leaf parsley leaves, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   { head radicchio, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup thin shavings of Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   1. One artichoke at a time, peel away outer leaves, leaving
tender pale green leaves. Cut off stem and spiny tops of leaves.
Cut artichoke in half lengthwise and remove fibrous choke. Slice
artichoke as thinly as possible and place in a bowl. Squeeze a few
drops of lemon juice over it and toss well. Repeat with remaining
artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add parsley, pine nuts and radicchio to bowl. Pour olive oil
over mixture and sprinkle with a little salt and pepper. Toss to
coat. Add cheese and toss gently. Taste for seasoning and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   FRITO MISTO OF ARTICHOKES AND FENNEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Reed Hearon, Black Cat restaurant, San Francisco &QL; 
Time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   12 small artichokes
</P>
<P>
   1 bulb fennel, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   \ cup thinly shaved Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts vegetable or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   { cup flour
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, cut into quarters
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt, to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Fill a large bowl with water, and add lemon juice. Peel away
outer leaves of artichokes, leaving tender pale green leaves. Peel
stems, and cut off spiny tops of leaves. Cut lengthwise into
quarters. Immediately add artichokes to water.
</P>
<P>
   2. Slice fennel bulb in half through the root. Slice each half
crosswise, about \ inch thick. Slices should be half-moon shapes.
Place fennel in a medium bowl, and set aside. In a small bowl,
combine cheese, garlic and parsley. Toss gently to mix.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large deep pan, heat oil over medium-low heat to 275
degrees. Drain artichokes, and dry completely with a dish towel.
Add artichokes to oil, and cook until they begin to open and brown.
Remove from pan, and let drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   4. Raise heat to medium-high or 350 degrees. Pour milk over
fennel, and place flour in a medium bowl. Strain fennel, then toss
lightly in flour to coat. Drop fennel and artichokes into oil, and
fry until golden brown and crispy. Using a strainer, remove from
oil and place on a plate lined with paper towels. Let drain for 30
seconds, then transfer to a large bowl. Sprinkle parsley mixture
and a little olive oil over artichoke mixture. Season with salt.
Toss briefly to combine ingredients. Transfer to a serving bowl or
platter, with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   ARTICHOKES A LA BARIGOULE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Traci des Jardins, Jardiniere restaurant, San
Francisco &QL; 
Time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   8 large artichokes
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, peeled and crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flat-leaf parsley leaves, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   1 white onion, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 bulb fennel, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, sliced on a bias, about \-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk celery, sliced on a bias, about \-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups chicken broth or water. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Fill a large bowl with water and add lemon juice. Peel the
dark green outer leaves from the artichokes and peel stem to remove
fibrous outer layer. Cut off spiny tops of leaves. Cut artichokes
lengthwise into quarters and remove chokes. Immediately add
artichokes to water.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large pot, warm olive oil over medium low heat. Add the
garlic, parsley stems, onion, fennel, carrots and celery. Season
lightly with salt and pepper. Gently cook vegetables until onions
are translucent but not brown, stirring frequently, about 10
minutes. Add white wine and cook until reduced by }.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add artichokes to pot and pour broth or water over them.
Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer, covered, until
artichokes are tender, offering no resistance when pierced with a
knife, about 35 minutes. Taste and adjust seasoning if necessary.
Discard parsley stems. Add whole parsley leaves to pot and wilt
slightly. Spoon artichokes and vegetables onto plates with a little
of the cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
