<P>
   COXNET-WHEELS 0305 _ The industry calls the Daewoo Lanos and
other cars in its class ``roller skates,'' meaning they're
generally small, sometimes peppy and almost always low-priced cars
targeting first-time buyers and those looking for basic, no-frills
transportation. Give Daewoo credit, though. The South Korean
builder reaches out to some prestigious sources _ primarily Italian
designer Porsche and General Motors, a former partner _ for help
designing and powering its lineup of cars. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box on the Daewoo Lanos.
</P>
<P>
   THE MECHANIC _ Once you have a battery that fits, you need to
determine its electrical capacity before you go ahead and connect
it correctly. It's a good idea to have knowledge of how a battery
is rated. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED _ ATLANTA _ Machinists union members at Lockheed Martin
Aeronautical Systems vote today on a revised contract proposal from
the company as a strike deadline nears. Some 4,200
Machinists-represented workers began voting before dawn. Results
expected late evening, only a few hours before the scheduled
walkout after midnight. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (a) general news and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   MCI-SCAM _ An alleged financial scam that defrauded MCI
Telecommunications Corp. and a number of banks out of more than $30
million is under investigation by federal authorities in Atlanta,
according to court documents filed recently in U.S. District Court.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLICY _ We are surveying a number of big Atlanta
employers to see what their policies are on giving employees
widespread Internet access. Some major companies have started to
restrict access because workers were spending hours surfing when
they should have been working. Among those surveyed: Coke,
BellSouth, Delta, Southern Co., Scientific Atlanta. (Kanell/Unger,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-BRAZIL _ BellSouth's big gamble in Brazil: Can its
wireless gambit ride out the economic crisis? Are the economic
problems taking an increasing toll on major companies doing
business there? A major competitor of BellSouth has announced its
telecommunications business is suffering. A look at the impact of
the economic troubles on BellSouth. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/BELLSOUTH-ANALYSIS _ BellSouth's international strategy; an
overview and an analyst's view. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTUIT-CHECKFREE _ A suit by Intuit against CheckFree, an
Internet transaction company, reveals details of a failed (?) deal
between CheckFree and Yahoo. We look to see what's interesting and
important in the case. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SEC-PROBE _ Peter Tosto, the mysterious Madison resident who was
connected with five small internet companies the stock trading of
which was frozen by the SEC, has been caught and disciplined
several times by the SEC and the Justice Department. However, he's
never spent time in jail and has paid little if any fines. Why? The
SEC has given him a letter of cooperation (meaning they're using
him as an informant). What does he know that's so valuable that he
can continue to set up allegedly sham companies over and over?
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING _ MindSpring in conjunction with knowledgy, to
provide cable modem service in several small southeastern markets.
Mindspring has said it would not let the advent of high speed
internet access stop it from growing. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NETBANK _ Net.Bnk has provided more than $100 million in
financing for home mortgages to consumers across the country during
the last six months of 1998, the bank announced recently. A look at
the growth in the number of homebuyers finding a mortage online.
Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CELLTOWER _ BellSouth pays $610 million to get out of the cell
tower business. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA _ Chattanooga officials expect to break ground in
October on a $43 million conference center that they hope will
attract business from Atlanta and other Southern cities within a
200-mile radius. (ABrice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-WORTH _ How do you determine what a business is worth?
We take a look at how business brokers size up the value of a
business. (Tyson, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-PROBLEMS _ Expect no Y2K cataclysm, but don't write-off the
millennium bug as a non-event. ``Nationally, there's a likelihood
of significant governmental services and utilities problems,'' said
Atlanta attorney Paul Arne. ``I am convinced that virtually every
large organization in the United States is going to experience some
Y2K problems.'' (Chambers, Atlanta Jornal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHARPDRIVING-COLUMN _ There may be some longtime Volvo die-hards
who see the corporate marriage with Ford as a potential
contamination of the Volvo heritage. My guess is that nothing could
be further from the truth. If Ford's track record with Jaguar and
Aston Martin is any indicator _ and there is no reason to think it
is not _ Ford will be more like a benevolent uncle than Big
Brother. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MECHANIC-COLUMN _ Mitch Schneider, an automotive writer for more
than 15 years, agreed that the consumer and the automotive industry
must come to some meeting of the minds. His article, ``Cognitive
Dissonance,'' appears in the January issue of MotorAge Magazine.
(http://www.motorage.com; click on Schneider's World) (Carter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ ATLANTA _ Here's a startling statistic: The Vanguard
Group of mutual funds netted more than $2 billion a week in new
investments last year. When you think about money moving that fast,
you expect the subject to be federal government spending, not
private investing. It indicates a lot of Americans have acted on
one of the basic lessons of successful investing: Lower costs mean
better returns. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
