<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIDOTE TO OVERSALTING 
RUBBERY SHIITAKES
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there an antidote to oversalting a dish?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are several, depending upon what sort of dish it is. In
most cases, stirring in some lemon juice or vinegar will help. If
the dish then tastes too tart, add a pinch or two of sugar as well.
</P>
<P>
   For soups, stews and ragouts, try adding chunks of peeled
potato, and then simmer the mixture until they are nearly tender,
about 15 minutes. The potatoes will absorb some of the excess salt
(remove them before serving the dish). A cup of rice or pasta, tied
up in cheesecloth, will also do the trick. Or, just add unsalted
chicken broth or vegetable broth or another unsalted liquid to
dilute the salty flavor, though this will give you a thinner
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't feel like dealing with the salty dish now, freeze
it for a few weeks. Once thawed and reheated, the salt flavor won't
be as pronounced because freezing dulls all flavors, especially
salty and spicy tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbery Shiitakes
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been using dried shiitake mushrooms to make a
wonderful soup from a Verbena restaurant recipe. Although I soak
the mushrooms for half an hour in hot water, they are rubbery and
tough when julienned. What am I doing wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. You may not be doing anything wrong; it could be the
mushrooms themselves. For the wild mushroom broth, Diane Forley,
the chef at Verbena, recommends fresh shiitake mushrooms if
possible for the most delicate flavor and best texture. Dried
shiitakes can be substituted, but they are always going to be a bit
more rubbery.
</P>
<P>
   When substituting dried mushrooms for fresh, use the best you
can find. Look for whole, firm mushrooms with no crumbling edges or
a deeply musty scent (they should smell fresh). Buy the mushrooms
from a reputable, busy store with a high turnover, since even dried
mushrooms can get too old. Take care to soak them for only the
prescribed time, and then don't overcook them once they are added
to the broth (this can intensify their chewy texture).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
