<SLUG> BC-DIET-GUIDELINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT'S DIETARY GUIDELINES COME UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Charging that federal dietary guidelines are biased
against minority groups, many of whose members are lactose
intolerant, a health organization called on the government Tuesday
to make its recommended daily intake of dairy products optional.
</P>
<P>
   The Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine, a nonprofit
group based here, said the government, which is now updating its
dietary recommendations, should take into account the food needs of
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dairy products should be considered optional and in no way
superior to other calcium sources such as green leafy vegetables,
beans and other legumes or fortified fruit juices,'' Dr. Neal
Barnard, a physician and the group's president, said at a news
conference. ``For many Americans, these are better choices than
cow's milk,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government currently recommends that Americans
consume two to three servings of dairy foods such as yogurt, cheese
and milk, which provide calcium for bone growth, each day. The
guidelines serve as the foundation for most school lunch programs
and virtually all other nutrition programs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But many people from minority groups cannot digest dairy
products, a condition known as lactose intolerance, which can
result in painful abdominal cramps, bloating and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Lactose intolerance occurs when a person's body no longer
produces enough of an enzyme known as lactase, which aids the
digestion of lactose, a milk sugar found in dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   According to the physicians group, as many as 70 percent of
African Americans, 70 percent of American Indians, 50 percent of
Hispanics and 95 percent of Asian Americans are lactose intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   This compares with about 15 percent of whites who suffer from
the condition.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Milton Mills, a physician and associate director of the
organization, charged that food guidelines advocating consumption
of dairy products reflect ``a profound racial bias.''
</P>
<P>
   But the top nutritionist at another medical advocacy
organization said the physicians group was taking ``an extremist
stance on milk and dairy products.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ruth Kava, director of nutrition for the New York-based
American Council on Science and Health, said that lactose-reduced
milk products are widely available and provide as much calcium as
regular dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Kava said that a dairy-rich diet can reduce high blood pressure
and prevent osteoporosis _ the loss of bone density _ later in
life. She said in a statement that ``to warn such people away from
valuable sources of calcium is to offer advice that is potentially
detrimental to their health.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Diary Council said that the physicians group
overstates the problem. While the council acknowledged that
minorities are more prone to lactose intolerance, it said that
gradually increasing one's intake of dairy products over time often
can eliminate the condition.
</P>
<P>
   Government revisions of the dietary guidelines are completed
every five years. An advisory committee consisting of officials
from the Departments of Agriculture and Health and Human Services
is scheduled to publish the new guidelines next January.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a snow storm in Washington, spokemen for the
Agriculture Department and HHS could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
