<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   SWEEPSTAKES _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate permanent investigations
subcommittee holds a hearing Tuesday on a bill related to deceptive
practices used in sweepstakes mailings. (Dart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EXPLORATORY _ WASHINGTON _ Everyone thinks Elizabeth Dole is
running for president, but she visits Iowa on Wednesday only to
announce that she's forming an ``exploratory committee.'' There are
legal and political reasons for the candidates' slow-motion
announcements. (Shepard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ Efforts by Microsoft and the Justice Department to
reach a settlement in the antitrust case are more likely to be made
in May after the rebuttal round, than now. Even so, at least one
newspaper, the Seattle Times, is speculating talks could begin
sooner. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   PENSION-REFORM _ Rob Portman is going to introduce a pension
reform bill that seeks to do a variety of things, such as making
401Ks more portable from job to job and creating a 'catch-up'
provision in IRA accounts so people can increase their
contributions as they get closer to retirement. This is one of
Portman's big things, and pension reform is also likely to be a big
piece of the puzzle pushed by the GOP in trying to rewrite Social
Security. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED _ ATLANTA _ Machinists union members at Lockheed Martin
Aeronautical Systems vote today on a revised contract proposal from
the company as a strike deadline nears. Some 4,200
Machinists-represented workers began voting before dawn. Results
expected late evening, only a few hours before the scheduled
walkout after midnight. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (a) general news and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAITIANS-PIERRE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hoping for interview
with Yvon Pierre-Louis, one of three survivors of a smuggling
mishap off South Florida's coast. About 40 are suspected dead from
the incident where two boats went under about 30 miles east of West
Palm Beach. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FAGAN-HEARING _ BOSTON _ Hearing in the case of Stephen Fagan,
the Palm Beacher accused of kidnapping his children years ago and
then setting up a double life. (Holland, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FLA-EVICTION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Few men are so defined by
location as sun-worn 67-year-old Clifton Lirette. When Lirette
first settled here 20 years ago, a sign across U.S. 27 read: ``Deem
City, Pop. 2.'' Then a fire destroyed the convenience store and
service station and, for practical purposes, Deem City ceased to
be. Yet Lirette remained at his remote outpost at the edge of the
Everglades in southwestern Palm Beach County, 100 yards from the
Broward line. Now the county wants Lirette to move himself off the
land. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post) 34 inches. MOVED.
</P>
