<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEEPSTAKES10-COX     03-09 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANGRY SENATORS THREATEN CRACKDOWN ON SWEEPSTAKES
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Angry senators warned operators of America's
best-known sweepstakes Tuesday that their industry may already be a
loser in a contest to avoid a congressional crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Publishers Clearing House, Reader's Digest,
American Family Enterprises, and Time Inc. defended practices such
as telling millions of potential sweepstakes players that ``it's
down to a 2 person race for $11 million,'' and they were one of the
lucky pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our promotions are clear and that no
reasonable person could be misled by them,'' said Deborah Holland,
senior vice president of Publishers Clearing House.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Governmental Affairs Committee's permanent
subcommittee on investigations were plainly peeved.
</P>
<P>
   Chairwoman Susan Collins, R-Maine, told the witnesses that she
was ``absolutely stunned'' by testimony that people who received
contest mailings would not be misled.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., called one letter with a personal tone
that Publishers Clearinghouse mailed to 9 million people ``a lie''
that was ``purposefully misleading, purposefully deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to correct this with or without support of
companies here with us today,'' he vowed.
</P>
<P>
   Levin proposed legislation that would require _ in type as big
as any on the page _ that making a purchase does not improve the
chances of winning. The same prominent disclaimer should also
disclose if a letter is computer-generated and the odds of winning
the contest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said she is ``gaining co-sponsors every day'' for
legislation that would regulate the mailings and impose stiff fines
for violations.
</P>
<P>
   The sweepstakes officials testified that most recipients of
their mass mailings understand that they don't have to subscribe to
a magazine or buy a sponsored product in order to enter the contest
and that their odds of winning are not enhanced by making a
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The officials denied targeting elderly people, and said the
contests have internal programs to find the few customers who don't
understand the rules and might be making excessive purchases in
their efforts to win.
</P>
<P>
   Sweepstakes are used ``to attract attention to mailings amidst
an extremely cluttered mailbox'' and to ``raise interest in the
product being promoted,'' explained Naomi Bernstein, vice president
of marketing services for American Family Enterprises, a consortium
of magazine publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of our mailings is not to convince people they've
won a sweepstakes, but rather to be excited about the possibility
of winning and to consider our products,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing horror stories on Monday(cq) about confused
elderly consumers spending thousands of dollars on unneeded
products in vain attempts to win the sweepstakes, senators
countered that the contests were clearly deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   They displayed a ``Dear Eustace Hall'' letter from Publishers
Clearing House in which Contest Manager Dorothy Addeo wrote that
her boss came into her office to say, ``It's not right when someone
as nice as Eustace Hall doesn't win.'' Addeo promised a prize if
Hall would just ``return the Guaranteed Winner Document.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying on Monday, Hall broke down in tears and said he
thought the message was a personal one. On Tuesday, Holland said
Publishers Clearing House had sent the same letter to 9 million
people _ each the subject of a conversation between ``Dorothy'' and
her boss.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the purposed conversation ``a dramatization,'' Holland
said ``of course'' no company officials had actually talked about
Eustace Hall or any other individual contestant. However, she
denied that the letter was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee members expressed outrage over the letter and other
sweepstakes promotions. They decried bulletins with headlines that
scream ``You're a winner'' and tiny type that says ``if you have
the winning number.'' They blasted complex rules that make it easy
to enter if the contestant subscribes to a magazine, but
discouragingly hard if no purchase if made.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not need a law degree or a magnifying glass to
read the rules or to decipher how to enter without placing an
order,'' said Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., said he was disappointed at hearing
the sweepstakes officials defend their practices. The hearing left
him even more convinced that legislation should be passed to end
the abuses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
