<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3732 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALCOHOL-INTERNET-HNS &LR;      03-09 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS LOOKING TO CRACK DOWN ON INTERNET ALCOHOL SALES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers introduced legislation Tuesday to make it
more difficult for minors to use the Internet to purchase alcoholic
beverages.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which would confer more power on state law
enforcement officials to crack down on such activity, also would
empower state officials to stop alcohol sales over the Internet,
mail-order catalog or phone in the 20 states where direct delivery
of alcoholic beverages is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Klein, assistant attorney general of Utah _ one of the 20
states _ said state officials recently intercepted 244 cases of
beer from a distributor called Beer Across America which sells beer
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that large numbers of minors actually use
the Internet to purchase alcohol, but several local television
stations have recently broadcast stories showing how easily it can
be done.
</P>
<P>
   One such story, which was displayed on monitors Tuesday during a
Senate Judiciary Committee hearing on Internet alcohol sales,
showed how a 13-year-old ordered a case of beer using a home
computer from a micro-brewery with her older brother's credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The teenager simply clicked on the icon that stated that she was
at least 21 years-old. Three weeks later the beer arrived at her
parents' door step, according to the TV station, KUTV, of Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a 13-year-old is capable of ordering beer and having it
delivered by borrowing a credit card and making a few clicks with
her mouse, there is something very wrong with the level of control
that is being exercised over these sales,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow states to use federal courts to go after
direct alcohol distributors. State officials have complained that
it is difficult to prosecute direct alcohol distributors if they
are located in another state.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, however, has raised the ire of the California
wine industry, which says it could inadvertently hurt its efforts
to sell wine over the Internet that is not readily available in
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Radanovich, R-Calif., who also operates a small
California winery, said the Hatch legislation ``would have the
unintended consequence of crippling small wineries in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   John DeLuca, president of the Wine Institute, an organization
that represents more than 450 California winemakers, said the
legislation would harm industry's efforts to lobby individual
states to change their laws to allow wineries to ship their
products to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry argues that liquor stores carry a limited
selection of wine and that small wine-makers suffer as a result.
The Internet and mail-order catalogues give consumers access to
virtually any wine or beer that is made.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is pushing legislation in some states that would
allow a limited amount of alcohol, such as a case of wine or beer
per month, to be shipped to individuals. Nineteen states currently
have laws that allow limited alcohol shipments.
</P>
<P>
   On the problem of teenager buyers on the Internet, DeLuca
acknowledged that underage drinking is a ``serious problem,'' but
said ``minors are not purchasing any significant amount of wine or
alcohol by the relatively expensive and slow path of direct
shipments, which leaves a clear trail of delivery records and
credit card information.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a member of the committee,
urged a cautious approach to regulating Internet purchases of
alcohol, saying the Hatch bill was ``over-kill.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Feinstein said she had ``seen precious
few examples of youths on their own initiative'' deciding to obtain
alcohol via the Internet, ``waiting days or weeks for shipment and
managing to be home without their parents at just the crucial time
when it arrives.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the examples of under-age-purchases on the
Internet ``involve youths who were prompted to do so, usually by a
local news organization,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Radonovich noted that there are already remedies available for
violations of liquor laws including revoking the federal permits
that are required to operate a winery or brewery.
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry is more supportive of efforts like one by Rep.
Juanita Millender-McDonald, D-Calif., who wants to require
distributors to clearly label a package as containing alcohol.
Shippers such as United Parcel Service would then be required to
obtain a signature of a person who is age 21 or older to leave a
package at a home or office.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she supports a similar approach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBY-THEATER-REVIEW-A     03-09 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBY-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVERYBODY'S RUBY': ONE INDELIBLE PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing in the first few scenes of ``Everybody's
Ruby'' prepares you for the moment when the actress Viola Davis
takes the play and makes it hers. It happens quite stealthily, in
the midst of the kind of speech that you are ready to believe you
have heard a hundred times before in a hundred other dramas
examining the facets of a hundred other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But then Ms. Davis, her face a pitiable blank, her eyes emptied
of illusion, sets about setting you straight. Portraying Ruby
McCollum, a black woman accused of shooting her white lover to
death in a redneck Florida backwater in the early 1950s, Ms. Davis
has the assignment of persuading the audience of the reasonable
irrationality of her attraction to a man who stirs and brutalizes
her, who arouses her with the mere sensation of his ``breath on my
eyelids.'' Yet this affinity is for a man also capable of walking
away from a violent encounter in her house ``smiling as if I'd won
a contest and rape was the prize.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress, nominated for a Tony three years ago for her saucy
portrayal of the object of the leading man's affections in August
Wilson's ``Seven Guitars,'' cuts to the quick with the raw assault
of her riveting account. Her hollow gaze is a window on an awful
surety that it is her lot in life to lose. At every turn of
``Everybody's Ruby,'' which opened Tuesday night at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater, Ms. Davis' impact is indelible; she practically
tattoos the production with her intensity. This ability to
transform the mundane, the expected, into something novel is an
artist's work. Her performance is so proximate, so real, you would
swear you could feel the actress' breath on your own eyelids.
</P>
<P>
   Shots ring out and lightning flashes in the course of
``Everybody's Ruby,'' but no effect in the production is as jolting
as Ms. Davis, whose contribution alone is enough to make Thulani
Davis' play worthwhile. (The actress is no relation to the
playwright.) Though it is far from a perfect work _ it unravels in
the second act without ever making a true tapestry of the complex
network of narrative threads laid out early on _ the writer has
composed an engrossing piece of theater with a manifest compassion
for downtrodden black women of underappreciated courage and
intelligence, women sentenced to discontent and rage by the low
expectations of an unenlightened age.
</P>
<P>
   The play is rangy and ambitious _ 14 actors, many of them
doubling in roles _in its effort to give flesh to the actual 1952
case of Ruby McCollum, convicted of the murder of Dr. C. Leroy
Adams, a white doctor and popular local politician in Live Oak,
Fla. The playwright deftly outlines the dark secrets and shady
alliances rampant in a small racially mixed Southern town in the
years before the civil rights movement took hold. But Thulani
Davis' real agenda here is taking stock of the presence of Zora
Neale Hurston, the celebrated and troubled author who, down on her
luck, took a freelance job with a black Pittsburgh newspaper and
traveled to Live Oak to cover the McCollum trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis discovers in these real events, in the crossed rutted
paths of McCollum and Hurston, an unusual kinship. Hurston, as
warmly rendered by Phylicia Rashad, understands instinctively,
perhaps because of the vicissitudes of her own personal and
professional life, that the slaying is a crime of infinitely more
subtlety than the town lets on. In making Hurston a missionary for
the truth, the playwright exposes a parallel complexity in the
community's social patterns, its unspoken rules and undercurrents
of nastiness; its respect for power, regardless of skin color, and
its surprising tolerance of the outrageous acts of its leading
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   So many acts and themes are grappled with, though, from the
gambling subculture overseen by Ruby's husband, Sam (Bill Nunn), to
the tempestuous relationship between Zora and the white reporter
(Tuck Milligan) she recruits to help her with the story, to the
elusive appetites of the doctor (Beau Gravitte), that plot nuances
are obscured by the reams of information. (As the story becomes
more and more preoccupied with Zora, it becomes less and less
interesting.) The director, Kenny Leon, artistic director of the
Alliance Theater in Atlanta, clarifies things to some degree with a
spare and handsome production and a cast filled with such expert
and thoroughly credible supporting players as Crystal Fox, Bernie
McInerney, Raynor Scheine, Chuck Patterson and Ron Cephas Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sturge's mood-enhancing lighting design and Dwight Andrews'
evocative original music create an emphatic tone without ever
drawing too much attention to themselves. Marjorie Bradley
Kellogg's set, however, reflects some of the confusing drift in the
text: When a character describes a bullet hole in the floor of a
doctor's office in which she is standing but sticks her hand into
brown Florida soil, something is a bit off.
</P>
<P>
   But the lapses seem insignificant whenever Ms. Davis is onstage.
There is a lovely sequence at the end of the play when Ruby allows
Zora, posing as a hairdresser, into her cell. The jailer may be
fooled but Ruby isn't, and as she allows Zora to brush out her hair
and apply some lipstick, Ruby reveals the depth of her sorrow,
forged by destiny and compounded by desire. ``He had ruined my
life, and I wanted him anyway,'' Ms. Davis says, at her most
tragic, and most beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EVERYBODY'S RUBY'
</P>
<P>
   Written by Thulani Davis; directed by Kenny Leon; sets by
Marjorie Bradley Kellogg; costumes by Mariann Verheyen; lighting by
Tom Sturge; sound by Jeffrey Carlson; original music by Dwight
Andrews; production dramaturg, Shirley Fishman; production stage
manager, Lisa Porter; senior director, external affairs, Margaret
Lioi; associate producer, Wiley Hausam; artistic associate, Brian
Kulick; associate producer, Bonnie Metzgar; general manager,
Michael Hurst. Presented by the Joseph Papp Public Theater/New York
Shakespeare Festival, George Wolfe, producer; Rosemarie Tichler,
artistic producer; Mark Litvin, managing director. At the Anspacher
Theater in the Joseph Papp Public Theater, 425 Lafayette St., N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   With: Viola Davis (Ruby McCollum), Phylicia Rashad (Zora Neale
Hurston), Beau Gravitte (Dr. C. Leroy Adams), Tuck Milligan
(William Bradford Huie) and Bill Nunn (Sam McCollum).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
