<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NIELSEN-COUNTERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA'S SENIOR WORKFORCE LURES NIELSEN MEDIA RESEARCH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGARET ANN MIILLE   
 Herald-Tribune (Sarasota, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Fla. _ The expansive Nielsen Media Research operation
here is busy closing the books on one of four major TV viewer
sampling periods, which ended last week.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite office for the New York-based corporate giant
collects and edits 375,000 weekly diaries kept by TV watchers in
210 local markets nationwide. In 44 of the largest ones, meters are
also installed in viewers' television sets.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the deadline looms, the mood hardly seems harried within
the 42,000-square-foot building. It resembles a hushed library,
with row upon row of editors entering the data into computers.
</P>
<P>
   The work is systematic and demands precision, conducted by two
shifts of mostly senior citizens who will input 8.32 million
entries this sweeps period alone, detailing who watched which
program in 15-minute increments during four weeks beginning Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Venice may seem an unlikely setting for an operation of such
scale, given its distance from the big cities and the fact that
many private employers in southwest Florida lament the scarcity of
qualified workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Nielsen's Venice Manager Gary Bentley said that the local
high retiree population is precisely what lured the media research
firm here 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said that seniors generally demonstrate a strong work ethic
and enjoy the flexibility offered by the cyclical sweeps, totaling
about 40 workweeks annually.
</P>
<P>
   The present site is Nielsen's third in Venice. Bentley said that
the company moved to the present $6-million building, set on seven
acres, in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   All but 18 of the 756 employees technically work part time. The
term is clearly relative. Two ``temporary'' workers two weeks ago
celebrated their 25-year work anniversaries with Nielsen in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   During its seven annual sweeps _ major ones in February, May,
July and November, and minor ones in January, March and October _
workers here input 36.2 million computer entries gleaned from 1.33
million diaries representing more than 30 million hours of TV
viewing.
</P>
<P>
   The TV viewing diaries are specific, giving the time, channel
and names of the station, program and viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Many diaries arrive incomplete. The main task of editors is to
interpret entries so they result in accurate station crediting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody followed those directions, it would be easy,''
Bentley said. ``They all interpret those instructions
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest to client stations, networks, advertisers
and cable stations are the back pages of diaries reserved for
comments.
</P>
<P>
   Many are left blank. But Jim Wrightson, who first retired in
1986 and now oversees several of the local editing teams, said that
the most prevalent written comment is that shows today have too
much sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Wrightson, 71, said that he has gained a keener appreciation of
TV programming since working at Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has increased my knowledge of what other people watch,'' he
said. ``I see something other people are watching, and I check it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Computerization has greatly improved and accelerated the editing
process. Before July 1994, tools consisted of piles of pens, paper
and TV guides.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research began as part of A.C. Nielsen Co., which
was founded in 1923 by Arthur C. Nielsen Sr. It became one of the
first firms to measure audience size for the rapidly developing
radio broadcasting and advertising industries, and has remained the
official national measurement service for television for more than
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen provides ratings for nearly every program seen on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Listed on the New York Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol
NMR, Nielsen last month announced that its 1998 pro forma earnings
rose 20.2 percent over the previous year to $48.8 million, or 82
cents per diluted share, a 15.5 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Those who yearn to become a Nielsen TV family should not hold
their breath _ or lose heart. Accepting volunteers, who receive $1
for their efforts, would skew the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen chooses you.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Ann Miille writes for the Herald-Tribune of Sarasota,
Fla. Distributed by the N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
