<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JULIAN-LENNON-2TAKES-     03-09 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULIAN-LENNON-2TAKES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIAN LENNON HAS A NEW ALBUM AND NO KIND WORDS FOR YOKO ONO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BILL DeYOUNG   
 THE GAINESVILLE (FLA.) SUN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's never been easy being Julian Lennon. The son of the world's
most beloved pop musician, Julian tried to carve a career for
himself in the early 1980s, only to find that everybody _ the
media, the fans, the world at large _ couldn't stop making
comparisons to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The nose, the voice, the droll Liverpudlian humor _ it was as if
John Lennon hadn't really died in that hail of bullets, and was
still writing songs and making music.
</P>
<P>
   Julian endured it because his first two singles, ``Valotte'' and
``Too Late For Goodbyes,'' were big hits, and the money and
attention were just fine for a young man barely in his 20s.
</P>
<P>
   But it started going sour quickly. ``I felt used and abused and
disrespected in many, many ways,'' says the now 35-year-old
singer-songwriter in a phone interview. ``And I recognized what
many people's perceptions of me were, which was more of a joke than
anything else. Not being taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennon didn't help things by living the high life, very
publicly, in Los Angeles. Alcohol and cocaine nearly killed him
before it was all over, and after his fourth album, in 1991, he
left Los Angeles and bought out his stagnating record deal.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to northern Italy, into a lake villa. ``Since entering
the business at age 20, it had been nothing but music or the music
industry,'' he says. ``That left no time to figure out who I was,
outside of the industry. So it was a good time for reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, Julian Lennon, inheritor of the
great Beatle legacy, disappeared. ``I actually lived and breathed
as an adult, which was the most wonderful thing,'' he explains. ``I
had a chance to catch up on people I'd sort of brushed to the side
during my mad years. To travel without working for a change, so I
had the chance to appreciate the places I was going to.''
</P>
<P>
   He took up painting and photography, and worked hard at his
first love, cooking. Eventually, slowly, he began writing songs
again.
</P>
<P>
   Lennon is back with the best music he's ever made. Released two
weeks ago, the album ``Photograph Smile'' was self-composed,
self-produced and is being marketed through his own new record
label _ the result, he says, of too many shady business deals and
two-sided contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say `You grew up around the industry, you must have had
some advice,' '' he says. ``Well, no. Dad walked out the door when
I was 5 and I maybe saw him a handful of times before he passed
away. I grew up on a farm in North Wales, amongst many other
places. I was nowhere near the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lennon left Cynthia Powell, his Liverpool-born wife, in
1968, when he took up with Yoko Ono. Little Julian _ he was the
inspiration for his father's songs ``Lucy in the Sky With
Diamonds'' and ``Good Night,'' as well as Paul McCartney's ``Hey
Jude'' _ thought of his mother's second husband, Roberto Bassanini,
as his father. He barely knew the former Beatle.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he was murdered in 1980, John Lennon gave several
interviews in which he said Julian had been ``born out of a bottle
of whiskey on a Saturday night,'' and that they were slowly,
arduously working on a long-distance father-son relationship.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the elder Lennon had a son, Sean, with Ono, whom he
doted on. Sean was the favored son.
</P>
<P>
   Although the world may never know the real John Lennon, says
Julian, he thinks he's got a good handle on it. ``Look, Mum grew up
with him, went to art college with him, got married and had me with
him,'' he says, ``so she knew him before and during what was going
on. So as far as the real man underneath all of that stuff, she's
got a pretty clear understanding. She's always been very grounded
and very honest and very truthful in anything she's ever had to say
about Dad. And she's never wanted to harm or hurt anybody else,
it's just pure honesty on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to the settlement, when they were finally
splitting up, the only thing Mum asked for _ so many people have
said `Why didn't your mother go for his balls?' _ all she wanted
was enough for me to go through school, food and clothes. She
didn't want anything for herself, the reason being: She loved this
man. She did not love his money, or the celebrity, or anything that
surrounded that. She fell in love with this man.''
</P>
<P>
   In the original divorce settlement, Cynthia was awarded around
$6,000 in annual child-care for Julian; he received a trust fund of
approximately $120,000 when he turned 25.
</P>
<P>
   In Lennon's will, Ono was named executor of an estate estimated
at more than $600 million. Two years ago, Julian settled with Ono _
with whom he'd never had an easy relationship _ for around $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   He's been given none of his father's possessions, and last year
bought some of them _ including guitars, song lyrics and the black
Afghan coat John wore in ``Magical Mystery Tour'' _ at an auction
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoko has everything,'' Lennon says. ``She has the rights, she
has the name, she has all his belongings, she has absolutely
everything. Which I find disgusting, but there's nothing I can do
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all look at him as the supposed intelligent man that he
was, and he was a man who talked about love and peace and fairness
in life, then he certainly didn't represent that within his own
family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Today, his venom is reserved exclusively for Ono. His sleeves
are rolled up, he says, and he's ready to take her on.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as history is concerned, it's Yoko and Sean and Dad are
the Lennon family. And that was it. I know for a fact she's tried
to squash my career in Europe _ and had a great effect on it, as a
matter of fact. I know of many things she's done to me, and to Mum,
and I'm not gonna put up with it any more. Because I don't owe her
anything. And I'm certainly not gonna bow down. Because I have
truth and honesty on my side, and factual information about some of
her wheelings and dealings. Which is not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't entirely know what people's perspective about Yoko is,
but it's certainly gonna change over the next year, without a
doubt.'' Lennon says he will discuss his position in the media,
every chance that he's offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Photograph Smile'' was released last summer in Europe, on the
same day that the debut album, by Sean Lennon, now 22, arrived in
record stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have copies of letters she's written, hand signed, to some
of the largest music magazines in Europe,'' Lennon explains.
``Saying that Sean should be seen as the genius son of John Lennon,
and that Julian should be seen as the used, wasted, drink-and-drug
useless son that didn't have anything to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the degree that if this was not complied, literally she
would buy up all the copies of this publication, or she would bury
the editor and owner of the magazine. Literally. And this is on
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lennon says, he and his stepbrother get along
well. ``Sean doesn't even know about half of this stuff. I don't
want to tell him face to face. He's got to learn for himself what's
going on, because it is his mother ... .That's a difficult one for
me, and I certainly don't want to put a wall up between us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, she doesn't have her own life. She meddled in
Dad's and now she's meddling in Sean's. And I certainly don't want
her to meddle in mine a.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bill DeYoung is Arts &AMP; Entertainment Editor of The Gainesville
Sun in Gainesville Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
