<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 10, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A wrong-way warm front moved from northeast to southwest across
the Canadian Maritimes on Tuesday, indicating an unusual weather
pattern over northeastern North America. With a high-pressure
system east of Newfoundland blocking the advance of the
low-pressure system over the Gulf of Maine, relatively mild ocean
air pinwheeled completely around the offshore low and then headed
west into Canada. Wednesday, accumulating snows and patchy ice will
fall across the upper St. Lawrence River Valley and parts of
northeast Maine as the unusual warm front presses slowly
southwestward.
</P>
<P>
   With the blocking high disrupting the normal eastward
progression of weather systems across Canada, the steering winds of
the jet stream will be diverted over the southern two-thirds of the
contiguous states. In northern California and Oregon, coastal rains
and mountain snows will develop as a Pacific disturbance is steered
inland. Precipitation will be generally light to moderate, owing to
a lack of moisture. This disturbance will move southeastward and
may pose a formidable threat to the East late in the week if it
develops into a major storm.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will accumulate across parts of northeast Wyoming and
western South Dakota early in the day as a weakening jet stream
disturbance combines with moist winds from the southeast. Four
inches of snow or more are possible in the Black Hills.
</P>
<P>
   A few flurries and patchy drizzle across the northern Middle
Atlantic States will mark the wake of a low-pressure system moving
out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Twin-City Snow
</P>
<P>
   Twelve and one-half inches of snow were measured at Minneapolis
on Monday, establishing a new record snowfall for the date and
raising the city's winter's snowfall to 53 inches. The average
winter snowfall is approximately 48 inches. On average, March is
the snowiest month at Minneapolis, with the city typically
positioned on the northern fringe of the range of moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico. Most of the snow that falls in cold Minneapolis is
fluffy, ``dry'' snow, with the typical water content of snowflakes
being relatively low. Such dry snow is ideal for winter-sport
recreation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
