<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-MONROE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARILYN MONROE'S HALF-SISTER REMEMBERS JOE DIMAGGIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BOB ARNDORFER   
 Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Joe DiMaggio's sister-in-law, a Gainesville
resident since 1951, guarded her memories of the baseball icon who
died Monday, saying she didn't think he'd approve of her being too
open about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked, but I don't think Joe would want me to say anything
about that,'' Berniece Miracle, Marilyn Monroe's half-sister, said
softly when asked if she and DiMaggio had stayed in touch over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Miracle, as staunch a defender of her privacy as DiMaggio was of
his, did reveal that she's certain the love between Marilyn and Joe
continued long after their 10-month marriage in 1954 ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was the love of her life, and she would have remarried him
if she had lived,'' she said. ``I'm sure of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miracle said she considered DiMaggio ``a wonderful man'' who
``was always my favorite brother-in-law.'' She'll never forget his
help after Marilyn Monroe's death in 1962, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always appreciated Joe's helping me with my sister's
funeral in California,'' said Miracle, 79, who retired in 1974 from
the University of Florida, where she worked as an accountant and
bookkeeper. ``I'm very, very sad about him passing away.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``My Sister Marilyn: A Memoir of Marilyn Monroe'' (Algonquin
Books, 1994), Miracle and her daughter, Mona Rae Miracle, touch on
the romance, marriage and breakup of Monroe and DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public loves the match between these two poor kids who
grew up to become a baseball hero and America's favorite blonde,''
the two women wrote. The union couldn't withstand the incessant
glare of the limelight and the demands of Monroe's career, the
authors write. But their love, Berniece Miracle is certain, did
survive.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Arndorfer is a reporter for The Gainesville Sun in
Gainesville, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
