<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERO-BOOK-REVIEW-2TAK     03-09 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERO-BOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHOW ME A HERO': A CITY DIVIDED BY A JUDGE'S DESEGREGATION ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Book notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 Patricia J. Williams, a professor at Columbia Law School, is the
author of ``Seeing a Color-Blind Future.''  
 By PATRICIA J. WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1992 the journalist Lisa Belkin was living in Westchester in
the first home she had ever owned. When the City of Yonkers, only
10 minutes down the road, was ordered by a federal judge to build
low-income housing in middle-class neighborhoods, Ms. Belkin found
herself drawn to the battle brewing her backyard. The result was
``Show Me a Hero.''
</P>
<P>
   While the near-riotous resistance to desegregation that
culminated with the judge's order had festered for nearly a decade
before this final resolution, Yonkers had had a much longer history
of intentional segregation. Virtually all of its black and poor
citizens had been shunted into densely populated high-rise housing
projects on the west side of town.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Belkin, a former reporter for The New York Times who is now
a contributing writer to The New York Times Magazine, begins her
story by introducing a young Dominican mother named Alma Febles, a
candidate for the court-ordered housing, in whom she sees
``mirrored'' her own yearning for the sanctity of home.
</P>
<P>
   A mirror she may be, but it is ``the muddled impurity'' of Ms.
Belkin's concern that becomes the central tension of this book: ``I
believed in the right of this woman to have her home. But what if
bulldozers were to clear a site for that home in the trees so close
to my own house?''
</P>
<P>
   With the lines thus drawn, there is not much to distinguish the
Yonkers case from similar standoffs in cities around the nation,
but for two factors. First, the city council members, backed by
their noisy east side constituents, seemed unusually willing to
bankrupt the city in the effort to prevent the court order from
taking effect. And second, the style of low-income housing finally
built has become the model for public housing nationally: i.e.,
``scatter-site'' homes, or small clusters of low-rise town houses
designed to blend into stable neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ``Show Me a Hero'' takes on the dimension of a cautionary
tale for what may happen in cities everywhere. Only the patient and
the stalwart adapt and survive in the Yonkers debacle, and in the
end there are no heroes of any race or ethnicity, just an exhausted
truce.
</P>
<P>
   The book owes much stylistically, as Ms. Belkin acknowledges, to
authors like Alex Kotlowitz, Nicholas Lemann and Andrew Hacker,
whose best sellers have challenged whites to wake up to the
humanity of people of color and to the costs to themselves of
stigmatizing others.
</P>
<P>
   But like many works in this genre there is something
fundamentally troubling about the positing of black and brown
people as those who are perpetually ``discovered'' to be ``just
like'' everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   A white woman is shocked to find that homes in the projects are
``so clean.'' An architect experiences the impatient apprehension
of ``one towering white man surrounded by six black women.'' A
community organizer expects ``outrage'' from black people who have
been taunted with racial insults but is surprised when they quietly
move on.
</P>
<P>
   A self-styled benefactor has to be taught that ``low income'' is
not a synonym for ``no income,'' lazy, or unemployed. A white
mother is ``transfixed'' and moved to see a black woman kiss her
son's skinned knees.
</P>
<P>
   And Nick Wasicsko, the idealistic young mayor of Yonkers who
makes the decision to obey the court order, discovers that the
.38-caliber pistol he wore while stumping in the projects he now
needs for visiting ``the safest parts of his city.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the structure is somewhat hackneyed, it is also hopeful.
Most of the central characters are indeed transformed by their
interactions with one another, and Ms. Belkin's skill in the art of
quick-paced suspense makes for engrossing reading.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, one is left with the sense that if this is what it
takes, then ``discover'' away, discover again, discover until there
are no more surprises. One of the greatest strengths of the book is
Ms. Belkin's ability to document not just the large
headline-grabbing events, but the small, grudging, baby steps of
perception that allow for major shifts in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, one is made aware of the staggering amounts of
money the west siders must spend to compensate for the lack of
basic public services in a community where everyone knows ``you
have no other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly one comes to realize that, while the east side residents
are repeatedly described as ``middle class,'' and the tenants in
the new housing are repeatedly described as ``poor,'' they are all
very close to one another on a short spectrum of anxious, generally
underpaid, working-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, slowly one senses how much of the war waged by so many
east siders _ all those years spent screaming and spitting and
sending bullets imprinted with the names of various public
officials _ was a showcase for all of the bad behavior they had
feared west siders would import.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Belkin has a talent for subtly revealing the psychology of
racial projection: One man worries that the mostly black tenants
will need to be taught not to sunbathe in front of their houses.
Another brings his dog to defecate on the new lawns of the town
houses, apparently as an expression of a general east side
sentiment that it is the new tenants whose unclean ways will lower
the property values.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the tenants turn out to be as peaceful and neat as
any in the surrounding private houses. Nevertheless the property
values are affected. It is ``difficult to sell a home in Yonkers _
anywhere in Yonkers,'' Ms. Belkin notes. The little shifts of
sympathetic connection that she so meticulously documents have not
yet been enough to dispel the galloping racial fear that,
throughout the United States, tends to become self-fulfilling
prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Yonkers becomes yet another
monument to white flight or whether instead it hunkers down
patiently for the long-term discoveries of real racial
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the book Alma Febles, recently installed in her
bright new home reflects upon the rumor that the city is about to
build more town houses on her street. Mrs. Febles is described as
wishing aloud, ``with no hint of irony,'' that the new construction
is not too close because ``this is such a quiet, pretty block.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a densely enigmatic statement with which to leave the
reader. One is unsure whether Ms. Belkin is using Mrs. Febles to
represent the next generation of bunkered fear of the unknown and
thus to mirror Ms. Belkin's own, self-professed, not-in-my-backyard
anxiety with which the book begins.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another way to hear Mrs. Febles' worry: Another
cluster of new units put right next to an existing cluster of town
houses is already a betrayal of the very notion of ``scatter-site''
housing.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that the effort to disperse poor minorities
throughout better-off white communities is not defeated by
resistance to the integrative notion of ``scattering'' itself. One
can only hope, as perhaps Alma Febles does, that high-rise
concentration is not replaced by low-rise sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `SHOW ME A HERO: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A Tale of Murder, Suicide, Race and Redemption' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Belkin  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   331 pages. Little, Brown. $25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
