<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCI-SCAM-COX     03-09 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-SCAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MCI accused in racketeering conspiracy
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal authorities in Atlanta are investigating an
alleged scheme that defrauded MCI Telecommunications Corp. and
several banks out of more than $30 million, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   So far, federal prosecutors have obtained one guilty plea by a
manager of an MCI financial services group in Atlanta. The manager,
James Wilkie IV, pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud and is
cooperating in the investigation. Under his plea agreement, Wilkie
acknowledges he may be liable for paying more than $2 million in
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month three banks, including NationsBank Corp., filed
a civil lawsuit against MCI, alleging a racketeering conspiracy by
the telecommunications giant.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal investigation is similar to ``the focus of our
claim against MCI and others for racketeering activities,'' said
Buddy Parker, the lead lawyer for NationsBank, National Bank of
Canada and the CIT Group of Livingston, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, accuses MCI of
covering up the fraud after it was discovered. It also said that
MCI should be held liable for the banks' losses _ and forced to pay
punitive damages plus mounting attorneys' fees _ because it is
responsible for alleged fraudulent acts committed by its own
managers.
</P>
<P>
   MCI contends that it, like the banks, is a victim of the alleged
fraud and estimates that it has lost more than $30 million,
according to court filings. The banks say they have suffered losses
of more than $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   MCI denies the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have maintained all along that MCI. . . was the victim in
this situation,'' MCI spokeswoman Jamie DePeau said. ``To that
point, one of the perpetrators has pleaded guilty to wire fraud in
federal court. We feel the case is moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the banks' lawsuit, MCI approached Manatee Partners
Ltd., an Atlanta investment firm, about buying the accounts
receivable of several MCI ``resellers'' _ companies that buy excess
space on MCI's network and then sell it to others, including
``1-900'' phone sex lines. Because ``1-900'' accounts are difficult
to collect, they became a cash-flow problem for MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Manatee obtained a line of credit from the three banks to
finance the purchases, the lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   But Manatee, which also is named as a defendant in the banks'
lawsuit, diverted money from the loans into offshore bank accounts
in the Cayman Islands and misled the banks about its ability to
repay the loans, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   In court filings, Manatee has denied any wrongdoing and has
filed its own lawsuit against MCI.
</P>
<P>
   MCI contends the ``perpetrators'' of the fraudulent scheme
include a network of companies specializing in the sale of phone
sex and two former ``middle-level'' MCI employees _ Wilkie and
Walter Pavlo Jr. The two employees altered MCI's books ``to conceal
the resellers' continuing delinquency and the fact that the
proceeds of (MCI's) receivables were being diverted,'' MCI said in
court filings.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlo, who joined MCI in 1992 but no longer works for the
company, worked for the company's Carrier Financial Services unit,
which was responsible for collecting accounts that resellers owed
to MCI. According to MCI court filings, Pavlo helped get lines of
credit from the banks, co-owned offshore accounts and received more
than $500,000 in diverted payments.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlo's attorney, Bruce Morris, said his client engaged in no
criminal misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said MCI's deal with Manatee to collect the receivables
was ``real, legitimate and intended to benefit MCI. And for a time,
it did.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the ``innovative program'' was designed to keep MCI's
bad debt at a minimum. ``There was great pressure within MCI to
accomplish that.'' he said. ``(Pavlo) was introducing a creative
program into the Carrier Finance division.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
