<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-BRAZIL-COX     03-09 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-BRAZIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth's big gamble in Brazil: Can its wireless gambit ride
out the economic crisis?By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Considering how bad things have gotten in Brazil, it
has really been pretty good _ at least for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company, the largest foreign
telecommunications investor in Latin America, has _ with its
Brazilian partners _ poured billions of dollars into purchase of
wireless licenses and construction of networks. They have seen
business news that was agreeable even as the economic reports grew
more grim.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 months, the government of Brazil, the region's
largest nation and largest economy, has been racked with crisis,
forced to cashier top officials, lay off tens of thousands of
workers and finally, devalue the country's currency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BellSouth went into the wireless business and, within
nine months, had one million subscribers. It took BellSouth's
operations seven years to reach a million subscribers in both
Venezuela and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a very bad year for Brazil,'' said Roberto Peon,
president of the Brazilian wireless unit part-owned by BellSouth.
``It was a great year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has for years been billing international as one-third
of its long-term growth strategy, along with domestic wireless and
local service in the nine southeastern states. In fact, golfer and
BellSouth Chief Executive Duane Ackerman calls the investments in
the nine Latin nations as ``the back nine.''
</P>
<P>
   But like any international investor, BellSouth has seen its
international plan threatened by the currency crisis that started
in the fall of 1997 and was first called the ``Asian Flu.''
BellSouth has only limited presence in Asia _ albeit in the two
largest nations on Earth: India and China. But even those are
low-level efforts aiming far into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Then the currency malady spread last year into Latin America,
casting suspicion on years of Pollyanna projections about rapid
economic growth and renewed political stability. Most ominous, the
region's largest economy seemed to have caught the most serious
version of the bug.
</P>
<P>
   Stakes are high. BellSouth and its partners spent $2.5 billion
to buy the license for Sao Paulo and surrounding area, turf where
about 18 million people live. Shortly after, the consortium ponied
up $512 million more to buy the right to offer wireless in the
nation's six-state northeast region. They promised to spend $950
million building and improving those networks over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a $23 billion-a-year company like BellSouth, that is a
healthy chunk of change. True, BellSouth doesn't carry the whole
burden. It owns about 45 percent of each Brazilian operation,
taking a similar share of profits _ and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   SUBHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities seemed even more sensational than the costs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview a yer ago in his Sao Paulo office, Luiz de
Oliveira Machado, president of Nortel in Brazil, called Brazil the
world's best market for telecom investment. Dropping a sheet of
paper onto his oak table, he pointed to three intersecting circles.
In one circle, names of countries with fewer than 10 phone lines
for every 100 residents _ where potential is the greatest. In
another circle, countries with populations greater than 50 million
_ where the market is the largest. The third circle named nations
with gross domestic product per person of more than $4,000 _ the
places where many people have the money to buy new service.
</P>
<P>
   Only one name appeared in all three circles: Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   So despite BellSouth's huge outlays, hopes were high. More than
a million people were on waiting lists for telephone service. Many
had given up expecting a wire into the home and would be satisfied
_ and maybe even prefer _ a wireless phone.
</P>
<P>
   But always there were fears. Of economic turmoil undoing demand.
Of recession unnerving delicate political systems.
</P>
<P>
   And turmoil, there has been.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate for Brazil hit a 16-year high in January,
even as the Brazilian currency collapsed to a record low against
the dollar. Meanwhile, interest rates rose as high as 40 percent. A
number of large companies announced layoffs, so the picture is not
likely to brighten soon. Economists say the Brazilian economy will
shrink by 4.1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund has been preparing a $9 billion
loan as part of its ongoing, $41.5 billion ``rescue'' effort, but
has demanded still more economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   When the economic crisis first hit, BellSouth officials said
they hoped mobile phones would stay immune. The theory was that
Brazil was so under-served by telecommunications that phones would
be one of the necessities that consumers would spend on.
</P>
<P>
   SUBHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Yet the year was not so kind for BellSouth's chief rival in
Brazil. Telesp Celular this month reported an earnings drop of 52
percent from earnings for the previous quarter. The company blamed
devaluation and a weakening of consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Manuel Romao Mateus, the company president, recently told
Bloomberg News that his ability to meet even existing demand was
damaged by devaluation, which raised prices for imported equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But he also blamed competition from BellSouth _ which has surged
to nearly 50 percent market share _ for keeping him from raising
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Peon doesn't like to talk about his competition, but he
will say he thinks he has a huge advantage. Because BellSouth has
built its network from scratch it doesn't face the costs of
transition from analog to digital _ something that its competition
is grappling with. BellSouth also had the good fortune of doing the
lion's share of its infrastructure improvements before the currency
crisis began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic malaise, Peon thinks he can customize his
offering to take advantage of the strengths in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he is emphasizing pre-paid plans. The idea is to
let customers know exactly how much they will spend on their phone
service while still encouraging use of the network. Unlike the
United States, where a wireless customer is charged whenever the
phone is used _ even to receive a call _ in Brazil, the calling
party pays. That means that a user who has run through his or her
pre-paid budget can still leave the phone turned on, hand out the
number, take calls and use BellSouth's network.
</P>
<P>
   Which is just fine with BellSouth, too, since the caller pays
the freight.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hit BellSouth has taken has been from devaluation.
Expected profits are down, since the debt from BellSouth's
Brazilian investment must be paid back to BellSouth's New
York-based lenders in dollars. But the continuing slide of Brazil's
currency means it will take ever-more revenues from Brazil to make
payments.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth too has seen an erratic supply of phones thanks to
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result was I only had the higher priced phones in the
stores for a while,'' Peon said. ``It slowed things down, but I
still made my numbers. We probably lost some sales because
customers wanted the lower priced phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Peon is convinced that the potential in Brazil has barely been
tapped, since customers thus far are only the wealthy and
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Brazil's middle class is proportionately much
smaller than that of the United States, and the rockier the
recession, the more it might shrink. But demographics bode well,
since the hottest consumer demand for wireless is among the young,
Peon said.
</P>
<P>
   More critically, BellSouth has not yet gone after many corporate
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   That delay was partly to serve the huge backlog of people on
waiting lists for phones, and partly to make sure the network was
broad enough to handle business needs, Peon said. ``The corporate
accounts are not inflation-sensitive. But going after corporate
accounts when you don't have good coverage, it's like committing
hara-kari.''
</P>
<P>
   Peon remains persuaded that his business is recession-proof, but
coats his predictions with caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in Brazil can say without a doubt that they are
optimistic, because you do not want to be a complete fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
