A3783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTUIT-CHECKFREE-COX     03-09 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTUIT-CHECKFREE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CheckFree stocks ride price roller coasterBy Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of CheckFree took a circular ride in the last
week after Intuit filed suit against the Norcross-based company.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree stock dropped 8.7 percent Wednesday, the day Intuit
filed suit in California.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares last Wednesday closed at $35.50, down 8.7
percent. The next day, Thursday, CheckFree shares dropped 11
percent, to close at $31.50. But by the time the market closed on
Tuesday, CheckFree shares had rebounded a total of almost 25
percent to close at the $39.81 1/4 with a gain of $4.56 1/4, or 13
percent, on strong volume. Intuit has a 19.9 percent stake in
CheckFree, so news of its suit stuck the Silicon Valley company
with a $75 million paper loss by the time the market closed
Thursday. Most of that paper loss has since been erased.
</P>
<P>
   Few people have seen the lawsuit. Intuit asked the Superior
Court of Santa Clara County, Calif., to seal the file four hours
after it filed the suit, according to the court clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit said it filed suit because CheckFree is not complying
with the terms of an April 1998 agreement. CheckFree said the suit
won't keep it from offering a service that lets customers get and
pay their bills from an Internet portal.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Franco, an analyst with Piper Jaffray in San Francisco,
said the stock price rebounded because the lawsuit is ``much ado
about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco said he has not seen the court filing, but believes it
involves CheckFree's negotiations with America Online to offer
Web-based bill paying and bill presenting, as well as the question
of whether the negotiations infringed on an earlier Intuit
agreement with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something they'll work out,'' Franco said. ``It just
might have the effect of dragging out AOL's ability to roll out the
CheckFree service.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco said he did not think CheckFree's distribution deal with
Yahoo!, a high-traffic Internet portal, would be affected by the
Intuit suit since Intuit did not have an earlier agreement with
Yahoo! CheckFree said on Jan. 26 that it had signed a deal with a
major Internet portal, but the company has yet to say which portal.
Avivah Litan, an analyst with the Gartner Group, said it was
Yahoo!.
</P>
<P>
   Franco maintains a 12-month target price on CheckFree stock of
$53. He recommends the stock as a ``strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Two analysts lowered their ratings on CheckFree shares on the
heels of the lawsuit: Robert V. Bolen, of J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co., in
Nashville, from ``strong buy'' to ``buy;'' Lehman Brothers' Patrick
M. Burton, from ``neutral'' to ``outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   But two other analysts issued ``buy'' ratings this week.
Deutsche Bank Securities analyst James M. Marks initiated coverage
of the company on Tuesday with a ``buy'' rating, and Legg Mason
Wood Walker analyst Pawan K. Malhotra raised his rating on Monday
to ``buy'' from ``outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, CheckFree announced it bought Mobius Group, a financial
planning software company, for about $18 million in stock. Mobius,
which makes money management databases for the financial services
industry, had $6.6 million in revenue in 1998. Mobius, based in
Research Triangle Park, N.C., employs about 70 people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
