<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING10-COX     03-09 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring offers cable Net access
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surf fast or die.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring, the Atlanta-based Internet service provider, entered
the fast-paced, high stakes world of cable Internet access this
week by offering service in Montgomery Ala.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to expand that service soon to other southern cities
served by West Point-based Knology, an interactive video, voice and
data services company. MindSpring and Knology are sister companies
with a common investor.
</P>
<P>
   Offering cable modem and other high-speed services is vital to
the survival of ISPs like MindSpring, Earthlink and even America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is heating up for the traditional dial-up customers.
AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom have scored deals with computer makers to
provide Internet service to new computer users. That, combined with
a cable industry determined to aggressively roll out its own
branded high-speed service, doesn't make things easy for
independent ISPs like MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   The ISPs must find alternative distribution outlets to keep pace
with technology, as well as remain major players in the ISP arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a baby step for MindSpring into the broadband space,''
says Jupiter Communications analyst Abhai Chaki of the Montgomery
rollout. Chaki and other analysts say MindSpring and other ISPs
have a long way to go to make serious inroads in the broadband
world.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring now has a toe-hold in the world of high-speed
Internet access, but it will need more than just a few small
Southern cities to become a major player in the broadband world,
currently locked up by traditional cable and telecommunications
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Montgomery, MindSpring's Fast Access service will
roll out eventually in Augusta, Columbus, Charleston, S.C, and
Panama City, Fla., once MindSpring's Knology upgrades the equipment
it needs to provide cable access in those cities.
</P>
<P>
   ITC Holdings owns a significant chunk of Knology and owns a part
of Mindspring. Because the two are ``sister companies,'' MindSpring
can offer cable modem Internet access in markets where Knology has
built a cable infrastructure without requiring customers to change
cable TV companies.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring's director of Fast Access, Jim Anderson, says as far
as he knows this is the first time an ISP has rolled out cable
modem service without hooking up with a traditional cable company
such as Media One, Time Warner or any of the other major cable
operators.
</P>
<P>
   Cable modem service allows users to access the Internet at
speeds up to 50 times faster than standard dial-up phone
connections.
</P>
<P>
   In Montgomery, the service will cost $39.95 per month with a
one-time installation fee of $149.95, which includes installation
of all equipment and service. The cable modem is available for
lease at $13 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``MindSpring has no current plans to offer cable modem service
in Atlanta,'' Anderson says. ``We would very much like to, but
don't have the access to the cable infrastructure that we need. So
far, we haven't been able to get that access, like we have with
Knology.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Anderson says the company still eventually hopes to
bring cable modem service into as many households as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had periodic discussions with other third party
providers, and we will talk with anyone who will talk to us about
the cable infrastructure,'' he says. However, cable companies are
not required to open their wires to any other service providers.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has joined with other ISPs in a lobbying group called
the Open Network Coalition to call upon Washington regulators to
open up cable lines to allow competition from the ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, cable companies such as Tele-Communications Inc. and
others who provide cable modem service do not allow subscribers to
choose an ISP.
</P>
<P>
   A TCI subscriber must use TCI's ISP, the At Home Network.
Similarly, Media One's cable modem subscribers must be Media One
Internet customers. They do not have the option to chose
MindSpring, Earthlink, America Online or any other ISP. Those ISPs
believe the government should force cable companies to share their
lines, as telephone companies must.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry observers see an irony in that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to broadband becoming a reality, MindSpring, AOL and
everybody else said the government shouldn't interfere with how
ISPs do business. They didn't want the government telling them how
to deal with privacy, content and spam,'' Chaki says. ``I see this
as a conflicting message. As soon as someone comes to challenge
their market, they want the government involved. That's disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (cable modem and DSL high-speed telephone access) reaches
critical mass, it will make sense for the Federal Communications
Commission to come in and regulate,'' Chaki says. He says what
MindSpring and others should do in the meantime is aggregate
customers so they can go to the cable companies with millions of
customers that the cable companies will be more than willing to
bring into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulatory business is very risky,'' Chaki says.
``MindSpring doesn't have a clue what it's getting into. The cable
companies and the telecos have had strong, powerful lobbies in
Washington for years. They own their cable and telephone customers.
They're not just going to roll over and die,'' Chaki says. ``It's
going to be difficult going for ISPs in the broadband world.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
