<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-SERMONS-ART-     03-09 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-SERMONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS WRITING IN AMERICA: GUIDING THE WEARY TO THE PROMISED
LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When you're a reader, you take your memorable
passages where you find them _ sometimes in unexpected, unheralded
places. Read, for example, these words of biblical power from a
commentary on Isaiah's ``shadow of a great rock in a weary land,''
spoken in Kansas in the mid-19th century by a preacher known as
Brother Carper:
</P>
<P>
   ``A scene of unrelieved waste; an ocean made of powder, into
which the curse of angered heaven had ground a portion of earth.
Now and then, a huge rock, like shattered shafts and fallen
monuments in a neglected graveyard, and big enough to be the
tombstone of millions, would lift its mossless sides above the
accumulating sands. No poisonous serpent or venomous beast here
await their prey, for death here has ended his work and dwells amid
silence.''
</P>
<P>
   That description of desolation, intended as a spiritual
metaphor, is a reminder of the wonderfully vivid language that can
be found in religious writing in America over centuries. Now the
Library of America has published ``American Sermons: The Pilgrims
to Martin Luther King Jr.'' This handsome 940-page book includes
about 60 sermons by the likes of John Winthrop, Jonathan Edwards,
Ralph Waldo Emerson, Fulton J. Sheen and many lesser-known
practitioners of the great American tradition of Sunday morning (or
for some, Saturday morning) preaching.
</P>
<P>
   To peruse this work is to become reacquainted with the literary
eloquence of our distant and recent past and to observe what has
happened to rhetoric itself over the centuries. For example, the
book may well demonstrate that the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
was the last of the great traditional American rhetoricians in a
line stretching back to the earliest sermon known to have been
preached on American soil: one by Robert Cushman, visiting Plymouth
Colony in 1621, a year after the arrival of the Mayflower.
</P>
<P>
   For those men who ``looke after great riches, ease, pleasure,
dainties and jollitie in this world ... I would not advise them to
come there, for as yet the country will afford no such matters,''
Cushman says. ``But if there be any who are content to lay out
their estates, spend their time, labors and endeavors for the
benefit of them that shall come after and in desire to further the
Gospell among those poore heathens ... such men I would advise and
encourage to goe, for their ends cannot faile them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way from Cushman to King, yet the two seem linked
by the tradition of protest and the search for freedom that are the
main strains of American history.
</P>
<P>
   In both _ Cushman obliquely, King explicitly _ there is the
metaphor of the American promised land, which can be attained if
only men would practice what King called ``a kind of dangerous
unselfishness.''
</P>
<P>
   The last sermon included in the Library of America book is a
famous King sermon delivered during a strike by sanitation workers
in Memphis on April 3, 1968, when he seemed to sense that his death
was near.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere I read that the greatness of America is the right to
protest for right,'' he said. He continues with a disquisition on
the preacher's special role: ``Somehow, the preacher must say with
Jesus, `The spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he hath anointed
me to deal with the problems of the poor.'''
</P>
<P>
   Probably half of the sermons reflect American Puritanism; for
example, sermons of a rather formal and predictable structure that
relate some passage of Scripture to the ``life and manners of men
in a simple and plaine speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Included, for instance, is a sober and scholarly defense of the
death sentence for murderers by Increase Mather, father of what may
have been Colonial America's most influential New England
theologian.
</P>
<P>
   ``For murder is such a crime as does pollute the very land where
it is done,'' Mather said. ``Not only the person that has shed
blood is polluted thereby, but the whole land lieth under pollution
until such time as justice is done upon the murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   While Increase Mather seems lawyerly and judicious, his son
Cotton's sermon ``The Wonders of the Invisible World,'' a sermon
about witches doing the Devil's bidding, appears today to be little
more than eloquent superstition:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil, exhibiting himself ordinarily as a small black man,
has decoy'd a fearful knot of proud, froward, ignorant, envious and
malicious creatures to list themselves in his horrid service by
entring their names in a book, by him tendred unto them.'' One of
the most striking statements is Theodore Parker's stinging 1846
protest against the Mexican War, through which the United States
annexed most of today's Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Parker issues a kind of bill of indictment against war, giving
detailed statistics on its terrible cost in money and materials. At
the center of his sermon is an almost cinematic vision of men who
do not know one another yet engage in ferocious, impersonal
slaughter:
</P>
<P>
   ``There they lie _ the two masses of burning valor _
extinguished, quenched and grimly dead, each covering with his body
the spot he defended with his arms. They had no quarrel; yet they
lie there, slain by a brother's hand.'' Parker continues with a
vivid picture of those who are maimed for life, ``pierced by the
lances and torn with the shot, till scarce anything human is
left.''
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, Parker declares, ``Our invasion of Mexico is
as bad as the partition of Poland in the last century.''
</P>
<P>
   Brother Carper's sermon was published from memory by a Methodist
missionary named J.V. Watson, who transcribed it into a kind of
black dialect, which I have retranscribed into standard English. In
the original transcription, ``of'' becomes ``ob'' and ``is''
becomes ``am,'' as in: ``Brederen, de text am as full ob latter-day
glory as am de sun ob light.'' At a time when many preachers were
railing against the slave power, Carper's statement is entirely
evangelical and nonpolitical. Slavery is not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of these sermons have the figurative power of a Brother
Carper or a Henry Ward Beecher. Some are, naturally enough, hokey,
at least as seen in today's irony-laden age. There is a good deal
of soggy moralism here as well. And there are plenty of statements
to be found in this book that would be offensive to one group or
another today.
</P>
<P>
   But taken as a whole, the sermon form is revealed to have
remarkable literary vitality. Influenced by the Bible, tinged by
African and evangelical cadences, the sermons constitute a very
American idiom. One can read these as historical artifacts, which
they are. I found them satisfying as literature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
