u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-GUILLEN-CO     03-09 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GUILLEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guillen not ready to rest
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Ozzie Guillen likes to moan about his
age by saying that he's old, ailing and just doesn't have it
anymore. But he leaves the complaints at the clubhouse door.
</P>
<P>
   Especially now. Guillen, the Braves 35-year-old backup
shortstop, is playing like a young man this spring, like a rookie
desperate to make the team. His performance even has caught some of
his teammates by surprise, including fellow Venezuelan Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You're signed to a two-year contract; take it
easy,' '' Perez said. ``He's like, `No, no, no, I've got to be
ready. I don't want to take it easy. I've got to go hard, so I can
be ready to play more this year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's game against the Mets, Guillen was hitting .571
in three games, with four hits in seven at-bats. He has a double, a
triple and five RBIs in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, I didn't even care about the spring,'' Guillen
said. ``I knew I was going to be the starting shortstop. . . . But
after the experience I had last year, every day is a challenge. You
never know what's going to happen. Every day to me is a big day.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen said he coasted last spring, as he had during springs
with the White Sox. But this year, he recognized the need to
change.
</P>
<P>
   After 13 years as a starter for the White Sox, Guillen, a former
American League rookie of the year and the three-time All-Star and
Gold Glove winner, got his first pink slip. He had signed with the
Baltimore Orioles in January, began the season by going 1 for 16
and was released on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Guillen said. ``After you play for so many
years with one team, you're a star, and then you get released. They
make you think you cannot play this game anymore. It breaks you
down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves signed him five days later.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen responded by hitting .277, his highest batting average
in four years. He filled in for the injured Walt Weiss and played
in 58 games. During the offseason, Guillen signed a two-year deal
worth $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ozzie saved our rear end last season,'' manager Bobby Cox
said. ``When Walt went down, we were really in trouble. He really
picked up the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen is a talker. And the Braves' young players are
listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart,'' Perez said. ``He talks a lot, but he knows what
he's saying.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, just watching him play might be example enough for
other Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to leave the game the way I came in, with my head
up,'' Guillen said. ``I know I can still play. The day I can't play
anymore is the day I go home.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
