<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALM BEACH OUT
 &HT;    CLINTON PRAISES TROOPS FOR HURRICANE EFFORTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) International categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras Visiting the troops who participated in
the largest military humanitarian mission since the Berlin Airlift
a half century ago, President Clinton praised them Tuesday for
their efforts in the wake of Hurricane Mitch last fall.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief speech at Soto Cano Air Force Base, the home of the
Honduran Air Force Academy, Clinton recalled the massive military
operation that rescued thousands of people and began to rebuild the
infrastructure of Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane killed more than 8,200 people in Central America.
Another 9,300 have been missing since the end of October and are
considered dead. The total of more than 17,000 deaths would equal
American losses during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that more than 47 million pounds of supplies moved
through Soto Cano.
</P>
<P>
   ``This long runway, turned into a lifeline ... (and) restored
faith in the future that nearly washed away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton visited a bridge linking two sides of
Tegucigalpa, the Honduran capital that was destroyed during the
hurricane and rebuilt by U.S. and Honduran troops. Clinton called
the bridge symbolic of ``building bridges between people and
nations in Central America with Central America itself the bridge
between North and South America.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the more than $250 million spent by the military
since Hurricane Mitch, Clinton announced a $56 million military
training operation would bring more than 23,000 National Guard and
U.S. Reserve troops to Central America between now and August to
build school, roads and health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the administration's request for $956 million in
emergency assistance to Central America remained tied up in
Congress because of a dispute over whether the money should come
from the federal budget surplus or reduced domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said the administration
expected the money to come from the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think we should pit one program against another when
aid is clearly needed,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
