<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE WHITNEY, THE BIENNIAL HAS TURNED INTO A TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Calif., Conn., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The other shoe has dropped at the Whitney Museum of
American Art. Five months after a staff shake-up, the museum
recently announced that for the first time in its history, its
Biennial survey of American art, scheduled to open in March 2000,
would be organized by a team of six curators from outside the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   The restructured 2000 Biennial is the latest shot by Maxwell
Anderson, the classicist and former director of the Art Gallery of
Ontario, who has been shaking up the Whitney ever since he took
over as director in early September.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the restructuring reflects his vision of the museum or
is a rabbit being skillfully pulled from a hat just in time remains
to be seen. But questions hang in the air: Can it be done in the
allotted time? Will so many cooks make it bland and characterless?
Is it really a Whitney Biennial if it is farmed out? And how does
the farming out affect the staff, almost all of which must be
involved in the show's final stages?
</P>
<P>
   Since its start in the late 1960s the Biennial has traditionally
been a two-year project overseen by three or four Whitney curators
who visit dozens of studios nationwide to make their choices. From
beginning to end there are delicate negotiations with artists,
dealers and collectors, vast amounts of paperwork and untold
advance planning.
</P>
<P>
   After a high-speed, three-to-four-week installation period the
show fills the entire museum with works in every art medium.
Sometimes artists make works specially for the show, like a
sculpture by Charles Ray, a toy firetruck blown up to life size,
which was installed in front of the Whitney during the 1993
Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   This time the works will be selected by a committee of six art
professionals from six regions, most of whom work full time at
other institutions. They will meet a few times in person, then
communicate through conference calls and on a private Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever organizes the Biennial, it has always been a flawed,
partial and contested sampling of current American art as well as
the Whitney's most prominent identifying characteristic. Basically
a Biennial is almost always on view or being planned at the
Whitney, and this gives the museum a presence unlike any other in
American art. Each new incarnation raises hopes, lets them down and
says something about the state of American art and even more about
the Whitney: what it thinks of American art and is willing to
tolerate as art.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Biennial has always been mutable, because it
has been constantly buffeted by criticism and changes in the art
landscape. In 1975, responding to perennial complaints that the
show was too New York-centric and market driven, the Whitney
curators selected only artists who lived outside New York or had
never had a solo gallery show in the city. During the tenure of
Anderson's predecessor, David Ross, the 1993, 1995 and 1997
Biennials were overseen by a single Whitney curator who usually
consulted with others at the museum but made the final choices,
resulting in an unusually distinct and personal series of
exhibitions that made no claim to objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on the new strategy, Anderson said the 2000
Biennial would take a ``fresh approach to the Whitney's signature
tradition'' and would have the benefit of a ``national
perspective.'' In a phone conversation last week, he declined to
say that this Biennial would set a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am eager to see how this works out, but I'm not prepared to
say that it's part of a larger scheme,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the 2000 Biennial had dangled in the wind since late
October when Thelma Golden, its organizer, resigned after Anderson
reorganized the staff.
</P>
<P>
   After she left, the show was to be organized by Lisa Phillips, a
veteran of many Biennials, but in December Ms. Phillips resigned to
become director of the New Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo.
Although she had been considering jobs outside the museum for some
time, many people inside and outside the Whitney hoped she would
provide continuity as Anderson acclimated himself to the New York
art world.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization, which assigned ``portfolios'' to curators by
medium or artistic period, was widely seen as a flashing exit sign
for Ms. Golden and Elizabeth Sussman, neither of whom received an
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   These two curators were closely associated with Ross and were
identified with the emphasis on political art in the first half of
his seven-year tenure. They were both criticized for exhibitions
that many considered too political, Ms. Golden for the 1994
exhibition ``Black Male: Representations of Masculinity in
Contemporary American Art,'' Ms. Sussman for the 1993 Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   Two other museum officials have resigned since Anderson took
over. Adam Weinberg, the senior curator, left in late October to
become director of the Addison Gallery of American Art in Andover,
Mass. In November Constance Wolf, head of the education department,
was named director of the newly established Jewish Museum in San
Francisco. The result has been the biggest shake-up at a major New
York museum in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz in art circles was multidimensional, including
conjecture about replacements for departed curators, possible job
hunting by other members of the Whitney staff, stress levels at the
museum, the advisability of the reorganization and whether there
were divisions on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports that the show would be organized by an outside
panel began to circulate early last month. The question was, who
would be on it?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson admitted that several of his first choices turned him
down _ ``When you want something done, you go to busy people,'' he
said _ and that he had met only half the people who accepted. Even
so, with the announcement he may have regained some control of a
chaotic situation. He has organized a team that, in terms of
resumes and backgrounds, is diverse enough to conceivably put
together a decent Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   With members from California, Texas and Illinois, Anderson's
team represents nearly all regions of the United States, though it
pointedly skips New York City, or at least Manhattan. Ranging in
age from 36 to 56 and including three men and three women, the
panel meets what might be called today's standard of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The spectrum of professional experience is broad, ranging from
that of Hugh Davies, director of the Museum of Contemporary Art,
San Diego, La Jolla, who organized its current exhibition of
Francis Bacon's Papal portraits, to Valerie Cassel, who is director
of the visiting artist program at the School of the Art Institute
of Chicago, where she has organized panels and one exhibition,
``Fierce Cravings: Deconstructing Black Sexuality in Film and
Video.''
</P>
<P>
   The other members are Lawrence Rinder, director of the Institute
for Exhibitions and Public Programs at the California College of
Arts and Crafts in San Francisco and Oakland; Andrea Miller-Keller,
who was until recently a curator of contemporary art at the
Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn.; Jane Farver, a former
director of exhibitions at the Queens (N.Y.) Museum of Art who has
just been appointed director of the List Visual Arts Center at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and Michael Auping, chief
curator at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this team will have enough time, knowledge and influence
necessary to put together a successful show remains a question; but
here, too, Anderson may be changing the mold. He said the group
would determine the selection process to be used in choosing works
for the Biennial over the next few weeks and that he hoped it would
be by consensus, not by voting.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and the group would meet in person ``at least a
couple of times'' and communicate with conference calls and on
their Web site, which will have images of art, artists'
biographies, a time line of the show's progress and a skeleton of
its catalog. The members of the team will travel in their regions
to the extent they need to.
</P>
<P>
   But selecting artists is not the same as planning a show, much
less getting it in place. This involves selecting specific works,
deciding which and how much space they will have and working
closely with the Whitney's support staff to determine how it will
all be engineered. To try this with people in different parts of
the country who have never worked with the Whitney staff or space,
or with one another, could be a recipe for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Other problems remain. This format could result in a return to
the more anonymous, by-consensus Biennials of the 1970s and '80s,
when blandness tended to prevail because of horse-trading and deal
making.
</P>
<P>
   The ``national perspective'' notion seems old-fashioned. Whitney
curators have always traveled extensively and talked to local
curators and critics in selecting their shows, taking advantage of
a fairly well-organized curatorial network that already includes
some of the new team members.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 68 artists in the 1997 Biennial, 31 lived outside New
York, and both the 1997 and 1995 Biennials moved toward defining
Americanness in the broadest sense by including artists from Mexico
and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the 2000 Biennial that Ms. Golden had been working
on for nine months before she left the Whitney and whose list she
has said she was just beginning to solidify. Her Biennial would
have been another of the relatively personalized single-curator
exhibitions that Ross instigated, the fourth in a string of
Biennials that have had the distinction of being extremely
different from one another and more memorable than most of their
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition the Whitney was poised to make a bit of history.
When black curators in major museums can be counted on the fingers
of one hand, Ms. Golden was the first black person to be in charge
of a Biennial, which put the Whitney on the forefront of changes
that are occurring throughout the art world. (In October the first
non-European, a Nigerian curator and poet named Okwui Enwezor, was
announced as the artistic director for Documenta XI, to be held in
Kassel, Germany, in 2003.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Golden's Biennial stood a good chance of being more than
just a benchmark in the history of the art world's integration.
Whatever one thought of ``Black Male,'' it was Ms. Golden's first
major exhibition, organized when she was only 26. Her recent,
beautifully installed retrospective of the 1960s figurative painter
Bob Thompson suggested a maturing of her talent as a curator.
Regardless of the quality of the revised 2000 Biennial, it is a
loss that Ms. Golden's efforts will not come to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is that this Biennial will be in but not of the
Whitney. The Biennial has always represented the Whitney's
curatorial voice. Whether it was done by several curators or by one
or two, it was the work of someone identified with and committed to
the institution. Can it have the same meaning or impact when it is
organized by curators who have no long-term stake in the
institution?
</P>
<P>
   None of this may matter much in the long run except as an
instance of either the Whitney choosing the safer road or its new
director making the changes new directors often make, only faster.
The stopgap Biennial will come and go and probably make people just
as unhappy as Ms. Golden's exhibition would have, but to different
people and for different reasons. In the meantime Anderson finds
himself in the position of a new president with several Supreme
Court positions to fill. The Whitney is changing. For better or
worse remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
