<HEADLINE>
KHMER ROUGE LEADER TO BE TRIED IN CAMBODIA, PROSECUTOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ The Khmer Rouge commander Ta Mok will be
charged under a 1994 law that bans membership in the brutal
communist group and may also face charges of genocide, a Cambodian
prosecutor said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said that Ta Mok, 72, who is implicated in the
deaths of more than a million people from 1975 to 1979 when the
Khmer Rouge held power, has refused to answer questions until he is
provided a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested on Saturday and is the first Khmer Rouge leader
to face legal proceedings. Three other top figures have been
allowed to ``defect'' to the government since mid-1996 and have
been living freely in Cambodia along with scores of second-level
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Ta Mok intensify the debate over the status
of these other leaders, and Cambodian officials have made
contradictory statements this week over whether they, too, might
face charges and whether a trial might be held in Cambodia or in an
international court.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Gen. Sao Sok, said that Ta Mok would be tried in
Cambodia but that it was unclear whether he would be tried by a
civilian or a military court.
</P>
<P>
   A team of three international lawyers has recommended to the
United Nations that as many as 20 to 30 Khmer Rouge figures face
charges in an international court. Most prominent among them, along
with Ta Mok, are Ieng Sary, the former foreign minister who
surrendered in 1996, as well as Khieu Samphan, the former head of
state, and Nuon Chea, a top ideologue, who both surrendered in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen has appeared to leave his options open,
both supporting an international tribunal and warning of its
potentially destabilizing consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In televised remarks on Tuesday, he repeated an earlier
assertion that he had given the Khmer Rouge leaders who surrendered
no guarantees of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to reaffirm my point that I have not guaranteed anyone
exemption from responsibility before the law,'' he said. ``I could
not even provide guarantees to my children and my wife that they
are free from charges by the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief government spokesman, Khieu Kanharith, suggested on
Tuesday that the prosecution of Ta Mok could lead to charges
against his colleagues. ``This is like a Pandora's box,'' he said.
``Ta Mok could point to this man or that man. Many people could be
implicated.''
</P>
<P>
   But Foreign Minister Hor Nam Hong took a different tack, saying
Ta Mok had been captured and was therefore vulnerable to charges,
whereas the other leaders had earned immunity by surrendering and
pledging allegiance to the government.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most foreign analysts argue that the Cambodian court system is
not capable of carrying out fair and procedurally sound trials of
this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   In their report to the United Nations, the international lawyers
recommended an international court because of the primitive and
politically dependent nature of the Cambodian legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Roth, executive director of Human Rights Watch, based in New
York, suggested that Cambodian officials should hold Ta Mok and
other Khmer Rouge leaders in custody while an international
tribunal is being set up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ta Mok will never receive a fair trial in a Cambodian court,
nor is a trial in Cambodia likely to bring out the full truth about
how the Khmer Rouge operated,'' he said. ``The lack of independence
and professionalism of the Cambodian courts is one of the primary
reasons an international tribunal is needed for the Khmer Rouge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
