<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE BAUER ASSAILS BUSH'S COMMENTS ON ABORTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to strengthen his beachhead on the
Republican right, prospective presidential contender Gary Bauer on
Tuesday criticized recent attempts by Gov. George W. Bush to
soft-pedal abortion as a key GOP issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party should not simply have a `pro-life tenor' but a
clear commitment to the intrinsic value of every unborn child,''
Bauer, a leading conservative activist and former Reagan
administration official, said in a statement issued by his
presidential exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent interview, Bauer said he was responding to a
Bush speech Sunday and interview Monday in which the Texas governor
expressed both his opposition to abortion and reluctance to make
the issue central to a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it was extraordinary'' that at the press
conference ``he referred to legislation to end abortion as being
hypothetical,'' Bauer said. ``This is a 26-year debate in a party
that has been unambiguously in favor of such legislation in its
platform since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how you can be a `compassionate conservative' and
be confused about protecting unborn children,'' Bauer said from his
committee headquarters in Virginia's Washington suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer refused to assign any political motivation to his remarks,
saying, ``I feel strongly enough about it that I couldn't let the
(Bush) comments go uncommented on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer supporters and other Republican analysts said Bush's
comments and Bauer's response could be useful in motivating voters
for whom opposition to abortion is a major reason for their
political involvement.
</P>
<P>
   That may be especially true in states that come early in the
nominating process, including Alaska, Louisiana, Iowa and New
Hampshire. Abortion opponents play a key role in Republican
politics in each of the four.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the Republican nominee in 2000, you've got to be able to
make in an articulate way the case for the idea that all of our
children are, in fact, protected by the Constitution,'' Bauer said.
``That means being willing to appoint only pro-life judges, to have
an unambiguous pro-life running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has steered clear of promising either.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been joined in his refusal to emphasize abortion by
Elizabeth Hanford Dole, the former Republican Cabinet official who
in national polling shares the GOP lead with Bush. Dole, like Bush,
has sidestepped questions about a number of specific policy
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the front-runners have been ironically vague about
where they stand on a whole host of very important issues,'' Bauer
said. ``Maybe intentionally. Maybe that's why they're
front-runners, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``So any time we can get clarity, I'm certainly going to speak
up if I think that the party is going in a direction different than
the Reagan vision that was so successful for us,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer criticized the refusal of the last two Republican
presidential candidates _ Bush's father in 1992 and Dole's husband
in 1996 _ to run strong anti-abortion campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope we have learned something from the last two
presidential elections, that we shrink the size of the (Republican)
tent when we seem confused about our pro-life position.''
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares a presidential campaign, the Texas governor has
been careful to include opponents and supporters of abortion
rights. Advocates of both positions were among the leaders of his
exploratory committee announced Sunday, but neither he or the
committee members spoke about abortion until it was raised by
reporters in questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
