<HEADLINE>
FORMER GOV. ALEXANDER MAKES ANOTHER RUN FOR PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ It was Lamar Alexander's turn in the
Republican presidential campaign spotlight Tuesday, but the
reflection of rival George W. Bush's effort could be seen _ or
heard _ anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, the former Tennessee governor and U.S. education
secretary in the White House administration of Bush's father,
formally announced his second try for the presidency with a call
for better schools and lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be on the side of parents raising children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who ran for the GOP nomination in 1996 and has been
aiming toward his latest candidacy ever since, took on criticism
that he is old news in the presidential sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say I've been working awfully hard to prepare for
the job of president,'' he said. ``I can assure you, if I could
find an easier way, I'd do it. But among Republicans in modern
times, only General (Dwight) Eisenhower made it the first time he
tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and former American Red Cross chief Elizabeth Hanford Dole,
the leading candidates for the GOP nomination in surveys of
Republican voters, will be taking their first shot at the White
House if they go through with plans to declare their candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Dole is to announce her exploratory committee, a preliminary
step in which a candidate can raise money without formally
declaring, Wednesday in Des Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a gray business suit, Alexander, 58, delivered his
speech to supporters in the State Capitol's Old Supreme Court
chamber. It was a marked departure from 1995, when he launched his
campaign in his hometown of Maryville, Tenn., in the foothills of
the Great Smoky Mountains, wearing his then-trademark red and black
lumberjack shirt and playing the bluegrass song ``Rocky Top'' on a
piano.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Alexander explained, he wanted to emphasize his
experience as a governor _ he served from 1979-1986 _ who helped
improve public schools and attracted foreign investment to the
state. Bush is expected to run by emphasizing his Texas record.
</P>
<P>
   And while Republican-elected officials from across the country
are flocking to Bush's campaign, Alexander's kick-off served as a
reminder that Bush has no monopoly on party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee and Tennessee Gov. Don Sundquist
were on hand to express support for Alexander, along with
Alexander's national campaign chairman, former Iowa Gov. Terry
Branstad. The Iowa caucuses early next year will be one of the
first key votes of the nomination race.
</P>
<P>
   Branstad remarked that the winner will be a leader in tune with
the concerns of common people, ``not the person with the most
famous name,'' an apparent reference to the political history
behind the Bush and Dole names.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has steadfastly criticized Bush's ``compassionate
conservative'' theme as ``weasel words'' for shallow thinking. In
his kick-off speech, Alexander vowed to be the kind of candidate
``who knows from the first day in office exactly what they would
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a former president of the University of Tennessee,
proposed to reduce government control of schools because ``teachers
and principals are suffering under court orders, union rules and
government regulations.'' He favors a national voucher-type program
that would give scholarship money for elementary school students to
attend the private or public school of their family's choice.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government should triple to personal income tax
deduction for each child, to $8,000, and abolish capital gains
taxes and estate taxes, Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the U.S. military needs strengthening to protect
the nation from terrorism, and that a new branch of the military
should be established to help stop the importation of illegal
drugs. He backed the deployment of a strategic missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when a strong economy and peace have buoyed President
Clinton's performance rating among voters, Alexander painted a dark
picture of the nation under Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, a
former Tennessee senator readying his own presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look behind their magic show and see what has really happened
in the last six years since they took over,'' Alexander said.
``Twelve more countries have jumped over us in high school
graduation rates, taxes are higher, the federal regulation book is
thicker, our national defense is weaker ... dictators thumb their
noses at us; we are more divided than ever by race; and our
standards of right and wrong have sunk to a new low.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Alexander started his campaign for the 1996
nomination with a declaration that the nation had a ``trouble of
the spirit'' that could only be cured by dismantling federal
programs in favor of letting states make decisions on such issues
as Medicaid, job training and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander placed third behind Bob Dole and Pat Buchanan in the
key 1996 Republican primary votes in Iowa and New Hampshire. His
campaign ran short of money and momentum afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out in 1994, before Republicans captured the majority
in Congress, Alexander said the antidote for the
Democratic-controlled Congress was to ``cut their pay and send them
home.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he did not advocate a curtailment of the GOP-led
Congress. Instead, he said public education can be improved if we
``send the Washington bureaucrats home, and send their money to the
states, the classrooms and especially to parents.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
