<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3837 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-ARTISTS     03-09 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-ARTISTS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EUROPEAN ART WORLD, TWO BIG MILESTONES AND A BIENNALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
 (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Europe, 1999 is a special year for some celebrated names in
art. Two revered old masters, Anthony van Dyck and Diego Velazquez,
are birthday boys (both born in 1599) and the marvelous textile
designer Anni Albers (1899-1994) is a birthday girl. Major parties
are being thrown for all three. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres, French portraitist
extraordinaire, is the focus of a much anticipated traveling
exhibition. And the Venice Biennale, that idiosyncratic monument to
the now slightly dusty ideal of The New in contemporary art, will
sail into view in June.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more where all this comes from, of course. And
with cheap flights available these days, and seriously warm weather
on the way, a European art trip is just a matter of spare time,
sensible shoes and a shrewd itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will do well to begin a trip in London, and early birds
will enjoy special rewards, among them ``Portraits by Ingres: Image
of an Epoch'' at the National Gallery through April 25.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingres' sitters were a virtual Who's Who of imperial France in
the Romantic era, from Napoleon I swathed in satin and ermine on
his throne, to the heart-throb handsome painter Francois-Marius
Granet. And his women, with their skimmed-milk skin and boneless
arms, are unforgettable. The portrait of the Vicomtesse
d'Haussonville, on first-time loan from the Frick Collection, is
included in the show, which will sweep on to the National Gallery
of Art in Washington and to the Metropolitan Museum.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of self-portraits, ``Rembrandt by Himself,'' will
take over at the National Gallery from June 9 to Sept. 5. Rembrandt
depicted himself in all moods and seasons, from a punch-drunk young
artist to an older man with a thing for funny hats and a face that
had seen too much. The material in the show may not be news, but
with loans from the Rijksmuseum and Rembrandthuis, no finer
gathering of its kind is likely to be found anywhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rembrandt, who collected Indian miniatures, would surely have
loved ``The Arts of the Sikh Kingdoms'' at the Victoria and Albert
Museum Museum (March 25 to July 25). The 19th-century Sikh
maharajas commissioned a wealth of album paintings, embroidered
silks and elaborately cut gems. No Manhattanite, after a glimpse at
these riches, will look at cabdrivers in turbans quite the same way
again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of London's biggest spring blockbusters have already played
this side of the Atlantic. The New York Museum of Modern Art's
Jackson Pollock retrospective is spinning its magic at the Tate
Gallery through June 6. And ``Monet in the 20th Century,'' which
broke box office records in Boston last fall, is at the Royal
Academy until April 18. Both reward repeat visits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A greater lure for some Americans, though, will be hot new
British art, and ``Neurotic Realism: Part One'' at the Saatchi
Gallery provides a chance to see what some of the fuss is about.
The participants are young, extremely watchable, and on view
through March 28. Also worth a look at the Hayward Gallery through
April 11 is the painter Patrick Caulfield, whose tabletop still
lifes and interiors have something of the crisp, bright urbanity
one associates with his contemporary David Hockney.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hockney himself appears at the Pompidou Center in Paris with a
show of landscapes through April 26, to be followed in June by
another outstanding colorist, Robert Delaunay. Perhaps more
interesting than either is a survey at the Jeu de Paume of the
Japanese avant-garde Gutai Group, which in the 1950s and '60s
generated intensely physical abstract paintings and Dada-inspired
happenings (May 4 to June 27).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paris is also the source of two very different shows of work
from northern Africa. An exhibition titled ``Egyptian Art in the
Age of the Pyramids'' at the Louvre (April 9 to July 12) will
center on spectacular sculpture from the Old Kingdom period, and
will come to the Met later. A historical survey of art from Morocco
is at the Musee des Beaux-Arts de la Ville de Paris from April 14
to July 18. Encompassing objects from prehistoric times to the
present, it could be yet another neo-colonialist folly, but the
bulk of the loans are from Moroccan museums, so there are bound to
be treasures.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Paris visitors will be able to preview another
Met-bound show, ``Cezanne to Van Gogh: The Collection of Doctor
Gachet'' at the Grand Palais (through April 25). Paul-Ferdinand
Gachet (1828-1909) was a physician, an amateur painter and a friend
to leading artists of his day. More important, he was a patron with
ready cash and a superb eye. And although the authorship of some of
the work in his collection has been questioned, there are wonderful
things here.
</P>
<P>
   Royal patronage secured the career of the Flemish painter
Anthony van Dyck, who is being feted by his home city of Antwerp,
Belgium, on the 400th anniversary of his birth. Court artist to
Charles I of England, he both created a type of high society
power-portrait and turned out magnetic religious images. A painting
retrospective at the Koninklijk Museum voor Schone Kunsten in
Antwerp (May 15 to Aug. 15) will be supplemented by exhibitions of
his breathtaking drawings at the Rubenshuis and his prints at the
Museum Plantin-Moretus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brussels is host to work by a latter-day virtuoso of the
celebrity icon in ``Andy Warhol: A Factory,'' at the Palais des
Beaux-Arts through Sept. 19. Organized by Germano Celant of the
Guggenheim Museum in New York, the show brings together some 700
items to document the prodigious industry of a figure who was, in
the American art world of the 1960's as today, a king of kings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of kings, another painter-for-hire to the rich and
famous, Diego Velazquez, will be honored in Spain. The Prado in
Madrid has announced that it will open its new Velazquez galleries
this spring, though exactly when is a question. A show of
Velazquez's early work is promised for next fall in Seville, where
he was born, but again, dates have not been firmed up.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim Bilbao will be host to an exhibition of Richard
Serra's sculptures from April 27 to Oct. 17, while another branch
of the multinational museum, far to the north, the Deutsche
Guggenheim Berlin, has scheduled ``Amazons of the Avant-Garde: Six
Russian Artists'' from July 10 to Oct. 3. As the title suggests,
the artists are women _ Liubov Popova and Natalia Goncharova are
the most familiar names _ who worked in the aftermath of the
Revolution, forging an alliance between fine and applied art that
had lasting repercussions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One artist who felt those repercussions was the Bauhaus weaver
Anni Albers, whose retrospective at the Peggy Guggenheim Collection
in Venice (March 24 to May 24) should be one of this season's quiet
beauties. Also in Venice, Claes Oldenburg and Coosje van Bruggen
will have the run of the Correr Museum and the Salone Napoleonico
from May 22 to Oct. 3 with 200 sculptures, some very large. And the
Venice Biennale opens on June 13 (through Nov. 7.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's always an anticipatory buzz about who will mastermind
this extravaganza, though the choice is usually stunningly
predictable. The ubiquitous Swiss curator Harald Szeemann is at the
helm this year. The installation artist Ann Hamilton will represent
the United States; Germany has given this ambassadorial role to one
if its genuine leading lights, Rosemarie Trockel. Other curatorial
plans, at least at this writing, remain mysterious.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine. For art professionals, the Biennale, whether it
causes waves or barely stays afloat, is a place to be, no matter
what. For other American visitors to Europe, Venice itself is
probably the real attraction, and it is sure to look as venerable
and as birthday-fresh as ever this spring and summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
