<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANUI, ROBA TO DEFEND BOSTON MARATHON TITLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two-time champions Moses Tanui of Kenya and Fatuma Roba
of Ethiopia will be on the starting line April 19 to defend their
Boston Marathon titles, according to the roster of elite athletes
for the 103d running announced Tuesday by race sponsor John
Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   So will 38-year-old Lynn Jennings, the 1992 Olympic bronze
medalist at 10,000 meters from Newmarket, N.H., who will be making
her long-awaited official marathon debut. The three-time World
Cross-Country champion unofficially ran Boston in 1978 when she was
17; had she been a year older and met the age minimum, her
approximate time of 2 hours 46 minutes would have been good for
third place.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings had planned to make her debut last year but, saying she
didn't feel ready, withdrew several weeks before the race.
</P>
<P>
   This time around she seems ready to make the step up in
distance, and has been comfortable enough to share her feelings and
training reports on the Runner's World Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Tanui, who ran a personal best of 2:07:34 to win
last year, is perhaps best known for ending Cosmas Ndeti's
three-year winning streak in 1996 to go down in history as the
champion of the 100th anniversary race. Roba, meanwhile, will be
looking for her third consecutive Boston win since bursting onto
the international scene by taking the gold medal at the 1996
Olympics as a virtual unknown. If she succeeds, the 25-year-old
Roba will become only the second woman to win three straight since
they were officially allowed to enter in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman to do so, Uta Pippig, is currently suspended
from competition, pending a hearing by the German federation, for
failing a drug test last spring. Pippig is disputing the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Roba and Jennings, other women to watch include Colleen
de Reuck (personal best 2:26:35), a 35-year-old South African
living in Boulder, Colo., who finished third here in 1997 and
second last fall in Chicago; Catherine Ndereba, a 26-year-old from
Kenya making her marathon debut who last year was ranked the No. 1
road racer in the world by Runner's World; and Yuko Arimori
(2:28:01), who moved to Boulder in 1997 from Japan. Arimori, 32,
has raced little in the US, but is a two-time Olympic marathon
medalist, with a silver in 1992 and a bronze in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The elite men's field, not surprisingly, is dominated by Kenyans
but also features strong runners from South Africa, Mexico, Brazil,
Ethiopia, Ecuador, and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Tanui has the title, but many Kenyans would love to wrest it
from him, especially 1998 runner-up Joseph Chebet, reigning New
York champion John Kagwe, and Ondoro Osoro, who ran a 2:06:54 to
win Chicago last October. Osoro's time was the third-fastest of all
time and the fastest debut marathon in history.
</P>
<P>
   Chebet, who also was runner-up in New York last year, won the
first two marathons he entered _ Amsterdam in 1996 and Turin in
1997 _ and reportedly has been training all winter toward his goal
of winning Boston.
</P>
<P>
   That's a goal shared by Jackson Kabiga, who in 1998 became the
first Kenyan to win the Fukuoka Marathon, where he set his personal
best of 2:08:42.
</P>
<P>
   Other Kenyans include Kenneth Cheruiyot, who will be making his
marathon debut, road racing veteran Peter Githuka, 1997 Boston
runner-up Joseph Kamau, talented Sammy Korir (2:08:02), and
marathon newcomer Julius Ondieki.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, as usual, will have strong representation with Vanderlei
Lima (2:08:31). Boston veteran Andres Espinosa, 36, who was second
here in 1994 when he ran his personal best of 2:07:19, would like
nothing more than to take a Boston win home to Mexico, as would
countryman German Silva, who has contended here the last two years
(sixth, fourth) and has won twice at New York.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to big-time marathoning include:
</P>
<P>
   --Ethiopian Ambesse Tolosa, 21, who trains in Japan, won at
Hokkaido last summer (2:10:13) and followed with a sixth at Fukuoka
(2:10:27).
</P>
<P>
   --Peruvians Jose Castillo (2:14:15 at London in 1997) and Miguel
Mallqui (2:11:36 at Chicago in '98).
</P>
<P>
   --South African Abner Chipu, who gave indications that he's
ready for a breakthrough with his performance as the pace-setter
for countryman Gert Thys's 2:06:33 in February's Tokyo Marathon _
the second-fastest marathon ever.
</P>
<P>
   --Franklin Tenorio of Ecuador, who ran a 2:10:22 in his debut
marathon in Rome last year, and whose sister, Martha, has been an
elite Boston runner in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the women's field:
</P>
<P>
   --Renata Paradowska, 28, of Poland, who ran a personal best of
2:27:17 here last year in only her second marathon to finish second
behind Roba.
</P>
<P>
   --Franca Fiacconi, 32, of Italy, a 2:25:17 marathoner who is the
defending New York champion.
</P>
<P>
   --Franziska Rochat-Moser, 32, of Switzerland, the 1997 New York
winner who has run 2:27:44.
</P>
<P>
   --Ludmila Petrova, 30, of Russia (2:30:26).
</P>
<P>
   --Christine McNamara, 33, of Boulder (2:28:18).
</P>
<P>
   --And two young runners from China: 20-year-old Sun Yingjie
(2:25:45) and 21-year-old Ai Dongmei (2:27:30).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bill Griffith of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
