<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3843 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-MUSIC-$     03-09 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-MUSIC-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EUROPE, BATONS AT THE READY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those seeking summer musical delight across the Atlantic,
there is always the danger that the musicians you heard all winter
will be on the plane with you.
</P>
<P>
   If that little bit of home in a foreign place is just the
comfort you are looking for, then by all means don't miss Jessye
Norman and Winton Marsalis in London, or Renee Fleming at the
Schleswig-Holstein Festival. If you couldn't get enough of Garrick
Ohlsson at New York's Lincoln Center this season, he will be at the
International Piano Festival of Roque d'Antheron in France in
mid-August, surrounded by a lot of the old gang: Radu Lupu, Helene
Grimaud, Stephen Hough, Jean Efflam Bavouzet, all of whom have made
recent passes through Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   If you are off to Europe for new and different experiences,
think about two festivals: the one at Aix-en-Provence in France and
the Salzburg Festival in Austria. At both, you will find
concentrated quality and innovation, as well as things less easily
come by at home.
</P>
<P>
   Salzburg offers new productions of Busoni's storied but little
seen ``Doktor Faustus'' with Thomas Hampson (American singers are
everywhere), Luciano Berio's new ``Cronaca del Luogo'' and from the
18th-century ``Les Boreades'' by Rameau. There will be a new ``Don
Giovanni'' and performances of Mussorgsky's ``Khovanshchina,''
Berg's ``Lulu'' and Berlioz's ``Damnation of Faust.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aix festival, with carefully prepared productions played in
delightful courtyard venues, brings new stagings of Monteverdi's
``Incoronazione di Poppea'' and ``Cena Furiosa,'' Offenbach's
``Belle Helene'' and Mozart's ``Magic Flute.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for the isolated exotic event, how about the
Bolshoi Theater's production of ``The Oprichnik'' having its final
performances in Moscow on June 22 and 26? Soviet censors thought
that Tchaikovsky's opera about intrigue at the court of Ivan the
Terrible hit a little too close to home. For this reason, and a few
built-in ones, it has virtually disappeared during this century.
</P>
<P>
   Russianness is flooding Europe in waves. For most of May in
Royal Festival Hall in London, Vladimir Ashkenazy and the
Philharmonia Orchestra take a long look at Rachmaninoff in a
festival titled ``Rachmaninoff Hidden Perspectives.'' All the big
piano favorites will be heard, with Evgeny Kissin, Arcadi Volodos
and Mikhail Pletnev to play them, as will the much loved Second
Symphony. But the real idea is to put the beloved together with
less familiar pieces like the ``The Bells'' and the opera
``Francesca da Rimini.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are also invading, of all places, Italy. By the
time Florence's Maggio Musicale has had done with Tchaikovsky's
``Queen of Spades'' in April, the Spoleto Festival will be
preparing for its run of Prokofiev's opera ``War and Peace'' (the
original version) beginning June 25, with seven as yet unspecified
repeat performances to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar Russian faces will present themselves at London's
Barbican Center: the St. Petersburg Philharmonic under Yuri
Temirkanov (June 9 and 11) followed in a few days by another
``Queen of Spades'' and Shostakovich's ``Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk,''
both with the ever-present Kirov Opera under the scarcely avoidable
Valery Gergiev.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to wait until September for the other major theme
event, when the Berliner Festwochen hopes to play every legitimate
note Mahler ever wrote. From Sept. 3 to 29, with only two days off,
the Berlin and Vienna Philharmonics, six other orchestras and
conductors, including Claudio Abbado and Simon Rattle, will cover
much ground and a lot of Weltschmerz. The finale on Sept. 29 is
``Das Lied von der Erde'' with the Berlin, Abbado, Ben Heppner and
Deborah Polaski.
</P>
<P>
   If you like your themes more metaphysical, think about
``Apokalypse,'' this year's title of the Vienna International
Festival, from May 7 until the middle of June. The mysterious
Biblical predictions of catastrophe and salvation will take musical
form in pieces like Franz Schmidt's ``Book of the Seven Seals,''
Schumann's ``Scenes From Goethe's `Faust','' Handel's ``Messiah,''
Haydn's ``Seven Last Words of Christ on the Cross'' and Messiaen's
``Quartet for the End of Time.''
</P>
<P>
   If this whets your appetite for mystery, wait until the middle
of August when the Lucerne Festival in Switzerland addresses the
subject of myths and mythology in music. From Aug. 14 to Sept. 11,
the legends of Faust, ``The Rite of Spring'' and ``Pelleas et
Melisande'' will be considered, as will Othmar Schoeck's opera
``Penthesilea.'' Resident mystics will be two composers from the
East: Frangis Ali-sade, of Azerbaijan, and Giya Kancheli, of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you are going to European music festivals for the places
as much as for the music, and so a few familiar faces won't be
bothersome. Indeed, you may have missed Thomas Ades' ``Powder Her
Face'' in Brooklyn or Wolfgang Holzmaier at Alice Tully Hall, or
Alfred Brendel playing the piano and reading his own poetry at
Carnegie Hall; if so, they will all be at Britain's Aldeburgh
Festival June 11-27, with varied events spread around this amiable
seaside town. Fresher for the ears will be Aldeburgh's featured
composer, Per Norgard, as well as a close look at Conlon Nancaroow.
</P>
<P>
   Another target for the sybarite is the Glyndebourne Festival
Opera with its customary intermission pleasures: alfresco picnics
among the sheep, dressed-up audiences and the occasional pretension
(candelabra and butlers).
</P>
<P>
   But Glyndebourne is, as always, serious business, with new
productions of Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande'' and Smetana's
``Bartered Bride.'' They will join such revivals as Handel's
``Rodelinda'' and the new Jonathan Dove piece ``Flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you want to sit in one place and see lots of
different operas, think about Munich, where in July you can witness
more than a dozen works from the standard repertory, in performance
just about every night of the month. That's easy on the travel
budget, but oh, those hotel bills! Maybe you can stay with a
friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
