<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KUBRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK'S FINAL FILM GENERATES JUICY RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick was putting the finishing touches on his last
film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' when he died of a heart attack in his
home in Hertfordshire, England, last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old filmmaker, whose penchant for secrecy was
extreme, made his cast and crew swear not to reveal anything about
the film, which is scheduled to be released by Warner Bros. on July
16.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement from the film's stars, Tom Cruise and
Nicole Kidman, the film is complete except for ``final looping and
mixing.'' That means the movie had passed final edit and the only
tasks remaining were for the actors to dub in a few lines that did
not meet Kubrick's precise specifications and for the soundtrack to
be tweaked.
</P>
<P>
   The film has been screened for two Warner executives, co-CEOs
Robert A. Daly and Terry Semel. ``It is a fantastic and a fitting
close to a tremendous career,'' they said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that the story of a Viennese doctor (Cruise)
and his wife (Kidman), who play out sexual fantasies, will be one
of Kubrick's most controversial. An overexcited Harvey Keitel was
allegedly released from the film because a sexual scene with Kidman
got out of control. He was replaced by actor-director Sydney
Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a story going around that a trailer for ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' features Kidman's bare breasts and Cruise's bare bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A rumor noted in the British press holds that there are scenes
in which Cruise's character plays a transvestite. According to The
Daily Telegraph, Kidman let slip that Kubrick dealt with her and
Cruise separately. ``When you see the film, you will see why,'' she
reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual themes have already caused some ripples at Warner
Bros., where executives are concerned that the film might receive
the dreaded NC-17 rating. Some newspapers refuse to take
advertisements for the rating, and many suburban theaters refuse to
show them. However, no matter what the rating, Warner Bros. is
contractually bound not to alter Kubrick's final cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1820EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
