A3850 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-DANCE-$     03-09 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-DANCE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN DANCE'S DIGITAL SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the happiest species of tourists traveling through Europe
this summer is likely to be the dance aficionado with an interest
in technology and how it enhances or changes the art. Technology
and dance _ an increasingly popular topic in the United States _
will be examined in festivals in Denmark and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A technological dance tour of Europe should probably start in
Barcelona with ``Merce Cunningham: 50 Years,'' an exhibition with
material on Cunningham's computer and video ``motion capture''
experimentation with Paul Kaiser and Shelley Eshkar. The show will
be at the exquisitely beautiful air-and-light-filled museum
Fundacio Antoni Tapies through April 4, before moving to Portugal
and the Fundacao de Serralves in Porto (Sept. 10 to Nov. 7).
</P>
<P>
   A next stop for dance techies might be Aarhus in Denmark, where
the biennial Dansedage International Dance Festival (May 20 to June
6) will feature performances created or enhanced by digital
technology, and workshops and seminars. Festival companies include
Le Corps Indice from Canada, Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker's troupe
from Belgium, and England's DV8, with the Kaiser-Eshkar video
installation ``Ghostcatching.'' And in Berlin, the international
Korper-tecnik festival (June 4 to July 4) will examine ``the
context of the body in digital times.''
</P>
<P>
   England wins the honors this summer for the most varied dance
menu. The Brighton Festival (May 1 to 23) features new work by
Siobhan Davies, a ``dance on camera'' minifestival and a dance that
unfolds in a landscape of charred wood and melting ice at locations
throughout this seaside city.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Ballet will present four programs at the historic
Sadler's Wells Theater in London (July 6 to 31), featuring
``Giselle,'' Frederick Ashton's ``Ondine'' and two mixed bills of
mostly recent English choreography.
</P>
<P>
   The Edinburgh Festival (Aug. 15 to Sept. 4) offers Meg Stuart,
the American modern-dance choreographer, and her Damaged Goods
company and the Cullberg Ballet of Sweden in Mats Ek's versions of
``Giselle'' and ``The Sleeping Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   For folk-dance enthusiasts, morris dancing is in this summer,
with chances to see and do it at festivals in East Sussex,
Scarborough, North Yorkshire, and Swanage, Dorset. In London in
June and July, the City of London Festival and the Docklands
International Festival offer opportunities to see performances at
historic sites, like the Tower of London.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing festivals promises to be Springdance
99 in Utrecht, the Netherlands (April 13 to 25), which celebrates
both Vaslav Nijinsky's 1913 ballet ``Le Sacre de Printemps'' and
the seminal Judson Church postmodernist dance movement of the 1960s
in New York City. Lisbon's Companhia Nacional de Bailado will
perform the reconstructed Nijinsky ballet, in conjunction with
``Sacred Solos,'' new commissioned works responding to the ballet.
The French Quatuor Knust will present historic Judson projects by
Yvonne Rainer and Steve Paxton. There also will be performances by
the company of Trisha Brown and 18 other groups and soloists.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the summer's most important modern-dance festivals
are in France, at Avignon (July 9 to 31), the Theatre de la Ville
in Paris (through June 26) and in Montpellier. The Montpellier
International Dance Festival (June 25 to July 10) includes
performances indoors and out. Ms. De Keersmaeker is on the bill,
along with Philippe Decoufle, Jose Montalvo, a number of pieces
that incorporate film and video, and an independent dance film
series.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Kuopio Dance Festival (June 30 to July 6) in Kuopio,
Finland, in its 30th year, will feature the Deutsche Oper am Rhein,
Ricardo Franco's Flamenco!!! and Robert North's Fabula Saltica
troupe, as well as Baroque dance and companies from Italy, Israel
and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, summer dance events in the yearlong celebration of
Weimar as the European City of Culture for 1999 include
performances by the Tokyo Ballet (April 3 to 5 and 8 to 10) the
Compania Nacional des Danza, Madrid (April 13, 14, 15, 28 and 29),
and the Bejart Ballet Lausanne (May 14 to 16 and 18 to 20).
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, because of dwindling government support, this may be the
last year for the ambitious, thought-provoking Hammoniale Festival
of Women (June 16 to July 3) in Hamburg. Among the 300 participants
from 25 countries, in all the arts, will be Ea Sola, the
French-Vietnamese choreographer, and the iconic Chandrilekha, from
India.
</P>
<P>
   The honors for the prettiest settings go to festivals in Spain
and Portugal. At the Festival Internacional de Musica y Danza de
Granada 1999 (June 18 to July 4), ballet and modern dance will be
performed outdoors in the gardens of the Alhambra in Granada,
Spain. In Barcelona, the ballet and modern dance attractions at the
Grec 99 festival (June 28 to mid-August) take place primarily
outdoors in the Teatro Grec, and the vast, handsome Mercat des
Flors, a converted flower market. The program includes Catalan
modern dance companies and Alexandre Petrov's Kremlin Ballet
performing ``Tom Sawyer'' and ``Napoleon Bonaparte.''
</P>
<P>
   Romantic dance in a romantic setting can be found in Seteais,
Portugal, at the Noites de Bailado (July 23 to Aug. 29) in the
gardens of the Seteais Hotel-Palace, with performances by the
Scottish Ballet, Danza Contemporanea de Cuba. Ballet de Toscana,
Pennsylvania Ballet and the Hermitage Ballet of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   For those intent on seeing classical ballet or familiar modern
dance in a proscenium theater, a stop at the Royal Theater in
Copenhagen may be in order. The Royal Danish Ballet will be
performing works by Mats Ek, the Swedish modernist, and by Serge
Lifar in April and May. The Tokyo Ballet will offer Maurice
Bejart's reworkings of three Diaghilev classics in early June,
moving on to La Scala in Milan and the Deutsche Oper in Berlin. The
new Peter Schaufuss Ballet Company will perform in Aarhus, Denmark
(Sept. 1 to 3).
</P>
<P>
   In Portugal, the always-exciting Ballet Nacional de Cuba will
perform ``Swan Lake'' at the Coliseu dos Recreios in Lisbon in late
April and early May, followed in late May by the Opera Ballet of
Novosibirsk in ``Giselle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holland Festival (July 5 to 26) and the Julidans festival
(July 5 to 18), both in Amsterdam, will give modern dance fans a
chance to see what European and Canadian modern-dance
choreographers are up to. There is also the Aarhus Festival in
Denmark (Aug. 27 to Sept. 5), this summer focusing on dance from
central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Those who love to dance as well as watch will find a wide range
of folk festivals in theaters, on outdoor stages and in the
streets. Who could resist the Festival Interceltique de Lorient in
the Breton harbor town of Lorient in France (Aug. 6 to 15), for
example, with its Grand Parade of the Celtic Nations and Gathering
of the Flute and Bombarde musicians? Or the exotic-sounding
Jutajaiset International Folklore Festival of Nightless Nights
(June 16 to 20) in Rovaniemi, Finnish Lapland, near the Arctic
Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden will be home to some of the liveliest folk events, among
them the Halsinge Hambo festival (opening July 10) in County
Halsingland, where couples will dance the hambo over 12 hours along
a country road. The Stockholm Water Festival (Aug. 6 to 14) boasts
salsa and African dancing in the city's Palace of Mirrors, and even
a nostalgia disco. There also will be medieval and folk-dancing in
the streets, squares and a 1911 dance hall in the Gotlands
Folkdansfestival (Aug. 15 to 18) on the island of Gotland.
</P>
<P>
   And the teen-agers in the family? Drop them off at the
Hultsfredfestival 1999 (June 17-19) in Hultsfred, where there will
be dancing by disco acts and audiences on seven stages, to the
music of such bands as the Scratch Perverts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
