A3867 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-CASS-BOS &LR;      03-09 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-CASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEGGY CASS, 74; COMIC TV ACTRESS; WON TONY FOR `MAME' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peggy Cass, a comic actress who appeared in many movies and
Broadway shows, died Monday in Memorial Sloan Kettering Hospital in
New York City. She was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cass appeared in dozens of films and stage productions, but
is perhaps best known for her role as Agnes Gooch, the secretary in
the stage show ``Mame'' and its movie adaptation ``Auntie Mame.''
She won a Tony Award for the role and was nominated for an Academy
Award.
</P>
<P>
   She was an honest, candid, and witty woman once described in the
Globe as an ``incessant chatterbox'' who ``oozes razzmatazz.'' Her
exuberance made her a natural for TV. She was a panelist on ``To
Tell the Truth'' and was Jack Paar's sidekick on his late-night TV
show.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cass was born in Somerville, Mass. and spent her childhood
and teenage years in nearby Cambridge, where she graduated from
Cambridge Latin School. ``I was in the drama club but they wouldn't
let me act,'' she said in a story published in the Globe on Dec.
26, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   She said she always considered herself a Bostonian. ``My roots
are in Boston,'' she said. ``I had my teeth straightened in Boston.
I had my appendix taken out in Boston. What memories.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, she moved to New York City,
where she made the rounds of casting calls with no luck.
Eventually, a press agent friend arranged a date with Clark Gable.
She recited poetry, sang, and danced for him. He told her she was
such a ham, she'd definitely make it. Paar heard about the unlikely
twosome and invited her to talk about the experience on TV. ``I was
so nervous, Paar couldn't shut me up,'' she said in another story
published in the Globe on Sept. 29, 1970. ``I've been talking ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   She got her start in a USO troupe, playing a Russian sniper in
``The Doughgirls'' on a tour of Australia. She made her Broadway
debut in ``Bernadine.'' She also appeared in ``The Front Page,''
``Plaza Suite'' and ``If It's Tuesday, It Must Be Belgium.''
</P>
<P>
   Her one TV series, ``The Hathaways,'' in which she co-starred
with Jack Weston and three chimpanzees, lasted only the 1961-62
season.
</P>
<P>
   Her gravelly voice became her signature. ``Now, I'm sensitive
about that gravel voice of mine,'' she said in 1973. ``Once, while
I was making a picture, clad in slacks, a man jostled me slightly
and said: `Excuse me miss _ or is it mister?' I told him, `You'll
never know!' ''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her husband, Eugene Feeney of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-LBO-NYT &LR;      03-09 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-LBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RJR NABISCO STORY FASCINATES BUSINESS HISTORIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP, RJR-NABISCO-TERMS,
RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL, RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN) 
(mk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday's move by RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. to break up and
spin off its tobacco business is a non-event for consumers. Oreo
cookies, Life Savers candies and Planters peanuts will continue to
roll off Nabisco's production lines and Camel and Winston
cigarettes will come out of the R.J. Reynolds tobacco factories.
</P>
<P>
   But the news is fascinating for Wall Street and business
historians.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco was born in 1985 when R.J. Reynolds Industries
bought Nabisco Brands Inc. for $4.9 billion, one of many giant
diversification moves by American companies in the 1970s and 1980s
that have failed to reward shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as the undoing of another dumb merger,'' said
Thomas Lys, a merger and acquisitions specialist at Northwestern
University's Kellogg School of Management.
</P>
<P>
   But RJR's story included an unusual response to Wall Street's
distaste for the Nabisco merger. RJR followed the lead of hundreds
of smaller companies that had been put in private hands during the
1980s by groups of financiers and insiders who borrowed vast sums
of money to buy out shareholders of publicly traded enterprises.
The leveraged buyout strategy hinged on selling pieces of the
company to reduce the debt piled up in buying it, rapidly
streamlining the rest and then selling shares back to the public at
prices that produced huge profits for the buyout investors.
</P>
<P>
   By October 1988, when F. Ross Johnson, RJR's brash and
high-living chairman and chief executive, joined with investment
bankers from Shearson Lehman Hutton to propose a $75-a-share
buyout, the leverage strategy was already controversial for its
disruptive effect on employees. The ensuing soap opera of greed and
clashing egos, recapped in the best-selling ``Barbarians at the
Gate,'' ended in a $109-a-share, $25 billion buyout organized by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   It also left Johnson's successors saddled with nearly $19
billion in debt, most of it junk bonds paying punishing interest
rates. It is not clear whether RJR could have dug out from such
burdens and prospered if everything had gone perfectly in the
decade that followed, but it did not.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s were marred by marketing missteps, including goading
Philip Morris into a cigarette price war, management strife and
recessions in key overseas markets. The company's financial
straitjacket and limited strategic options made it impossible to
hang on to high profile executives like Louis Gerstner Jr. and
Charles Harper, whom Kohlberg Kravis had recruited to lead the
turnaround. And hanging over everything was increasingly expensive
and uncertain tobacco litigation.
</P>
<P>
   When Steven Goldstone became chairman and chief executive in
1996, he said the company was in better shape than other companies
with shares trading at such a low multiple to earnings, but that he
still had ``to demonstrate we're through punishing shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's change in course was a final concession that RJR never
quite managed to do that and was unlikely to in its present form,
inherited from the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
