<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HONDURAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS LITTLE IN AID TO HONDURAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ President Bill Clinton offered messages
of encouragement Tuesday to exhausted Hondurans, who last fall
watched four days of torrential rain wash away decades of economic
and social progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disaster has taught us that what happens to one in the
Americas affects us all,'' Clinton told an audience of Hondurans
and American troops gathered in an aircraft hangar. Speaking at the
Enrique Soto Cano Air Force Base on the second day of a four-day
Central America trip, he thanked the US soldiers for their efforts
in helping the Hondurans rebuild, and added in Spanish, ``We are
all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did not have much new aid to offer Honduras, the
country most severely hit by Hurricane Mitch. He announced a $56
million expansion of a two-week training program for military
disaster relief and repeated his support of a $956 million
emergency aid package that has stalled as Congress debates how to
finance the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the president's visit carried great symbolic meaning for
the poverty-stricken residents of this country of six million, who
have long considered themselves neglected friends of their North
American ally. Clinton's visit to Honduras was the first since
Ronald Reagan made a brief stop in the northern city of San Pedro
Sula in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having (Clinton) here gives us a message of hope for the
future,'' said Juan Ventura, mayor of Santa Ana, a farming town of
13,000 residents in the central state of La Paz. ``We're optimists,
but we're poor people, and we've been through a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's first stop was at the Soto Cano base, which the United
States built in 1982 and which served as a key training ground for
US-backed rebels against the leftist Nicaraguan government in the
late 1980s. Today, the base houses the Honduran Air Force and is
home to about 500 US troops conducting disaster relief and
anti-narcotics operations.
</P>
<P>
   Honduran President Carlos Flores thanked Clinton for including a
visit to Central America as one of his legacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come here not when our tears are fresh,'' Flores said,
``but in our new stage of rehabilitation and reconstruction that we
have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the four countries hit hard by Mitch in October, Honduras
suffered the greatest human and structural losses. Six thousand
people died in floods and mudslides and from storm-related disease,
and another 9,000 are still unaccounted for, according to
government figures. Two million people were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of moving north through the Caribbean Sea toward Mexico
in late October, as most forecasters had predicted, Mitch stalled
over Central America, pounding the region with as much as 7 feet of
heavy rain. In Honduras, which suffered an estimated $3.4 billion
in storm damage, scores of rivers overflowed, destroying 170
bridges and 70 percent of the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras had received more than $230 million in US aid as of
March 1, and thousands of its nationals who immigrated illegally
into the United States have been temporarily exempted from
deportation to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expressed his gratitude to the US soldiers who assisted
in the relief operations by transporting supplies, rescuing
stranded victims and rebuilding bridges and roads. He called the
effort one of the largest humanitarian missions by the US military
since the Berlin Airlift 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The president did not address other issues that Central American
leaders call crucial to the region's interests, especially
immigration policy, debt relief, and greater economic trade with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane crippled Honduras's already delicate economy,
based largely on agricultural products such as coffee, beans and
bananas. Because of weak harvests for coffee and other products,
some towns report unemployment rates as high as 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people give up, and they move to the cities or they try
to get all the way into the United States,'' said Juan Capistran
Benitez, mayor of the central village of Cabanas. ``Sometimes I
don't blame them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
