A3873 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-ANALYSIS-CO     03-09 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth ready to ride the tide of Latin American economics
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The economic winds might be starting to whip Latin
America, but BellSouth plans to ride out the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The company is staying the course, even as the nine nations
where it has multi-billion dollar investments in wireless networks
are buffeted by the global currency turbulence that started in Asia
a year ago. Latin America has come to be increasingly important for
BellSouth. The bet is that the region might suffer a bit now, but
will bounce back quickly with a payoff to those who have gambled on
it. In the meantime, BellSouth's biggest bet is on Brazil, the
hardest hit of all the region's economies _ and the largest.
</P>
<P>
   The company and analysts see international as one-third of
BellSouth's growth strategy, sharing the long-term load with
domestic wireless and local service in the nine southeastern
states. Local service still accounts for the vast majority of
BellSouth revenues, but the pendulum has slowly begun to swing
toward wireless and international. Yet in 1998, BellSouth's
expansion in Latin America seemed somewhat stymied. Once expected
to extend its reach throughout the region, BellSouth for months
hunkered down in the properties it had already purchased, spread
thin in the effort to build out those networks.
</P>
<P>
   During auctions of licenses last year in Brazil, BellSouth's bid
but was conservative enough to come away without a single win. By
the same token, BellSouth has shown no signs of retreat. And as
this year began, officials reaffirmed their interest in expansion.
Last week, BellSouth picked up another wireless license, paying $90
million for the right to offer service across Chile. The company,
which already serves the Chilean capital of Santiago, then
announced plans to invest $100 million to improve its wireless
phone system throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Roddy, chief telecom economist for Deloitte &AMP; Touche, said
global companies should look at their investments as a
``portfolio.'' Like managers of mutual funds, global investors
should make sure not to get caught with one kind of holding. If I
am only in the United States and Latin America, I want some
positioning in Western Europe and in Asia Pacific. I want to be
counterbalancing the risks. Almost like the mentality of having a
ski shop and a swimsuit store.''
</P>
<P>
   Performance of the emerging economies is uncertain. ``Over the
next 10 years, more economic growth will occur outside the United
States and Western Europe and the need for telecommunications
services is huge,'' Roddy said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
