<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLTOWER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth sells rights to run its cellular towers
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth has agreed to sell most of the rights
governing 1,850 of its cellular telephone towers for $610 million
in cash and stock to a Houston company, the companies announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Castle International, which rents tower usage to cellular
companies, will then lease tower space back to the Atlanta-based
telephone giant for $1,200 a month per tower.
</P>
<P>
   In this deal, though, BellSouth retains actual ownership of the
towers. That's because the company wants to keep a back door
guarantee that the towers, essential to its wireless telephone
service, never go out of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tower industry is young, and there is some consolidation
going on,'' said BellSouth spokesman Jeff Battcher ``We don't
anticipate getting the towers back except in case of something such
as a bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Crown Castle the right to manage and maintain
BellSouth's towers, which are in every Southeastern state and
Indiana. The number of towers Crown Castle is buying represents a
``sizable chunk'' of BellSouth's wireless tower system, said
Battcher.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Castle also has the right to expand BellSouth's wireless
system, building up to 500 additional towers over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies described Tuesday's deal as a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It releases us from the burden of having to be in the tower
business,'' said Battcher.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, it has become increasing difficult to build or
place towers. Suitable sites are either too expensive or
unavailable. In addition, a growing number of residents object to
having the towers as neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   As for Crown Castle, it can resell the space BellSouth isn't
using on the 1,850 towers to other wireless communications
providers. Those providers include AT&AMP;T, Sprint PCS and Nextel
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal grew out of an earlier agreement between Crown
Castle and BellSouth, said Battcher. He explained that, in a test
run, BellSouth sold the management rights of its tower system in
Kentucky to Crown Castle last year.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
