<SLUG> BC-AHOLD-PATHMARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL AHOLD BUYING PATHMARK STORES OF NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing rapid consolidation in the $436 billion US grocery
industry, the Dutch parent of Stop &AMP; Shop Cos. said Tuesday it
plans to cement its position as the largest grocer on the East
Coast by purchasing Pathmark Stores Inc. of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ahold NV said it will pay $1.74 billion, including $1.5
billion in debt, for Pathmark, whose 132 stores had estimated 1998
sales of $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Stop &AMP; Shop, which serves southern New England, Ahold
operates chains in New York, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Northern
Virginia, and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Pathmark will beef up Ahold's presence in New Jersey and
in the New York City and Long Island markets, said Bob Tobin, chief
executive of Ahold's US operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahold owns the East Coast,'' said Paul Weitzel, director of
Willard Bishop Consulting, an Illinois firm that advises the
supermarket industry.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved by government regulators, Ahold would
integrate its existing Edwards chain of 67 stores into Pathmark.
</P>
<P>
   The Edwards nameplate, which was once well known in
Massachusetts and Connecticut, would disappear from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Pathmark once operated stores in Connecticut but retrenched in
New Jersey after a leveraged buyout left it heavily in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Given rapid industry consolidation, the acquisition of Carteret,
N.J.-based Pathmark ``really didn't surprise anyone,'' said Craig
Faucher, editor of Griffin Update, a Rockland newsletter that
follows the food industry.
</P>
<P>
   A look at a supermarket's balance sheet helps explain why the
giants are snapping up smaller players at a rapid pace.
</P>
<P>
   As a percentage of revenues, supermarkets tend to have miniscule
profits _ about 1 to 2 percent on average.
</P>
<P>
   With such narrow margins, supermarket chains need size to hold
down distribution costs and increase their buying power as Wal-Mart
Stores Inc., a $139 billion behemoth, looks to take a greater share
of the US consumer's food dollar away from them.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart seems to have spurred consolidation. Recent deals
include Ohio-based Kroger Co.'s merger with Fred Meyer Inc.;
Idaho-based Albertson's plan to combine with American Stores Co. of
Utah; and Ahold's purchase of Giant of Landover, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Giant along with the purchase of Pathmark
could boost Ahold's annual US revenues from about $16 billion to
$25 billion; that amount could still leave Ahold behind Kroger,
Albertson's, Wal-Mart, and Safeway Inc. in US food sales.
</P>
<P>
   These giants are likely to only get bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong regional players are being gobbled up by the big
conglomerates,'' said consultant Weitzel. ``In two or three years,
there won't be any left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
