<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-CASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEGGY CASS, 74; COMIC TV ACTRESS; WON TONY FOR `MAME' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peggy Cass, a comic actress who appeared in many movies and
Broadway shows, died Monday in Memorial Sloan Kettering Hospital in
New York City. She was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cass appeared in dozens of films and stage productions, but
is perhaps best known for her role as Agnes Gooch, the secretary in
the stage show ``Mame'' and its movie adaptation ``Auntie Mame.''
She won a Tony Award for the role and was nominated for an Academy
Award.
</P>
<P>
   She was an honest, candid, and witty woman once described in the
Globe as an ``incessant chatterbox'' who ``oozes razzmatazz.'' Her
exuberance made her a natural for TV. She was a panelist on ``To
Tell the Truth'' and was Jack Paar's sidekick on his late-night TV
show.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cass was born in Somerville, Mass. and spent her childhood
and teenage years in nearby Cambridge, where she graduated from
Cambridge Latin School. ``I was in the drama club but they wouldn't
let me act,'' she said in a story published in the Globe on Dec.
26, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   She said she always considered herself a Bostonian. ``My roots
are in Boston,'' she said. ``I had my teeth straightened in Boston.
I had my appendix taken out in Boston. What memories.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, she moved to New York City,
where she made the rounds of casting calls with no luck.
Eventually, a press agent friend arranged a date with Clark Gable.
She recited poetry, sang, and danced for him. He told her she was
such a ham, she'd definitely make it. Paar heard about the unlikely
twosome and invited her to talk about the experience on TV. ``I was
so nervous, Paar couldn't shut me up,'' she said in another story
published in the Globe on Sept. 29, 1970. ``I've been talking ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   She got her start in a USO troupe, playing a Russian sniper in
``The Doughgirls'' on a tour of Australia. She made her Broadway
debut in ``Bernadine.'' She also appeared in ``The Front Page,''
``Plaza Suite'' and ``If It's Tuesday, It Must Be Belgium.''
</P>
<P>
   Her one TV series, ``The Hathaways,'' in which she co-starred
with Jack Weston and three chimpanzees, lasted only the 1961-62
season.
</P>
<P>
   Her gravelly voice became her signature. ``Now, I'm sensitive
about that gravel voice of mine,'' she said in 1973. ``Once, while
I was making a picture, clad in slacks, a man jostled me slightly
and said: `Excuse me miss _ or is it mister?' I told him, `You'll
never know!' ''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her husband, Eugene Feeney of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-PROBLEMS-COX     03-09 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PROBLEMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Problems will arise but no catastrophe expected, authority
saysBy Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Expect no Y2K cataclysm, but don't write off the
millennium bug as a nonevent, a local authority said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, there's a likelihood of significant governmental
services and utilities problems,'' said Atlanta attorney Paul Arne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that virtually every large organization in the
United States is going to experience some Y2K problems,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean that they're going to shut down. That
doesn't mean that utilities wont be operating. And at that doesn't
mean there needs to be mass panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Arne learned Tuesday that he has been named to Georgia's
Citizen's Y2K Task Force sponsored by Gov. Roy Barnes and chaired
by Southern Co. head A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg.
</P>
<P>
   Given Arne's credentials, the appointment is appropriate.
Nationally, he's on the board of legal advisers of the Bureau of
National Affairs Year 2000 Law Report, a legal publication, and
he's also on the board of legal advisers of the Rx2000 Solutions
Institute, a national health care organization with headquarters in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Arne's a board member of the Atlanta Year 2000 Users
Group and an organizer of its common services committee. The latter
consists of top computer technology people from the state's largest
corporations and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Arne said the citizens group members will meet shortly to
discuss the scope of their new job.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Arne shared his own thoughts about the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large organizations are going to have some Y2K problems. The
state of Georgia is not an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, he said, ``My overall impression is that the
state is aware of the problem and that state government has placed
experienced technology people at the top of its organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard of any particular problems'' the state is
facing, he said, ``but a number of people have expressed concern
about the payroll system. The state is in the process of converting
its existing system, and the conversion needs to be watched
carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Arne said he's ``been impressed'' by Fulton County's Y2K
efforts, but he thinks ``that there are a lot of local governments
that don't understand the problems and haven't reacted
appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   He asks if all of these entities have taken an inventory and
assessed it. ``If you have a system that doesn't work, it's obvious
that it has to be fixed. The trick is, determining what doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Arne mentioned that the chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission warned about a year ago there could be Y2K troubles with
certain police wireless systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be willing to bet that not every governmental
organization in the state that has a police department is looking
at this problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
