<HEADLINE>
FOUR SLAIN IN SOUTH AFRICA, RAISING FEAR OF MORE VIOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ Four local officials of a new
political party have been killed in this area in the last 48 hours,
raising fears that the violence that swept the country before the
1994 elections may be repeated before the national elections
scheduled for June.
</P>
<P>
   Bantu Holomisa, the head of the party, the United Democratic
Movement, is flying here Wednesday to ask for a meeting of all
political parties to try to defuse the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The killings came six weeks after the party's No. 3 official was
gunned down in KwaZulu/Natal, setting off a spate of revenge
killings. Holomisa went there too to call for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither side says so, the violence is assumed to be
between the UDM and the governing African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the local branch of the ANC said the party had
``no objection in principle'' to a Cape Town meeting, but said
there might be difficulties convening one quickly. He also played
down the notion of a countrywide war between the parties, saying
some of those killed were also involved in a local dispute over
plans to seize land for housing.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to the 1994 elections _ the first in which the
country's black majority was allowed to take part _ thousands of
people died in fighting between the ANC and the Zulu nationalist
Inkatha Freedom Party, which got covert help from the South African
Police.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the two parties have made some headway
toward resolving their differences, but in recent weeks each side
has again accused the other of fomenting violence.
</P>
<P>
   Bad blood developed rapidly between the African National
Congress and the United Democratic Movement. The movement was
founded last year by Holomisa, who was ejected from the congress
for accusing party leaders of accepting bribes, and Roelf Meyer,
the heir apparent of the National Party, who was ousted in a power
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   There were different reports on the identity of the latest
victim, who was found Tuesday in a pool of blood in a field behind
a squatter camp east of the city. A local radio report said a
witness saw a young man follow him through the field, pull out a
gun and shoot him dead.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the area was full of police officers because of the
earlier violence, no arrest was made.
</P>
<P>
   The movement's general secretary for the Western Cape Province,
Malizole Diko, said the killer had jumped out of a convoy of armed
ANC supporters who had been driving through the black and
mixed-race townships on Tuesday intimidating officials like Diko.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the ANC of plotting assassinations out of frustration
at losing its grip in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
