<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ATLANTA-TICKETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tickets for Cracker Barrel lagging
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Motor Speedway president Ed Clark says his
facility has one of the more attractive dates on NASCAR's schedule
for the Nov. 21 NAPA 500, Winston Cup's season finale.
</P>
<P>
   But annually, AMS has faced a tougher challenge selling its
spring race, Sunday's Cracker Barrel Old Country Store 500, the
fourth race on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   With the weather forecast for Atlanta predicting cool
temperatures and a 40 percent chance of rain Sunday, ticket sales
are lagging.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Tuesday that AMS has sold about 85,000 tickets,
leaving at least 50,000 tickets available. That means ABC's
broadcast will be blacked out in the Atlanta and Macon areas. About
94,000 tickets were sold for the spring race last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up in (ticket) sales for this race,'' Clark said. ``Not
substantially, but we're up. Generally, we've got pretty good sales
during race week if the forecast is good. But most of the Winston
Cup dates are sold-out in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark says he has approached NASCAR president Bill France Jr.
and chief operating officer Mike Helton about a later race date,
which Clark believes would decrease the chance of inclement
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to move it,'' Clark said. ``I think they'd like to
help us out. But where are you going to move it, and who's going to
move their date?''
</P>
<P>
   Helton, general manager at the Hampton facility in 1985-86, says
he understands Clark's dilemma. But with the Winston Cup schedule
sandwiching 36 events in 40 weekends, he says, there's little room
for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was running the place 15 years ago, I asked NASCAR if
there was another opportunity for Atlanta's first race,'' Helton
said. ``The answer I got then is the same one I'm giving Ed now. .
. . Certainly, NASCAR would like to come to Atlanta when the sun's
shining and the temperatures are (warmer), but finding the right
slot for it is very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said AMS owner Bruton Smith has approached WSB-TV,
Atlanta's ABC affiliate, about lifting the blackout in the past,
but a financial deal never was reached. Under its contract with the
network, AMS has the option of a blackout if the race doesn't sell
out, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got more of a national appeal with the season finale,''
he said. ``I think this race has got more of a regional appeal.
It's not a sell-out, but it's still the second-largest sporting
event in the state behind the fall race.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
