<HEADER>
A3883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOLSHOI-BALLET-2TAKES     03-09 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLSHOI-BALLET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `LURCHING' BOLSHOI STILL THINKS BIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Nobody has ever accused the Bolshoi Theater of thinking
small: after all, the word ``bolshoi'' means big, great or grand.
People are trained from childhood to assume, and to assert, not
only that Russia's premier opera and ballet company is bigger than
its best-known rivals and performs more often, but also that it is
simply the best.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last decade, most everyone knew that was not
true. The theater's ballet company had gone into a serious slump
during the last years of the reign of Yuri Grigorovich, a brilliant
but dictatorial choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Grigorovich was forced out. Vladimir Vasilyev,
one of the Bolshoi's most famous ballet stars, was named director
of the entire theater, which comprises its ballet and opera
companies as well as its orchestra, and hopes for the restoration
of the Bolshoi's former grandeur rose. But the first years of the
Vasilyev reign have brought more disappointment than triumph, and
among Moscow's loyal Bolshoi fans, there is a sense that maybe its
greatness has become a grand illusion.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bolshoi being the Bolshoi, it still thinks big. Among
its more far-fetched plans is a colossal building project,
supported by UNESCO; if it is ever finished, it could cost almost
$400 million and would shut the main theater for renovation
starting next January. Where the money would come from, however, is
an ever-deepening mystery, as the finances of the Russian
government, the theater's main sponsor, grow ever more precarious.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the Bolshoi's artistic program lack ambition. This year
the ballet company, which because of Russia's financial crisis lost
a private sponsor for the staging of a Maurice Bejart ballet late
last year, is committed to a premiere this spring of George
Balanchine's ``Symphony in C,'' and with only two months to
rehearse some critics worry whether its dancers will be prepared to
make the artistic leap required.
</P>
<P>
   Then in June, for the first time in eight years, both the ballet
and the opera company will go on a four-week tour to London, where
Vasilyev will have his first chance to test his new productions
before a foreign audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know what has happened post-Grigorovich,'' said
Sir John Tooley, a former director of Covent Garden in London and a
member of the UNESCO-sponsored Bolshoi steering committee. ``This
tour will put the Bolshoi back on show.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that Bolshoi artists, solo or in groups, have not
traveled the world in recent years. They have, and some argue that
these mini-tours, a way for dancers to augment their small Bolshoi
salaries, have squandered the theater's once-august reputation. Add
to that ``pirate'' tours by artists with only the slimmest
associations with the Bolshoi, and many here, starting with
Vasilyev, say the time has come for the Bolshoi to reassert itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of the Bolshoi was badly damaged in recent years,''
Vasilyev said. ``I have deliberately not done big tours because
when we do it, it should be done with a new repertory and a new
level of quality. Now we have arrived at a point when we can show
not only that the Bolshoi has not died, but that the Bolshoi has
climbed to new heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees about the new level of quality at the
Bolshoi. With a few exceptions Vasilyev's new productions, of which
there have been at least 17 over three years, have not been warmly
received. Russian critics have been generally unimpressed by new
versions of some of the Bolshoi's classics, or ``calling cards'' as
they are called, and several have wondered, aloud and in print, if
in its frantic search for a new identity the Bolshoi has lost its
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all convinced that by replacing Grigorovich with
Vasilyev, a great future would open up,'' said Vadim Gayevsky, a
ballet scholar and critic. ``Vasilyev had been abroad; he had a lot
of energy. We thought he could wake up the slumbering kingdom, like
the prince in `Sleeping Beauty.' We were right. He did have a lot
of energy, but he used it to take the ballet backward, not
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The most vehement attacks have been reserved for Vasilyev's
``Swan Lake,'' which, to the horror of many, dispenses with Odile,
the Black Swan, and invents a father-son rivalry for the affections
of the surviving Swan Princess. The new version, reportedly as
unpopular inside the theater as it was with the critics, shares the
spotlight in the Bolshoi repertory with Grigorovich's 1969 version,
a sign, some say, of the theater's split personality.
</P>
<P>
   The theater has tried, so far only tentatively, to incorporate
the classics of Western 20th-century choreography into its
repertory while adding forgotten 19th-century Russian works like
Tchaikovsky's historical opera ``Oprichnik.'' The result, some say,
is neither inspiring nor reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bolshoi keeps lurching from side to side, which is
dangerous because in the end it could lose its foundations,'' said
Yaroslav Sedov, a music and dance critic for the news magazine
Itogi. ``It should do what it does best, which is the grand
spectacle. That is its tradition, and it is a tradition that has
hardly been exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bolshoi still plays to virtually sold-out audiences, but
here and abroad there is a sense that the baton has been passed
from it to the Mariinsky Theater (formerly the Kirov) in St.
Petersburg in the latest replay of a rivalry two centuries old.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Valery Gergiev, the Mariinsky's dynamic director, St.
Petersburg's old imperial theater has found a champion with the
talent and savvy needed to clinch international attention. Even
though Gergiev's forte is not ballet, the Mariinsky troupe has
benefited from his energy and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every theater should have its ideologue, a leader,'' Gayevsky
said. ``Grigorovich had his ideas; Gergiev has his. Vasilyev is the
artistic director of the Bolshoi: he should be talking about art,
about ideas, but instead he is always talking about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial crisis has hit the Bolshoi hard. The theater
still depends heavily on government subsidies, which this year,
like last year, barely cover salaries. A new contract system has
given the theater more flexibility and its dancers, singers and
musicians better protection from the whims of its directors. But
the salaries remain paltry; top soloists earn $200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolshoi's defenders wince, however, at what they consider an
unfair comparison with the Mariinsky, which they say has been fed
by the Bolshoi's failure to tout itself. ``There is competition
with other Russian theaters that have an interest in lowering the
reputation of the Bolshoi,'' said Aleksei Fadeyechev, a 38-year-old
former dancer and partner to the ballerina Nina Ananiashvili. As
the new ballet director for the Bolshoi, Fadeyechev said, ``The
most important task now is to show the world that we have excellent
artists who can present the Bolshoi as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bolshoi's most audacious plan is rooted inside the company's
great pink temple, which, like the Kremlin, is a symbol of Moscow
and a landmark of Russian culture.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction program, announced in December, was actually
begun four years ago with construction of a second Bolshoi theater,
steps away from the main theater's western flank. That project,
half completed, includes a second stage, with seating for 1,000,
compared with the main theater's 2,000; a duplicate rehearsal
stage; dressing rooms; office space; an underground electrical
complex, and a three-story atrium. Altogether, the plan comprises a
second mega-Bolshoi complex of some 650,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the project calls for the renovation of the
143-year-old theater. The idea is to finish the sister theater by
January so the company will have a place to perform when the main
theater closes for renovation. Afterward, when both theaters are in
use, the new house will be dedicated to more modern, experimental
productions, leaving the main stage for classic works.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a problem. The Bolshoi, like Russia, does not have
the money to fulfill its dreams of grandeur. The federal government
has not allocated the $100 million needed to finish the sister
stage, said Yakov Sarkisov, deputy director of Mospromstroi, the
construction company that is building the sister theater complex.
It has not even paid Mospromstroi the $10 million it owes for work
already completed, he added.
</P>
<P>
   As for the estimated $200 million renovation of the main
theater, not only has the money not been earmarked, but no plans
have been drawn up. Neither Sarkisov nor Vasilyev can describe in
any detail what the renovations will entail or how much they will
cost. ``As long as they can't say that they definitely have the
money, we can't say definitely what it is we want to do,'' Sarkisov
said.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that the Bolshoi, like most public buildings in
Russia, is in poor repair. Sir John recalled how the Royal Ballet,
on tour in Russia 10 years ago, decided not to perform at the
Bolshoi because it was deemed unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring and preserving the Bolshoi, one of the world's
cultural treasures, was an original UNESCO goal in 1993 when the
agency adopted the theater as one of its three flagship projects in
Russia. But UNESCO officials are open about their frustration in
dealing with the Bolshoi bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have building plans; we don't have cost estimates,''
said Horst Godicke, director of UNESCO's program for Central and
Eastern Europe. ``In order to make the project more credible, they
are going to have to introduce some transparency in their budget
planning.''
</P>
<P>
   But what Russia lacks in organization, it sometimes makes up in
last-minute improvisation, which explains how monumental projects
are completed in defiance of mundane considerations like budgets
and timetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes miracles happen,'' Godicke said. ``These are normal
things in Russia. You can't apply Western standards to a country up
to its neck in its own traditions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
