<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3885 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YO-YOS-COMEBACK-TEX     03-09 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YO-YOS-COMEBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING WITH THE 'YO: YO-YOS ARE HOT NOW, BUT HAVE HAD AN UP-AND-DOWN
HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by YO-YOS-TYPES and YO-YOS-POP CULTURE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The yo-yo has, ahem, certainly had its ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the plaything is hot _ about 50 million were sold
last year, more than any single year, even during the yo-yo's
heyday in the '60s. That includes some top-of-the-line models that
can go for up to $150. They're so pervasive that a number of local
schools have banned them from campus.
</P>
<P>
   But will they last? In the larger sense, yes _ but for some
perspective, let's take a look at the yo-yo in history.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo is invented, probably in China, although the first
historical mention is in Greece. 500 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: Philippine hunters hide in trees and use a rock with a
long cord to throw at wild animals; a mistaken belief that this was
the yo-yo's origin attaches a certain ugly stigma to the toy. 16th
century.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo travels from the Orient to Europe, making its
debut with the aristocracy of France, Scotland and England. 1765.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: The French aristocracy is forced to flee France during the
``Reign of Terror,'' taking their yo-yos with them. The yo-yo was
nicknamed ``l'emigrette,'' which means ``leave the country.''
Reportedly, condemned prisoners played with yo-yos to relieve the
considerable stress of walking to the guillotine. 1789.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo makes its theatrical debut in Beaumarchais' play
``The Marriage of Figaro,'' in which a nervous Figaro describes his
``emigrette'' as ``a noble toy, which dispels the fatigue of
thinking.'' 1791.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: The yo-yo accompanies Napoleon and his troops to Waterloo,
where they suffer a crushing defeat. 1815.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo makes its first recorded appearance in America.
1866.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN AND SLEEPING: Nothing significant happens to the yo-yo for
nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   UP: Pedro Flores begins the States' first yo-yo company; Donald
F. Duncan buys it soon after, creating the world's biggest yo-yo
firm. 1928-29.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: Duncan receives a trademark for the word ``yo-yo,''
forcing competitors to use weird appellations such as ``twirler.''
1932.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The Duncan Co. moves to Luck, Wis., which becomes the Yo-Yo
Capital of the World, producing 3,600 yo-yos ``per hour.'' 1946.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: Really, there were a lot of ``ups'' for the next two
decades, so here's where we'll tell you that calling someone a
``yo-yo'' becomes a popular insult.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The Duncan Co. sells a record 45 million yo-yos in a country
with only 40 million kids. 1962.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: Demand is so great, the Duncan can't keep up with
advertising expenses, overtime wages or the legal fees involved in
keeping ``yo-yo'' trademarked. 1962.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The word ``yo-yo'' is liberated from its trademark status by
the Federal Court of Appeals. 1965.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: The Duncan Co. is forced into bankruptcy. 1965.
</P>
<P>
   UP: Flambeau Plastics Co. successfully bids for Duncan, keeping
the name alive. 1965.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: Abbie Hoffman is cited for contempt when he ``walks the
dog'' in an attempt to entertain congressional investigators. 1968.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo makes headlines when it appears at the opening of
the Grand Ole Opry. 1974
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: It makes more headlines by appearing with Richard Nixon.
1974.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo undergoes three decades of technological
innovations. Mid-'70s-present.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: The innovations make yo-yos more expensive.
Mid-1970s-present.
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo travels into space on the space shuttle Discovery
to see how it performs in low gravity. 1985.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN: It won't ``sleep'' in low gravity, making it difficult to
perform many tricks. 1985
</P>
<P>
   UP: The yo-yo returns to space on the space shuttle Atlantis,
and is featured in an educational video including slow-motion
yo-yo-ing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
