<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS REPUBLICAN SEEKS TO BLOCK U.S. MISSION FUNDS FOR KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison unveiled legislation
Tuesday that would prohibit U.S. defense spending on a NATO-led
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo until President Clinton lays out for
Congress the mission and objectives of sending U.S. forces into the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is likely to be introduced within the week as an
amendment to an emergency spending bill that would provide nearly
$1 billion in relief aid to help Honduras and Nicaragua rebuild
from the devastation caused by Hurricane Mitch last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is a very different situation from Bosnia. I think it's
important that Congress weighs in when we are talking about going
into a sovereign nation,'' the Texas Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to say to the president, you cannot fling U.S.
troops all over the world without, A, coming to Congress, B,
telling us where you want the money to come from and, C, having an
achievable mission and exit strategy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has committed to sending U.S. forces to Kosovo as part
of a NATO peacekeeping mission if the Serbs and ethnic Albanian
rebels agree to a Washington-authored peace plan that would give
the Albanians limited autonomy. Rebel leaders have signaled that
they might accept the terms of the accord, but Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic has refused to sign off on it because it calls
for placing NATO forces in Serbian territory.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping mission was outlined to members of Congress
several weeks ago when Defense Secretary William Cohen testified
before the Senate and House committees responsible for overseeing
the Pentagon. Thought the plan was still being put together, Cohen
suggested that the number of U.S. forces committed to Kosovo could
range from 4,000 to 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Key Republicans and Democrats on the committees voiced support
at that time for sending U.S. troops to participate in the NATO
mission. But, some lawmakers have begun to object to the idea of
committing any troops under any circumstances to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, has emerged as one of
the strongest critics on the House side of U.S. involvement in any
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in an op-ed piece Tuesday for the Wall Street Journal,
DeLay said committing U.S. forces to Kosovo would be ``a risky
mistake'' that would set a dangerous precedent for the NATO
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed Kosovo mission is much more dangerous than the
one in Bosnia,'' DeLay wrote. ``It cannot honestly be called a
peacekeeping mission because there is not even the semblance of a
cease-fire between the battling parties, who refuse to negotiate
directly with one another. No number of soldiers can keep the peace
where none exists.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay also plans to introduce his own legislation this week that
would go much further than Hutchison's. It would prohibit defense
money from being spent to support a peacekeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has long been an opponent of committing U.S. forces abroad
for any other reason than U.S. security. In his Wall Street Journal
piece, he wrote that it was time for America to ``recommit itself
to securing its own defense first before sending troops abroad to
build nations upon foundations of sand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are playing with a scorpion in the Balkans, and it is only
a matter of time before we get stung,'' DeLay wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
