<HEADLINE>
WRESTLING FANS WRESTLING IMAGE  
 TELEVISION LIFE 
POIROT POPPING UP  
 WITHOUT MONICA
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: bylines follow notebook items.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Smashing the stereotype that viewers of professional
wrestling are all blue-collar, undereducated Neanderthals watching
a macho soap opera, students at some of the nation's most elite
colleges have made a minicult of staging Monday night parties to
watch ``WCW Monday Nitro Live'' on cable.
</P>
<P>
   They contribute hugely to a viewing group that advertisers
covet: young adult males. To help gussy up wrestling's rather
unsavory image and to remind advertisers how popular it is with big
men on campus, the TNT network took its World Championship
Wrestling show on the road to four universities in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The network, part of the Turner Broadcasting System, as is World
Championship Wrestling itself, asked students to send in videotapes
of their Monday Nitro parties. The winners' parties were televised
on TNT during ``WCW Monday Nitro Live'' bouts.
</P>
<P>
   The four winners (from more than 50 submissions) were Brown
University, the University of California at Berkeley, the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and the University of
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are schools you might not typically associate a
wrestling crowd with,'' said Joe Uva, president for sales at Turner
Entertainment. ``But it shows you wrestling's popularity with that
young adult audience.'' And, he said, ``It's a terrific way for
advertisers to tap into'' that college audience weekly.
</P>
<P>
   These college guys are the most difficult-to-reach slice of an
audience that makes pro wrestling by far the biggest driving force
in prime-time Nielsen ratings for basic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 most-watched shows on cable television in February, 21
were wrestling shows _ either World Wrestling Federation bash-fests
on Monday nights on the USA network, ``WCW Monday Nitro Live'' or a
spinoff called ``WCW Thunder'' (Thursday nights on TBS), with the
top shows drawing about 4.5 million households. (The No. 1 show on
cable in February was a NASCAR race; two movies and the Westminster
Kennel Club dog show rounded out the top 25.)
</P>
<P>
   And wrestling's popularity doesn't stop with college students.
Teen-agers and children are big fans, too, and now Kids WB, the
children's programming branch of the WB network, has scheduled a
wrestling-themed show, ``On the Ropes,'' for its Saturday morning
children's lineup. It features high school wrestlers, so it ought
to be tamer than the cable shows _ presumably.
</P>
<P>
   _ BY LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tolan, a comedy writer whose credits include both ``The
Larry Sanders Show'' and the top box office movie ``Analyze This,''
has had so much experience dealing with television executives, most
of it bad, that he is writing one sitcom for HBO based on how these
executives do their work (tentatively called ``The Web'') and
another based on a book written by a television executive.
</P>
<P>
   As Tolan put it during the U.S. Comedy Arts Festival in Aspen,
Colo., last weekend, ``Dealing with television executives is
something I know a lot about, and I have the scars to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   The second show, to be produced by Tom Hanks' production
company, Playtone, will be based on the satirical business novel
``Lloyd: What Happened?,'' published last year by Crown and written
by Stanley Bing, who also writes a humor column for Fortune
magazine when he isn't spinning the corporate information issued by
CBS. Of course, in that role he has the not-so-hidden identity of
Gil Schwartz, senior vice president for communications at that
network.
</P>
<P>
   Bing said that beyond expressing happiness about his book's
being adapted for television he was ``incredibly flustered'' and
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   POIROT POPPING UP
</P>
<P>
   The fussbudget detective Hercule Poirot has been a figure of
reruns for some years now, popping up regularly on the A&AMP;E cable
network. The character, as embodied by the British actor David
Suchet, was so popular with American audiences that A&AMP;E has
persuaded Suchet to do a reprise of the role, after a five-year
hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Suchet will appear in two feature-length Poirot
films, each two hours long and based on an Agatha Christie novel.
Produced by Brian Eastman _ who did the original British ``Poirot''
episodes, which first ran from 1988 to 1994 in Britain and migrated
to the United States on PBS, then A&AMP;E _ the new films will appear
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Murder of Roger Ackroyd'' and ``Lord Edgware Dies'' are
the two Christie novels being produced as A&AMP;E originals. No word
yet on whether Poirot's secretary, Miss Lemon, his friend Captain
Hastings or their sometime colleague Inspector Japp will appear in
the new movies.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   WITHOUT MONICA
</P>
<P>
   Even though ABC has special access to the newswoman of the sweep
month, Monica Lewinsky (though Barbara Walters could also fit that
description), NBC's ``Nightly News With Tom Brokaw'' came away from
the news competition for February a rather easy winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightly News'' had the highest rating: 8.6, compared with 8.2
for ABC and 7.6 for CBS (each rating point represents 994,000
homes); the most viewers, 11.35 million, compared with 11.25
million for ABC and 10.2 million for CBS, and the best showing
among the group that advertisers with news programs seek to reach
most: ages 25 to 54.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a consistent pattern; NBC has won nine straight
sweep competitions among that group of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
