<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BIGHOUSE (Paradise Valley, Ariz.) - The priciest home sale in
Arizona history has been concluded. Sports team mogul John McCaw
sells his 10-acre spread on the north side of Camelback Mountain
for $8.3 million. A company called MICI bought it. By CHARLES KELLY
and CATHERINE REAGOR. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MEXICAN-TRUCKS (Nogales, Ariz.) - For safety inspectors at
Arizona's six ports of entry, a recent study only confirmed what
they already knew: Too few big rigs from Mexico are being inspected
at the border, and too few inspected trucks comply with U.S safety
standards. Oh yeah, state inspector Richard Saspe says emphatically
as the Mexican 18 wheelers stream across the scales outside his
plate-glass window, there are more than a few reasons to be worried
about the rigs traversing this country as scheduled under the NAFTA
agreement come Jan. 1. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ARIZONA PARK (Phoenix) - A proposal for a new national park in
southwestern Arizona, backed by scientists, writers and former
federal officials, would combine two current national preserves and
a military testing range into the Sonoran Desert National Park _
``5,000 square miles of silence,'' the organizers say. By SETH
LANDAU. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABBEY-REMEMBERED (Phoenix) - Ten years after his death,
environmentalist/author Edward Abbey is having an increasing impact
on the West. We talk to folks about why Abbey has a lasting appeal.
His books helped spawn the Earth First! movement, and some
associated violence and conspiracy. Today, that movement is
flowering as a non-violent, mainstream effort to protect vast
tracts of wild lands across the continent. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story
moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ARTPOP (Phoenxi) - Some pop transcends the triviality of the form.
While the Spice Girls or Mary's Danish will eventually disappear,
certain people contain in their very voice the seed of all
humanity: Ray Charles, Louis Armstrong, Billie Holiday. A single
note is not only identifiable, but heartbreaking. Others, like the
dancing of Fred Astaire or the guitar notes of BB King, do the
same: They function at the level of high art. By RICHARD NILSEN.
Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Strutting someday soon on an
international fashion runway: Sarah Alford. Or so she hopes. More
than anything else. Alford, 15, was one of more than 250 girls and
women who showed up at Dillard's at Fashion Square Mall, hoping to
have their faces and features grace an ad for Roxy, a clothing
line. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
