Southeast, is starting to make a name for himself by trekking the
country for the third time on an acoustic tour with pal Dave
Matthews. By KEVIN MURPHY. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCGARVEY-COLUMN (Undated) - During their brief respite at my home,
a Chiapas father and son consumed big bowls of rice and ranchero
beans, 24 smallish corn tortillas, and big salad plates of lettuce,
ripe tomatoes and sliced avocados that I garnished with mayonnaise,
red chile flakes and chopped cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   They also ate a dozen raw jalapenos and peeled four oranges.
They drank nearly a gallon of milk and later snacked on a bag of
microwave popcorn. They were astounded by the microwave. They also
drank a liter of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Father Ignacio and son Pedro were famished, having subsisted
only on cornmeal gruel during their two-month odyssey north to the
chilly Promised Land from the tropical, revolutionary Mexican state
of Chiapas. By JACK MCGARVEY. Story moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-ORGANS (Phoenix) - A quixotic bid to exempt Arizona from a
national human organ allocation system should make people sick. The
national plan itself could make people sicker.
</P>
<P>
   Both systems prompt shouts of protest. But when the shouting is
done, when all arguments are made about any system of rationing
human body parts, a somber reality sinks in: No matter which system
is in place, patients will die because of a severe shortage of
lifesaving organs.
</P>
<P>
   Story moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOK-FESTIVAL (Undated) _ Flagstaff, Ariz., plays host to a monster
