<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAID-SERVICE-TWOTAKES     03-09 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAID-SERVICE-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER BLENDS PASSION FOR BUSINESS WITH COMPASSION FOR WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ When Alice Errett began operating The
Maids franchise in Johnson County, Kan., she thought getting
customers would be her biggest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting workers. Good workers,'' she soon learned. ``I
never struggled to find customers. The issue from Day One was
finding reliable, dependable, good-natured people to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Most business owners and operators can relate. (ital)I just
can't find good help!(end ital) is the hirers' lament of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Continued low unemployment rates _ plus entry into the work
force of former welfare recipients who have no sustained job
histories _ continue to make it hard to fill front-line jobs.
People who take entry-level jobs often need to acquire the most
basic skills, including a work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   But, while many employers moan about the worker dearth, Errett
in the last five years has gone to heroic lengths to solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't come across another employer who goes out of her way
that much,'' says Tom Sprenkel, job developer for the Kansas
Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services in Kansas City,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her willingness to go outside her normal routine to contact
pockets of unemployed people is unmatched. You see her at job
fairs, at social service agencies, at community meetings, anywhere
she thinks she might find people who need work.''
</P>
<P>
   Errett emphasizes she is not running a charity. She says she
makes a good living at what she believes is the largest cleaning
service now operating in Johnson County. She expects to gross just
under a million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
   But dollars and cents are not the full measure of Errett's
success. She thrives because she has:
</P>
<P>
   _ Driven the streets of Kansas City, Kan., stopping in at
community centers and social service agencies to say, ``Hi, I'm
Alice. I'm looking for workers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Created a first-name relationship with state welfare and job
service officials to find job candidates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forged a public-private partnership with transit officials to
subsidize a bus that picks up her workers in Kansas City, Kan., and
deposits them at her Overland Park office door.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put a full-service kitchen in the office so workers can fix
breakfast or dinner for themselves or their families.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set up a bilingual library of periodicals and books for her
employees to read. All workplace materials are in Spanish and
English.
</P>
<P>
   _ Become an expert in day care and sick-child care referrals, in
car loans and even bail bond resources.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trained employees in household budget management.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provided team-building and interpersonal skills training
classes to help workers get along with each other.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paid for her employees' flu shots and vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything in my power to make it possible for the
people who work for me to be healthy and be here,'' says Errett.
</P>
<P>
   Errett is a former Sprint Corp. group manager for product
development who decided in 1994 that she was an entrepreneur at
heart. A financial partner, Glenn Golden, helped her buy The Maids
franchise, and she got off to a decent business start with two
early hires, Andrea Matthes and Ron Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   Matthes and Schmidt have stayed with the organization and
advanced to run the office, the scheduling, the billing and many of
the day-to-day business details. That leaves Errett ``free'' to do
what she loves: recruiting, training and helping workers prosper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That woman walks on water as far as I'm concerned,'' says Joel
Schroeder, who bought a competing area cleaning service, Lulu &AMP;
Mimi's Housecleaners, last June. ``She heard the panic in my voice
and came right over and sat down with me for about three hours to
share how she handles staffing. We still talk every other week.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder says his goal is to one day operate ``just like
Alice.'' Meanwhile, though, he says he's managing his business by
himself and can't carve out time to do the grass-roots search for
workers that Errett does. Errett has a standard pitch when she
talks to applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm getting close to hiring someone, I tell him or her
that `You have to do these three things to work for me:
</P>
<P>
   `Be here. Have a smile for everyone, and that means not coming
in this door with any racism baggage. Clean my way.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I say, `Call me back if you can do that.' Some do. Some
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Errett employs about 28 full-time workers and eight
others who work on call. They earn between $6 and $9 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her efforts, turnover remains a problem. She estimates
she's hired about 100 workers in the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   She loses about one-third of her trained cleaning team members
in a year. But if she considers those who leave before their
training period is finished, her turnover rate approaches 300
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, my employees come in needing many things. One
thing I learned quickly is that most of them didn't `live'
anywhere. They said they were `staying' places. Most of them move
often, from house to house, sometimes because of family problems,
sometimes because of income problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made my resolve stronger to make this office a home away
from home. It also made me resolve to help some of them with
getting mortgages.''
</P>
<P>
   She has built a kitchen, living room and library//computer room
into The Maids office, partly to use as a training ground and
partly as a homey gathering place before and after her workers fan
out to clean customers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Errett also has helped about a half-dozen employees buy houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I do, I tell them to say, `I (ital)live(end ital)
here.' And I tell them to come to me if they have problems with
their mortgages. We will work on their financial problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping employees buy houses is an extraordinary step that few
other employers can take. And it certainly wasn't the first
challenge that Errett tackled.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, we ran into transportation
problems,'' she recalls. ``The people I interviewed didn't have
cars and there was no public transportation route that could get
them to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Errett allowed some of The Maids' company cars to
be driven home at night by employees who were responsible for
chauffeuring other employees to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't successful for a variety of reasons, one of which
was that our vehicles sometimes ended up in places we didn't want
them to be,'' she recalls.
MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
