<HEADLINE>
OWNER BLENDS PASSION FOR BUSINESS WITH COMPASSION FOR WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ...she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Then Errett subsidized a commuter van provided through the
Mid-America Regional Council and the Economic Opportunity
Foundation. That program ceased, and Errett next teamed with
Wyandotte and Johnson county public transit officials to get a
dedicated public bus route through the JobLinks program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a little guy. I have no political clout. But today, I
subsidize a full-size Johnson County bus that picks up 15 to 20 of
my people at two locations in Wyandotte County every morning and
drops them off here and here alone,'' Errett beams.
</P>
<P>
   After she got the bus, Errett threw a thank-you luncheon at The
Central Exchange for ``the government bureaucrats who helped make
it happen _ the people who do great work day in and day out and
hardly ever get recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Errett thought other employers could benefit from her
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was, using only about a third of a public bus,'' Errett
relates. ``I figured, why wouldn't other employers want to use the
rest of the seats. I went to the Overland Park Chamber of Commerce,
to other retailers, to some of the fast food places around here,
and I tried to get others to show interest in the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frustrating to me. I heard a lot of `We don't have
good luck with people from that area' and a variety of other
reasons why they weren't interested. So, at this point, it's my
bus, and I'm absolutely delighted with it because people are not
quitting my jobs because of a transportation problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing transportation was only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that once I got people in the door and solved their
transportation problems that people would say, `Thank you, Alice.'
That's not what I got. I got people coming in every day and asking
for advances on their pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Errett discovered the need to be a financial and family
counselor as well. Partly for that reason, she entered a
partnership with Tom Lawson, a mentor from the Older Kansans
Employment Program, who spends 20 hours a week advising The Maids'
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People from disadvantaged backgrounds often have trouble
making good choices about how to manage their money,'' Errett said.
``They get paychecks on Friday and it's gone on Monday. We work
hard to teach money management skills, but when someone truly needs
an advance, I'll give it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Errett also found a need to provide social and work-ethic
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to get an alarm clock when they come to work for
me,'' she says. ``Many have never had one before. We talk about
manners and responsibility. I teach them to clean, yes, but it's
more important that I teach them how to work with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, workers quit for no obvious financial or
family-related reason. Errett follows up to find out why.
Previously, she often heard that they didn't like their co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now we work extra hard to create compatible teams and
celebrate team successes. We work hard to explain that even on a
team, different workers have different responsibilities, that
everyone doesn't do exactly the same thing. We work hard to teach
them that quality isn't something the supervisor dictates; it's
something that has to be in everyone's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive, Errett offers a bonus that adds $5 to team
members' paychecks for each day a cleaning team gets no complaints.
The company gets complaints from only 1 to 2 percent of all jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to build good teams. We look at personality, not
race or ethnicity. We expect everyone to communicate with each
other. That means learning a few phrases of Spanish or listening to
our ESL (English-as-a-second-language) tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Errett says she's rigorous about using a pre-employment
screening service. She also does random drug screening. Her
cleaning teams are bonded through a third-party fidelity bond. They
don't get to work in paying customers' homes until they've
completed her training.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she admits, all her efforts fail. But, sometimes,
they succeed wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Errett's favorite success story involves a former welfare
recipient who came to The Maids encumbered by financial and
personal problems. Errett said the woman breezed through The Maids'
training and was a top performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were limiting her, that we didn't have anything for
someone of her intelligence and ability,'' Errett says.
</P>
<P>
   Errett made a few referrals. Today, the woman has an income
that's well more than double The Maids' entry wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this job, I get to change lives. I see people who have
never been successful at anything before. I teach them how to
clean, and they have a skill that they can be proud of. It may not
be the skill you'd choose, but it's a skill, and they get money for
doing it. They get more money than they ever had before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
