<HEADLINE>
ITALY GREETS IRANIAN LEADER WITH OPEN ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Seeking to break his country's isolation, President
Mohammad Khatami of Iran arrived in Italy on Tuesday for a
three-day visit, the first Iranian leader to visit Western Europe
since the Islamic Revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's faltering economy badly needs foreign investment, and
Khatami hopes to improve his government's credibility and thus
attract trade and loans. The United States, which still views Iran
as supporting terrorism, has gingerly sought to encourage reform
but has not lifted its trade embargo. Europe has proven far less
diffident.
</P>
<P>
   Italy has taken a lead in seeking economic and political
rapprochement with Iran, and it welcomed Khatami with tight
security and full honors, starting with a greeting at the airport
by Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, a Shiite Muslim cleric, expects to meet with the pope
on Thursday, a meeting the Vatican welcomes as a chance to improve
relations with Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, each visit has a means of friendship that is very
important to our country,'' Khatami said on Tuesday after meeting
with President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro.
</P>
<P>
   For Italy, diplomacy is tightly entwined with economic
interests. A week ago, the Italian energy group Ente Nazionale
Idrocarburi and the French oil company Elf-Aquitaine signed a
$1-billion contract to develop the Dorood oil field in Iran, a deal
that Washington greeted with dismay.
</P>
<P>
   But Italian officials say their overtures to Khatami, whom they
view as a moderate intent on modernizing Iranian society and
loosening the grip of its fundamentalist clergy, will help the
United States as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not convinced that the United States does not view with
favor our initiative toward Iran,'' Dini said in an interview on
Tuesday. Dini, who accompanied Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema on
his visit to the White House last week, said American officials had
expressed ``great interest'' in Italy's effort to support what he
described as Khatami's ``new course.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 U.S. law requires that the administration impose
sanctions on companies or countries that invest more than $20
million in Iran's energy industry. Last May, the administration
established a policy to waive sanctions in certain cases, and it
recently granted a waiver to the French company Total, which signed
a $2-billion deal in 1997 to develop an Iranian gas field. Italy
hopes the State Department will follow that precedent with ENI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy of course will be very careful to condemn abuses of
human rights and democracy in Iran,'' Dini said. But he added that
it was in everyone's interest to support modernization in Iran.
``Iran is a big country, and its democracy and stability are
important to the entire Middle East,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, who was elected 21 months ago, has been immersed in a
power struggle between moderates in the government and hard-line
factions. He got a boost earlier this month when moderate
candidates won control of local councils in the country's first
municipal elections since 1979. But nationally, conservative
clerics still control dominate major institutions, and ultimate
authority lies with the senior religious leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations say that even under Khatami's
presidency, progress has been slow. The State Department's report
on human rights for 1998, which was published last month, agreed.
``Systematic abuses included extrajudicial killings and summary
executions, disappearances, widespread use of torture and other
degrading treatment,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   While Khatami had lunch at the presidential palace on Tuesday, a
few miles away more than 3,000 Iranian dissidents and some Italian
opposition figures demonstrated to protest his visit. In Amsterdam,
seven Iranians briefly occupied the Italian Consulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khatami is not a moderate, even if he said he is,'' said
Perviz Khazai, who was an ambassador under Khomeini and is a leader
in the National Council of Resistance of Iran, an Iranian dissident
group, who helped organize Tuesday's rally in Rome. He cited
assassinations of Iranian dissidents abroad and public executions
and stonings.
</P>
<P>
   Khazai accused Italy of courting Khatami for its own economic
ends. ``They should call a spade a spade and say they want to deal
with this regime because they want oil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This accusation was echoed by Italian protesters. ``Khatami made
Rome his first visit because Italians are always open to
business,'' said Marco Taradash, an opposition member of
Parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
