<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TYPE ONCE MEANT BIG NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) You sometimes hear that TV and a general withering of
the reading habit are threats to the survival of print journalism.
But the people who say that are dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The main danger to newspapers comes from the fact we've already
used up all the big headlines.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, as a youngster in the Army, my twin duties were
to lead a platoon of men charged with defending our way of life
against godless communism and to supervise production of the
division's weekly paper.
</P>
<P>
   During my two years of service no godless communists ever showed
themselves in that part of North Carolina, so I ended up devoting a
good share of my time to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The Paraglide, our sheet was called _ a carryover from the day
when airborne infantrymen might arrive at the battle either by
parachute or by glider.
</P>
<P>
   The paper was a tabloid, and the first thing I was told upon
assuming this heavy responsibility was that the format was
sacrosanct. Each week the bottom half of the front page was to be
filled by one large photograph, the top half by a single screamer
headline.
</P>
<P>
   What was written inside the paper wasn't so important, as long
as the commanding general's name _ a rather goofy name _ was
spelled correctly. But the rule about Page One was inflexible.
</P>
<P>
   As you perhaps know, not much electrifying news occurs on a
military post. And anything that might resemble real news is
forbidden to be circulated. Yet there we were, committed to this
gigantic headline _ two enormous lines of type, each letter 3 or 4
inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   So we just made the best of what we had.
</P>
<P>
   TOWN TATTOO PARLORS
</P>
<P>
   PUT OFF LIMITS
</P>
<P>
   Or,
</P>
<P>
   POST EXCHANGE GETS
</P>
<P>
   NEW SALAD BAR
</P>
<P>
   After a while the glory years were over, and I came back to the
world of civilian journalism, which was governed by greater
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   In those days we had what the editors called a ``scare''
headline. It was one, or at most two columns wide, with letters
maybe a half-inch high. There also was a ``plain scare,'' not much
different except the type was somewhat fainter.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for anything bigger than a scare, you needed at least
a quadruple homicide, a hotel fire, or a tree down across the
street the publisher drove to work.
</P>
<P>
   The really huge headlines _ banners that ran all the way across
the top of the page _ were held in reserve for declarations of war,
men in orbit, important assassinations, American League pennants
and such.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing 40 years there have been changes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new breed of consultants whose specialty it is to tell
newspapers how to look more dynamic and snazzy, there's a widely
held belief that enormous headlines get readers' glands pumping and
put them in a rage to subscribe.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any day now you pick a newspaper anywhere in the land and
you'd think, from a quick glance at Page One, that space aliens
finally had arrived or California had slid into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder what editors would do if, instead of the
usual run of the day's news, they got a call from a famous
astronomer, telephoning from his mountaintop observatory to report
an incoming asteroid roughly the size of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers would be in pretty much the same fix as the poor old
Paraglide _ kind of like a soldier who's fired all his best shots
before the fight begins.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the world might be at hand, but it would be hard to
interest readers in that fact when, only the day before, we'd used
the same size type to notify them of the expanded salad bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
