<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, March 14,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ From the Mexican border to the
Mark Taper Forum here, theater is alive _ and well enough _ in
Southern California, and the stars of film and television are
dabbling in it in ever greater numbers. This season alone, familiar
faces as diverse as Carol Burnett, Annette Bening, Donald
Sutherland, Al Pacino and Molly Ringwald have appeared, or are
scheduled to do so, on Los Angeles stages, in new works, revivals
of classics, or reworkings of recent New York offerings. By Todd S.
Purdum. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STAND-ALONE-FILM (Paris) _ After seeing ``I Stand Alone,'' after
meeting its director, Gaspar Noe, 35, one couldn't help but ask:
How could a pleasant young man with a positive view of life make a
film as dark and desperate as this one? Well, Noe might of course
have confessed that he was a secret nihilist, that ``I Stand
Alone'' (``Seul Contre Tous'') was a public form of psychotherapy.
Reassuringly, his answer was more straightforward. ``I can make a
film like this because I feel at ease with myself,'' he said. By
Alan Riding. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANCE-FILM (Rotterdam, the Netherlands) _ If you can't dazzle
them, shock them!'' the adolescent heroine of Catherine Breillat's
1989 film ``36 Fillette'' declares, with a glance at her own daring
decollete. Could that be the French director's motto? Ms. Breillat,
who is 50, is no stranger to scandal. From her first novel, written
when she was 17, to her most recent film, ``Romance,'' her candid
dissections of human sexuality have ignited debate at home and
abroad. ``Romance'' enjoyed a noisy premiere last month at the
International Film Festival here alongside a retrospective of Ms.
Breillat's six previous films. (``Romance'' is being shown as part
of the series ``Rendez-Vous with French Cinema Today'' at the
Walter Reade Theater on Friday and next Sunday and has just been
acquired by Trimark Pictures for an American release.). By Leslie
Camhi.
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-FILMS (Undated) _ When Stanley Kubrick died a week ago,
he left behind the monolith from ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' as the
single most salient image of his career. This (who could forget?)
ws the dark, austere object that arrived in the midst of primitive
ape-men. It drove them into a state of high anxiety as they rallied
around the thing, touched it, recoiled, tried to fathom it, sensed
its intense power without quite grasping what that power might
mean. The arrival of each new mind-blowing Kubrick film was much
the same. By Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DLUGOSZEWSKI-DANCE (New York) _ It's not often that someone
starts making dances after turning 60. Lucia Dlugoszewski, who
makes her choreographic debut on March 23 at Playhouse 91, is not a
total neophyte, though. A seasoned composer and musician, she
carried on a creative partnership, and marriage, with the
choreographer Erick Hawkins for more than 40 years. After Hawkins
died, Ms. Dlugoszewski set about staging three pieces outlined in a
notebook he kept at his deathbed. Mikhail Baryshnikov's White Oak
Dance Project performed the first of these posthumous works,
``Journey of a Poet,'' to mixed reviews at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music in 1997. The Hawkins company will present the two others
during its one-week run at Playhouse 91, which wraps up the 92d
Street Y's monthlong Harkness Dance Project. By Christopher
Reardon.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR-MITCHELL-DANCE (New York) _ It is a landmark year for
Arthur Mitchell. In the coming months, he will be celebrating his
50th year in dance, the 30th anniversary of The Dance Theater of
Harlem and his 65th birthday. Dressed in a black silk shirt, black
jacket and black slacks, he makes as striking an impression now as
he did as a principal dancer with the New York City Ballet in the
1950s and 60s. On his bookcase in his office are photographs of
himself with Balanchine, another with Jacqueline Kennedy at the
White House and a more recent shot with President Clinton in 1993,
when Mitchell won the Kennedy Center Honors. By Valerie Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Vincent Canby reviews: ``Annie Get
Your Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS-JOLSON-THEATER (Undated) _ Theater critic Frank Rich
talks with Arthur Laurents about his play ``Jolson Sings Again.''
</P>
<P>
   HEDDA-GABLER-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ Ever since Henrik Ibsen
wrote ``Hedda Gabler'' in 1890, the role has tantalized and lured
actresses. The tragedy, about a bored, vengeful wife on the edge of
madness, has been interpreted, with various degrees of Freudian and
feminist shadings, by Eva Le Gallienne, Geraldine Page, Maggie
Smith, Glenda Jackson, Jane Alexander and Dianne Wiest, among
others. ``What Hamlet is to men, Hedda is, in some ways, to
women,'' said Annette Bening, the latest Hedda, who has found the
role the most complex and relentless of her career. The production,
which begins previews Sunday evening will open on March 24 for a
limited run at the Geffen Playhouse in Westwood. By Bernard
Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   BETTY'S-VACATION-THEATER (New York) _The playwright Christopher
Durang's latest play ``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' directed by
Nicholas Martin, opens Sunday at Playwrights Horizons. By Bob
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-THEATER (Berlin) _ Competition can be good for business
_ even among cultural institutions. But in Germany in the last few
months, a rivalry involving three leading men of the theater has
revealed the intensity with which German theaters and German
cultural politicians can vie with one another for headlines, renown
and as large a piece as possible of the country's cultural pie. By
Anne Midgette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELMORE-LEONARD-POP (Undated) _ Elmore Leonard, 73, who's new
novel is ``Be Cool,'' talks with the pop-music editor of Arts and
Leisure, Fletcher Roberts, about his interest in pop music and its
role in the novel. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   STEVE-REICH-MUSIC (Undated) _ On the new album ``Reich
Remixed,'' American, British and Japanese DJs pay tribute to the
American minimalist composer Steve Reich, at the invitation of his
label, Nonesuch (CD, 79552-2). Some of the DJs, notably DJ Spooky
(aka Paul Miller) were versed in his music; others just saw it as
an archive of cool sounds. Either way, their attraction to Reich's
work is anything but arbitrary. Drumming phases and sampling _ the
central components of contemporary dance music _ have formed an
integral part of his style since the mid-1960s. By Adam Shatz.
</P>
<P>
   BETH-ORTON-MUSIC (Undated) _ The English singer-songwriter Beth
Orton, 28, whose 1997 album ``Trailer Park'' was a spellbinding
successs, has completed a new album ``Central Reservation''
(Deconstruction/Arista, CD, ARCD-9038). Once again, the songs
wander a mist-laden terrain of romantic yearning, of loves lost and
sought. By Anthony DeCurtis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOCKNEY-POSTER-ART (London) _ If you have ever dreamed of owning
a David Hockney but haven't had $20,000 (or considerably more) to
spend on a drawing, oil painting or lithograph, Christie's South
Kensington has come along with the largest-ever sale of Hockney
posters, to be held here on March 25. And although one might argue
that posters are not in the same league as paintings and
lithographs, the collection testifies to precisely that dazzling
breadth and wit that have made Hockney, now 61, one of the most
popular and admired of contemporary artists. By Matt Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA-MORGAN-PHOTOGS (Undated) _ A retrospective of 47
photographs of dancers by Barbara Morgan from the late 1930s to the
early 1940s, will be shown at the James Danziger Gallery through
March 27. By Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ Architecture or real estate, what's
it going to be? Does New York have room for both? These are the
basic questions raised by the Canadian Center for Architecture's
competition to redesign an important piece of land on the west side
of midtown Manhattan. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
