<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, March 10, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-SALARIES (Los Angeles) _ Salaries for middle managers and
technicians in Los Angeles County are among the highest in the
nation, according to a survey released Tuesday. Coupled with
national economic reports that concluded that worker production _
and salaries _ increased dramatically, and the future looks
especially bright for Angelenos. According to the salary survey, a
job that paid an average of $50,000 nationally would pay nearly 14
percent more in Los Angeles, or $56,900. By Gregory J. Wilcox.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial and ``n'' California state wire.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TRAILERS (Los Angeles) _ The major studios are finally
bowing to the will of the people: They're turning down the volume
on their trailers. Movie patrons have long complained that the
volume is too high on those previews that come on before the main
attraction. And some theater owners have taken to turning down the
volume on trailers, which is great for getting through a whiz-bang,
special-effects-loaded trailer, but makes dialogue nearly
impossible to hear. But don't expect the volume to be lower the
next time you go to the multiplex; most trailers for the summer are
already in the can. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f''
financial and ``e'' entertainment news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ The nation's theater owners,
studio executives and marketing honchos gather in Las Vegas to
concoct better schemes of luring more customers to multiplexes. Top
studio lobbyist Jack Valenti and theater-chain advocate William
Kartozian give their ``state of the industry'' addresses and
disclose the key tracking numbers for the U.S. film industry _
admissions, average ticket price, total box office and production
and marketing costs. Attendance was up, and production costs for
the seven major studios decreased by 1.4 percent. By Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial and ``e'' entertainment news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   HELLS-ANGEL-KILL (Los Angeles) _ An arrest has been made in the
slaying of the 400-pound Hells Angel and his girlfriend in a
Chatsworth storage facility where they lived. By Lisa Van Proyen.
(Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
