<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YO-YOS-POPCULTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YO-YO IN POP CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost anything can worm its way into pop culture, and the yo-yo
is no exception. There's even a famous cellist, Yo-Yo Ma. Here are
some other places where the yo-yo had popped up (and down):
</P>
<P>
   _ The all-time Yo-Yo Man is, of course, Tommy Smothers of the
Smothers Brothers, who would do yo-yo tricks onstage while his
brother Dick narrated.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yo-Yo'' was a big hit for the Osmond Brothers in the early
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Holmes and Yoyo'' was a short-lived TV sitcom that ran from
Sept. 25 to Dec. 11, 1976. It starred John Schuck Gregory ``Yoyo''
Yoyonovich, a 427-pound robot who was also a cop.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I Wanna Be a Cowboy,'' by one-hit wonder '80s band Boys
Don't Cry, contains the line ``yo, yo, yippie-yo-yo.''
</P>
<P>
   _ One of Echo and the Bunnymen's songs is ``Yo-Yo Man.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Yo-Yo, a female rapper who's a protege of Ice Cube, had a hit
in the early '90s with ``You Can't Play With My Yo-Yo.'' (She no
doubt was featured on ``Yo! MTV Raps!'')
</P>
<P>
   _ In ``Ernest Goes to Africa'' (1997), Ernest P. Worrell somehow
winds up with some stolen diamonds, which he makes into a yo-yo.
</P>
<P>
   _Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
