<HEADER>
A3916 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANDERS-MAGAZINE-TEX     03-09 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-MAGAZINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NEW MAGAZINE, CAROLYN SANDERS TURNS A PAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolyn Sanders believes in the value of quiet, still moments,
that time she takes each day alone, to get to know who she is and
to tell God those things only he can hear.
</P>
<P>
   As a recently divorced mother of two and the editor and
publisher of Link Magazine, a new publication aimed at
African-American Texans, she says she has much to talk over with
him and will not make a move without consulting him first.
</P>
<P>
   It's what she did when she needed to find a new home for herself
and her two children two years ago after separating from Cowboys
cornerback Deion Sanders. And it's what she did more recently when
she wanted to do something with her life, to make it count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the Lord to show me something to do that I would enjoy
and something I could be successful at,'' Sanders said in a
telephone interview recently from her Houston office.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her talk with God, Sanders was getting her hair
done and met Rose-Mary Tucker, an entertainment promoter, who spoke
of her dream to start a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a sign for me,'' Sanders said. `I didn't
have a journalism degree, but starting a magazine stayed on my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the women _ Tucker as vice president and chief operating
officer and Sanders as the founder, publisher and editor in chief _
head Link Magazine, a slick monthly publication they hope will
connect African-American communities across the state. Link is
available at more than 500 bookstores, airport, grocery chains and
convenience store outlets in Houston, San Antonio and the
Metroplex, and has a circulation of 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 33, said that research showed that though there were
black magazines in Houston, none of them circulated beyond the
city's boundary. That, she thought, left a big void that needed to
be filled.
</P>
<P>
   And so with a small business loan, Link Magazine came into
being, and now has a staff of 11 full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine debuted in January at 56 pages. The current issue
features an interview with basketball greats Clyde Drexler and
Avery Johnson; Dr. Joye Carter, Houston's first female
African-American medical examiner; and the UniverSoul Circus, an
African-American company owned and operated by Big Top Circus.
Marketing efforts include radio spots in the magazine's target
markets and promotional booths at events such as concerts and a
sports fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said she wanted to create a product that all blacks,
regardless of age, gender and socioeconomic status, could enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the avenue for the advertisers who want to reach Texas'
$24 billion annual African-American market,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aadvertisers include Noel Furniture store of Houston, a variety
of minority small businesses and Texas Southern University. No
long-term contracts have been signed yet, though.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, a San Antonio native who has a bachelor's degree in
psychology and was once executive director and co-owner of Players
Network, a sports entertainment show, said starting a magazine is
in keeping with her desire to provide a service to the black
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very spiritual person who puts God first in my life and
cares for others,'' she said. ``That's why in addition to the
magazine, I'm going to start the Prime Life Foundation here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders founded the nonprofit organization in Dallas to help
relieve the economic uncertainty that can make it difficult for
working-class families to stay together. She closed its doors when
she moved from Dallas to Houston two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For now, her time is divided among the magazine, her children _
8-year-old Deiondra and 5-year-old Deion Jr. _ and her church,
Abundant Life Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since coming to Houston, I have a good life,'' she said. ``I'm
at home. I have peace of mind, because I don't dwell on the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who divorced her husband in February 1998, said that
she had a very good marriage with the football great in the
beginning, but that they grew apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen for a reason and you just have to make the best
of the rest of your life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
