</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-USA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS-USA DEAL WEAKENED AS DIRECTOR QUITS BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The controversial merger between Internet company Lycos Inc. and
USA Networks Inc. is teetering on the brink of ruin, after a key
director quit Lycos's board and launched a vocal attack on terms of
the deal .
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that the resignation of David Wetherell could be a
critical turning point in the proposed merger. Lycos could be
forced to renegotiate the deal or seek another merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``After further consideration, it is my opinion that the terms
of the USA/Lycos transaction are inadequate for Lycos
shareholders,'' said Wetherell, chief executive of CMGI Inc., an
Andover, Mass. venture capital company that is Lycos's biggest
investor, with a stake of about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As such, I am resigning from the Lycos board in order to be
free to explore the best options available to Lycos shareholders,
including the possibility of Lycos remaining independent,'' said
Wetherell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a greater chance that the deal is in
trouble, given that the other investors have now found a rallying
point,'' said Ullas Naik, Internet analyst for First Albany Corp.
in Boston. Naik said he knows of a number of institutional
shareholders who are angry about the Lycos-USA transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Lycos stock soared $12 3/8 Tuesday to $96 1/4, as
investors bought shares, hoping for a new, more profitable deal.
CMGI shares declined $5 1/4 to $194 7/16, and USA Networks lost
13/16 to end at $37 11/16..
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced on Feb. 9, would merge Lycos, of Waltham,
Mass., with a number of USA Networks businesses, including the Home
Shopping Network television network; its related Internet Shopping
Network; Ticketmaster, which sells tickets to major public events ;
and Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch, which delivers tickets, as well
as travel and entertainment information, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks chief executive Barry Diller and Bob Davis, chief
executive of Lycos, had hailed the plan as an Internet deal that
would generate $1.2 billion in revenues in its first year. They
also stressed that while other Internet firms don't have the
real-world assets necessary to sell retail goods to millions of
people, the new USA-Lycos company would be able to use the Home
Shopping Network's established product delivery system.
</P>
<P>
   But shareholders were not impressed. They had seen the vast
premiums paid for other Internet companies, such as the $4.56
billion that Yahoo Inc. is paying for GeoCities, a business that
lets people create their own Web pages. CMGI owned a sizable stake
in GeoCities and is expected to net about $1 billion from that
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The USA-Lycos transaction is far different. Shareholders of New
York-based USA Networks will own 56.5 percent to 61.5 percent of
the new company, while Lycos shareholders will get 30 to 35
percent. Lycos investors complained that the deal valued their
shares too cheaply, and felt that they would have gotten a better
deal if Lycos had been acquired by one of the major media companies
that had also been negotiating with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos stock plunged over 30 percent after the deal was
announced. It had reached a high of $137 on Feb. 5, just before the
announcement. Monday, it sank to a low of 83 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal was announced, Wetherell had backed the deal. But
two days later, CMGI said that it wouldn't back the transaction
given the stock's dramatic drop. Later that day, CMGI moderated its
position but reserved the right to back out of the deal. Tuesday,
Wetherell exercised that right.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI has hired Morgan Stanley to press other shareholders for
changes on the Lycos merger, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like he's been pounding on the wall, saying
`Listen to me,' and this is the only way he can get more
attention,'' said Michael Goldston, principal of Cambridge Equity
Advisors Inc. in Nashville, Tenn., and an opponent of the current
deal. Goldston's firm owns about 100,000 shares in Lycos and about
65,000 shares in CMGI.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell's resignation raised the prospect that Lycos might
back out of the USA deal and resume talks with other suitors.
Industry watchers have said that Time Warner Inc., the German media
firm Bertelsmann, and the NBC television network had all expressed
an interest in acquiring the firm.
</P>
<P>
   It's also conceivable that Lycos could seek better terms from
USA Networks. But during a computer industry conference in New York
last week USA Networks' Diller said he had no intention of
renegotiating the terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Diller could not be reached for comment Tuesday. Charles Conn,
chief executive of Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch, one of the USA
Networks companies involved in the deal, remained hopeful that
something could be worked out. He argued that Wetherell's public
repudiation of the deal might actually prompt investors to take a
closer look. ``Anything that provides some greater attention to the
deal will only help people understand why the deal makes sense,''
Conn said.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' Davis could not be reached for comment. His spokeswoman,
Michelle Perry, said that Davis remained confident that the
transaction would go through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1923EST &QL; 
