</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL DELAYS ACTION ON MEDICARE REFORM PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unable to reach consensus, a blue-ribbon commission charged with
recommending Medicare reforms has delayed action for a week, hoping
to use the time to pull together a last-minute compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Tuesday illustrates the devilish complexity of
the commission's task: to overhaul Medicare, and to avert the
financial crisis of the federal health insurance program for 39
million elderly and disabled Americans, which could run out of
money as early as 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The closely watched commission is contemplating a package of
far-reaching reforms that includes increasing the eligibility age
from 65 to 67 years; requiring seniors, particularly wealthier
seniors, to pay more for their care; further cutting payments to
hospitals and doctors; and giving private insurance plans a greater
role in caring for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of moving pieces right now,'' said Senator
John Breaux, chairman of the 17-member commission and a Louisiana
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest pieces being debated is how to pay for the
$210-billion annual program, whose tab is expected to grow
dramatically over the next several decades. President Clinton and
some commission members, including Stuart Altman, a professor of
health policy at Brandeis University, are arguing that 15 percent
of the projected federal budget surplus be dedicated to Medicare.
But others on the commission loudly disagree, saying the surplus
should instead finance a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bill Frist (R-Tenn) also argued that the use of surplus
funds would give people a false sense of security about the
financial soundness of the Medicare program. ``That takes the
pressure inappropriately off the commission to address the
fundamental challenge of Medicare going bankrupt,'' Frist said.
</P>
<P>
   Another stumbling block is prescription drugs, which is
currently not covered by Medicare. Altman and others are lobbying
for a drug benefit that would be available to all Medicare
beneficiaries, but conservatives on the commission say the cost of
such a broad benefit would be prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   A third area of conflict is geographic distribution of vast
amounts of Medicare funds, according to Altman. Providers in
Boston, for example, are reimbursed at a higher rate than, say,
Portland, Ore., for the same care. Whether such disparities are
fair is the subject of much debate, Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen any numbers on how different areas would be
affected,'' Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux requires 11 votes to produce a consensus report to
Congress. He has 10 and is frantically juggling to come up with his
last vote. Breaux reportedly said the chances of a compromise are
``50-50,'' but commission members privately say a consensus is
further away than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to meet for a final time next week to
vote on a package of reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3924 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-ART-2T     03-09 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA LAWYER IS POINT MAN IN LEGAL CRUSADES AGAINST TOBACCO AND
GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Whether over grits and eggs at his favorite diner
or before a jury, Wendell Gauthier is so self-effacing that he
would be the first to admit the many malapropisms that pop out of
his mouth, like the time he lamented a cattle investment because so
many cows died of ``amtraks.'' Or the time he characterized another
lawyer's argument as the height of ``epitome.''
</P>
<P>
   His homespun and seemingly guileless demeanor before juries,
something he perfected while teaching high-school math and science
before he went to night law school, has made him famous _ and rich
_ from big jury awards. In February, he stood before a mock jury
practicing how he would ask for $10 million to compensate a seaman
for a ruined kneecap and bad back from an on-the-job accident in
the Gulf of Mexico. The jurors said his argument was so persuasive
he should have asked for $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, there is nothing guileless about this
up-from-the-country lawyer endowed with a mischievous Cajun charm
and the twangy Francophone drawl of southern Louisiana. Over the
last five years, Gauthier (pronounced goat-CHAY) has organized the
largest ever group of American trial lawyers and led them in a
sustained assault against the tobacco industry for the damage
caused by nicotine addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Though he claims to be neither the smartest nor the richest of
the trial lawyers who have taken on the tobacco industry, he is the
architect and chairman of a growing legal enterprise that is
mounting a similar assault on the gun industry, seeking to force
gun makers to install safety locks on every weapon they sell. Of
the five cities that have sued gun manufacturers this winter for
their alleged culpability in the proliferation of handgun violence,
Gauthier recruited one, New Orleans, and serves as a consultant to
another, Atlanta. A half-dozen other major cities are talking to
Gauthier about joining the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Gauthier and his colleagues as a national legal
phenomenon is a surprising illustration of the rapidly evolving
business of mass litigation, with its broad syndication of legal
and financial resources and political clout across an industry
better known for flamboyant mavericks. These well-organized
courthouse crusades hold the potential to change laws and make
national policy affecting public welfare on issues where
congressional and legislative action remains blocked by a lack of
consensus, fierce lobbying or political contributions financed by
large corporate interests.
</P>
<P>
   Some business and political leaders fear that trial lawyers
nationwide, armed with billions of dollars in fees earned thus far
from tobacco industry settlements, are out to usurp legislative
prerogatives through class-action lawsuits on a whole range of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where lobbying has gotten so intense and money has gotten so
great that they can't legislate,'' Gauthier said, ``I think
legislatures need our help.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, 56, and some of his colleagues assert that if their
model of large-scale litigation proves successful, they will expand
it by bringing actions against the chemical industry over the
contamination of drinking water and against the health care
industry over negligence and abuse in managed-care programs.
</P>
<P>
   They have been shopping not just for individual clients but for
state and municipal governments willing to litigate. And they have
shaped their litigation strategies to focus on compelling questions
of public policy; in part, to immunize themselves from charges that
they are merely ambulance-chasing on a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
   Many government doors have opened because American trial lawyers
as a class are a powerhouse of political financing, one of the
largest single sources of money for the Democratic Party. On the
credenza beside his desk, Gauthier has two framed photographs of
himself with President Clinton. He and his family are prolific
campaign contributors. And Gauthier's friendship with Edwin
Edwards, the former Louisiana governor now under indictment in a
mammoth casino payoff investigation, was so close that Gauthier's
own finances were put under a microscope in the federal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the millions Gauthier has made representing
victims of plane crashes and hotel fires that makes him choose his
words carefully these days, it is the billions of dollars that
trial lawyers _ though not Gauthier _ have been awarded in the
first wave of tobacco settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Those awards have led some to question whether trial lawyers are
gold-digging at the public-policy trough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to make money,'' Gauthier said, ``but at some
point it becomes not just for the money. Everybody alive would love
a situation where they could do good things that accomplish public
good and you are applauded for it and you get paid well for it. I
mean, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   But his critics say that Gauthier is the epitome of greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did this with tobacco and they will do it with other
industries if they win here,'' said state Rep. Steve Scalise, a
Republican who is running for Congress in Louisiana to fill the
seat being vacated by Rep. Bob Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we step in and put a stop to it,'' Scalise said, ``they
will keep on attacking industries that are obeying the law because
it is a source of money for the trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalise has already filed a bill for the coming legislative
session that would effectively immunize the gun industry from the
lawsuit brought by Gauthier's syndicate on behalf of New Orleans
Mayor Marc Morial. Gov. Mike Foster has promised to sign it into
law if it passes. State legislatures in Georgia and Florida have
introduced similar bills.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association is mobilizing across the country
to counter the wave of litigation against the gun industry underway
here and in Chicago, Atlanta, Miami and Bridgeport, Conn. Lawsuits
are also under consideration in Newark and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Fineran, a spokesman for the National Association of
Manufacturers in Washington, said, ``The NAM is very concerned
about where this is going to take us. They have started with two
very disfavored industries, tobacco and guns, and we are concerned
that they are just going to keep going and going.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce announced in February that it would
undertake a nationwide campaign to portray trial lawyers as
self-interested exploiters of the court system, seeking, as
Gauthier's group is, to garner huge fees off of issues that should
be considered more rationally by Congress and by state
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   But Gauthier and his colleagues say they have a role to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courtrooms and juries are the safety valves in the pressure
cooker of our democracy,'' says Russ Herman, a former president of
the Association of Trial Lawyers of America and a wealthy New
Orleans lawyer who joined Gauthier in both the tobacco and gun
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not end-running the legislature,'' said John Coale, a
Washington lawyer who confers with Gauthier every day on group
strategy ``The legislature has failed.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier is the chairman of the Castano Group, a loose
collection of 65 law firms that in 1994 pooled $100,000
contributions from each firm and launched a broad campaign of
litigation against the tobacco industry for damages related to
nicotine addiction. Separately, another group of wealthy trial
lawyers, led by Richard Scruggs, persuaded Mississippi Attorney
General Michael Moore to sue the industry for the state's cost of
treating smoking-related diseases. Scruggs then recruited more than
three dozen states to join that suit, and they hired more than
fifty law firms to represent them in the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the White House eventually stepped in, hoping for a
huge settlement that would reimburse state medical costs, pay for
smoking-cessation projects and end cigarette marketing intended to
appeal to youth.
</P>
<P>
   A legislative settlement under which the tobacco industry would
have paid out $368 billion for health and education programs
collapsed last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But with so many states suing the industry, the tobacco
companies last fall agreed to a $206 billion settlement with 46
states and five U.S. territories. The money will be paid out over
25 years as reimbursement for states' smoking-related medical
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier is quick to say that he has yet to be paid a nickel
from the tobacco industry because the Castano Group lawsuits in 26
states were not covered by the deal. Those class-action lawsuits
seek damages for smoking addiction and have suffered several
judicial setbacks. A decision in February by the Louisiana Supreme
Court validated Castano's class-action petition, clearing the way
for the first trial on nicotine addiction in April in state court.
</P>
<P>
   Litigating on so many fronts has turned Gauthier into as much
politician as lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Castano Group has been forced to develop a lobbying strategy
to explain its goals in Congress, at the White House, in state
legislatures, in the news media and to local chambers of commerce.
It sends lawyers out to make presentations to cities contemplating
litigation against the gun industry, giving each city the option to
attack guns on safety grounds or on grounds that marketing
practices are a public nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Carter, a respected New Orleans political figure who ran
unsuccessfully for mayor in 1994 and who represents the black
political establishment of the city, was recruited by Gauthier to
become one of the group's spokesmen in Washington and, more
recently, to offer Castano's services to big-city mayors interested
in suing the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be a good cause for me,'' said Carter, who had a
$400,000 campaign debt when he joined the group. ``But it also has
to have the possibility of making some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Castano's technology department has converted millions of pages
of tobacco and gun industry documents onto compact disks for easy
retrieval and sharing among law firms around the country. The group
even has an Internet site that advertises for addicted smokers
seeking damages and offers a consumer tobacco litigation kit to
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as way overdue,'' said Ralph Nader, whose Public
Citizen organization has pressed consumer and public safety
campaigns for three decades, often in close cooperation with trial
lawyers. ``All the pre-conditions are there. What is new is the
level of organization between the lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, however, seemed a little skeptical that any new model for
large-scale litigation could succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't consistently do this unless they develop a very
powerful legislative lobbying arm,'' he said, adding, ``They can't
work the courts unless they work the legislatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern that well-paid trial lawyers are pre-empting legislative
prerogatives is the heart of the matter for some critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is support for the effort in gun safety,'' said New
Orleans City Councilman Oliver Thomas, ``but I am also concerned
with people suing everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is lawyers' fees.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers stand to win billions in legal fees by taking on
whole industries on behalf of millions of plaintiffs. Some already
have struck gold in the tobacco litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers who represented the first three states to settle
with the cigarette makers were awarded $8.2 billion in fees in
December, the largest award of fees in history. Though it will be
paid over 25 years, the award, the first of several related to the
tobacco cases, has prompted criticism that trial lawyers are being
compensated far beyond any reasonable assessment of the value of
the time they have invested.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gauthier was somewhat astounded by the scale of the award.
He predicted that if the Castano Group prevailed, the fees would be
far more modest, perhaps several billion dollars spread over 25
years and 65 law firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us is going to retire as a result of the tobacco
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Gauthier has often been straightforward in stating
that he is in it for the money, at the same time speaking
passionately against smoking. The Castano Group is named for Peter
Castano, a longtime friend of Gauthier's who died of lung cancer in
1993 after a life addicted to cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The gun litigation began last fall, after Gauthier discovered
that Morial was willing to sue gun manufacturers over the many
accidental shootings and drug-related gun violence that threatened
New Orleans tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier dispatched his partner, Daniel Abel, to Washington to
sound out the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence on whether it
would join such a lawsuit with an aim to force the industry to
install safety locks on handguns, rifles and shotguns. The center,
whose chairwoman is Sarah Brady, wife of President Ronald Reagan's
bullet-scarred former press secretary, James Brady, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, Gauthier, on behalf of the city of New Orleans, sued
Smith and Wesson Corp.; Beretta, U.S.A.; Colts Manufacturing Co.;
Glock Inc., and a number of other manufacturers, for damages caused
by what he contended was unsafe gun design.
</P>
<P>
   The gun manufacturers have challenged the suit on procedural
grounds, seeking to have it removed from state court to federal
court. A hearing is scheduled to resolve the issue March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The next great issue will be managed health care, said Herman,
whose New Orleans law firm has contributed $6 million in time and
resources to the tobacco litigation with Gauthier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Congress has an opportunity to do something about it,''
Herman said, ``but if they don't act, my guess is that in five
years you will see a massive lawsuit brought to destroy and
dismember managed care as it currently operates.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, at times, seems reluctant to predict where the crusade
is going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I thought about it since we branched into guns? Yes, he
said, posing and answering his own questions. ``Are there other
public issues that in my view merit this type of litigation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Water,'' he replies. ``We have a problem right now with
chemicals that are flooding into the water supply and an industry
that again just refuses to address the problem and wants to
litigate rather than resolve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
