<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, March 10. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP (Undated) _ Dismantling what the
swashbuckling corporate mentality of the 1980s wrought, RJR Nabisco
announces it is splitting up its food and tobacco businesses and
selling its foreign tobacco company to the Japanese. The company
becomes the biggest casualty of a decade-long court battle over
tobacco companies' liabilities in smoking-related illnesses and
deaths. By Constance L. Hays. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m.
ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars and graphics inside.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Richard Holbrooke, the American
envoy. warns that Yugoslavia is only a few days away from a tragedy
of greater proportions than ever, as he arrives in Belgrade to try
to push forward a peace agreement for the separatist province of
Kosovo. Holbrooke, who will meet with President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yogoslavia on Wednesday, says the West and Yugoslavia are on a
collision course that could draw in NATO. By Carlotta Gall.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead: 3-column photo reefer to CLINTON; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ The White House is resisting a House
panel's efforts to make public information about the handling of
China's campaign to acquire sensitive American military technology.
By Jeff Gerth. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-AIDS (Paris) _ A former prime minister and a member of
his Cabinet are acquitted on charges of criminal negligence and
manslaughter in the deaths of hundreds of people who contracted
AIDS in the mid-1980s from transfusions of tainted blood. By Craig
R. Whitney. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIDS (Beijing) _ Song Pengfei, 17 years old, is one of a
small but growing number of Chinese infected with the virus that
causes AIDS in a country that is emotionally, financially and
medically largely unprepared to deal with them. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) With photo.
1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BOOK (Mexico City) _ A new children's book in Spanish and
English is being published by a small press in El Paso _ a
profusely illustrated ``History of Colors,'' which tells an ancient
Mexican Indian myth of how colors came into the world. The
publisher received a grant from the National Endowment for the
Arts. Open the book and on the jacket is a picture of the author:
Subcommandate Insurgente Marcos, leader of the left-wing Zapatista
rebellion in Mexico. By Julia Preston. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``i'' news file.) With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWYER (New Orleans) _ Over the last five years, Wendell
Gauthier has organized the largest ever group of American trial
lawyers and led them in a sustained assault against the tobacco
industry for the damage caused by nicotine addiction. Though he
claims to be neither the smartest nor the richest of the trial
lawyers who have taken on the tobacco industry, he is the architect
and chairman of a growing legal enterprise that is mounting a
similar assault on the gun industry. By Patrick E. Tyler.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) With photo.
2,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   photo reefer: ALEXANDER-POLITICS (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Lamar
Alexander formally declares his candidacy for the Republican
presidential nomination by recalling his achievements as governor
of Tennessee and vowing to restore respect for the presidency. By
Richard L. Berke. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-COIA (Undated) _ An independent hearing officer cleared
Arthur Coia, president of the laborers' union and one of the
nation's best-known labor leaders, of associating with members of
organized crime but fines him $100,000 for buying a $450,000
Ferrari with improper financial help from a supplier to the union.
By Steven Greenhouse. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AHOLD-PATHMARK (Undated) _ In a deal that pushes it further into
some of the toughest U.S. markets, Royal Ahold NV, the scrappy
Dutch food retailer, says it will acquire Pathmark Stores Inc. for
$250 million in cash and the assumption of $1.5 billion in debt. By
Dana Canedy. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SUN-FORECAST (Undated) _ Analyzing X-ray images of transient
S-shaped patterns on the Sun, scientists think they have found a
reliable way to forecast powerful solar eruptions that can cause
disruptive magnetic storms in the Earth's atmosphere, knock out
electrical systems and communications and disable orbiting
spacecraft. By John Noble Wilford. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
