<SLUG> BC-ATHLETES-SATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIKES DOWN SAT MEASURE OF STUDENT-ATHLETES' ABILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Higher education officials Tuesday defended the need for minimum
academic standards for student athletes, saying that Monday's court
decision striking down minimum admissions scores would return to
the days when colleges and universities admitted athletes who could
build a better team, with little regard to whether those students
could read or write.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court on Monday struck down the minimum SAT scores set
by the National Collegiate Athletic Association for its Division I
schools in 1986, saying the standards discriminated against black
students, who have been shown to perform lower than their white
peers on standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   It suggested the NCAA find other ways to make sure students were
academically qualified, including perhaps a combination of scores
and grades.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches welcomed the decision _ not because it could allow them
to pull poor academic performers off the bench, they said, but
because the standards had unfairly sidelined promising students.
For many minority and poor students, they said, low scores reflect
poverty, not lack of potential.
</P>
<P>
   But NCAA officials and college presidents who helped set the bar
for the scores reminded the public Tuesday that the rules had been
adopted overwhelmingly by NCAA members, who were horrified at how
college athletic departments were admitting students who had no
chance of academic success. High schools were inflating grades to
win admission for star students, and once in college, many of those
students were being allowed to slide by in gut courses. This might
have helped the team, but only ended up hurting individual students
once their athletic careers ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you return back to the reasons the rule was adopted
overwhelmingly it was to deal with...the exploitation of student
athletes,'' said Kevin Lennon vice president for member service at
the NCAA. ``There's more individuals who because the standards have
been in place have had better success in college because they were
better prepared. The clear point is, the vast majority of students
have been better served by having an eligibility standard.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials recalled the widely-publicized scandals that
prompted the rules, when one student was so ill-prepared he could
not read his college diploma.
</P>
<P>
   While coaches said they welcomed the decision because it would
open up access to disadvantaged students, the decision also set off
a flurry of speculation about its effect on the NCAA basketball
finals, scheduled to begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the NCAA operating without any minimum standards for
admission or participation, some speculated that teams could pull
students who had been deemed unqualified under the NCAA standards
off the bench to play in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wethington, president of the University of Kentucky and
chair of the NCAA Executive Committee, said he hoped that wouldn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole situation is too fluid, too undecided, too much at
risk,'' he said, ``and it would be sending absolutely the wrong
signal.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA said it would appeal the decision, and also try to come
up with a measure of academic preparedness the court could agree
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other standards that admissions directors will tell
you are more indicative of success in college,'' said Richard
Lapchick, director of the Center for Sport in Society at
Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College athletic director Gene DeFilippo agreed. ``I've
always believed that grade point average and class ranking should
carry the most weight and are a better indicator than test
scores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Davis, the football coach at the University of Miami, said
doing away with minimums based on standardized test scores would
allow students who might not score well to prove that they can
achieve despite their rank on standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer in who leaves rather than who comes in that's
important,'' he said. ``If you maintain your grades and do your
work, you can get a degree, and that reflects better on a
university than the decision about who they let in before those
students have a chance to prove themselves. It gives athletes an
opportunity to overachieve and cuts down on some of the inequities
in the testing system.''
</P>
<P>
   At FairTest in Cambridge, Mass., which launched the initial
lawsuit, Bob Schaeffer said the NCAA had targeted the wrong people
in setting the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a serious problem over the years, there were very
clearly kids who were being exploited by the system, particularly
minority and low-income students,'' he said. ``But instead of
dealing with the abusers _ the institutions, the coaches, the
administrators, they decided to dump on the next generation of
kids. The rule was discriminatory, the NCAA knew the rule was
discriminatory.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Staff member Mark Blaudschun contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
