<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-AIDS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH EX-PREMIER ACQUITTED IN HIV-TAINTED BLOOD SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A former prime minister and a member of his Cabinet were
acquitted on Tuesday on charges of criminal negligence and
manslaughter in the deaths of hundreds of people who contracted
AIDS in the mid-1980s from transfusions of tainted blood.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Laurent Fabius, now speaker of the lower
house of Parliament, and Georgina Dufoix, social affairs minister
in the government that Fabius headed from 1984 to 1986, were
cleared by a specially convened jury of legislators and judges.
</P>
<P>
   Edmond Herve, heath minister under Mrs. Dufoix, was convicted of
two cases of negligence. The court ruled that he should have
ordered untreated blood supplies destroyed as soon as the risk of
their being contaminated with the virus that causes AIDS was known.
</P>
<P>
   But the court imposed no sentence. It could have given Herve up
to five years in prison. But it ruled that the protracted scandal
had deprived him of the right to the presumption of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't have the courage to find me fully innocent,'' Herve,
56, said of the court after the verdict. ``Nor did it have the
courage to convict me really.''
</P>
<P>
   One advocacy group for transfusion victims, the French
Transfusion Association, declared the acquittal of Fabius
``disgraceful'' and the trial ``manipulated and discredited.''
Lower-ranking experts and functionaries had been tried and found
guilty for crimes in the scandal, the group said, but members of
the government were untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are like gangsters,'' a surviving infected victim,
Sylvie Rouy, 35, said. ``Unless you catch them red-handed, you
never get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Herve was found guilty of involuntary injury in Ms. Rouy's case
and of involuntary manslaughter in the death of a 2-year-old
infected by a transfusion given to her mother before the girl's
birth.
</P>
<P>
   That there had been government negligence in screening blood
supplies was never in dispute. But it has taken France more than a
decade to face the question of whether high elected officials
should bear more than political responsibility for their response
to the problem when first confronted with it in the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   Holding ministers criminally responsible for official actions
was vigorously disputed. In all, 4,400 people, many hemophiliacs or
others who needed transfusions, contracted AIDS from inadequately
tested blood here from the period when Fabius' Socialist government
was in power. About 40 percent died.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the dead and others contended that Fabius and his
health officials had deliberately delayed introducing systematic
testing of blood banks for the AIDS virus, even though an American
test developed by Abbott Laboratories was on the market in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The government, they said, stalled until a French test developed
by Diagnostics Pasteur could be approved for reimbursement by the
state health system.
</P>
<P>
   Fabius vigorously disputed that and testified at the monthlong
trial that he had been unaware of discussions about giving the
French test an edge. He said he had ordered systematic testing as
soon as he was aware that it was available, advancing the date to
Aug. 1, 1985, two months earlier than originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict Tuesday, he said, ``The accusations made
against me all these years were shown by the decision to be clearly
unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Even acquittal, however, left Fabius' political prospects
uncertain. Now 52, he was France's youngest prime minister when he
was named in 1984, and until he was caught up in the scandal, had
been thought a possible candidate for the presidency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Awkwardness pervaded the trial. Even the prosecution called for
acquitting the three defendants in its summation late last month.
</P>
<P>
   The presiding judge, Christian Le Gunehec, one of three
magistrates in the 15-member court, at one point described the
proceeding as surrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Uneasiness ran across the spectrum Tuesday, from Fabius'
Socialist colleagues to their conservative opponents, whose
legislators outnumbered those from leftist parties on the jury, 7
to 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken as a whole, the health policy of the government of
France from April to September 1985 was catastrophic, as far as the
struggle against the spread of AIDS was concerned,'' the chief
prosecutor, Jean-Francois Burgelin, said. ``Badly informed,
indecisive, pusillanimous, unconscious of the gravity of the
epidemic, those politically responsible for public health did not
rapidly take the measures that could have limited the extent of the
disaster,'' he said in his summation.
</P>
<P>
   But Burgelin concluded that governments always made mistakes.
``Will we one day see the responsible ministers charged before this
court with the deaths of the 2,544 people who have been victims
over the past 30 years of accidents at railroad crossings that
could have been avoided by building bridges, as people are
constantly demanding?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
