<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-COX     03-09 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr's bill on gun suits draws opposition
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgia Republican Rep. Bob Barr's legislation
banning cities and states from suing gunmakers is creating a
political maelstrom on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, officially unveiled Tuesday, was severely criticized
by lawyers and politicians who say it would take away a fundamental
American right: the right to seek recourse in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's bill is in reaction to lawsuits filed by Atlanta,
Bridgeport, Chicago, Miami-Dade and New Orleans that seek to hold
the gun industry accountable for violent crime on their streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is NRA-driven insanity,'' said Sen. Chuck
Schumer (D-N.Y.), pointing out that Georgia is the leading supplier
of guns to out-of-state criminals, according to data kept by the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. ``Why draft legislation to
protect those who are in the business of arming dangerous
criminals?''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill won support from an array of organizations such as
the Americans for Tax Reform, the National Rifle Association and
the Southern States Police Benevolent Association. In a single day,
two dozen lawmakers signed on, including five Republicans from the
Georgia delegation and three Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   If the lawsuits against the gun industry are allowed to
continue, it would set a dangerous precedent for other industries,
said Grover Norquist, head of the taxpayer group. It would mean
that the cities would be allowed to use taxpayer dollars to go
after any industry targeted by trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   That was music to Barr's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unholy alliance between trial lawyers, big city mayors and
anti-gun activists is about far more than gun control,'' Barr said.
If the lawsuits are allowed to continue, then it will be a
``Katie-bar-the-door'' situation, said Barr, warning that even the
maker of the Louisville Slugger could face a lawsuit because the
baseball bat has been used to kill people.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Barbara Boxe (D-Calif.) said she intends to introduce
legislation that would guarantee cities the right to sue gun
manufacturers and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government sends billions of dollars to local
communities to fight crime,'' she said. ``If local governments
believe the fight against crime is being hampered because of a mass
proliferation of guns, I believe it is in the national interest to
allow them to take action in court.''
</P>
<P>
   About 13 states are following Georgia in banning local lawsuits
against gun manufacturers. But Barr, a board member of the NRA,
said a federal law is needed to ensure that gun manufacturers are
treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's bill amounts to granting the gun industry special
protection from lawsuits, said Denise Dunleavy, an attorney who won
a $4 million verdict against 15 gun manufacturers last month on
behalf of a shooting victim. ``I think it's an outrage.'' he
said.Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
