<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLAR-FLARES-BOS &LR;      03-09 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAR-FLARES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW METHOD GIVES EARLY WARNING ABOUT SOLAR FLARES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Solar-Telescope)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes the sun blows its stack, sending explosive outbursts
of energy out into space and occasionally right toward Earth. This
can cripple satellites, cause power blackouts, and threaten
astronauts heading into space, but scientists Tuesday reported a
dramatic new find that should help them to see such blasts brewing
a week in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a breakthrough discovery in forecasting the largest
explosions in the modern-day solar system,'' said space scientist
George Withbroe.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery came from detailed pictures of the sun's X-ray
emissions, taken by a Japanese-built satellite called Yohkoh, which
revealed that a characteristic S-shaped formation usually appears
on the sun's surface just before these tremendous explosions,
called Coronal Mass Ejections.
</P>
<P>
   ``S marks the spot,'' said Alphonse Sterling of Virginia-based
Computational Physics Inc., who has been working on the project for
the Japanese space science agency ISAS. Whenever these S-shaped
regions appear on the sun, he said, it is ``like a loaded gun that
we know has a high probability of going off.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting explosions unleash as much energy as billions of
nuclear explosions, the scientists said Tuesday at a National
Aeronautics and Space Administration press conference announcing
the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   While such events can occur as often as once or twice a day,
only a small fraction of them are aimed toward Earth, and even
those that do reach us have most of their energy blocked by Earth's
magnetic field so that none reaches the ground in a form that can
directly harm people.
</P>
<P>
   But indirect effects can cause damage, especially as the world
becomes more dependent on electrical power distribution and on
satellites used for communications, navigation, and weather
prediction. A so-called coronal mass ejection ten years ago, for
example, caused a major power blackout in Quebec and temporarily
disrupted some satellites.
</P>
<P>
   That came during the last peak in the sun's 11-year cycle of
activity. The next peak of activity, already starting to build up,
is expected about a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts aboard the space shuttle and space stations such as
Mir and the new International Space Station are protected by
Earth's magnetic field. But any astronauts who leave Earth's
environs would be vulnerable to deadly radiation from such solar
outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   During the Apollo moon missions, ``we were lucky that nothing
bad happened,'' said Withbroe, who is NASA's science director for
sun-Earth connections. ``If we go to Mars, we'll have to worry more
than we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   With enough warning, astronauts heading to Mars could simply
ride out the storm by huddling together in a small ``storm cellar''
_ a heavily-shielded compartment inside the spacecraft. But without
such warning, Withbroe said, the radiation from such solar
outbursts ``can be extremely hazardous _ can be deadly, in fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the practical results of the new finding in terms of
enabling better forecasts, it should also help scientists to better
understand how the sun itself works. Many features that can be seen
on the sun's surface, said Richard Canfield, a physicist at Montana
State University, ``are related to events going on deep inside,''
in the same way that volcanos on Earth are related to things going
on deep below.
</P>
<P>
   The S-shaped structures seen on the sun's surface are probably
magnetic field lines emanating from the ``solar dynamo'' at its
center, a swirling mass that theorists believe produces the sun's
intense magnetic field. The S shapes may be places where ``you
twist the magnetic field up like you twist a rubber band, and it's
ready to release,'' said Withbroe.
</P>
<P>
   These distinctive shapes on the surface ``are important because
they give us an indication of the twistedness of the magnetic field
and its likeliness to erupt,'' said Sarah Gibson, a theorist at
Cambridge University in England.
</P>
<P>
   So far, calculations about the amount of energy built up and
expelled by each of these outbursts closely matches calculations
based on theorists' present ideas of the sun's structure, said
David McKenzie of Montana State University. ``It's tending to
confirm a very important, fundamental understanding about the
sun,'' he said. ``It can be developed into a very powerful
prediction tool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major step forward in understanding these tremendous
storms,'' said Withbroe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
