<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FIGHTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE TREATY STILL UNSIGNED, GUNFIRE STILL ROCKS KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ Serbs and ethnic Albanians traded gun and mortar fire
in Kosovo Tuesday, while frustrated international mediators
scrambled to get at least one side's signature on a Western-crafted
peace agreement neither the Serbs nor the Albanians like.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians have been trying the patience of Western
mediators, who have been repeatedly assured that the Albanian
delegation would sign the peace pact but have yet to see it happen.
Most recently, Albanian officials told a longtime supporter, former
US senator Bob Dole, that they would sign the agreement Sunday.
They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they took the best friend they have in US politics
and messed with him. They embarrassed Bob Dole,'' said a Western
diplomat. If the Albanians continue to delay, ``their support is
just going to evaporate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians have enjoyed American diplomatic support
and public empathy because of their suffering in the yearlong
conflict, but their delegation has been divided between moderates,
who are willing to accept political autonomy for the disputed
province, and hard-liners, who insist on full independence. The
last holdout is the Kosovo Liberation Army _ a critical faction
because they are the ones with weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Albanians failed to sign the pact at the end
of a first round of peace talks in Rambouillet, France, a slap to
US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright. Albright is so admired
by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo that they affectionately call her
``mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are anxious to get an Albanian signature on the
peace deal so they can pressure Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to do the same. Until the Albanians sign, the West cannot
credibly threaten Milosevic with a NATO airstrike _ a threat few
Serbs take seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Balkan negotiators Richard Holbrooke and Chris Hill went to
Belgrade Tuesday, and are to meet Wednesday with Milosevic, who
objects to the proposed deployment of 28,000 NATO peacekeeping
troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the KLA is nervous about the pact, too, since if they
disarm, they would have to rely completely on NATO to protect them,
said Jim Hooper of the Washington, D.C.-based Balkan Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Albanians really want is to keep the KLA intact in
some form,'' he said. ``They want to remain intact, since they
don't trust the Serbs, and they're not sure they trust NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting escalated Tuesday in Kosovo, in what monitors for the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe called a
continuing pattern by both sides to best their positions before
peace talks resume next week in Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both doing it equally. Violations of the cease-fire
have been even-handed,'' said an OSCE spokeswoman, Beatrice
Lacoste.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have greatly increased their military presence in
Kosovo, telling international monitors that the buildup is just a
part of their military ``winter exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serb Army Tuesday shelled the town of Kacanik, in what
Lacoste called a ``cleanup operation'' designed to drive out any
remaining KLA forces there. Warfare also continued in the town of
Vucitrn, which has been the site of violence over the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbia Media Center in Pristina reported that two Serb
police were killed and three wounded Monday by an anti-tank mine
planted by Albanian ``terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting also erupted along two tenuous borders _ the southern
border of Macedonia, where US troops are stationed, and the western
border with Albania, Lacoste said. An estimated 250 refugees were
forced to flee the area along the southern border as Serb tanks
swept the area.
</P>
<P>
   The western border is particularly volatile, since Albania is
itself unstable, and its prime minister has called for NATO
military action in Kosovo to stop Serb aggression. The north of
Albania is a known base for gun-runners supplying arms to the
Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   International workers have been harassed recently, Lacoste said.
The OSCE _ charged with supervising the cease-fire brokered last
year _ has ``not been able to monitor'' recently, because they have
been denied access to some areas, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the daily violations of the cease-fire, both sides are
picking apart the peace agreement. The KLA has given mixed signals,
suggesting in a statement Tuesday that they would not sign a peace
pact unless they get peace first.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has had difficulty getting full agreement from all of
its leaders, in part because the army's political leader, Hashim
Thaqi, has been in neighboring Albania for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   US negotiators are still counting on an eventual approval from
the KLA. The delay ``is standard. It's the same old stuff,'' said
Philip Reeker, spokesman for Hill. ``They said they will sign. Who
knows? Nobody can read their minds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
