<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDITOR DECRIES ABANDONED PROPERTY RECORD-KEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is stuffed with 82 bank bags, many of which are not
sealed, dozens of envelopes and boxes, four US Postal tubs
overflowing with financial documents, two suitcases, and a filing
cabinet filled with jewelry, savings bonds, Krugerrands, a firearm,
and war medals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the piles, there are 1942 Dutch pennies, a briefcase, 1988
Bruins tickets, and a silver sugar and creamer service.
</P>
<P>
   The items, thrown ``haphazardly'' into the state treasury's
abandoned property vault on Beacon Hill, represent only a fraction
of the millions of dollars' worth of assets that might never be
returned to their rightful owners because of poor record keeping,
according to a scathing report Auditor Joseph DeNucci released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly confirmed Tuesday
that his office is expanding its investigation beyond the nearly $9
million allegedly stolen from the treasury's Unpaid Check Fund and
is looking into the related abandoned property account, which at
one point swelled to $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there was no way to determine whether the above
items represented all of the inventory that should have been found
within these containers, because . . . the office did not reconcile
these items upon their receipt,'' the audit said.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of the Abandoned Property Division, which holds
everything from dormant passbook savings accounts to large real
estate parcels, inaccurately documented or did not thoroughly
inventory its assets, the audit found.
</P>
<P>
   The report, mandated by law whenever there is a change in the
administration, comes amid a vigorous investigation into thefts
from the accounts that hold money and other property for people and
companies across the state who may have died or cannot be located.
</P>
<P>
   New Democratic Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien said ``garbage put
into the system is garbage out,'' suggesting permanent limbo for
some assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the property has real and sentimental value to people
across the Commonwealth,'' she said. She added later: ``We may
never be able to find out who the rightful owners are.''
</P>
<P>
   Her GOP predecessor, Joseph D. Malone, dismissed the audit as
political.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past eight years, the treasury has been audited
annually by Joe DeNucci's office and by private accounting firms,''
Malone said in a statement. ``The office was found to be in fine
shape. . . . A few bad apples should not be allowed to tarnish that
record.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the audit found systemic problems in the treasury,
particularly with the way the department has handled abandoned
property.
</P>
<P>
   Often, assets were not labeled or itemized, the report said. And
although the treasury is required to publish annual lists of those
with abandoned assets, the advertisements did not include property
from banks, hospitals, and uncashed state checks.
</P>
<P>
   Such omissions are illegal, the auditor said. Further, that
list, which usually appears in major newspapers informing unwitting
owners of their property, was not published in every county, as
required by law.
</P>
<P>
   This year's list, due out within weeks, will be ``problematic''
and incomplete because of the poor records, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the report's other findings:
</P>
<P>
   --Abandoned assets were not liquidated as quickly as the law
requires.
</P>
<P>
   --Abandoned physical property stored within a vault in the state
government's McCormack Building was strewn about in a ``haphazard
and disorganized manner.'' And only two people, former assistant
treasurer Thomas Trimarco and division director Michael Flaherty,
had access to the safe's combination, which had not been changed
over the last eight years. Trimarco resigned during the transition.
Flaherty will be retained, according to Deputy Treasurer Michael
Travaglini.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said she has not seen the inside of the vault combed by
auditors Jan. 29 but is considering moving the safe. Meanwhile, she
is grappling with ``palettes'' of worthless property.
</P>
<P>
   --Exacerbating the buildup of abandoned goods, Malone held
liquidating auctions only three times during his eight-year tenure,
despite the fact that law allows for annual bidding. One former
abandoned property administrator told auditors that Malone slashed
the staff from 45 to 15, making it difficult to handle all the
property.
</P>
<P>
   --BankBoston, which controlled a portfolio of more than $136
million in abandoned stocks, bonds, cash dividends, and other
abandonded financial property, was not selected by an open bid
process and no written contract existed.
</P>
<P>
   --The treasury did not know how much in fees the state paid
BankBoston to manage the portfolio and, at one point, BankBoston
had not turned over more than $3.4 million in dividends over six
years. Also, the treasury did not notice a $30 million discrepancy
between its own portfolio records and BankBoston's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
