A3966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHATTANOOGA-COX     03-09 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHATTANOOGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is Chattanooga on a rival track?
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chattanooga, Tenn. officials expect to break ground in
October on a $43 million conference center they hope will attract
business from Atlanta and other Southern cities within a 200-mile
radius.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in the city's efforts to shore up a once-sagging
downtown, the 210,000-square-foot center will sit on five acres and
have a 200-room hotel, a 30,000-square foot conference facility, a
7,700-square foot ballroom, a 125-seat amphitheater, 12 meeting
rooms and a restaurant and pub. The facility is to open in early
2001, and Chattanooga officials expect to make $2 million in profit
by 2003 and $2.8 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some great success over the past five to six years
in bringing the whole downtown back,'' said Mayor Jon Kensey. ``The
conference center is a great addition. But we can't be satisfied
with what we've done. We've got to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga's downtown, once considered one of the shabbiest in
the Southeast, started its march back toward respectability with
the May 1992 opening of the $45 million Tennessee Aquarium. Within
a few years, an IMAX theater and the Creative Discovery Museum
opened nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown redevelopment efforts continued in October 1997 with
the opening of Finley Stadium, a $28 million project.
</P>
<P>
   The conference center will be financed through a $100 million
bond issue paid by sales taxes collected in a special downtown
district. The rest of the bond money will be used for an expansion
of the nearby 100,000-square-foot Chattanooga and Hamilton County
Convention and Trade Center and construction of the Development
Resource Center, a government complex that will house city and
county permitting and regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga officials are negotiating with the Tennessee Valley
Authority for purchase of the parcel on which the center will be
built. The sale is expected to be final within six to eight weeks,
said Rob Taylor, who is in charge of the project for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor declined to indicate how much the parcel is expected to
cost, but said he expects no glitches because the TVA has been
cooperating with the city since the project's early development
stages.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga also is negotiating with Benchmark Hospitality Inc.,
a Texas company, to manage the property once completed. Those
negotiations are expected to be completed in four to six weeks,
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The conference center, which is being designed by Rabun Hogan
Ota Rasche Architects of Atlanta, will rely on package
meeting-lodging sales for most of its revenue. City officials hope
to attract business from metro Atlanta, Nashville, Birmingham,
Knoxville and Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   In scope and size, the facility will resemble such Atlanta area
conference centers as Evergreen at Stone Mountain, the Peachtree
Conference Center in Peachtree City and the Marietta Conference
Center, said Geoff Kirkland, chairman of Charlotte, N.C.-based
Horwath Hospitality Consultants U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland has served as a consultant to the Chattanooga project,
which will differ from most conference centers because of its urban
location. Most other centers have suburban settings and feature
such amenities as golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our urban location for this is a distinction
and a selling point, not a disadvantage,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   COMPARABLE FACILITIES IN GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   Most major cities have convention centers, which are designed to
hold thousands of people at one time. Many of those facilities also
have break-out capabilities to host smaller conferences. Facilities
built exclusively as conference centers have lodging and eating
facilities and are designed to host smaller groups, often
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   _ Evergreen Conference Center, Stone Mountain: 31,000 square
feet of conference facilities; 249 hotel rooms; 35 meeting rooms;
golf course; swimming pool; tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marietta Conference Center &AMP; Resort: 20,000 square feet of
meeting space; 199 hotel rooms; 300-seat restaurant and 116-seat
pub; 6,500-square-foot ballroom; 18 meeting rooms that seat 10-170
people; golf course; outdoor swimming pool and hot tub; two outdoor
tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brasstown Valley Resort, Young Harris: 14,300 square feet of
meeting space; 134 lodging rooms (102-room lodge and eight
four-bedroom cottages); 3,872-square-foot ballroom that can be
converted into four meeting rooms; eight additional meeting rooms;
75-seat amphitheater; swimming pool; four tennis courts; golf
course; hiking trails; bar/lounge and dining room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Savannah Civic Center: 11 meeting rooms; 8,000-seat theater;
1,600-seat banquet facility; 100 conference/classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
