<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-SAT-COX     03-09 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-SAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minimum SAT scores unfair to African-Americans, says judge; NCAA
eligibility on line
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In February 1998, Terrence Edwards realized a lifelong
dream when he signed to play football at the the University of
Georgia. One of the South's top players, he was looking forward to
following in the footsteps of his brother Robert, a star running
back for the Bulldogs. But Edwards' dream would be painfully
deferred.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a B average at Washington County High School, Edwards
could not make the NCAA's minimum required score of 820 on the
Scholastic Aptitude Test or 68 on the American College Test. As a
result, Edwards did not enroll in college in the fall of 1998 as he
continued to take the test. Finally, on his eighth try, Edwards
made an 840 on the SAT and enrolled at Georgia for the winter
semester of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Edwards looks forward to spring practice and his first
season as a Bulldog. But Edwards also wonders if he'll ever get
over the public stigma of not meeting the NCAA standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' he said. ``People in high school know
you're not dumb, but people who don't know you pass judgment on
you. They read in the newspaper you didn't qualify, and people all
over the country automatically think you're dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   The system that affected Edwards so negatively could be
changing. A Philadelphia judge ruled Monday that the NCAA's
requirement for a minimum standardized test score is unfair to
African-Americans and is therefore illegal. If the ruling survives
an appeal by the NCAA, all 302 Division I schools could be on their
own to determine which freshmen are eligible to play college
sports.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling brought mixed reactions throughout the academic and
athletic communities. One side praised the ruling as a victory for
African-American athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the most significant ruling ever in college
athletics,'' said Perry Clark, the head basketball coach at Tulane,
who is black. ``A test score is not a way of measuring your desire,
your heart, your character, because, for a lot of folks, they start
at a disadvantage. You can't put a formula on some people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, some college administrators are concerned
that, depending on what happens next, the net effect could be bad
for college athletic and academic endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has asked U.S. District Judge Ronald L. Buckwalter to
stay his ruling, pending an appeal to the U.S. 3rd Circuit Court in
Philadelphia. If Buckwalter refuses, the NCAA will have to scramble
to get a new set of guidelines in place that address the court's
concerns. ``I think this ruling caught a lot of people by surprise,
and we're wondering what's next,'' said Hoke Wilder, Georgia's
assistant athletics director for NCAA compliance. ``Surely, we
won't go back to the old days when there was no standard. Then we
really could have some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Until 1986, there was not an NCAA-wide standard for athletic
eligibility. As a result there were numerous cases where athletes
with no chance of passing college work were admitted. College
athletics was rocked by a series of stories about star athletes
leaving college unable to read and no where close to a degree.
</P>
<P>
   One of those highly publicized academic scandals took place at
Georgia, where the Jan Kemp case revealed that football players
with SAT scores in the 400s _ out of a maximum 1,600 points _ had
been admitted into the University.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that situation, the NCAA passed Proposition 48 at
its January 1986 convention. Prop 48 required a minimum grade-point
average and standardized test score in order to be eligible to
participate in athletics as a freshman. The NCAA has amended the
policy over the years to its current form, which calls for a 2.5
grade-point average in 13 college-preparatory subjects _ such as
English, math, science _ plus a minimum score on the SAT or ACT.
</P>
<P>
   Since the policies went into effect, some educators and social
scientists have argued that the standardized test requirement
descriminates against African-Americans who, studies have shown,
perform worse on the tests in general than whites do. Georgetown
basketball coach John Thompson, who is black, once boycotted a pair
of basketball games in 1989 to protest the policy.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit which brought about Monday's ruling was filed by
Leatrice Shaw and Tae Kwan Cureton, track-and-field athletes at
Philadelphia's Simon Gratz High in 1996. Shaw had a GPA of 3.5;
Cureton's was 2.8. Both were in the top 10 percent of their class,
but they could not get athletic scholarships because they had not
made the minimum test scores. Buckwalter used the NCAA's own
studies to make his ruling. Those studies showed that the
ineligibility rates, which represent the percentage of athletes who
fail to qualify academically as freshmen, disproportionately hurt
blacks. According to NCAA statistics, 3.7 percent of white athletes
failed to quality as freshmen, while the corresponding number for
African-Americans was 20.6 percent. Among those praising the ruling
Tuesday was Duke basketball coach Mike Krzyzewski. The president of
the National Association of Basketball Coaches, Krzyzewksi long has
said that the minimum test score descriminates against students
from lower socio-economic backgrounds. ``This court ruling will
certainly open a new discussion for creating better legislation for
all youngsters,'' he said. ``I look forward to participating in
those discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who retired as coach at Georgetown earlier this year,
said he had mixed emotions about the ruling. ``Changes will
obviously come about, but how do you go back and change the kids
this hurt?'' Thompson asked. ``All you can say is, 'Sorry,' and
there's something very very wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Edwards agrees. ``Basically, the SAT doesn't reflect
how smart a person is, in my opinion,'' he said. ``I know some
people who had 4.0s (as GPAs) in high school who made 700s. I wish
(the ruling) had happened before. It might've save me some
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Chip Towers and Norman Arey contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
