<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKMUN-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKMUN RECALLED AS COMPASSIONATE JUDGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Supreme Court Justice Harry A. Blackmun, who
died last week, was remembered Tuesday as a compassionate judge and
a loving but often absent father.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer, who succeeded Blackmun on the high
court in 1994, recalled his predecessor as a man of
``conscientious, humane judicial vision'' whose respect for
personal liberty led him to write the landmark, but highly
controversial, Roe vs. Wade decision in 1973 legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmun's daughter Nancy, speaking at the same memorial
service, said her father's compassion came at a high price. She
described his Minnesota childhood as wrought with family deaths and
financial difficulty, producing lifelong scars that drove him to
work long hours and spend little, though precious, time at home.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and many current and former
justices attended the 2 1/2-hour memorial to Blackmun. The ceremony
at a Methodist church here was held as a winter storm blustered
outside, inspiring some speakers to recall the former justice's
ability to weather adversity.
</P>
<P>
   That adversity often took the form of heated criticism from
opponents of abortion who never forgave Blackmun for writing the
majority opinion in Roe vs. Wade. But Blackmun accepted the
criticism with grace and good humor, Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unpopularity may have displeased him, but it would not shake
him,'' Breyer said. ``He would sometimes read those criticisms
publicly, making it clear that he had considered the criticism, but
still he had to make up his own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer recalled that Blackmun, who served on the court from 1970
to 1994, once received a highly critical letter in which the writer
asked if the justice would resign. In response, Blackmun wrote,
``Dear Sir, No. Sincerely, Harry A. Blackmun.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Blackmun, one of the former justice's three daughters,
praised her father's compassion for the less fortunate. She
recalled that Blackmun had a younger brother who died in early
childhood and a young cousin who died of influenza when Blackmun
was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   These experiences fueled Blackmun's sensitivity and drive, his
daughter said. But Nancy Blackmun also remembered fondly stolen
moments with her father, such as when he would sing to his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cry for him as well as for us,'' she said, expressing her
wish that her father had spent more time at home. ``His were the
most comforting hands to hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanning the crowd, which included high-powered Washington
attorneys, Nancy Blackmun urged the audience to learn from her
father's work habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of parents who work too hard,'' she said. ``Try
not to work too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Garrison Keillor, whose folksy stories about Minnesota
helped him forge a bond with the former justice, led the
congregation in singing the Yale University pep song, ``The
Whiffenpoof Song.'' Nancy Blackmun recalled that her father would
often sing the melody about lost lambs who have gone astray.
</P>
<P>
   William McDaniel Jr., who served as a law clerk to Blackmun,
recalled at the memorial service a justice who believed strongly,
and often without fanfare, that the Constitution protects Americans
who are victims of discrimination or mired in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man vilified for his beliefs, who never returned
vilification,'' McDaniel said. ``He was a man of the law, who
adhered to a fundamental belief that law must serve the people
whose misery and need brought them to the bar of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. William Holmes, a friend and former pastor of
Blackmun's, said the Constitution and the Bible were ``the two most
important documents'' in the former justice's life. ``What he
brought to both was a creative fidelity marked with humility and
always with a twinkle in his eye,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, who was out of town due to an illness in
his family, was the only member of the high court to miss the
memorial service. Byron R. White, the last surviving former
justice, sat with the current justices in the front pew.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
