<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONVERSE-MASTERP-BOS &LR;      03-09 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVERSE-MASTERP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERSE GOES THE HIP-HOP ROUTE TO OVERCOME SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Converse Inc., meet Master P.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball players are not selling $100 sneakers for your
struggling company anymore. How about trying a hip-hop recording
artist, instead?
</P>
<P>
   Athletic shoe sales have been in the tank, industry-wide, since
at least 1997. Converse's sales in 1998 were down 31.5 percent to
$308.5 million, and the fourth quarter was particularly harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, company officials said it was time to try something
really different.
</P>
<P>
   How about a hip-hop guy who plays basketball and has become
among the most successful entrepreneurs in the country _ earning
$56 million last year according to Fortune Magazine. Master P's
name is suddenly everywhere, from the cover of CDs, to trying out
with the Charlotte Hornets, to representing Heisman Trophy winner
Ricky Williams as an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The North Reading, Mass. company now says it has entered into a
marketing partnership with Master P's No Limit Entertainment, that
will eventually provide for co-branded Converse and No Limit
footwear.
</P>
<P>
   For Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports Celebrity Service, a
Chicago company that links advertisers with athletes for
endorsements, Converse's agreement with Master P means that the
shoe industry is trying to shake off its irrelevant marketing
strategies. ``This demonstrates the point to a far greater degree
than Nike dropping a lot of its athlete endorsers over the past
four or five years,'' Williams said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it's no secret that athletes are out as endorsers,''
said Peter Land, executive vice president of Edelman Public
Relations Worldwide, who used to preside over marketing for the
NBA. ``And, by and large there is a lot of cross over between
entertainment and sports. That's why Rupert Murdoch bought the Los
Angeles Dodgers. It's why NASCAR has a rock concert every year _ to
reach a new audience. It's why Ally McBeal shows up at a World
Series game _ it's a promotion for Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Converse or Master P _ his real name is Percy Miller,
and he calls himself simply P _ would discuss the terms of the
agreement Tuesday. But industry sources said it is a
multimillion-dollar deal over two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   Converse's immediate benefit? In-store, point-of-sale displays
with P's image and posing his trademark query from lyrics and
albums, ``Who you with?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we feel there has been a big change in the performance
and basketball shoe line,'' said Jim Solomon, Converse's senior
vice president of Marketing and Sales. ``It's no longer the old
rules of hero basketball player selling his hero shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we've seen a lot of interplay between music and sports,''
Solomon said. ``We really think that we are catching part of a
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Master P's immediate benefit?
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a shoe company that's going to be there,'' P said in
a telephone interview from a hotel in Charlotte, N.C. He said he
will announce later this week that he has joined the Charlotte
Hornets as a player _ adding to the multiple dimensions of a sports
and entertainment renaissance man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like Nike and Mike,'' he said, referring to Michael
Jordan. ``P, and No Limit and Converse are going to ride this
together and go where no one has gone before, because there truly
are no limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Master P, 28, is a self-made millionaire who is building one of
the most powerful entertainment businesses in the country. Emerging
from New Orleans as a rapper, an actor, a screenwriter and a record
and film producer, he eventually became chief executive officer of
his own company, No Limit Entertainment. He has branched out more
recently to begin representing athletes, including the Boston
Celtics' Ron Mercer as well as Williams, who he lured away from
Boston's Woolf Associates.
</P>
<P>
   For Nelson George, the author of Hip Hop America, the Master P
and Converse agreement is part of an increasing mainstreaming of
hip-hop. While Addidas used the recording artists Run DMC in
commercials in the 1980s, it was the clothing manufacturer Tommy
Hilfiger who really picked up of the marketing in the 1990s, before
Calvin Klein and others followed course, George said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's athletes or entertainers, we're talking about
aspirational marketing,'' said Tom George, senior vice-president at
the marketing behemoth, Advantage International. ``It's about
people, especially young people, aspiring to certain fashion
trends. What is cool is part of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that makes Converse's products more aspirational, or
cool, is good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
