<HEADER>
A3980 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FRUGAL-FLA-ORL     03-09 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FRUGAL-FLA-ORLANDO-3TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUGAL TRAVELER: AN ORLANDO WEEKEND OF BLOOMS, BIRDS AND TIFFANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
 (bl)  
 By SARAH FERRELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The snow, sleet and ice that we were hoping to escape delayed
our departure from New York for several hours, but Tom and I
couldn't complain. Unlike many other flights, ours made it to
Florida that Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando had much to recommend it as a quick winter getaway: warm
weather, low air fare, cheap rental cars. I had telephoned Budget
and discovered, to my delight, that the cheapest available rental
vehicle, at a promotional rate of $19.99 a day, was a Ford Ranger
pickup _ spanking new, painted metallic cinnabar, with a locking
cover for the truck bed. In the cab, two comfortable bucket seats
provided an overview of the heavy rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Since we intended to avoid downtown Orlando and all things
Disney, I had negotiated a $71.10 room at a Fairfield Inn, a
Marriott economy chain, in the suburb of Winter Park. Our room, No.
137, was nicely, if generically, furnished; the dressing area and
sink were at the back of the bedroom, while the tub-shower
combination and toilet had a little room of their own. A
fair-sized, lighted swimming pool lay just outside the door.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we checked in, it was dark and we were hungry. The
path of least resistance led directly across the highway to a
Denny's, where we checked the menu for regional specialties and
came up with the chicken-fried steak dinner. Two big pieces of meat
apiece, carrots and real mashed potatoes with peppery country gravy
were $5.09; endlessly refillable iced tea, $1.28. We went back to
our room to count our cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   We awoke to bright sunlight and the song of a cardinal.
Breakfast, which came with the room, offered a choice of teas,
coffee, cereals, toast, fresh fruit and individually wrapped
breakfast breads _ very odd, when the bread in question is a bagel.
And orange juice, which, like tea and coffee, was always available
in the lobby. As we ate, we watched televised scenes of frozen
crowds waving to the cameras in New York's Rockefeller Center and
tried not to giggle.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Winter Park is, well, pretty cute. A street of
mostly two-story stucco buildings containing boutiques and
galleries and cafes parallels the park that gives the street its
name, Park Avenue. The park itself is called Central Park, and is
charmingly green, with old live oaks and tiny squirrels, a
decorative fountain and an Amtrak station _ the railroad came
through in 1882, shortly before the city was founded. The town is
surrounded by lakes, and is anchored by Rollins College, a small,
private liberal-arts college founded in 1885.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the Charles Hosmer Morse Museum of American Art, at
the northern end of the brief commercial district, is usually $3,
but it was temporarily free because the galleries were being
reconstructed to house the chapel that Louis Comfort Tiffany
designed for the 1893 Chicago world's fair. If only a part of the
collection of Tiffany glass and art pottery and jewelry were on
display, we didn't mind. The collection was assembled by Jeannette
McKean and her husband, Hugh McKean, a former fellow at the Tiffany
Foundation who was also a president of Rollins. ( Morse, an early
settler, was her grandfather.)
</P>
<P>
   The glowing favrile glass vases and dragonfly and spider-web
lamps are, of course, glorious, but the windows are a wonder,
especially the three-panel ``Magnolia'' window that was made for
the Tiffany mansion on East 72nd Street in New York. (You can touch
an exhibit of the types of glass that Tiffany developed for his
work, including the semi-opaque ``draped'' glass used to create the
magnolias.) After several passes through the galleries, we were
giddy with color.
</P>
<P>
   We had lunch at a modest vegetarian establishment, the
Powerhouse Cafe, just off the avenue. I had vegetarian grape
leaves, Tom a sandwich of many kinds of veggies in pita bread. We
drank smoothies: Mine was the fairly straightforward berry-cherry
(174 calories); Tom's was 255 calories worth of cosmic crunch _
papaya juice, strawberries, bananas, dates, granola and honey. The
drinks came in pretty tropical pastel shades of coral and lilac.
The bill was less than $15.
</P>
<P>
   We had decided to take the Scenic Boat Tour through three of
Winter Park's lakes, but later in the afternoon, which left us with
some time to kill. None of our guidebooks mentioned Mead Botanical
Garden, but it was on one of our maps, and nearby. It turned out to
be less of an actual garden than a piece of untouched semiswamp,
through which a boardwalk snaked its way. We wandered past sawgrass
and wax myrtle, listening to the palmettos clatter in the wind and
enjoying the boggy smell.
</P>
<P>
   In the hour or so we spent there, we saw only one other person,
a young man seated in silent contemplation at the edge of a stream.
But there was a pileated wookpecker, and monarchs cavorting in the
designated butterfly garden. We felt as if we had discovered a
secret.
</P>
<P>
   The Scenic Boat Tours leave from the foot of Morse Avenue on
Lake Osceola. The tour, which costs $7, takes a little over an
hour, traversing Lakes Osceola, Virginia and Maitland, which are
connected by narrow, shady canals. The boat, which looks like a big
sardine tin on three pontoons, seats 18 on open benches.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
