<SLUG> BC-FASHION-JACKETS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parisians sport ``Michelin Man'' coats
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Suppose the Michelin Man shedded a few pounds and went
Gothic . Then, he'd epitomize the look so prevalantly seen around
Paris, where the style-conscious are currently confronted with a
daily mix of rain, sleet and snow.
</P>
<P>
   On the boulevards and on the Metro, quilted black jackets are
the way to go, it seems. In New York, they're called ``Michelin
Man'' coats. Here, they'd aptly be referred to as
``indispensible.''
</P>
<P>
   They're puffy. They're sporty. And when worn over suits and
smart separates, they look rather chic. Most importantly, they're
practical: the nylon shells repel the cold; the down filling fights
the chill; and the color conceals stains that accompany life in a
city that's fast-paced and congested.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing especially new about quilted down parkas, of
course. Designer, athletic and militaristic versions have been
around for years. Still, there's that certain je ne sais quoi about
the way people dress in Paris that keep this look from appearing
tired.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
