</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PARIS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A trouser taboo serves Ocimar Versolato well
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS, France _ The Brazilian-born designer Ocimar Versolato
made a rather novel proposition with the fall/winter collection he
previewed Tuesday. Imagine: a wardrobe almost devoid of pants. Of
the 71outfits Versolato displayed on his revolving runway, only
three featured pants; and even in those instances, the pants were
partly concealed by jackets and capes.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts, dresses and gowns are the distinctly un-versatile
Versolato's specialty. And for next season's cold-weather wear, he
seems especially focused on luxe fabrics such as mohair, buckskin,
combed wool and cashmere. Unlike most of the New York, Milanese and
Parisian designers whose shows preceded his, Versolato restricted
his color palette to off-white, black, pale pastels and deep blue.
He embellished his otherwise austere designs with high slits,
drawstrings, stencil painting and beading in the shape of long,
thin crosses. Skirts were either hiked to the thigh or dropped to
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   His most noteworthy creations were the knitwear separates that
appeared both plush and sheer. But his decision to outfit models in
knee-high space boots detracted from the collection's air of
elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Few fall/winter shows, seen so far, rival the elegance of the
Hermes collection shown at the flagship store on Monday night.
Somehow, Hermes designer Martine Margiella made sweater-dressing
look remarkably refined.
</P>
<P>
   Reversible cashmere, lambskin and fine tweeds were the main
fabrics employed. The clothes were shown in sedate shades of greys
and browns. Also, in a stark departure from the stick-thin teens
coming down most runways, most of Margiella's models were in the
35-and-older age range.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-outfit collection featured one skirt and five dresses.
These, like all the pants shown, had a loose, loungey silhouette
and closed at the waist with gold-tipped drawstrings. Cushy
turtleneck and cowl neck sweaters were the collection's mainstay.
Buttonless camp shirts tucked into high-waisted pants were a
tantalizing twist. Hermes' outerwear innovation, cashmere stoles
with conveniently-placed pockets, were true delights.
</P>
<P>
   These were styles for the woman who takes life easy. Evidently,
Margiella was in no rush to complete this lovely line for Hermes as
well as his own signature collection. He took his time, and did it
right.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
