<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3984 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FRUGAL-FLA-ORL     03-09 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FRUGAL-FLA-ORLANDO-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: open benches. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We passed the backs of grand houses and boathouses in every
conceivable style, and admired a landscape of cypress knees, live
oaks, philodendrons and Spanish moss. The guide-narrator gave us
bad jokes and good information, particularly about the fauna. We
did not see the alligators or barred owls that occasionally appear,
but we did see cormorants, and herons blue and white and great and
small, and egrets and a whole tree full of anhingas, those strange
denizens of the Everglades also know as snake birds because they
hunt with only their heads and long, serpentish necks sticking out
of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Park, we window-shopped art glass and jewelry and
European toys for a bit, then settled into the Park Avenue Grill
for dinner. At the bar, Tom, the designated driver, had a virgin
mary, and I had a gimlet. In a fit of false economy, since it was
still happy hour, with $1 off every drink, I had two. The bill, for
drinks and dinner in the skylighted dining room, came to less than
$40: Tom had a huge chunk of prime rib and I had a full dozen giant
coconut-fried prawns _ more than I could eat.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the next day, a Saturday, at the Kennedy Space Center,
a little more than an hour's drive from Orlando. Fast-food urban
sprawl gave way to vicious-looking palmetto scrub and then, as we
approached the center itself, to a truly surreal skyline. There,
gleaming against a huge blue sky, were the seven great boosters
that stand like monoliths in the outdoor Rocket Garden display. For
the first of several times, our jaws dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Entrance to the Space Center is free, but you have to take a bus
through restricted areas to get to the really good stuff. We
decided that the best value for us was the Crew Pass ($19), which
would get us on the bus and allow us to see one of three IMAX
movies. Since I had a book of coupons (widely available) that gave
us $2 off each pass, we paid $17 each.
</P>
<P>
   The bus makes three stops: at the LC 39 observation gantry, at
the International Space Station Center and at the Apollo-Saturn V
Center. Since we had only a day, we chose to devote ourselves to
the last. But the center is also a nature preserve, filled with the
usual (by now) egrets and herons. From the bus, we also spotted a
couple of alligators snoozing beside a drainage ditch. Then
suddenly, the driver pointed out a bald eagle seated on a cement
stanchion. Major jaw-drop. A few yards farther on, an enormous
conical eagles' nest hung in a tree. Golly.
</P>
<P>
   You enter the Apollo-Saturn V Center through a gigantic Flash
Gordonish time lock. After some orientation movies, you pass
through a big metal door and into the firing room, where blinking
lights and audio clips recreate the Apollo 8 launching. Anyone old
enough to remember the moon landing is apt to be awe-struck; we
were. In the next room, hanging horizontally, is a Saturn V
booster; we'd always known they were big, but its length still came
as a surprise. The same gallery has a lot of interactive exhibits
and toys and (what had become of great interest to us) a cafeteria.
We took our hot dogs, fries and lemonades ($10.90 total) out onto a
broad terrace, and watched turkey buzzards circle over yet another
lake.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Visitor Complex, we chose the IMAX movie ``The Dream
Is Alive,'' with some truly stomach-churning footage of a landing
taken from the nose of a shuttle. We poked around the gift shop and
the Rocket Garden and had a few snacks until it was suddenly time
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Our route to Winter Park took us along the Beeline Expressway,
the last few miles of which was lined with huge billboards, many in
3-D, for the big-budget attractions that we were ignoring. Traffic
was heavy, and we moved slowly. This stretch, as Tom observed, must
be hell if you have children in the car.
</P>
<P>
   On an earlier stroll along Park Avenue, we had caught a glimpse
of what appeared to be Tiffany glass in La Venezia Cafe. And so it
was, three big panels on loan from the Morse Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Since the cocktail hour had arrived, we settled down at the bar
to admire the shining window that, appropriately, showed grapes on
a trellis, and ordered a couple of what turned out to be expensive
drinks. My gimlet was $6.50, and the designated driver's virgin
mary was a shocking $5.95, more than a whole chicken-fried steak
dinner. But it was probably worth it, since it came with a slab of
carrot, a celery stalk, a large stuffed olive, an onion, lemon and
lime slices and a giant shrimp. ``When we garnish, we  &UR; garnish &LR; ,''
the young woman behind the bar said.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner, served on a patio with louvers opening onto the street,
was of necessity something of an anticlimax, although my lamb with
couscous was fine. (Tom's paella, made with orzo instead of rice,
was less successful.) Still, at $32 for two, not counting drinks,
it wasn't a bad buy. We wished we had left room for dessert, since
the pastry selection looked superb; or perhaps we should have just
stopped in for coffee and cake, as others seemed to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   We had most of a day on Sunday, since we did not have to return
the Ranger until 5 p.m. If I had been disappointed in anything, it
was that we had not seen many flowers, a situation that we decided
to remedy by a visit to the Harry P. Leu Gardens, overlooking Lake
Rowena (Lake Ivanhoe is just up the road) in Orlando proper.
Admission to the gardens is $4, but that day it was free, since it
was the annual Camellia Weekend. Events included a camellia ikebana
workshop and a juried exhibit of camellia blossoms _ several
hundred, singly or in groups, in every possible color and shape.
</P>
<P>
   By official count, the nearly 50 acres of gardens, donated to
the City of Orlando by Harry P. Leu, a local businessman, and his
wife, Mary Jane, contains some 2,200 camellias, planted between
1936 and the early 1960s. Their peak blooming period is from
mid-January to mid-March, and most of them have grown into
substantial trees. Many of them, in full bloom, were veiled in
Spanish moss, as mysterious and magical as anything in the Brothers
Grimm. But camellias are only part, although a large one, of the
gardens. There are, among other things, an orchid house, a rose
garden, a butterfly garden and an enchanting, cool forest of
bamboo, palms and cycads, as well as an overlook on the lake, where
one can spy on herons.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
