<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;     THE BOTTOM LINE: VARIATIONS FROM A THEME PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: on herons. 
  &HT;    We found lunch at the Red Rose Cafe, which had been set up
exclusively for the camellia festival to serve sort of
church-bazaar food at church-bazaar prices. A generous ham-and-brie
sandwich was $3, lemonade $1, a homemade lemon-coconut square $1.
We ate on a terrace under a giant live oak, and watched cloud
reflections on the lake. Refreshed and rejoicing in our good luck,
we took another leisurely tour of the gardens, then headed for the
airport. A few drops of rain were falling.
 &HT;    Back in New York, braving the icy winds, we still felt warm. &HT;     By SARAH FERRELL    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our three-night escape to Florida cost us about $950, including
farewell drinks at the Orlando airport, where the designated driver
allowed himself a martini.
</P>
<P>
   Our New York-Orlando fares on Delta were $208 each. The pickup
rental came to just under $100, with tax and gasoline; tolls were
$3.50.
</P>
<P>
   Three nights at the Fairfield Inn, 951 Wymore Road, Winter Park,
telephone and fax (407) 539-1955, were $236.76, with tax and
breakfast. Other meals, including snacks and drinks, were about
$150.
</P>
<P>
   By fluke, we avoided $14 in admission fees; the Winter Park boat
tour and Crew Pass at the Kennedy Space Center cost a total of $48.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   The Powerhouse Cafe, 111 E. Lyman Ave., Winter Park, (407)
645-3616, is open from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m., Monday through Friday;
from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. on Saturday, and closed Sunday. Healthy
soups ($2 to $2.75), salads ($3.50 to $5) and sandwiches ($2.50 to
$4.50), as well as vegetarian Middle Eastern specialties and
smoothies ($2.75).
</P>
<P>
   Both Park Avenue Grill, 358 Park Avenue North, Winter Park,
(407) 647-4556, and La Venezia Cafe, 142 Park Avenue South, Winter
Park, (407) 647-7557, are open daily for lunch and dinner. At
either, a meal for two with drinks should be about $40 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   Fast food and snacks are available at the Kennedy Space Center.
Specialties include Apollo beer and Space Dots, ``the ice cream of
the future'' ($2.75 for more than you'll probably want to eat). We
had our modest lunch ($10.90) on the terrace of the Moon Rock Cafe
in the Apollo-Saturn V Center. Sightseeing
</P>
<P>
   The Charles Hosmer Morse Museum of American Art, 445 Park Avenue
North, Winter Park, (407) 645-5311. Open 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Tuesday to Saturday, 1 to 4 p.m. Sunday. Admission is $3. The
opening of the expansion that contains the Tiffany chapel is
scheduled for April 17.
</P>
<P>
   To get to Mead Botanical Garden, (407) 599-3334, go south on
Park Avenue and turn right onto Fairbanks Avenue. Then turn left
onto Denning Avenue and left again on Garden. It is open from dawn
to dusk. Free.
</P>
<P>
   The Scenic Boat Tour departs from the end of East Morse
Boulevard, on Lake Osceola, Winter Park (407) 644-4056. Tours leave
on the hour, from 10 to 4, daily except Christmas. The fare is $7.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Space Center, (407) 452-2121, is about an hour's drive
from Orlando. Open daily (except Christmas and during some
launchings) 9 a.m. to dusk. Tours leave the visitor center at short
intervals between 9:30 a.m. and 3 p.m.; you can get off at any of
the three destinations and spend as much time as you like. Several
packages are available, including the $19 Crew Pass, which includes
the Space Center Tour and an IMAX movie, as well as a tour of old
Cape Canaveral, which departs at 3:30 p.m. (the time can vary).
</P>
<P>
   Harry P. Leu Gardens, 1920 N. Forest Ave., Orlando; (407)
246-2620. Open daily, except Christmas, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. (later in
summer). Admission ($4, schoolchildren $1) includes a brief tour of
the Leu House; the last tour is at 3:30 p.m.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
