<SLUG> BC-KROGER-BING0-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seniors in uproar after cancellation of weekly bingo game
 &HT;    By Jerry Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Some party pooper with a grudge in Irving set
in motion a series of events that devastated several dozen senior
citizens when a Longview supermarket halted a goodwill gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday morning bingo game for senior citizens will no longer
be played at the Kroger Food Store on W. Marshall Ave.
</P>
<P>
   The winners never expected to become millionaires. After all,
the prizes were coupons for a loaf of bread here, a cup of cottage
cheese there.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, it was a chance to socialize, an incentive for
an 80-year-old to get out of bed every Monday, one of the senior
citizens said.
</P>
<P>
   But it also is illegal, a felony crime, no less, because Kroger
does not have a license to run a bingo game. And that is where the
party pooper in Irving comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Atkins of Austin, director of the charitable bingo
division of the Texas Lottery Commission, said the agency received
a complaint that a Kroger store in Irving was running an illegal
bingo game.
</P>
<P>
   He said two or three weeks ago, a lottery investigator notified
the Irving store manager it is illegal to operate a bingo game
without a license.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed, the Irving bingo game stopped and Atkins
said he thought that was the end of it. That is, until he got a
call from the Longview News-Journal with questions about why the
Lottery Commission rained on the parade of senior citizens here.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior citizens called the newspaper to complain that
the Lottery Commission had halted the bingo game at the Kroger in
Longview. They were dismayed that their once-a-week excursion to
the bingo tables in the deli section were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``As near as I can tell, we haven't said anything to the store
in Longview,'' Atkins said. ``I think it is Kroger's that sent out
this notification to all their stores.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Bingo Enabling Act of Texas, only nonprofit,
charitable organizations are authorized to have a license to
conduct bingo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The act is strict and says it is irrelevant whether the winner
receives a prize or pays to participate, Atkins said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the complaints about unauthorized bingo games are rare.
The last one the commission received was several years ago about a
chain discount store running a similar game for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like our goal in life is to go out and prevent these
folks from having any fun. But the Bingo Enabling Act is very
strict in its definition of what bingo is and how it is
conducted,'' Atkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The senior citizens who complained to the Longview News-Journal
did not want to be quoted, fearful that zealots in the Lottery
Commission would shut down every bingo game in area nursing homes
if they were identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an exception for games that are conducted in senior
citizens facilities, nursing homes and hospitals. Organizations
like that can apply to us for an exemption. They can be exempted
from licensure if the games are conducted there at the facility for
the enjoyment of the patients,'' Atkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Longview Kroger Manager Terisa Smith said the senior citizens
would gather each Monday morning in the deli section for breakfast.
After eating, they would play cards or dominoes until the one-hour
bingo game started at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been doing it for years, and we had no idea that we
were doing something illegal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the seniors are welcome to continue their Monday
morning routine, minus the bingo game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with them coming up here at all, if
they want to get together, drink coffee and socialize. They can
still do that. I just can't have them doing the bingo anymore and
giving away the prizes that they got,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to abide by the law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Graham writes for the Longview News-Journal, Longview,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
