<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LEWIS-COX     03-09 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Lewis, it's greatness or obscurity
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former heavyweight champion was sitting adjacent to
a reigning one ringside at a recent boxing card when an autograph
seeker approached. Larry Holmes obliged the fan's request for his
signature, then motioned to the large man next to him and asked the
youth, ``Don't you want his, too?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that?'' the boy responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never heard of him,'' said the boy, who turned and walked
away.
</P>
<P>
   That a boxer can maintain such anonymity despite winning an
Olympic gold medal as an amateur, twice holding a title belt as a
pro and banking several million dollars is remarkable _ which is
not to suggest it's a good thing. For the better part of the 1990s,
Lennox Lewis has been boxing's biggest afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as his own trainer, Emanuel Steward, put it, ``If Lennox
loses this fight, he'll just be another guy from England with
dreadlocks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight'' is Saturday's heavyweight title unification
against Evander Holyfield, who embraces something with a far
greater shelf life than his WBA and IBF title belts: a significant
place in history. Ring Magazine recently voted Holyfield boxing's
third greatest heavyweight champion behind Muhammad Ali and Joe
Louis. Even those who might debate Holyfield's place in the
all-time rankings won't question his place as the best in this era,
having beaten every other major contender or champion: Mike Tyson,
Riddick Bowe, Michael Moorer, George Foreman, Ray Mercer, Holmes
and, OK, James ``Buster'' Douglas. Of those, Lewis has fought only
Mercer, and won a decision that many felt judges tiltled in the
wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   Even Lewis' two reigns as WBC champion are tainted. In 1993, he
won a decision over Tony Tucker for the vacant title. Bowe had just
beaten Holyfield for the unified crown but renounced the WBC
portion rather than make a mandatory defense against Lewis. The
following year, Lewis lost his ``paper'' title to a glorified club
fighter, Oliver McCall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Lewis went to court to secure a title shot against
Tyson, but Tyson chose instead to fight Holyfield. Lewis got the
belt, then won his first two defenses when: 1) McCall suffered a
nervous breakdown in the ring and; 2) Henry Akinwande was
disqualified for excessive holding.
</P>
<P>
   Fights against all of the marquee names in the 1990s have
fizzled, either because of Lewis or his would-be opponents,
depending on your point of view and source of income. The only
certainty is Lewis' place among heavyweights will cease being a
mystery Saturday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my time,'' said Lewis, who was born in London, but
splits his residence between Canada and the U.S. ``There's a reason
for everything and the reasons that I wasn't able to put my stamp
on things before, whether it was politics or whatever, now it has
finally come time to make my mark and create history. This will be
a defining fight for Lennox Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis created high expectations after beating Bowe for the gold
medal in the 1988 Olympics. But a number of his performances in the
pros have been lackluster, and while he possesses a solid right
hand, there have been few moments when he has displayed any boxing
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never lived up to what I thought he should be,'' said Don
Turner, Holyfield's trainer. ``I just don't believe he's obsessed
about fighting like the real fighters. He is a champion of the
world but to me, he just never really developed.''
</P>
<P>
   Most irritating to Lewis is the suggestion that he is overly
robotic in the ring and rarely fights with any emotion _ sort of
the anti-Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard for a long time, especially with the American
media, that Lennox Lewis has no heart,'' Lewis said. ``Where does
that come from? When Evander Holyfield gets hit and he comes back,
he shows heart. Maybe since I don't get hit and don't come back,
that's why they say that. Evander Holyfield doesn't have a monopoly
on hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has talked negatively more about Lewis than any of his
previous foes, in part because Lewis claimed Holyfield had been
ducking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fights are not classic,'' Holyfield said.. ``There's no
skills. He just goes in there swinging his arms. He's insecure
because he doesn't think he can get somebody out with his skills
and conditioning. This is the man who calls somebody else
chicken.'' Lewis' purse ($8 million) pales in comparison to
Holyfield's ($20 million) and he is a slight underdog in Las Vegas,
despite being younger, taller and stronger with a 34-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm the underdog,'' Lewis said. ``I like the
atmosphere of having something to fight for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
