u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALEXANDER-POLITICS-75     03-09 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-POLITICS-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMAR ALEXANDER, RUNNING SINCE '96, MAKES IT OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ALEXANDER-POLITICS-BIO) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Repeatedly invoking a cheery mantra that he
would ``bring out the best in America,'' Lamar Alexander formally
declared his candidacy for the Republican presidential nomination
on Tuesday by recalling his achievements as governor of Tennessee
and vowing to restore respect for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's dogged quest for the White House never ceased after
he pulled out in 1996, a campaign in which he is remembered for
casting himself as a down-home Washington outsider by wearing a
red-and-black plaid shirt. In his announcement speech four years
ago, he tapped out the bluegrass standard, ``Rocky Top,'' on an
electronic keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Alexander had no gimmicks. He wore a dignified dark
suit, and picked the state Capitol as the venue for reintroducing
himself as a businesslike, accomplished leader who brought new jobs
to this state, improved roads and public education.
</P>
<P>
   He ridiculed the scandals of President Clinton directly, saying
``If we are going to bring out the best in America, we need a
president who talks straight and who will listen &UR; . &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``A new American century will require a moral
foundation laid by a president who respects the office and respects
those who put him in the office, a president who understands what
makes this nation great and who understands what will keep it that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   His underlying message was more subtle: Republicans should not
rush this early into backing either of the two most popular
contenders, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas or Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time the race is wide open,'' said Alexander, who is 58.
``There is no one whose `turn' it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his bearing is mild-mannered, Alexander has not shied
away in recent weeks from lambasting Bush's ``compassionate
conservative'' slogan as ``weasel words.'' He left no doubt that he
is primed for oratorical combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a tea party on the English countryside,'' he said
in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, he never mentioned his rivals' names. Instead he
cited the last Republican hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1980, Ronald Reagan asked the American people, `Are you
better off today than you were four years ago?' And most people
said `no,' '' he said. ``My question today is different. It is
about the future and it is this: Will our country be better four
years from now than it is today?''
</P>
<P>
   His fear, Alexander said, was that ``if we continue along the
path of the wizard Clinton and his faithful assistant Gore are
taking us, the answer won't be yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who after serving as governor and president of the
University of Tennessee, was Education Secretary under President
Bush, said his three fundamental goals as president would be to
improve public education, to raise family incomes by cutting taxes
and securing the Social Security system, and to strengthen the
military.
</P>
<P>
   While some Republicans dismiss Alexander's candidacy, noting
that his ideas did not catch on the last time, he contended in the
interview that he is in a stronger position now because he
persevered though the process before _ and has painstakingly
assembled perhaps the most potent organizations in the pivotal
early states of New Hampshire and Iowa. (He has spent 121 days in
Iowa since 1996.) He also argues that he can amass more money than
most of the competitors, in part because, as in 1996, he has signed
up one of the most successful fund-raisers in the party, Ted Welch.
</P>
<P>
   Selling himself as perhaps not flashy but certainly more tested
than his rivals, Alexander said he was ``someone who knows from the
first day that he or she is in office exactly what they will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his sturdy campaign structure, Alexander has been
frustrated that his candidacy has been completely eclipsed by Bush
and, to a lesser extent, Ms. Dole. Their prospective bids have
stirred far more anticipation _ and registered far higher in the
polls. And Alexander's capacity to raise as much money as he did
last time is in doubt because Bush has already enlisted several of
his most prodigious fund-raising backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shouldn't laugh too much because if Bush fails to live
up to his Mount Everest high expectations, Lamar will have a shot
to upset him,'' said Mike Murphy, who was one of Alexander's top
strategists in 1996 but who has not joined any campaign this year.
``He's going to take a pounding for the next few months. But he's
built to do that. And the real game is at the end of the year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Struggling to make his case, Alexander relies on scenarios of
what-might-have-happened in 1996: that he finished a respectable
third place in Iowa and New Hampshire, almost nipping ahead of Bob
Dole in the New Hampshire primary. Alexander emerged, briefly, as
the most credible alternative to Dole, but he was unable to survive
a media storm financed by the Dole campaign that condemned his
personal financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander explained in an interview that he was well-positioned
to emerge if Bush faltered. ``The next president will be me or Bush
or Vice President Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander showed a reporter polling figures not from the current
campaign _ where his support is stuck in the single digits _ but
from March of 1996, which showed that his performance in New
Hampshire catapulted him to third place in a poll in California.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has dwarfed him in endorsements from governors,
Alexander trumpeted the two governors who are backing him and who
introduced him Tuesday: Don Sundquist of Tennessee and Mike
Huckabee of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he gave top billing Tuesday to his biggest catch, former
Gov. Terry Branstad of Iowa, an influential figure in the state
that traditionally holds the first caucuses. Branstad was not
bashful about contrasting Alexander to his better-known rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Iowans are the first to have the opportunity to make
their choice known for president, I believe it will not be the
person with the most money _ it will not be the person with the
most famous name,'' Branstad said. ``But it will be someone like
us: straight talking, hard-working, somebody that puts quality
education at the top of the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   While Alexander has abandoned his call for abolishing the
Department of Education _ an applause line in his announcement four
years ago _ he emphasized that his chief concerns were ``parents
raising children'' and freeing teachers and principals who are
``suffocating under union rules, court orders and government
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his competitors, Alexander is not known as a
hard-edged conservative. Instead, he tries to blend his
conservative ideas in an agreeable manner. For example, he said
that when he was governor, he appointed the first black justice to
the state Supreme Court. But as Education Secretary, he said, he
opposed scholarships based solely on race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government's helping hand _ affirmative action _ is for
everyone,'' he said. ``Always based on need, never based on race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
