<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-THEATER-ART-3TA     03-09 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-THEATER-ART-3TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE SCREEN IS KING, THE STAGE IS QUEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Near the end of ``All About Eve,'' Hollywood's
enduring, self-loathing take on the vanities of Broadway, the
scheming anti-heroine accepts an award for her debut performance in
New York's biggest new hit, casts her doe eyes downward and starts
the inexorable process of selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although ... I am going to Hollywood next week to make a
film,'' Anne Baxter breathlessly intones, ``do not think for a
moment that I'm leaving you. How could I? My heart is here, in the
theater, and 3,000 miles are too far away to be from one's heart.
I'll be back to claim it _ and soon. That is, if you
(italics)want(end italics) me back.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Eve Harrington wouldn't have to worry too much about
her heart _ or her air fare. She could always, as her rival Margo
Channing might say, put a starring role in an L.A. play where her
heart ought to be. From the Mexican border to the Mark Taper Forum
here, theater is alive _ and well enough _ in Southern California,
and the stars of film and television are dabbling in it in ever
greater numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This season alone, familiar faces as diverse as Carol Burnett,
Annette Bening, Donald Sutherland, Al Pacino and Molly Ringwald
have appeared, or are scheduled to do so, on Los Angeles stages, in
new works, revivals of classics, or reworkings of recent New York
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Teri Hatcher has traded her ``Lois and Clark'' notepad on
television for Sally Bowles' garters in the opening of the national
tour of ``Cabaret,'' and Jenna Elfman, the hot star of the series
``Dharma and Greg,'' spends her Saturdays and Sundays in a tiny
theater with Miguel Ferrer, performing in half of ``Visions and
Lovers: Variations on a Theme,'' two one-act musings on
relationships by Milton Katselas, an acting teacher.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, a region that has long been a net exporter of
social trends and pop culture has increasingly added serious
theater to the list of products it ships East. South Coast
Repertory in neighboring Orange County, for example, developed
``Wit'' by Margaret Edson, ``Three Days of Rain'' by Richard
Greenberg and ``Collected Stories'' by Donald Margulies, all plays
that have been seen in New York over the last two seasons, while at
the Taper, the Stephen Sondheim revue ``Putting It Together'' was
put together again last fall in a new form with Ms. Burnett and is
being sent back to Manhattan next season with better reviews than
it got Off Broadway in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are special challenges for theater here. The
biggest may simply be the competition for attention in a place
where it is neither a major tourist attraction nor an important
commercial presence, where auditoriums are spread around a
sprawling region with chronic traffic problems and little adjacent
after-show night life, where advertising is even more expensive
than in New York, where no local television station has a full-time
theater critic, and where theater coverage in the Sunday Calendar
section of The Los Angeles Times begins on page 30 or 40, miles
behind the movie ads and other listings.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of the most serious theater in Southern California
is not in Los Angeles at all, but 45 minutes by car at South Coast
Rep in Costa Mesa, or three hours away at the La Jolla Playhouse
and the Old Globe Theater in San Diego, both of which in recent
years have sent a batch of offerings to Broadway, from revivals of
``Damn Yankees'' and ``How to Succeed in Business Without Really
Trying'' to ``Tommy'' by the Who.
</P>
<P>
   A short hop over the Hollywood Hills is the Pasadena Playhouse,
which in its glory days helped train actors like William Holden and
Gene Hackman. The theater reopened more than a decade ago after
being dark for 20 years and now presents new works and revivals.
</P>
<P>
   If geography and movie mania are the biggest obstacles,
producers here say the captive talent pool of the film industry is
the city's single greatest asset in generating theatrical vehicles.
These range from big commercial productions to nonprofit mountings
of experimental, ethnic and gay plays, to a student version of
``Once Upon a Mattress'' at the University of California at Los
Angeles, where an alumna, Ms. Burnett, made her directorial debut
last month in a revival of the musical that made her famous 40
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a movie town, clearly,'' said Gilbert Cates, the
veteran director and stage and film producer. Cates, whose credits
range from the play and film of Robert Anderson's ``I Never Sang
for My Father'' to the annual Academy Awards telecast, and who is
now in his third season as producing director of the Geffen
Playhouse, is presenting Ms. Bening there in ``Hedda Gabler''
(previews begin Sunday night, with an opening scheduled for March
24).
</P>
<P>
   ``But the truth is,'' he said, ``this city is filled with tens
of thousands of actors, writers and directors, and what are they
going to do when they're not making movies? Theater is still the
place where you can do a show.'' Indeed, Cates will be directing
Linda Lavin and Samantha Mathis at the Geffen in ``Collected
Stories'' in May, when Margulies' play completes its circle and
returns to California.
</P>
<P>
   All around town, stages are filled with aspiring stars eager for
exposure and the chance to practice, and established ones happy to
return to their roots and stretch new muscles _ and not just in
legitimate houses. The Groundlings, the comedy troupe that helped
promote performers like Mike Myers, Phil Hartman and Jon Lovitz, is
still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   And most every Sunday night, Jay Leno returns to his origins in
stand-up while testing ``Tonight Show'' monologues at the Comedy
and Magic Club in Hermosa Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Actors from Tim Robbins to Noah Wyle, the boyish heartthrob of
``E.R.,'' have been instrumental in starting or supporting
respected small theater companies in Hollywood. At the same time,
they take advantage of agreements with Actors Equity that allow
union performers to experiment in lower-paying work with nonunion
actors in theaters with 99 seats or less.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, as a UCLA student, Robbins helped found the Actors'
Gang, a company that performs in a 99-seat theater and on whose
board Ms. Bening sits. Though he now lives on the other coast,
Robbins still supports the troupe and is underwriting its current
production of ``Broadway,'' the 1926 Philip Dunning-George Abbott
melodrama set in speak-easy New York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
