<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIBBS' KNEE IFFY FOR NIT OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Pepperdine men's basketball team stumbled to
the finish line in the regular season. Fortunately for the Waves,
they have another race to run in the National Invitation
Tournament. Will they be running it on one leg?
</P>
<P>
   When Pepperdine warms up for tonight's first-round NIT game at
Boulder, Colo., the host coaches will be watching Waves sophomore
forward Kelvin Gibbs, who has an infected knee.
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff is scheduled for 6 p.m. at Coors Events Center.
</P>
<P>
   If Gibbs can overcome the injury, the Waves have a chance. If he
can't play, Pepperdine is in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado (17-14) finished the regular season on a roll, winning
six of its past eight. The Buffaloes, ranked No.111 in the RPI,
were first in the Big 12 Conference in scoring and fourth in
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (19-12) lost five of its final eight games and was
sixth in scoring and rebounding in a weaker conference, the West
Coast. Still, the Waves have a higher RPI ranking than CU _ 105.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs is the Waves' second-leading scorer and top rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   The team left for Boulder on Tuesday morning. On Monday, Waves
coach Lorenzo Romar said he was doubtful Gibbs could play. But
Jennifer Chelton, Pepperdine's head athletic trainer, said on
Monday Gibbs would be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Romar, who has guided Pepperdine to six, 17 and 19 wins in three
years, will see a familiar face on the Colorado bench. Sophomore
forward Jamahl Mosley was recruited by Romar out of high school in
San Diego. Mosley is CU's fifth-leading scorer (9.6 ppg) and
leading rebounder (6.5).
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted (Mosley),'' Romar said. ``Early on we were in (the
running).''
</P>
<P>
   When Romar got the call that the Waves were invited to the NIT,
he said he was ``very, very excited.'' Mark Trakh, the Pepperdine
women's coach, wasn't as enthusiastic when he found out the Waves
were in the women's NIT.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, who play at New Mexico (22-6) on Friday, were
co-champions of the WCC in the regular season and 21-8. They lost
in the WCC Tournament final to St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little disappointed,'' Trakh said.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, which shared the regular-season title with
Pepperdine, was given an at-large bid for the women's tournament
despite losing in the semifinals of the WCC Tournament. Trakh said
he wasn't bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally see them taking Santa Clara over us,'' Trakh said.
``They beat Stanford and lost a close game to Colorado State.
You've got to beat top-25, top-50 teams to get in. We only played
one top-25 team (UCLA) and got blown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's RPI rating is 57th. New Mexico is No. 58.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
