<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3998 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-THEATER-ART-2ND     03-09 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: New York.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, as a 19-year-old upstart, Wyle wandered into
the Blank Theater Company to audition for David Mamet's ``Sexual
Perversity in Chicago,'' landed the part of a 29-year-old and is
now the artistic producer and chief fund-raiser for the company,
which was founded nine years ago by Daniel Henning, a New York
transplant. Its latest production is ``Starr Struck: A Musical
Investigation'' into the world of the special Whitewater
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   All this cross-pollination requires special accommodations. For
example, Ms. Elfman and Ferrer split their roles with other actors
and only appear on weekends in their current play, to allow for
their taping schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Film and television work pays the bills for most actors here,
but with the profusion of cable networks and television movies, the
long summer breaks that used to prevail in network television,
leaving stars free for the stage, are getting shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed is that hiatus has virtually totally
disappeared,'' said Gordon Davidson, the artistic director and
producer of the Taper since its founding 32 years ago. The grand
not-so-old man of Los Angeles theater, he first staged plays like
``The Trial of the Catonsville Nine'' by Daniel Berrigan.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most recent, the first installment of ``The Cider
House Rules,'' a two-part epic version of the John Irving novel
performed at the Taper last spring, opens May 6 at the Atlantic
Theater Company in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, Davidson has also run the Ahmanson Theater,
the other playhouse at the Music Center of Los Angeles, which books
tours, like Christopher Plummer in ``Barrymore,'' musicals and
special productions, like the concert version of Sondheim's
``Sweeney Todd'' this weekend by the local nonprofit company
Reprise: Broadway's Best in Concert. It celebrates the show's 20th
anniversary and stars Kelsey Grammer and Christine Baranski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, I heard a comment that I thought I'd never
hear again, but sure enough, I heard it recently,'' Davidson
recalled. ``An agent said, `What if my client gets a job?' I said,
`What do you think I'm offering?'''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Marshall, the producer-director-actor who made his fortune
with situation comedies like ``Happy Days'' and ``The Odd Couple,''
used some of that fortune to open the 99-seat Falcon Theater in
Burbank in late 1997, and it has since presented ``Death of a
Salesman'' starring his old friend Jack Klugman, as well as
children's theater and readings of new works by the likes of Ms.
Bening.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, it will join forces for the second year with the
Blank Theater Company to sponsor a young playwrights festival in
which authors ages 19 and under from around the country are invited
to submit new works, with the winners assigned established
playwrights as mentors.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall, who says he has had a ``theater addiction'' since
his childhood in the Bronx, knows his adopted hometown well enough
to insist on special architectural features to avoid annoying
disruptions by agents and studio executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of big shots don't come for the whole play,'' he said
dryly. ``They come to see their client and leave. So in the
lighting booth, we put about 10 chairs for people to use if they
have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many producers say that theater here is better, more lively and
more diverse than popular perception might suggest, and most
grumble to varying degrees about lack of news media coverage and
unevenness of critical scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably as good a theater scene as anywhere outside New
York, except possibly Chicago,'' said Jack Viertel, a former
theater critic for the now-defunct Los Angeles Herald-Examiner and
former dramaturge at the Taper, who is now creative director for
the Jujamcyn theater organization in New York. ``But I don't think
it commands the kinds of newsworthiness in the city that the
theater does in Chicago, which doesn't have another entertainment
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for an audience is constant, say producers, with
nonprofit theaters like the Taper and the Geffen depending heavily
on subscription ticket buyers who are disproportionately older,
white, affluent residents of Westside neighborhoods from Beverly
Hills to Brentwood. Or, as Viertel put it, ``groups of four who get
together four times a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for large, commercial tours of Broadway musicals, marketing
shows in Los Angeles can be trickier than in Boston or Chicago.
``It's a really hard sell,'' said one Broadway publicist, speaking
on condition of anonymity. ``I put it down partly to a movie
mentality; there, it's all about the opening weekend, and the
excitement dies down pretty quickly. A lot of shows just can't get
the stamina. Even something like `Sunset Boulevard' was very hot
for a time when Glenn Close was in it, but none of the big
commercial properties has proven to be really long running there.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater L.A., the local industry trade group and service
organization, has 159 members that range from large for-profit
chain theaters like the Shubert in Century City to small
nonprofits. Theater L.A. claims there are more live theater
productions in Los Angeles than in any other city in the world, and
estimates there were 200 world premieres here last season.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not enough to keep the group's half-price ticket
sales office _ which operates from a branch of Jerry's Famous Deli
in West Hollywood _ open seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that the bulk of business was Thursday to Sunday,''
said the group's executive director, Alisa Fishbach, who noted that
estimates of theater attendance are purely anecdotal because no
marketing study has been done in about a decade. The group is
currently trying to raise money to do another.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ms. Fishbach added: ``Personally, I think things are
changing. I've been in the industry here for 15 years, and the
knocks aren't so prevalent anymore. We're getting a little bit more
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   For many actors, of course, the theater remains the ultimate
test of their abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Southern California has the largest talent
pool of actors anywhere in the world, and while they have not
primarily come here to do theater, our experience is that the very
best of them have come from the theater,'' said David Emmes,
co-founder and producing artistic director of South Coast Rep. Now
in its 35th season, the organization has a $7.5 million annual
budget, 65 full-time employees and plans to add a new 300-seat
theater designed by Cesar Pelli.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
