<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-THEATER-ART-3RD     03-09 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-THEATER-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: Cesar Pelli.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Theater is the actor's art, whereas film is obviously the
director's, so I think that the really good actor longs to get back
on the stage,'' Emmes added. ``While they would be reluctant to go
out of town, to some other part of the country, they can work at
the Taper or South Coast Rep, sleep in their own beds and keep up
some sense of family life, if they have one, and still keep their
contact with their primary purpose, namely Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ferrer, the eldest son of the stage and film actor Jose
Ferrer and the singer Rosemary Clooney, ``Visions and Lovers'' was
his first return to the stage after a decade of work in films and
television, most recently on the NBC sitcom ``Lateline,'' in which
he plays the darkly comic producer of a ``Nightline''-style news
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of sounding melodramatic or outright silly, it's
really kind of sparked a genuine artistic reawakening for me,''
said Ferrer, who has tended in film work to be typecast as a bit of
a heavy and leaped at the offer to play a passionate writer for his
old acting teacher, Katselas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honest to God, I'm a different guy because of this play,''
Ferrer said. ``It's the hardest work I've ever done, and the least
money, but as a result of working on this, I started listening to
music in the car again instead of talk radio, and waking up my wife
in the middle of the night to read her a passage from Walt
Whitman.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, as on Broadway, nothing sells a show like a
star, and there is pressure to have a marquee name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, there's a flurry of stars working on Broadway and
here,'' Davidson said. ``It used to be thought, in the inner circle
of agentry, that it meant the client wasn't doing so well, but I
think that stigma is not the case now.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson quoted a facetious rule of thumb: audiences at the
750-seat Taper ask ``What's playing?'' while those at the
2,000-seat Ahmanson want to know ``Who's in it?'' But he noted that
early on, the Taper presented stars like Jack Lemmon, and Walter
Matthau and Maureen Stapleton in ``Juno and the Paycock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has never hurt to have a star,'' Davidson said. ``But there
are plays that are ensemble plays and sometimes you just want an
ensemble.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, in fact, you just want a play. Two of the stars who
will appear at the Taper later this year _ Sutherland, in the
American premiere of ``Enigma Variations'' by the French playwright
Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt, in May and June, and Pacino, directing and
acting in his Los Angeles stage debut in Eugene O'Neill's
``Hughie,'' in June and July _ are replacements for works that did
not pan out.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland will slip into a slot vacated by the writer, director
and performance artist Anna Deavere Smith, whose new play, ``House
Arrest,'' about the American Presidency and the press, originally
seen in Washington in 1997, will now be presented as a
work-in-progress for a shorter run. Pacino, who will be performing
with Paul Benedict, as he did in his production of ``Hughie'' at
Circle in the Square in New York in 1996, will be filling a vacancy
left when Athol Fugard recently decided to stop acting.
</P>
<P>
   The South African playwright had appeared in his memory play
``The Captain's Tiger'' in New York, but did not want to continue
in the role. Davidson decided not to present the play without him.
</P>
<P>
   Most producers here agree that the biggest challenge for local
theaters is to make the leap from the 99-seat union-waiver house to
a mid-size operation that pays a living wage. One that recently did
so is East-West Players in the Asian neighborhood known as Little
Tokyo. The company specializes in Asian-American themes and has
staged a well-received revival of Sondheim's musical ``Pacific
Overtures.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Davidson, who runs the biggest, most established theater
operation in town, is in a constant quest for grants, donors and
new ways to keep the Taper _ with an annual budget of $12.4 million
_ alive. ``It's complex, at times frustrating,'' he said. ``I'm not
one to put down the complications. But it's exciting to be able to
do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
