</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-SEX-VOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPISCOPAL BISHOPS TO AVOID SEXUALITY ISSUES AT 2000 CONVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Colo., Calif.) 
 
By RICHARD VARA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAVASOTA, Texas _ The Episcopal Church's national House of
Bishops concluded a six-day retreat Tuesday agreeing to avoid votes
on controversial gay rights issues such as the blessing of same-sex
unions during the denomination's convention in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More than 140 bishops, including Presiding Bishop Frank
Griswold, attended the retreat at Camp Allen, the Episcopal Diocese
of Texas' retreat and conference center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we did not vote on it here, the sense was that we
will not vote up or down on the hot-button sexuality issues at the
General Convention in 2000,'' said Diocese of Texas Bishop Claude
Payne, who hosted the retreat. It was the first time the House of
Bishops had met in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not minimizing the issues,'' he said. ``But there's a new
framework that is: What are we called to do when we identify
Episcopalian?'' Payne has been emphasizing outreach and missions as
the church's primary focus.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions within the 2.2 million-member denomination are building
as the national church's triennial meeting draws near. For nearly
25 years, the denomination has been bitterly divided between
liberals who support the ordination of openly gay candidates for
the priesthood and church blessings for gay unions, and
traditionalists who oppose the actions.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop William Wantland, a leader of American traditionalists,
was guardedly optimistic that a denominational split could be
avoided next year when about 1,500 American Episcopal leaders
gather in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general consensus was that we needed very thorough
discussions on both sides of the divisive issues, but that we are
not at a point where we can resolve them one way or the other,''
Wantland said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he noted that another meeting of bishops would take
place before the general convention. He said he hopes the bishops'
new sense of unity holds during the September meeting in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Catherine Roskam of New York agreed there was a growing
unity among the church leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The retreat) does not wash away our differences in a
superficial way,'' Roskam said, adding that the bishops were openly
discussing their differences on the issues. ``We are re-examining
everything including the way we do business with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Chilton Knudsen of Maine said many of her own diocesan
members want a decisive vote at Denver. She said she answers them
that the church's leaders are not ready to make any decisions on
these controversial issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are discovering that up-and-down votes have such dreadful
and dire consequences and that they don't resolve the question they
are purporting to resolve,'' Knudsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned that to continue to pick at it just spreads the
deep pain. The sores are our differences, particularly our
differences about human sexuality. We're leaving it alone for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is so divisive that some traditionalists last month
petitioned the world's Anglican bishops for ``protection of
orthodox Anglicans in the United States until the Episcopal Church
of the United States of America is reformed or replaced as a
province of the (Anglican) Communion.'' They want a separate
province composed of conservative U.S. bishops, clergy and parishes
headed by a traditionalist presiding bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists argue that U.S. bishops are generally ignoring
the resolution overwhelmingly approved by the world's Anglican
bishops during the once-a-decade Lambeth Conference held in England
last year. It stated that homosexual activity was incompatible with
scripture and noncelibate homosexuals should not be ordained.
</P>
<P>
   Several international Anglican archbishops wrote Griswold on
Feb. 26 expressing disappointment at American criticism of the
Lambeth resolution. Sixty-five U.S. bishops signed a pastoral
letter apologizing for the conference's ``sense of rejection''
toward gays and lesbians immediately after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, some bishops and dioceses have passed resolutions
rejecting the Lambeth stand. Griswold, who ordained gay candidates
to the priesthood when he was bishop of Chicago, abstained during
the Lambeth vote.
</P>
<P>
   The primates' letter urged him to support the Lambeth stand.
</P>
<P>
   Griswold said Tuesday he would reply to the letter ``in the
fullness of time.'' He said he was talking with other church
leaders and members for an appropriate reply.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
