A4003 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-AUTO-INSPECT-BOS &LR;      03-09 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTO-INSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARAGES SAY HIGHER EMISSIONS INSPECTION PAYMENTS NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Days before the formal unveiling of a new system for
detecting pollution in motor vehicle exhaust, Gov. Paul Cellucci
faces a growing revolt from the service station owners that must
give the emissions tests, with some threatening to boycott the
program if they don't get more money.
</P>
<P>
   The federally mandated tests, scheduled to begin by October,
would require about one in four Massachusetts vehicles each year to
undergo high-tech pollution screening in addition to their annual
safety inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But service station owners are balking at Cellucci's pledge to
keep the combined price of safety and emissions tests under $25 per
vehicle. Station owner advocates, who are scheduled to meet with
top administration officials Thurdsay, say the fee needs to be $35
to $45 to cover the added costs of the new test.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Commonwealth forces upon us a ridiculously low fee,
stations won't sign up in sufficient numbers,'' warned Roger
Montbleau of the New England Service Station and Automotive Repair
Association, in a letter to station owners. ``Irate motorists will
find themselves driving miles from their homes, and waiting in long
lines, to get their vehicles inspected.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the stations would make more money under
the new system, but not at drivers' expense. One source said that
millions of dollars diverted from fees collected in the current
inspection program to other state initiatives might be returned to
station owners under the new program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an understanding that many of these are small
businesses and they need some help. We get it,'' said John Rodman,
assistant secretary of environmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The battle with service stations comes just as the state ends a
four year row with the US Environmental Protection Agency over how
to get the most-polluting cars off the road. The EPA has repeatedly
threatened to punish the state if officials didn't improve the
antiquated emissions testing system.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials preferred to fight with the federal
government rather than risk an inspection program that would anger
the public. Fearing long lines and high prices, Gov. William Weld
never implemented a 1996 state law that would have set up 60
centralized centers to inspect all vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan to be unveiled March 19, the 2,100 inspection
stations could continue offering inspections. Vehicles would
require a safety inspection annually, and most would need a 15 to
20 minute emissions test every other year.
</P>
<P>
   However, about 40 percent of the state's 4.1 million motor
vehicles would not have to take the emissions test, either because
they are new, very old, or from a vehicle family known for durable
emissions controls. Over time, as newer, cleaner cars come onto the
roads, up to 60 percent of vehicles could be excused from emissions
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Tuesday that they were mostly satisfied
with the modified test program, noting it would help Massachusetts
reduce the 20-plus days each summer when the air contains unhealthy
levels of ozone, the main ingredient in smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, the Commonwealth's program is a sound program
that provides substantial air quality benefits for the citizens of
Massachusetts,'' said John DeVillars, EPA regional administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the service stations are the ones who are unhappy. They
note that the current $15 fee for the combined emissions and safety
checks hasn't been raised since 1988 and that other states that
have added high-tech emissions testing, such as Connecticut, hiked
the fee to $40 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all kinds of documentation of why we need more
money,'' said Tom Porter of Porter's Firestone in Arlington, part
of the service station delegation meeting with Cellucci's deputy
chief of staff and Administration and Finance officials Thursday.
If the inspection fee isn't raised to at least $35, ``some guys are
going to say `I'm not going to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they hope to satisfy the service stations,
but, ultimately, they need only about 1,200 of the 2,100 current
inspection stations for the new program to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
