<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-09 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ICKING UP THE PEN AND THE BRUSH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Curator  &UR; Baird Jones &LR; ' ``Writerly Art'' show at the Trenton City
Art Museum in Trenton, N.J., includes paintings by  &UR; Allen &LR; 
 &UR; Ginsberg &LR; ,  &UR; Kurt Vonnegut &LR; ,  &UR; Gregory Corso &LR; ,  &UR; William Burroughs &LR; 
and  &UR; Lawrence Ferlinghetti &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Among the Ferlinghetti works is ``The Sea Within Us III,'' a
lithograph typical of writers' art, notes Jones, because it
``includes writing in a banner style.'' Writer-painters ``always
seem to include a phrase or two. ... There is a playful, sexy,
upbeat punch to the painting, and even when Ferlinghetti is
describing a descent into Hades, the art is always fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti, who thinks that Dante shared his view of the
descent, is lecturing at the L.A. County Museum of Art on March 17,
and is represented in San Francisco by  &UR; George Krevsky  &LR; Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In an interview with the Telegraph of London,  &UR; Monica &LR; 
 &UR; Lewinsky &LR;  said her newfound maturity and the press of publicity
appointments have brought an ``interesting realization. ... Gosh,
the president has a schedule like this every single day. I could
never understand why he didn't call me more. ... Today I think,
`Gee, look at my schedule,' and unlike him I don't even have
meetings on top of it. And he had to do this every day, all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jim Schock &LR;  says he and about 10 other Northern California
screenwriters planned to visit  &UR; Stanley Kubrick &LR;  on his birthday in
2001, ``to pay homage, worship, get drunk, all of the above. Never
once did it occur to us he wouldn't make it.'' Meanwhile,
 &UR; Steven Spielberg &LR;  said Sunday that Kubrick ``gave us complete
environmental experiences that got more, not less, intense the more
you watched his pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post pointed out that Kubrick was not such a fan
of Spielberg's, revealing in a 1987 interview that Kubrick had
turned away from ``The Color Purple'' after 10 minutes ``because it
made me so nauseated.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DADDY DEAREST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Men can now bear children, say British researchers quoted in a
Sunday Times of London story forwarded by  &UR; Joe Honick &LR; . The news
that an embryo could be implanted and nurtured in the abdomen of a
man elicited a range of responses:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tim Hedgley &LR; , chairman of the national fertility association
Issue, said it was good news, and ``you certainly could not stop a
man from doing this in legal terms on the grounds of sex because
that would be discrimination'';  &UR; Mark Watson &LR; , director of the
lesbian and gay rights group Stonewall foresaw gay couples taking
``advantage of it as another way of having children''; and
 &UR; Ian Craft  &LR; of the London Fertility Center called it ``dangerous and
a distortion of nature.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Affairs? He'll tell you about affairs.  &UR; Lynn Redgrave &LR; 's
estranged husband,  &UR; John Clark &LR; , who has admitted fathering a child
by the woman who became his daughter-in-law, told the Times of
London that Redgrave had strayed from their marriage, too. Among
her alleged lovers, he claims, is  &UR; Brian Dennehy &LR; , who's starring
on Broadway in ``Death of a Salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FRUITS OF RESEARCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A recent Georgetown University study found that heart doctors
were more likely to recommended sophisticated tests for white men
than for black men or for women of any race. The researchers noted
in their study that each of the doctors who participated was
presented with a bottle of Williams-Sonoma tomato sauce as a
thank-you.
</P>
<P>
   - A survey taken by Cornell University Professor  &UR; Michael Lynn &LR; ,
quoted in Travel Holiday magazine, found that restaurant waiters
get bigger tips when they draw smiley faces on checks.
</P>
<P>
   - Despite statistics showing an increase in teenage alcoholism,
and in the number of stories about college students drinking
themselves to death, the ad agency Bozell Worldwide has proposed to
the Distilled Spirits Council a $20 million to $40 million ad
campaign for late-night TV, when young people are presumed to be
watching, to encourage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he learned Italian first, Joe, now 24, speaks English
without an accent, and is otherwise well adapted to most U.S.
mores. Instead of olive oil or smelly bear grease he keeps his hair
slick with water. He never reeks of garlic and prefers chicken chow
mein to spaghetti.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; - Life magazine, in a 1939 article praising  &UR; Joe DiMaggio. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
