<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSIONARY-TECH-TEAM-     03-09 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSIONARY-TECH-TEAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Missionary TECH Team use their computer expertise for a higher
purpose
 &HT;    By Robin Galiano
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ The neatly separated cubicles, drafting tables
and lots of computers which greet visitors to Missionary TECH
Team's international headquarters in Longview indicate that an
office full of technically-minded folks work there.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let the ``left-brain'' surface fool you. Beneath it
all are some hearts beating with a real passion for the lost. These
are people on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's designing a brochure for a medical clinic in Haiti
or completing a geographical survey for a church in Russia, MTT
staff members say their technical expertise is just a tool to
accomplish something much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we're back here drawing lines and gettings cars in
service, providing technical services isn't why we're in
existence,'' founder and president Birne Wiley said. ``We're here
to see people come to Christ as Lord and Savior. We're just using
our technical services to accomplish that. The giftedness of our
people is providing the behind-the-scenes service that
</P>
<P>
   enables the Great Commission to be fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Though each of the staff members could be thriving in well-paid
secular jobs as architects, engineers or graphic artists, they have
chosen to commit themselves to a faith-supported missionary career,
and one for which it's often hard to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
   They don't wear pith helmets, after all, and their stories from
the mission field are more likely to be that of surveying a church
building than planting a church among a remote tribe. It can be a
hard sell, and yet each one has managed to raise his or her own
salary from a cadre of financial and prayer supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's because they are faith-supported themselves that the
staff can provide low-cost technical help to those on the ``front
lines'' of mission work _ the churches, Christian camps and
missions agencies who say that MTT's support is essential in
freeing them up to do that for which they were sent.
</P>
<P>
   Now celebrating its 30th year of ministry, MTT has evolved from
what founder Wiley envisioned as a sort of spiritual SWAT team _
``three or four of us going out on emergencies to provide technical
support'' _ to a staff of 16 who complete hundreds of projects each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some departmental highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Facilities planning services: Headed by civil engineer Jim
Foster, the staff has developed an ``exportable'' design package
where an architect and engineer spend a few work-intensive days on
site with a client, conducting interviews, generating a ground map
and developing an architectural program that will fit in with the
site plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest trip we've had has been four days. We've actually
drawn up plans sitting at someone's dining table,'' Foster said.
Jet lag? ``We don't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of frugal stewardship that solidifies trust
between MTT staff and clients with financial constraints. Clients
are billed for only a minimal fee, a fraction of what they'd pay
for similar professional services.
</P>
<P>
   Though the division has been without an architect for two years,
several professionals have filled in on projects, providing
schematic designs and color renderings. Then the staff engineers _
structural, mechanical and civil _ step in to complete assignments
with the help of an architectural model builder and landscape
intern.
</P>
<P>
   Among their recent projects: designing a church in Russia and a
facility for a children's ministry in Dominican Republic, and
renovating several churches in Mexico. ``You have to be culturally
sensitive,'' Foster said. ``If you build this gigantic building and
look around and there are no others, it gives the impression that
this is a rich ministry.'' In the Dominican Republic, for instance,
he said staff designed smaller cottage type homes for the children
that fit in well with the area.
</P>
<P>
   Foster says his division stays focused by accepting the
God-given gifts of each staff member. ``We're not be overseas doing
church planting, Bible translation or evangelism, but we help all
these ministries. We can participate through the gift of helps
talked about in 1 Corinthians 12:28.''
</P>
<P>
   Communication services: When MTT was established in 1969, most
requests for media support were for displays, brochures and other
literature. Last year's requests, says manager John Goodding,
included video production and Web site design.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cox, hired in August as a graphic designer, is now
working full time producing videos. ``We were having to turn people
away with video requests, but with digital video equipment it's now
feasible to do editing on computer. We can now provide
professional-quality videos for clients who would not otherwise
been able to afford it,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   And staffer Jim Collins has set up the first Web page request
for a children's camp ministry, complete with links to a virtual
postcard for parents to communicate with their kids. Graphic
artists Amy Easley and Larry Wiklund now prepare brochures and
logos on computers.
</P>
<P>
   Goodding said his staff can save missionaries time and help them
make wiser use of limited resources. ``Most clients come in with
only a vague idea of what they want,'' he said. ``From their fax or
e-mail suggestions we take them from one point, which is a very
limited scope of their ministry, and take them down the road of
what they can do. What I focus on is, with the amount of time and
resources available, what would help them accomplish their goals?''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has revolutionized the communication process for
clients around the world. MTT's clients can view architectural
drawings or proposed logo designs by logging onto the Web site. And
though some missionaries are inaccessible by mail, they can be
reached through e-mail and can approve their display designs so
that they're ready when they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The communications staff, like their other MTT colleagues, are
content to work behind the scenes. ``The only by-line we need to
hear is the words of Jesus Christ, 'Well done, thou good and
faithful servant,''' Goodding said.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical services: One of the most practical ways MTT supports
other ministries is with its fleet of 21 vehicles, which are loaned
to overseas missionaries who are home on furlough. There's no time
limit on vehicle loans, said mechanical services head Ted
Burnfield, and nominal fees cover costs only. Burnfield said it
comes out to less than half a commercial car rental rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one else who provides this kind of service. When
missionaries bring their family back from the field, they can't
afford to buy and sell a car.''
</P>
<P>
   To maintain the fleet, MTT accepts any kind of car donations.
``Most of our donors have some kind of Christian connection, and
want their dollars to be used for the Lord's work,'' Burnfield
said. ``We take everything, from scrap material to usable vehicle.
We turn them into fleet vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 cars donated to the ministry last year, Burnfield said
four were ready-to-use. Most of the fleet vehicles are minivans or
full-size and mid-size sedans to accomodate missionary families.
</P>
<P>
   Burnfield said he also services staff cars. ``Those are
face-to-face needs I can meet. I get their vehicles fixed and back
to them as fast as I can. They've got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's ministries: Grief specialist Mary Ann Kuechler drove
over 15,000 miles last year to present her popular ``Wisdom for
Widows'' seminar at churches across the country, and has developed
a leader's guide, workbook and a video based on the seminar. She's
ministered to widows at 20 churches, from New York to Seattle, and
began researching grief issues after her
</P>
<P>
   husband died in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 concern I had was that couples, even Christians,
will often drop the widow within a very short time. It's because
they don't want to face the pain of their own grief and loss. We
are taught to avoid pain at all costs, but the only way to go
through it is to face it head on.''
</P>
<P>
   What does grief feel like? ``It's intense pain, fear, anger,
depression. You feel as though your whole life has collapsed. And
there are doubts. Why didn't God stop this? Even when the
relationship was not good, you grieve longer because there's guilt
mixed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer services: When he came to MTT four and a half years
ago, computer coordinator Chuck Cox said the staff's 10 computers
had no Internet access or in-house e-mail. ``First I had to
integrate all the Macs and PCs on network, and get them all talking
to one another. Then we moved out onto the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Now computer services maintains some 30-40 units, whether it's
MACs for the graphic artists or PCs for the engineers. Project
requests for MTT often comes through e-mail now instead of mail or
phone calls, he said. And clients can give same day feedback for
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Cox also provides networking support for ministries. ``I'd like
to offer a standardized computer package with installation
instructions and volunteer support links, but we'd need more staff
to implement that.''
</P>
<P>
   In reflecting on 30 years of ministry with Missionary TECH Team,
founder Birne Wiley calls it ``a richly rewarding experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have stats on how many churches have been started,
souls saved or numbers discipled, even though we're for these
things. But it's been thrilling to see TECH impact hundreds of
thousands of lives spiritually by partnering with other ministries.
TECH gives people a chance to serve who otherwise would be left out
of the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Galiano writes for the Longview News-Journal, Longview,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
