<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-LEGIS-STATE-COX     03-09 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-LEGIS-STATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor wants to spend surplus on schools
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. Bob Taft on Tuesday outlined an
``opportunity agenda'' for Ohioans that calls for spending all of a
state budget surplus _ expected to be at least $400 million _ to
fix school buildings and provide students with the technology
assistance they need to compete in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   While Taft's plans for Ohio schools dominated his first
State-of-the-State speech, the governor also presented a joint
session of the Legislature with his ideas for economic development,
health care reform, higher education, aid to senior citizens and
spending the billions of dollars Ohio is to receive from the
tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The speech drew some encouraging words from the Ohio Education
Association, but brought cries of ``big government'' from the
fiscally conservative National Taxpayers Union, which would like to
see tax cuts not spending hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's plans for education omitted any mention of Perry County
Judge Linton Lewis Jr.'s' Feb. 26 decision that Ohio's system of
paying for primary and secondary education is unconstitutional.
Taft and Republican legislative leaders have said they will appeal
to the Ohio Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The mood inside the House chamber was warm and fuzzy Tuesday, in
contrast to blistery, snowy weather outside which closed schools
and prevented some legislators, including Rep. Dixie Allen,
D-Dayton, from getting to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's Kimberly Brown was one of four citizen-heroes Taft
brought to Columbus for the speech. He saluted Brown, a single
mother with four children, for working her way off welfare to a
nursing job that pays $17 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The usually low-key Taft waved his arms and even pounded the
podium, mindful, he said, of addressing the lawmakers from the spot
where Abraham Lincoln once stood. His wife, Hope, blew a kiss to
the governor and the audience after Taft introduced her and praised
her work in fighting substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   His ``opportunity agenda'' called for ``a future with
opportunity for every child to get a good education in a safe,
secure classroom, opportunity for Ohioans to obtain good jobs at
good wages, opportunity to keep more of their hard-earned money and
opportunity to improve the quality of their daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity that drew the most comment after the 37-minute
speech _ interrupted 18 times by applause _ was his proposal for
spending 100 percent of any state budget surplus for school
construction and technological assistance. The surplus would be for
the two-year period that ends next June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be in addition to the $600 million for school
construction Taft will put in his proposed budget for the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jeff Jacobson, R-Phillipsburg, was among the Republicans
who approved of using $400 million of the surplus for construction
and technical assistance, but resisted pledging 100 percent of a
surplus that could be much higher than $400 million. Secretary of
State Ken Blackwell, who agreed with Jacobson, said the surplus
could be as high as $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some of such a big surplus should be returned to Ohioans as a
tax refund, Jacobson, Blackwell and other Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats such as Sen. Rhine McLin of Dayton declined
to support spending 100 percent of a surplus for schools. There are
other pressing needs, such as rebuilding urban areas, McLin said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Milburn, Taft's press secretary, said the governor is
committed to using 100 percent of the surplus, however big it is.
How it would be divided between construction and technical
assistance hasn't been decided, Milburn said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he will propose spending more than $13 billion
on primary and secondary schools during the next two years, ``an
all-time record.''
</P>
<P>
   His education proposals included: $10 million in incentive
grants for schools that improve annually on proficiency test
scores, attendance and graduation rates; $25 million to help school
districts with academic problems; expansion of charter schools; $80
million for professional development of teachers and schools
leaders and pay raises of $2,500 for teachers who achieve National
Board Certification.
</P>
<P>
   While taking up nearly half of his speech, the education
proposals failed to impress some of those who side with Judge Lewis
and want Ohio's system for funding schools overhauled to provide
for more equitable funding between rich and poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those initiatives are fine but they don't get at the
systemic problem, the structural problem, the meat and potatoes
issues. These (initiatives) are frosting on the cake,'' said
William L. Phillis, executive director of the Ohio Coalition for
Equity and Adequacy, the group that successfully challenged the
school funding system.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate President Richard Finan, R-Cincinnati, said the court
case has nothing to do with the state's plans for funding schools.
``(This) shows we're gong to (move) down our path come hell or high
water. What's enough? We've got the formula in place and we're
going to fund the formula.''
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that education is his top priority, Taft told
the legislators schools alone will not guarantee Ohio a top spot in
the national and world economy.
</P>
<P>
   The state must enact electric energy deregulation this year to
remain competitive with neighboring states which could compete for
Ohio jobs with lower rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for spending $10 million on Urban Redevelopment
Loans to clean up and reuse ``brownfields'' _ abandoned and
polluted industrial and commercial sites _ in urban areas such as
Dayton. The governor also said development Director Lee Johnson
will head an Urban Revitalization Task Force to develop plans for
rebuilding central cities. The group will report back to Taft in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   On health care, Taft said he will propose tax deductions to help
uninsured Ohioans buy insurance, to encourage all Ohioans to buy
long-term care insurance and to help with excessive medical
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also said he wants to provide health insurance to
an additional 27,000 children in families of the working poor. He
would do this by raising the income eligibility limits from 150
percent of the federal poverty level to 200 percent. For a family
of four, the income limit would go from $24,675 to $32,900.
</P>
<P>
   To assist senior citizens, Taft would increase spending for the
PASSPORT program to allow more than 24,000 older Ohioans to receive
home care and support services.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he will ask the Controlling Board to set up a
separate fund to hold money from the tobacco settlement and will
convene a bipartisan task force to determine how the money should
be spent. The task force will report back to him in 60 days, the
governor said. The top priority, he added, should be reducing the
number of young smokers in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats reacted politely to the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speech was a safe speech,'' said Sen. Ben Espy of
Columbus, the Senate minority leader. ``You couldn't argue with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What was left out, however, may have been more important than
what was included, Espy said. For example, he said, the $10 million
to clean up urban industrial sites won't go far in Ohio's eight
major metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
