<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AHOLD-PATHMARK-500&AMP;AD     03-09 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHOLD-PATHMARK-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH FOOD RETAILER TO ACQUIRE PATHMARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Mass., Md.)  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a deal that pushes it further into some of the toughest
American markets, Royal Ahold NV, the scrappy Dutch food retailer,
said Tuesday that it would acquire Pathmark Stores Inc., the
leading chain in metropolitan New York, for $250 million in cash
and the assumption of $1.5 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Pathmark deal is Ahold's ninth acquisition of an American
chain since it entered the market more than two decades ago with
the purchase of the Bi-Lo chain, which competes in the Carolinas.
Ahold is the leading supermarket operator on the Eastern seaboard
and the fourth-largest chain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the company's revenues of nearly $30 billion
comes from the United States, where its chains include Stop &AMP; Shop
stores in Boston, Tops in Buffalo and Giant-Landover in the
Washington and Baltimore metropolitan areas, as well as Edwards
supermarkets in New Jersey, New York and Long Island, N.Y., which
it will convert into Pathmark stores. Pathmark, based in Carteret,
N.J., operates 132 stores and has estimated revenues of $3.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The move gives Ahold a stronger presence in the fiercely
competitive and densely populated metropolitan New York area. In
contrast to many large domestic chains, which have avoided the New
York area because of logistical headaches, including a scarcity of
space for needed new stores, the high cost of real estate and
unionized labor, Ahold has intensified its focus on the metro area
and the entire Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a signature move by Ahold and demonstrates their
commitment to the U.S. and the region,'' said Tom Burnett, director
of Merger Insight, an institutional research firm in New York.
``They are not just taking the easy, low-lying fruit _ they are
going to climb the tree and reach for the apple on the top
branch.''
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers, Ahold's latest expansion is likely to mean better
prices, a wider selection and expanded services in stores that the
company says it will spruce up. Analysts and supermarket industry
experts said Ahold's strategy when entering or expanding into a
territory is to drive down costs by commanding better purchasing
terms from suppliers, using money-saving inventory control
technology and spreading marketing expenses over a larger
geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   The company then tries to attract more shoppers by passing those
savings on with better prices and by offering higher-quality
private label goods and conveniences like in-store dry cleaning and
gas stations in parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been able to lower prices to consumers and realize
greater profitability through operating synergies primarily in the
areas of information technology, logistics, which would be
warehousing and transportation, and corporate buying of services,''
said Burt Flickinger III, who has been studying regional retail
patterns for three decades and is now managing director of Reach
Marketing, a retail and marketing consulting agency in Westport,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pathmark deal, Ahold said it expected to save $30 million
in costs the first year and $50 million the second.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The acquisition of Pathmark provides Ahold with a large number
of high- quality locations in attractive markets where our position
left room for improvement,'' said Bob Tobin, president and chief
executive of Ahold USA.
</P>
<P>
   In following a strategy of aggressive growth in the United
States, Ahold has sought to capitalize on a stable and robust
market whose consumers it understands. ``Obviously when you are an
international company, the money follows where the opportunities
are, and currently the returns in the U.S. are somewhat
favorable,'' Tobin said. ``Secondly, we've had great success in the
U.S., so we're comfortable with our investment there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pathmark deal is subject to regulatory approval. Management
said it might have to divest some stores to avoid potential
antitrust issues.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the the transaction, Ahold will pay $250 million
for all the capital stock of SMG-II Holdings Corp., which controls
Pathmark through a subsidiary, Supermarket General Holdings Corp.
The price also includes the preferred stock of the subsidiary.
Ahold will make a tender offer of $38.25 per share for all of the
publicly traded preferred stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Pathmark competitors, including Grand Union,
A&AMP;P and American Stores Co., would almost certainly feel the
pressure when Ahold took over Pathmark. ``Everyone will have to
raise their game a little bit because Pathmark should be a more
efficient, better operator under the ownership of Ahold,'' said
David Shriver, an analyst in London who follows the company for
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that Pathmark was sagging under massive debt that
it incurred when it was taken private in 1987 by an investment
group headed by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Because heavy interest payments
burned up much of its cash, ``Pathmark was four or five years
behind its capital expenditure plan to build new stores and remodel
existing stores,'' said Flickinger of Reach Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Under new ownership, said James Donald, Pathmark's chief
executive, who will continue to serve in that capacity for Ahold,
the chain can ``step up our services in the local communities and
improve the company's results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
