<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENSION-REFORM-COX     03-09 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENSION-REFORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congressmen propose privitized pensions
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Socking away money for retirement in private
accounts would be easier for most workers under a bill proposed
Tuesday by U.S. Rep. Rob Portman of Cincinnati, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Portman, a Republican, serves on the tax-writing House Ways and
Means Committee and he introduced the bill with Maryland Democrat
Ben Cardin as an essential counterpart to the one job on everyone's
political agenda this year: revamping Social Security so it will
last through the retirement of Baby Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saving Social Security) is good and we all support that,''
Portman said when unveiling the private pension bill. ``But we need
to go beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing national statistics that show personal saving in America
at its lowest rate since 1933, Portman and Cardin are offering a
bill designed to encourage the creation of private pension funds,
particularly for workers in small businesses that are least likely
to offer company plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face a major retirement challenge in this country today,''
Portman said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would make the following changes in existing pension
laws:
</P>
<P>
   Increase permitted employee contributions to 401(k) plans from
$10,000 in a year to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Increase the total combined contribution of employee and
employer in 401(k) account from $30,000 to $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Create a ``catch-up'' provision for workers 50 and older by
permitting them an additional $5,000 in tax-deferred savings each
year to compensate for years, such as during child rearing, when
their incomes might have dipped.
</P>
<P>
   Allow workers to more easily roll savings from one tax-deferred
plan, such as a 401(k), into another when they change jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Portman estimates that the changes would cost between $5 billion
and $7 billion over five years in lost tax revenue to the federal
government, but he and the bill's advocates argue that the extra
money in savings would further fuel economic growth that would
generate tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   One such supporter of the bill is Ohio's Rep. John Boehner,
(R-West Chester), chairman of the Employer-Employee Relations
subcommittee of the House Education and Workforce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pension reform is a critical issue for our nation's
increasingly mobile workforce, and it spans the generation gap,''
Boehner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is contemplating similar legislation, but a final
version has not yet been introduced. Also, last month Vice
President Al Gore unveiled the administration's take on how best to
reform pension laws.
</P>
<P>
   The White House proposal is more expansive than what Portman and
Cardin are offering. It advocates the creation of tax credits to
encourage small business owners to offer pension plans. Portman and
Cardin simply want to remove rules that prohibit small business
owners from participating in the pension plans they offer
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also advocates creating Universal Savings
Accounts, which would be free-standing retirement accounts not
linked to employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those proposals are very costly,'' Cardin said flatly. ``Our
proposal is very modest. We don't need to be part of a budget
resolution. . .'' to enact these changes.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
