<SLUG> BC-LEXIS-NEXIS-LAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lexis-Nexis buys legal information company
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Ohio, Washington state editors)
 &HT;    By Jim Bohman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Lexis-Nexis, a Miami (Ohio) Twp.-based law
database and news retrieval service, has purchased CD Law Inc., a
publisher of CD-ROM and Internet-based legal research information
for Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the cash acquisition were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   CD Law Inc. provides Washington state case law, statutes,
regulations and other information to attorneys and courts. Included
are the Revised Code of Washington, the Washington Administrative
Code, the Washington State Register and Attorney General opinions,
a variety of administrative law materials plus municipal and county
codes.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Durman, general manager and vice president of
publishing for Lexis-Nexis, said Lexis-Nexis will link its coverage
of Washington case law, reaching back to 1889, with CD Law, CD-ROM
and Web services. Included in the package will be Shepard's
citations Service and federal materials such as the United States
Code Services.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brown, chief executive of Matthew Bender Inc., another
recent Lexis-Nexis acquisition, said the CD Law purchase continues
to flesh out a strategy of identifying publishing businesses large
and small that add value to the customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll buy 'em if we can,'' Brown said. Brown is a board member
of Lexis-Nexis Group responsible for non-online legal businesses
including Matthew Bender Inc. and Lexis Law Publishing
</P>
<P>
   He said CD Law provides a range of material similar to those
sold by the Lexis Law Publishing business in Charlottesville, Va.,
which includes state codes, regulations and case law.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a few remaining independent publishers operating
on a limited scale in a single state, Brown explained. ``Some are
mom-and-pop Web publishers and others, like Anderson in Cincinnati,
are jolly well established good companies.'' He said Lexis-Nexis
often has licensing arrangements to obtain the services of selected
small companies.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Lexis-Nexis strategy involves acquisitions as
appropriate. ``But it equally involves partnering and licensing
with all and sundry in the legal and associated worlds to provide
the right kind of information for our legal and related
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexis-Nexis is a division of Reed Elsevier Inc., an Anglo-Dutch
publishing and information business with annual revenues topping $5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bohman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
