<HEADER>
A4027 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-ELECTRIC-DEREGUL     03-09 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-ELECTRIC-DEREGULATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposal could have Ohioans shopping for electricity
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Ohio residents will be able to chose where they
buy their electricity beginning Jan. 1, 2001, if state lawmakers
adopt a proposal introduced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited, much-debated electricity deregulation plan was
unveiled Tuesday in Columbus. It left many people trying to
decipher the 21-page proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more complicated than we thought it would be,'' said Rob
Tongren of the Ohio Consumers' Counsel. ``We're still trying to
figure it out and we were part of the group that wrote the damn
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even state Rep. Priscilla Mead, R-Upper Arlington, who is
sponsoring the legislation, said she cannot explain all the details
of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Power &AMP; Light officials declined comment, saying they are
reviewing the complex proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The plan describes how competition will be introduced into
Ohio's $11 billion electric industry, which has been served by
regulated monopolies for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation is expected to drive down the cost of electricity,
saving residential customers an average of $17 a month, consumer
groups say.
</P>
<P>
   How the savings will be passed on remains to be worked out, in
light of several complex issues:
</P>
<P>
   How existing utilities can recover ``stranded costs'' _ big
investments they made in nuclear power plants and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   How local governments and school districts will recoup lost
property tax revenues
</P>
<P>
   What consumer protection measures will be in place.
</P>
<P>
   How customers will be able to assess an electric company's
environmental friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deregulation plan:
</P>
<P>
   Electric companies must give customers accurate, understandable
bills, reliable service and descriptions of how to terminate
service. Existing companies must freeze their rates for four to
five years during the transition to a open marketplace. And $33
million will be provided to the Public Utilities Commission of Ohio
and the Ohio Consumers' Counsel to educate consumers on the new
system. Existing low-income customer assistance programs will be
consolidated and run by the Ohio Department of Development
beginning Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal includes ways to make sure competing power
companies do business in the existing monopolies service areas.
First, customers will be given shopping credits to encourage them
to switch to a different power company if they so chose. If after
four or five years, no competing power companies have moved in, the
existing company must auction off parts of its customer base in a
competitive bid. The existing company may bid to keep its own
customers. The auction only applies to companies that also own
generating plants in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Existing utilities will be allowed to recover their investments
over a four- to five-year period by continuing to charge existing
customers at the regulated rates and by charging customers who pick
a different power company a ``transition fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers bills will show how their power is generated _ coal,
nuclear, solar or wind _ and how it compares with other generators
in the region for environmental factors such as smog production.
Kurt Waltzer of the Ohio Environmental Council said ``Just based on
the facts, you can chose cleaner power if you want to...We liken it
to a nutrition label on a cereal box.'' Energy efficiency programs
will be continued, administered by the state, and funded by a
surcharge on customer bills.
</P>
<P>
   The way utility companies' equipment is taxed will be changed.
Utilities currently are taxed at 88 percent of market value of
their personal property while other companies are taxed at 25
percent. The proposal would reduce the tax rate on generating
equipment to 25 percent and on production equipment to 50 percent.
That will mean less money in property tax. As a replacement, a tax
based on the kilowatt-hours distributed by companies will be levied
beginning May 1, 2001. That tax will likely be passed on to
consumers. The revenue will be passed on by the state to local
governments and school districts to make sure they don't lose or
gain money in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said consumers will have to do their homework to figure out
the best deal once the new system gets underway.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said the proposal is being written into bill form now and
she expects hearings to begin before House and Senate committees
within two weeks. The proposal is expected to draw controversy,
lots of changes and probably follow-up legislation to iron out
wrinkles, she said.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators and Gov. Bob Taft have dubbed electricity
deregulation a top issue and something Ohio must do if it wants to
compete among neighboring states for economic development projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``To improve our ability to attract and retain the good jobs of
the 21st century ... Ohio needs a competitive market for
electricity,'' Taft said in his state of the state address Tuesday.
``But time is running out. Most of our neighbor states have acted
and improved their ability to compete for our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is behind several other states, including Pennsylvania,
that have gotten deregulation underway.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said ``I think competition is great for Ohio and it's great
for the utilities too. They are asking for deregulation. It's the
right move but it is a very, very difficult one.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
