<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-RAPE2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT ACCUSED IN DATE RAPE CASE THROWN OUT OF HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Capping a day of angry protests from students, Harvard
College faculty voted Tuesday to dismiss a student accused of rape,
despite an effort by some professors to reduce the punishment
because, they said, the sex had been largely consensual.
</P>
<P>
   The college stated its decision in the starkest of terms, trying
to deflect student complaints that the nation's oldest college does
not take rape seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no circumstances foreseen today under which this
student will be readmitted,'' said a college statement after the
vote, which noted the dismissal came with a wide margin of the 250
voting. ``Dismissal is the strongest sanction that has been voted
in modern times for disciplining a student.''
</P>
<P>
   While many students protesting outside the faculty vote,
welcomed the decision, the victim of the rape continued to argue
that her assailant should have been expelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that someone can cheat on a paper or an
(admissions) application and be expelled, but a student can rape me
and not be expelled,'' she said. ``Given the options at today's
faculty meeting, I was happy that they chose dismissal.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, expulsion is the toughest sanction at Harvard _ the
equivalent of the death penalty _ because it allows no chance for
readmission. Dismissal, by contrast, offers the extremely remote
possibility that a student can be readmitted if there is new
exonorating evidence and the entire faculty readmits. But Harvard
characterizes dismissal as effectively expulsion, or ``life
imprisonment,'' and says it is essentially the same as expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   The faculty who had proposed the lesser punishment, which would
have required the student to withdraw but allowed him to reapply to
Harvard within five years, said they based their proposal on the
statements the two students involved had given to the campus
disciplinary board, made up of faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The faculty group said that in those statements, which were not
released to students, the two involved acknowledged they had been
drinking, and had spent several hours in bed together before the
young man penetrated the young woman. The dissenting faculty, two
women and three men on the elected faculty council, suggested the
young woman had granted a degree of consent. She, they argued,
should accept some responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The young woman rejected that notion, saying it was merely
violating her once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `no' repeatedly,'' she said. ``I was shocked that
anyone could have seen those statements and not duly noted that
both he and I wrote in our statements...that I had repeatedly said
`no' to his advances.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident happened in early April, but campus outrage about
it flared only recently because of an interview the woman granted
to a campus weekly, in which she said the college administration
had been unhelpful after the rape.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted women's groups on campus to suggest Harvard
belittles concerns about rape _ a charge only worsened by the
proposal by faculty members to lessen the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, when the faculty met inside University
Hall to vote on the case, there were pink posters papering campus:
``Are you outraged that Harvard doesn't expel convicted rapists?''
Students dressed in winter clothing chanted ``Stop rape'' as they
marched in front of Memorial Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   As the faculty neared a vote inside, about 40 students began a
candlelight vigil, holding signs reading, ``Rape happens at
Harvard,'' a direct rebuttal to one administrator who students said
last year had suggested in a private comment that Harvard students
were too intelligent to commit such heinous crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But the dissenting faculty group said the young man had been
subjected to a witch hunt, and worried that political correctness _
a fear of being seen as ``blaming the victim'' _ would prompt the
college to give him a worse punishment than he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The professors seeking a lesser penalty said the students'
statements described an evening that began with drinking. The two
spent several hours in bed together, with some sexual interaction,
but not intercourse. At the end of the evening, the young man
penetrated the woman.
</P>
<P>
   The man's lawyer, James L. Sultan, said that when the young
woman was upset, the young man wrote her a letter taking
responsibility for what happened. He repeated that responsibility
in a conversation later, Sultan said, because he did not want his
friend to feel bad.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Administrative Board, Harvard's disciplinary council,
the young man again took responsibility for intercourse, agreeing
he had penetrated her against her will.
</P>
<P>
   The board recommended the student be dismissed. The young woman
wanted him expelled and when he was not, took the case to Middlesex
court. The young man pleaded guilty to a charge of indecent assault
and battery, which Sultan characterized as ``unwanted sexual
touching.'' He was given 18 months house arrest at his home in
Wisconsin, and five years probation. The charge of rape was not
considered, and will not be unless he violates probation.
</P>
<P>
   The woman said she did not press the rape case because she
wanted to get on with her life; Sultan said had the charge been
considered in court, he would have raised questions about whether
the sex had been consensual.
</P>
<P>
   The undergraduate faculty _ 650 potential votes _ was supposed
to consider the board's recommendation to dismiss the student in
October, but there was so much dissension over the appropriate
penalty that the motion was tabled. Several faculty suggested the
case was only ``technically rape.'' It was an error in judgment,
they said, but not a violent crime, and should not merit the same
punishment as a violent rape.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the five faculty members proposed the alternate
punishment, noting that Harvard policy allows a variety of
punishments for sexual assault and rape. According to the handbook,
those guilty of rape are subject to a range of ``severe
penalties...including expulsion or a requirement to withdraw from
the campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Sultan's lawyer says his client has no interest in returning to
Harvard, not least because he would have to register as a sex
offender if he returned to Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he understood the faculty opposition to
dismissal. ``I think reasonable people can have some difference of
opinion about what's an appropriate sanction,'' Sultan said. ``As a
practical matter, here is a kid who had a very promising career.
His life at Harvard is over. The consequences are enormous and
incredibly devastating. He's paying an extremely high price for a
mistake in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sultan accused the young woman of publicizing the incident _
however anonymously _ to further embarrass his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sheer vindictiveness, under the guise of some sort of a
great reform movement,'' he said, ``That's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, the young woman replied: ``People have forgotten how
much my life has been ruined. I not only was the victim of a
violent crime, but it's a real challenge to speak out about these
things. I don't do it lightly. I'm doing it for the other rape
victims on this campus who for many reasons can't speak out. I was
willing to endure this firestorm because i thought it was worth it,
not because of some petty complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Matthew Falconer contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
