<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUDGET-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT IS PLEDGED FOR REPUBLICAN BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans pledged support on Tuesday for the
budget outline worked out last week by their leaders, but
acknowledged that turning the plan into legislation would be
fraught with political risks and difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   After separate briefings on the plan, House and Senate
Republicans said they expected to adopt a tax and spending
guideline in the next several weeks that would set aside all money
generated by the Social Security system, increase spending for the
military and education, cut taxes and remain within the tight
spending limits in current budget law.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to present a united front as they head into another season
of battles with the Clinton administration over fiscal priorities,
Republicans said they were willing to put aside their long-running
internal divisions and to suspend for now their doubts about the
plan's political viability.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans appear to have resigned themselves to limiting the
size of their proposed tax cut for next year to a much smaller
level than they had initially envisioned. But several influential
Republicans said that the party would ultimately have to confront
the hard choices their plan would force on them, most notably its
requirement for deep cuts in domestic programs outside the Pentagon
and education to remain within the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, the head of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, said that there was little will in the
Senate for cuts in nonmilitary spending but a strong desire for an
increase in Pentagon spending. As a result, Stevens said, the
appropriations committees, which draw up the bills that finance
specific programs, would inevitably come under heavy pressure to
break the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can live with them,'' he said, referring to the caps. ``But
I'm not sure Congress can take the actions necessary to live within
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and other Republicans said they wanted to avoid a replay
of last year, when Congress and the administration agreed on a
spending plan during a flurry of last-minute negotiations that got
around the spending limits by designating $20 billion in
expenditures as ``emergencies'' that are not subject to normal
budget rules.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the Republican whip, said: ``To
stay within the caps will require fiscal discipline. We broke that
discipline last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan, which has been endorsed by the party's
leaders in both the House and the Senate, is an effort to claim the
high ground in this year's budget battle by promising to go further
than President Clinton in saving projected federal budget surpluses
for Social Security and preserving fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will be the basis for the budget resolution, a
nonbinding measure that guides the appropriations and tax-writing
committees in both chambers. Because it is not legislation, the
budget resolution cannot be vetoed by the president, although White
House officials have already attacked the plan for requiring deep
cuts in domestic spending and for not earmarking part of the
projected budget surplus to shore up Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Budget politics this year are particularly complicated, in part
because they are caught up in the related question of how to shore
up Social Security and in part because of the eagerness in both
parties to position themselves for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ideological divide between Republicans and Democrats
appears especially deep this year, the size of the projected budget
surpluses could provide a useful bridge.
</P>
<P>
   This is because the strength of the economy seems likely to make
the surplus even bigger than projected for the next year or two.
Members of both parties said the prospects for a compromise
improved with each increase in the pool of money available to them,
in much the same way that the 1997 bipartisan budget agreement was
built on the improving fiscal outlook.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The potential for a larger-than-expected surplus is already
playing into Republican plans. Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, who
heads the House Budget Committee, told House Republicans on Tuesday
that he expected next year's tax cut to be $10 billion to $15
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Kasich later told reporters that if the Congressional Budget
Office increased its estimate of next year's surplus in coming
months, the size of the tax cut could expand. Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the majority leader, said the tax cut next year could
be as much as $25 billion, and would grow rapidly in subsequent
years as the non-Social Security budget surplus increased.
</P>
<P>
   The budget wrangling also continued to ensnare a $1.9-billion
supplemental spending bill that includes disaster relief aid for
Central American countries hit by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has proposed paying for the spending by dipping
into this year's surplus, all of which comes from Social Security.
But Republicans insisted again Tuesday that the aid be paid for by
offsetting spending cuts in programs including welfare and food
stamps, a condition the White House has rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
