<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLA     03-09 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NABISCO: A RESPONSE TO SHAREHOLDER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP, RJR-NABISCO-TERMS,
RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL, RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN, RJR-NABISCO-LBO,
RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For months, shareholders of RJR Nabisco Holdings have
besieged the company with requests to spin off the Nabisco food
operations. They urged the company to create a nontobacco entity
that would be able to rise above the depressed valuation of what
should be one of the world's premier consumer-product companies.
</P>
<P>
   No can do, Steven Goldstone, RJR's chairman, answered
repeatedly. The parent company's liabilities from years of tobacco
litigation were too sticky to allow the businesses to be separated.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out investors had the wrong target in their sights.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a month after he said a spinoff of Nabisco was
impracticable, Goldstone announced Tuesday that RJR Nabisco instead
would sell its international tobacco business, use the proceeds to
reduce debt, and split off not the food company but its domestic
tobacco business, to be known once again as R.J. Reynolds tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   By spinning off the American tobacco company and letting it
trade separately from the remaining food company, Goldstone said he
intended to give shareholders a good portion of what they wanted:
separate companies with a clear delineation between the cigarette
operations and the cookie and biscuit business.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, however, were not impressed. After jumping sharply in
early trading, shares of RJR Nabisco Holdings finished the day up
only 12.5 cents, at $28.75. Investors essentially deemed the
per-share value created by the separation of the two businesses to
be worth less than the price of a single cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was so discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ingenious idea with a lot of hypotheticals attached,''
said David Dreman, the chairman of Dreman Value Management, who
owns shares of RJR Nabisco. ``If it works, it adds enormously to
shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   But the remaining questions about the tobacco-related
liabilities of the parent company, he added, ``are probably why the
market isn't all that enthused about the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The tepid reaction also reflects the uncertainty around a deal
whose details will not be announced until the sale of the foreign
tobacco operations is completed, probably not until next month at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   For all the initial skepticism, the announcement does provide a
somewhat brightened outlook for shareholders of both the parent RJR
Nabisco and for investors in the class A shares of Nabisco
Holdings, the publicly traded food subsidiary whose shares are
80-percent owned by RJR.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, the sale of the overseas tobacco business will
give RJR a big wad of cash to pay off debt. Since its contentious
leveraged buyout in 1989, RJR Nabisco has labored under a heavy
debt load that has squashed the company's investment potential by
dragging down earnings and limiting its financial flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts Tuesday, RJR officials said
the new tobacco company would begin life with only about $1 billion
in debt and $7 billion in equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking almost all of the debt out of a very highly
leveraged company,'' Dreman said. With a debt-to-equity ratio of
only 14 percent, the Reynolds tobacco company's balance sheet would
be substantially stronger than most of the companies whose shares
are part of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, in which the
average debt load is about equal to shareholders' equity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the tobacco company should pay an attractive
dividend. On Tuesday, RJR Nabisco Holdings declared its regular
quarterly dividend of 51.25 cents a share, which gives its shares
an annual dividend yield of about 7 percent _ far above the 1.25
percent dividend yield of the S&AMP;P 500. The tobacco business is
expected to pay a similar dividend after the company splits,
financial analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Nabisco food operations, meanwhile, have struggled recently
with restructurings and big changes in distribution. But that
company too might prosper as it gets out from under some of the
parent company's distractions and, later this year, begins to see
anticipated improvements in profit margins from recent overhauls of
its sales and marketing ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that has very powerful brands and a strong
market position,'' said Michael Kassen, co-manager of the Neuberger
&AMP; Berman Partners fund, which holds the food company's class A
shares. ``It's a real fixer-upper. With a reasonable time horizon,
I think the company can do much better. We're only in the second or
third inning of that ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco sales force has been reorganized in more than half
the markets around the country and the remaining areas should
complete overhauls by the end of the year. That should help the
company defend its turf against competitors, which have been
attacking many of the company's best-known brands.
</P>
<P>
   But the company continues to rely heavily on discounts and
promotions to maintain sales, a practice that has squeezed profit
margins. Revenues from continuing food businesses were $8.1 billion
last year, flat with the previous year's results. Overall, RJR's
food business actually shrank slightly last year because it sold
some operations. This year, analysts expect the food company's
sales to grow about 3 percent and the company to earn about $1.30 a
share, up from $1.21 last year.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nabisco foods unit taking a slow path toward recovery,
some investors are still hoping that the parent will consider
selling the business in the next year or two, or do something else
to lift the prices of the shares of the separately traded
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The values of the two companies in the stock market diverge in
odd ways. And the spread between the value of the parent company's
investment in the Nabisco Holdings subsidiary and the parent
company's own stock price widened even more Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nabisco Holdings, the food subsidiary, closed at
$44.9375, up 31.25 cents. RJR Nabisco's 80 percent investment in
the food subsidiary, therefore, should be worth about $29.58 a
share to the parent company's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But with RJR Nabisco's share price closing at $28.75, less than
the value of its investment in the food company alone, investors _
despite Tuesday's announcement _ were still putting a negative
value on the tobacco operations. Once the tobacco company starts
trading, of course, that will not be the case; financial analysts
said they expected the tobacco company's shares to trade for at
least several dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   The low value still being assigned to tobacco reflects, at least
in part, the feeling among many investors that Tuesday's
restructuring announcement did not lift all of the uncertainty from
RJR Nabisco's future. Lawyers in tobacco-liability lawsuits may
well challenge the deal, and few investment professionals were
willing to predict the outcome of those battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company was responding to pressure to improve shareholder
returns,'' said Brian Rogers, manager of the T. Rowe Price
Equity-Income fund, a shareholder in the parent company. ``That is
a welcome move. But we're going to have to see how this thing
evolves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
