<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON HIT WITH SURPRISE SNOWSTORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Ill., Ind., Mass., Md., Mich., Minn., N.Y., Ohio, Pa.,
W.Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After sweeping a thousand miles from the Upper
Midwest, a late-winter snowstorm roared into the East on Tuesday,
surprising many people, especially those in the Washington area,
where a mild winter had lulled residents into complacency and where
shoots from tulip bulbs are already five inches high.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey Walston, a meteorologist at the National Weather Service
station in suburban Virginia, said that 6 to 10 inches had fallen
by this evening in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   He said that people should not be surprised by such a big storm
less than two weeks before the first day of spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the biggest snowstorms have come in the month of
March,'' Walston said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the case in the Washington area, he said, because
winters are usually cold enough for snow but there is not enough
moisture in the air to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get warm, moist air when spring starts to approach,''
Walston said. ``That's what happened today. Moisture came in from
the gulf.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm began far to the west, dumping 16 inches of snow in
the Minneapolis-St. Paul area on Monday, The Associated Press
reported, and moved eastward bringing 10 inches of snow to Indiana
and Ohio and making as much as a foot possible by Wednesday in the
West Virginia mountains. Snow also extended into Delaware, Michigan
and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the weather service had issued a warning that
heavy snow could hit the mountains of western Maryland. By 4 a.m.
Tuesday, the warning had been broadened to include the Washington
area, and by 7 a.m. the snow started falling. That led federal
agencies to allow their employees to leave early, and schools
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Hamilton, the spokesman for both Washington Reagan National
Airport and Dulles International Airport, said: ``It's been a rough
day for air travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, she said, flights into the airports were
disrupted because snow had kept planes on the ground in upstate New
York, Boston, Chicago and other places in the Midwest. ``Then we've
had nonstop snow throughout the day,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 percent of the flights at the Washington airports
were canceled during the day, with the number rising to 70 percent
by Tuesday evening, much higher than the 25 percent cancellation
rate in the usually snowier Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a much smaller storm but it has proven
not to be,'' Ms. Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why this was, Andy Woodock, another meteorologist in
suburban Virginia, said: ``There's a band of air that's just not
moving. It just snowed and snowed and snowed instead of moving
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In Frostburg, Md., John Kunis, the manager of a Domino's Pizza
store, said the snow had slowed, but not stopped, his deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally run a 20-minute estimated delivery time,'' he
said. ``Now we're running a 35. But we're still out there fighting
it, kind of like the Postal Service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
