<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Wednesday, March 10, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443
or Catherine Laidlaw at 415-777-6057.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MICROSOFT  &LR; _ The pretrial settlement of an antitrust suit
between Intel Corp. and the government fueled reports yesterday
that Microsoft Corp. and the U.S. Justice Department are
negotiating a settlement of their own.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Seattle Times, quoting unnamed sources close to the
negotiations, said Microsoft and Justice officials were talking
about a possible agreement to end the government's landmark
antitrust suit against the software firm. But later in the day,
Reuters quoted a government lawyer saying there were no talks going
on. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PEOPLESOFT &LR;  _ PeopleSoft Inc., whose meteoric growth stalled
last year, said yesterday it is searching for someone to succeed
founder David Duffield as president and possibly chief executive
officer. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED &LR;  _ Four more technology powers have taken minority stakes
in Red Hat Software, bolstering the company's position as the
leading purveyor of the Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The investments by IBM, Compaq Computer, Novell and Oracle,
which were announced yesterday, come on top of similar investments
in Red Hat by Intel and Netscape Communications (before it was
acquired by America Online). The amounts were not disclosed. By
David Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENENTECH &LR;  _ Genentech Inc. is one step away from seeking Food
and Drug Administration approval to sell a new drug designed to
dissolve blood clots with a single injection. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCI &LR;  _ MCI WorldCom Corp. is challenging the Federal
Communication Commission's ruling that says calls to the Internet
are long-distance instead of local.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's ruling could prevent Baby Bell competitors such as
MCI from collecting hundreds of millions of dollars from regional
phone companies like Pacific Bell. &UR;  &LR; The decision also could lead to
higher costs for consumers who use the Internet. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET  &LR; (column) _ Vive la Vivus?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of Muse, an also-ran male impotency treatment dwarfed
by the gonzo success of Viagra, knocked a double Monday after
announcing that it won a patent for a topical cream aimed at
helping women with sexual dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Vivus shareholders (and I'm trying to resist
the temptation to use colorful double entendre here because this is
a family newspaper), the one-day rally didn't last very long.
Yesterday, Vivus' shares plunged 19 percent to close at $3.91. By
columnist Mark Veverka
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ENTREPRENEUR PACKAGE &QC;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TEN &LR;  _ Erick Hachenburg was late for a key company meeting, but the
executive couldn't pull himself away from a far more urgent task: a
game of online solitaire on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait, I have to finish this,'' said Hachenburg, the CEO of
Total Entertainment Network, as he moved his cursor over a six of
hearts and studied his options. A company vice president politely
urged him to hurry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Hachenburg's fixation on the card game was understandable.
After all, it was his decision to switch the company's focus from
online shoot-em-up games for hard-core players to low-tech games
like solitaire and chess. The move opened a broader market and
helped revive the San Francisco firm in just one year. By Benny
Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW  &LR; _ Question: What tax breaks are available to someone
starting a business? There are a lot of costs before any revenue
rolls in. Columnist Peter Sinton has the answer
</P>
</TEXT>
