<HEADLINE>
NIHILISM GETS A BUTCHER'S FACE, FRANCE A JOLT OF REALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After seeing ``I Stand Alone,'' after meeting its
director, Gaspar Noe, 35, one couldn't help but ask: How could a
pleasant young man with a positive view of life make a film as dark
and desperate as this one?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Noe might of course have confessed that he was a secret
nihilist, that ``I Stand Alone'' (``Seul Contre Tous'') was a
public form of psychotherapy. Reassuringly, his answer was more
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make a film like this because I feel at ease with
myself,'' he said. ``I was raised in a comfortable household with
adorable parents who gave me nothing but love, and this allows me
to make a film about depression that in the end is very
combative.''
</P>
<P>
   An Argentine-born Frenchman, Noe was talking in a cafe beside
one of the two Paris theaters where his movie is playing. On
Wednesday it opens in New York for a two-week run at the Film
Forum. ``I Stand Alone'' is his first feature film, but in fact it
picks up where his award-winning 1991 short, ``Carne,'' left off in
its portrayal of an ill-starred Paris butcher of horse meat, again
played by the burly Philippe Nahon.
</P>
<P>
   The new film stands on its own, but to explain why its central
character is about to move still closer to the edge, Noe opens with
a series of stills, accompanied by the butcher's raspy voiceover,
recapitulating the story so far:
</P>
<P>
   The butcher has achieved his dream of opening his own shop when
he meets a factory worker who becomes pregnant and then abandons
him, leaving their mute daughter for him to raise. When the girl
reaches puberty, she is frightened by her first menstruation and
rushes to her father's shop. Seeing blood on her dress and
imagining she has been raped, he stabs an innocent passer-by.
</P>
<P>
   After serving time in jail, with his daughter now
institutionalized, he finds work as a barman and promptly seduces
the owner's wife. Then, when she becomes pregnant, they decide to
start a new life in Lille.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Stand Alone'' finds the butcher living in the crammed
apartment of his mistress' mother, growing ever more depressed as
he struggles to find work. ``You have to smile to be a butcher,''
he is told when he applies for a job in the meat section of a Lille
supermarket. He cannot and is ordered to leave.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the walls close in on him as his mistress baits him for
watching television. One night he explodes in anger, attacking her
and pummeling her swollen stomach. He grabs his pistol and
hitchhikes to Paris, never looking back.
</P>
<P>
   He still imagines that hope is somewhere to be found. He checks
into the very hotel room where his daughter was conceived and again
looks for work without success. He tries to borrow money from old
friends, but they, too, are down at heel or simply tightfisted.
</P>
<P>
   As his anger mounts, he is freshly humiliated: he gets into an
argument in a bar and is forced to leave by a shotgun-waving owner.
When a gay meat supplier turns him down for yet another job because
of his jail record, he swears revenge. He has three bullets in his
pistol and he plans to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Recounted in this way (without revealing its ending), the story
seems to be that of a middle-aged man driven to despair by
unemployment, rejection and lack of love. What gives the film its
extraordinary intensity, though, is the stream-of-consciousness
voice-over that records the butcher's descent into hate for the
world and disgust with himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are always alone, alone when you're born, alone when you
die, alone, always alone,'' the butcher's mind tells him at one
point. ``The older you get, the lonelier you are, alone with a few
memories that life steadily destroys. Life is like a tunnel.
Everyone has his little tunnel. But at the end of the tunnel, there
is no light. There is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing the movie as ``devastating'' after it was shown at
last fall's New York Film Festival, Stephen Holden wrote in The New
York Times that `` `I Stand Alone' probes as relentlessly into the
psychology of nihilism as any movie has ever attempted.''
</P>
<P>
   Noe reinforces this message in the way he has shot and cut the
film (he was the film's cameraman as well as its screenwriter,
director, producer and co-editor), using close-up images of
violence and hard-core pornography followed by sudden camera
movements accompanied by amplified gunshots that heighten the
tension. Interspersed, he has one-word tabloid headlines, like
``Morality'' and ``Justice,'' as well as a ``Warning'' _ giving
audiences time to leave the theater _ before the film's denouement.
</P>
<P>
   Nahon's performance has deservedly won praise, not least because
Noe's endless difficulties in raising money for the movie meant
that the 30 days of filming were spread over almost three years.
For ``Carne,'' the actor learned how to handle and cut meat; for
``I Stand Alone,'' it was more a question of entering into a state
of mind. But he said he was unfazed by the interruptions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaspar would call up and say, `We're shooting tomorrow because
I have found money for some film stock,''' said Nahon, who is 60.
``We'd meet and work out if we were shooting before or after the
last scene we did. He'd say, `Action!' and I was inside the
character. It wasn't difficult. You see people like that every day
everywhere. Homeless people. At 50, no one can find a job. If
you've spent a few days in jail, it's worse. You're finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``I Stand Alone'' is essentially a psychological study,
not political commentary, some French critics have seen it as an
indictment of contemporary France and, indirectly, of a French
movie industry that until recently has been dominated by comedies,
historical costume dramas and intimate love stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is not that France at the end of the 20th
century can be as sordid, ugly and pitiless as that,'' Le Monde's
film critic, Jean-Michel Frodon, wrote of Noe's movie. ``It can be.
But since movies tend all too often to forget this, one that points
this out is to be welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   That this film was ever made is itself surprising. Neo-realism
may be making a comeback here, as witnessed by Mathieu Kassovitz's
``Hate,'' Bruno Dumont's ``Life of Jesus,'' Erick Zonca's
``Dreamlife of Angels'' and Bertrand Tavernier's still-unreleased
``Life Begins Today,'' but Noe's screenplay proved too realistic to
win the backing of any French television company. And since this is
the first step toward making a film here, he was on his own.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help that Noe was not part of the Paris movie world.
He attended a Paris film school, L'Ecole Lumiere, but he said that
until he made ``Carne'' he was more interested in amusing himself
than in working. And it was thanks to ``Carne'' that he eventually
won support to make another 40-minute movie from the short-films
division of the pay-TV channel, Canal Plus.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, it was almost two years before the French designer,
Agnes B., provided him with the funds to make a feature-length
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The television people said to me, `Why don't you come with a
real project, a real police thriller, with real producers, real
actors?''' Noe recalled. ``The people who read screenplays are
employees worried about losing their jobs if they approve something
too explosive. They prefer to give money to an established director
even if he makes a flop. Anyway, I worked once or twice as an
assistant director on big productions and they're not for me. They
resemble the Normandy landings more than a work of art. I like to
work with a small team, without makeup, with little decor, where
you can improvise, you can invent scenes on location.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inevitably, ``I Stand Alone'' has been compared with
Martin Scorsese's ``Taxi Driver,'' but Noe also speaks admiringly
of numerous other directors, among them Luis Bunuel, Elia Kazan,
Sam Peckinpah, Roberto Rosselini, Vittorio de Sica and Pier Paolo
Pasolini.
</P>
<P>
   And for his next film, he said, he would like to follow in the
footsteps of Nagisa Oshima's erotic 1976 classic, ``In the Realm of
the Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to make a film that shows people making love
without it being pornographic, like `In the Realm of the Senses,'
but perhaps less morbid,'' he said. ``I'd like to show a love story
where people make love from time to time, but where the camera does
not then turn to the fireplace. You can show a lot about people's
psychology in the way they make love.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the young director was asked, does he like to shock?
</P>
<P>
   ``My film does not set out to shock,'' he said. ``I think that
in English the word `shock' is more negative than in French. In
French, it means more `to disturb.' I don't think you should remove
things that stir the emotions. If something disturbing leads
somewhere else, why not? You know, perhaps strangely, no one has
said that the violence in `I Stand Alone' is gratuitous violence.
All I have done is filter out the positive side of life. I have
left the butcher with nothing more than the negative power of his
existence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
