<HEADLINE>
ICAHN SILENT ABOUT NEWS OF NABISCO SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP, RJR-NABISCO-TERMS,
RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL, RJR-NABISCO-LBO, RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH,
RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where's Carl Icahn?
</P>
<P>
   Icahn, the financier who has made not one but two attempts to
shake up RJR Nabisco Holdings over the last four years, was
strangely quiet Tuesday despite recent threats of a proxy battle to
force the company to split up its food and tobacco businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He had raised his stake in RJR Nabisco to 7.7 percent recently
from 5.6 percent in late December. But traders suggested Tuesday
that he was in a selling mood and could have been part of the
reason RJR Nabisco's stock dropped sharply from an the day's high
of $31 to close at $28.75, up 12.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In recent Securities and Exchange Commission filings, Icahn
disclosed that he and his affiliates had bought an additional 3.6
million shares for prices ranging from $25.94 to $27.87, increasing
the total to 25 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago he was on the phone with investors seeking
support for his proxy battle as well as seeking candidates for the
board, traders and investors said. He faces a deadline on Friday
for filing his slate of candidates for election to the board in
May. But one investor who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
Icahn was having limited success and might nominate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn and his affiliated companies had said they were planning
to seek board seats if RJR Nabisco did not split its food and
tobacco businesses. The announcement the company made Tuesday may
help placate Icahn, who for years has been agitating for a
like-minded plan.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows exactly what Icahn intends to do, and he will
by no means remain silent, analysts said. He recently sued a New
York law firm for $3.5 million, saying it violated an agreement to
help him pursue his proxy fight.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn did not return phone calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco, for its part, is hoping investors will be pleased
with its plan. Executives close to RJR Nabisco said company
officials were concerned that noise from Icahn's camp could have
hurt the company's chances of getting the best price possible for
the international operations in the last days of their two-year
auction process.
</P>
<P>
   They also contended that Icahn did not force them to act and
that they had been considering splitting off the domestic tobacco
business.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven F. Goldstone, RJR Nabisco's chief executive, is not
assuming that Tuesday's development will make Icahn go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said to an analyst group recently, when I hear the song
of the first robin in spring I always know I'm going to hear the
lyrics of Carl Icahn,'' Goldstone said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
