<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIENFUEGOS PREPARED TO SIT OUT SEASON, AGENT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ In what looks like a lousy game of chess
between Major League Soccer and Mauricio Cienfuegos, the Los
Angeles Galaxy could be the big loser.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, a three-time MLS all-star, has been a holdout since
training camp began last month and is prepared to sit out the
season, his agent said.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's main gate attraction and assists leader in the
team's first three seasons, Cienfuegos remains in El Salvador with
fellow holdout Raul Diaz Arce of San Jose. Cienfuegos has not
resolved a contract dispute that began when he hired agent Corey
Clemetson.
</P>
<P>
   Clemetson, who represents Diaz Arce as well, believes that other
marquee foreign players are paid well over what the MLS league
maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos stands to make $103,000 this season. Clemetson says
he believes the league maximum to be $250,000. That amount is
disputed by MLS officials, however.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Cienfuegos met with Ivan Gazidis and other league
officials to discuss his contract. Gazidis, the executive vice
president of player relations for MLS, said Cienfuegos was offered
a raise, but Clemetson called the offer ``insulting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemetson says Cienfuegos, 31, is looking for a contract well
above $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their (MLS) offer was $30,000 to $40,000 more than what he
(Cienfuegos) was getting, and that's ridiculous,'' Clemetson said.
``These guys left El Salvador and came to talk in good faith about
working out these (contract) differences and they were totally
insulted by their (MLS) offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players aren't stupid; they're prepared for the long
haul (of holding out). If the offers continue to be where they're
at, he (Cienfuegos) won't sit out the whole season but could make
an announcement that he will never play in MLS again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not at that point where he'll never play again, but if
something doesn't work out in the next couple weeks, it could,''
Clemetson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gazidis, who has taken over league contract negotiations for
Sunil Gulati (fired earlier this month), says Cienfuegos and Diaz
Arce are not improving their position by not reporting to camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advice he's (Cienfuegos) receiving from his agent is that
he will improve his negotiating position if he holds out,'' Gazidis
said. ``We're prepared to make a better offer, but we're not about
to sign a new piece of paper while he's refusing to honor the
existing piece of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have no choice but to let this go the whole season, then
it's very unfortunate. He has two years left on his contract and by
not showing up he would be essentially throwing away the rest of
his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Gazidis also said Clemetson's numbers are way off. First, he
says, the league maximum is in the $230,000 range; second, he says
no player is earning more than the league maximum, although signing
bonuses cloud the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot variables that go into these contracts and
signing bonuses are one of them, which in turn increases the
overall value of the deal.'' Gazidis said. ``The numbers aren't as
cut and dried as he (Clemetson makes them appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jorge) Campos, for example, makes a lot of money in Mexico
when he's not here. He's a player in high demand because of his
market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mauricio's case, he hasn't had any offers overseas. If he's
really in demand, we need to see the interest. If he wants to make
more money, he could play year-round like the others. We would be
willing to work out a loan arrangement if he can show the interest
is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano, in charge of player
personnel decisions for the team, is left with only one foreign
starter on his team -- Welton.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Hermosillo won't return for a couple of months while he
finishes his season in Mexico. MLS sold defensive midfielder Martin
Machon to a Mexican club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do; I can't even set any deadlines,''
said Zambrano. ``It's out of my hands. The problem with single
entity is that these things are handled through the league; we have
no way of working things our ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if Cienfuegos decides to hold out and the league
decides to punish Cienfuegos by not trading his rights to another
league or terminating his contract (which is highly likely), the
Galaxy is a big loser because it can't seek a foreign replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to play the season without Mauricio,''
Zambrano said. ``That's just the reality. What can I do? I can't
worry about it. I learned a long time ago that you can't worry
about things that are out of your hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
