<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Genentech Drug Close To Seeking FDA's OK  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Genentech Inc. is one step away from seeking Food and Drug
Administration approval to sell a new drug designed to dissolve
blood clots with a single injection.
</P>
<P>
   The company released a study yesterday showing that its new drug
candidate, TNK, was as effective as its current clot-buster,
Activase, for treating people who had already suffered a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two drugs was given to 8,500 heart attack patients.
One month later, more than 93 percent of the patients given either
drug survived. Before clot-busters came along, the one-month
survival rate would have been more like 90 percent, Genentech said.
</P>
<P>
   The Phase III or final-stage study was designed specifically to
show that TNK was as effective as Activase, which is administered
in a 90-minute intravenous infusion.
</P>
<P>
   Based on yesterday's positive results, analysts said Genentech
must quickly seek FDA approval to start selling TNK, because
Activase, which accounts for a roughly a fifth of its revenues, is
losing sales. Activase slipped from $260.7 million in 1997 sales to
$213 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Newer clot-busters, like Retavase made by Centocor Inc. of
Pennsylvania, are winning ground against Activase because they are
more convenient, according to analyst Meirav Chovav, who follows
Genentech for Salomon Smith Barney. Retavase is given to patients
in two injections.
</P>
<P>
   With the single-shot TNK, ``Genentech has stolen (Centocor's)
thunder,'' Chovav said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Stump, Genentech vice president for clinical trials, said
his firm would soon ask for FDA permission to sell TNK as a heart
attack treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the FDA gives Genentech the quick approval it
expects, TNK could face competition from a rival single-shot
clot-buster. At the same scientific meeting in New Orleans where
Genentech presented its test results, Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
showed off positive Phase III results for nPA, another single-shot
drug designed to dissolve blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   In its study of 15,000 heart patients, Bristol-Myers compared
nPA to Genentech's Activase and reported that nPA was effective as
the current Genentech drug in preventing death or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Genentech slipped 6 cents to close at $81.44.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
