<SLUG> BC-PEOPLESOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PeopleSoft Looking for New Leader  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PeopleSoft Inc., whose meteoric growth stalled last year, said
yesterday it is searching for someone to succeed founder David
Duffield as president and possibly chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Duffield, 58, would continue as chairman, but might turn over
his CEO title to lure a star, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,600-person maker of business-management software said
Duffield will set PeopleSoft's long-term strategy while the new
executive will oversee day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft has hired an unnamed executive recruiting firm to
look for outside candidates and is also considering internal ones,
a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Duffield could not be reached for comment. The spokesman said
Duffield has been ``looking several months for someone with a
strong operations background.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, PeopleSoft earned $143.2 million on sales of $1.3
billion. The year before, it earned $139.8 million on sales of
$815.6 million. In recent quarters, however, its growth rate has
tapered off.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been hurt by competition from heavyweights
Oracle Corp. and SAP AG, slumping markets in Asia and Latin
America, and its own struggle to integrate several acquisitions.
Compounding matters, PeopleSoft's sales of software to fix the Year
2000 computer problem have fallen short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dramatic series of unfortunate events hit them all at
once,'' said analyst Eric Upin of BancBoston Robertson Stephens in
San Francisco. ``The wheels have come off their rapid growth. The
good times are over.''
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft's shares have fallen two-thirds from a 52-week high
of $55.94 in April. The stock inched up 31 cents, to $18.94, in
Nasdaq trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The company cut jobs for the first time in January, when it laid
off 430 people. It also formed a new division, &UR;  &LR; called Momentum
Business Applications, to &UR;  &LR; develop software applications.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Duffield would be one of several top PeopleSoft executives to
change jobs recently.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Ronald Codd resigned in January to head
Momentum, and Albert Duffield, the chairman's brother, last week
said he will retire as PeopleSoft's senior vice president of sales
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said David Duffield's decision to diminish his role at
PeopleSoft was influenced partly by his growing interests outside
the company. He has adopted several children and last summer the
animal-rights activist started a $200 million ``no-kill'' project
for cats and dogs at shelters throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PEOPLESO () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Duffield's personal net worth, based largely on his PeopleSoft
stock, is estimated at more than $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PEOPLESO () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
