r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-SFCHRON &LR;      03-09 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Net Gaming Firm Makes Right Moves  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Erick Hachenburg was late for a key company meeting, but the
executive couldn't pull himself away from a far more urgent task: a
game of online solitaire on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait, I have to finish this,'' said Hachenburg, the CEO of
Total Entertainment Network, as he moved his cursor over a six of
hearts and studied his options. A company vice president politely
urged him to hurry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Hachenburg's fixation on the card game was understandable.
After all, it was his decision to switch the company's focus from
online shoot-em-up games for hard-core players to low-tech games
like solitaire and chess. The move opened a broader market and
helped revive the San Francisco firm in just one year.
</P>
<P>
   Through a series of exclusive deals, Ten has become the company
that runs online parlor games for Netscape Netcenter, Alta Vista,
Cnet, Excite, GeoCities, Infoseek, Prodigy and WebCrawler.
</P>
<P>
   Ten also has lined up deals with Lycos, onetime rival game
service Heat.Net and Internet cable services AtHome and Road
Runner. And in what some game-industry observers called a major
coup, Ten sewed up a deal this month with the Station, an Internet
game site run by a division of Sony Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly all of its 1.5 million new registered members signed
up in the past six months, Ten has made a remarkable comeback for a
3-year-old startup that game industry analysts thought was on the
verge of shutting down in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were dead in the water,'' said David Cole, executive
editor of the industry magazine Game Intelligence of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Ten's struggles illustrate the promise and pitfalls of the
fast-moving and highly competitive Internet gaming industry.
Forrester Research predicts that industry revenues will grow from
just $277 million in 1998 to $2 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Adaptability was Ten's key &LR;   &LR; to survival.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held company's original game plan was to sell
monthly subscriptions to hard-core fans who wanted to play popular
computer fantasy or shoot-em games like Duke Nukem or Quake with
others through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While those hard-core gamers were passionate, there were not
enough of them to generate sufficient revenues for Ten to survive.
Its subscriptions peaked at about 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Ten stubbornly held onto the subscription-revenue model,
competitors like MPath Interactive in Mountain View switched to
offering free games supported by advertising. Redwood City's
SegaSoft also launched a free gaming site called Heat.Net.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of TEN10 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In another blow, Ten originally planned to license PC games for
play online. But before long, the PC gamemakers themselves began
offering their own online versions, cutting Ten out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ten had to scale back operations and lay off about
36 workers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Seema Williams of Forrester Research said she was
``horribly pessimistic'' about Ten's chances for survival through
1998 and that she believed the company would be forced to sell
itself to a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At that point, Ten adopted a slightly different strategy. It
launched a Professional Gamers League _ a series of continuing
tournaments that attracted hard-core online game enthusiasts and
much-needed revenue from corporate sponsorships. Using that same
approach, Ten later started its NASCAR Racing Online Series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This moves appealed to Ten's original audience of hard-core
gamers and lined up about $3 million in sponsorship money.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hachenburg and his management team knew the PGL had to
reach beyond hard-core gamers. ``We figured we had to do something
different,'' said Hachenburg, who replaced Ten's original CEO, Jack
Heistand, in December 1997. ``When you're facing life or death, it
forces you into doing something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hachenburg helped devise a new business plan that featured
online versions of familiar, time-tested games like spades, hearts,
chess, crossword puzzles and Jumble. Ten was following a trend that
showed that fans of those games were the fastest-growing segment of
online gamers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ten moved to broaden its audience by offering these
parlor games on a ``Family Games Network'' to as many Internet
sites as it could sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Hachenburg had to sell this unique but unproven strategy to
Ten's investors, which include Kleiner Perkins Caulfield and Byers,
Ameritech, the Carlyle Group and Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the better part of December 1997 and January 1998
convincing existing investors to support the company and its new
business plan,'' Hachenburg said.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts paid off. By February 1998, Ten had lined up an
additional $8 million in financing to give Ten time and money ``to
reposition the business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of TEN10 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  With some elbow room to operate, Ten started to line up exclusive
agreements with Internet portals, starting with Excite last May.
</P>
<P>
   Under these agreements, Ten's computers host free parlor games,
without players having to leave the Internet site they initially
visit.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the competition can start as soon as the player
clicks the Ten logo on the Netcenter Web site. Meanwhile, the other
player may be logged to Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   During the game, the player on Netcenter will see that Web
site's advertising. The same is true for the Cnet player.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenues are split 50-50 &UR;  &LR; between Ten and the
Internet sites. Hachenburg said the Ten player tends to remain
online for 60 minutes, providing the sort of staying power, or
``stickiness,'' that Internet sites and advertisers highly desire.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kraus, senior vice-president and co-founder of Internet
directory Excite Inc., said the format works. ``Excite lives and
dies by its ability to attract and retain customers,'' he noted.
``We use gaming to build loyalty''.
</P>
<P>
   For Ten, the demographics of parlor game players is much broader
than hard-core gamers, who tend to be 90 percent male and mostly
under the age of 24. The company says about 52 percent of its
parlor game players are women, 64 percent of whom are between 18
and 49.
</P>
<P>
   That profile is important to a site like the Station, which is
picking up Ten's parlor games. The online game site offers its 2.5
million registered users the Internet version of TV classics such
as ``Jeopardy,'' ``Wheel of Fortune'' and, coming soon, ``The
Dating Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten has a good slate of games that will benefit our program
slate,'' said Lisa Simpson, president of Sony Online Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Since adopting the Family Games Network idea, Ten's game playing
audience has grown dramatically, though it still is below
competitors like MPath and Microsoft's Internet Gaming Zone, each
of which have 2 million or more registered players.
</P>
<P>
   Ten spokesman Garth Chouteau said the peak number of players
online at any one time has nearly doubled from 4,500 in early
December to 9,500 this month. That compares with 20,000 peak users
on Yahoo's game site.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in players has been enough for Ten to attract at least
20 new advertisers, including Intel Corp. and Disney.com. And
there's the ``Pepsi One Casual Lounge,'' a cardroom with the
beverage giant's logo emblazoned on the backs of the virtual
playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of TEN10 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although Hachenburg declined to reveal specifics, he said the
company expects revenues to double in the next two years and hopes
to finally turn a profit late next year. Advertising from parlor
games should account for about 75 percent of the Ten's revenue
stream by next year.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, the online game industry still is not mature
enough to be profitable, said Forrester analyst Seema Williams. One
of Ten's original competitors, Dwango, another subscriber-based
online game service based in Houston, folded its cards last
October.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too early to tell whether the mass-market approach
will work in the long run, Ten's prognosis is at least better than
before, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is happening is that more (players)
continue to come online,'' Williams said. ```Once they play (online
games), they tend to bring friends and family, and it turns
somewhat habitual.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten, which has corralled the most-popular Internet portals
except Yahoo and MSN, which run their own games, is now targeting
smaller sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Market share is everything,'' said George Jones,
editor-in-chief of Computer Gaming World magazine in San Francisco.
``What they're doing is brilliant. They've done a great job of
reinventing themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of TEN10 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
