<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MCI Appeals FCC Ruling That Calls to the Net Are Long-Distance  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MCI WorldCom Corp. is challenging the Federal Communication
Commission's ruling that says calls to the Internet are
long-distance instead of local.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's ruling could prevent Baby Bell competitors such as
MCI from collecting hundreds of millions of dollars from regional
phone companies like Pacific Bell. &UR;  &LR; The decision also could lead to
higher costs for consumers who use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MCI filed an appeal of the ruling late Monday with the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, arguing that the
FCC's decision should be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the decision is arbitrary and capricious,'' said
Peter Lucht, a spokesman for MCI. ``We've expressed concerns for a
while that classifying dial-up calls to the Internet as interstate
could possibly lead to higher costs for Internet service providers
and, in turn, for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies also are expected to appeal the FCC's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's ruling exempts local phone companies, such as
Pacific Bell, from paying hefty fees to competitors such as MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1996 Telecommunications Act, local phone companies are
obligated to pay one another for completing competitors' local
calls. For example, if a Pac Bell customer calls a business that
uses MCI for local phone service, Pac Bell pays MCI for
``terminating'' the call.
</P>
<P>
   The fee, called ``reciprocal compensation,'' is supposed to help
phone companies maintain their networks so that they are capable of
receiving calls from other phone providers.
</P>
<P>
   Many competing local phone companies, such as MCI, provide phone
service to Internet service providers. Because the traffic to ISPs
is one way _ from the caller to the ISP _ the incumbent local phone
companies have been paying millions of dollars to their competitors
for terminating those calls.
</P>
<P>
   But the same rules don't apply to long-distance calls, so the
FCC's decision could prevent companies like MCI from collecting
money from incumbent local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Without that revenue, some companies could be forced to pass
along the costs to ISPs. Critics of the FCC's decision fear that
ISPs then could pass along the costs to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Lucht said MCI considers the decision unfair and wants a court
to take a look at the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We receive a lot of money from reciprocal compensation. ... We
want this decision to be reviewed,'' Lucht said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
