<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tech Giants Betting on Leader of Linux  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Four more technology powers have taken minority stakes in Red Hat
Software, bolstering the company's position as the leading purveyor
of the Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The investments by IBM, Compaq Computer, Novell and Oracle,
which were announced yesterday, come on top of similar investments
in Red Hat by Intel and Netscape Communications (before it was
acquired by America Online). The amounts were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   All the heavyweight investors are betting that Linux, which is
freely available on the World Wide Web, eventually will pose a
challenge to Microsoft's Windows NT to run servers and
workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Linux's ease-of-use and reliability already have attracted more
than 10 million users worldwide, and it was the fastest-growing
operating system for computer networks last year, according to
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Red Hat, based in Research Triangle, N.C., has
capitalized on the Linux craze by selling a packaged version of the
software and by backing up the product with service and support _
benefits that don't usually come with free software.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the challenges that Linux has had to address has been
credibility in the corporate environment,'' said analyst Chris
LeTocq of Dataquest. ``What Red Hat is selling is the idea that
they will be on the other end of the phone when a company needs
service.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenal success of Linux, and Red Hat's leadership in the
new market, have prompted a number of technology giants to embrace
its technology. Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Compaq and Dell all have said
they will ship Red Hat Linux with their PCs and workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the investments announced yesterday could extend
Red Hat's market lead over Caldera Systems, based in Orem, Utah,
Germany's SuSE and other private firms that sell Linux packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Hat will become the premiere flavor of Linux,'' said Jon
Oltsik of Forrester Research, adding that ``this puts Caldera in a
really bad position of becoming a second-tier version of Linux.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Young, co-founder and chief executive of Red Hat, said
the company was happy to have Compaq, IBM, Novell and Oracle as
equity partners ``because of their leadership positions in the
computing industry. Their support of Red Hat is a broad endorsement
of the (free software) model that is changing the entire software
industry and driving the rapid adoption of Linux.''
</P>
<P>
   Although its most visible target is Windows NT, Linux also
competes with forms of the Unix operating system made by companies
such as IBM and HP. In fact, said Oltsik, only Sun Microsystems'
version of Unix, called Solaris, may be strong enough to fend off
Linux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun is in good position, but everyone else is pretty much
behind the eight ball,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
