A4056 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LEWIS-LADN     03-09 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS TO GET BIG CHANCE TO PROVE HIMSELF SATURDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No heart.
</P>
<P>
   That is what the critics say about Lennox Lewis. Always have.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing is, there appears to be no reason for such
criticism. Lewis is 34-1 with 27 knockouts. He has made four
defenses of the WBC title he won back from Oliver McCall in
February of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow he gets blamed for others' unwillingness to fight
him.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Lewis' fault that Riddick Bowe gave up his WBC
heavyweight belt in 1992 rather than fight him.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Lewis' fault that in 1996 Mike Tyson paid Lewis, the
mandatory challenger to Frank Bruno for the WBC title, $4 million
to step aside so he could fight Bruno. After beating Bruno, Tyson
vacated the belt rather than fight Lewis. Instead, Tyson fought the
much weaker Bruce Seldon for the WBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has always wanted the ultimate heavyweight championship
bout, the kind that proves points and defines careers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at Madison Square Garden, Lewis finally will get
what his trainer, Emanuel Steward, says will be his one big
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In challenging WBA and IBF champion Evander Holyfield, Lewis
will get the chance to show his courage and anything else it might
take to place him atop that pedestal of boxing eminence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it amusing in one sense and I find it offensive in
another sense,'' Lewis said. ``How dare anybody question my heart?
I have never shown anybody I don't have heart. You have to have
heart in the first place to step into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander Holyfield does not have the monopoly on heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has been unable to find the career-defining fight
until now, Lewis has shown his mettle. On Halloween night, 1992,
the 21-0 Lewis faced the hard-hitting Razor Ruddock, who was
heavily favored.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis knocked out Ruddock in the second round. The winner was
supposed to get a shot at the winner of the Bowe-Holyfield fight,
which was held just two weeks later. Bowe won, then relinquished
the belt.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the fight that proved Lewis' heart most was his
grueling 10-round decision over Ray Mercer in 1996 at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis took punishment; his face was battered and swollen. But he
won the later rounds in courageous fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that fight was living proof that Lennox Lewis has
heart,'' Lewis' promoter, Dino Duva, said. ``Ray Mercer fought the
fight of his life that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime trainer/commentator Gil Clancy believes Lewis has
heart, but hasn't utilized it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hired Emanuel Steward, who is a fine trainer, to be
his trainer a couple of years ago, it looked like he would become
one of the best heavyweight champions in a long time,'' Clancy
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've told Lennox, `You haven't improved one iota. You are
the same Lennox Lewis you always were.' I think that kind of got
him riled.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lewis: ``They ought to call him `Gil Can't-see.' He has
never even seen me train.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward has not exactly been overwhelmingly positive in
assessing Lewis, either. He calls both Holyfield and Lewis
inconsistent in title bouts, but adds ``tentative'' to Lewis'
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is more of a distant fighter; he uses his strength
better,'' said Steward when asked to compare Lewis to Bowe, who is
also 6-foot-5 and defeated Holyfield twice. ``But Lennox has had
his tentativeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Lennox come out tentatively, like he did against (Zeljko)
Mavrovic (in a distance-going title defense last September)? Or
will he come out aggressive like he did against (Andrew) Golota (in
a first-round knockout in October 1997)?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Steward expects his man to knock out Holyfield,
perhaps by the fifth round. The emotions that are running through
each fighter as the bout approaches will make Lewis show his
aggressiveness from the start, Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 33, had better, Steward said, because he will probably
never get an opportunity like this again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how anyone can be as hungry as Lennox Lewis at
this time,'' Steward said. ``Evander Holyfield has been in a lot of
big fights. This is (Lewis') whole career right here, as far as I'm
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been trying so hard to get a major fight, but after
this, this is it. There are no other big fights. He is going into
this with his eyes wide open. He knows he needs to win this fight
if he is going to be considered among the great heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been asking a lot of questions, studying a lot of film.
So he's doing everything he can.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's Lewis' time. So says the Brit with the heart in
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, I think this is my time,'' Lewis said. ``The
rwAqon I wasn't able to put my stamp on (the heavyweight division)
before, whether it was politics or whatever, this is my time to put
my stamp on it for this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has been waiting for this unification and it's
going to help me prove that I'm the best heavyweight on the
planet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
