<HEADER>
A4057 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      03-09 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editors: Note ``underscore'' in Web address should be
replaced  with keystroke)   Column: Good, Bad Tax News For Startups 
 &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  What tax breaks are available to someone starting a
business? There are a lot of costs before any revenue rolls in.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The good news is that you may qualify for significant
deductions for startup expenses. The bad news is that it's a
cumbersome process and that you can't write off the costs all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Startup costs, including what you pay to investigate creating or
purchasing a business, are called ``capital expenses.'' The
California Society of CPAs says you may elect to amortize these
startup costs over a period of 60 months, commencing the month the
business begins, if they meet the following tests:
</P>
<P>
   _The costs would be deductible if they were paid or incurred by
an existing business in the same field.
</P>
<P>
   _They are paid or incurred before you actually begin business
operations.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Internal Revenue Service, legitimate expenses
include: surveys of potential markets; analyses of available
facilities, labor and supplies; travel and other necessary costs to
secure distributors, supplies or customers; advertisements for the
opening of the business; salaries and wages for employees who are
being trained; and fees for consultant and professional services.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, for example, you are starting a catering business
with startup expenses totaling $12,000. After landing your first
catering job in July, you can amortize all previous expenses and
begin deducting $200 per month for five years ($12,000 divided by
60 months). That means during the first year of business, you can
deduct $1,200 (July through December) and $2,400 for the following
first full year of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you want to amortize your startup expenses, you must
elect to do so by the tax return due date (including extensions)
for the year your business actively begins. If you wait another
year, you're out of luck. ``You do it right or lose it,'' said CPA
Craig Malmgren of Oakland's Lautze &AMP; Lautze Accountancy Corp.
``There's no safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the deduction, you must include a description of
the expenses, the amounts, the dates they were incurred, the month
in which the business began and the number of months in the
amortization period. Sole proprietors, partners and
limited-liability company members claim these deductions on IRS
Form 4562, Depreciation and Amortization.
</P>
<P>
   If you sell or otherwise dump your business before the end of
the amortization period, the startup costs that you have not yet
deducted may be deducted to the extent that they qualify as a
business loss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  However, if you never actually opened for business, the rules
are different. You must divide startup costs into two categories.
Those costs associated with market analysis or preliminary
investigation become personal expenses and are not deductible if
you are not organized as a corporation. Other startup expenses may
be deducted as a business loss in the year that your attempt to go
into business fails.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW10 (80974 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Self-Employment Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am retired, age 67, and last year earned $1,700 for two
weeks' work as a consultant. As a self-employed person, must I pay
taxes on my consulting work?
</P>
<P>
   A: Alas, you must. If you are self-employed and have more than
$400 earned income, you owe self-employment tax. ``The
self-employment tax is really Social Security and Medicare tax for
the self-employed,'' says CPA Sharon Kreider of Sunnyvale. If you
work for someone else, you pay 7.65 percent and your employer pays
a matching amount. If you are self-employed, you pay both amounts,
or 15.3 percent of net income.
</P>
<P>
   You will need to file the $1,700 of income on your Schedule C as
well as Form SE, where you compute the self-employment tax. (The
Social Security tax is 12.4 percent of profits up to $65,400. The
2.9 percent Medicare tax applies to all profits.)
</P>
<P>
   If your total income is more than $8,000, excluding Social
Security benefits, then you also will have to pay federal income
tax. (If you do have to pay income tax, half of the self-employment
tax you pay can be deducted from taxable income.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAX FORMS: &LR;  Here are toll-free phone numbers and Web sites
where you can send for or download current federal and California
tax forms and schedules:
</P>
<P>
   _Internal Revenue Service _ (800) 829-3676;
 &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/forms(UNDERSCORE)pubs/forms.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _California Franchise Tax Board _ (800) 338-0505;
 &LR; www.ftb.ca.gov/forms &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _California Board of Equalization _ (800) 400-7115;
 &LR; www.boe.ca.gov/boelist.htm &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There also are plenty of business startup books and tax guides
that come with business and tax forms, either printed or on
CD-ROMs. Make sure these are current. Two big publishers are IDG
Books Worldwide and its ``Dummies'' titles ( &LR; www.dummies.com &LR; ) and
Nolo Press ( &LR; www.nolo.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLARIFICATION: &LR;  Regarding an item in last week's column: The
standard mileage rate is 32.5 cents for 1998. The scheduled
reduction to 31 cents per mile won't occur until after March 31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
