<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RJR NABISCO TO SPIN OFF ITS TOBACCO OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the twin burdens of debt and the persistent threat of
smoking lawsuits, RJR Nabisco announced that it was splitting up
its food and tobacco businesses and selling its foreign tobacco
operations to the Japanese. The company will pay down most of its
debt and effectively remove itself from the tobacco business in
hopes of appeasing shareholders, but the changes unravel one of the
biggest mergers and most fought-over leveraged buyouts of the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL AND DISNEY LEAD STOCKS LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks declined, led lower by concern about the performance of
Intel and Walt Disney. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 33.85
points, or four-tenths of a percent, to 9,693.76. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index declined 2.89 points, or two-tenths of a
percent, to 1,279.84. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 4.68, to
2,392.94.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rose as the yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury
fell to 5.53 percent from 5.59 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   SONY SEEKS TO REINVENT ITSELF
</P>
<P>
   In an extensive overhaul, Sony, one of Japan's truly global
companies, plans to reinvent itself using a combination of enduring
strength in consumer electronics and emerging high technology. ``In
the last three years, we have made a lot of effort to move from
being a `box' company to becoming an information technology
company,'' said Nobuyuki Idei, Sony's president. ``I think we've
had a fair amount of success.''
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN SEEN PAYING OFF UNIT'S DEBT
</P>
<P>
   Eager to resolve a sticking point in merger negotiations with
DaimlerChrysler, Nissan Motor, the world's sixth-largest automaker,
plans to announce that it is paying off debts at a troubled unit,
people close to Nissan said.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SETTLEMENT TALKS DENIED
</P>
<P>
   With the Microsoft antitrust trial now in a six-week recess, no
settlement talks are under way, a person close to the case said. A
report by The Seattle Times that Microsoft and the Government were
``exploring ways'' to settle led to a morning rally in Microsoft
stock.
</P>
<P>
   IVILLAGE ACCOUNTING IS CRITICIZED
</P>
<P>
   Just days before the planned initial public offering of
iVillage, a New York Internet service for women, a former chief
financial officer of the company has filed court documents accusing
iVillage of ``inappropriate'' accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   FLUOR TO CUT 5,000 JOBS IN OVERHAUL
</P>
<P>
   Fluor, the nation's largest engineering and construction
company, said it would cut 5,000 employees, reorganize its
operations and narrow its range of projects. Shares of the company,
which has been suffering from the Asian economic crisis and its own
bloated cost structure, fell $1.75, to $34.3125. The stock price is
near its 12-month low of $33.25.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH FIRM EXECUTIVE REJOINS FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years after founding what would become one of the
nation's largest executive search firms, Russell S. Reynolds Jr. is
at it again. Mr. Reynolds, 67, has merged his current business with
a small New York search firm and plans to begin recruiting
corporate directors and senior executives.
</P>
<P>
   USA TODAY NAMES NEW EDITOR
</P>
<P>
   USA Today, the nation's largest newspaper, promoted Karen
Jurgensen, editor of the editorial page, to editor, succeeding
David Mazzarella, 60, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTIVITY UP 4.6 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Workers' productivity shot up 4.6 percent in the fourth quarter,
for the fastest growth pace in six years. The report eased concerns
that the Fed might raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   HEINZ PROFIT MEETS FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz, one of the world's leading food processors, posted
third-quarter operating profit in line with estimates and said it
was on track to meet expectations for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
