<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Microsoft, U.S. Deal May Be Possible  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The pretrial settlement of an antitrust suit between Intel Corp.
and the government fueled reports yesterday that Microsoft Corp.
and the U.S. Justice Department are negotiating a settlement of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Seattle Times, quoting unnamed sources close to the
negotiations, said Microsoft and Justice officials were talking
about a possible agreement to end the government's landmark
antitrust suit against the software firm. But later in the day,
Reuters quoted a government lawyer saying there were no talks going
on.
</P>
<P>
   Both Microsoft and the Justice Department declined to comment on
reports that they had renewed talks about a settlement that would
end the antitrust trial that began last October. The trial, now in
recess before each side calls rebuttal witnesses, is set to resume
April 12.
</P>
<P>
   But Caroline Boren, a Microsoft spokeswoman, said the company
remains open to government proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government hasn't made any good-faith attempts to settle
this in any matter that wouldn't violate the fundamental principles
of the marketplace, such as Microsoft's right to continue
innovating new products,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said that even if Microsoft and the government are
indeed talking during the recess, there is little chance of a full
settlement, given the complexity of the issues and the fact that
the trial is nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bet the house that some discussions are taking
place,'' said Hillard Sterling, a Chicago antitrust attorney.
``During a trial, parties don't ignore each other during a long
recess, particularly when external developments suggest the
reasonableness of settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he said a partial settlement on some minor issues was
possible, Sterling did not expect an accord on the major issues of
the government's case that Microsoft abused its monopoly powers to
stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MICROSOF (5428 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Both sides have gone too far along in this passionate, divisive
battle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel averted an antitrust trial that was scheduled to start
yesterday by agreeing to a proposed settlement with the Federal
Trade Commission. Terms of the settlement won't be disclosed until
FTC commissioners approve it, which may take two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Dwight Davis of Summit Research said Microsoft might
agree to a settlement that would, for example, prevent it from
forcing exclusive contracts on computer-makers like Compaq. The
government has tried to prove Microsoft used strong-arm tactics on
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft would not agree to a settlement that would force a
breakup of the Redmond, Wash., company or one that would open
Windows software code to developers, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Balderston, an analyst with Zona Research Inc. in Redwood
City, has a novel theory on the case. He speculated that
Microsoft's ``apparent nonchalance'' in handling the case is a ploy
to force the government to split it up into different companies
that could focus on specific markets, like Internet content and
consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's defense, which many legal analysts contend the
company bungled with poor videotape presentations and conflicting
testimony, may actually indicate the company's interest in a forced
breakup, Balderston said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock rose $2.81 to close at $161.81.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
