<HEADLINE>
WEN HO LEE: THIS MAN IS THE TALK OF LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-NUKE) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, New Mexico _ To his next-door neighbors of 20 years,
Wen Ho Lee is a generous man who shares plums from his backyard
orchard and brings over steaming plates of Peking duck on
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   To a nuclear weapons scientist familiar with his work, ``Lee was
a behind-the-barn scientist,'' who was ``never out front
interfacing with the public or the government.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the FBI, Lee is the prime suspect in a damaging spy case,
one that federal investigators say helped China leapfrog a
generation of nuclear weapons research and develop lighter, more
powerful bombs that can be launched from submarines or placed in
groups on land-based missiles.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson fired Lee from the
Los Alamos National Laboratory for security breaches. He has not
been charged with any crime, but on Tuesday the allegations cast a
shadow over Barcelona Avenue, the quiet suburban street where Lee
and his wife, Sylvia, built their house more than 20 years ago.
With photographers staking out the house on Tuesday, hoping to snap
pictures of the couple, the Lees hired a Los Angeles lawyer,
refused to answer their doorbell, and disconnected their phone. The
Lees' two children, Alberta and Tse Chung, who work in scientific
fields in Ohio and North Carolina, did not return calls left on
Tuesday at their work places.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is either a very, very good actor, or he is not your man,''
Don Marshall, a lab worker, said, staunchly defending his longtime
neighbor as reporters gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Marshall, his wife, added: ``There was talk around the lab
today. Who is it? Who is it? I just can't believe it is him.''
</P>
<P>
   As other neighbors and lab workers spoke in Lee's defense, their
words seemed to reveal the ambiguities of the post Cold War era,
when international scientific cooperation is the mantra, and
enemies are cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Built as a forbidden city to develop the atom bomb during World
War II, this government town was closed to the public until 1957.
Sentry boxes guarded the sole entrance, a two-lane road that
climbed to an isolated, 7,400- foot plateau. After the bomb was
used on Japan, Los Alamos became a mirror of the Soviet Union's
secret atomic cities, banning private land ownership until 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember hearing about a scientist in the 1950s, who used to
take paper and pencils home from the lab to his kids,'' recalled
Bill Redmond, a Republican who represented this district in
Congress until his defeat last fall. ``One day, a government moving
van rolled up to his door, and they asked him, `where do you want
to go?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, as Tuesday morning's newspapers carried front page
headlines about the spy charges, breakfast tables at the Holiday
Inn on Trinity Avenue were occupied by members of a Russian
delegation, their plastic visitors' badges clipped to their suit
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought China was part of the club now,'' a nuclear
scientist in Washington said of changing perceptions of friends and
enemies. ``It could be this guy was a little ahead of his time, or
he could be a bona fide spy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Barcelona Avenue, there is the same confusion. ``The security
is always tight in terms of someone trying to sneak in from the
outside, but once you get in they give classes on nuclear weapon
design,'' said Bill Partain, a nuclear engineer, who worked until
recently at the laboratory with Mrs. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, two other Taiwan-born scientists of Lee's
generation lost their jobs after federal investigators suspected
that they had passed secrets from the laboratory here to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was born in Taiwan in 1939, near the end of half a century
of Japanese rule of the island. His neighbor, Marshall, said, ``He
said he could remember the Japanese occupation of the island.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lee earned his bachelor of science degree in engineering
from Taiwan Provincial Cheng Kung University in 1963, he joined a
flow of Taiwan's college graduates seeking higher technical
education in the the United States. In the spring of 1965, he
enrolled at Texas A&AMP;M University, earning his master's degree in
engineering in 1966 and his doctorate in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a pretty good hard worker,'' recalled C.F.
Kettleborough, a Texas A&AMP;M mechanical engineering professor.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors recall that the Lees moved here in the late 1970s.
During their years in New Mexico, the Lees put their two children
through college, and managed to buy two houses in an Albuquerque
suburb's investment properties.
</P>
<P>
   At the 44-square-mile laboratory here, Lee gradually moved into
more sensitive areas. One scientist in Washington who is familiar
with Lee's work said that in the late 1980s, he began working in
the area of nuclear weapons design that looks at the triggering
mechanism of thermonuclear bombs.how the primary bomb triggers the
secondary, thermonuclear, bomb. This scientist said, ``He was a
classic staff scientist, not in management, quietly working away.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors remember the couple visiting Beijing in 1985. They
were active in the Los Alamos Chinese Cultural Association, a small
social group made up largely of immigrants from Taiwan that holds
Chinese celebrations and teaches Chinese character writing to
children at the library.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
