A4083 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-ART-     03-09 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
FACED WITH DEBT AND LAWSUITS, RJR NABISCO SPLITS FOOD AND TOBACCO
BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
 RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-ART-2TAKES-NYT  (See also: RJR-NABISCO-TERMS, RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL, RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN,
RJR-NABISCO-LBO, RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH, RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: 3 graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with the twin burdens of debt and the
persistent threat of lawsuits over smoking, RJR Nabisco announced
Tuesday that it was splitting its food and tobacco businesses and
selling its foreign tobacco company to a Japanese buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The moves will let the company pay down most of its debt and
effectively remove itself from the tobacco business in hopes of
appeasing shareholders. But the changes unravel one of the biggest
mergers and most fought-over leveraged buyouts of the 1980s, one
that became a symbol of the decade's excesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, eager to raise the company's share price, RJR Nabisco's
management announced a plan to take the company private for $17
billion. That move attracted other would-be owners, including the
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts investment firm, which ultimately bid the
price up to $30 billion. The entire deal relied on junk bonds,
which left the company with a mountain of debt. The saga inspired a
best-seller, ``Barbarians at the Gate,'' which also became a
television movie. In early 1991, KKR sold stock in the company back
to the public to reduce its debt.
</P>
<P>
   But with the changes announced Tuesday, Steven F. Goldstone, the
chairman and chief executive of RJR Nabisco, acknowledged that
mixing the maker of Oreos and Nilla Wafers with the maker of
Winston cigarettes had not worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for these businesses to be under the same
roof,'' he said. ``They are very different enterprises, with
different problems, different challenges and different investor
groups.'' People should have ``the opportunity to choose whether
they want to invest in a tobacco company or a food company,'' he
added, acknowledging the ``tobacco taint'' that many analysts have
described at Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic tobacco will become a separate company, which will be
responsible for any smoking-related claims in the United States.
The holding company will continue to own the food business and
could be liable for claims if the domestic tobacco company goes
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The international tobacco division, perennially smaller and
weaker than its rivals, is being sold to Japan Tobacco, which is
controlled by the government, for $8 billion, considered a hefty
price by even the most optimistic stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts are intended to bolster what has been a chronically
depressed stock price. Wall Street responded cautiously, sending
RJR's share price up a mere 75 cents to close at $29.375, although
it initially rose nearly $2 a share following the early-morning
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Philip Morris also rose slightly, by 62.5 cents, with
some investors betting it would separate its tobacco and food
operations as well. A spokesman for Philip Morris said the company
had decided against that option in 1994 and had not changed its
mind.
</P>
<P>
   RJR's foreign sale, which is expected to be completed by
mid-May, will shore up the domestic tobacco company, which will be
known as R.J. Reynolds Tobacco. Most of the $5 billion in after-tax
proceeds from the sale will be used to pay down that company's
debt, now about $6 billion, said Marc Cohen, who follows stocks of
tobacco companies for Goldman, Sachs. ``It will then have a very
conservatively managed and strong financial position,'' he said,
calling the spinoff ``a very bold move.''
</P>
<P>
   Current investors in RJR Nabisco will also receive one share of
the tobacco company for each share they own in a transaction that
will be tax free to shareholders and the company.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco will remain a holding company, with its sole asset
the 80.6 percent of Nabisco that it now owns. Since it will no
longer own any part of the tobacco company, it will be renamed
Nabisco Group Holdings. Most of its 90 or so employees at its
headquarters in New York will be laid off. A few corporate officers
of Nabisco Group Holdings will have similar titles at Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4084 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-A     03-09 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
 NEW YORK: at Nabisco.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in smoking lawsuits would be able to sue the holding
company, several experts said Tuesday, should the tobacco company
be unable to meet its obligations. But with a reduced debt load,
the free-standing tobacco company will be in a stronger financial
position.
</P>
<P>
   John Coale, a lawyer in Washington, D.C., who is involved in
lawsuits against R.J. Reynolds, said he did not foresee the new
corporate structure interfering with his cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all past conduct and present litigation, they are not off
the hook,'' he said. ``We would try to put Humpty Dumpty together
again and then we would collect.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstone noted that the original plan had failed.
``Unfortunately, it didn't work out that way,'' he said. ``Then
you've got to try something else.''
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco holds 80.6 percent of Nabisco's shares, and the
remainder of the stock is held by the public. While the public's
shares were trading at $45 yesterday, the stock price of RJR
Nabisco was less than $30. When the tobacco companies are spun off
and sold, Cohen predicted, shares in RJR should rise closer to $45.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Icahn, the corporate takeover specialist who has repeatedly
bought and sold big stakes in RJR, re-entered the picture this
winter and threatened to nominate his own board of directors by
this Friday if the company did not spin off the food unit. Pressure
from Icahn was not a motivating factor, Goldstone said. ``It would
be Carl's third attempt up the wall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the lawsuits brought by the Attorneys General of dozens of
states were resolved last year in a $206 billion industry
settlement, Goldstone said, his priority was ``finding a home'' for
the international tobacco business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find a value for our shareholders that was high
enough to fix the balance sheet of our tobacco business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Tobacco agreed to pay a 33 percent premium for the
international tobacco division, which had been valued at about $6
billion. Japan Tobacco's chief long-term strategist, Yasushi
Shingai, said in an interview that he did not feel the price was
too high. ``These are very strong and prestigious brands, and there
is a lot of potential to grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the deal, Japan Tobacco will vault from the fifth-biggest
to the third-biggest global cigarette maker and gain a presence in
Western Europe and Russia, among other markets. Its revenues last
year were $27.2 billion, and its holdings include pharmaceuticals
and food as well as tobacco products. It also controls Japan's
largest vending-machine company, a key asset in a country where
many consumer products are sold that way. Formed in 1985 after
privatization, Japan Tobacco owns Japan's biggest-selling cigarette
brand, Mild Seven, and makes Marlboro cigarettes locally for Philip
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the company was concerned about liability from
smokers' lawsuits, Shingai replied: ``We have three pending
litigations, but the law system and the culture are very different
than in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation yesterday about a possible sequel to
the story, particularly if Nabisco becomes a takeover target again.
``Somebody like Philip Morris may find them appetizing,'' said Gary
M. Black, who tracks tobacco stocks for Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ABORTION-COX     03-09 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ABORTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pro-life activists support Bush's parental notification bill
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The anti-abortion lawmakers and activists who
gathered on the Capitol steps Tuesday wanted to make one thing
clear: They weren't there to ban abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here today to argue Roe versus Wade. Like it or
not, it's the law of the land,'' said Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower
Mound.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Nelson, Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington, and
representatives of the Texas Christian Coalition and the Texas
Right to Life Committee supported bills that would require parental
notification or consent before doctors perform abortions on minors.
The Senate Human Services Committee is scheduled to consider
several notification and consent bills today.
</P>
<P>
   The comments echoed recent remarks by Gov. George W. Bush _
remarks that have spurred some religious conservatives to attack
Bush's stance as lukewarm. Bush, who is almost certainly running
for president, said Monday that he is a ``pro-life person'' but
wouldn't push a constitutional amendment banning abortion because
most Americans aren't ready to support it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush said, the focus should be on attainable goals such
as parental notification and consent bills.
</P>
<P>
   The activists on the Capitol steps pointedly refrained from
criticizing Bush's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to discuss parental notification legislation. We
haven't discussed anything further during the legislative session
with the governor,'' said Chuck Anderson of the Texas Christian
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson noted that at the state level, abortion opponents can't
go much further than consent and notification bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts say that women should have legal access to
abortion, and there's nothing that I can do about that as a state
senator. I'm trumped by a higher authority,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential candidate Gary Bauer acknowledged that Bush
can't go further on the state level _ but he expects more from him
if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's's answer was the answer of a politician, not
someone who wants the party of Lincoln and Reagan to be unambiguous
on this issue,'' said Bauer, who promised that as president he'd
appoint only anti-abortion Supreme Court justices and would submit
a constitutional amendment banning abortions within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Texas notification and consent bills say they
would restore parental rights and reduce the number of teenage
pregnancies and abortions. They also say that the bills would put
abortion on a par with other major medical procedures, which
require parental consent. The bills include a provision allowing
teenagers in abusive families to get consent from a judge instead
of a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is not about abortion, it's about parenting. Minor
children are not adults _they don't think like adults, they don't
behave like adults and they don't make decisions like adults,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say girls who are afraid to tell their parents
that they are pregnant will resort to illegal, and dangerous,
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've carefully picked issues that market well to mainstream
public,'' said Kae McLaughlin of the Texas Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League. ``They know the reality of
mandated parental involvement is that young women will seek illegal
abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
