A4088 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARIZONA-PARK-AZR &LR;      03-09 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-PARK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED PARK WOULD BE BIGGER THAN YELLOWSTONE, GRAND CANYON
COMBINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SETH LANDAU  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It's more than 3 million acres of federal land in
southwestern Arizona with no timber, cattle-grazing or mining
rights. Its only official tenant is the Air Force, which uses a
fraction of it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a perfect opportunity, says a group of self-proclaimed
active thinkers, to turn a huge chunk of desert into the premier
desert park in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Broyles, leader of the drive to create a Sonoran Desert
National Park, has put together a group of environmentally minded
professionals to support the cause, which is formally tabbed a
``citizens proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoran Desert National Park supporters, including Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt and former Interior Secretary Stewart
Udall, want to combine three areas to create the state's fourth
national park.
</P>
<P>
   Those areas: Organ Pipe National Monument, administered by the
National Park Service; Cabeza Prieta National Wildlife Refuge,
overseen by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service; and the Barry M.
Goldwater Air Force Range, managed by the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoran Desert National Park would be bigger than
Yellowstone and Grand Canyon national parks combined. It would be
open to camping, hiking, hunting and other amenities, which much of
the land offers now.
</P>
<P>
   Making it a park, supporters say, would protect it from illegal
dumping, off-roading and destruction of archaeological sites.
</P>
<P>
   Broyles, a Tucson freelance writer, said he has received a
positive response from the National Park and U.S. Fish and Wildlife
services. Representatives from both agencies said Tuesday they
cannot comment now.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department also said it can't comment on the
proposal, which would change the lease on the Goldwater Range.
Broyles said he believes military officials are interested.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative was first introduced to Congress in 1968 by
Udall, then secretary of the Interior. It was shot down by
President Lyndon Johnson and mostly forgotten after that.
</P>
<P>
   The latest push was made public earlier this week with the
release of a detailed brochure, which called for the process to be
completed within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers have submitted their plans to Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., among other government officials. The creation of a
national park requires the approval of the House, Senate and
president.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason the group reintroduced the plan now is to
coincide with the renewal of the lease of the Goldwater Range, used
by pilots from Phoenix, Tucson and Yuma.
</P>
<P>
   Broyles said the lease will expire between December 1999 and
January 2001. His group is asking for a transfer of the lease from
the Defense Department to the National Parks Service.
</P>
<P>
   Parks officials would allow representatives of the military to
stay at the Goldwater Range until they are ready to leave. After
that, the land would be officially part of the proposed park.
</P>
<P>
   The range covers about 1.8 million acres. The group says the Air
Force uses less than 10 percent of the land, mostly for bombing
drills. The Air Force uses all the airspace above the range.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan succeeds, group members say, the 5,000 square &UR; miles
will be better managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most biologically extravagant desert in North
America,'' said Charles Bowden, a Tucson writer who backs the park.
He said the land would have more resources if backed by National
Park Service coffers.
</P>
<P>
   The three areas are hampered by environmentally harmful
activity, Broyles said, and some archaeological sites have been
trashed, sometimes unwittingly.
</P>
<P>
   Although the formation of a national park would not stop all
such activity, Broyles said, it would give the land more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought (the land) would be magically preserved and I
didn't have to do anything,'' Bowden said, ``then I wouldn't do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The group estimates that less than $1 million is spent annually
for the upkeep of the three areas. Broyles did not know how much
the federal government would spend on upkeep if it becomes a
national park. &QL; 
Seth Landau can be reached at 444-4883 or at seth.landau(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
