<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH-NYT     03-09 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TOBACCO COUNTRY, TIMES HAVE CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP, RJR-NABISCO-TERMS,
RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL, RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN, RJR-NABISCO-LBO,
RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE) 
(mk) 
 By BARLOW HERGET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ In the old days, when R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co. made a big announcement, civic and business leaders
here where the company started more than 100 years ago met with
Reynolds officials to learn about the news. The announcement
Tuesday reflected the changing times for tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about it on the radio,'' said Alderman Wanda Merschel,
vice president for branch administration at Lexington State Bank.
``A representative from Reynolds called about 10:30. He had tried
to reach me earlier. My biggest reaction was that I didn't have a
big reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The news _ that the conglomerate RJR Nabisco was splitting up
its food and tobacco businesses and selling its foreign tobacco
company to the Japanese _ struck a similar note among other
community leaders. John Gates, editorial page editor of The
Winston-Salem Journal, said: ``It was inevitable. It's been in the
works for a long time. We knew it was going to happen.'' David
Ibister, a retired R.J. Reynolds senior vice president and now
business lecturer at Wake Forest University here, added, ``It's not
a huge surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Lyons Gray, a Republican whose family has long been
associated with R.J. Reynolds, spent most of his day on state
tobacco settlement legislation. He said Steven Goldstone, RJR's
chairman, ``had intimated this a month or so ago.'' Recalling his
first job with Reynolds, selling Tempo brand cigarettes in Detroit,
Gray mused: ``It's a great company, and I'm sorry to see it broken
into pieces. It grew dramatically as a domestic tobacco company,
and I hope it will have that same opportunity now.''
</P>
<P>
   His colleague in the state Senate, Hamilton Horton, also a
Republican, said wistfully: ``Tobacco is big, big stuff for us in
Winston-Salem; it used to be the dominant crop and now it's only
about 16 percent of the state's farm income.'' When asked if any of
his fellow legislators talked about the news at lunch, Horton said
flatly, ``No one.''
</P>
<P>
   Maura Payne, vice president for communications at R.J. Reynolds,
had to work late Monday evening because of the impending
announcement, and she came in early Tuesday to start notifying
people. When she went to lunch in the company cafeteria in the
downtown Little Empire State Building headquarters, she found most
of her fellow employees ``pleased to hear the news,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, its a win-win situation,'' she observed. ``The
reaction here has been extremely positive. It clarifies your
decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   That optimistic view is shared by Gayle Anderson, another former
Reynolds Tobacco employee who is now president of the Greater
Winston-Salem Chamber of Commerce. ``People who have been calling
me have said, `Thank goodness,''' she said. Ms. Anderson
understands the local importance of Reynolds Tobacco, which has a
payroll of 6,500 here. Civic leaders, she said, believe that the
sale and split ``will give the company an opportunity to focus on
their domestic business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrel Guillory, director of the University of North Carolina
program on Southern politics, media and public life, believes the
sale and split to be ``the kind of corporate restructuring that is
caused by global economic forces that have resulted in a
diminishing of the domestic tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as RJR was announcing this restructuring,'' he said, the
state Legislature ``was creating a nonprofit foundation to respond
to the needs of communities that over the next few years will be
weakened by trends that are running against tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   RJR announced a prospective job reduction of 1,300 in December,
and Ms. Payne said Tuesday's announcement would not mean more job
cuts. To the contrary, she said, ``We may have to increase by a
handful.'' It was unclear what would happen to the 50 to 60
employees who worked for the international division here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
