<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-DEFENSE-ART-NY     03-09 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-DEFENSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR SEIZES CHANCE AT LEADERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an institution that runs on comity and
tradition, Sen. John W. Warner has mastered the art of fitting in.
With his impeccably tailored suits, silver-gray hair and
associations with Elizabeth Taylor and Barbara Walters, the
gentleman from Virginia looks, at first glance, like the senator
from central casting.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner's back-slapping bonhomie has not always gotten him
the respect that some colleagues say he really wants. As he assumes
a leadership role as chairman of the Armed Services Committee, the
Republican is working to overcome a question that still lingers
among some of his peers: Is John Warner really up to the task?
</P>
<P>
   The 72-year-old World War II veteran and Secretary of the Navy
under President Richard Nixon, has been preparing a long time for
the day when he would take the reins from Sen. Strom Thurmond, the
96-year-old South Carolina Republican who stepped down as chairman
in January.
</P>
<P>
   Now Warner is trying to pump new life and credibility into a
panel whose prestige and relevance have slipped badly since the end
of the Cold War dulled the public's appetite for affairs of state.
And he is wasting no time.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate's first major bill this year, he and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi rammed through the
biggest military pay and pension increase in nearly two decades.
Warner has reorganized the armed services panel, creating a
subcommittee to focus on terrorism, chemical and biological
weapons, and cyber warfare. By next month, the committee will have
held nearly 50 hearings on subjects from recruiting to national
missile defenses since he took over.
</P>
<P>
   And with his old friend and Senate Republican colleague William
Cohen now running the Pentagon, Warner has forged the closest
relationship in recent memory between an Armed Services chairman
and a defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   It is a relationship that is already paying dividends for the
administration. Following his rule to ``check politics at the
water's edge'' when it comes to military and foreign policy, Warner
has bucked his party's leaders and backed Clinton's plan to put
4,000 troops into the warring Yugoslav province of Kosovo as part
of the NATO peacekeeping force if a peace accord is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, he held off an interview for 25 minutes while he
fielded phone calls from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
President Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, to
discuss the latest diplomatic wrinkle in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having John out front leading this issue enhanced the
president's ability to make the case,'' said Cohen, who meets
regularly with Warner over breakfast at the Pentagon to hash out
military issues.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Sam Nunn of Georgia held the job when Democrats
controlled the Senate has an Armed Services chairman been so
involved in major foreign policy and national security issues.
``I'd like to be in the camp that constructively comments and, if
necessary, criticizes the administration, taking out the political
element,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner has an almost theatrical courtliness that borders on a
caricature of the Virginia gentleman farmer he once was. It is a
Southern-style formality that his supporters call patrician charm
and his critics call pompous.
</P>
<P>
   He has had to overcome derision from some colleagues and critics
who dismissed him early in his career as a dilettante and later as
an intellectual lightweight. Nixon helped start the snickering when
he once said the Navy secretary job could not be that difficult if
John Warner was doing it.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner's defenders say that what he lacks in innovativeness
or vision, he makes up for in diligence and experience. ``He's as
knowledgeable on national security as anyone,'' said Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., a Vietnam veteran on the committee. ``My God, he's
lived it for the last 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, before he took over the committee, Warner spent
hours at the Pentagon in briefings. After the first night of air
strikes against Iraq, Warner joined the Joint Chiefs of Staff in
their situation room to review damage-assessment reports. ``John is
willing to work, no question about that,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, who heads the Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The senator draws upon his experience to back up his instincts.
He quit high school at 17 and enlisted in the Navy for the last
months of World War II. At the outbreak of the Korean War, Warner
left law school and joined the Marine Corps as a communications
officer. (He discounts his own military background as
``inconsequential.'')
</P>
<P>
   His office in the Russell Senate Building is a historical
anecdote. On one wall hangs a photograph of his father, a field
surgeon at the Battle of Verdun in World War I, with a great-uncle
who fought in Robert E. Lee's Confederate Army. On an opposite wall
is the 1991 Gulf War resolution, which Warner sponsored and the
Senate passed, 52 to 47.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the doubters persist. Conservatives have accused Warner
of working too closely with Democrats. When the Senate defeated the
nomination of Sen. John G. Tower, R-Texas, to be defense secretary
in 1989, many conservatives blamed Warner for being unduly
cooperative with Nunn's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives were outraged when Warner voted against Robert
Bork's nomination to the Supreme Court in 1987, and when he said
Oliver North was unfit to run for Virginia's Senate seat in 1994.
Warner was one of 10 Republicans to oppose the perjury charge
against Clinton (he voted for the obstruction of justice count).
</P>
<P>
   The senator's supporters say the attacks come largely from
Republicans who resent Warner's independent streak and willingness
to reach across the aisle. ``It's not that he's incapable of being
partisan, but on foreign policy, he'll rise above party politics
and do the right thing,'' said Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., former deputy head of the Veterans
Administration, credits Warner with crucial support to build the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial, and explains the raps this way: ``Warner
is the kind of guy who speaks rather plainly, and when you do that,
you run the risk of saying something some people wish you hadn't
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the sniping, Warner shrugs it off: ``I'm just going
to continue to follow my own objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 20-year Senate career, that has meant focusing on
military issues, like bigger Pentagon budgets and robust missile
defenses. He has also pumped billions of dollars and thousands of
jobs into his state, and its huge shipbuilding industry, and
insulated Virginia from the devastating losses that hurt many other
once defense-rich states.
</P>
<P>
   Now Warner is trying to help Congress bridge the Cold War era
with today's more uncertain landscape. He supports a Pentagon plan
to appoint a military commander for defense of the continental
United States against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   And with American troops stretched globally thin, Warner worries
about the public's commitment to far-flung military missions. He
even suggests that America's 37,000 troops in South Korea be pared
over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to continue to press other nations to dig into their
treasuries and expend the funds to prepare themselves for these
contingencies,'' Warner said, ``and not expect the U.S. always to
come when they dial 911.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
