<HEADER>
A4106 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-09 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Column: Vivus Stock Plunge Raises Doubts About Firm's
Staying  Power  By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Vive la Vivus?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of Muse, an also-ran male impotency treatment dwarfed
by the gonzo success of Viagra, knocked a double on Monday after
announcing that it won a patent for a topical cream aimed at
helping women with sexual dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Vivus shareholders _ and I'm trying to resist
the temptation to use colorful double entendre here because this is
a family newspaper _ the one-day rally didn't last very long.
Yesterday, Vivus' shares plunged 19 percent to close at $3.91.
</P>
<P>
   Give the troubled Mountain View medical device company credit
for not calling it quits, but Vivus' attempt to develop a winning
treatment for women is a Hail Mary Pass. There are several other
formidable pharma-companies, including Pfizer of New York and Eli
Lilly of Indiana, that are racing to develop similar treatments for
women.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, we already know how Vivus fared against Pfizer
during their initial battle. Vivus' Muse product for men was
clinically successful and got approved by the Food and Drug
Administration before Pfizer's Viagra, but ultimately, it lost in a
rout, notes pharmaceutical analyst Sergio Traversa of Mehta
Partners, a New York biotechnology and pharmaceutical research
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Oftentimes, being first to market can prove to be a big
advantage for medical device stocks. And for a while, it worked for
Vivus, when its shares hovered near $40 in the first quarter of
1997. The strategy, though, backfired as the much-bigger Pfizer
used the buzz stirred by Muse to build anticipation for Viagra and
to prime its powerful marketing machine, Traversa says.
</P>
<P>
   ``One problem they had was being first, and you can't blame them
for doing that,'' Traversa says.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger problem was that Muse wasn't very well accepted
by doctors and patients in the first place. Suffice it to say, it
was more awkward to use than Viagra because it required a patient
to inject a tiny pill into his urethra. Viagra, on the other hand,
is a pill that can be discreetly swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history. Viagra rocketed to become an international
pop-culture phenomenon while Muse was left in the dust. Now, Vivus
is trying to stay in the game by competing for a treatment for
women.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET10 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  No doubt, while there may not be the same market potential as for
male impotency, there is a lucrative opportunity for a female
treatment, Traversa says.
</P>
<P>
   However, the analyst says Vivus' patent is ``broad'' and not
likely to offer much protection from other companies that try to
use a topically administered cream, Traversa says.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Vivus is taking the same active drug used with
Muse, alprostadil, and is using it as a cream that women can apply
externally. He says several other companies are working with
alprostadil cream applications.
</P>
<P>
   But what might be more daunting for Vivus is that other drug
companies are testing oral pills for women, which once again might
prove to be preferable _ as they were with men, he says. Pfizer,
for example, is running a trial for Viagra with women.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ICOS of Seattle has partnered with Lilly to develop
a pill to challenge Viagra that has the potential to offer fewer
side-effects than the current market leader, he says. (ICOS is led
by the first CEO of Amgen, George Rathmann.) And it is expected
that the joint venture also will vie for the female market.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there's a lot of confusion on how well Viagra will
work with women. British news publications have reported that young
women are buying Viagra on the black market in nightclubs and are
claiming that it improves their sexual performance. Meanwhile,
there have been recent academic studies released in the United
States saying the exact opposite: Viagra does little to offer
relief for female sexual dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the club-hoppers aren't asking for Muse. Still,
the clamor created by Vivus' announcement on Monday triggered an
explosion in trading volume. The number of shares trading hands
Monday and yesterday was more than 30 times the stock's usual
average.
</P>
<P>
   And judging by the lack of consensus between Vivus bears and
bulls debating the stock's prospects on Internet chat rooms,
current investors might want to steer clear of the volatile stock _
at least until more details of its trials with women are available,
says Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET10 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I always tell people that you should never buy a stock based on
breaking news,'' McCamant says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
