<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-COMMUTE-ART-2TAK     03-09 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-COMMUTE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI-AREA TRAFFIC JAMS FORCE COLORADANS TO RECONSIDER MASS TRANSIT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMA, Colo. _ Early-morning rays illuminated snowcapped peaks of
the Continental Divide as a group of people gathered in front of a
log cabin down in this village, waiting for the 7:15 and clutching
plastic coffee mugs, the universal emblem of a commuter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the view, I love staring out the window,'' Caroline
Grubbe said, settling into her reclining bus seat for the 40-minute
commute over an 11,541-foot mountain pass to her job running a
dentist's office in the ski resort town of Breckenridge. ``I could
never afford to live in Breck, and I love taking the bus to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Westerners have viewed mass transit as something
vaguely synonymous with socialism. But here in the Colorado
Rockies, surging tourism, employment, population and real estate
prices are forging transportation strategies that look positively
European.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, an increasing number of mountain ski
communities have adopted a combination of publicly and privately
operated bus services, weaving a network of ``community bus
routes'' that together now link 20 towns. Since 1989, Total annual
ridership on such routes has tripled to 16 million.
</P>
<P>
   And from Denver westward, congestion on Interstate 70, the ski
areas' Main Street, is prompting Denverites to pack car-pool
parking lots to overflow levels and to pack a Ski Train, bound for
Winter Park, to levels not seen since it started carrying
passengers in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these dodges, though, Interstate traffic routinely
freezes on the weekends into an alpine version of the Long Island
Expressway, with sport utility vehicles stretching in 25-mile,
bumper-to-bumper lines down from the Continental Divide.
</P>
<P>
   So, with skier traffic up by 20 percent in the last three years,
a state agency is pushing for construction of a high-speed monorail
that would run 160 miles from Denver's new airport through the
Rockies to a string of ski areas, including Vail.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by Swiss voters' approval in a referendum last
November of $20 billion in public spending to improve rail service
in the Alps, Colorado planners believe that the state's voters will
pass a proposal next year to build a multimillion-dollar, 6.5-mile
monorail segment in the mountains that would test both technology
and public acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the worst times,'' like Sunday nights, ``traffic is to
double in five years,'' said Miller Hudson, executive director of
the Colorado Intermountain Guideway Authority, the agency pushing
for the monorail. ``If the voters reject it, we will just wait
until the misery index increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Already the misery index is rising fast. On Monday mornings,
conversations in Denver center more on Sunday's traffic conditions
than on conditions on the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's laughable _ it's the most important industry in Colorado,
and it's a mess,'' one skier, Italo Laneri, said the morning after
battling traffic on a day trip to the mountains. ``Think of how
many people don't go because of the traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   With skiers' decisions driven by traffic volume, ski areas are
fighting back with some new tactics:
</P>
<P>
   _ As the days lengthen in March, Colorado's busiest skiing
month, some areas are staying open later, hoping to help skiers
avoid the mountain rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vail, which gets most of its skiers from outside Colorado,
encourages them to fly into the new Eagle Airport, 50 miles west of
the Interstate's chronic bottlenecks. Already one-third of Vail's
out-of-state skiers arrive at this airport.
</P>
<P>
   _ And this winter Loveland, the ski area closest to Denver,
started selling ``flex passes,'' tickets that allow a buyer to ski
any four-hour segment in a day rather than paying for the entire
day, the manner in which tickets must typically be purchased.
``It's for people who want to avoid peak times on the I-70
corridor,'' said Scott Fortner, director of marketing for Loveland.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the ski areas are too cautious in responding to
the traffic congestion they create. In general, the resorts are
skeptical of the monorail and offer only lukewarm support to bus
service from Denver. Instead, they lobbied for $1 billion worth of
improvements on the mountain segment of the Interstate, work that
is to start next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ski areas are not advocating any particular solution,''
said Omar Jabara, a political consultant who supports running buses
between Denver, the nation's largest ski market, and the ski areas.
``If people are stuck in traffic on I-70, that means they are
getting to the ski area later. But they are still paying for the
lift ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   A ski-bus fleet, Jabara argues, would be better than a monorail
because it would be far cheaper than the monorail's $5 billion
cost, would not mar the scenery with a 160-mile string of towers
and, unlike the monorail, would not be subject to doubts about its
technology at mountain altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   In retort, Hudson said his monorail would charge less than the
$56 that existing van services demand for the 100-mile ride from
Denver's airport to Vail. Arguing that buses will not relieve the
pressure, he warned, ``In five years, every weekend will be a
problem, and the big holiday weekends will be just horrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the gains in bus ridership in the mountain towns to the
west, for the moment the old resistance to buses still reigns in
Denver, where a three-year-old bus service, SkiXpress, carries no
more than several thousand skiers a winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get people to take the bus _ it's a life-style
thing out here,'' said Deborah Sakaguchi, manager of SkiXpress. She
said riders generally fell into two groups: teen-agers whose
parents will not lend them a car, and ``elderly people who still
want to ski but don't want to drive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But in the high country, transit attitudes have changed
radically as escalating real estate prices have forced many resort
workers to become commuters. In Vail, apartment rents are on a par
with those in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   While Breckenridge, Vail and other ski towns draw up plans to
build more worker housing, commuting over the Continental Divide is
expected to be the way of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all workers, they aren't high-dollar tourists, they
are regular,'' Mike Westover said of his full load of passengers
this morning as he steered his bus around the seven high-altitude
hairpin turns that separate Alma from Breckenridge. ``Most of these
people can't afford to live in Breckenridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus service from here to Breckenridge was started this
winter with financing from the Breckenridge Ski Resort and the
Summit Stage, a mass transit system supported by a county sales
tax. With the high country registering Colorado's fastest growth in
mass transit, the Summit Stage has seen its annual ridership jump
to 1.3 million, from 300,000 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Among the converts to bus commuting is Barbara Jacobus, a bank
employee. As Westover eased his bus down Hoosier Pass, taking turns
at 15 miles an hour, Mrs. Jacobus said: ``The first day I drove,
two people spun out and hit each other. I feel much better about
taking the bus than driving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
