<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-WINNERS-N     03-09 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-WINNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WALL STREET, THEY LOVE RJR NABISCO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP, RJR-NABISCO-TERMS,
RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL, RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN, RJR-NABISCO-LBO,
RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH, RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE)) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON and JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street has always found creative ways to make
money. But probably no other company over the years has done more
to enrich the coffers of investment bankers than RJR Nabisco. Even
going back to 1985 when R.J. Reynolds first acquired Nabisco Brands
for $4.9 billion _ the fourth-largest deal that year _ bankers
walked away with $19 million in advisory fees, including Morgan
Stanley, Shearson Lehman and Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   Not a tiny sum then, especially compared to J.P. Morgan and
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which earned about $20 million last year when
Exxon Corp. acquired Mobil Corp. in the largest merger ever. (True,
the chief executives of Exxon and Mobil were the real deal makers
in that transaction.)
</P>
<P>
   But no deal made bankers as notoriously wealthy as Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.'s two-month battle for RJR Nabisco in 1988.
Then, almost every bank on Wall Street its their pockets, either by
advising the companies or by financing the loans necessary for the
$25 billion takeover.
</P>
<P>
   According to Securities and Exchange Commission filings, $325
million was paid upfront to about 200 commercial banks for
providing $14.5 billion in financing for the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Firms aiding Kohlberg Kravis in its successful bid were among
those to benefit the most.
</P>
<P>
   The now defunct Drexel Burnham Lambert reaped $227 million.
Morgan Stanley and Wasserstein, Perella each got $25 million.
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. got $109 million for its role in the financing.
And Kohlberg Kravis itself pocketed $75 million in fees from its
investors.
</P>
<P>
   According to an account in the book ``Barbarians at the Gate,''
the 1989 best seller that chronicled the RJR battle, Richard
Beattie, now chairman of the law firm Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett,
even joked about it. ``It's wonderful to see all these friends of
KKR here tonight,'' he is reported to have said in front of 400
people at the celebratory dinner Henry Kravis threw at the Pierre
Hotel's grand ballroom. ``To think it only took a billion dollars
in fees to get us all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers representing RJR Nabisco also fared well. Dillon Read
and Lazard Freres each earned $14 million for advising RJR's board.
And there was plenty of more money to be made, especially with
later financings and corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1995, several investment banks, including
Goldman, Sachs, earned a total of $46.8 million in underwriting
fees in Nabisco Holdings Inc.'s $1.1 billion stock offering,
according to Securities Data Co.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tuesday's sale and subsequent spinoff of the domestic
tobacco unit guarantees bankers fat paychecks for months to come.
RJR Nabisco was loathe to disclose just how much the company paid
Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley and lawyers Davis Polk &AMP; Wardwell,
who advised them on the $8 billion sale of the company's
international tobacco business. But merger experts say that they,
along with Salomon Smith Barney, which advised the buyer, Japan
Tobacco, could reap between $30 million and $40 million for that
transaction alone.
</P>
<P>
   And that does not include how much RJR Nabisco will have to pay
bankers who will be responsible for splitting off the domestic
tobacco business later this year. With fees like those in the past,
RJR Nabisco may well earn a place as Wall Street's best customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
