<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-COX     03-09 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Workers ratify contract, won't strike against Lockheed Martin
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Union workers at Lockheed Martin Corp.'s Marietta
plant ratified a new contract Tuesday, ending a strike threat at
Cobb County's largest private employer.
</P>
<P>
   Machinists union Local 709 said 59 percent of voting members
approved the three-year pact.
</P>
<P>
   The deal covers 4,200 Machinists at the military aircraft plant,
or just under half the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Union members had rejected an initial tentative agreement Feb.
28 by a 68 percent vote, despite an endorsement by Local 709
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   A strike deadline was set for 12:01 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   The company modified its proposal in last-ditch, federally
mediated talks Monday, prompting Tuesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   A union spokesman said the company withdrew a plan to shift some
workers to four-day, 10-hour-a-day workweeks, which opponents said
would be disruptive and could also cut down on overtime. It also
agreed to reduce the number of job classifications that will be
combined in the new pact, a move some workers believe is a
precursor to more job cuts at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The company also offered a compromise on a tougher attendance
policy that angered some workers, the union spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the narrowness of Tuesday's ratification showed many among
the rank-and-file remain unhappy with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Basic economic elements in the contract, including 3 percent
annual pay raises, were unchanged from the first proposal and
apparently were not a key issue in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin spokeswoman Susan Miles called the revised
proposal a ``fair contract'' and added the changes ``addressed
specific concerns of the union membership.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement doesn't end the plant's broader problems, which
include delivery delays and slow sales in the C-130J cargo plane
program.
</P>
<P>
   Employment has fallen slowly but steadily in recent years, and
executives have warned it could fall further as they seek to cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The plant also leads development of the F-22 fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
