<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4129 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKE-1STLD-WRIT     03-09 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BATTLE IN WASHINGTON: WHAT TO REVEAL ON CHINA ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs 1st-6th grafs for new material, rewriting; inserts new 16th
graf) (wg) 
 By JEFF GERTH and ERIC SCHMITT 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and congressional
Republicans are wrangling over how much information to make public
about official findings that China acquired some of the most
sensitive American military technology.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, a bipartisan committee unanimously approved a
voluminous report concluding that China had harmed national
security during the last 20 years by stealing American nuclear
secrets and acquiring other American technology.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the committee and the White House have been quietly
negotiating how much of the report could be released. Both agree
that something should be released, but not on what specifically.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the discussions have become increasingly tense.
They are now taking on a more partisan tone, and the issue is
providing ammunition to critics of President Clinton's China policy
in the days leading up to important talks between Beijing and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   China has consistently denied any theft of nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The committee that produced the report is to disband at the end
of the month unless Congress extends its life. A few days later
China's premier is scheduled to come to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican member of the panel, Rep. Curt Weldon of
Pennsylvania, said in an interview Tuesday: ``They're trying to
spin this thing to get the best play for themselves and avoid
further embarrassment. They want to drag it out as long as long as
they can. I'm so mad I can't see straight.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chairman, Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., gave a
more restrained assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are debating whether we can state what we found,'' he said.
The risk , he added, is that the panel's secret findings would be
lost in the layers of the declassification process.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the panel, who asked not to be identified, said
they believe the administration's efforts to keep some information
secret is based on legitimate concerns of protecting
intelligence-gathering methods.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic member also said that recent press accounts about
the Cox Committee's findings had affected the negotiations,
creating the possibility that the administration ``might be a
little more willing to declassify.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House denied the Republican accusations, noting it met
the committee's March 1 deadline to submit the administration's
classification concerns, and continued to cooperate with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working in good faith to help the committee declassify
as much of the report as possible, consistent with the intelligence
community's requirement to protect its sources and methods,'' said
P.J. Crowley, a spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the administration had suggested how the panel
could rewrite portions of the highly classified report to make it
available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, details of the Cox Committee's work, including
the determination by U.S. officials that China stole nuclear
secrets from an American weapons laboratory, have surfaced. On
Monday, a scientist at Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico
was dismissed for security breaches after he was questioned by the
FBI in connection with the suspected theft of nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   [In Boston on Tuesday, a federal grand jury indicted Yao Yi, a
Chinese scientist, and Collin Shu, a Canadian, on charges of
conspiracy to violate export control laws by attempting to ship
fiberoptic gyroscopes to China. Yao is being transported to Boston
after his arrest two weeks ago at a scientific conference in San
Diego. The Customs Service contends that the shipments, had they
succeeded, could have helped China improve the accuracy of their
missiles.)
</P>
<P>
   Other Clinton administration officials also addressed the issue
Tuesday. The White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart said that
President Clinton supported the energy secretary's decision to
dismiss the scientist.
</P>
<P>
   And Vice President Al Gore, asked in a CNN interview about
allegations that the administration had been lax in pursuing
security breaches at the weapons labs, said: ``That happened during
the previous administration. That happened back in the 1980s. And
as soon as the investigation identified targets of that
investigation, then the law enforcement community handled that very
aggressively, and it resulted in a presidential directive that
completely changed the security procedures in the weapons labs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Intelligence Committee is negotiating with the
administration over how much information it can make public in
connection with its inquiry into Chinese contributions to the 1996
election campaign and the transfer of satellite technology to
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, has
suggested that the Senate might consider contempt charges against
administration officials if they do not cooperate sufficiently with
the committee. He did not specify the target of contempt charges or
explain his legal reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Lott told reporters Tuesday that he ``assumed a major portion''
of the House panel's report would be released.
</P>
<P>
   Without a compromise, there could be a constitutional clash
between Congress and the White House because both the
administration and the House have the power to declassify
information. Typically, the administration works out a compromise
in consultation with various agencies and Congress, the process now
under way.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In these cases, broad findings and conclusions are released, but
precise details are kept secret in order to protect
intelligence-gathering sources and methods or ongoing law
enforcement investigations.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the administration will even finish its
review before the panel's charter expires, according to an
administration official at one of the agencies being asked to
review the report.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the committee uncovered the evidence of Chinese theft
of American nuclear secrets. Democrats say they feared the
Republicans would disclose that evidence before the election. But
their fears proved unfounded. The committee filed its huge report
at the end of the year and went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   A week later the new Congress convened and gave the committee 90
more days to produce a declassified report in collaboration with
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   The review is being coordinated within the administration by the
President's National Security Council. NSC officials farmed out the
report to various agencies for a word by word review, but only
after the report was screened by the Justice Department to protect
ongoing law enforcement investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the NSC leading the fight with the other agencies
weighing in,'' said one House staff member. ``The Energy Department
is worried about the stuff at the labs. The intelligence community
is worried about disclosing their sources and methods. And the FBI
and the Justice Department are concerned about on-going criminal
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the White House released a redacted version of the
committee's recommendations but with little input from the
committee, members said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Cox and the panel's ranking Democrat, Norman
Dicks, of Washington, sent a letter to President Clinton requesting
a meeting to discuss the report. The White House has not yet
replied to their letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
