joins scores of area workers who are taking advantage of free
busing provided by local counties to commute to work from towns and
villages where the workers can afford to live. Surging tourism,
employment, population, and real estate prices in the Colorado
Rockies are forging transportation strategies that look positively
European. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BECKENRIDGE, Colo. -- March 09, 1999 -- COLO-COMMUTE-1,
3-09 -- Driver Mike Westover leans out of his bus to make sure a
passenger successfully unloaded his gear last week. Traditionally,
Westerners have viewed mass transit as something vaguely synonymous
with socialism. But, here in the Colorado Rockies, surging tourism,
employment, population, and real estate prices are forging
transportation strategies that look positively European. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
