<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH BANK SEEKS TO BUY 2 BIG RIVALS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Making an unexpected takeover bid that would create the
largest bank in the world, Banque Nationale de Paris SA offered $37
billion in stock on Tuesday night to acquire two of its biggest
French rivals, Societe Generale SA and Paribas SA, which just last
month had agreed to merge.
</P>
<P>
   The French stock market regulator said that Banque Nationale was
offering 15 of its shares for 7 Societe Generale shares, and 11 of
its shares for 8 Paribas shares, to form a banking group with more
than $1 trillion in assets. At that size, Banque Nationale de Paris
would eclipse UBS of Switzerland, now the world's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   The regulator, the Conseil des Marches Financiers, said that
Banque Nationale would bid for all outstanding shares of both
banks, but that the offer would hinge on its ability to acquire at
least a majority of each bank's shares. It said nothing of possible
cost-cutting or savings if the takeover effort was successful.
</P>
<P>
   The bid would offer a premium of 14 percent over Societe
Generale's closing share price on Tuesday of 145.5 euros, or
$157.14, and a 24 percent premium over the Paribas share price of
85.95 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Banque Nationale shareholder approval is required, the regulator
said, and trading in the stock of all three banks will be suspended
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes little more than a month after Societe
Generale said it would pay about $18 billion in stock to acquire
Paribas, France's fifth-largest bank. That announcement contributed
to speculation about a possible new wave of mergers and takeovers
in France and across Europe. Also last month, Olivetti SpA, Italy's
No. 2 phone provider, announced a $60-billion hostile bid for the
largest Italian phone company, Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, Banco Santander moved in January to solidify its
position as that country's biggest bank by acquiring Banco Central
Hispano for $11.3 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Societe Generale's announced move on Paribas, which would have
formed a group called SG Paribas, was intended to bring together
the two institutions' investment banking businesses and give
Paribas access to Societe Generale's 2,700 retail branches for its
consumer finance and asset management services.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were lukewarm toward that plan, reflecting the view
that such a merger would contribute little to bringing down their
costs, since Societe Generale and Paribas had few overlapping
activities.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of consolidation in France is unlikely to slacken.
Later this year, the Socialist Cabinet of Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin plans to sell its stake in Credit Lyonnais, the
government-owned bank that has lost billions. Lyonnais has sought
out as a future core shareholder Credit Agricole, which has the
largest branch network of any French bank.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of Banque Nationale de Paris with Societe Generale
and Paribas would offer considerable room for consolidation and
cost reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Banque Nationale is moving from a position of relative strength.
Last week, it said that its net income in 1998 rose 23 percent, to
1.1 billion euros _ a little more than $1 billion _ as vigorous
French economic growth caused domestic banking income to soar.
Similarly, Societe Generale reported a 15 percent rise in 1998
earnings last month, to 1.07 billion euros, while Paribas reported
earnings largely unchanged from 1997 at 1 billion euros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
