<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-CHARGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AG MAY SEEK LIFE SENTENCE IN TREASURY EMBEZZLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The two former treasury officials who were arrested in
recent weeks for allegedly stealing nearly $9 million in state
funds are facing indictment under a post-Revolutionary War statute
that carries a maximum sentence of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources familiar with the investigation, Attorney
General Thomas F. Reilly intends to use the threat of the heavy
sentence to underline the seriousness of the crime and to persuade
the two to tell about other possible wrongdoing in the department.
</P>
<P>
   Absent the use of the 1791 statute, which prohibits embezzlement
from the state treasury by any treasury employee, the two would
likely be charged with embezzlement or larceny of over $50,000,
both of which carry a maximum sentence of five years.
</P>
<P>
   While it is improbable that a judge would impose the maximum
sentence upon conviction, the 1791 law would allow the imposition
of a far stiffer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said that the investigators believe that of the two
officials arrested, Robert E. Foley, one of the top five deputies
in the state treasurer's office under Joseph D. Malone, has more to
offer them than John F. Trischitta, who supervised the fund that
was allegedly looted for $8.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold the cards,'' said one investigator. ``Foley is on the
hot seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley's lawyer, Gary L. Meyers, said Tuesday that he would move
to have any indictment based on the statute thrown out since he
believes it would be the first time _ at least in the past 100
years _ that the law was used to bring a case. Meyers would not say
whether Foley might be willing to cooperate with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   As one of Malone's top deputies, in charge of the treasury's
Cash Management Department, Foley was responsible for keeping track
of the flow of billions of dollars in state revenues. He was also
close to Malone politically, having raised money for Malone's
campaigns for treasurer and governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported last Friday that Malone had resisted the
entreaties of several co-workers and a top supervisor that Foley be
fired or at least transferred due to allegedly abusive behavior.
Malone instead asked that the employees work out the problem with
Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was traveling Tuesday and could not be reached for
comment. On Saturday, Malone said during a radio interview that he
was not worried that Foley might implicate him in any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people look at the facts they will see the problems
stopping with Mr. Foley and his department,'' Malone said in the
interview on WRKO. ``I have full confidence that when this process
takes its course, no matter what anybody says to try to save their
skin, people will realize that this was a conspiracy between Mr.
Foley and one of his underlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to bed feeling badly that this incident occurred, but by
no means do I think it will go up any higher,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Judith L. Lindahl of Boston, Trischitta's lawyer, declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Two others have also been arrested in the case, Thomas Ciliberto
of Woonsocket, R.I., and Martin Robbins of Peabody, Mass. According
to the charges, they represented themselves as ``heir finders who
were acting on behalf of individuals or firms who were owed money
from the state's Unpaid Check Fund. In fact, however, the two had
no such clients but acted in concert with Foley and Trischitta to
embezzle the money out of the Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   All four have pleaded innocent to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have now turned to the formidable task of combing
through the thousands of transactions and documents involving the
Unpaid Check Fund over the last eight years, one source said
Tuesday. That source said Reilly's investigators expect to show far
more money was stolen from the fund by Foley, Trischitta, Robbins,
and Ciliberto but they do not expect others to be charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long process,'' said an investigator. ``We
are recreating literally a thousand or more transactions and trying
to trace them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain when the indictments will be returned but some
involved in the cases say they could be issued by a Suffolk County
grand jury before the end of the month. The arrests were based on
criminal complaints sought by Reilly's office from Boston Municipal
Court. The four men are due back in municipal court on either March
25 or April 1 for status hearings on their individual cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
