<HEADLINE>
BAKER WINS SECOND POLK AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty journalists whose work documented corporate
deceit, political impropriety and ethnic bloodletting have been
chosen as recipients of the 1998 George Polk Awards, the awards'
sponsor announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners this year are two writers for The New York
Times. Russell Baker, who for 36 years wrote the ``Observer''
column in The Times, won the George Polk Career Award. It was
second Polk Award for Baker, who retired last year. He won the
prize for commentary in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford J. Levy, the Albany, N.Y., bureau chief of The Times,
won the local reporting award for his exploration of political
fund-raising in the state government. His scrutiny of candidates'
donor lists exposed conflicts of interest and led to continuing
criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   This year is the 50th anniversary of the awards, which were
established in memory of George W. Polk, a CBS correspondent who
was killed in 1948 while covering the civil war in Greece. The
awards, which are administered by Long Island University, will be
presented on April 14 at the Roosevelt Hotel in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners this year included Alix M. Freedman of The Wall
Street Journal, who won the international reporting award for her
investigation of efforts to sterilize women in the Third World,
often without their consent.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, a columnist for The Daily News for more than two
decades, won the commentary award for his writings on New York's
poor and disenfranchised.
</P>
<P>
   The award for foreign reporting went to Tracy Wilkinson of The
Los Angeles Times, who wrote about the struggles between ethnic
Albanian separatists and Serb nationalists in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The other winners are:
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reporting _ Mary Jordan, Keith Richburg and Kevin
Sullivan of The Washington Post, for their eight-part series
illustrating the human toll of the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   National Reporting _ Donald L. Barlett and James B. Steele of
Time magazine for their series on wasteful government subsidies to
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Book _ Philip Gourevitch, for his account of genocide in ``We
Wish to Inform You that Tomorrow We Will be Killed With Our
Families: Stories from Rwanda'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux).
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Reporting _ Gardiner Harris and R.G. Dunlop of The
Louisville Courier-Journal for their investigation into how illegal
practices among coal mine operators lead to the death each year of
1,500 workers from black lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Reporting _ Amy Goodman and Jeremy Scahill, producers for
Pacifica Radio's ``Democracy Now'' series, for their documentary on
Chevron's role in the murder of two environmentalists in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Television Reporting _ Brian Ross and Rhonda Schwartz of the ABC
News program ``20/20'' for a report on the labor practices of
American clothing manufacturers in Saipan, a U.S. territory where
sweatshop conditions persist.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Reporting _ Robert Whitaker and Dolores Kong of The
Boston Globe for their series on how mentally ill people are harmed
by federally financed drug trials.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Reporting _ Joe Stephens of The Kansas City Star for a
report that exposed widespread conflicts of interest among federal
judges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
