<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-REORG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SONY: THE WALKMAN GOES DIGITAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 BY STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Sony Corp., one of Japan's truly global companies,
plans to do nothing less than reinvent itself, using a combination
of enduring strength in consumer electronics and emerging high
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In an extensive overhaul announced Tuesday, the company that
introduced the pocket-sized transistor radio, the Walkman tape
player and the Trinitron television screen showed that it wants the
next generation of consumers to know Sony as a leader in networking
_ enabling computers, television sets, pagers, cellular phones and
other electronics products to communicate with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three years, we have made a lot of effort to move
from being a `box' company to becoming an information technology
company,'' Nobuyuki Idei, Sony's president, said in an interview.
``I think we've had a fair amount of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sony's Vaio laptop computers are receiving high praise,
and an advanced computer chip it introduced last week as part of a
preview of the next-generation Playstation game machine is
generating lots of talk.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy takes Sony into unexplored territory. Analysts
regard its semiconductor-manufacturing abilities as still unproven.
And Sony's move also puts it in intense competition with other
technology producers, all seeking ways to make their products more
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Idei conceded that the plans, which will require significant
investment in research and development, could hurt earnings for a
while. ``Short-term profit and investment in networking _ frankly,
I cannot satisfy the two things at once,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just the investment that Sony has made in developing the new
Playstation computer chip almost insures that it will not profit
from the new machine until well after its introduction, scheduled
sometime before March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Idei expressed confidence that the stock market would
recognize the steps announced Tuesday as enhancing the company's
long-term prospects. In fact, Sony's shares climbed almost 9
percent here, and Moody's Investor Service affirmed its Aa3 rating
on some of the company's unsecured debt, citing the latest
developments in its business.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Sony is also taking some more conventional steps to
improve its earnings. The company said it would reduce its staff by
10 percent, or 17,000 workers, over the next three years, and 15 of
its 70 manufacturing plants will be closed. Sony is already in the
process of closing two of its four plants in Malaysia, and Idei
said it would look for similar opportunities in Japan and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sony is also bringing three publicly traded subsidiaries back
under its wing through a stock swap. Idei said that absorbing the
Sony Chemicals Corp. and Sony Precision Technology made sense
because the two really do little more than supply Sony with
products. He said the decision to fold Sony Music Entertainment
(Japan) back into the mother company made sense because
shareholders did not invest with the idea that it would commit
significant capital to develop computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   As joint owner with Sony of Sony Computer Entertainment, the
entity that developed the Playstation and the new chip for its
successor, the music company was venturing into operations far
afield of its core business. The consolidation will allow Sony to
better allocate capital and workers, Idei said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony contends that such steps, in combination with the new
strategy, will create significant value for stockholders, a reason
rarely offered by Japanese companies for making major shifts. Idei
noted that while Sony's annual revenue exceeded $50 billion, its
market capitalization ranges between $30 billion and $35 billion,
which he said was a sign it was undervalued. ``Take America Online,
for example,'' he said. ``AOL's revenues are a few percent of the
revenues of the Sony Corp., but its market value is probably two
times as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Idei said he thought that companies like America Online and
Yahoo had only scratched the surface of what the Internet
potentially offers businesses. ``They are really only content
aggregators or direct marketers,'' he said. ``There's an
opportunity for more complex services.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, there may be demand for a provider of services for
companies seeking to enter electronic commerce, or demand for a
seller of hardware that gives consumers access to online merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The one area of Sony's business unaffected by the new plan was
its American movie and music businesses. Idei said Sony had not yet
decided what to do with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
