<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLUOR-CUTBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUOR TO CUT 5,000 JOBS AND REORGANIZE OPERATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ The Fluor Corp., suffering from the Asian
economic crisis and its own bloated cost structure, said Tuesday
that it would cut 5,000 employees, reorganize its operations, and
narrow the range of construction projects it undertakes.
</P>
<P>
   Fluor, the nation's largest engineering and construction
company, said the moves were expected to reduce overhead costs by
$160 million annually but would require a $130 million pretax
charge against earnings in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a cost structure that is unsustainable,'' Philip J.
Carroll, the company's chairman and chief executive, told
shareholders at the annual meeting here Tuesday. He said a
reorganization would have been needed even if business conditions
had been better.
</P>
<P>
   But those conditions continue to deteriorate. The company said
Tuesday that it expected only $6 billion in new construction orders
this year, about half the level of two years ago and less than the
$8 billion it had previously been forecasting for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fluor said it expected to record net income this fiscal year of
$107 million, or $1.42 a share, after the restructuring charge.
That is less than half the $235 million, or $2.97 a diluted share,
it earned last year on revenues of $13.5 billion. Even excluding
the charge, which amounts to $1.23 a share, expected earnings of
$2.65 a share are below the $2.99 or so that analysts have been
estimating.
</P>
<P>
   Fluor shares closed Tuesday at $34.3125, down $1.75. The shares,
which have traded as high as $52.50 in the last year, are near
their 12-month low of $33.25.
</P>
<P>
   The construction industry has been buffeted by the Asian
financial crisis, which derailed many large projects. The Asian
crisis also helped precipitate a decline in oil prices, slowing
capital spending by oil companies, which are prime Fluor customers.
Fluor's A.T. Massey coal production subsidiary, meanwhile, has been
hurt by weak domestic steel production caused in part by an influx
of cheaper steel from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000 job cuts amount to about 9 percent of the nearly
57,000 employees the company had at the end of last fiscal year.
The cuts are coming mainly from salaried employees in the
engineering and construction division, and constitute nearly 20
percent of that group. Some 1,000 of the cuts will be in
staff-support positions, which constitute overhead, and 4,000 will
be of people working directly on construction projects. The company
will also close 15 of its roughly 75 offices.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization bears the stamp of Carroll, who came to Fluor
as chief executive last July after serving as the president of the
Shell Oil Co., the American arm of the Royal/Dutch Shell Group.
Carroll, 61, who had reached Shell's retirement age of 60, replaced
Lester G. McCraw, who resigned as Fluor's chief executive at the
end of 1997 after being diagnosed with bladder cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Under McCraw, Fluor, which is based in Irvine, south of Los
Angeles, expanded into many different types of construction in an
effort to boost its revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have poured your driveway if you wanted us to,''
James O. Rollans, the chief financial officer, said.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the new business was not profitable. Carroll, aiming
to double construction profit margins within five years, said Fluor
would now focus on sectors in which it had a strong expertise and
could command better profits, such as in petrochemicals and mining.
It will phase out construction of office buildings, paper mills and
other low-margin activities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company will also reorganize into four units, each with
profit-and-loss responsibility. They are Fluor Daniel, the
construction division; A.T. Massey, the coal producer; Fluor Global
Services, which combines businesses such as equipment leasing and
temporary staffing that the company sees as fast growing; and
Shared Services, which will sell computing and administrative
services to the other divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Alan L. Boeckmann was promoted to head the construction
division, which accounted for the bulk of revenues and about 40
percent of profits last year. That puts him in contention to
succeed Carroll, who is expected to stay for several more years.
Another contender is John Hopkins, who was named Tuesday to head a
new global business development, sales and marketing group.
</P>
<P>
   Fluor bucked the recent corporate trend of divesting noncore
businesses by deciding to keep the coal division, which
historically has been a strong performer. Carroll said there was
some synergy between coal and construction, but that Fluor would
continue to evaluate whether selling the coal business made sense.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the company said Fluor believed Massey,
still financially strong, would be able to acquire some weaker
rivals during the current hard times. That would make it more
valuable if it were spun off in future years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
