<SLUG> BC-USATODAY-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANNETT'S USA TODAY NAMES NEW EDITOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Fla., N.C., Mich.)  (nk) 
 BY SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a largely unexpected move, Karen Jurgensen, editor of the
editorial page of USA Today, has been named editor of the
publication, the nation's largest newspaper, the paper announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She will replace David Mazzarella, 60, who is retiring. Ms.
Jurgensen, 50, will be replaced by Brian Gallagher, deputy editor
of the editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will be effective on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``USA Today has experienced both significant improvement and
growth under David Mazzarella, and we are grateful for his
contributions,'' said Thomas Curley, the paper's president and
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Jurgensen said that Mazzarella's retirement had
been expected, newspaper industry executives differed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not expected,'' said Bob Giles, executive director of
the Media Studies Center and senior vice president of the Freedom
Forum, a journalism foundation. ``People who are fairly close
watchers of USA Today were fairly surprised,'' said Giles, a former
editor of The Detroit News, which, like USA Today, is owned by the
Gannett Co.
</P>
<P>
   However, the management change is not expected to lead to
widespread changes in the newspaper's direction or coverage, Giles
and others said.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzarella headed USA Today's international operations before
becoming editor in 1994. He joined Gannett in 1976 as international
editor for the Gannett News Service after working for The
Associated Press and as editor of The Rome Daily American. He will
continue as a senior vice president for strategic projects until
his retirement, expected at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jurgensen joined USA Today in 1982. She became editor of the
editorial page in 1991 after two years as senior editor/days. She
had previously been life section editor, managing editor for cover
articles and senior editor for special projects. As the special
projects editor, she established the newspaper's data base analysis
group and was responsible for polling.
</P>
<P>
   She began her career in 1972 in Charlotte, N.C., and later
worked at The Miami News. USA Today is the nation's top-selling
newspaper, with an average daily circulation of 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1982, when it was dubbed McPaper, ``the
newspaper's reputation has changed dramatically,'' said Rem Rieder,
editor and senior vice president of the American Journalism Review
in College Park, Md. He said that for a long time it was known for
being colorful, but was not regarded as a serious newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The paper is now respected for its coverage of breaking news and
special reports and is considered one of Gannett's largest profit
centers. Executives are considering expanding space for news
coverage and working to attract more women readers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
