<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAPPEN-THEORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAPPEN TISSUE SAMPLE CAUSES FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN AND SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Microscopic brain tissue from eight-month-old Matthew
Eappen was turned over by defense lawyers for Louise Woodward to a
freelance journalist whose report formed the basis for Sunday
night's ``60 Minutes'' broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, Katie Leishman, gave the sample to Dr. Floyd
Gilles, a California specialist in neuropathology, who after
analyzing it along with other evidence concluded that Matthew died
of strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   Leishman's lengthy story of the new findings was rejected for
publication by the New York Times Sunday Magazine, she said
Tuesday, but she was hired by ``60 Minutes'' as a co-producer of
the controversial segment.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation that Leishman was given slides of brain tissue
samples incensed friends of the Eappens, who said it raised
questions about the independence of the research, and was
criticized by medical ethicists Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, there's got to be some kind of ethical limitations to
what a defense attorney can do with evidence they get in a criminal
trial,'' said Matthew McCue, a friend of the Eappens. ``To take a
piece of their child and give it away to a reporter to support
their cause is unconscionable and it's sleazy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, underscoring the murkiness of the issue, even Middlesex
District Attorney Martha Coakley, one of the prosecutors in the
case, said she too would have made the sample available for
investigation by ``somebody we trusted to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   As debate swirled, the ``60 Minutes'' team vigorously defended
the independence of their report Tuesday and rejected any
suggestions that, in the words of producer Walt Bogdanich, they
were ``stalking horses for the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilles' theory that the baby could have been strangled up to 48
hours before he died was backed by a colleague, Dr. Marvin Nelson,
who was paid a fee by the defense team as a prospective witness in
1997 but did not testify in Woodward's murder trial. Their theory
conflicted with a jury's verdict that Woodward killed Matthew
Eappen in February 1997 by violently shaking him and slamming his
head against a hard object. Woodward's second-degree murder
conviction was reduced to manslaughter by Judge Hiller B. Zobel,
and she was allowed to return to her home in England.
</P>
<P>
   Now, armed with the ``60 Minutes'' report, defense lawyers have
called for a new probe into Eappen's death. But prosecutors say
there is no new evidence to warrant reopening the case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Globe has learned that scores of physicians are
preparing an open letter refuting the strangulation theory put
forward on Sunday night's program.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Tuesday evening in the offices of ``60 Minutes,''
Leishman defended her role in providing the brain sample to Gilles
as necessary to fully evaluate the case. She said she sought the
sample from the defense after Coakley told her both sides had
identical samples. ``It was evidence in the case,'' she said,
adding: ``I got a box in the mail. I transported it without opening
it to Dr. Gilles.''
</P>
<P>
   The law is unclear on who owns pathological specimens, but it
has emerged as a ``big time ethical issue,'' according to George J.
Annas, a professor of health law at Boston University's School of
Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a body part and the family has a right to have that
treated with respect,'' Annas said. ``I think it can be kept for
reasonable scientific purposes, but can't be shipped around the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and experts who are given custody of pathological
evidence during a trial don't own the material and should be
required to return it to the medical examiner when the case is
over, Annas said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense team's payment to Nelson was not mentioned in the
``60 Minutes'' broadcast. However, the program did note that
Nelson, the chief of radiology at Children's Hospital in Los
Angeles, had been contacted by the defense team, but had not
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Mike Wallace Tuesday maintained that the small fee paid
to Nelson by the defense team in 1997 _ which Bogdanich said was
$300 _ did not color Nelson's judgment. As for mentioning the fee
on the broadcast, Wallace said ``it was discussed and felt to be
unnecessary'' because viewers understand that ``when the defense
calls an expert witness, the expert witness gets paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Leishman said the other doctor, Gilles, ``had absolutely no
connection to the defense team.'' Neither Gilles nor Nelson could
be reached Tuesday, but they defended their conclusions at a news
conference in California on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Elaine Whitfield-Sharp, a former member of the Woodward
defense team, said she paid Nelson $700 in September 1997 for
examining CT scans of Matthew. She said he concluded that Matthew
died of an old injury.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield Sharp also says that she met both Nelson and Gilles in
Feb. 1998 and provided them with a variety of evidence from the
Woodward case. She said she consulted more than 35 medical experts
about the cause of Matthew's death and none of them, including
Gilles or Nelson, suggested he died of strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   Leishman said she has no connection with the defense team or any
other entity involved in the Woodward case. ``I have not been paid
one penny except by `60 Minutes,' '' she said. ``I did this on my
own steam.'' Bogdanich noted that the program sought evidence and
input from both the prosecution and defense teams, and reiterated
that the suggestion of Gilles to analyze the case came from a
prosecution witness. Moreover, he noted, the story concluded that
``the defense and the prosecution got it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Leishman, while watching the Woodward trial in late
1997, she was struck by ``the polarization of experts.'' So she
undertook her own research.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jan Leestma, associate medical director of the Chicago
Institute of Neurosurgery and Neuropathology, who testified for the
defense at Woodward's trial, said he turned over the microscopic
samples of Matthew's brain tissue to Leishman at a defense lawyer's
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, the case was over, but since I'd been retained by the
firm, I didn't want to make trouble or difficulty,'' said Leestma.
``They said there was no reason (not to give Leishman the
samples.)''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Andrew Good, who represents Woodward, said, ``We'd
called for an independent, not associated with either side,
investigation. That can't be done without the scientist in question
looking at the tissue in the case. We provided it to the doctors
through her. There's absolutely nothing wrong with doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   But several observers were troubled by the fact that tissue had
been handed over for a media report.
</P>
<P>
   McCue, the Eappen friend, said the Eappens didn't watch the ``60
Minutes'' broadcast, but were devastated to learn that doctors were
now suggesting that their son was strangled up to two days before
he died. He said they were also unaware that microscopic samples of
Matthew's brain tissue had been provided to the doctors who came up
with this new theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the middle of a criminal trial, defense
attorneys are given access to all evidence and privacy rights are
waived in favor of the rights of the defendant,'' McCue said. ``But
it's different when you give that evidence to a reporter without
the consent of a parent. That's disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of Matthew that they're just mailing out. It's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was inappropriate,'' said the Eappens' lawyer,
Fredric Ellis. ``The defense obtained these samples for use in a
criminal case, and that's why I believe it's inappropriate for them
to forward it on to a media source. The law's not clear on this. As
far as I can tell it's an area that hasn't really been addressed,
but it's clearly a disturbing practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Before going to ``60 Minutes'' last summer, Leishman had
submitted a 75-page story outlining her findings to the New York
Times magazine. The magazine rejected the story, according to
Leishman, because it was ``too medical and technical.'' A
spokeswoman for Adam Moss, editor of the New York Times magazine,
said ``We do not comment on why we reject stories.''
</P>
<P>
   On another disputed matter, ``60 Minutes'' spokesman Kevin
Tedesco Tuesday said the program has a tape and a transcript that
confirms it did not take out of context a quote from Dr. Eli
Newberger of Children's Hospital, in which Newberger appeared to
say that the strangulation theory was ``potentially valid.'' A
spokesman for Newberger said the doctor stands by his assertion
that the quote used was in response to a different question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Yvonne Abraham of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
