<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, MARCH 10
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-KUBRICK-NYT (moved on Sunday, Mar. 7)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Stanley Kubrick sent by the New York Times News
Service on Sunday, Mar. 7, misstated the number of times he was
married and misstated the given name of his widow. His most recent
marriage, which lasted from 1958 until his death on Sunday, was his
third. His wife was Christiane Harlan, not Susanne. (Suzanne Harlan
was her stage name during a brief acting career.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-CORIO-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 8)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Ann Corio sent by the New York Times News
Service on Monday, Mar. 8, misstated the given name of another
prominent performer in her field. She was Margie Hart, not Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Mar. 8,
about a tiny mouse that breathes through its skin after birth
misstated its weight. It weighs about 6 10-thousandths of an ounce
at birth, not half an ounce, and about one-hundredth of an ounce at
three weeks, not 10 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-AGING-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Mar. 8,
about research on extending the human life span misstated the
classification of the canary, whose life span of two years appears
to be genetically determined. It is of the class Aves, not
Mammalia.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ANIMAL-ANTIBIOTICS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Mar. 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Mar. 7,
about efforts to limit the use of antibiotics in animals omitted
part of a quotation in some copies. The comment, by Dr. Fred
Angulo, an epidemiologist with the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, should have read, ``The way we will make major
progress, unfortunately, is when there is continuing emergence of
treatment problems, not just in humans, but when these drugs don't
work in sick animals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
