<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLICE-NYT &LR;      03-09 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MEETING ADDRESSES ALLEGED `RACIAL PROFILING' IN N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A two-year-old federal investigation into
allegations of racial discrimination by the New Jersey State Police
proceeded slowly in its early stages because the police lagged in
forwarding requested information to Washington, a top Justice
Department official told a group of New Jersey lawmakers and black
ministers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department acknowledged last month that it had been
conducting a civil rights investigation since 1996 into charges
that New Jersey state troopers routinely stopped black and Hispanic
drivers on state highways solely because of their skin color, a
tactic commonly known as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed-door meeting on Capitol Hill, Deputy Attorney
General Eric Holder told the ministers, members of Congress and
state legislators that information and documents requested from the
state police trickled in slowly to investigators during the first
14 or 15 months of the inquiry, several people in the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons he could not explain, the flow of information
improved markedly around March 1998, Holder told the group, people
in the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
   Holder did not accuse the state police of trying to delay or
obstruct the federal investigation. But several people who attended
the meeting did just that afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like stonewalling to me,'' said Rep. Robert Andrews,
a Democrat from Haddon Heights. ``The people responsible for this
ought to be asked back in Trenton why the delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Black Ministers Council and the Black and Latino
Legislative Caucus who attended the session said Tuesday's meeting
made them wonder whether the state police had tried to alter
documents before sending them to the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure the information they got isn't tainted,'' said
state Sen. Wayne Bryant, a Democrat from Camden. ``When you take a
long while to document information, we often wonder, did you sit
down and cook the books?''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the New Jersey Department of Law and Public Safety
and the State Police Department denied that there had been any
delays in forwarding information to the Justice Department or any
effort to doctor documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Jersey State Police have fully cooperated with the
Justice Department probe since the requests for information started
in 1996,'' said John Hagerty, director of communications for the
department. ``And we will continue to work closely with Justice
Department investigators as they move forward with their review.''
</P>
<P>
   State police officials and Gov. Christie Whitman have contended
that there is no widespread practice of racial profiling by state
troopers. But late last month, Whitman fired the state police
superintendent, Col. Carl Williams, after he suggested in a
newspaper interview that black and Hispanic people were more likely
than members of other racial or ethnic groups to be involved with
marijuana and cocaine traffic.
</P>
<P>
   People in the meeting said Holder told them that he expected the
Justice Department to reach some preliminary decisions about the
investigation in the next few months. If the Justice Department's
civil rights division finds evidence of discriminatory practices,
it can file a federal lawsuit and ask a judge to order the state
police to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   In brief comments to reporters after the meeting, Holder
defended the pace of the investigation, saying: ``We want to make
sure we are being fair to both sides. We go into these things with
an open mind. We don't presume there is in fact a problem. These
things take a long time. It takes a lot of data.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Attorney General Janet Reno said during
testimony before a Senate appropriations subcommittee that the
department considered the New Jersey racial profiling investigation
``one of our highest priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   During his meeting on Capitol Hill, Holder, a New Jersey native
who is black, told the group a personal story about having his
trunk searched for guns by the state police when he was a college
student.
</P>
<P>
   According to people in the meeting, Holder said he wore his hair
in an Afro at the time and was driving from Howard University in
Washington to visit relatives in Atlantic City. He indicated to the
group that the experience had given him added sensitivity to
complaints about racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was made to feel, as he described it, very uncomfortable
with the incident, and understands only too well what a humiliating
situation it is,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Holder declined to elaborate about the incident, other than to
say, ``I didn't think I was doing anything wrong at the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
