<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TO HAVE SEASON OF SHARING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIERA, Fla. _ If the Los Angeles Dodgers move their spring
training site to Arizona they may be forced to spend their first
season sharing a ballpark with, of all teams, the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are contemplating a move from Dodgertown after 51
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is the stadium may not be ready for next spring
training,'' Dodgers director of business development Fred Coons
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coons said an option would be to play spring training home games
at another team's complex, something commonly done in the Cactus
League. The Seattle Mariners and San Diego Padres share a site in
Peoria and the Arizona Diamondbacks and Chicago White Sox split a
complex in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   While Coons declined to comment on which team would share a
stadium with the Dodgers, a source said the choice was the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the time frame, the proposed $30 million project in
the Scottsdale area would have to be completed in two phases: the
practice fields and construction of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers would practice at Fort McDowell but take the 15- to
20-minute trip to Scottsdale Stadium for games.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions are ongoing between the Dodgers and the Fort
McDowell Indian Community. The Dodgers, who own Dodgertown, are
also talking with Indian River County (Fla.) and the city of Vero
Beach about selling the complex to them and leasing it back.
</P>
<P>
   Young's MRI negative: The MRI done on second baseman Eric
Young's back was negative, but not without incident. Young went to
have the MRI done Monday and was halfway finished when he was told
the clinic was closing and that he would have to come back Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Young has been slowed by back stiffness the past week, but has
resumed hitting and fielding grounders. Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said that barring a setback, Young might play for the first
time Sunday against the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   A moment of thanks: Before the Dodgers' game against the Florida
Marlins at Space Coast Stadium, left fielder Gary Sheffield was
keeping an eye out for Marlins owner John Henry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to say `Thank you for keeping the team in South
Florida and giving the people there a team to watch,''' said
Sheffield, who was born in Tampa. ``I'm just happy he kept it
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Outfielder Jacob Brumfield, who played
in the majors for six seasons, was signed by the Dodgers to a
minor-league contract Monday and played against the Marlins. The
34-year-old spent last season with the Marlins' Triple-A affiliate
in Charlotte.... Four days after joining the minor-league camp,
former Chicago Cubs catcher Rick Wilkins was the starter against
the Marlins and went 0 for 2.... Right-hander Dave Mlicki, fighting
for a spot in the rotation, had his second strong outing. He gave
up one run on three hits in four innings. ``I started throwing the
slider a little bit, which felt pretty good,'' Mlicki said....
Shortstop Jose Vizcaino was walking with a pronounced limp after
getting hit with a ball thrown by Roberto Mejia, but he said he
would be ready to play Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
