<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-DEBTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN PLANNING TO PAY OFF DEBTS OF SUBSIDIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Eager to resolve a sticking point in merger
negotiations with DaimlerChrysler AG, the Nissan Motor Co. plans to
announce on Wednesday that it is paying off debts at a troubled
subsidiary, people close to Nissan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan wants to reach a deal soon because credit rating agencies
have been threatening to lower its rating. Nissan already has the
lowest possible investment-grade rating from Standard &AMP; Poor's. A
further lowering, to junk bond status, would hurt Nissan's ability
to raise money it needs for development of new car models and other
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, the world's sixth-largest automaker, had been trying for
nearly a year to sell its 39.8 percent stake in the Nissan Diesel
Motor Co., one of the world's largest makers of diesel engines, to
DaimlerChrysler. Those negotiations have included the possibility
that DaimlerChrysler, the world's fifth-largest automaker, might
take a stake in Nissan itself.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as mid-February, DaimlerChrysler's leaders were
saying that no agreement was likely with Nissan for three or four
months. But Robert J. Eaton, DaimlerChrysler's co-chairman, told
The Associated Press at the Geneva International Motor Show Tuesday
that the German-American automaker will likely decide before the
end of this month whether to take a stake in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   A persistent problem in all of these negotiations has been the
debt of another Nissan subsidiary, Nissan Diesel Sales, in which
Nissan and Nissan Diesel each own 50 percent stakes. Under Japan's
accounting practices, neither Nissan nor Nissan Diesel has had to
include the debts on their balance sheets because neither company
actually controls Nissan Diesel Sales. But this tangle of debt has
complicated negotiations with DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   To remove this obstacle, Nissan and Nissan Diesel will announce
on Wednesday that they will each put 20 billion yen, or about $167
million, into Nissan Diesel Sales; the combined sum of 40 billion
yen in cash will cover most of Nissan Diesel Sales' debts, people
close to Nissan said, adding that they thought that this would make
a sale imminent, at least for Nissan Diesel.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler declined to comment this evening on Nissan's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler officials have generally been reluctant to move
quickly, trying instead to drive a hard bargain while letting
Nissan's problems worsen. Juergen Schrempp, DaimlerChrysler's
co-chairman, said last month in Chicago that it could take three or
four months to complete a transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 billion yen is a tiny sum compared with Nissan's total
debts, estimated at $20 billion to $35 billion. Many financial
analysts had expressed surprise that any automaker would be
interested in such a heavily indebted partner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
