<HEADER>
A4175 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BOOK-ART-1STLD     03-09 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BOOK-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-718&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CANCELS GRANT FOR CHILDREN'S BOOK WRITTEN BY MEXICAN
GUERRILLA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 6th graf to add context; moves up 9th graf) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By JULIA PRESTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A macaw with scarlet and violet plumes soars
across the cover of a book called ``The Story of Colors,'' inviting
children to read a folk tale about Mexican gods who took a gray
world and filled it with brilliant hues.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few surprises, though, in this eye-catching
bilingual children's book just published by a small publisher in El
Paso, Texas, which won a grant from the National Endowment for the
Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Its author is Subcomandante Marcos, the political mastermind and
military strategist of the Zapatista guerrillas of southern Mexico.
On the inside flap, he appears in a photo with a black ski mask
hiding his face and bullet-laden ammunition belts slung across his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the chairman of the Endowment, William J. Ivey _ who
is working to rebuild the agency after its recent reprieve from a
death sentence issued by congressional Republicans _ abruptly
canceled the grant for the book. Ivey overruled a multilayered,
year-long grant approval process, acting within hours after the
book was brought to his attention by a reporter's phone call.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was worried that some of the Endowment's funds might
find their way to the Zapatista rebels, who led an armed uprising
in 1994 against the government of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey's decision stunned the Cinco Puntos Press, a shoestring
operation that had laid out $15,000 to print 5,000 copies of the
book, half of which was to be paid by the Endowment grant. The
agency canceled grant funds of about $7,500, which was to have paid
for about half of the printing cost. The books are ready to be
distributed and carry the Endowment's logo on the last page,
together with an acknowledgment of ``generous support'' from the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is spineless,'' said Bobby Byrd, a poet and editor of
books on border issues who runs the publishing company with his
wife and daughter from their home in El Paso. ``This book is
essentially about diversity and tolerance, everything the NEA is
supposed to stand for, and they just don't have the courage to
publish it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Colors'' reflects a literary, sometimes whimsical
side that has distinguished Subcomandante Marcos, the only
non-Indian among the Zapatistas' highest leaders, from other steely
Latin American guerrilla commanders. (His real name is Rafael
Sebastian Guillen Vicente, and he is a former university graphics
professor.)
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Byrd said he had made clear in his grant proposal that no
part of the grant would go to the author, Subcomandante Marcos,
because the guerrilla leader had declared that he did not believe
in copyright and had formally waived his rights in talks with the
Mexican press. Mr. Byrd said the Guadalajara press would be paid a
small amount for the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   In the text the masked rebel leader describes himself as
lighting up his pipe, one of his hallmarks, and sitting down on a
jungle pathway to hear a tale from an Indian elder named Antonio.
The old man recounts how mythical gods grew bored with the universe
when it was tinted only in grey, and went about inventing colors
one by one. In the end they pin all the colors on the tail feathers
of the macaw.
</P>
<P>
   The bird ``goes strutting about just in case men and women
forget how many colors there are and how many ways of thinking, and
that the world will be happy if all the colors and ways of thinking
have their place,'' the text concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The illustrations are bright, broad-stroked paintings of gods
with horns and bug-eyes done by Domitila Dominguez, a Mexican
Indian artist.
</P>
<P>
   Spun in the sensuous tradition of Latin storytelling, the tale
includes elements that might be controversial in the mainstream
American children's book market. As the story opens, the text
reads, ``The men and women were sleeping or they were making love,
which is a nice way to become tired and then go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The double-page illustration shows a reclining naked woman in a
sexual embrace with figure that appears to be a male god.
</P>
<P>
   There are no references to the Zapatistas' cause or their
military tactics, but in a cover blurb, Amy Ray, a member of the
Indigo Girls, a Grammy-winning American song duo, says, ``This
beautiful book reminds us that the Zapatista movement is one of
dignity that emanates from the grassroots of the indigenous people
of Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that it is a beautiful book,''
said Byrd, whose press specializes in bilingual children's books.
``A lot of our stories in the United States have been cleaned up
with a politically correct sentiment, and so much detail has been
washed away.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I can imagine how someone would rewrite this for an
Anglo audience,'' referring to non-Hispanic Americans. ``There
wouldn't be anybody smoking or making love.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The Story of Colors'' was originally published in Spanish in
1997 by a press in Guadalajara, Mexico called Colectivo Callejero,
which supports the Zapatistas' cause.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said that he provided a copy of the original to the
Endowment when he applied for the grant to translate it in March
1998. His first request, for $30,000 to translate a total of five
books, passed two levels of review at the agency but the funds were
cut back to $15,000. Byrd said he conferred repeatedly with
literature experts at the Endowment when he chose to leave ``The
Story of Colors'' in a revised grant request he presented to
translate only two books.
</P>
<P>
   Cinco Puntos Press (the name means Five Points in Spanish)
received a written notice in February that the funds had been
approved. The only step left was for the agency to send the money.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey, the Endowment chairman, said that he was not concerned
about the book's contents and had not seen the finished printed
book. When he went over the grant records Monday night, he said, he
became worried about rights payments, which the El Paso press had
contracted to make to the publishing group in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an uncertainty about the ultimate destination of
some part of the funds,'' Ivey said. ``I am very aware about
disbursing taxpayer dollars for Americans' cultural life, and it
became clear to me as chairman that this just wasn't right for the
agency. It was an inappropriate use of government funds.''
</P>
<P>
   An Endowment official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said that it is very unusual for the chairman to step in at the
last moment to override the work of several review committees,
including the 26-member National Council on the Arts, which
includes six federal lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans gained control of the Congress in 1995, they
were frustrated with the Endowment's support for art works they
regarded as offensive and vowed to eliminate the agency. But the
House moderated its views under election year pressures and voted
overwhelmingly in July 1998 to keep the agency alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS &LR;      03-09 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON A STEP CLOSER TO GETTING EMERGENCY FUNDS FOR CENTRAL
AMERICA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ President Clinton inched closer Tuesday
to securing emergency aid for Central America as he toured the
region devastated by Hurricane Mitch, warmly praising U.S. military
personnel for their rescue and recovery efforts, and promising
closer ties with democracies in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton outlined plans for expanding, at least temporarily, the
U.S. military role in helping with reconstruction of the region's
schools, highways and bridges, and in providing medical aid for
thousands who were left homeless and without safe drinking water
after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the president acknowledged the need to revise
U.S. immigration laws, but he stopped short of committing to any
changes that would allow more emigres from the economically
troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a mistake to openly encourage more people
to come (to the United States) in violation of the laws and
established quotas,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton said, the United States will work with the
governments of Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua to
rebuild their economies to be capable of providing jobs so
residents of the impoverished region would not feel their only hope
is to migrate northward.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end Clinton is wrestling with Congress over an aid
package worth more than $950 million for the four countries hardest
hit by the hurricane. The package also would postpone for two years
the $600 million in annual interest payments made by Honduras and
Nicaragua, which between them owe $9.9 billion to the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bill, the president has asked Congress to
temporarily lift trade barriers for nations in Central America and
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Republican congressional leaders said they were
committed to approving the aid package, which also has money for
U.S. farmers. The major disagreement with the White House is where
the money comes from. Clinton wants to use part of the anticipated
budget surplus. Republicans want to offset the costs with cut in
other programs, such as food stamps and environmental initiatives
favored by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the suffering (in Central America) is great and
Congress will make every effort to pass (an aid bill) as soon as
possible,'' Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts, chairman of the House
Republican Conference, said Tuesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee already has approved $977
million in relief aid and House Appropriations Committee Chairman
C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., said his committee would likely complete
work on a similar aid package Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Once the two bills are merged in conference, the full Senate and
House are expected to vote on them by March 26 when Congress begins
a two-week Easter recess.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with community leaders in Tegucigalpa, Honduras,
Clinton said he wants ``to be sure political considerations in the
United States that have nothing to do with Central America, things
back home, don't hold up consideration'' of the aid package and
free-trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called the devastation seen
during the first half of the president's four-day, four-country
tour a ``textbook case for emergency spending.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think we should pit one program against another
program when we have a clear emergency here,'' Lockhart told
reporters. ``We need to get the money freed up and we need to get
it down here where it can be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said Congress is insisting on control of the funding, so
that disbursements are made directly to organizations and companies
involved in rebuilding the nations' infrastructure and economy.
Under guidelines set by the House and Senate, the funds would be
administered by the State Department and the U.S. Agency for
International Development.
</P>
<P>
   Young said President Clinton had wanted, in effect, to ``take
the cash'' with him (on his trip) and ``hand it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make this very clear,'' he said. ``We are not
sending cash to these countries. We have more of an obligation to
the American taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, at Honduras' Sato Cano Air Base, Clinton lauded
the hurricane rescue and relief efforts of the 500 Air Force and
Army personnel assigned to the facility, and outlined plans for
expanding their involvement in reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots and soldiers, whose primary mission is drug
interdiction, are credited with rescuing 1,052 people, including
Honduran President Carlos Roberto Flores Facusse and his wife,
Mary, from rising water when the remnants of Mitch dumped heavy
rain during a five-day period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the real test came, (you) passed with flying colors,''
Clinton told the troops gathered in a hangar normally used to
shelter Black Hawk helicopters. ``To all who were a part of it, I
thank you for your courage, your confidence, your compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said National Guard and military reservists, who each
year spend two weeks in intensive training, will rotate through
Sato Cano over the next year. Officials said the part-timers would
help dig new high-capacity wells, reconstruct flood-damaged
highways and bridges, build schools and libraries, and provide
medical assistance to more than 70,000 Central Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane, considered the worst natural disaster to hit the
Americas, and the flooding came at a time when countries in the
region were wrestling with political and social changes following
decades of civil wars, border conflicts and military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 1980s, the U.S. invested billions in military and
economic aid to prevent a communist takeover of the region. U.S.
spending in the region has dropped sharply, with some countries
receiving less than a fourth of previous levels, which makes Japan
and the European Union the biggest financial boosters of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction ``threatens to direct efforts away from further
consolidation of democracy,'' said Peter F. Romero, acting
assistant secretary of state for the western hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resources that could be used ... to reform judicial systems,,
to build transparent financial sectors, or to ensure equal
opportunity for all, now must meet basic needs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
