<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO UNVEIL NEW REGULATIONS AS PART OF AIRLINE PASSENGER RIGHTS
PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airlines that sell tickets for travel on another
carrier will have to tell passengers in advance the name of the
other airline, under a new Transportation Department regulation
that Vice President Al Gore plans to announce on Wednesday as part
of a ``passenger rights'' package.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule means that when an airline books a passenger on a
commuter line flying under a brand name like United Express or
Delta Connection, the passenger will be told the name of the
smaller airline actually flying the plane. This will let passengers
know that the planes they board are not flown by the companies from
which they bought the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The rule will take effect in 120 days, along with another rule
that will require airlines to tell passengers if a single
``flight'' includes a change of planes at an intermediate stop.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will also announce that the Department of Transportation
will increase the size of the office that handles customer
complaints, Clinton administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The office now has 15 people, and for most of the roughly 9,600
complaints they receive each year, they do little more than
categorize them, analyze them and discuss the trends with the
airlines, said an administration official involved in the new
proposal, who called the office ``pitifully small.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore will also announce that the administration is proposing its
own legislation, with provisions intended to help consumers to
comparison shop among airlines based on their fares and on their
policies for compensating travelers for flight cancellations and
delays, bumping, lost baggage and similar problems. The airlines
would be required to report their policies to the Transportation
Department, which would then post them on the Internet, according
to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the administration's proposals overlap two popular
bipartisan bills already introduced. One is sponsored by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz, chairman of the Commerce Committee, and Sen. Ron
Wyden, D-Ore., who is active on airline issues. The other is
sponsored by Rep. Bud Schuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House
Transportation Committee, and Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Wyden bill, for example, would make the airlines
disclose how many seats are available for passengers to buy with
frequent flier miles. The administration bill would require the
airlines to disclose, for each of their 500 most popular flights,
how many seats they had sold for frequent flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision in the administration bill would require the
airlines to hold reservations for 48 hours, allowing a consumer to
price-shop. Currently, airline reservation agents often advise
callers that unless they buy the ticket immediately, the fare is
not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is also putting before Congress a few
proposals that the Transportation Department could enforce without
legislation, under existing authority. For example, the
administration bill will propose doubling the minimum required
payment per passenger for lost baggage, to $2,500 from $1,250, and
doubling the payment to passengers for ``bumping,'' or denying a
seat to a passenger who has a reservation and shows up at the
appointed hour. The current payments for bumping on domestic
flights are $200 for delays of one to two hours, and $400 for
delays of more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, airlines often avoid bumping passengers by
soliciting volunteers to give up seats, and the main effect of
raising the limits would be to make the airlines more generous when
they solicit such volunteers, aviation experts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
