<SLUG> BC-CT-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT CHIEFS ASSAIL PLAN TO RECORD RACE OF DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NJ-POLICE) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The Connecticut State Police and police chiefs
from across the state on Tuesday attacked a senior legislator's
plan to require officers to record the race of every motorist they
pull over, saying that questioning drivers could inflame racial
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Alvin Penn, the co-chairman of the Public Safety
Committee, asserting that black drivers face a much greater chance
than white drivers of being stopped for routine violations, said he
wanted to inhibit the use of racial profiling by police.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal by Penn, a Democrat from Bridgeport, state
troopers and local officers would record 10 facts about every stop,
whether or not a ticket was issued, including the driver's race or
ethnicity, approximate age, and whether or not English was the
driver's primary language. The bill directs that the information be
collected for two years and then analyzed for ``the prevalence of
discriminatory and race-based traffic stops.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Lee, who as the commissioner of public safety is head of
the state police, said the requirement ``could cause problematic
situations for all law enforcement personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking personal information about their ethnic backgrounds or
if English is their primary language can be very insulting,'' he
said in a written statement presented during a committee hearing.
``This may be considered intrusive and offensive to the public and
will not help our public relations issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee added that he does not object to the bill's purpose. ``We
believe that racial profiling is clearly illegal, and we will not
condone any practice that has that effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying Tuesday, two officials of the Connecticut Police
Chiefs Association sparred testily at times with Penn over his
proposal. ``If you really think that we're a bunch of liars and
bigots out there, why have us collect the stats?'' asked Chief
James Strillacci of the West Hartford Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Strillacci also said the questions could inflame an otherwise
tame encounter. ``A good cop doesn't care about color, unless it's
whether the light is red, yellow or green,'' he said. And Chief
Anthony Salvatore of the Cromwell Police Department said the
measure might deter officers from making routine stops, which is
how police often find people who are wanted for serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Penn, who is black, told the chiefs, who are white, that in
most cases, the race of the driver could be determined visually.
And he said the data on traffic stops were needed in order to
convince ``gentlemen such as yourselves'' that there is a problem
with race-based policing.
</P>
<P>
   Penn said that although he is willing to negotiate the
specifics, he plans to bring the measure to a vote in the next
several weeks. After the hearing, he responded to the argument that
the project would be racially divisive by saying, ``They divide
America already when they pull over people of color and have them
lay out on the sidewalks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
