<SLUG> BC-NY-STABBING-DEATH-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASPIRING SOCIAL WORKER IS SLAIN IN KNIFE ATTACK NEAR HOME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE and JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not long after leaving the community center where she
worked with battered women, a 26-year-old graduate student from
Kansas who had come to New York to become a social worker was
killed Monday night when she was stabbed in the back while walking
home, the police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Amy Watkins, was attacked less than two blocks from
her apartment in Brooklyn, the police said. Residents of the
neighborhood's brownstones, accustomed to placid evenings in the
quiet residential area, told investigators of hearing two screams,
the first as if in fear, the second in agony.
</P>
<P>
   The police found Ms. Watkins with a kitchen knife in her back,
her body surrounded by fallen groceries. She was taken to a
hospital and pronounced dead an hour after being found.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Ms. Watkins was found with no purse or
identification, leading them to believe that robbery was the
motive. The police said that there were no witnesses to the attack,
and that they did not have a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins' slaying stunned her friends, her professors at the
Hunter College Graduate School of Social Work in Manhattan and her
colleagues at New Settlement Apartments in the Bronx, where she
worked in the community center three days a week, counseling
battered women and working with children.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Ms. Watkins had organized a community meeting
of parents to discuss poor reading scores at a local elementary
school. Last Oct. 29, she organized a candlelight vigil of 200
women in protest of domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anything we can learn from this, we can use this
to live our lives every day, very fully,'' said Adam Green, 26, who
had dated Ms. Watkins for four months and also worked at New
Settlement. ``She did. She was doing exactly what she wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Green said he and Ms. Watkins had taken the
subway from the Bronx after the community meeting. Green had dinner
plans with his parents in Manhattan, but Ms. Watkins declined an
invitation to join them.
</P>
<P>
   Disembarking in Brooklyn, Ms. Watkins bought groceries and began
walking home when she was attacked, the police said. Investigators
believe that Ms. Watkins attempted to fight off her assailant, and
residents of the brownstones told of horrible screams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't sound human,'' said one man, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``I thought a cat had gotten run over. I
looked out my window and I didn't see anything, but then someone
rang my doorbell and told us there was a girl lying in the street
with a knife in her back.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Ms. Watkins had moved to Prospect Heights, which
like so many other Brooklyn neighborhoods has rapidly gentrified in
recent years. But in its brutality and apparent randomness, Ms.
Watkins' slaying is the kind of homicide that has become an
increasing rarity at a time when crime has fallen to historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   Police statistics from the 77th Precinct show that there were
seven homicides in the precinct last year, compared with 34 in
1997, a drop of 79 percent. The only previous homicide this year
was the stabbing death of a 21-year-old man who lived in a public
housing project. There has been no arrest in that attack, but the
police said the two killings did not appear to be related.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always considered the neighborhood safe, so this really
hits home,'' said Calvin Bellerand, who lives next door to Ms.
Watkins' apartment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Born in Illinois and raised in Topeka, Kan., Ms. Watkins
graduated from the University of Kansas in Lawrence in 1996 with a
degree in social work. While attending the university, she
volunteered at the largest women's shelter in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins' friend, Abbie Bassin, 26, said they met in Kansas
and spent a college summer volunteering in the Israeli Army. The
pair also traveled to to Egypt, Jordan and Turkey, Ms. Bassin said.
</P>
<P>
   After her graduation, Ms. Watkins worked outside Boston
counseling mentally ill people. She moved to New York to after
being accepted by Hunter College.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a vitality, an incandescent quality about her,'' said
Michael Fabricant, a professor of research and policy at the
school. ``She was very alive, a passionate human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Megan Nolan, her supervisor at New Settlement, said Ms. Watkins
worked most often with a group of battered women, supervising a
weekly Wednesday meeting. Recently, the group had been planning to
paint a mural on a nearby building depicting positive images of
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll still do it,'' said Jack Doyle, the director of New
Settlement. ``In one way or another, it will memorialize Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   Classmates at Hunter gathered Tuesday in Fabricant's office,
mourning Ms. Watkins' death and discussing the possibility of
creating a second mural at the school in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw the development of the mural as a way for the women to
get to know each other, and for her to get to know them,''
Fabricant said. ``But she was concerned that the mural not be the
beginning and ending of the relationships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
