<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 ARRESTED DURING SIT-IN TO PROTEST DIALLO KILLING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A dozen people protesting the killing of Amadou
Diallo were arrested Tuesday after staging a sit-in in front of
Police Headquarters, and organizers vowed to continue with daily
acts of civil disobedience until the police officers involved in
the shooting are arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A group of protesters broke off from a demonstration of about 50
people in front of One Police Plaza shortly after noon, sat down in
front of the building's revolving doors and chanted ``No justice,
no peace!'' After they were warned that they faced arrest if they
did not move, they were placed in plastic handcuffs and led away
one by one.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton led the rally but was not arrested. He
noted that he was arrested at another rally last week and said that
he hoped to have different people arrested each day to prove to the
world that ``it's not just the same people getting arrested every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, five to 12 people will come to Police Plaza and
nonviolently submit to an arrest to protest the lack of action on
the police who murdered Amadou Diallo,'' he said. ``Why do civil
disobedience? Because we want the world to see this city is willing
to arrest nonviolent protesters but not willing to arrest police
that would shoot an unarmed man 41 times.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bronx grand jury is still hearing evidence about the Feb. 4
shooting; it is charged with deciding whether the four police
officers involved should be charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a youth rally against police brutality, the Diallo
shooting and the Police Department's plan to begin using new
ammunition is scheduled to be held in City Hall Park. The rally,
billed as a ``hip-hop generation march against hollow-point bullets
and police brutality,'' has been advertised extensively on the
radio and in fliers distributed around the city that have exhorted
students to attend the rally instead of school.
</P>
<P>
   But a police officer who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said that he and a number of other officers across the city had
been placed on a special assignment and ordered to look for truants
Wednesday. ``A lot of these kids, if they decide to go, will never
get over the bridge,'' the officer said. Marilyn Mode, a Police
Department spokeswoman, said that the department has no special
anti-truancy efforts planned for Wednesday. ``Our truancy patrols
will be the same as they always are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said that he would be disturbed if the police made
an effort to keep young people from attending a rally against
police brutality. ``When the Yankees have a celebration, not only
do they not put truancy patrols on the street, but the mayor
encourages people not to go to school,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
