<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMTRAK-HIGH-SPEED-840     03-09 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-HIGH-SPEED-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK UNVEILS HIGH-SPEED TRAIN TO RUN IN NORTHEAST CORRIDOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aiming to bring high-speed rail service to Boston by
the start of the new millennium, Amtrak said Tuesday that it would
start rolling out the first of its new 150 mile-an-hour trains by
December.
</P>
<P>
   The new high-speed rail line intends to change commuting habits
along the Northeast corridor from Washington to Boston by competing
head on with air shuttles and interstate highways. But more
important for Amtrak, the high-speed train provides a model for its
rail service across the nation, and is the centerpiece of its hopes
of economic redemption after operating for three decades with
government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are kicking off the revitalization of train service
in America,'' Gov. Tommy G. Thompson of Wisconsin, who is the
chairman of Amtrak's board, said at a Manhattan news conference. He
described the new Northeast corridor trains, comparable to the
bullet trains of France and Japan, as the first installment of
high-speed rail service in this country, with his corner of the
Midwest coming next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are giving notice to our competitors,'' said George D.
Warrington, the president of Amtrak, the National Railroad
Passenger Corp., addressing the more mundane, unresolved question
of whether trains _ even those making the New York-to-Washington
run in two and a half hours _ can compete with discount regional
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   With a phalanx of brand-name politicians on the rostrum _
including the former governors Michael S. Dukakis of Massachusetts
and Linwood Holton of Virginia, both board members _ the conference
provided a more rounded but still incomplete picture of the
railroad's long-awaited high-speed service.
</P>
<P>
   Central to its plan, Warrington said, are trains that speed from
Pennsylvania Station in Manhattan to South Station in Boston in
three hours, cutting 1 hour and 40 minutes off the time of the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   With new, electrified engines pulling rebuilt Amtrak cars, the
three-hour schedule has been made possible by extensive track work
and electrification from New Haven to Boston, a project that cost
$1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The trains will also be used along the line to Union Station in
Washington, beginning some time before mid-2000. With the new
trains, the trip from Manhattan to Washington will take a half-hour
shorter than the current three-hour trip of Amtrak's Metroliner
express train, which went into service in 1969 after track upgrades
and has a top speed of 125 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Just as critical as their speed, according to transportation
analysts, will be the cost of riding the new trains. The
announcement comes only weeks after several discount regional
airlines disclosed plans to enter the hotly competitive New York
regional market, prompting widespread predictions of lower air
fares, if not an airline price war.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Amtrak refused to say what they would charge for
the high-speed rail trip. Compared with the current differential
between air shuttle and train tickets _ about 40 percent between
New York and Washington, where the Metroliner charges $119 and
full-fare air shuttles cost just under $200 _ Warrington said
high-speed trains would offer a smaller discount.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still have a more attractive fare'' than competing air
shuttles to Washington and Boston from New York, he said. But where
the savings is now closer to 40 percent, he said riders on the
high-speed trains could expect to pay about 30 percent less than
for airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's ticket pricing for high-speed trains could be crucial
to its success. Its executives said Tuesday that it planned to
retain slower, lower-priced service that has always held an appeal
with more budget-conscious travelers or those traveling between
smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market they have to go after is the business traveler who
at the moment wouldn't consider Amtrak unless he is just somebody
who doesn't like to fly,'' said Jeffrey Zupan, a transportation
analyst for the Regional Plan Association in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To attract more riders, Amtrak said it would schedule more
trains along the length of its Northeast corridor, with the biggest
service expansion between Boston and New York City. While declining
to provide detailed schedules, it said it would begin offering 17
round-trip trains between the two cities sometime next year,
compared with nine round trips currently. It declined to say how
many would be high-speed versions making the projected three-hour
run.
</P>
<P>
   Another question left unanswered Tuesday was how many stops the
high-speed trains would make, another complex equation for Amtrak
planners, since every stop increases travel time for those on
board.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary plans by Amtrak that were released yesterday call
for stops of its high-speed express service in Boston, Providence,
R.I., New Haven, Conn., New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore and
Washington. But executives of the railroad said it had not been
determined how such heavily used rail hubs as Route 128 outside
Boston, New London and Stamford, Conn., and Trenton would figure
into their plan for high-speed service.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Obviously, not every train is going to stop at every station,
and we are going to have to look at what makes most sense in
consideration of speed and convenience,'' said Barbara J.
Richardson, Amtrak's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   With such questions remaining until sometime later this year,
Amtrak officials sought Tuesday to emphasize several improvements
in comfort and service that are planned for the new trains, largely
aimed at to business travelers in an era of cellular phones, laptop
computers and increased demands for executive productivity, even on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, Warrington said, will be electrical outlets next to
every train seat that enable travelers to plug in their laptop
computers. Video monitors in each train's cafe car will provide
news updates, while audio plugs will be provided with headsets for
each rider, with pre-recorded music.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak plans to name the trains Acela (pronounced uh-SELL-uh),
which is a made-up name, not an acronym.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-99 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
