<HEADER>
A4295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIMAGGIO-NYT &LR;      03-09 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIMAGGIO-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DiMAGGIO BUILT A LEGEND, THEN TOOK CARE NEVER TO STEP ON IT 
 (rk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Allen Johnson tells it, he was 12 years old and
making his first trip to Yankee Stadium, when he saw Joe DiMaggio
glide silkily under a fly ball in center field. Johnson, who is
black and lives in Harlem, said he could never forget DiMaggio
because his father kept telling him that here was a white man who
combined hustle with absolute cool.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this memory, the chronological part, cannot possibly be
true.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who works in an Au Bon Pain restaurant in midtown, is
now 51 years old. Years before he attended his first game in the
Bronx, DiMaggio had retired and moved back to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But the essential part _ the mesmerizing allure of a man
committed to craft and to self-restraint _ remains rock-solid true,
so that today Johnson tells his son that if he wants to imitate a
sports hero, forget self-glorifying, motor-mouth superstars and be
calmly superb like DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every step in his life, DiMaggio was what New Yorkers
wanted in a hero,'' said Richard Ben Cramer, who is writing a
biography of the Yankee great, who retired in 1951 and died on
Monday at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the tidal wave of print and electronic remembrance that
was unleashed by DiMaggio's death there lies a remarkable case
study in image management, New York-style.
</P>
<P>
   Students of his career say that DiMaggio, the son of an
immigrant fisherman, had a nearly flawless instinct for dressing
himself up in myths that wowed New Yorkers. He did it the same way
he caught fly balls, without apparent effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anticipation is the heart of both games,'' Cramer said.
``DiMaggio was never a rube. He was very smart and very urban.
Coming out of the Great Depression, he was the immigrant boy who
made it big. Coming back from World War II, he had all the wealth
and power that New York aspired to. When New York saw itself as the
center of the world, he was its paragon of class.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio survives his long-ago career, the vagaries of memory
and even his mortality because, in the nearly five decades of his
denouement, he took care not to step on his legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He polished his image as a player and then guarded it as the
years went along,'' said Roger Angell, the baseball writer for The
New Yorker, who as a boy did see DiMaggio play in Yankee Stadium.
``He wouldn't talk to the writers. You really couldn't get near
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he did the TV commercials,'' he continued, referring to
advertisements for Coffee and Bowery Bank, ``they were gravely
done. He did not suffer from overexposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer, who angled for years to talk to DiMaggio for his
biography, finally did get to him. But even then, DiMaggio was much
too shrewd to give away the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was no help. Don't get any ideas,'' Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Like a fairy tale mirror, DiMaggio's carefully tended image
encouraged generations of New Yorkers to glimpse what seemed like a
nobler version of themselves and of how they might play the game,
any game.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's enduring legacy _ prideful and self-possessed
excellence _ meshed seamlessly with the temper of New York during
the dominant Yankee years of the 1930s, '40s and '50s. The baseball
club won World Series after World Series as the city dominated the
nation in culture, wealth and high-toned razzle-dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He arrived in 1936 at the moment of the great Yankee years,
and he personified the Yankees and the city more than any other
player,'' Angell said. ``Babe Ruth was himself, but DiMaggio was
the Yankees. The way he played was not exuberant. He did everything
in a restrained and deadly way. He was authoritative in a way that
New York was authoritative. That is when we all thought of
ourselves as very much the center of things.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 13 years that he played for the Yankees, DiMaggio had
an uncanny knack of plugging into the imaginative and emotional
life of New York by standing apart from it, according to Angell. He
took his cool, almost clinically detached, style of baseball with
him as he became a player on the Broadway scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a private public life in a way that would be very
difficult today,'' Angell said. ``He hung out with Broadway people
in Broadway restaurants, but they respected his privacy. He was not
gossiped about and he was not quoted. It was strange. You couldn't
get near him. He had friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he moved away after retirement, first to California and
then to the home in Florida where he died, DiMaggio always kept his
hand in the New York image game. He made the commercials, he paid
royal visits to Yankee Stadium (always few enough to be special
events) and he resisted all blandishments to emote about his failed
marriage to Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   The end result of this calculated pursuit of privacy amid almost
deafening acclaim was what many people on the streets of New York
described this week as an ``aura.'' It transcended sport, weathered
the long years of retirement and still had enough stroke this week
to move New Yorkers to tears.
</P>
<P>
   John Cortez, 72, who supervises the umpiring staff for a fall
baseball league in Park Slope, Brooklyn, got a choked-up call on
Monday as news spread that the great DiMaggio was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son, who is 42 years old, called up crying when he heard
about it, and he never saw Joe play,'' Cortez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
