<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-1STL     03-09 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
FACED WITH DEBT AND LAWSUITS, RJR NABISCO SPLITS FOOD AND TOBACCO
BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
 RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT   (Eds: SUBS first 4 grafs to add background on Nabisco-Reynolds
merger,   recast; SUBS 10th graf, The efforts ..., to EXPAND on
RJR's stock performance; minor editing changes elsewhere.) 
 (See also: RJR-NABISCO-TERMS, RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL,
RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN, RJR-NABISCO-LBO, RJR-NABISCO-SOUTH,
RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Three graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Burdened by debt and the persistent threat of
lawsuits over smoking, RJR Nabisco announced Tuesday that it was
splitting its food and tobacco businesses and selling its foreign
tobacco company to a Japanese buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The moves will effectively remove RJR Nabisco from the tobacco
business, while the money from the sale will reduce its debt. The
actions will also unravel one of the biggest mergers and most
fought-over leveraged buyouts of the 1980s, a battle that became a
symbol of the decade's excesses.
</P>
<P>
   The original merger between R.J. Reynolds and Nabisco in 1985
was intended to enhance the tobacco company's increasingly negative
image. Then in 1988, eager to raise the company's share price, RJR
Nabisco's management announced a plan to buy all the shares held by
outside investors for $17 billion. That move attracted other
would-be owners, including the Kohlberg Kravis Roberts investment
firm, which ultimately bid the price up to $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was financed at high interest rates, leaving a mountain
of debt. The battle for the company and the huge fees it generated
for investment bankers inspired a best seller, ``Barbarians at the
Gate,'' which became a television movie. In early 1991, Kohlberg
Kravis sold stock in the company back to the public.
</P>
<P>
   With the changes announced Tuesday, Steven F. Goldstone, the
chairman and chief executive of RJR Nabisco, acknowledged that
mixing the maker of Oreos and Nilla Wafers with the maker of
Winston cigarettes had not worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for these businesses to be under the same
roof,'' he said. ``They are very different enterprises, with
different problems, different challenges and different investor
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   People should have ``the opportunity to choose whether they want
to invest in a tobacco company or a food company,'' he added,
acknowledging the ``tobacco taint'' that many analysts say has
hampered the stock performances of Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic tobacco will become a separate company, which will be
responsible for any smoking-related claims in the United States.
The holding company will continue to own the food business and
could be liable for claims if the domestic tobacco company goes
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The international tobacco division, perennially smaller and
weaker than its rivals, is being sold to Japan Tobacco, which is
controlled by the government, for $8 billion, considered a hefty
price by even the most optimistic stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts are intended to bolster what has been a chronically
depressed stock price. An investment in RJR Nabisco in late March
1991 would have shown a loss of 53 percent by the end of last
month, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index has appreciated
230 percent in that time and the S&AMP;P index of tobacco stocks has
returned 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded cautiously Tuesday, sending RJR's share
price up a mere 75 cents to close at $29.375, although it had
initially rose nearly $2 a share after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Philip Morris also rose slightly, by 62.5 cents, with
some investors betting it would separate its tobacco and food
operations as well. A spokesman for Philip Morris said the company
had decided against that option in 1994 and had not changed its
mind.
</P>
<P>
   RJR's foreign sale, which is expected to be completed by
mid-May, will shore up the domestic tobacco company, which will be
known as R.J. Reynolds Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $5 billion in after-tax proceeds from the sale will
be used to pay down that company's debt, now about $6 billion, said
Marc Cohen, who follows stocks of tobacco companies for Goldman,
Sachs. ``It will then have a very conservatively managed and strong
financial position,'' he said, calling the spinoff ``a very bold
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Current investors in RJR Nabisco will also receive one share of
the tobacco company for each share they own in a transaction that
will be tax free to shareholders and the company.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco will remain a holding company, with its sole asset
the 80.6 percent of Nabisco it now owns. No longer owning any part
of the tobacco company, it will be renamed Nabisco Group Holdings.
Most of its 90 or so employees at the New York headquarters will be
laid off.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
