<DOCNO> NYT19990309.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4299 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-A     03-09 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
 NEW YORK: laid off.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in smoking lawsuits would be able to sue the holding
company, several experts said Tuesday, should the tobacco company
be unable to meet its obligations. But with a reduced debt load,
the free-standing tobacco company will be in a stronger financial
position.
</P>
<P>
   John Coale, a lawyer in Washington, D.C., who is involved in
lawsuits against R.J. Reynolds, said he did not foresee the new
corporate structure interfering with his cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all past conduct and present litigation, they are not off
the hook,'' he said. ``We would try to put Humpty Dumpty together
again and then we would collect.''
</P>
<P>
   How much potential liability the holding company faces will be
reflected in the stock price. RJR Nabisco now holds 80.6 percent of
Nabisco's shares, and the remainder is held by the public.
</P>
<P>
   While the food operation's shares were trading at $45 Tuesday,
the stock price of RJR Nabisco was less than $30. When the tobacco
companies are spun off and sold, Cohen predicted, shares in RJR
should rise closer to $45.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Icahn, the corporate takeover specialist who has repeatedly
bought and sold big stakes in RJR, re-entered the picture this
winter and threatened to nominate his own board of directors by
this Friday if the company did not spin off the food unit. But
pressure from Icahn was not a motivating factor, Goldstone said.
``It would be Carl's third attempt up the wall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the lawsuits brought by the attorneys general of dozens of
states were resolved last year in a $206 billion industry
settlement, Goldstone said, his priority was ``finding a home'' for
the international tobacco business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find a value for our shareholders that was high
enough to fix the balance sheet of our tobacco business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Tobacco agreed to pay a 33 percent premium for the
international tobacco division, which had been valued at about $6
billion. Japan Tobacco's chief long-term strategist, Yasushi
Shingai, said in an interview that he did not feel the price was
too high. ``These are very strong and prestigious brands, and there
is a lot of potential to grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the deal, Japan Tobacco will vault from fifth place to
third in global cigarettes and gain a presence in Western Europe
and Russia. Its revenues last year were $27.2 billion, and its
holdings include pharmaceuticals and food.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1985 after privatization, Japan Tobacco owns Japan's
biggest-selling cigarette brand, Mild Seven, and makes Marlboro
cigarettes locally for Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the company was concerned about liability from
smokers' lawsuits, Shingai replied: ``We have three pending
litigations, but the law system and the culture are very different
than in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation Tuesday about a possible sequel to
the story, particularly if Nabisco becomes a takeover target again.
``Somebody like Philip Morris may find them appetizing,'' said Gary
M. Black, who tracks tobacco stocks for Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
