<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPISCOPALS-HOMOSEXUAL     03-09 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPALS-HOMOSEXUALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Episcopal Church averts split over homosexuality
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAVASOTA, Texas _ The nation's Episcopal bishops ended a six-day
closed meeting Tuesday, saying they were convinced that divisive
issues, especially homosexuality, are best dealt with outside of
the church's legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops said that they had set aside for now the issues of
ordaining homosexuals and women, and of blessing same-sex unions,
in hopes of encouraging the 2.4 million members of the American
church to curtail efforts to change church doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, the church has been under the cloud of a
potential schism. The most recent threat came in February when, in
an unprecedented move, eight international Anglican church primates
said they would help conservative Episcopalians start a new church
if the Episcopal Church took punitive action against four bishops
who will not support the controversial ordinations or homosexual
unions.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church, which in 1997 began requiring bishops to
ordain women, has not taken any action against the four bishops,
including Bishop Jack Iker of Fort Worth, who was out of the
country and did not attend the bishops' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a sore upon our body, and we've discovered that
to continue to pick at it leads to a systemic infection,'' said
Bishop Chilton Knudsen of Maine. She was one of 140 bishops who
attended the meeting at Camp Allen, the retreat center for the
Diocese of Texas, which includes Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Claude Payne of the Diocese of Texas said trying to
settle divisive church issues through church law creates a win-lose
outcome that is not productive. ``We will not vote up or down on
the hot sexuality issues,'' Payne said. He said he does not expect
the church to take punitive action against bishops who ordain
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the issue to go away, Payne said, but bishops can
lead the church to focus on its mission to help the poor and those
in need. The Episcopal Church is one in a string of mainline
denominations that have been grappling with homosexual ordinations
and unions. In January, 90 Methodist ministers in California
blessed a lesbian marriage in a ceremony that was part protest and
part wedding. The Methodist Church's governing body in 1996 ordered
the church's ministers to stop performing homosexual weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America defrocked
a pastor who was living with a male partner.
</P>
<P>
   Lambeth Conference
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's Lambeth Conference, the once-a-decade meeting of
the worldwide Anglican Communion, dealt Episcopal liberals a
stunning defeat by overwhelmingly approving a resolution that
declared homosexual relationships are contrary to Scripture and
advising against homosexual ordination and same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Episcopalians in the United States, with the
support of international church primates, have demanded that the
Episcopal Church conform to the Lambeth resolution or they will
start a new church. The archbishop of Canterbury, George Carey, has
said he would not support a separate church.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church is one of 38 provinces in the worldwide
Anglican Communion. The bishops who head the provinces of Kenya,
Sydney, Rwanda, Jerusalem and the Middle East, Tanzania, South East
Asia, and the Southern Cone of America have sided with
conservatives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop William Wantland of Wisconsin, an outspoken conservative
who does not ordain women, said that whatever the Episcopal Church
does creates ripples throughout the Anglican Communion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Episcopal Church must not fall into the trap of thinking
it is a superpower just because America is a superpower,'' he said.
``The whole idea of a separate province depends on whether or not
the Episcopal Church remains true to the faith as perceived by the
Anglican Communion.''
</P>
<P>
   Presiding Bishop Frank Griswold said he plans to write the
primates a letter next week that will, in part, let them know what
happened at the meeting here. Payne said he is confident the
primates will back off.
</P>
<P>
   Avenue for discussion
</P>
<P>
   Resolutions passed at Lambeth are only advisory and not binding
on provinces, Griswold said. Earlier this century, Lambeth came out
against birth control and forbade divorce, positions it has since
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the resolution that upheld traditional Bible teaching
about homosexuality opens the door for the Anglican Communion to
begin regularly discussing the issue, Griswold said. Before the
resolution, Griswold pointed out that ``the communion had never
discussed it before.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Griswold said he and the other bishops hope their efforts
will be able to keep the matter off the table at the next church
convention, which will be held in Denver in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're asking is the church as a whole consider in its
decision making what are the things that lend themselves to the
legislative community and what are the things that lend themselves
to more reflection and discussion,'' Griswold said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. Rebecca Thatcher contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
