<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DUCKING: HOLYFIELD SAYS HE WILL KNOCK LEWIS OUT IN THIRD ROUND
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One fighter worked out for two hours in a
dungeon-like gym in Lower Manhattan, the booming bass line of
gospel music filling the sweat-filled air. The other didn't spar
and barely worked up a sweat over 45 minutes as a reggae beat
pulsated in the spacious Theater at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes were as different as the two men who will climb into
the ring at Madison Square Garden Saturday night for the undisputed
world heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield, his chest and abdomen heavily muscled, looked
fit, as usual, as he snapped the head of his sparring partner with
a couple stiff uppercuts. Holyfield, the World Boxing Association
and International Boxing Federation champion, is supremely
confident. The attitude has altered the way he normally conducts
himself before a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has never predicted that he would knock an opponent
out, let alone pick a round. But he is sticking to his prediction
of knocking Lennox Lewis out in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still holding to the truth,'' Holyfield said during an
eight-minute interview with the news media. ``The truth of the
matter is I'm going to knock him out in the third round. I'm not
asking anybody in here to believe that or to write that. You can
write it now or later. On the 13th you'll have the answer
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield (35-3) said it was nothing personal against Lewis, who
had claimed that Holyfield had been ducking him for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with Lennox Lewis,'' Holyfield said.
``It just so happens that Lennox Lewis is the opponent I'm going to
knock out in the third round.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's lawyer, said Holyfield began his weight
training for the fight with his conditioning trainer, Tim Hallmark,
in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Tim back in November and asked him if there was
anything I could do to help get Evander ready,'' Thomas said. ``He
said make sure that Evander gets 10 workouts in December. Evander
did 12 workouts and had Tim supervise them in Atlanta. He's started
out faster and better for this camp than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield left quickly after his workout, because he had to do
satellite television interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lewis, the World Boxing Association champion, wore a
black-and-blue sleeveless spandex shirt with matching knee-high
shorts. It looked more like a scuba-diving outfit than boxing togs.
Lewis' workout was punctuated by punches thrown at the hand pads
held by his trainer, Emanuel Steward.
</P>
<P>
   With his bulging biceps, Lewis looks fit. There is no doubt that
he is massive. Before he left camp, Lewis said he weighed 260
pounds and expected to fight at 255. If he comes in at 260, he will
be the heaviest opponent Holyfield, who expects to fight at 214 to
217 pounds, has faced. George Foreman weighed 257 pounds when the
two fought in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis seemed fed up with the talk from Holyfield on that
third-round knockout. ``I don't know where he's getting that,''
Lewis said. ``I'm his hardest fight. Who has he ever knocked out in
three rounds? He should have knocked out Vaughn Bean. Amazing. He
comes out trying to knock me out, he'll get knocked out himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis excused himself after a couple more minutes of questions,
because he was cooling down from his workout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the flu season, a chill on the eve of the fight would not be
a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   He gave way to Steward, no stranger to fight-week hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they both come out wired up like I expect, I can see this
being a good fight,'' Steward said. ``It could be another
Hagler-Hearns. I wouldn't be surprised.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
