<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-STRIKE-ZONE-NYT &LR;      03-09 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRIKE-ZONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL RAISES AND BRINGS IN THE EVER-SHIFTING STRIKE ZONE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Larry Parrish saw nothing different about the
strike zone during the Detroit Tigers' first exhibition game
against the Pittsburgh Pirates last Friday. The next day, when he
went to home plate to exchange lineup cards for the game against
the Cleveland Indians, the umpires delivered a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they got a letter that day,'' the Tigers' manager
said Tuesday, ``and this was the way they were going to call it.
They said you can expect the ball to be called up a little bit and
we're going to tighten it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exhibition season less than a week old, umpires have
begun implementing the changes in the strike zone that clubs were
informed about last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they've called the ball up a little better and
they've moved it in,'' said Parrish, a former major league hitter.
``They're actually calling the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Jefferies, the Tigers' designated hitter, said the umpires
were ``definitely calling a higher strike,'' adding: ``They're
calling it probably in the chest area. It's up there. I've noticed
it the last two, three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Roe, an American League umpire, said that in his first
spring training appearance behind the plate Monday he called five
or six strikes that he wouldn't have in the past. ``I think where
you'll see a difference,'' he said, ``is the real good curveball,
where the arc is coming through the strike zone. In the past we
would have had a tendency to call it a ball. We're making a
conscious effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort comes at the behest of Major League Baseball
officials, who are trying to address one of the most controversial
on-field issues in the game: the shifting strike zone. In recent
seasons, players and fans have seen the zone become lower and
wider, evolving into a rectangle more horizontal than vertical.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials want umpires to move back toward the strike
zone that is defined in the rule book, where a ball has to cross
home plate and the upper limit of the zone is ``a horizontal line
at the midpoint between the top of the shoulders and the top of the
uniform pants.''
</P>
<P>
   That upper-limit line, in the past two decades or so, descended
to a vague point somewhere below the waist. At the same time, the
strike zone expanded horizontally to where umpires were calling
strikes on pitches that were anywhere from one inch to six inches
(at least in the eyes of some beholders) off the outside corner of
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In moving to reconstruct the strike zone that was in practice,
the commissioner's office was more concerned about the wide strike.
Pitchers such as Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux of Atlanta have made
their living making hitters chase pitches wide of the strike zone
because umpires have called them strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strike zone across has been so big that hitters can't
reach it,'' Cleveland Manager Mike Hargrove said Tuesday before a
game against the Kansas City Royals in nearby Haines City. ``Or if
they do get the bat out there, there's no way they can do anything
with those pitches because they have no leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But if umpires were going to take away the outside strike,
officials decided, they would compensate pitchers with a higher
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pitch up, you have a chance to make contact,'' Parrish said.
``But a ball this far outside, you can't get to it without diving
into it and then you have to worry about getting domed.''
</P>
<P>
   So the commissioner's office decided that, the rule book
notwithstanding, the upper limit of the strike zone would extend
two inches above the top of the uniform pants. The idea, one
official said, was to make the strike zone better, not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations
in the commissioner's office, informed general managers and
managers about the changes in a Feb. 19 memo. The umpires, however,
refused initially to cooperate in the strike-zone venture because
they said they worked for the league presidents, not the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Although an internal battle has raged between the commissioner's
office and the league presidents over the general area of umpiring,
the presidents issued directives to the umpires last week telling
them to enforce the commissioner's interpretation of the strike
zone this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want it from the bill of the cap to the top of the
shoes, that's what we have to do,'' said Roe, who joined the AL
staff in 1981. ``They're our employers, and they're telling us what
to do. As long as we feel we're being backed and that's what they
want, that's what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   NL umpires, however, will apparently not do it happily. Bruce
Froemming, who in his 29th season is the league's senior umpire,
said he, for one, would have to lower his strike zone if he were to
follow the directive. But when he was asked if there was talk among
NL umpires not to follow the directive, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only talk among National League umpires is the total
disrespect that has been shown. It's a total lack of respect to
change something against the rule book definition and not sit down
with a group of umpires and say, `This is what we'd like to do. How
do you feel about it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson tried to meet with umpires in both leagues, but the
umpires in each league voted not to meet with him. When three AL
umpires _ Jim Evans, Dave Phillips and Tim Tschida _ met with him
nevertheless, they were harshly criticized by some of their
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work for Len Coleman and Gene Budig,'' Froemming said,
speaking of the league presidents. ``We don't work for Sandy
Alderson.''
</P>
<P>
   But the umpires appear ready to cooperate despite what their
political feelings may be. They just caution that they are not
robots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a human element in it,'' Durwood Merrill of the
American League said. ``What I might see two inches up, he might
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and hitters will have to adjust the same as umpires.
``It's going to be tough,'' said George Brett, a Hall of Fame
hitter and a spring coach with the Royals. ``You're so programmed
to swing at balls from here to here.'' He indicated an area from
the groin to the knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the strike zone was. All of a sudden, when they
start calling this one'' _ he drew a line above his waist _ ``it's
going to feel like mid-torso to the hitters. They're going to start
swinging at those balls up here'' _ chest high _ ``because they're
not going to be sure it's a strike.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
