<HEADER>
A4311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-STRIKE-ZONE-2NDTA     03-09 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRIKE-ZONE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LAKELAND, Fla.: a strike.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Facing pitchers with a good fastball, Brett said, hitters will
very likely pop up the high-strike pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Most hitters look for the ball down because that's where
pitchers have been taught to throw it. The change, Parrish said,
will help power pitchers but not finesse pitchers. He mentioned in
the latter group the Atlanta pitchers, some of whom he said ``have
gotten six inches off the plate outside the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could hurt some of their pitchers,'' he added, ``because
they're not power pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine readily acknowledged that he stood to be affected if
umpires stopped calling the outside strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``But can they stop?'' he asked at the Braves' camp in
Kissimmee. ``I don't know. Some of these guys have been calling
pitches the way they have for a long time. Just like it's hard to
ask a pitcher to change his style overnight, it's hard to ask an
umpire to change his style overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the left-hander said he didn't see the high
strike helping pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling a strike above the belt is going to help probably five
guys _ Clemens, Schilling, Randy Johnson and anyone else who throws
in the upper 90s and pitches up in the strike zone,'' Glavine said,
referring to the Yankees' Roger Clemens and the Phillies' Curt
Schilling. ``Everybody else, no, it's not going to help them. I
don't care if they give me from the belt to the chest, I can't
afford to pitch up there. It's not going to do me any good. I'm
successful by keeping the ball down, and I always will be, as most
pitchers are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
