<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-WARMUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE-YEAR-OLDS GETTING READY FOR THEIR BIG WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The best 3-year-old horses in America were
being primed Tuesday for their busiest weekend of the year, a
splashy series of shakedown races on the East and West coasts and
at a track in between. And they will be gunning for the prize of a
lifetime when their paths cross seven weeks later at the starting
gate for the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Exploit, the son of Storm Cat and the best in the West, takes
the stage in the $250,000 San Felipe Stakes on Saturday at Santa
Anita. Undefeated in five races, he is one of five Triple Crown
candidates being trained by Bob Baffert, and all of them are in
action this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Another star from the Baffert barn, Prime Timber, will also run
in the San Felipe.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar, a son of Wild Again, leaped into the top spot in the East
two weeks ago when he won the Fountain of Youth Stakes at
Gulfstream Park. He returns to the same track Saturday as the
favorite in the $750,000 Florida Derby. He is trained by Carl
Nafzger, who trained Unbridled, the 1990 Florida Derby and Kentucky
Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, there will be an encore: the $600,000 Louisiana Derby
at the Fair Grounds in New Orleans, where another Baffert star
heads the cast. He is General Challenge, unbeaten in three starts
in California, and he will be racing Answer Lively, winner of the
Breeders' Cup Juvenile and the 2-year-old champion last year but a
loser, by a nose, in the Risen Star Stakes two weeks ago. The horse
who beat him, Ecton Park, will also be spicing things by returning
in the Louisiana Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The crowded weekend stage will include fillies as well as colts.
On Saturday, last year's juvenile filly champion, Silverbulletday
(also trained by Baffert), is very likely to be the heavy favorite
in the $350,000 Fair Grounds Oaks in her second start of the year
and her second at the Fair Grounds. And on Sunday, more fancy
fillies will run in the Santa Anita Oaks, led by Excellent Meeting
(trained by you know who).
</P>
<P>
   But in spite of the achievements and uncommon speed of several
fillies in this year's 3-year-old class, doubts linger that any
filly will challenge tradition by challenging colts in the Triple
Crown. And history reminds us that only 36 fillies have tried to
win the Kentucky Derby and only three have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is keeping Excellent Meeting and Silverbulletday with
other fillies right now, though he is keeping his options open for
dramatic switches by Derby Day. Three Ring, who won the Davona Dale
Stakes on Feb. 21 by nearly 15 lengths, is not nominated to the
Triple Crown but her trainer, Eddie Plesa Jr., said he would enter
her Wednesday in the Florida Derby and hope for an inside post
position. And Honest Lady, a daughter of Seattle Slew trained by
Bobby Frankel, is still booked into the Santa Anita Derby but has
raced only three times anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our time, we tried to keep fillies and colts separate,''
said Jimmy Jones, who trained eight Derby winners for Calumet Farm
with his father, Ben Jones. ``Fillies can often run fast, maybe
faster than colts. But they don't really start to mature until
later in their 3-year-old seasons. It's probably a physical fact of
life. Later, they can hold their own against colts.''
</P>
<P>
   But until the best of the fillies are declared no longer in
contention for the Triple Crown, they must be ranked with the best
of the colts: Exploit, Cat Thief, Prime Timber, Menifee, General
Challenge and a pair of long-distance travelers from Dubai in the
Middle East who are being groomed in a most unusual way, Worldly
Manner and Aljabr.
</P>
<P>
   The last two are training in Dubai, where they will run in trial
races and then presumably take the voyage to Kentucky to challenge
the Derby horses who got there in the more or less conventionally
grinding way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
