<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC TO FACE RUSTY WYOMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took the better part of Tuesday for the USC
basketball team to fly to Denver, then drive 2{ hours to Laramie,
Wyo., for tonight's first-round game against Wyoming in the
National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't take into account the sub-30-degree
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   But none of it could dampen the Trojans' enthusiasm over playing
the Cowboys in their first postseason appearance in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty special,'' forward David Bluthenthal said. ``We're
happy we're in the NIT. It's good for us. We're heading in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Even usually reluctant USC coach Henry Bibby has become almost
sugary in his assessment of playing in the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get into an NIT has been a dream for me, just to get into a
tournament with this basketball team,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is how far the Trojans (15-12) can go,
considering they probably will be relegated to the road as long as
they continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   Before worrying about advancing to the semifinals at Madison
Square Garden, however, the Trojans must play a rusty Cowboys squad
that hasn't played since Feb. 27, when they defeated Nevada Las
Vegas 79-76.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (17-9) play a run-and-gun style, with no starter
taller than 6-foot-8 forward Ugo Udezue, who is a member of the
Nigerian junior national team. Udezue scored just 98 points in 28
games last year, but is averaging 20.5 points per game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very athletic. Not big. Similar to our team,'' Bibby
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming coach Steve McClain is in his first season after
spending three years as an assistant at Texas Christian under coach
Billy Tubbs. He also coached at Hutchinson Community College in
Kansas, where he won the National Junior College Championship in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting sidelights to the game will be how
Wyoming point guard Chris McMillian plays against the Trojans.
McMillian is from Brea, where former USC point guard Kevin
Augustine grew up. The Trojans did not recruit McMillian because
they believed Augustine was their point guard of the future, but he
quit the team in December.
</P>
<P>
   Today they would love to have McMillian. He's averaging 9.5
points and 4.9 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good little player. But you can't recruit everybody,''
Bibby said. ``I'm sure he wants to show SC why we didn't take him
was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans would also like to use a good showing in the NIT as
a stepping stone for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so close. For most of us, we know how good we'll be
next year,'' Bluthenthal said. ``We'll definitely make the NCAA's
next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
