</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TRUCKS' SAFETY IN QUESTION AS OPEN U.S. ROADS LOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOGALES, Ariz. _ State safety inspector Richard Saspe still
can't confirm that Mexican truck drivers give him trustworthy
documents about their rigs' safety, insurance and titles.
</P>
<P>
   He had suspected that something was fishy about all the
commercial drivers' licenses he was seeing. Saspe was right. A spot
check at the border the last six months has documented more than
100 drivers using false licenses.
</P>
<P>
   So, Saspe and other federal and state inspectors are concerned
about a Jan. 1 date rapidly approaching which is scheduled to allow
Mexican long-haul trucks to traverse the United States under the
North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Saspe marvels at how modern many Mexican
trucking companies have become recently.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies will do just fine when Arizona roads open to
them for long hauls outside the border commercial zone, Saspe says.
Gone are the days when brakes that worked were a luxury, when tires
were slick as a playground basketball, when brake lights and turn
signals simply stayed dark.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts remain, however, about the other Mexican shippers.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Inspector General of the U.S. Department
of Transportation found that 44 percent of the trucks inspected
crossing the U.S. border were ordered out of service for serious
safety violations in 1997. Federal inspectors in Nogales say that
number is slightly above 50 percent now for those trucks entering
Arizona. U.S. trucks have a 25 percent out-of-service rate and
Canadian trucks 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Mexican haulers are inspected with any kind of
regularity. Of the about 800 trucks that pass through the Nogales
port of entry daily, only about one in 30 receives anything more
than a cursory glance.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials claim that the out-of-service rate is so high
because safety inspectors repeatedly target the small number of
trucks that make the local runs from Nogales, Sonora, to warehouses
just north of Nogales, Ariz. Those trucks would not be used to
transport expensive cargos over long distances in this country,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Delaossa, who has been inspecting trucks the last six years
in Nogales, the last two for the U.S. Department of Transportation,
says he has no idea which trucks would stay and which would go.
</P>
<P>
   But he calls the quality of Mexican inspections ``poor'' and
says that he is constantly inspecting trucks ``which, if you could
believe the documents, have just gotten a clean bill of health over
there only to have numerous safety violations here.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaossa also said he has been involved in numerous instances in
which he ordered Mexican trucks out of service only to have them
try to re-enter Arizona without fixing the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Delaossa thought long and hard one recent day in his office when
he was asked if Mexican trucks should be allowed to cross this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'd try it for four or five years just in the border
states and see if the fatality rates increased,'' Delaossa said.
'`I don't know if this is something I would want to push too
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress say it shouldn't be pushed at all. They
question whether sufficient progress has been made within the
Mexican trucking industry since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks were supposed to be allowed to travel throughout
Arizona, California, New Mexico and Texas beginning in December of
that year but were delayed until it could be decided how to improve
safety and security regulations. Now, another NAFTA deadline is
rapidly approaching.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal inspectors still have no access to databases
kept in Mexico on the trucks. And although Mexico has agreed in
principle to use uniform inspection standards for trucks like in
the United States and Canada, Mexican officials said that documents
to that effect remain to be signed.
</P>
<P>
   There are no restrictions on the number of hours a day a Mexican
driver can be behind the wheel and no requirements to keep
logbooks, vehicle maintenance standards, a safety rating system and
regular roadside inspections, according to the federal
transportation study.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberto Rodriguez, Mexico's consul in Nogales, Ariz., said
the country's agency that oversees transportation has a system in
place to conduct inspections to U.S. standards and that the signing
of the tri-national document for uniform standards is a ``mere
formality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just a small number of trucks which make the local
runs up to the produce warehouses north of Nogales with which the
inspectors have problems,'' Rodriguez said. ``I would say that
between 80 and 90 percent of our truckers are ready for the next
phase of NAFTA and many of them have new equipment for the long
hauls.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Ken Barton, who administers the state Department of Public
Safety truck inspection program, also agrees that Mexican trucks
are ready to rumble on U.S. highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we open it up, there's no doubt in my mind that they will
get in compliance,'' Barton said. ``When those statistics are
brought up about out of service Mexican trucks in Nogales, I'm
reminded of a time that a study was done on the out of service
trucks in a commercial zone in Kansas City of local carriers and it
was 58 percent. We haven't cut off trade with Kansas City because
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Police agencies in the Nogales area acknowledged that the
Mexican trucks have a good safety record in the area and haven't
been involved in any noteworthy accidents in which they were at
fault. Rodriguez also said that the out-of-service rate of the
trucks would drop dramatically if the state would build a new
truck-inspection station 30 miles north of the border rather than
at the border, which is the plan now.
</P>
<P>
   That would weed out many of the older-model trucks that make as
many as seven runs a day between produce storage warehouses in
Nogales, Sonora, and Rio Rico, north of Nogales, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of trucks would never be making long hauls in the
United States because the potential for breakdowns is high and
there is too much economically at stake with each load, said Miguel
Pacheco, who heads an organization of 34 border truck companies
called Central de Servicio.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco said that the flames being fanned against the Mexican
trucking industry are the work of the Teamsters union and U.S.
truckers who fear Mexican competition.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco also is circulating a petition among Mexican truckers to
be sent to Congress concerning what he calls harassment and
outrageous fines by federal safety inspectors in Nogales. Pacheco
said that some Mexican truckers have been fined as much as $1,000
for having one light out on their rigs and that they have been
threatened with seizure of their passports and drivers licenses for
minor violations.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Andrade Corella, who owns a Nogales, Sonora, trucking
company called Transportes OA with his two brothers, was one of
those fined heavily for having a brake light out in the back of one
of his company's 18 trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trucking companies in Mexico know exactly what they are
going to have to do if they run long routes in the States,''
Andrade said. ``We need to invest $50,000 in our trucks for better
tires, brakes and motors. Money is hard to come by with the falling
peso and interest rates being very high. But we still want to make
the investment even though we only make four or five trips a year
to Phoenix and Tucson and have no desire to make more trips.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the type of attitude that Saspe, the state's top
inspector in Nogales, says he has grown accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody says, these trucks are a lot better
than they used to be and the truckers I know are not trying to beat
the system,'' Saspe said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that everyone is on the up and up. Saspe
noted that the abundance of false commercial driver's licenses was
traced to a printing press in the Mexican state of Sinaloa that
apparently was part of a counterfeiting ring that had connections
inside a local office of the government transportation agency.
</P>
<P>
   Saspe also said that Mexican truckers entering Arizona are
feeling a lot more relaxed these days because the time spent in
crossing to Arizona has been greatly reduced with the completion in
mid-February of a four-lane highway on the Mexican side that
bypasses downtown Nogales, Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definitely helps their frustration level before they get
on our highways,'' Saspe said. '`Now, I just hope they start
turning on their lights before it gets completely dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
